line 1=>In this reprint several minor inaccuracies, most of them noted by readers, have been corrected. For example, the rune text now corresponds exactly with the runes on  Thror's  Map.  More  important  is  the  matter  of  Chapter  Five.  There  the  true  story  of  the  ending  of  the  Riddle  Game,  as  it  was  eventually  revealed  (under  pressure)  by Bilbo  to Gandalf,  is  now  given  according  to  the Red Book,  in  place  of  the  version  Bilbo  first  gave  to  his  friends,  and  actually  set  down  in  his  diary. This  departure  from  truth  on  the  part  of  a  most  honest  hobbit  was  a  portent  of great  significance.  It  does  not,  however,  concern  the  present  story,  and  those who in this edition make their first acquaintance with hobbit-lore need not troupe about it.  Its  explanation  lies in the history of the Ring, as it was set out in the chronicles of the Red Book of Westmarch, and is now told in The Lord of the Rings. 
line 2=>
line 3=>A final note may be added, on a point raised by several students of  the  lore of 
line 4=>the  period.  On  Thror's  Map  is  written  Here  of  old  was  Thrain  King  under  the 
line 5=>Mountain;  yet  Thrain  was  the  son  of  Thror,  the  last  King  under  the  Mountain 
line 6=>before  the  coming  of  the  dragon.  The  Map,  however,  is  not  in  error.  Names  are 
line 7=>often  repeated  in  dynasties,  and  the  genealogies  show  that  a  distant  ancestor  of 
line 8=>Thror  was  referred  to,  Thrain  I,  a  fugitive  from  Moria,  who  first  discovered  the 
line 9=>Lonely Mountain, Erebor, and ruled there for a while, before his people moved on 
line 10=>to the remoter mountains of the North. 
line 11=>
line 12=>####-Chapter I <br>
line 13=>
line 14=>An Unexpected Party
line 15=>
line 16=>In a hole in the ground there lived a hobbit. Not a nasty, dirty, wet hole, filled with 
line 17=>the ends of worms and an oozy smell, nor yet a dry, bare, sandy hole with nothing 
line 18=>in it to sit down on or to eat: it was a hobbit-hole, and that means comfort. 
line 19=>It  had  a  perfectly  round  door  like  a  porthole,  painted  green,  with  a  shiny 
line 20=>yellow  brass  knob  in  the  exact middle. The  door  opened  on  to  a  tube-shaped hall 
line 21=>like  a  tunnel:  a  very  comfortable  tunnel without  smoke, with  panelled walls,  and 
line 22=>floors  tiled  and  carpeted,  provided with  polished  chairs,  and  lots  and  lots of pegs 
line 23=>for  hats  and  coats - the hobbit was  fond of visitors. The  tunnel wound on  and on, 
line 24=>going  fairly  but  not  quite  straight  into  the  side  of  the  hill  -  The  Hill,  as  all  the 
line 25=>people for many miles round called  it - and many little round doors opened out of 
line 26=>it,  first  on  one  side  and  then  on  another.  No  going  upstairs  for  the  hobbit: 
line 27=>bedrooms,  bathrooms,  cellars,  pantries  (lots  of  these),  wardrobes  (he  had  whole 
line 28=>rooms devoted to clothes), kitchens, dining-rooms, all were on the same floor, and 
line 29=>indeed  on  the  same  passage. The  best  rooms were  all  on  the  left-hand side (going 
line 30=>in),  for  these  were  the  only  ones  to  have  windows,  deep-set  round  windows 
line 31=>looking over his garden and meadows beyond, sloping down to the river.  
line 32=>This  hobbit  was  a  very  well-to-do  hobbit,  and  his  name  was  Baggins.  The 
line 33=>Bagginses  had  lived  in  the  neighbourhood  of  The  Hill  for  time  out  of mind,  and 
line 34=>people considered them very respectable, not only because most of them were rich, 
line 35=>but  also  because  they  never had  any  adventures or did  anything unexpected: you 
line 36=>could tell what a Baggins would say on any question without the bother of asking 
line 37=>him. This  is a story of how a Baggins had an adventure,  found himself doing and 
line 38=>saying things altogether unexpected. He may have lost the neighbours' respect, but 
line 39=>he gained-well, you will see whether he gained anything in the end.
line 40=>The  mother  of  our  particular  hobbit  â€¦  what  is  a  hobbit?  I  suppose  hobbits 
line 41=>need  some description nowadays,  since  they have become  rare  and  shy of the Big 
line 42=>People,  as  they  call  us.  They  are  (or  were)  a  little  people,  about  half  our  height, 
line 43=>and  smaller  than  the  bearded Dwarves. Hobbits  have  no  beards. There  is  little  or 
line 44=>no  magic  about  them,  except  the  ordinary  everyday  sort  which  helps  them  to 
line 45=>disappear  quietly  and  quickly  when  large  stupid  folk  like  you  and  me  come 
line 46=>blundering  along,  making  a  noise  like  elephants  which  they  can  hear  a  mile  off. 
line 47=>They  are  inclined  to  be    at  in  the  stomach;  they  dress  in  bright  colours  (chiefly 
line 48=>
line 49=>####-green  and  yellow);  wear  no  shoes,  because  their  feet  grow  natural  leathery  soles 
line 50=>and thick warm brown hair like the stuff on their heads (which is curly); have long 
line 51=>clever brown fingers, good-natured faces, and laugh deep fruity laughs (especially 
line 52=>after  dinner,  which  they  have  twice  a  day when  they  can  get  it). Now  you  know 
line 53=>enough  to  go  on  with.  As  I  was  saying,  the  mother  of  this  hobbit  -  of  Bilbo 
line 54=>Baggins, that is  - was  the fabulous Belladonna Took, one of  the  three remarkable 
line 55=>daughters  of  the  Old  Took,  head  of  the  hobbits  who  lived  across  The Water,  the 
line 56=>small river that ran at the foot of The Hill. It was often said (in other families) that 
line 57=>long  ago  one  of  the  Took  ancestors  must  have  taken  a  fairy  wife.  That  was,  of 
line 58=>course,  absurd,  but  certainly  there  was  still  something  not  entirely  hobbit-like 
line 59=>about  them,  -  and  once  in  a while members  of  the  Took-clan would go and have 
line 60=>adventures. They discreetly disappeared, and  the  family hushed  it up; but  the  fact 
line 61=>remained  that  the  Tooks  were  not  as  respectable  as  the  Bagginses,  though  they 
line 62=>were undoubtedly richer. Not that Belladonna Took ever had any adventures after 
line 63=>she  became  Mrs.  Bungo  Baggins.  Bungo,  that  was  Bilbo's  father,  built  the  most 
line 64=>luxurious  hobbit-hole  for  her  (and  partly  with  her  money)  that  was  to  be  found 
line 65=>either  under  The  Hill  or  over  The  Hill  or  across  The  Water,  and  there  they 
line 66=>remained  to  the  end  of  their  days.  Still  it  is  probable  that  Bilbo,  her  only  son, 
line 67=>although  he  looked  and  behaved  exactly  like  a  second  edition  of  his  solid  and 
line 68=>comfortable  father,  got  something  a  bit  queer  in  his makeup  from  the Took  side, 
line 69=>something  that  only  waited  for  a  chance  to  come  out.  The  chance  never  arrived, 
line 70=>until Bilbo Baggins was grown up, being about fifty years old or so, and living in 
line 71=>the  beautiful  hobbit-hole  built  by  his  father,  which  I  have  just described  for you, 
line 72=>until he had in fact apparently settled down immovably.  
line 73=>By some curious chance one morning long ago in the quiet of the world, when 
line 74=>there  was  less  noise  and  more  green,  and  the  hobbits  were  still  numerous  and 
line 75=>prosperous,  and  Bilbo  Baggins  was  standing  at  his  door  after  breakfast  smoking 
line 76=>an  enormous  long  wooden  pipe  that  reached  nearly  down  to  his  woolly  toes 
line 77=>(neatly brushed)  - Gandalf  came  by. Gandalf!  If  you  had  heard  only  a  quarter  of 
line 78=>what  I  have  heard  about  him,  and  I  have  only  heard  very  little  of  all  there  is  to 
line 79=>hear,  you  would  be  prepared  for  any  sort  I  of  remarkable  tale.  Tales  and 
line 80=>adventures  sprouted  up  all  over  the  place  wherever  he  went,  in  the  most 
line 81=>extraordinary  fashion.  He  had  not  been  down  that  way  under  The  Hill  for  ages 
line 82=>and  ages,  not  since  his  friend  the  Old  Took  died,  in  fact,  and  the  hobbits  had 
line 83=>almost forgotten what he looked like. He had been away over The Hill and across 
line 84=>The  Water  on  business  of  his  own  since  they  were  all  small  hobbit-boys  and 
line 85=>hobbit-girls. 
line 86=>
line 87=>####-All that the unsuspecting Bilbo saw that morning was an old man with a staff. 
line 88=>He had a tall pointed blue hat, a long grey cloak, a silver scarf over which a white 
line 89=>beard hung down below his waist, and immense black boots. 
line 90=>"Good  morning!"  said  Bilbo,  and  he  meant  it.  The  sun  was  shining,  and  the 
line 91=>grass was very green. But Gandalf looked at him from under long bushy eyebrows 
line 92=>that  stuck  out  further  than  the  brim  of  his  shady  hat.  "What  do  you  mean?"  be 
line 93=>said. "Do you wish me a good morning, or mean that it is a good morning whether 
line 94=>I  want  not;  or  that  you  feel  good  this  morning;  or  that  it  is  morning  to  be  good 
line 95=>on?" 
line 96=>"All  of  them  at  once,"  said  Bilbo.  "And  a  very  fine  morning  for  a  pipe  of 
line 97=>tobacco out of doors, into the bargain. If you have a pipe about you, sit down  and 
line 98=>have  a  fill of mine! There's no hurry, we have  all  the day before us!" Then Bilbo 
line 99=>sat down on a seat by his door, crossed his legs, and blew out a beautiful grey ring 
line 100=>of  smoke  that  sailed  up  into  the  air without  breaking  and  floated  away  over  The 
line 101=>Hill. 
line 102=>"Very  pretty!"  said  Gandalf.  "But  I  have  no  time  to  blow  smoke-rings  this 
line 103=>morning.  I  am  looking  for  someone  to  share  in  an  adventure  that  I  am  arranging, 
line 104=>and it's very difficult to find anyone." 
