line 171=>and  very  bright  eyes  under  his  dark-green hood.  As  soon a  the door was opened, 
line 172=>he pushed inside, just as if he had been expected. 
line 173=>He hung his hooded cloak on the nearest peg, and "Dwalin at your service!" he 
line 174=>said with a low bow.  
line 175=>"Bilbo  Baggins  at  yours!"  said  the  hobbit,  too  surprised  to  ask  any  questions 
line 176=>for  the  moment.  When  the  silence  that  followed  had  become  uncomfortable,  he 
line 177=>added:  "I  am  just  about  to  take  tea;  pray  come  and  have  some with me." A  little 
line 178=>stiff  perhaps,  but  he  meant  it  kindly.  And  what  would  you  do,  if  an  uninvited 
line 179=>dwarf came and hung his things up in your hall without a word of explanation? 
line 180=>They had not been at table long, in fact they had hardly reached the third cake, 
line 181=>when there came another even louder ring at the bell. 
line 182=>"Excuse me!" said the hobbit, and off he went to the door.  
