line 237=>marched  with  their  broad  hands  stuck  in  their  gold  and  silver  belts  to  join  the 
line 238=>others. Already  it had almost become a  throng. Some called  for ale, and some  for 
line 239=>porter,  and  one  for  coffee,  and  all  of  them  for  cakes;  so  the hobbit was kept very 
line 240=>busy for a while. 
line 241=>A  big  jug  of  coffee  bad  just  been  set  in  the  hearth,  the  seed-cakes were gone, 
line 242=>and  the  dwarves  were  starting  on  a  round  of  buttered  scones,  when  there  came-a 
line 243=>loud  knock.  Not  a  ring,  but  a  hard  rat-tat  on  the  hobbit's  beautiful  green  door. 
line 244=>Somebody was banging with a stick! 
line 245=>Bilbo  rushed  along  the  passage,  very  angry,  and  altogether  bewildered  and 
line 246=>bewuthered-this  was  the  most  awkward  Wednesday  he  ever  remembered.  He 
line 247=>pulled open the door with a jerk, and they all fell in, one on top of the other. More 
line 248=>dwarves,  four  more!  And  there  was  Gandalf  behind,  leaning  on  his  staff  and 
line 249=>laughing. He had made quite a dent on the beautiful door; he had also, by the way, 
line 250=>knocked out the secret mark that he had put there the morning before. 
line 251=>"Carefully!  Carefully!"  he  said.  "It  is  not  like  you,  Bilbo,  to  keep  friends 
line 252=>waiting  on  the  mat,  and  then  open  the  door  like  a  pop-gun!  Let  me  introduce 
line 253=>Bifur, Bofur, Bombur, and especially Thorin!" 
line 254=>"At your service!" said Bifur, Bofur, and Bombur standing in a row. Then they 
line 255=>hung  up  two  yellow  hoods  and  a  pale  green  one;  and  also  a  sky-blue one with  a 
line 256=>long silver tassel. This last belonged to Thorin, an enormously important dwarf, in 
line 257=>fact  no  other  than  the  great  Thorin  Oakenshield  himself,  who  was  not  at  all 
