line 411=>As they sang the hobbit felt the love of beautiful things made by hands and by 
line 412=>cunning and by magic moving through him, a fierce and jealous love, the desire of 
line 413=>the  hearts  of  dwarves.  Then  something  Tookish  woke  up  inside  him,  and  he 
line 414=>wished  to  go  and  see  the  great  mountains,  and  hear  the  pine-trees  and  the 
line 415=>waterfalls, and explore the caves, and wear a sword instead of a walking-stick. He 
line 416=>looked  out  of  the  window.  The  stars  were  out  in  a  dark  sky  above  the  trees.  He 
line 417=>thought  of  the  jewels  of  the  dwarves  shining  in  dark  caverns.  Suddenly  in  the 
line 418=>wood  beyond  The  Water  a  flame  leapt  up--probably  somebody  lighting  a  wood-
line 419=>fire-and he thought of plundering dragons settling on his quiet Hill and kindling it 
line 420=>all  to  flames. He  shuddered;  and  very  quickly  he was  plain Mr.  Baggins  of  Bag-
line 421=>End, Under-Hill, again. 
line 422=>He got up trembling. He had less than half a mind to fetch the lamp, and more 
line 423=>than  half  a  mind  to  pretend  to,  and  go  and  hide  behind  the  beer  barrels  in  the 
line 424=>cellar,  and  not  come  out  again  until  all  the  dwarves  had  gone  away. Suddenly  he 
line 425=>found that the music and the singing had stopped, and they were all looking at him 
line 426=>with eyes shining in the dark. 
line 427=>"Where  are  you  going?"  said  Thorin,  in  a  tone  that  seemed  to  show  that  he 
line 428=>guessed both halves of the hobbit's mind. 
line 429=>"What about a little light?" said Bilbo apologetically.  
line 430=>"We like the dark," said the dwarves. "Dark for dark business! There are many 
line 431=>hours before dawn." 
line 432=>"Of  course!"  said Bilbo,  and  sat down  in  a hurry. He missed  the  stool  and  sat 
line 433=>in the fender, knocking over the poker and shovel with a crash. 
