line 583=>"First  I  should  like  to  know  a  bit  more  about  things,"  said  he,  feeling  all 
line 584=>confused and a bit shaky inside, but so far still lookishly determined to go on with 
line 585=>things.  "I mean  about  the  gold  and  the  dragon,  and  all  that,  and  how  it  got  there, 
line 586=>and who it belongs to, and so on and further." 
line 587=>"Bless  me!"  said  Thorin,  "haven't  you  got  a  map?  and  didn't  you  hear  our 
line 588=>song? and haven't we been talking about all this for hours?" 
line 589=>"All  the  same,  I  should  like  it  all plain  and  clear,"  said he obstinately, putting 
line 590=>on  his  business  manner  (usually  reserved  for  people  who  tried  to  borrow money 
line 591=>off him),  and doing his best  to  appear wise  and prudent  and professional  and  live 
line 592=>
line 593=>####-up  to Gandalf's  recommendation. "Also  I  should  like  to know about  risks, out-of-
line 594=>pocket  expenses,  time  required  and  remuneration,  and  so  forth"-by  which  he 
line 595=>meant: "What am I going to get out of it? and am I going to come back alive?" 
line 596=>"O  very  well,"  said  Thorin.  "Long  ago  in  my  grandfather  Thror's  time  our 
line 597=>family  was  driven  out  of  the  far  North,  and  came  back  with  all  their  wealth  and 
line 598=>their tools to this Mountain on the map. It had been discovered by my far ancestor, 
line 599=>Thrain the Old, but now they mined and they tunnelled and they made huger halls 
line 600=>and greater workshops  -and  in  addition  I  believe  they  found  a  good  deal  of  gold 
line 601=>and a great many  jewels  too. Anyway they grew immensely rich and famous, and 
line 602=>my  grandfather  was  King  under  the  Mountain  again  and  treated  with  great 
line 603=>reverence  by  the  mortal  men,  who  lived  to  the  South,  and  were  gradually 
line 604=>spreading  up  the  Running  River  as  far  as  the  valley  overshadowed  by  the 
line 605=>Mountain.  They  built  the merry  town  of  Dale  there  in  those  days.  Kings  used  to 
line 606=>send  for  our  smiths,  and  reward  even  the  least  skilful most  richly.  Fathers would 
line 607=>beg  us  to  take  their  sons  as  apprentices,  and  pay  us  handsomely,  especially  in 
line 608=>food-supplies, which we  never  bothered  to  grow  or  find  for  ourselves. Altogether 
line 609=>those were good days for us, and the poorest of us had money to spend and to lend, 
line 610=>and leisure to make beautiful things just for the. fun of it, not to speak of the most 
line 611=>marvellous  and  magical  toys,  the  like  of  which  is  not  to  be  found  in  the  world 
line 612=>now-a-days.  So  my  grandfather's  halls  became  full  of  armour  and  jewels  and 
line 613=>carvings and cups, and the toy-market of Dale was the wonder of the North. 
line 614=>"Undoubtedly  that  was  what  brought  the  dragon.  Dragons  steal  gold  and 
line 615=>jewels, you know, from men and elves and dwarves, wherever they can find them; 
line 616=>and  they  guard  their  plunder  as  long  as  they  live  (which  is  practically  forever, 
line 617=>unless they are killed), and never enjoy a brass ring of it. Indeed they hardly know 
line 618=>a  good  bit  of  work  from  a  bad,  though  they  usually  have  a  good  notion  of  the 
line 619=>current market value; and they can't make a thing for themselves, not even mend a 
line 620=>little  loose  scale of  their armour. There were  lots of dragons  in  the North  in  those 
line 621=>days, and gold was probably getting scarce up there, with the dwarves flying south 
line 622=>or  getting  killed,  and  all  the  general  waste  and  destruction  that  dragons  make 
line 623=>going  from  bad  to  worse.  There  was  a  most  specially  greedy,  strong  and  wicked 
line 624=>worm called Smaug. One day he flew up into the air and came south. The first we 
line 625=>heard of  it was a noise  like a hurricane coming from  the North, and  the pine-trees 
line 626=>on  the  Mountain  creaking  and  cracking  in  the  wind.  Some  of  the  dwarves  who 
line 627=>happened  to  be  outside  (I  was  one  luckily  -a  fine  adventurous  lad  in  those  days, 
line 628=>always wandering about, and it saved my life that day)-well, from a good way off 
line 629=>we saw the dragon settle on our mountain in a spout of flame. Then he came down 
line 630=>
line 631=>####-the slopes and when he reached the woods they all went up in fire. By that time all 
line 632=>the bells were  ringing  in Dale and  the warriors were arming. The dwarves  rushed 
line 633=>out  of  their  great  gate;  but  there was  the  dragon waiting  for  them. None  escaped 
line 634=>that way.  The  river  rushed  up  in  steam  and  a  fog  fell  on Dale, and  in  the  fog  the 
line 635=>dragon came on them and destroyed most of the warriors-the usual unhappy story, 
line 636=>it was only too common in those days. Then he went back and crept in through the 
line 637=>Front  Gate  and  routed  out  all  the  halls,  and  lanes,  and  tunnels,  alleys,  cellars, 
line 638=>mansions  and passages. After  that  there were no dwarves  left  alive  inside,  and he 
line 639=>took  all  their  wealth  for  himself.  Probably,  for  that  is  the  dragons'  way,  he  has 
line 640=>piled it all up in a great heap far inside, and sleeps on it for a bed. Later he used to 
line 641=>crawl  out  of  the  great  gate  and  come  by  night  to  Dale,  and  carry  away  people, 
line 642=>especially maidens, to eat, until Dale was ruined, and all the people dead or gone. 
line 643=>What goes on there now I don't know for certain, but I don't suppose anyone lives 
line 644=>nearer to the Mountain than the far edge of the Long Lake now-a-days. 
line 645=>"The  few  of  us  that  were  well  outside  sat  and  wept  in  hiding,  and  cursed 
line 646=>Smaug;  and  there we were unexpectedly  joined by my  father  and my grandfather 
line 647=>with singed beards. They looked very grim but they said very little. When I asked 
line 648=>how  they had got away,  they  told me  to hold my  tongue, and said  that one day  in 
line 649=>the proper time I should know. After that we went away, and we have had to earn 
line 650=>our  livings  as  best we  could  up  and  down  the  lands,  often enough sinking as  low 
line 651=>as  blacksmith-work  or  even  coalmining.  But  we  have  never  forgotten  our  stolen 
line 652=>treasure. And even now, when I will allow we have a good bit laid by and are not 
line 653=>so  badly  off"-here Thorin  stroked  the gold  chain  round his neck-"we still mean to 
line 654=>get it back, and to bring our curses home to Smaug-if we can. 
line 655=>"I  have  often  wondered  about  my  father's  and  my  grandfather's  escape.  I  see 
line 656=>now  they  must  have  had  a  private  Side-door  which  only  they  knew  about.  But 
line 657=>apparently  they made a map, and  I  should  like  to know how Gandalf got hold of 
line 658=>it, and why it did not come down to me, the rightful heir." 
line 659=>"I did not 'get hold of it,' I was given it," said the wizard. 
line 660=>"Your grandfather Thror was killed, you  remember,  in  the mines of Moria by 
line 661=>Azog the Goblin â€”" 
line 662=>"Curse his name, yes," said Thorin. 
line 663=>"And  Thrain  your  father  went  away  on  the  twenty-first  of  April,  a  hundred 
line 664=>years ago last Thursday, and has never been seen by you sinceâ€”" 
line 665=>"True, true," said Thorin. 
line 666=>"Well,  your  father  gave me  this  to  give  to  you;  and  if  I have  chosen my own 
line 667=>time and way of handing it over, you can hardly blame me, considering the trouble 
line 668=>
line 669=>####-I had to find you. Your father could not remember his own name when he gave me 
line 670=>the  paper,  and  he  never  told  me  yours;  so  on  the  whole  I  think  I  ought  to  be 
line 671=>praised and thanked. Here it is," said he handing the map to Thorin. 
line 672=>"I don't understand," said Thorin, and Bilbo felt he would have liked to say the 
line 673=>same. The explanation did not seem to explain. 
line 674=>"Your  grandfather,"  said  the  wizard  slowly  and  grimly,  "gave  the map  to  his 
line 675=>son for safety before he went  to  the mines of Moria. Your father went away  to  try 
line 676=>his  luck with  the map after your grandfather was killed; and  lots of adventures of 
line 677=>a  most  unpleasant  sort  he  had,  but  he  never  got  near  the  Mountain. How  he  got 
line 678=>there  I  don't  know,  but  I  found  him  a  prisoner  in  the  dungeons  of  the 
line 679=>Necromancer." 
line 680=>"Whatever  were  you  doing  there?"  asked  Thorin  with  a  shudder,  and  all  the 
line 681=>dwarves shivered. 
line 682=>"Never  you  mind.  I  was  finding  things  out,  as  usual;  and  a  nasty  dangerous 
line 683=>business it was. Even I, Gandalf, only just escaped. I tried to save your father, but 
line 684=>it  was  too  late.  He  was  witless  and  wandering,  and  had  forgotten  almost 
line 685=>everything  except  the  map  and  the  key."  "We  have  long  ago  paid  the  goblins  of 
line 686=>Moria,"  said  Thorin;  "we  must  give  a  thought  to  the  Necromancer."  "Don't  be 
line 687=>absurd! He is an enemy quite beyond the powers of all the dwarves put together, if 
line 688=>they could all be collected again from the four corners of the world. The one thing 
line 689=>your  father  wished  was  for  his  son  to  read  the map  and  use  the  key.  The  dragon 
line 690=>and the Mountain are more than big enough tasks for you!" 
line 691=>"Hear, hear!" said Bilbo, and accidentally said  it aloud, "Hear what?"  they all 
line 692=>said  turning  suddenly  towards  him,  and  he  was  so  flustered  that  he  answered 
line 693=>"Hear what I have got to say!" "What's that?" they asked. 
line 694=>"Well, I should say that you ought to go East and have a look round. After all 
line 695=>there  is  the Side-door, and dragons must sleep sometimes, I suppose. If you sit on 
line 696=>the  doorstep  long  enough,  I daresay you will  think of  something. And well, don't 
line 697=>you  know,  I  think  we  have  talked  long  enough  for  one  night,  if  you  see  what  I 
line 698=>mean.  What  about  bed,  and  an  early  start,  and  all  that?  I  will  give  you  a  good 
line 699=>breakfast before you go." 
line 700=>"Before  we  go,  I  suppose  you  mean,"  said  Thorin.  "Aren't  you  the  burglar? 
line 701=>And isn't sitting on the door-step your job, not to speak of getting inside the door? 
line 702=>But  I agree about bed and breakfast.  I  like eggs with my ham, when starting on a 
line 703=>journey: fried not poached, and mind you don't break 'em." 
line 704=>After  all  the  others  had  ordered  their  breakfasts  without  so  much  as  a  please 
line 705=>(which  annoyed  Bilbo  very much),  they  all  got  up.  The  hobbit  had  to  find  room 
line 706=>
line 707=>####-for  them  all,  and  filled  all  his  spare-rooms  and  made  beds  on  chairs  and  sofas, 
line 708=>before  he  got  them  all  stowed  and  went  to  his  own  little  bed  very  tired  and  not 
line 709=>altogether  happy. One  thing  he  did make  his mind  up  about was  not  to  bother  to 
line 710=>get up very early and cook everybody else's wretched breakfast. The Tookishness 
line 711=>was  wearing  off,  and  he  was  not  now  quite  so  sure  that  he  was  going  on  any 
line 712=>journey  in  the morning.  As  he  lay  in  bed  he  could  hear  Thorin  still  humming  to 
line 713=>himself in the best bedroom next to him: 
line 714=> 
line 715=>
line 716=>Far over the misty mountains cold  
line 717=>To dungeons deep and caverns old  
line 718=>We must away, ere break of day,  
line 719=>To find our long-forgotten gold. 
line 720=>
line 721=> 
line 722=>Bilbo went  to  sleep with  that  in  his  ears,  and  it  gave  him  very  uncomfortable 
line 723=>dreams. It was long after the break of day, when he woke up. 
line 724=>
line 725=>####-Chapter 2
line 726=><br>
line 727=>Roast Mutton 
line 728=><br>
line 729=> 
line 730=>Up jumped Bilbo, and putting on his dressing-gown went into the dining-room. 
line 731=>There he saw nobody, but all the signs of a large and hurried breakfast. There was 
line 732=>a  fearful  mess  in  the  room,  and  piles  of  unwashed  crocks  in  the  kitchen.  Nearly 
line 733=>every pot and pan he possessed seemed to have been used. The washing-up was so 
line 734=>dismally real that Bilbo was forced to believe the party of the night before had not 
line 735=>been part of his bad dreams, as he had rather hoped. Indeed he was really relieved 
line 736=>after  all  to  think  that  they  had  all  gone  without  him,  and  without  bothering  to 
line 737=>wake him up ("but with never a thank-you" he thought); and yet in a way he could 
line 738=>not help feeling just a trifle disappointed. The feeling surprised him. 
line 739=>"Don't be a fool, Bilbo Baggins!" he said  to himself, "thinking of dragons  and 
line 740=>all  that  outlandish  nonsense  at  your  age!"  So  be  put  on  an  apron,  lit  fires,  boiled 
line 741=>water,  and  washed  up.  Then  he  had  a  nice  little  breakfast  in  the  kitchen  before 
line 742=>turning  out  the  dining-room. By  that  time  the sun was shining; and  the front door 
line 743=>was  open,  letting  in  a  warm  spring  breeze.  Bilbo  began  to  whistle  loudly  and  to 
line 744=>forget about the night before. In fact he was just sitting down to a nice little second 
line 745=>breakfast  in  the  dining-room by  the open window, when  in walked Gandalf.  "My 
line 746=>dear  fellow,"  said  he,  "whenever  are  you  going  to  come?  What  about  an  early 
line 747=>start?-and here you are having breakfast, or whatever you call  it, at half past  ten! 
line 748=>They left you the message, because they could not wait." 
line 749=>"What message?" said poor Mr. Baggins all in a fluster.  
line 750=>"Great Elephants!" said Gandalf, "you are not at all yourself this morning-you 
line 751=>have never dusted the mantel- piece!" 
line 752=>"What's  that  got  to  do  with  it?  I  have  had  enough  to  do  with  washing  up  for 
line 753=>fourteen!" 
line 754=>"If  you  had  dusted  the  mantelpiece  you  would  have  found  this  just under  the 
line 755=>clock,"  said  Gandalf,  handing  Bilbo  a  note  (written,  of  course,  on  his  own  note-
line 756=>paper). 
line 757=>This is what he read: 
line 758=> 
line 759=>
line 760=>"Thorin and Company to Burglar Bilbo greeting! 
line 761=>For  your  hospitality  our  sincerest  thanks,  and  for  your  offer  of 
line 762=>professional assistance our grateful acceptance. Terms: cash on delivery, up to 
line 763=>and  not  exceeding  one  fourteenth  of  total  profits  (if  any);  all  traveling 
line 764=>
line 765=>####-expenses  guaranteed  in  any  event;  funeral  expenses  to  be  defrayed  by  us  or 
line 766=>our representatives, if occasion arises and the matter is not otherwise arranged 
line 767=>for. 
line 768=>"Thinking  it  unnecessary  to  disturb  your  esteemed  repose,  we  have 
line 769=>proceeded  in  advance  to  make  requisite  preparations,  and  shall  await  your 
line 770=>respected person at the Green Dragon Inn, Bywater, at II a.m. sharp. Trusting 
line 771=>that you will be punctual. 
line 772=> 
line 773=>"We have the honour to remain 
line 774=>                                  "Yours deeply 
line 775=>                                              "Thorin& Co." 
line 776=>
line 777=> 
line 778=>"That leaves you just ten minutes. You will have to run," said Gandalf. 
line 779=>"Butâ€”" said Bilbo. 
line 780=>"No time for it," said the wizard. 
line 781=>"Butâ€”"said Bilbo again. 
line 782=>"No time for that either! Off you go!" 
line 783=>To  the  end  of  his  days  Bilbo  could  never  remember  how  he  found  himself 
line 784=>outside,  without  a  hat,  walking-stick  or  say  money,  or  anything  that  he  usually 
line 785=>took  when  he  went  out;  leaving  his  second  breakfast  half-finished  and  quite 
line 786=>unwashed-up,  pushing  his  keys  into  Gandalf's  hands,  and  running  as  fast  as  his 
line 787=>furry  feet  could  carry  him  down  the  lane,  past  the  great Mill,  across  The Water, 
line 788=>and then on for a whole mile or more. Very puffed he was, when he got to Bywater 
line 789=>just  on  the  stroke  of  eleven,  and  found  he  had  come  without  a  pocket-
line 790=>handkerchief! 
line 791=>"Bravo!" said Balin who was standing at the inn door looking out for him. 
line 792=>Just  then  all  the  others  came  round  the  corner  of  the  road  from  the  village. 
line 793=>They were on ponies, and each pony was  slung about with all kinds of baggages, 
line 794=>packages, parcels, and paraphernalia. There was a very small pony, apparently for 
line 795=>Bilbo. 
line 796=>"Up you two get, and off we go!" said Thorin. 
line 797=>"I'm  awfully  sorry,"  said Bilbo,  "but  I  have  come without my  hat,  and  I  have 
line 798=>left my pocket-handkerchief behind, and I haven't got any money. I didn't get your 
line 799=>note until after 10.45 to be precise." 
line 800=>"Don't  be  precise,"  said  Dwalin,  "and  don't  worry!  You will  have  to manage 
line 801=>without pocket-handkerchiefs, and a good many other things, before you get to the 
line 802=>journey's end. As for a hat, I have got a spare hood and cloak in my luggage." 
line 803=>
line 804=>####-That's  how  they  all  came  to  start,  jogging  off  from  the  inn  one  fine  morning 
line 805=>just  before  May,  on  laden  ponies;  and  Bilbo  was  wearing  a  dark-green  hood  (a 
line 806=>little  weather-stained)  and  a  dark-green cloak borrowed  from Dwalin. They were 
line 807=>too large for him, and he looked rather comic. What his father Bungo would have 
line 808=>thought of him, I daren't think. His only comfort was he couldn't be mistaken for a 
line 809=>dwarf, as he had no beard. 
line 810=>They had not been riding very long when up came Gandalf very splendid on a 
line 811=>white  horse.  He  had  brought  a  lot  of  pocket-handkerchiefs,  and Bilbo's  pipe  and 
line 812=>tobacco.  So  after  that  the  party  went  along  very  merrily,  and  they  told  stories  or 
line 813=>sang  songs  as  they  rode  forward  all  day,  except  of  course  when  they  stopped  for 
line 814=>meals. These didn't  come quite  as often  as Bilbo would have  liked  them, but  still 
line 815=>he began to feel that adventures were not so bad after all. At  first they had passed 
line 816=>through  hobbit-lands,  a  wild  respectable  country  inhabited  by  decent  folk,  with 
line 817=>good  roads,  an  inn  or  two,  and  now  and  then  a  dwarf  or  a  farmer  ambling  by  on 
line 818=>business.  Then  they  came  to  lands where people  spoke  strangely,  and  sang  songs 
line 819=>Bilbo  had  never  heard  before.  Now  they  had  gone  on  far  into  the  Lone-lands, 
line 820=>where  there were  no  people  left,  no  inns,  and  the  roads  grew  steadily worse. Not 
line 821=>far  ahead were  dreary  hills,  rising  higher  and  higher, dark with trees. On some of 
line 822=>them  were  old  castles  with  an  evil  look,  as  if  they  had  been  built  by  wicked 
line 823=>people.  Everything  seemed  gloomy,  for  the  weather  that  day  had  taken  a  nasty 
line 824=>turn. Mostly  it  had  been  as  good  as May  can  be,  even  in  merry  tales, but now  it 
line 825=>was  cold  and  wet.  In  the  Lone-lands  they  had  to  camp  when  they  could,  but  at 
line 826=>least  it  had  been  dry.  "To  think  it  will  soon  be  June,"  grumbled  Bilbo  as  he 
line 827=>splashed  along  behind  the  others  in  a  very  muddy  track.  It  was  after  tea-time;  it 
line 828=>was  pouring with  rain, and had been all day; his hood was dripping  into his eyes, 
line 829=>his cloak was full of water;  the pony was  tired and stumbled on stones;  the others 
line 830=>were  too  grumpy  to  talk.  "And  I'm  sure  the  rain  has  got  into  the  dry  clothes  and 
line 831=>into  the  food-bags," thought Bilbo. "Bother burgling and everything to do with it! 
line 832=>I wish  I was at home  in my nice hole by  the  fire, with  the kettle  just beginning  to 
line 833=>sing!" It was not the last time that he wished that! 
line 834=>Still  the  dwarves  jogged  on,  never  turning  round  or  taking  any  notice  of  the 
line 835=>hobbit.  Somewhere  behind  the  grey  clouds  the  sun  must  have  gone  down,  for  it 
line 836=>began  to  get  dark.  Wind  got  up,  and  the  willows  along  the  river-bank  bent  and 
line 837=>sighed. I don't know what river it was, a rushing red one, swollen with the rains of 
line 838=>the  last  few  days,  that  came  down  from  the  hills  and mountains  in  front  of  them. 
line 839=>Soon it was nearly dark. The winds broke up the grey clouds, and a waning moon 
line 840=>appeared  above  the  hills  between  the  flying  rags.  Then  they  stopped,  and  Thorin 
line 841=>
line 842=>####-muttered  something  about  supper,  "and  where  shall  we  get  a  dry  patch  to  sleep 
line 843=>on?" Not until  then did  they notice  that Gandalf was missing. So far he had come 
line 844=>all  the way with  them, never  saying  if he was  in  the adventure or merely keeping 
line 845=>them  company  for  a  while.  He  had  eaten  most,  talked  most,  and  laughed  most. 
line 846=>But now he simply was not there at all! 
line 847=>"Just  when  a  wizard  would  have  been  most  useful,  too,"  groaned  Dori  and 
line 848=>Nori  (who  shared  the hobbit's views about  regular meals, plenty and often). They 
line 849=>decided in  the end that they would have to camp where they were. So far they had 
line 850=>not  camped  before  on  this  journey,  and  though  they  knew  that  they  soon  would 
line 851=>have to camp regularly, when they were among the Misty Mountains and far from 
line 852=>the  lands  of  respectable  people,  it  seemed  a  bad  wet  evening  to  begin,  on.  They 
line 853=>moved to a clump of trees, and though it was drier under them, the wind shook the 
line 854=>rain  off  the  leaves,  and  the  drip,  drip,  was  most  annoying.  Also  the  mischief 
line 855=>seemed to have got into the fire. Dwarves can make a fire almost anywhere out of 
line 856=>almost anything, wind or no wind; but they could not do it that night, not even Oin 
line 857=>and Gloin, who were specially good at it. 
line 858=>Then one of  the ponies  took  fright at nothing and bolted. He got  into  the  river 
line 859=>before they could catch him; and before they could get him out again, Fili and Kili 
line 860=>were  nearly  drowned,  and  all  the  baggage  that  he  carried  was  washed  away  off 
line 861=>him. Of course it was mostly food, and there was mighty little left for supper, and 
line 862=>less  for  breakfast.  There  they  all  sat  glum  and wet  and muttering, while Oin  and 
line 863=>Gloin  went  on  trying  to  light  the  fire,  and  quarrelling  about  it.  Bilbo  was  sadly 
line 864=>reflecting  that  adventures  are  not  all  pony-rides  in  May-sunshine,  when  Balin, 
line 865=>who was  always  their  look-out man, said:  "There's a light over there!" There was 
line 866=>a hill  some way off with  trees on  it, pretty  thick  in parts. Out of  the dark mass of 
line 867=>the  trees  they  could  now  see  a  light  shining,  a  reddish  comfortable-looking light, 
line 868=>as  it  might  be  a  fire  or  torches  twinkling.  When  they  had  looked  at  it  for  some 
line 869=>while,  they  fell  to  arguing.  Some  said  "no"  and  some  said  "yes."  Some  said  they 
line 870=>could but go and see, and anything was better than little supper, less breakfast, and 
line 871=>wet  clothes  all  the  night. Others  said:  "These  parts  are  none  too well known, and 
line 872=>are  too  near  the mountains. Travellers  seldom  come  this way  now. The  old maps 
line 873=>are  no  use:  things  have  changed  for  the  worse  and  the  road  is  unguarded.    They 
line 874=>have seldom even heard of the king round here, and the less inquisitive you are as 
line 875=>you  go  along,  the  less  trouble  you  are  likely  to  find."  Some  said:  "After  all  there 
line 876=>are  fourteen  of  us."  Others  said:  "Where  has  Gandalf  got  to?"  This  remark  was 
line 877=>repeated  by  everybody.  Then  the  rain  began  to  pour  down  worse  than  ever,  and 
line 878=>Oin and Gloin began to fight. That settled it. "After all we have got a burglar with 
line 879=>
line 880=>####-us,"  they said; and so  they made off,  leading  their ponies (with all due and proper 
line 881=>caution)  in  the  direction  of  the  light.  They  came  to  the  hill  and  were  soon  in  the 
line 882=>wood.  Up  the  hill  they  went;  but  there  was  no  proper  path  to  be  seen,  such  as 
line 883=>might  lead  to  a  house  or  a  farm;  and  do  what  they  could  they  made  a  deal  of 
line 884=>rustling  and  crackling  and  creaking  (and  a good deal of grumbling  and drafting), 
line 885=>as they went through the trees in the pitch dark. 
line 886=>Suddenly  the  red  light  shone  out  very  bright  through  the  tree-trunks  not  far 
line 887=>ahead.  "Now  it  is  the  burglar's  turn,"  they  said, meaning Bilbo.  "You must  go  on 
line 888=>and  find  out  all  about  that  light,  and what  it  is  for,  and  if  all  is  perfectly  safe and 
line 889=>canny," said Thorin to the hobbit. "Now scuttle off, and come back quick, if all is 
line 890=>well.  If  not,  come  back  if  you  can!  It  you  can't,  hoot  twice  like  a  barn-owl and 
line 891=>once like a screech-owl, and we will do what we can." 
line 892=>Off Bilbo had  to go, before he  could explain that he could not hoot even once 
line 893=>like  any  kind  of  owl  any  more  than  fly  like  a  bat.  But  at  any  rate  hobbits  can 
line 894=>move quietly  in woods,  absolutely quietly. They  take  a pride  in  it,  and Bilbo had 
line 895=>sniffed  more  than  once  at  what  he  called  "all  this dwarvish  racket," as  they went 
line 896=>along,  though  I  don't  sup-pose  you  or  I  would  notice  anything  at  all  on  a  windy 
line 897=>night,  not  if  the  whole  cavalcade  had  passed  two  feet  off.  As  for  Bilbo  walking 
line 898=>primly  towards  the  red  light,  I  don't  suppose  even  a  weasel  would  have  stirred  a 
line 899=>whisker  at  it.  So,  naturally,  he  got  right  up  to  the  fire-for  fire  it  was  without 
line 900=>disturbing anyone. And this is what he saw. Three very large persons sitting round 
line 901=>a  very  large  fire  of  beech-logs. They were  toasting mutton  on  long  spits of wood, 
line 902=>and  licking  the  gravy  off  their  fingers.  There  was  a  fine  toothsome  smell.  Also 
line 903=>there was a barrel of good drink at hand, and  they were drinking out of  jugs. But 
line 904=>they were  trolls. Obviously  trolls.  Even Bilbo,  in  spite  of  his  sheltered  life,  could 
line 905=>see  that:  from  the great heavy  faces of  them, and  their size, and  the shape of  their 
line 906=>legs, not to mention their language, which was not drawing-room fashion at all, at 
line 907=>all. 
line 908=>"Mutton yesterday, mutton today, and blimey, if it don't look like mutton again 
line 909=>tomorrer," said one of the trolls. 
line 910=>"Never  a  blinking  bit  of  manflesh  have  we  had  for  long  enough,"  said  a 
line 911=>second.  "What  the  'ell William was  a-thinkin' of to bring us into these parts at all, 
line 912=>beats me  - and  the drink  runnin'  short, what's more," he  said  jogging the elbow of 
line 913=>William, who was taking a pull at his jug. 
line 914=>William  choked.  "Shut  yer  mouth!"  he  said  as  soon  as  he  could.  "Yer  can't 
line 915=>expect  folk  to stop here  for ever  just  to be et by you and Bert. You've et a village 
line 916=>and a half between yer, since we come down from the mountains. How much more 
line 917=>
line 918=>####-d'yer want? And time's been up our way, when yer'd have said 'thank yer Bill' for a 
line 919=>nice bit o'  fat valley mutton  like what  this  is." He  took a big bite off a  sheep's  leg 
line 920=>he was toasting, and wiped his lips on his sleeve. 
line 921=>Yes, I am afraid trolls do behave like that, even those with only one head each. 
line 922=>After  hearing  all  this  Bilbo  ought  to  have  done  something  at  once.  Either  he 
line 923=>should  have  gone  back  quietly  and  warned  his  friends  that  there  were  three  fair-
line 924=>sized  trolls  at  hand  in  a  nasty  mood,  quite  likely  to  try  toasted  dwarf,  or  even 
