line 1137=>"Looking behind," said he. 
line 1138=>"Exactly!" said Thorin; "but could you be more plain?" 
line 1139=>"I  went  on  to  spy  out  our  road.  It  will  soon  become  dangerous  and  difficult. 
line 1140=>Also  I  was  anxious  about  replenishing  our  small  stock  of  provisions.  I  had  not 
line 1141=>gone very far, however, when I met a couple of friends of mine from Rivendell." 
line 1142=>"Where's that?" asked Bilbo, 
line 1143=>"Don't interrupt!" said Gandalf. "You will get there in a few days now, if we're 
line 1144=>lucky, and find out all about it As I was saying I met two of Elrond's people. They 
line 1145=>
line 1146=>####-were  hurrying  along  for  fear  of  the  trolls.  It  was  they  who  told  me  that  three  of 
line 1147=>them had come down from the mountains and settled in the woods not far from the 
line 1148=>road;  they  had  frightened  everyone  away  from  the  district,  and  they  waylaid 
line 1149=>strangers. 
line 1150=>"I  immediately had  a  feeling  that  I was wanted back. Looking behind  I  saw  a 
line 1151=>fire  in  the  distance  and  made  for  it.  So  now  you  know.  Please  be  more  careful, 
line 1152=>next time, or we shall never get anywhere!" 
line 1153=>"Thank you!" said Thorin. 
line 1154=>
line 1155=>####-<h4>Chapter 3 </h4> <br>
line 1156=><br>
line 1157=>A Short Rest 
line 1158=><br>
line 1159=> 
line 1160=>They  did  not  sing  or  tell  stories  that  day,  even  though  the weather  improved; 
line 1161=>nor the next day, nor the day after. They had begun to feel that danger was not far 
line 1162=>away on either side. They camped under the stars, and their horses had more to eat 
line 1163=>than  they had; for there was plenty of grass, but there was not much in their bags, 
line 1164=>even with what  they had got  from  the  trolls. One morning  they  forded a  river at a 
line 1165=>wide  shallow  place  full  of  the  noise  of  stones  and  foam.  The  far  bank  was  steep 
line 1166=>and slippery. When they got to the top of it, leading their ponies, they saw that the 
line 1167=>great mountains had marched down very near to them. Already they I seemed only 
line 1168=>a day's easy journey from the feet of the nearest. Dark and drear it looked, though 
line 1169=>there were patches of sunlight on its brown sides, and behind its shoulders the tips 
line 1170=>of snow-peaks gleamed. 
line 1171=>"Is  that  The  Mountain?"  asked  Bilbo  in  a  solemn  voice,  looking  at  it  with 
line 1172=>round eyes. He had never seen a thing that looked so big before. 
line 1173=>"Of  course  not!"  said  Balin.  "That  is  only  the  beginning  of  the  Misty 
line 1174=>Mountains,  and we  have  to  get  through,  or  over,  or  under  those  somehow,  before 
line 1175=>we  can  come  into  Wilderland  beyond.  And  it  is  a  deal  of  a  way  even  from  the 
line 1176=>other  side  of  them  to  the  Lonely Mountain  in  the  East Where  Smaug  lies on our 
line 1177=>treasure." 
line 1178=>"O!"  said  Bilbo,  and  just  at  that  moment  he  felt  more  fared  than  he  ever 
line 1179=>remembered  feeling  before. He was  thinking  once  again  of  his  comfortable  chair 
line 1180=>before  the  fire  in  his  favourite  sitting-room  in  his  hobbit-hole,  and  of  the  kettle 
line 1181=>singing. Not for the last time! 
line 1182=>Now  Gandalf  led  the  way.  "We  must  not  miss  the  road,  or  we  shall  be  done 
line 1183=>for,"  he  said.  "We  need  food,  for  one  thing,  and  rest  in  reasonable  safety-also it is 
line 1184=>very necessary  to  tackle  the Misty Mountains by  the proper path, or else you will 
line 1185=>get  lost  in  them,  and  have  to  come  back  and  start  at  the  beginning  again  (if  you 
line 1186=>ever get back at all)." 
line 1187=>They asked him where he was making for, and he answered: "You are come to 
line 1188=>the very edge of the Wild, as some of you may know. Hidden somewhere ahead of 
line 1189=>us  is  the  fair valley of Rivendell where Elrond  lives  in  the Last Homely House.  I 
line 1190=>sent a message by my friends, and we are expected." 
line 1191=>That  sounded  nice  and  comforting,  but  they  had  not  got  there  yet,  and  it was 
line 1192=>not  so  easy  as  it  sounds  to  find  the  Last  Homely  House  west  of  the  Mountains. 
line 1193=>
line 1194=>####-There  seemed  to  be  no  trees  and  no  valleys  and  no  hills  to  break  the  ground  in 
line 1195=>front  of  them,  only  one  vast  slope  going  slowly  up  and  up  to meet  the  feet  of  the 
line 1196=>nearest  mountain,  a  wide  land  the  colour  of  heather  and  crumbling  rock,  with 
line 1197=>patches and slashes of grass-green and moss-green showing where water might be. 
line 1198=>Morning  passed,  afternoon  came;  but  in  all  the  silent waste  there was  no  sign 
line 1199=>of  any  dwelling.  They  were  growing  anxious,  for  they  now  saw  that  the  house 
line 1200=>might be hidden almost anywhere between them and the mountains. They came on 
line 1201=>unexpected valleys, narrow with deep sides, that opened suddenly at their feet, and 
line 1202=>they  looked  down  surprised  to  see  trees  below  them  and  running  water  at  the 
line 1203=>bottom.  There  were  gullies  that  they  could  almost  leap  over;  but  very  deep  with 
line 1204=>waterfalls in them. There were dark ravines that one could neither jump nor climb 
line 1205=>into. There were bogs, some of them green pleasant places to look at with flowers 
line 1206=>growing  bright  and  tall;  but  a  pony  that  walked  there  with  a  pack  on  its  back 
line 1207=>would never have come out again. 
line 1208=>It was indeed a much wider land from the ford to the mountains than ever you 
line 1209=>would have guessed. Bilbo was astonished. The only path was marked with white 
line 1210=>stones  some  of  which  were  small,  and  others  were  half  covered  with  moss  or 
line 1211=>heather.  Altogether  it  was  a  very  slow  business  following  the  track,  even  guided 
line 1212=>by Gandalf, who seemed to know his way about pretty well. 
line 1213=>His head and beard wagged  this way and  that as he looked for the stones, and 
line 1214=>they  followed  his  head,  but  they  seemed  no  nearer  to  the  end  of  the  search when 
line 1215=>the day began to fail. Tea-time had long gone by, and it seemed supper-time would 
line 1216=>soon  do  the  same.  There  were  moths  fluttering  about,  and  the  light  became  very 
line 1217=>dim,  for  the  moon  had  not  risen.  Bilbo's  pony  began  to  stumble  over  roots  and 
line 1218=>stones.  They  came  to  the  edge  of  a  steep  fall  in  the  ground  so  suddenly  that 
line 1219=>Gandalf s horse nearly slipped down the slope. 
line 1220=>"Here  it  is  at  last!"  he  called,  and  the  others  gathered  round  him  and  looked 
line 1221=>over the edge. They saw a valley far below. They could hear the voice of hurrying 
line 1222=>water in rocky bed at the bottom; the scent of trees was in the air; and there was a 
line 1223=>light  on  the  valley-side across the water. Bilbo never forgot the way they slithered 
line 1224=>and  slipped  in  the  dusk  down  the  steep  zig-zag  path  into  the  secret  valley  of 
line 1225=>Rivendell. The air grew warmer as  they got  lower, and  the  smell of  the pine-trees 
line 1226=>made  him  drowsy,  so  that  every  now  and  again  he  nodded  and  nearly  fell off, or 
line 1227=>bumped  his  nose  on  the  pony's  neck.  Their  spirits  rose  as  they  went  down  and 
line 1228=>down. The  trees changed  to beech and oak, and hire was a comfortable  feeling  in 
line 1229=>the  twilight. The  last green had  almost  faded out of  the grass, when  they  came  at 
line 1230=>length to an open glade not far above the banks of the stream. 
line 1231=>
line 1232=>####-"Hrnmm!  it  smells  like  elves!"  thought  Bilbo,  and  he  looked  up  at  the  stars. 
line 1233=>They  were  burning  bright  and  blue.  Just  then  there  came  a  burst  of  song  like 
line 1234=>laughter in the trees: 
line 1235=> 
line 1236=>
line 1237=>O! What are you doing, 
line 1238=>And where are you going? 
line 1239=>Your ponies need shoeing! 
line 1240=>The river is flowing! 
line 1241=>O! tra-la-la-lally 
line 1242=>here down in the valley! 
line 1243=> 
