line 1272=> 
line 1273=>
line 1274=>####-So  they  laughed  and  sang  in  the  trees;  and  pretty  fair  nonsense  I  daresay  you 
line 1275=>think  it. Not  that  they would  care  they would only  laugh  all  the more  if you  told 
line 1276=>them  so.  They  were  elves  of  course.  Soon  Bilbo  caught  glimpses  of  them  as  the 
line 1277=>darkness deepened. He loved elves, though he seldom met them; but he was a little 
line 1278=>frightened of  them  too. Dwarves don't get on well with  them. Even decent enough 
line 1279=>dwarves  like  Thorin  and  his  friends  think  them  foolish  (which  is  a  very  foolish 
line 1280=>thing to think), or get annoyed with them. For some elves tease them and laugh at 
line 1281=>them, and most of all at their beards. 
line 1282=>"Well,  well!"  said  a  voice.  "Just  look!  Bilbo  the  hobbit  on  a  pony,  my  dear! 
line 1283=>Isn't it delicious!" 
line 1284=>"Most astonishing wonderful!" 
line 1285=>Then  off  they  went  into  another  song  as  ridiculous  as  the  one  I  have  written 
line 1286=>down  in  full. At  last one, a  tall young  fellow, came out  from  the  trees and bowed 
line 1287=>to Gandalf and to Thorin. 
line 1288=>"Welcome to the valley!" he said. 
line 1289=>"Thank you!"  said Thorin a bit gruffly; but Gandalf was already off his horse 
line 1290=>and among the elves, talking merrily with them. 
line 1291=>"You  are  a  little  out  of  your way,"  said  the  elf:  "that  is,  if  you  are making for 
line 1292=>the only path across the water and to the house beyond. We will set you right, but 
line 1293=>you had best get on foot, until you are over the bridge. Are you going to stay a bit 
line 1294=>and  sing  with  us,  or  will  you  go  straight  on?  Supper  is  preparing  over  there," he 
line 1295=>said. "I can smell the Wood-fires for the cooking." 
line 1296=>Tired as he was, Bilbo would have liked to stay awhile. Elvish singing is not a 
line 1297=>thing  to  miss,  in  June  under  the  stars,  not  if  you  care  for  such  things.  Also  he 
line 1298=>would  have  liked  to  have  a  few  private  words  with  these  people  that  seemed  to 
line 1299=>know  his  name  and  all  about  him,  although  he  had  never  been  them  before.  He 
line 1300=>thought  their  opinion  of  his  adventure might  be  interesting. Elves  know  a  lot  and 
line 1301=>are wondrous  folk  for news, and know what  is going on among the peoples of the 
line 1302=>land,  as  quick  as water  flows,  or  quicker. But  the  dwarves were  all  for  supper  as 
line 1303=>soon  'as  possible  just  then,  and  would  not  stay.  On  they  all  went,  leading  their 
line 1304=>ponies, till they were brought to a good path and so at last to the very brink of the 
line 1305=>river.  It  was  flowing  fast  and  noisily,  as  mountain-streams  do  of  a  summer 
line 1306=>evening, when  sun  has  been  all  day  on  the  snow  far  up  above.  There was  only  a 
line 1307=>narrow bridge of stone without a parapet, as narrow as a pony could well walk on; 
line 1308=>and  over  that  they had  to go, slow and careful, one by one, each  leading his pony 
line 1309=>by  the  bridle. The  elves  had  brought  bright  lanterns  to  the  shore,  and  they  sang  a 
line 1310=>merry song as the party went across. 
line 1311=>
line 1312=>####-"Don't dip your beard in the foam, father!" they cried to Thorin, who was bent 
line 1313=>almost on to his hands and knees. "It is long enough without watering it." 
line 1314=>"Mind  Bilbo  doesn't  eat  all  the  cakes!"  they  called.  "He  is  too  fat  to  get 
line 1315=>through key-holes yet!" 
line 1316=>"Hush,  hush!  Good  People!  and  good  night!"  said  Gandalf,  who  came  last. 
line 1317=>"Valleys have ears, and some elves have over merry tongues. Good night!" 
line 1318=>And  so  at  last  they  all  came  to  the  Last  Homely  House,  and  found  its  doors 
line 1319=>flung wide. 
line 1320=>Now  it  is  a  strange  thing,  but  things  that  are  good  to  have  and  days  that  are 
line 1321=>good  to spend are soon told about, and not much to listen to; while things that are 
line 1322=>uncomfortable, palpitating, and even gruesome, may make a good tale, and take a 
line 1323=>deal of telling anyway. They stayed long in that good house, fourteen days at least, 
line 1324=>and  they  found  it  hard  to  leave.  Bilbo  would  gladly  have  stopped  there  for  ever 
line 1325=>and  ever-even  supposing  a  wish  would  have  taken  him  right  back  to  his  hobbit-
line 1326=>hole without trouble. Yet there is little to tell about their stay.  
line 1327=>The  master  of  the  house  was  an  elf-friend-one  of  those  people whose  fathers 
line 1328=>came  into  the  strange  stories  before  the  beginning  of History,  the wars  of  the  evil 
line 1329=>goblins and the elves and the first men in the North. In those days of our tale there 
line 1330=>were  still  some  people who  had  both  elves  and  heroes  of  the North  for ancestors, 
line 1331=>and Elrond the master of the house was their chief. He was as noble and as fair in 
line 1332=>face  as  an  elf-lord,  as  strong  as  a warrior,  as wise  as  a wizard,  as  venerable  as  a 
line 1333=>king  of  dwarves,  and  as  kind  as  summer. He  comes  into. many  tales, but his part 
line 1334=>in  the  story  of  Bilbo's  great  adventure  is  only  a  small  one,  though  important,  as 
line 1335=>you  will  see,  if  we  ever  get  to  the  end  of  it.  His  house  was  perfect,  whether  you 
line 1336=>liked  food,  or  sleep,  or  work,  or  story-telling,  or  singing,  or  just  sitting  and 
line 1337=>thinking best, or a pleasant mixture of them all. Evil things did not come into that 
line 1338=>valley.  
line 1339=>I wish I had  time  to  tell you even a few of  the  tales or one or  two of  the songs 
line 1340=>that  they  heard  in  that  house. All  of  them,  the  ponies  as well,  grew  refreshed and 
line 1341=>strong  in  a  few  days  there.  Their  clothes  were  mended  as  well  as  their  bruises, 
line 1342=>their tempers and their hopes. Their bags were filled with food and provisions light 
line 1343=>to  carry  but  strong  to  bring  them  over  the  mountain  passes.  Their  plans  were 
line 1344=>improved  with  the  best  advice.  So  the  time  came  to  mid-  summer  eve,  and  they 
line 1345=>were to go on again with the early sun on midsummer morning. 
line 1346=>Elrond  knew  all  about  runes  of  every  kind. That  day  he  looked  at  the  swords 
line 1347=>they had brought from the trolls' lair, and he said: "These are not troll-make. They 
line 1348=>are old swords, very old swords of the High Elves of the West, my kin. They were 
line 1349=>
line 1350=>####-made  in  Gondolin  for  the  Goblin-wars.  They  must  have  come  from  a  dragon's 
line 1351=>hoard  or  goblin  plunder,  for  dragons  and  goblins  destroyed  that  city  many  ages 
line 1352=>ago.  This,  Thorin,  the  runes  name  Orcrist,  the  Goblin-cleaver  in  the  ancient 
line 1353=>tongue  of  Gondolin;  it  was  a  famous  blade.  This,  Gandalf,  was  Glamdring,  Foe-
line 1354=>hammer that the king of Gondolin once wore. Keep them well!" 
line 1355=>"Whence  did  the  trolls  get  them,  I wonder?"  said Thorin  looking at his  sword 
line 1356=>with new interest. 
line 1357=>"I  could  not  say,"  said  Elrond,  "but  one  may  guess  that  your  trolls  had 
line 1358=>plundered other plunderers, or come on the remnants of old robberies in some hold 
line 1359=>in  the mountains  of  the North.  I  have heard  that  there are  still  forgotten  treasures 
line 1360=>of  old  to  be  found  in  the  deserted  caverns  of  the mines  of Moria,  since  the  dwarf 
line 1361=>and goblin war." 
line 1362=>Thorin  pondered  these  words.  "I  will  keep  this  sword  in  honour,"  he  said. 
line 1363=>"May it soon cleave goblins once again!" 
line 1364=>"A  wish  that  is  likely  to  be  granted  soon  enough  in  the  mountains!"  said 
line 1365=>Elrond.  "But  show  me  now  your  map!"  He  took  it  and  gazed  long  at  it,  and  he 
line 1366=>shook  his  head;  for  if  he  did  not  altogether  approve  of  dwarves  and  their  love  of 
line 1367=>gold, he hated dragons and their cruel wickedness, and he grieved to remember the 
line 1368=>ruin  of  the  town  of  Dale  and  its  merry  bells,  and  the  burned  banks  of  the  bright 
line 1369=>River Running. The moon was  shining  in  a  broad  silver  crescent. He  held  up  the 
line 1370=>map  and  the  white  light  shone  through  it.  "What  is  this?"  he  said.  "There  are 
line 1371=>moon-letters  here,  beside  the  plain  runes  which  say  'five  feet  high  the  door  and 
line 1372=>three may walk abreast.' " 
line 1373=>"What  are moon-letters?" asked  the hobbit  full of excitement. He  loved maps, 
line 1374=>as  I  have  told  you  before;  and  he  also  liked  runes  and  letters  and  cunning 
line 1375=>handwriting, though when he wrote himself it was a bit thin and spidery.  
line 1376=>"Moon-letters  are  rune-letters,  but  you  cannot  see  them,"  said  Elrond,  "not 
line 1377=>when  you  look  straight  at  them.  They  can  only  be  seen  when  the  moon  shines 
line 1378=>behind  them,  and what  is more, with  the more  cunning  sort  it must  be  a moon  of 
line 1379=>the  same  shape  and  season  as  the  day  when  they  were  written.  The  dwarves 
line 1380=>invented  them  and  wrote  them  with  silver  pens,  as  your  friends  could  tell  you. 
line 1381=>These  must  have  been  written  on  a midsummer's  eve  in  a  crescent moon,  a  long 
line 1382=>while ago." 
line 1383=>"What  do  they  say?"  asked Gandalf  and Thorin  together,  a  bit  vexed  perhaps 
line 1384=>that even Elrond should have found this out first, though really there had not been 
line 1385=>a  chance  before,  and  there  would  not  have  been  another  until  goodness  knows 
line 1386=>when. 
line 1387=>
line 1388=>####-"Stand  by  the  grey  stone  when  the  thrush  knocks,"  read  Elrond,  "and  the 
line 1389=>setting sun with the last light of Durin's Day will shine upon the key-hole." 
line 1390=>"Durin,  Durin!"  said  Thorin.  "He  was  the  father  of  the  fathers  of  the  eldest 
line 1391=>race of Dwarves, the Longbeards, and my first ancestor: I am his heir." 
line 1392=>"Then what is Durin's Day?" asked Elrond. 
line 1393=>"The  first day of  the dwarves' New Year," said Thorin, "is as all should know 
line 1394=>the first, day of the last moon of Autumn on the threshold of Winter. We still call it 
line 1395=>Durin's  Day  when  the  last  moon  of  Autumn  and  the  sun  are  in  the  sky  together. 
line 1396=>But this will not help us much, I fear, for it passes our skill in these days to guess 
line 1397=>when such a time will come again." 
line 1398=>"That remains to be seen," said Gandalf. "Is there any more writing?" 
line 1399=>"None  to  be  seen  by  this  moon,"  said  Elrond,  and  he  gave  the  map  back  to 
line 1400=>Thorin; and then they went down to the water to see the elves dance and sing upon 
line 1401=>the midsummer's eve. 
line 1402=>The  next  morning  was  a  midsummer's  morning  as  fair  and  fresh  as  could  be 
line 1403=>dreamed: blue sky and never a cloud, and the sun dancing on the water. Now they 
line 1404=>rode away amid songs of farewell and good speed, with their hearts ready for more 
line 1405=>adventure,  and  with  a  knowledge  of  the  road  they  must  follow  over  the  Misty 
line 1406=>Mountains to the land beyond. 
line 1407=>
line 1408=>####-<h4>Chapter 4 </h4> <br>
line 1409=>
line 1410=>Over Hill and Under Hill 
line 1411=>
line 1412=> 
line 1413=>There  were  many  paths  that  led  up  into  those  mountains,  and  many  passes 
line 1414=>over them. But most of the paths were cheats and deceptions and led nowhere or to 
line 1415=>bad ends; and most of the passes were infested by evil things and dreadful dangers. 
line 1416=>The  dwarves  and  the  hobbit,  helped  by  the  wise  advice  of  Elrond  and  the 
line 1417=>knowledge and memory of Gandalf, took the right road to the right pass. 
line 1418=>Long  days  after  they  had  climbed  out  of  the  valley  and  left  the  Last  Homely 
line 1419=>House  miles  behind,  they  were  still  going  up  and  up  and  up.  It  was  a  hard  path 
line 1420=>and  a  dangerous  path,  a  crooked  way  and  a  lonely  and  a  long.  Now  they  could 
line 1421=>look  back  over  the  lands  they  had  left,  laid  out  behind  them  far  below.  Far,  far 
line 1422=>away in the West, where things were blue and faint, Bilbo knew there lay his own 
line 1423=>country  of  safe  and  comfortable  things,  and  his  little  hobbit-hole. He shivered.  It 
line 1424=>was  getting  bitter  cold  up  here,  and  the  wind  came  shrill  among  the  rocks. 
line 1425=>Boulders,  too,  at  times  came  galloping  down  the  mountain-sides,  let  loose  by 
line 1426=>midday  sun  upon  the  snow,  and  passed  among  them  (which  was  lucky),  or  over 
line 1427=>their heads (which was alarming). The nights were comfortless and chill, and they 
line 1428=>did not dare  to sing or  talk  too  loud,  for  the echoes were uncanny, and  the silence 
line 1429=>seemed  to  dislike  being  broken-except by  the noise of water and  the wail of wind 
line 1430=>and the crack of stone. 
line 1431=>"The  summer  is  getting  on  down  below,"  thought  Bilbo,  "and  haymaking  is 
line 1432=>going  on  and  picnics. They will  be  harvesting  and  blackberrying,  before we  even 
line 1433=>begin to go down the other side at this rate." And the others were thinking equally 
line 1434=>gloomy  thoughts,  although  when  they  had  said  good-bye  to  Elrond  in  the  high 
line 1435=>hope  of  a  midsummer  morning,  they'  had  spoken  gaily  of  the  passage  of  the 
line 1436=>mountains,  and  of  riding  swift  across  the  lands  beyond.  They  had  thought  of 
line 1437=>coming  to  the  secret  door  in  the  Lonely  Mountain,  perhaps  that  very  next  first 
line 1438=>moon  of  Autumnâ€”"  and  perhaps  it  will  be  Durin's  Day"  they  had  said.  Only 
line 1439=>Gandalf had  shaken his head  and  said nothing. Dwarves had not passed  that way 
line 1440=>for  many  years,  but  Gandalf  had,  and  he  knew  how  evil  and  danger  had  grown 
line 1441=>and  thriven  in  the Wild, since  the dragons had driven men from the lands, and the 
line 1442=>goblins had spread  in secret after  the battle of  the Mines of Moria. Even  the good 
line 1443=>plans  of  wise  wizards  like  Gandalf  and  of  good  friends  like  Elrond  go  astray 
line 1444=>sometimes when  you  are  off  on  dangerous  adventures  over  the Edge  of  the Wild; 
line 1445=>and Gandalf was a wise enough wizard to know it. 
line 1446=>
line 1447=>####-He  knew  that  something  unexpected  might  happen,  and  he  hardly  dared  to 
line 1448=>hope  that  they  would  pass  without  fearful  adventure  over  those  great  tall 
line 1449=>mountains  with  lonely  peaks  and  valleys  where  no  king  ruled. They did not. All 
line 1450=>was  well,  until  one  day  they  met  a  thunderstorm  -  more  than  a  thunderstorm,  a 
line 1451=>thunder-battle.  You  know  how  terrific  a  really  big  thunderstorm  can  be  down  in 
line 1452=>the  land  and  in  a  river-valley;  especially  at  times  when  two  great  thunderstorms 
line 1453=>meet  and  clash. More  terrible  still  are  thunder  and  lightning  in  the  mountains  at 
line 1454=>night,  when  storms  come  up  from  East  and  West  and  make  war.  The  lightning 
line 1455=>splinters  on  the  peaks,  and  rocks  shiver,  and  great  crashes  split  the  air  and  go 
line 1456=>rolling  and  tumbling  into  every  cave  and  hollow;  and  the  darkness  is  filled  with 
line 1457=>overwhelming noise and sudden light. 
line 1458=>Bilbo had never seen or imagined anything of the kind. They were high up in a 
line 1459=>narrow place, with a dreadful fall into a dim valley at one side of them. There they 
line 1460=>were  sheltering  under  a  hanging  rock  for  the  night,  and  he  lay  beneath  a  blanket 
line 1461=>and  shook  from  head  to  toe. When  he  peeped  out  in  the  lightning-flashes, he saw 
line 1462=>that  across  the  valley  the  stone-giants  were  out  and  were  hurling  rocks  at  one 
line 1463=>another  for a. game, and catching  them, and  tossing  them down  into  the darkness 
line 1464=>where  they  smashed among  the  trees  far below, or  splintered  into  little bits with a 
line 1465=>bang.  Then  came  a  wind  and  a  rain,  and  the  wind  whipped  the  rain  and  the  hail 
line 1466=>about  in  every  direction,  so  that  an  overhanging  rock  was  no  protection  at  all. 
line 1467=>Soon  they were  getting  drenched  and  their  ponies were  standing with  their  heads 
line 1468=>down  and  their  tails  between  their  legs,  and  some  of  them  were  whinnying  with 
line 1469=>fright.  They  could  hear  the  giants  guffawing  and  shouting  all  over  the 
line 1470=>mountainsides. 
line 1471=>"This won't  do  at  all!"  said Thorin.  "If we  don't  get  blown  off  or  drowned,  or 
line 1472=>struck by lightning, we shall be picked up by some giant and kicked sky-high for a 
line 1473=>football." 
line 1474=>"Well,  if  you  know  of  anywhere  better, take us there!" said Gandalf, who was 
line 1475=>feeling very grumpy, and was far from happy about the giants himself. 
line 1476=>The  end of  their  argument was  that  they  sent Fill  and Kili  to  look  for  a better 
line 1477=>shelter. They had very sharp eyes, and being the youngest of the dwarves by some 
line 1478=>fifty  years  they  usually  got  these  sort  of  jobs  (when  everybody  could  see  that  it 
line 1479=>was  absolutely  no  use  sending Bilbo). There  is  nothing  like  looking,  if  you want 
line 1480=>to find something (or so Thorin said to the young dwarves). You certainly usually 
line 1481=>find  something,  if  you  look,  but  it  is  not  always  quite  the  something  you  were 
line 1482=>after. So it proved on this occasion. 
line 1483=>
line 1484=>####-Soon  Fili  and  Kili  came  crawling  back,  holding  on  to  the  rocks  in  the  wind. 
line 1485=>"We have  found a dry cave,"  they said, "not  far  round  the next corner; and ponies 
line 1486=>and all could get inside." 
line 1487=>"Have  you  thoroughly  explored  it?"  said  the wizard, who  knew  that  caves  up 
line 1488=>in the mountains were seldom unoccupied. 
line 1489=>"Yes,  yes!"  they  said,  though  everybody  knew  they  could  not  have  been  long 
line 1490=>about  it;  they had come back too quick. "It isn't all that big, and it does not go far 
line 1491=>back." 
line 1492=>That,  of  course,  is  the  dangerous  part  about  caves:  you  don't  know  how  far 
line 1493=>they  go  back,  sometimes,  or  where  a  passage  behind  may  lead  to,  or  what  is 
line 1494=>waiting for you inside. But now Fili and Kill's news seemed good enough. So they 
line 1495=>all  got  up  and  prepared  to  move.  The  wind  was  howling  and  the  thunder  still 
line 1496=>growling, and  they had a business getting  themselves and  their ponies along. Still 
line 1497=>it was not very far to go, and before long they came to a big rock standing out into 
line 1498=>the path. If you stepped behind, you found a low arch in the side of the mountain. 
line 1499=>There was just room to get the ponies through with a squeeze, when they had been 
line 1500=>unpacked  and  unsaddled.  As  they  passed  under  the  arch,  it was  good  to  hear  the 
line 1501=>wind and the rain outside instead of all about them, and to feel safe from the giants 
line 1502=>and their rocks. But the wizard was taking no risks. He lit up his wand  - as he did 
line 1503=>that  day  in Bilbo's  dining-room  that  seemed  so  long ago,  if you rememberâ€”, and 
line 1504=>by its light they explored the cave from end to end. 
line 1505=>It seemed quite a fair size, but not  too  large and mysterious. It had a dry floor 
line 1506=>and some comfortable nooks. At one end there was room for the ponies; and there 
line 1507=>they stood (mighty glad of the change) steaming, and champing in their nosebags. 
line 1508=>Oin  and Gloin wanted  to  light  a  fire  at  the  door  to  dry  their  clothes,  but Gandalf 
line 1509=>would not hear of  it. So  they  spread out  their wet  things on  the  floor, and got dry 
line 1510=>ones out of  their bundles;  then they made their blankets comfortable, got out their 
line 1511=>pipes  and  blew  smoke  rings,  which  Gandalf  turned  into  different  colours  and  set 
line 1512=>dancing  up  by  the  roof  to  amuse  them.  They  talked  and  talked,  and  forgot  about 
line 1513=>the  storm, and discussed what each would  do with his share of the treasure (when 
