line 1533=>crack,  before  you  could  say  tinder  and  flint.  But  not  Gandalf.  Bilbo's  yell  had 
line 1534=>done  that  much  good.  It  had  wakened  him  up  wide  in  a  splintered  second,  and 
line 1535=>when  goblins  came  to  grab  him,  there  was  a  terrible  flash  like  lightning  in  the 
line 1536=>cave, a smell like gunpowder, and several of them fell dead. 
line 1537=>The  crack  closed with  a  snap,  and  Bilbo  and  the  dwarves were  on  the wrong 
line 1538=>side  of  it! Where was Gandalf? Of  that neither they nor the goblins had any idea, 
line 1539=>and  the  goblins  did  not  wait  to  find  out.  It  was  deep,  deep,  dark,  such  as  only 
line 1540=>goblins  that  have  taken  to  living  in  the  heart  of  the  mountains  can  see  through. 
line 1541=>The  passages  there  were  crossed  and  tangled  in  all  directions,  but  the  goblins 
line 1542=>knew  their  way,  as  well  as  you  do  to  the  nearest  post-office;  and  the  way  went 
line 1543=>down and down, and it was most horribly stuffy. The goblins were very rough, and 
line 1544=>pinched  unmercifully,  and  chuckled  and  laughed  in  their  horrible  stony  voices; 
line 1545=>and Bilbo was more  unhappy  even  than when  the  troll  had  picked  him  up  by  his 
line 1546=>toes.  He  wished  again  and  again  for  his  nice  bright  hobbit-hole. Not  for  the  last 
line 1547=>time. 
line 1548=>Now  there  came  a  glimmer  of  a  red  light  before  them.  The  goblins  began  to 
line 1549=>sing,  or  croak,  keeping  time  with  the  flap  of  their  flat  feet  on  the  stone,  and 
line 1550=>shaking their prisoners as well. 
