line 1585=>I  am  afraid  that  was  the  last  they  ever  saw  of  those  excellent  little  ponies, 
line 1586=>including  a  jolly  sturdy  little  white  fellow  that  Elrond  had  lent  to  Gandalf,  since 
line 1587=>his  horse  was  not  suitable  for  the  mountain-paths.  For  goblins  eat  horses  and 
line 1588=>ponies  and  donkeys  (and  other much more  dreadful  things),  and  they are always 
line 1589=>hungry.  Just  now  however  the  prisoners  were  thinking  only  of  themselves.  The 
line 1590=>goblins  chained  their  hands  behind  their  backs  and  linked  them  all  together  in  a 
line 1591=>line  and dragged  them  to  the  far  end of  the  cavern with  little Bilbo  tugging  at the 
line 1592=>end of the row.  
line 1593=>There in the shadows on a large flat stone sat a tremendous goblin with a huge 
line 1594=>head,  and  armed  goblins were  standing  round  him  carrying  the  axes  and  the  bent 
line 1595=>swords that they use. Now goblins are cruel, wicked, and bad-hearted. They make 
line 1596=>no beautiful things, but they make many clever ones. They can tunnel and mine as 
line 1597=>well as any but the most skilled dwarves, when they take the trouble, though they 
line 1598=>are  usually  untidy  and  dirty.  Hammers,  axes,  swords,  daggers,  pickaxes,  tongs, 
line 1599=>and  also  instruments of  torture,  they make very well, or get other people  to make 
line 1600=>to  their design, prisoners and  slaves  that have  to work  till  they die  for want of air 
line 1601=>
line 1602=>####-and light. It is not unlikely that they invented some of the machines that have since 
line 1603=>troubled  the  world,  especially  the  ingenious  devices  for  killing  large  numbers  of 
line 1604=>people at once, for wheels and engines and explosions always delighted them, and 
line 1605=>also  not  working  with  their  own  hands  more  than  they  could  help;  but  in  those 
line 1606=>days  and  those  wild  parts  they had not  advanced  (as  it  is  called)  so  far. They did 
line 1607=>not  hate  dwarves  especially,  no  more  than  they  hated  everybody  and  everything, 
line 1608=>and  particularly  the  orderly  and  prosperous;  in  some  parts  wicked  dwarves  had 
line 1609=>even  made  alliances  with  them.  But  they  had  a  special  grudge  against  Thorin's 
line 1610=>people,  because  of  the war which  you  have  heard mentioned,  but which  does  not 
line 1611=>come  into  this  tale; and anyway goblins don't care who  they catch, as  long as  it  is 
line 1612=>done smart and secret, and the prisoners are not able to defend themselves. 
line 1613=>"Who are these miserable persons?" said the Great Goblin. 
line 1614=>"Dwarves, and this!" said one of the drivers, pulling at Bilbo's chain so that he 
line 1615=>fell forward onto his knees. 
line 1616=>"We found them sheltering in our Front Porch." 
line 1617=>"What do you mean by it?" said the Great Goblin turning to Thorin. "Up to no 
line 1618=>good, I'll warrant! Spying on the private business of my people, I guess! Thieves, I 
line 1619=>shouldn't  be  surprised  to  learn!  Murderers  and  friends  of  Elves,  not  unlikely! 
line 1620=>Come! What have you got to say?" 
line 1621=>"Thorin  the  dwarf  at  your  service!"  he  replied-it was merely a polite nothing. 
line 1622=>"Of the things which you suspect and imagine we had no idea at all. We sheltered 
line 1623=>from  a  storm  in what  seemed  a  convenient  cave  and  unused;  nothing was  further 
line 1624=>from  our  thoughts  than  inconveniencing goblins  in any way whatever." That was 
line 1625=>true enough! 
line 1626=>"Urn!"  said  the Great Goblin.  "So you  say! Might  I  ask what you were doing 
line 1627=>up in the mountains at all, and where you were coming from, and where you were 
line 1628=>going to? In fact I should like to know all about you. Not that it willdo you much 
line 1629=>good,  Thorin  Oakenshield,  I  know  too  much  about  your  folk  already;  but  let's 
