line 1711=>At  this  point  Gandalf  fell  behind,  and  Thorin  with  him.  They  turned  a  sharp 
line 1712=>corner. "About turn!" he shouted. "Draw your sword, Thorin!" 
line 1713=>There was nothing else  to be done; and  the goblins did not  like  it. They came 
line 1714=>scurrying  round  the corner  in  full cry, and  found Goblin-cleaver and Foe-hammer 
line 1715=>
line 1716=>####-shining  cold  and  bright  right  in  their  astonished  eyes.  The  ones  in  front  dropped 
line 1717=>their  torches  and  gave  one  yell  before  they  were  killed.  The  ones  behind  yelled 
line 1718=>still  more,  and  leaped  back  knocking  over  those  that  were  running  after  them. 
line 1719=>"Biter  and Beater!"  they  shrieked;  and  soon  they were  all  in  confusion,  and most 
line 1720=>of them were hustling back the way they had come. 
line 1721=>It was quite a  long while before any of  them dared  to  turn  that comer. By  that 
line 1722=>time the dwarves had gone on again, a long, long, way on into the dark tunnels of 
line 1723=>the  goblins'  realm.  When  the  goblins  discovered  that,  they  put  out  their  torches 
line 1724=>and they slipped on soft shoes, and they chose out their very quickest runners with 
line 1725=>the sharpest ears and eyes. These ran forward, as swift as weasels in the dark,  and 
line 1726=>with hardly any more noise than bats. 
line 1727=>That  is  why  neither  Bilbo,  nor  the  dwarves,  nor  even  Gandalf  heard  them 
line 1728=>coming. Nor did they see them. But they were seen by the goblins that ran silently 
line 1729=>up  behind,  for  Gandalf  was  letting  his  wand  give  out  a  faint  light  to  help  the 
line 1730=>dwarves as they went along. 
line 1731=>Quite suddenly Dori, now at the back again carrying Bilbo, was grabbed from 
line 1732=>behind in the dark. He shouted and fell; and the hobbit rolled off his shoulders into 
line 1733=>the blackness, bumped his head on hard rock, and remembered nothing more. 
line 1734=> 
line 1735=>
line 1736=>####-<h4>Chapter 5 </h4> <br>
line 1737=>
line 1738=>Riddles in the Dark 
line 1739=>
line 1740=> 
line 1741=>When Bilbo opened his eyes, he wondered  if he had; for  it was  just as dark as 
line 1742=>with them shut. No one was anywhere near him. Just imagine his fright! He could 
line 1743=>hear nothing, see nothing, and he could feel nothing except the stone of the floor.  
line 1744=>Very slowly he got up and groped about on all fours, till he touched the wall of 
line 1745=>the  tunnel;  but  neither  up  nor  down  it  could  he  find  anything:  nothing  at  all,  no 
line 1746=>sign of goblins, no sign of dwarves. His head was swimming, and he was far from 
line 1747=>certain  even  of  the  direction  they  had  been  going  in  when  he  had  his  fall.  He 
line 1748=>guessed  as well  as  he  could,  and  crawled  along  for  a  good way,  till  suddenly  his 
line 1749=>hand met what felt like a tiny ring of cold metal lying on the floor of the tunnel. It 
line 1750=>was  a  turning  point  in  his  career,  but  he  did  not  know  it.  He  put  the  ring  in  his 
line 1751=>pocket  almost without  thinking;  certainly  it  did  not  seem  of  any  particular  use  at 
line 1752=>the moment. He did not go much  further, but sat down on  the cold  floor and gave 
line 1753=>himself  up  to  complete  miserableness,  for  a  long  while.  He  thought  of  himself 
line 1754=>frying bacon and eggs  in his own kitchen at home  - for he could feel inside that it 
line 1755=>was high time for some meal or other; but that only made him miserabler.  
line 1756=>He could not think what to do; nor could he think what had happened; or why 
line 1757=>he  had  been  left  behind;  or  why,  if  he  had  been  left  behind,  the  goblins  had  not 
line 1758=>caught  him;  or  even  why  his  head  was  so  sore.  The  truth  was  he  had  been  lying 
line 1759=>quiet, out of sight and out of mind, in a very dark corner for a long while. 
line 1760=>After some time he felt for his pipe. It was not broken, and that was something. 
line 1761=>Then  he  felt  for  his  pouch,  and  there  was  some  tobacco  in  it,  and  that  was 
line 1762=>something more. Then he felt for matches and he could not find any at all, and that 
line 1763=>shattered his hopes completely. Just as well for him, as he agreed when he came to 
line 1764=>his senses. Goodness knows what the striking of matches and the smell of tobacco 
line 1765=>would  have  brought  on  him  out  of  dark  holes  in  that  horrible  place.  Still  at  the 
line 1766=>moment he felt very crushed. But in slapping all his pockets and feeling all round 
line 1767=>himself  for matches his hand came on  the hilt of his  little sword  - the little dagger 
line 1768=>that he got from the trolls, and that he had quite forgotten; nor do the goblins seem 
line 1769=>to have noticed it, as he wore it inside his breeches. 
line 1770=>Now  he  drew  it  out.  It  shone  pale  and  dim  before  his  eyes.  "So  it  is  an  elvish 
line 1771=>blade, too," he thought; "and goblins are not very near, and yet not far enough." 
line 1772=>But  somehow  he was  comforted.  It was  rather  splendid  to be wearing  a blade 
line 1773=>made  in Gondolin for  the goblin-wars of which so many songs had sung; and also 
line 1774=>
line 1775=>####-he  had  noticed  that  such  weapons made  a  great  impression  on  goblins  that  came 
line 1776=>upon them suddenly.  
line 1777=>"Go  back?"  he  thought.  "No  good  at  all!  Go  sideways?  Impossible!  Go 
line 1778=>forward? Only  thing  to  do! On we  go!"  So  up  he  got,  and  trotted  along with  his 
line 1779=>little sword held in front of him and one hand feeling the wall, and his heart all of 
line 1780=>a patter and a pitter.  
line 1781=> 
line 1782=>Now  certainly  Bilbo  was  in  what  is  called  a  tight  place.  But  you  must 
line 1783=>remember  it  was  not  quite  so  tight  for  him  as  it  would  have  been  for  me  or  for 
line 1784=>you. Hobbits are not quite like ordinary people; and after all if their holes are nice 
line 1785=>cheery  places  and  properly  aired,  quite  different  from  the  tunnels  of  the  goblins, 
line 1786=>still they are more used to tunnelling than we are, and they do not easily lose their 
line 1787=>sense  of  direction  underground-not  when  their  heads  have  recovered  from  being 
line 1788=>bumped.  Also  they  can  move  very  quietly,  and  hide  easily,  and  recover 
line 1789=>wonderfully  from  falls  and  bruises,  and  they  have  a  fund  of  wisdom  and  wise 
line 1790=>sayings that men have mostly never heard or have forgotten long ago. 
line 1791=>I  should  not  have  liked  to  have  been  in Mr. Baggins'  place,  all  the  same. The 
line 1792=>tunnel seemed to have no end. All he knew was that it was still going down pretty 
line 1793=>steadily  and  keeping  in  the  same  direction  in  spite  of  a  twist  and  a  turn  or  two. 
line 1794=>There were passages leading off to the side every now and then, as he knew by the 
line 1795=>glimmer of his sword, or  could feel with his hand on the wall. Of these he took no 
line 1796=>notice,  except  to  hurry  past  for  fear  of  goblins  or  half-imagined  dark  things 
line 1797=>coming out of them. On and on he went, and down and down; and still he heard no 
line 1798=>sound of anything except  the occasional  whirr of a bat by his ears, which  startled 
line 1799=>him at first, till it became too frequent to bother about. I do not know how long he 
line 1800=>kept  on  like  this,  hating  to  go  on,  not  daring  to  stop,  on,  on,  until  he was  tireder 
line 1801=>than tired. It seemed like all the way to tomorrow and over it to the days beyond. 
line 1802=>Suddenly  without  any  warning  he  trotted  splash  into  water!  Ugh!  it  was  icy 
line 1803=>cold. That  pulled  him  up  sharp  and  short. He  did  not  know whether  it was  just  a 
line 1804=>pool in the path, or the edge of an underground stream that crossed the passage, or 
line 1805=>the  brink  of  a  deep  dark  subterranean  lake.  The  sword was  hardly  shining  at  all. 
line 1806=>He  stopped,  and  he  could  hear,  when  he  listened  hard,  drops  drip-drip-dripping 
line 1807=>from an unseen roof into the water below; but there seemed no other sort of sound. 
line 1808=>"So  it  is  a  pool  or  a  lake,  and  not  an  underground  river,"  he  thought.  Still  he 
line 1809=>did  not  dare  to  wade  out  into  the  darkness.  He  could  not  swim;  and  he  thought, 
line 1810=>too,  of  nasty  slimy  things,  with  big  bulging  blind  eyes,  wriggling  in  the  water. 
line 1811=>There  are  strange  things  living  in  the  pools  and  lakes  in  the  hearts  of mountains: 
line 1812=>
line 1813=>####-fish whose fathers swam in, goodness only knows how many years ago, and never 
line 1814=>swam out again, while their eyes grew bigger and bigger and bigger from trying to 
line 1815=>see  in  the  blackness;  also  there  are other  things more  slimy  than  fish. Even  in  the 
line 1816=>tunnels  and  caves  the  goblins  have  made  for  themselves  there  are  other  things 
line 1817=>living unbeknown to them that have sneaked in from outside to lie up in the dark. 
line 1818=>Some  of  these  caves,  too,  go  back  in  their  beginnings  to  ages  before  the  goblins, 
line 1819=>who  only  widened  them  and  joined  them  up  with  passages,  and  the  original 
line 1820=>owners are still there in odd comers, slinking and nosing about. 
line 1821=>Deep down here by  the dark water  lived old Gollum, a small slimy creature. I 
line 1822=>don't  know where  he  came  from,  nor who  or what  he was. He was Gollum  â€” as 
line 1823=>dark  as  darkness,  except  for  two  big  round  pale  eyes  in  his  thin  face.  He  had  a 
line 1824=>little boat, and he rowed about quite quietly on the lake; for lake it was, wide and 
line 1825=>deep  and  deadly  cold.  He  paddled  it  with  large  feet  dangling  over  the  side,  but 
line 1826=>never a ripple did he make. Not he. He was looking out of his pale lamp-like eyes 
line 1827=>for  blind  fish,  which  he  grabbed  with  his  long  fingers  as  quick  as  thinking.  He 
line 1828=>liked  meat  too.  Goblin  he  thought  good,  when  he  could  get  it;  but  he  took  care 
line 1829=>they  never  found  him  out.  He  just  throttled  them  from  behind,  if  they  ever  came 
line 1830=>down  alone  anywhere  near  the  edge  of  the  water,  while  he  was  prowling  about. 
line 1831=>They  very  seldom  did,  for  they  had  a  feeling  that  something  unpleasant  was 
line 1832=>lurking down there, down at the very roots of the mountain. They had come on the 
line 1833=>lake, when  they were  tunnelling down  long ago, and  they  found  they could go no 
line 1834=>further;  so  there  their  road  ended  in  that  direction,  and  there was no  reason  to go 
line 1835=>that  way-unless  the  Great  Goblin  sent  them.  Sometimes  he  took  a  fancy  for  fish 
line 1836=>from the lake, and sometimes neither goblin nor fish came back. 
line 1837=>Actually Gollum  lived on a slimy  island of  rock  in  the middle of  the  lake. He 
line 1838=>was  watching  Bilbo  now  from  the  distance  with  his  pale  eyes  like  telescopes. 
line 1839=>Bilbo could not see him, but he was wondering a lot about Bilbo, for he could see 
line 1840=>that he was no goblin at all. 
line 1841=>Gollum got  into his boat  and  shot off  from  the  island, while Bilbo was  sitting 
line 1842=>on  the  brink  altogether  flummoxed  and  at  the  end  of  his  way  and  his  wits. 
line 1843=>Suddenly up came Gollum and whispered and hissed: 
line 1844=>"Bless  us  and  splash  us, my  precioussss!  I  guess  it's  a  choice  feast;  at  least  a 
line 1845=>tasty morsel  it'd make  us,  gollum!" And when  he  said gollum he made a horrible 
line 1846=>swallowing  noise  in  his  throat.  That  is  how  he  got  his  name,  though  he  always 
line 1847=>called himself 'my precious.' 
line 1848=>The  hobbit  jumped  nearly  out  of  his  skin when  the  hiss  came  in  his  ears,  and 
line 1849=>he suddenly saw the pale eyes sticking out at him. 
line 1850=>
line 1851=>####-"Who are you?" he said, thrusting his dagger in front of him. 
line 1852=>"What iss he, my preciouss?" whispered Gollum (who always spoke to himself 
line 1853=>through  never  having  anyone  else  to  speak  to). This  is what  he  had  come  to  find 
line 1854=>out,  for  he was  not  really  very  hungry  at  the moment, only  curious; otherwise he 
line 1855=>would have grabbed first and whispered afterwards. 
line 1856=>"I  am Mr. Bilbo Baggins.  I  have  lost  the  dwarves  and  I  have  lost  the wizard, 
line 1857=>and I don't know where I am; and "I don't want to know, if only I can get ,away." 
line 1858=>"What's  he  got  in  his  handses?"  said Gollum,  looking  at  the  sword, which  he 
line 1859=>did not quite like. 
line 1860=>"A sword, a blade which came out of Gondolin!" 
line 1861=>"Sssss,"  said  Gollum,  and  became  quite  polite.  "Praps  ye  sits  here  and  chats 
line 1862=>with  it  a  bitsy,  my  preciousss.  It  like  riddles,  praps  it  does,  does  it?"  He  was 
line 1863=>anxious  to  appear  friendly,  at  any  rate  for  the  moment,  and  until  he  found  out 
line 1864=>more  about  the  sword  and  the  hobbit, whether  he was  quite  alone  really, whether 
line 1865=>he  was  good  to  eat,  and  whether  Gollum  was  really  hungry.  Riddles were  all  he 
line 1866=>could  think  of.  Asking  them,  and  sometimes  guessing  them,  had  been  the  only 
line 1867=>game  he  had  ever  played  with  other  funny  creatures  sitting  in  their  holes  in  the 
line 1868=>long, long ago, before he lost all his friends and was driven away, alone, and crept 
line 1869=>down, down, into the dark under the mountains. 
line 1870=>"Very  well,"  said  Bilbo,  who  was  anxious  to  agree,  until  he  found  out  more 
line 1871=>about  the  creature, whether  he was  quite  alone, whether  he was  fierce  or  hungry, 
line 1872=>and whether he was a friend of the goblins. 
line 1873=>"You ask first," he said, because he had not had time to think of a riddle. 
line 1874=>So Gollum hissed: 
line 1875=> 
line 1876=>
line 1877=>What has roots as nobody sees, 
line 1878=>Is taller than trees, 
line 1879=>Up, up it goes, 
line 1880=>And yet never grows?  
line 1881=>
line 1882=> 
line 1883=>"Easy!" said Bilbo. "Mountain, I suppose." 
line 1884=>"Does  it  guess  easy?  It  must  have  a  competition  with  us,  my  preciouss!  If 
line 1885=>precious asks, and it doesn't answer, we eats it, my preciousss. If it asks us, and we 
line 1886=>doesn't answer, then we does what it wants, eh? We shows it the way out, yes!" 
line 1887=>"All  right!" said Bilbo, not daring  to disagree, and nearly bursting his brain to 
line 1888=>think of riddles that could save him from being eaten. 
line 1889=> 
line 1890=>
line 1891=>Thirty white horses on a red hill, 
line 1892=>
line 1893=>####-First they champ, 
line 1894=>Then they stamp, 
line 1895=>Then they stand still. 
line 1896=>
line 1897=> 
line 1898=>That was all he could think of to ask-the idea of eating was rather on his mind. 
line 1899=>It was rather an old one, too, and Gollum knew the answer as well as you do. 
line 1900=>"Chestnuts,  chestnuts,"  he  hissed.  "Teeth!  teeth!  my  preciousss;  but  we  has 
line 1901=>only six!" Then he asked his second: 
line 1902=> 
line 1903=>
line 1904=>Voiceless it cries, 
line 1905=>Wingless flutters, 
line 1906=>Toothless bites, 
line 1907=>Mouthless mutters. 
line 1908=>
line 1909=> 
line 1910=>"Half  a  moment!"  cried  Bilbo,  who  was  still  thinking  uncomfortably  about 
line 1911=>eating.  Fortunately  he  had  once  heard  something  rather  like  this  before,  and 
line 1912=>getting  his  wits  back  he  thought  of  the  answer.  "Wind,  wind  of  course,"  he  said, 
line 1913=>and  he was  so  pleased  that  he made  up  one  on  the  spot.  "This'll  puzzle  the  nasty 
line 1914=>little underground creature," he thought: 
line 1915=> 
line 1916=>
line 1917=>An eye in a blue face 
line 1918=>Saw an eye in a green face. 
line 1919=>"That eye is like to this eye"  
line 1920=>Said the first eye, 
line 1921=>"But in low place, 
line 1922=>Not in  high place."  
line 1923=>
line 1924=> 
line 1925=>"Ss, ss, ss," said Gollum. He had been underground a long long time, and was 
line 1926=>forgetting  this  sort  of  thing.  But  just  as  Bilbo  was  beginning  to  hope  that  the 
line 1927=>wretch  would  not  be  able  to  answer,  Gollum  brought  up  memories  of  ages  and 
line 1928=>ages and ages before, when he lived with his grandmother in a hole in a bank by a 
line 1929=>river, "Sss, sss, my preciouss," he said. "Sun on the daisies it means, it does." 
line 1930=>But  these  ordinary  aboveground  everyday  sort  of  riddles  were  tiring  for  him. 
line 1931=>Also  they  reminded  him  of  days  when  he  had  been  less  lonely  and  sneaky  and 
line 1932=>nasty, and that put him out of temper. What is more they made him hungry; so this 
line 1933=>time he tried something a bit more difficult and more unpleasant: 
line 1934=> 
line 1935=>
line 1936=>It cannot be seen, cannot be felt, 
line 1937=>Cannot be heard, cannot be smelt. 
line 1938=>
line 1939=>####-It lies behind stars and under hills, 
line 1940=>And empty holes it fills. 
line 1941=>It comes first and follows after,  
line 1942=>Ends life, kills laughter.  
line 1943=>
line 1944=> 
line 1945=>Unfortunately  for  Gollum  Bilbo  had  heard  that  sort  of  thing  before;  and  the 
line 1946=>answer  was  all  round  him  anyway.  "Dark!"  he  said  without  even  scratching  his 
line 1947=>head or putting on his thinking cap. 
line 1948=> 
line 1949=>
line 1950=>A box without hinges, key, or lid, 
line 1951=>Yet golden treasure inside is hid, 
line 1952=>
line 1953=> 
line 1954=>he asked  to gain  time, until he could  think of a really hard one. This he  thought a 
line 1955=>dreadfully  easy  chestnut,  though  he  had  not  asked  it  in  the  usual  words.  But  it 
line 1956=>proved a nasty poser for Gollum. He hissed to himself, and still he did not answer; 
line 1957=>he whispered and spluttered. 
line 1958=>After  some  while  Bilbo  became  impatient.  "Well,  what  is  it?"  he  said.  "The 
line 1959=>answer's  not  a  kettle  boiling  over,  as  you  seem  to  think  from  the  noise  you  are 
line 1960=>making." 
line 1961=>"Give us a chance; let it give us a chance, my preciouss-ss-ss." 
line 1962=>"Well," said Bilbo, after giving him a long chance, "what about your guess?" 
line 1963=>But  suddenly  Gollum  remembered  thieving  from  nests  long  ago,  and  sitting 
line 1964=>under  the  river bank  teaching his grandmother,  teaching his grandmother  to suck-
line 1965=>"Eggses!" he hissed. "Eggses it is!" Then he asked: 
line 1966=> 
line 1967=>
line 1968=>A live without breath, 
line 1969=>As cold as death; 
line 1970=>Never thirsty, ever drinking, 
line 1971=>All in mail never clinking. 
line 1972=>
line 1973=> 
line 1974=>He  also  in  his  turn  thought  this  was  a  dreadfully  easy  one,  because  he  was 
line 1975=>always  thinking  of  the  answer. But  he  could  not  remember  anything  better  at  the 
line 1976=>moment,  he was  so  flustered  by  the  egg-question. All  the  same  it was  a poser  for 
line 1977=>poor  Bilbo,  who  never  had  anything  to  do  with  the  water  if  he  could  help  it.  I 
line 1978=>imagine you know the answer, of course, or can guess it as easy as winking, since 
line 1979=>you  are  sitting  comfortably  at  home  and  have  not  the  danger  of  being  eaten  to 
line 1980=>disturb  your  thinking.  Bilbo  sat  and  cleared  his  throat  once  or  twice,  but  no 
line 1981=>answer came. 
line 1982=>
line 1983=>####-After  a  while  Gollum  began  to  hiss  with  pleasure  to  himself:  "Is  it  nice,  my 
line 1984=>preciousss? Is it juicy? Is it scrumptiously crunchable?" He began to peer at Bilbo 
line 1985=>out of the darkness. 
line 1986=>"Half  a  moment,"  said  the  hobbit  shivering.  "I  gave  you  a  good  long  chance 
line 1987=>just now." 
line 1988=>"It must make  haste,  haste!"  said Gollum,  beginning  to  climb  out  of  his  boat 
line 1989=>on to the shore to get at Bilbo. But when he put his long webby foot in the water, a 
line 1990=>fish jumped out in a fright and fell on Bilbo's toes. 
line 1991=>"Ugh!"  he  said,  "it  is  cold  and  clammy!"-and  so  he  guessed.  "Fish!  Fish!"  he 
line 1992=>cried. "It is fish!" 
line 1993=>Gollum was  dreadfully  disappointed;  but Bilbo  asked  another  riddle  as  quick 
line 1994=>as ever be could, so that Gollum had to get back into his boat and think. 
line 1995=> 
line 1996=>No-legs lay on one-leg, two-legs sat near on three-legs, four-legs got some. 
line 1997=> 
line 1998=>It was not really the right time for this riddle, but Bilbo was in a hurry. Gollum 
line 1999=>might  have  had  some  trouble  guessing  it,  if  he  had  asked  it  at  another time. As it 
line 2000=>was,  talking  of  fish,  "no-legs" was not so very difficult, and after that the rest was 
line 2001=>easy. "Fish on a  little  table, man at  table sitting on a stool,  the cat has  the bones"-
line 2002=>that  of  course  is  the  answer,  and  Gollum  soon  gave  it.  Then  he  thought  the  time 
line 2003=>had come to ask something hard and horrible. This is what he said: 
line 2004=> 
line 2005=>
line 2006=>This thing all things devours:  
line 2007=>Birds, beasts, trees, flowers;  
line 2008=>Gnaws iron, bites steel; 
line 2009=>Grinds hard stones to meal; 
line 2010=>Slays king, ruins town, 
line 2011=>And beats high mountain down. 
line 2012=>
line 2013=> 
line 2014=>Poor  Bilbo  sat  in  the  dark  thinking  of  all  the  horrible  names  of  all  the  giants 
line 2015=>and ogres he had ever heard told of in tales, but not one of them had done all these 
line 2016=>things.  He  had  a  feeling  that  the  answer  was  quite  different  and  that  he  ought  to 
line 2017=>know it, but he could not think of it. He began to get frightened, and that is bad for 
line 2018=>thinking.  Gollum  began  to  get  out  of  his  boat.  He  flapped  into  the  water  and 
line 2019=>paddled  to  the  bank;  Bilbo  could  see  his  eyes  coming  towards  him.  His  tongue 
line 2020=>seemed  to  stick  in  his mouth; he wanted  to  shout out:  "Give me more  time! Give 
line 2021=>me time!" But all that came out with a sudden squeal was: 
line 2022=>"Time! Time!" 
line 2023=>
line 2024=>####-Bilbo was saved by pure luck. For that of course was the answer.  
line 2025=>Gollum was  disappointed  once more;  and  now  he was  getting  angry,  and also 
line 2026=>tired  of  the  game.  It  had made  him  very  hungry  indeed.  This  time  he  did  not  go 
line 2027=>back  to  the  boat.  He  sat  down  in  the  dark  by  Bilbo.  That  made  the  hobbit  most 
line 2028=>dreadfully uncomfortable and scattered his wits. 
line 2029=>"It's  got  to  ask  uss  a  quesstion, my  preciouss, yes, yess, yesss.  Jusst one more 
line 2030=>quesstion to guess, yes, yess," said Gollum. 
line 2031=>But  Bilbo  simply  could  not  think  of  any  question  with  that  nasty  wet  cold 
line 2032=>thing  sitting  next  to  him,  and  pawing  and  poking  him.  He  scratched  himself,  he 
line 2033=>pinched himself; still he could not think of anything. 
line 2034=>"Ask us! ask us!" said Gollum. 
line 2035=>Bilbo  pinched  himself  and  slapped  himself;  he  gripped  on  his  little  sword;  he 
line 2036=>even felt  in his pocket with his other hand. There he found  the ring he had picked 
line 2037=>up in the passage and forgotten about. 
line 2038=>"What have I got in my pocket?" he said aloud. He was talking to himself, but 
line 2039=>Gollum thought it was a riddle, and he was frightfully upset. 
line 2040=>"Not fair! not fair!" he hissed. "It isn't fair, my precious, is it, to ask us what it's 
line 2041=>got in its nassty little pocketses?" 
line 2042=>Bilbo seeing what had happened and having nothing better  to ask stuck  to his 
line 2043=>question. "What have I got in my pocket?" he said louder.  
line 2044=>"S-s-s-s-s,"  hissed  Gollum.  "It  must  give  us  three  guesseses,  my  preciouss, 
line 2045=>three guesseses." 
line 2046=>"Very well! Guess away!" said Bilbo. 
line 2047=>"Handses!" said Gollum. 
line 2048=>"Wrong," said Bilbo, who had luckily just taken his hand 
line 2049=>out again. "Guess again!" 
line 2050=>"S-s-s-s-s,"  said Gollum more  upset  than  ever. He  thought  of  all  the  things  he 
line 2051=>kept  in  his  own  pockets:  fishbones,  goblins'  teeth, wet  shells,  a  bit  of  bat-wing, a 
line 2052=>sharp stone to sharpen his fangs on, and other nasty things. He tried to think what 
line 2053=>other people kept in their pockets. 
line 2054=>"Knife!" he said at last. 
line 2055=>"Wrong!" said Bilbo, who had lost his some time ago. "Last guess!" 
line 2056=>Now Gollum was  in  a much worse  state  than when  Bilbo  had  asked  him  the 
line 2057=>egg-question.  He  hissed  and  spluttered  and  rocked  himself  backwards  and 
line 2058=>forwards, and slapped his feet on the floor, and wriggled and squirmed; but still he 
line 2059=>did not dare to waste his last guess. 
line 2060=>
