line 2310=>Bilbo was  dreadfully  frightened,  but  he  had  the  sense  to  understand what  had 
line 2311=>happened and to sneak behind a big barrel which held drink for the goblin-guards, 
line 2312=>and  so  get  out  of  the  way  and  avoid  being  bumped  into,  trampled  to  death,  or 
line 2313=>caught by feel. 
line 2314=>"I must  get  to  the  door,  I must  get  to  the  door!"  he  kept  on  saying  to  himself, 
line 2315=>but  it was  a  long  time  before  he ventured  to  try. Then  it was  like a horrible game 
line 2316=>of  blind-man's  buff.  The  place  was  full  of  goblins  running  about,  and  the  poor 
line 2317=>little  hobbit  dodged  this  way  and  that,  was  knocked  over  by  a  goblin  who  could 
line 2318=>not  make  out  what  he  had  bumped  into,  scrambled  away  on  all  fours,  slipped 
line 2319=>between the legs of the captain just in time, got up, and ran for the door.  
line 2320=>It  was  still  ajar,  but  a  goblin  had  pushed  it  nearly  to.  Bilbo  struggled  but  he 
line 2321=>could  not  move  it.  He  tried  to  squeeze  through  the  crack.  He  squeezed  and 
line 2322=>
line 2323=>####-squeezed, and he  stuck!  It was awful. His buttons had got wedged on  the edge of 
line 2324=>the  door  and  the  door-post.  He  could  see  outside  into  the  open  air:  there  were  a 
line 2325=>few  steps  running  down  into  a  narrow  valley  between  tall  mountains;  the  sun 
line 2326=>came  out  from  behind  a  cloud  and  shone  bright  on  the  outside  of  the  door-but he 
line 2327=>could not get through. 
line 2328=>Suddenly  one  of  the  goblins  inside  shouted:  "There  is  a  shadow  by  the  door. 
line 2329=>Something is outside!" 
line 2330=>Bilbo's  heart  jumped  into  his mouth. He  gave  a  terrific  squirm. Buttons burst 
line 2331=>off in all directions. He was through, with a torn coat and waistcoat, leaping down 
line 2332=>the steps  like a goat, while bewildered goblins were still picking up his nice brass 
line 2333=>buttons on the doorstep. 
line 2334=>Of course they soon came down after him, hooting and hallooing, and hunting 
line 2335=>among  the  trees. But  they  don't  like  the  sun:  it makes  their  legs wobble  and  their 
line 2336=>heads giddy. They could not find Bilbo with the ring on, slipping in and out of the 
line 2337=>shadow of  the  trees,  running quick and quiet, and keeping out of  the sun; so soon 
line 2338=>they went back grumbling and cursing to guard the door. Bilbo had escaped. 
line 2339=> 
