line 2343=>Out of the Frying-Pan into the Fire 
line 2344=>
line 2345=> 
line 2346=>Bilbo had escaped the goblins, but he did not know where he was. He had lost 
line 2347=>hood,  cloak,  food,  pony,  his  buttons  and  his  friends. He wandered  on  and  on,  till 
line 2348=>the  sun  began  to  sink westwards-behind  the mountains. Their shadows fell across 
line 2349=>Bilbo's  path,  and  he  looked  back.  Then  he  looked  forward  and  could  see  before 
line 2350=>him  only  ridges  and  slopes  falling  towards  lowlands  and  plains  glimpsed 
line 2351=>occasionally between the trees. 
line 2352=>"Good  heavens!"  he  exclaimed.  "I  seem  to  have  got  right  to  the  other  side  of 
line 2353=>the Misty Mountains,  right  to  the  edge  of  the Land Beyond! Where  and O where 
line 2354=>can  Gandalf  and  the  dwarves  have  got  to?  I  only  hope  to  goodness  they  are  not 
line 2355=>still back there in the power of the goblins!" 
line 2356=>He  still wandered on, out of  the  little high valley, over  its edge, and down  the 
line 2357=>slopes beyond; but all the while a very uncomfortable thought was growing inside 
line 2358=>him.  He  wondered  whether  he  ought  not,  now  he  had  the magic  ring,  to  go  back 
line 2359=>into  the  horrible,  horrible,  tunnels  and  look  for  his  friends.  He  had  just made  up 
line 2360=>his  mind  that  it  was  his  duty,  that  he  must  turn  back-and  very miserable  he  felt 
line 2361=>about it-when he heard voices. 
line 2362=>He  stopped  and  listened.  It  did  not  sound  like  goblins;  so  he  crept  forward 
line 2363=>carefully. He was  on  a  stony  path winding  downwards with  a  rocky wall.  on  the 
line 2364=>left hand; on the other side the ground sloped away and there were dells below the 
line 2365=>level  of  the  path  overhung with  bushes  and  low  trees.  In  one  of  these  dells  under 
line 2366=>the bushes people were talking. 
line 2367=>He crept still nearer, and suddenly he saw peering between  two big boulders a 
line 2368=>head with a red hood on:  it was Balin doing  look-out. He could have clapped and 
line 2369=>shouted  for  joy,  but  he  did  not.  He  had  still  got  the  ring  on,  for  fear  of  meeting 
line 2370=>something unexpected and unpleasant, and he saw that Balin was looking straight 
line 2371=>at him without noticing him. 
line 2372=>"I will  give  them  all  a  surprise,"  he  thought,  as  he  crawled  into  the  bushes at 
line 2373=>the edge of the dell. Gandalf was arguing with the dwarves. They were discussing 
line 2374=>all  that  had  happened  to  them  in  the  tunnels,  and  wondering  and  debating  what 
line 2375=>they were  to  do  now. The  dwarves were  grumbling,  and Gandalf was  saying  that 
line 2376=>they could not possibly go on with their journey leaving Mr. Baggins in the hands 
line 2377=>of  the  goblins,  without  trying  to  find  out  if  he  was  alive  or  dead,  and  without 
line 2378=>trying to rescue him. 
line 2379=>
line 2380=>####-"After  all  he  is  my  friend,"  said  the  wizard,  "and  not  a  bad  little  chap.  I  feel 
line 2381=>responsible for him. I wish to goodness you had not lost him." 
line 2382=>The  dwarves  wanted  to  know  why  he  had  ever  been  brought  at  all,  why  he 
line 2383=>could not  stick  to his  friends  and  come  along with  them,  and why  the wizard had 
line 2384=>not chosen someone with more sense. "He has been more trouble than use so far," 
line 2385=>said  one.  "If  we  have  got  to'  go  back  now  into  those  abominable  tunnels  to  look 
line 2386=>for him, then drat him, I say." 
line 2387=>Gandalf answered angrily: "I brought him, and  I don't bring  things  that are of 
line 2388=>no use. Either you help me to look for him, or I go and leave you here to get out of 
line 2389=>the mess as best you can yourselves. If we can only find him again, you will thank 
line 2390=>me before all is over. Whatever did you want to go and drop him for, Dori?" 
line 2391=>"You would  have  dropped  him,"  said Dori,  "if a goblin had suddenly grabbed 
line 2392=>your  leg  from  behind  in  the  dark,  tripped  up  your  feet,  and  kicked  you  in  the 
line 2393=>back!" 
line 2394=>"Then why didn't you pick him up again?" 
line 2395=>"Good  heavens!  Can  you  ask!  Goblins  fighting  and  biting  in  the  dark, 
line 2396=>everybody falling over bodies  and hitting one another! You nearly chopped off my 
line 2397=>head  with  Glamdring,  and  Thorin Was  stabbing  here  there  and  everywhere  with 
line 2398=>Orcrist.  All  of  a  sudden  you  gave  one  of  your  blinding  flashes,  and  we  saw  the 
line 2399=>goblins running back yelping. You shouted 'follow me everybody!' and everybody 
line 2400=>ought  to  have  followed. We  thought  everybody  had. There was  no  time  to  count, 
line 2401=>as  you  know  quite  well,  till  we  had  dashed  through  the  gate-guards,  out  of  the 
