line 2543=> 
line 2544=>"Must we go any further?" asked Bilbo, when it was so dark that he could only 
line 2545=>just  see  Thorin's  beard  wagging  beside  him,  and  so  quiet  that  he  could  hear  the 
line 2546=>dwarves'  breathing  like  a  loud  noise.  "My  toes  are  all  bruised  and  bent,  and  my 
line 2547=>legs ache, and my stomach is wagging like an empty sack." 
line 2548=>"A bit further," said Gandalf. 
line 2549=>After  what  seemed  ages  further  they  came  suddenly  to  an  opening  where  no 
line 2550=>trees  grew.  The  moon  was  up  and  was  shining  into  the  clearing.  Somehow  it 
line 2551=>struck  all of  them  as not  at  all  a nice place,  although  there was nothing wrong  to 
line 2552=>see. 
line 2553=>All  of a sudden  they heard a howl away down hill, a  long shuddering howl. It 
line 2554=>was  answered  by  another  away  to  the  right  and  a  good  deal  nearer  to  them;  then 
line 2555=>by  another  not  far  away  to  the  left.  It  was  wolves  howling  at  the  moon,  wolves 
line 2556=>gathering together! 
line 2557=>There were no wolves living near Mr. Baggins' hole at home, but he knew that 
line 2558=>noise.  He  had  had  it  described  to  him  often  enough  in  tales.  One  of  his  elder 
line 2559=>cousins  (on  the  Took  side),  who  had  been  a  great  traveller,  used  to  imitate  it  to 
line 2560=>frighten him. To hear  it  out  in  the forest under  the moon was  too much for Bilbo. 
line 2561=>Even  magic  rings  are  not  much  use  against  wolves-especially  against  the  evil 
line 2562=>packs that lived under the shadow of the goblin-infested mountains, over the Edge 
line 2563=>of  the Wild  on  the  borders  of  the  unknown. Wolves of  that sort smell keener  than 
line 2564=>goblins, and do not need to see you to catch you! 
line 2565=>
line 2566=>####-"What  shall  we  do,  what  shall  we  do!"  he  cried.  "Escaping  goblins  to  be 
line 2567=>caught  by wolves!"  he  said,  and  it  became  a  proverb,  though we  now  say  'out  of 
line 2568=>the frying-pan into the fire' in the same sort of uncomfortable situations. 
line 2569=>"Up the trees quick!" cried Gandalf; and they ran to the trees at the edge of the 
line 2570=>glade,  hunting  for  those  that  had  branches  fairly  low,  or  were  slender  enough  to 
line 2571=>swarm  up.  They  found  them  as  quick  as  ever  they  could,  you  can  guess;  and  up 
line 2572=>they went as high as ever  they could  trust  the branches. You would have  laughed 
line 2573=>(from a safe distance), if you had seen the dwarves sitting up in the trees with their 
line 2574=>beards dangling down, like old gentlemen gone cracked and playing at being boys. 
line 2575=>Fili and Kili were at the top of a tall larch like an enormous Christmas tree. Dori, 
line 2576=>Nori,  On,  Oin,  and  Gloin  were  more  comfortable  in  a  huge  pine  with  regular 
line 2577=>branches  sticking  out  at  intervals  like  the  spokes  of  a  wheel.  Bifur,  Bofur, 
line 2578=>Bombur,  and  Thorin  were  in  another.  Dwalin  and  Balin  had  swarmed  up  a  tall 
line 2579=>slender fir with few branches and were  trying  to find a place  to sit  in  the greenery 
line 2580=>of  the  topmost  boughs.  Gandalf,  who  was  a  good  deal  taller  than  the  others,  had 
line 2581=>found  a  tree  into  which  they  could  not  climb,  a  large  pine  standing  at  the  very 
line 2582=>edge  of  the  glade. He was  quite  hidden  in  its  boughs,  but  you  could  see  his  eyes 
line 2583=>gleaming in the moon as he peeped out. 
line 2584=>And Bilbo? He could not get into any tree, and was scuttling about from trunk 
line 2585=>to trunk, like a rabbit that has lost its hole and has a dog after it. 
line 2586=>"You've left the burglar behind again}" said Nori to Dori looking down. 
line 2587=>"I  can't  be  always  carrying  burglars  on  my  back,"  said  Dori,  "down  tunnels 
line 2588=>and up trees! What do you think I am? A porter?" 
line 2589=>"He'll be eaten if we don't 'do something," said Thorin, for there were howls all 
line 2590=>around  them  now,  getting  nearer  and  nearer.  "Dori!"  he  called,  for  Dori  was 
line 2591=>lowest down in the easiest tree, "be quick, and give Mr. Baggins a hand up!" 
line 2592=>Dori was really a decent fellow in spite of his grumbling. Poor Bilbo could not 
line 2593=>reach  his  hand  even  when  he  climbed  down  to  the  bottom  branch  and  hung  his 
line 2594=>arm down as far as ever he could. So Dori actually climbed out of the tree and let 
line 2595=>Bilbo scramble up and stand on his back. 
line 2596=>Just  at  that  moment  the  wolves  trotted  howling  into  the  clearing.  All  of  a 
line 2597=>sudden  there  were  hundreds  of  eyes  looking  at  them.  Still  Dori  did  not  let  Bilbo 
line 2598=>down.  He  waited  till  he  had  clambered  off  his  shoulders  into  the  branches,  and 
line 2599=>then he jumped for the branches himself. Only just in time! A wolf snapped- at his 
line 2600=>cloak as he swung up, and nearly got him. In a minute there was a whole pack of 
line 2601=>them yelping all round  the  tree and  leaping up at  the  trunk, with eyes blazing and 
line 2602=>tongues hanging out. 
line 2603=>
line 2604=>####-But  even  the  wild  Wargs  (for  so  the  evil  wolves  over  the  Edge  of  the  Wild 
line 2605=>were named) cannot climb  trees. For a  time  they were  safe.  'Luckily  it was warm 
line 2606=>and not windy. Trees are not very comfortable to sit in for long at any time; but in 
line 2607=>the  cold  and  the wind, with wolves  all  round  below waiting  for  you,  they  can  be 
line 2608=>perfectly miserable places. 
line 2609=>This  glade  in  the  ring  of  trees  was  evidently  a  meeting-place  of  the  wolves. 
line 2610=>More  and  more  kept  coming  in.  They  left  guards  at  the  foot  of  the  tree  in which 
line 2611=>Dori  and  Bilbo  were,  and  then  went  sniffling  about  till  they  had  smelt  out  every 
line 2612=>tree that had anyone in it. These they guarded too, while all the rest (hundreds and 
line 2613=>hundreds  it  seemed) went  and  sat  in  a  great  circle  in  the  glade;  and  in the middle 
line 2614=>of  the circle was a great grey wolf. He  spoke  to  them  in  the dreadful  language of 
line 2615=>the  Wargs.  Gandalf  understood  it.  Bilbo  did  not,  but  it  sounded  terrible  to  him, 
line 2616=>and  as  if  all  their  talk  was  about  cruel  and  wicked  things,  as  it  was.  Every  now 
line 2617=>and then all the Wargs in the circle would answer their grey chief all together, and 
line 2618=>their dreadful clamour almost made the hobbit fall out of his pine-tree. 
line 2619=>I  will  tell  you  what  Gandalf  heard,  though  Bilbo  did  not  understand  it.  The 
line 2620=>Wargs  and  the  goblins  often  helped  one  another  in wicked  deeds. Goblins  do  not 
line 2621=>usually venture very  far  from  their mountains, unless  they  are driven out  and  are 
line 2622=>looking  for  new  homes,  or  are marching  to  war  (which  I  am  glad  to  say  has  not 
line 2623=>happened for a long while). But in those days they sometimes used to go on raids, 
line 2624=>especially to get food or slaves to work for them. Then they often got the Wargs to 
line 2625=>help  and  shared  the  plunder with  them. Sometimes  they  rode  on wolves  like men 
line 2626=>do  on  horses.  Now  it  seemed  that  a  great  goblin-raid  had  been  planned  for  that 
line 2627=>very  night.  The  Wargs  had  come  to  meet  the  goblins  and  the  goblins  were  late. 
line 2628=>The  reason,  no  doubt,  was  the  death  of  the  Great  Goblin,  and  all  the  excitement 
line 2629=>caused  by  the  dwarves  and  Bilbo  and  the  wizard,  for  whom  they  were  probably 
line 2630=>still hunting. 
line 2631=>In spite of  the dangers of  this  far  land bold men had of  late been making  their 
line 2632=>way  back  into  it  from  the  South,  cutting  down  trees,  and  building  themselves 
line 2633=>places to live in among the more pleasant woods in the valleys and along the river-
line 2634=>shores. There were many of  them, and  they were brave and well-armed, and even 
line 2635=>the Wargs dared not attack  them  if  there were many  together, or  in  the bright day. 
line 2636=>But  now  they  had  planned with  the  goblins'  help  to  come  by  night  upon  some  of 
line 2637=>the  villages nearest  the mountains.  If  their plan had been carried out,  there would 
line 2638=>have been none  left  there next day;  all would have been killed  except  the  few  the 
line 2639=>goblins kept from the wolves and carried back as prisoners to their caves. 
line 2640=>
line 2641=>####-This was dreadful talk to listen to, not only because of the brave woodmen and 
line 2642=>their  wives  and  children,  but  also  because  of  the  danger  which  now  threatened 
line 2643=>Gandalf  and his  friends. The Wargs were  angry  and puzzled  at  finding  them here 
line 2644=>in  their  very meeting-place. They  thought  they were  friends of  the woodmen, and 
line 2645=>were  come  to  spy  on  them,  and  would  take  news  of  their  plans  down  into  the 
line 2646=>valleys,  and  then  the  goblins  and  the wolves would  have  to  fight  a  terrible  battle 
line 2647=>instead  of  capturing  prisoners  and  devouring  people  waked  suddenly  from  their 
line 2648=>sleep. So  the Wargs  had  no  intention  of  going  away  and  letting  the  people  up  the 
line 2649=>trees escape, at any rate not until morning. And long before that, they said, goblin 
line 2650=>soldiers would be coming down  from  the mountains; and goblins can climb  trees, 
line 2651=>or cut them down. 
line 2652=>Now you can understand why Gandalf, listening to their growling and yelping, 
line 2653=>began  to be dreadfully afraid, wizard  though he was, and  to feel  that  they were  in 
line 2654=>a very bad place, and had not yet escaped at all. All  the same he was not going to 
line 2655=>let them have it all their own way, though he could not do very much stuck up in a 
line 2656=>tall  tree  with  wolves  all  round  on  the  ground  below.  He  gathered  the  huge 
line 2657=>pinecones  from  the  branches  of  his  tree.  Then  he  set  one  alight  with  bright  blue 
line 2658=>fire, and  threw  it whizzing down among  the circle of  the wolves.  It  struck one on 
line 2659=>the back, and  immediately his shaggy coat caught  fire, and he was  leaping  to and 
line 2660=>fro  yelping  horribly.  Then  another  came  and  another,  one  in  blue  flames,  one  in 
line 2661=>red,  another  in  green.  They  burst  on  the  ground  in  the  middle  of  the  circle  and 
line 2662=>went off in coloured sparks and smoke. A specially large one hit the chief wolf on 
line 2663=>the  nose,  and  he  leaped  in  the  air  ten  feet,  and  then  rushed  round  and  round  the 
line 2664=>circle biting and snapping even at the other wolves in his anger and fright. 
line 2665=>The  dwarves  and  Bilbo  shouted  and  cheered.  The  rage  of  the  wolves  was 
line 2666=>terrible  to  see,  and  the  commotion  they  made  filled  all  the  forest.  Wolves  are  
line 2667=>afraid of fire at all times, but this was a most horrible and uncanny fire. If a spark 
line 2668=>got  in  their coats  it stuck and burned  into  them, and unless  they  rolled over quick 
line 2669=>they  were  soon  all  in  flames.  Very  soon  all  about  the  glade  wolves  were  rolling 
line 2670=>over  and over  to put out  the  sparks on  their backs, while  those  that  were burning 
line 2671=>were running about howling and setting others alight, till their own friends chased 
line 2672=>them  away  and  they  fled  off  down  the  slopes  crying  and  yammering  and  looking 
line 2673=>for water.  
line 2674=> 
line 2675=>"What's  all  this  uproar  in  the  forest  tonight?"  said  the  Lord  of  the  Eagles. He 
line 2676=>was  sitting,  black  in  the moonlight,  on  the  top  of  a  lonely  pinnacle  of  rock  at  the 
