line 2682=>upon  the  ring  of  the Wargs,  a  tiny  spot  far  far  below.  But  eagles  have  keen  eyes 
line 2683=>and  can  see  small  things  at  a  great  distance.  The  lord  of  the  eagles  of  the  Misty 
line 2684=>Mountains had eyes  that could  look at  the  sun unblinking, and could  see a  rabbit 
line 2685=>moving on the ground a mile below even in the moonlight. So though he could not 
line 2686=>see  the  people  in  the  trees,  he  could make  out  the  commotion  among  the wolves 
line 2687=>and  see  the  tiny  flashes  of  fire,  and  hear  the  howling  and  yelping  come  up  faint 
line 2688=>from far beneath him. Also he could see the glint of the moon on goblin spears and 
line 2689=>helmets,  as  long  lines  of  the wicked  folk  crept  down  the  hillsides  from  their  gate 
line 2690=>and wound into the wood. 
line 2691=>Eagles are not kindly birds. Some are cowardly and cruel. But the ancient race 
line 2692=>of  the  northern  mountains  were  the  greatest  of  all  birds;  they  were  proud  and 
line 2693=>strong and noble-hearted. They did not love goblins, or fear them. When they took 
line 2694=>any  notice  of  them at all (which was seldom, for they did not eat such creatures ), 
line 2695=>they  swooped on  them and drove  them  shrieking back  to  their caves, and  stopped 
line 2696=>whatever  wickedness  they  were  doing.  The  goblins  hated  the  eagles  and  feared 
line 2697=>them, but could not reach their lofty seats, or drive them from the mountains. 
line 2698=>Tonight  the  Lord  of  the  Eagles  was  filled  with  curiosity  to  know  what  was 
line 2699=>afoot;  so  he  summoned  many  other  eagles  to  him,  and  they  flew  away  from  the 
line 2700=>mountains,  and  slowly  circling  ever  round  and  round  they  came  down,  down, 
line 2701=>down towards the ring of the wolves and the meeting-place of the goblins. 
line 2702=>A  very  good  thing  too!  Dreadful  things  had  been  going  on  down  there.  The 
line 2703=>wolves  that  had  caught  fire  and  fled  into  the  forest  had  set  it  alight  in  several 
line 2704=>places.  It  was  high  summer,  and  on  this  eastern  side  of  the  mountains  there  had 
line 2705=>been little rain for some time. Yellowing bracken, fallen branches, deep-piled pine-
line 2706=>needles, and here and there dead trees, were soon in flames. All round the clearing 
