line 2797=>
line 2798=>####-Bilbo  never  forgot  that  flight,  clinging  onto Dori's  ankles. He moaned  "my  arms, 
line 2799=>my arms!"; but Dori groaned "my poor legs, my poor legs!" 
line 2800=>At  the  best  of  times  heights  made  Bilbo  giddy.  He  used  to  turn  queer  if  he 
line 2801=>looked over the edge of quite a little cliff; and he had never liked ladders, let alone 
line 2802=>trees  (never  having  had  to  escape  from wolves  before).  So  you  can  imagine  how 
line 2803=>his head swam now, when he  looked down between his dangling  toes and saw  the 
line 2804=>dark  lands opening wide underneath him,  touched here and there with the light of 
line 2805=>the moon on a hill-side rock or a stream in the plains. 
line 2806=>The  pale  peaks  of  the mountains were  coming  nearer, moonlit  spikes  of  rock 
line 2807=>sticking  out  of  black  shadows.  Summer  or  not,  it  seemed  very  cold.  He  shut  his 
line 2808=>eyes  and wondered if he could hold on any longer. Then he imagined what would 
line 2809=>happen  if he did not. He  felt  sick. The  flight  ended only  just  in  time  for him,  just 
line 2810=>before  his  arms  gave  way.  He  loosed  Dori's  ankles  with  a  gasp  and  fell  onto  the 
line 2811=>rough  platform  of  an  eagle's  eyrie.  There  he  lay  without  speaking,  and  his 
line 2812=>thoughts were  a mixture  of  surprise  at  being  saved  from  the  fire,  and  fear  lest  he 
line 2813=>fell off that narrow place into the deep shadows on either side. He was feeling very 
line 2814=>queer indeed in his head by this time after the dreadful adventures of the last three 
line 2815=>days with next to nothing to eat, and he found himself saying aloud: "Now I know 
line 2816=>what a piece of bacon feels like when it is suddenly picked out of the pan on a fork 
line 2817=>and put back on the shelf!" 
line 2818=>"No  you  don't!"  be  heard  Dori  answering,  "because  the  bacon  knows  that  it 
line 2819=>will get back in the pan sooner or later; and it is to be hoped we shan't. Also eagles 
line 2820=>aren't forks!" 
line 2821=>"O  no!  Not  a  bit  like  storks-forks,  I mean,"  said Bilbo  sitting up  and  looking 
line 2822=>anxiously  at  the  eagle  who  was  perched  close  by.  He  wondered  what  other 
line 2823=>nonsense he had been  saying, and  if  the eagle would  think  it  rude. You ought not 
line 2824=>to  be  rude  to  an  eagle, when  you  are  only  the  size  of  a  hobbit,  and  are  up  in  his 
line 2825=>eyrie at night! 
line 2826=>The  eagle  only  sharpened  his  beak  on  a  stone  and  trimmed  his  feathers  and 
line 2827=>took no notice. 
line 2828=>Soon  another  eagle  flew  up.  "The  Lord  of  the  Eagles  bids  you  to  bring  your 
line 2829=>prisoners to the Great Shelf," he cried and was off again. The other seized Dori in 
line 2830=>his  claws  and  flew  away  with  him  into  the  night  leaving Bilbo  all  alone. He  had 
line 2831=>just strength  to wonder what  the messenger had meant by  'prisoners,' and  to begin 
