line 2834=>This  time  he  flew  only  a  short  way.  Very  soon  Bilbo  was  laid  down,  trembling 
line 2835=>
line 2836=>####-with  fear,  on  a wide  shelf  of  rock  on  the mountain-side. There was no path down 
line 2837=>on to it save by flying; and no path down off it except by jumping over a precipice. 
line 2838=>There  he  found  all  the  others  sitting  with  their  backs  to  the  mountain  wall.  The 
line 2839=>Lord of the Eagles also was there and was speaking to Gandalf. 
line 2840=>It  seemed  that  Bilbo  was  not  going  to  be  eaten  after  all.  The  wizard  and  the 
line 2841=>eagle-lord  appeared  to  know  one  another  slightly,  and  even  to  be  on  friendly 
line 2842=>terms. As a matter of fact Gandalf, who had often been in the mountains, had once 
line 2843=>rendered  a  service  to  the  eagles  and  healed  their  lord  from  an  arrow-wound. So 
line 2844=>you  see  'prisoners'  had  meant  'prisoners  rescued  from  the  goblins'  only,  and  not 
line 2845=>captives  of  the  eagles. As Bilbo  listened  to  the  talk  of Gandalf  he  realized  that  at 
line 2846=>last  they  were  going  to  escape  really  and  truly  from  the  dreadful  mountains.  He 
line 2847=>was  discussing  plans  with  the  Great  Eagle  for  carrying  the  dwarves  and  himself 
line 2848=>and Bilbo far away and setting  them down well on  their  journey across  the plains 
line 2849=>below.  
line 2850=>The Lord of  the Eagles would not  take  them anywhere near where men  lived. 
line 2851=>"They  would  shoot  at  us  with  their  great  bows  of yew," he  said,  "for  they would 
line 2852=>think  we  were  after  their  sheep.  And  at  other  times  they  would  be  right.  No!  we 
line 2853=>are  glad  to  cheat  the  goblins  of  their  sport,  and  glad  to  repay  our  thanks  to  you, 
line 2854=>but we will not risk ourselves for dwarves in the southward plains." 
line 2855=>"Very  well,"  said  Gandalf.  "Take  us  where  and  as  far  as  you  will!  We  are 
line 2856=>already deeply obliged to you. But in the meantime we are famished with hunger." 
line 2857=>"I am nearly dead of it," said Bilbo in a weak little voice that nobody heard. 
line 2858=>"That can perhaps be mended," said the Lord of the Eagles. 
line 2859=>Later on you might have seen a bright fire on  the shelf of rock and  the figures 
line 2860=>of the dwarves round it cooking and making a fine roasting smell. The eagles had 
line 2861=>brought  up  dry  boughs  for  fuel,  and  they  had  brought  rabbits, hares, and a  small 
line 2862=>sheep.  The  dwarves  managed  all  the  preparations.  Bilbo  was  too  weak  to  help, 
line 2863=>and  anyway  he was  not much  good  at  skinning  rabbits  or  cutting  up meat,  being 
line 2864=>used  to  having  it  delivered  by  the  butcher  all  ready  to  cook.  Gandalf,  too,  was 
line 2865=>lying  down  after  doing  his  part  in  setting  the  fire  going,  since Oin  and Gloin  had 
line 2866=>lost their tinder-boxes. (Dwarves have never taken to matches even yet.) 
line 2867=>So  ended  the  adventures  of  the  Misty  Mountains.  Soon  Bilbo's  stomach  was 
line 2868=>feeling full and  comfortable  again,  and he  felt he  could  sleep  contentedly,  though 
line 2869=>really  he  would  have  liked  a  loaf  and  butter  better  than  bits  of  meat  toasted  on 
line 2870=>sticks. He slept curled up on the hard rock more soundly than ever he had done on 
line 2871=>his feather-bed in his own  little hole at home. But all night he dreamed of his own 
line 2872=>
line 2873=>####-house and wandered in his sleep into all his different rooms looking for something 
line 2874=>that he could not find nor remember what it looked like. 
line 2875=> 
line 2876=>
line 2877=>####-<h4>Chapter 7 </h4> <br>
line 2878=>
line 2879=>Queer Lodgings 
line 2880=>
line 2881=> 
line 2882=>The next morning Bilbo woke up with the early sun in his eyes. He jumped up 
line 2883=>to  look  at  the  time  and  to  go  and  put  his  kettle  on-and  found he was not home at 
line 2884=>all.  So  he  sat  down  and  wished  in  vain  for  a  wash  and  a  brush.  He  did  not  get 
line 2885=>either,  nor  tea  nor  toast  nor  bacon  for  his  breakfast, only cold mutton and  rabbit. 
line 2886=>And after that he had to get ready for a fresh start. 
line 2887=>This time he was allowed to climb on to an eagle's back and cling between his 
line 2888=>wings.  The  air  rushed  over  him  and  he  shut  his  eyes.  The  dwarves  were  crying 
line 2889=>farewells  and  promising  to  repay  the  lord  of  the  eagles  if  ever  they  could,  as  off 
line 2890=>rose  fifteen  great  birds  from  the  mountain's  side.  The  sun  was  still  close  to  the 
line 2891=>eastern  edge  of  things.  The morning was  cool,  and mists were  in  the  valleys  and 
line 2892=>hollows  and  twined  here  and  there  about  the  peaks  and  pinnacles  of  the  hills. 
line 2893=>Bilbo opened  an  eye  to peep  and  saw  that  the birds were  already high up  and  the 
line 2894=>world  was  far  away,  and  the  mountains  were  falling  back  behind  them  into  the 
line 2895=>distance. He shut his eyes again and held on tighter.  
line 2896=>"Don't pinch!" said his eagle. "You need not be frightened like a rabbit, even if 
line 2897=>you  look  rather  like  one.  It  is  a  fair morning  with  little  wind. What  is  finer  than 
line 2898=>flying?" 
line 2899=>Bilbo  would  have  liked  to  say:  "A  warm  bath  and  late  breakfast  on  the  lawn 
line 2900=>afterwards;"  but  he  thought  it  better  to  say  nothing  at  all,  and  to  let  go  his  clutch 
line 2901=>just a tiny bit. 
line 2902=>After  a good while  the  eagles must have  seen  the point  they were making  for, 
line 2903=>'even  from  their  great  height,  for  they  began  to  go  down  circling  round  in  great 
line 2904=>spirals. They did this for a long while, and at last the hobbit opened his eyes again. 
line 2905=>The earth was much nearer, and below  them were  trees  that  looked  like oaks and 
line 2906=>elms, and wide grass lands, and a river running through it all. But cropping out of 
line 2907=>the ground, right in the path of the stream which looped itself about it, was a great 
line 2908=>rock, almost a hill of stone,  like a  last outpost of  the distant mountains, or a huge 
line 2909=>piece cast miles into the plain by some giant among giants. 
line 2910=>Quickly  now  to  the  top  of  this  rock  the  eagles  swooped  one  by  one  and  set 
line 2911=>down their passengers. 
line 2912=>"Farewell!"  they  cried,  "wherever  you  fare,  till  your  eyries  receive  you  at  the 
line 2913=>journey's end!" That is the polite thing to say among eagles. 
line 2914=>
line 2915=>####-"May  the  wind  under  your  wings  bear  you  where  the  sun  sails  and  the moon 
line 2916=>walks," answered Gandalf, who knew the correct reply.  
line 2917=>And so they parted. And though the lord of the eagles became in after days the 
line 2918=>King  of  All  Birds  and  wore  a  golden  crown,  and  his  fifteen  chieftains  golden 
line 2919=>collars  (made  of  the  gold  that  the  dwarves  gave  them),  Bilbo  never  saw  them 
line 2920=>again-except high and  far off  in  the battle of Five Armies. But as  that comes  in at 
line 2921=>the end of this tale we will say no more about it just now.  
line 2922=>There was a flat space on the top of the hill of stone and a well worn path with 
line 2923=>many steps leading down it to the river, across which a ford of huge flat stones led 
line 2924=>to  the  grass-land  beyond  the  stream.  There  was  a  little  cave  (a  wholesome  one 
line 2925=>with a pebbly floor) at the foot of the steps and near the end of the stony ford. Here 
line 2926=>the party gathered and discussed what was to be done. 
line 2927=>"I  always meant  to  see you  all  safe  (if possible) over  the mountains,"  said  the 
line 2928=>wizard,  "and  now  by  good management  and  good  luck  I  have  done  it.  Indeed we 
line 2929=>are  now  a  good  deal  further east than I ever meant to come with you, for after all 
line 2930=>this  is not my adventure.  I may  look  in on  it again before  it  is all over, but  in  the 
line 2931=>meanwhile I have some other pressing business to attend to." 
line 2932=>The  dwarves  groaned  and  looked  most  distressed,  and  Bilbo wept.  They  had 
line 2933=>begun to think Gandalf was going in come all the way and would always be there 
line 2934=>to  help  them  out  of  difficulties.  "I  am  not  going  to  disappear  this  very  instant," 
line 2935=>said  he.  "I  can  give  you  a  day  or  two more.  Probably  I  can  help  you  out of your 
line 2936=>present  plight,  and  I  need  a  little  help myself. We  have  no  food,  and  no  baggage, 
line 2937=>and no ponies to ride; and you don't know where you are. Now I can tell you that. 
line 2938=>You are still some miles north of the path which we should have been following, if 
line 2939=>we  had  not  left  the mountain  pass  in  a  hurry.  Very  few people  live  in  these parts, 
line 2940=>unless  they  have  come  here  since  I was  last  down  this way, which  is  some  years 
line 2941=>ago.  But  there  is  somebody  that  I  know  of,  who  lives  not  far  away.  That 
line 2942=>Somebody made the 
line 2943=>steps on the great rock-the Carrock I believe he calls it. He does not come here 
line 2944=>often,  certainly  not  in  the  daytime,  and  it  is  no  good  waiting  for  him.  In  fact  it 
line 2945=>would  be  very  dangerous. We  must  go  and  find  him;  and  if  all  goes  well  at  our 
line 2946=>meeting,  I  think I shall be off and wish you like the eagles  'farewell wherever you 
line 2947=>fare!' " 
line 2948=>They  begged  him  not  to  leave  them. They  offered  him  dragon-gold and silver 
line 2949=>and jewels, but he would not change his mind. 
line 2950=>"We  shall  see, we  shall  see!" he  said,  "and  I  think  I have earned already some 
line 2951=>of your dragon-gold - when you have got it." 
line 2952=>
line 2953=>####- 
line 2954=>After that they stopped pleading. Then they took off their clothes and bathed in 
line 2955=>the river, which was shallow and clear and stony at the ford. When they had dried 
line 2956=>in the sun, which was now strong and warm, they were refreshed, if still sore and a 
line 2957=>little  hungry.  Soon  they  crossed  the  ford  (carrying  the  hobbit),  and  then  began  to 
line 2958=>march  through  the  long  green  grass  and  down  the  lines  of  the  wide-armed oaks 
line 2959=>and the tall elms. 
line 2960=>"And  why  is  it  called  the  Carrock?"  asked  Bilbo  as  he  went  along  at  the 
line 2961=>wizard's side. 
line 2962=>"He  called  it  the  Carrock,  because  carrock  is  his  word  for  it.  He  calls  things 
line 2963=>like  that  carrocks,  and  this  one  is  the Carrock  because  it  is  the  only  one  near  his 
line 2964=>home and he knows it well." 
line 2965=>"Who calls it? Who knows it?" 
line 2966=>"The  Somebody  I  spoke  of-a  very  great  person.  You  must  all  be  very  polite 
line 2967=>when  I  introduce  you.  I  shall  introduce  you  slowly,  two  by  two,  I  think;  and  you 
line 2968=>must  be  careful  not  to  annoy  him,  or  heaven  knows what will  happen. He can be 
line 2969=>appalling  when  he  is  angry,  though  he  is  kind  enough  if  humoured.  Still  I  warn 
line 2970=>you he gets angry easily." 
line 2971=>The dwarves all gathered round when they heard the wizard talking like this to 
line 2972=>Bilbo.  "Is  that  the  person  you  are  taking  us  to  now?"  they  asked.  "Couldn't  you 
line 2973=>find someone more easy-tempered? Hadn't you better explain it all a bit clearer?"-
line 2974=>and so on. 
line 2975=>"Yes  it  certainly  is!  No  I  could  not!  And  I  was  explaining  very  carefully," 
line 2976=>answered  the  wizard  crossly.  "If  you  must  know  more,  his  name  is  Beorn. He  is 
line 2977=>very strong, and he is a skin-changer." 
line 2978=>"What!  a  furrier,  a  man  that  calls  rabbits  conies,  when  he  doesn't  turn  their 
line 2979=>skins into squirrels?" asked Bilbo. 
line 2980=>"Good gracious heavens, no, no, NO, NO!" said Gandalf. "Don't be a fool Mr. 
line 2981=>Baggins  if you  can help  it; and  in  the name of all wonder don't mention  the word 
line 2982=>furrier  again  as  long  as  you  are  within  a  hundred  miles  of  his  house,  nor,  rug, 
line 2983=>cape,  tippet, muff, nor any other such unfortunate word! He  is a skin-changer. He 
line 2984=>changes  his  skin;  sometimes  he  is  a  huge  black  bear,  sometimes  he  is  a  great 
line 2985=>strong black-haired man with huge arms and a great beard. I cannot tell you much 
line 2986=>more,  though  that ought  to be enough. Some say  that he  is a bear descended from 
line 2987=>the  great  and  ancient  bears  of  the  mountains  that  lived  there  before  the  giants 
line 2988=>came. Others  say  that he  is  a man descended  from  the  first men who  lived before 
line 2989=>Smaug  or  the  other  dragons  came  into  this  part  of  the  world,  and  before  the 
line 2990=>
line 2991=>####-goblins came into the hills out of the North. I cannot say, though I fancy the last is 
line 2992=>the true tale. He is not the sort of person to ask questions of. 
line 2993=>"At any rate he is under no enchantment but his own. He lives in an oak-wood 
line 2994=>and has a great wooden house; and as a man he keeps cattle and horses which are 
line 2995=>nearly  is marvellous  as himself. They work  for him  and  talk  to him. He does not 
line 2996=>eat  them;  neither  does  he  hunt  or  eat  wild  animals.  He  keeps  hives  and  hives  of 
line 2997=>great fierce bees, and  lives most on cream and honey. As a bear he ranges far and 
line 2998=>wide.  I  once  saw  him  sitting all alone on the top of the Carrock at night watching 
line 2999=>the  moon  sinking  towards  the  Misty  Mountains,  and  I  heard  him  growl  in  the 
line 3000=>tongue  of  bears;  'The  day  will  come  when  they  will  perish  and  I  shall  go  back!' 
line 3001=>That is why I believe he once came from the mountains himself." 
line 3002=> 
line 3003=>Bilbo and the dwarves had now plenty to think about, and they asked no more 
line 3004=>questions. They still had a long way to walk before them. Up slope and down dale 
line 3005=>they  plodded.  It  grew  very  hot.  Sometimes  they  rested  under  the  trees,  and  then 
line 3006=>Bilbo felt so hungry that he would have eaten acorns, if any had been ripe enough 
line 3007=>yet to have fallen to the ground. 
line 3008=>It  was  the  middle  of  the  afternoon  before  they  noticed  that  great  patches  of 
line 3009=>flowers had begun to spring up, all the same kinds growing together as if they had 
line 3010=>been  planted.  Especially  there  was  clover,  waving  patches  of  cockscomb  clover, 
line 3011=>and  purple  clover,  and wide  stretches  of  short white  sweet  honey-smelling clover. 
line 3012=>There  was  a  buzzing  and  a  whirring  and  a  droning  in  the  air.  Bees  were  busy 
line 3013=>everywhere. And such bees! Bilbo had never seen anything like them. 
line 3014=>"If one was to sting me," he thought, "I should swell up as big again as I am!" 
line 3015=>They  were  bigger  than  hornets.  The  drones  were  bigger  than  your  thumb,  a 
line 3016=>good  deal,  and  the  bands  of  yellow  on  their  deep  black  bodies  shone  like  fiery 
line 3017=>gold. 
line 3018=>"We are getting near," said Gandalf. "We are on the edge of his bee-pastures." 
line 3019=>After  a  while  they  came  to  a  belt  of  tall  and  very  ancient  oaks,  and  beyond 
line 3020=>these to a high thorn-hedge through which you could neither see nor scramble. 
line 3021=>"You had better wait here," said the wizard to the dwarves; "and when I call or 
line 3022=>whistle  begin  to  come  after  me â€”  you  will  see  the  way  I  go-but  only  in  pairs, 
