line 3440=>As  soon as  they  left his high hedges at  the east of his  fenced lands they turned 
line 3441=>north  and  then  bore  to  the  north-west. By his  advice  they were no  longer making 
line 3442=>for  the main  forest-road to the south of his land. Had they followed the pass, their 
line 3443=>path  would  have  led  them  down  the  stream  from  the  mountains  that  joined  the 
line 3444=>great  river miles  south  of  the Carrock. At  that  point  there was  a  deep  ford which 
line 3445=>they might have passed,  if  they had  still had  their ponies, and beyond  that a  track 
line 3446=>led  to  the  skirts of  the wood and  to  the entrance of  the old  forest  road. But Beorn 
line 3447=>had  warned  them  that  that  way  was  now  often  used  by  the  goblins,  while  the 
line 3448=>forest-road itself, he bad heard, was overgrown and disused at the eastern end and 
line 3449=>led  to  impassable marshes where  the paths had  long been  lost.  Its eastern opening 
line 3450=>had also always been far to the south of the Lonely Mountain, and would have left 
line 3451=>them  still  with  a  long  and  difficult  northward  march  when  they  got  to  the  other 
line 3452=>side. 
line 3453=>
line 3454=>####-North  of  the Carrock  the  edge  of Mirkwood  drew  closer  to  the  borders  of  the 
line 3455=>Great River, and though here the Mountains too drew down nearer, Beorn advised 
line 3456=>them to take this way; for at a place a few days' ride due north of the Carrock was 
line 3457=>the  gate  of  a  little-known  pathway  through  Mirkwood  that  led  almost  straight 
line 3458=>towards the Lonely Mountain. 
line 3459=>"The  goblins,"  Beorn  had  said,  "will  not  dare  to  cross  the  Great  River  for  a 
line 3460=>hundred  miles  north  of  the  Carrock  nor  to  come  near  my  house  â€“  it  is  well 
line 3461=>protected  at  night!â€“  but  I  should  ride  fast;  for  if  they  make  their  raid  soon  they 
line 3462=>will cross the river to the south  and scour all the edge of the forest so as to cut you 
line 3463=>off,  and  Wargs  run  swifter  than  ponies.  Still  you  are  safer  going  north,  even 
line 3464=>though you seem to be going back nearer to their strongholds; for that is what they 
line 3465=>will  least  expect,  and  they  will  have  the  longer  ride  to  catch  you.  Be  off  now  as 
line 3466=>quick as you may!" 
line 3467=>That  is  why  they  were  now  riding  in  silence,  galloping  wherever  the  ground 
line 3468=>was grassy and  smooth, with  the mountains dark on  their  left, and  in  the distance 
line 3469=>the line of the river with its trees drawing ever closer. The sun had only just turned 
line 3470=>west  when  they  started,  and  till  evening  it  lay  golden  on  the  land  about  them.  It 
line 3471=>was  difficult  to  think  of  pursuing  goblins  behind,  and  when  they  had  put  many 
line 3472=>miles between them and Beorn's house they began to talk and to sing again and to 
line 3473=>forget  the  dark  forest-path  that  lay  in  front.  But  in  the  evening  when  the  dusk 
line 3474=>came on and  the peaks of  the mountains glowered against  the  sunset  they made a 
line 3475=>camp and set a guard, and most of them slept uneasily with dreams in which there 
line 3476=>came  the  howl  of  hunting wolves  and  the  cries  of  goblins.  Still  the  next morning 
line 3477=>dawned bright and fair again. 
line 3478=>There  was  an  autumn-like mist  white  upon  the  ground  and  the  air  was  chill, 
line 3479=>but  soon  the  sun  rose  red  in  the  East  and  the  mists  vanished,  and  while  the 
line 3480=>shadows were still long they were off again. So they rode now for two more days, 
line 3481=>and all  the while  they saw nothing save grass and  flowers and birds and scattered 
line 3482=>trees,  and  occasionally  small  herds  of  red  deer  browsing  or  sitting  at noon  in  the 
line 3483=>shade.  Sometimes  Bilbo  saw  the  horns  of  the  harts  sticking  up  out  of  the  long 
line 3484=>grass,  and  at  first  he  thought  they  were  the  dead  branches  of  trees.  That  third 
line 3485=>evening  they were so eager  to press on,  for Beorn had said  that  they should  reach 
line 3486=>the  forest-gate  early  on  the  fourth  day,  that  they  rode  still  forward  after  dusk  and 
line 3487=>into  the night beneath  the moon. As  the  light faded Bilbo  thought he saw away  to 
line 3488=>the  right,  or  to  the  left,  the  shadowy  form  of  a  great  bear  prowling  along  in  the 
line 3489=>same  direction.  But  if  he  dared  to  mention  it  to  Gandalf,  the  wizard  only  said: 
line 3490=>"Hush! Take no notice!" 
line 3491=>
line 3492=>####-Next day they started before dawn, though their night had been short. As soon 
line 3493=>as it was light they could see the forest coming as it were to meet them, or waiting 
line 3494=>for  them  like a black and  frowning wall before  them. The  land began  to  slope up 
line 3495=>and  up,  and  it  seemed  to  the  hobbit  that  a  silence  began  to  draw  in  upon  them. 
line 3496=>Birds  began  to  sing  less.  There  were  no  more  deer;  not  even  rabbits  were  to  be 
line 3497=>seen. By  the  afternoon they had reached the eaves of Mirkwood, and were resting 
line 3498=>almost beneath  the great overhanging boughs of  its outer  trees. Their  trunks were 
line 3499=>huge  and  gnarled,  their  branches  twisted,  their  leaves  were  dark  and  long.  Ivy 
line 3500=>grew on them and trailed along the ground. 
line 3501=>"Well,  here  is  Mirkwood!"  said  Gandalf.  "The  greatest  of  the  forests  of  the 
line 3502=>Northern  world.  I  hope  you  like  the  look  of  it.  Now  you  must  send  back  these 
line 3503=>excellent ponies you have borrowed." 
line 3504=>The  dwarves  were  inclined  to  grumble  at  this,  but  the  wizard  told  them  they 
line 3505=>were  fools. "Beorn  is not as  far off as you seem  to  think, and you had better keep 
line 3506=>your promises  anyway,  for he  is  a bad  enemy. Mr. Baggins'  eyes  are  sharper  than 
line 3507=>yours,  if you have not seen each night after dark a great bear going along with us 
line 3508=>or sitting far of in the moon watching our camps. Not only to guard you and guide 
line 3509=>you, but to keep an eye on the ponies too. Beorn may be your friend, but he loves 
line 3510=>his animals as his children. You do not guess what kindness he has  shown you  in 
line 3511=>letting dwarves ride them so far and so fast, nor what would happen to you, if you 
line 3512=>tried to take them into the forest." 
line 3513=>"What  about  the  horse,  then?"  said  Thorin.  "You  don't  mention  sending  that 
line 3514=>back." 
line 3515=>"I don't, because I am not sending it." 
line 3516=>"What about your promise then?" 
line 3517=>"I will look after that. I am not sending the horse back, I am riding it!" 
line 3518=>Then  they  knew  that  Gandalf  was  going  to  leave  them  at  the  very  edge  of 
line 3519=>Mirkwood, and they were in despair.  
line 3520=>But nothing they could say would change his mind. 
line 3521=>"Now we had this all out before, when we landed on the Carrock," he said. "It 
line 3522=>is no use arguing. I have, as I  told you, some pressing business away south; and I 
line 3523=>am already late through bothering with you people. We may meet again before all 
line 3524=>is  over,  and  then  again of  course we may not. That depends on your  luck  and on 
line 3525=>your courage and  sense; and  I am  sending Mr. Baggins with you.  I have  told you 
line 3526=>before  that  he  has  more  about  him  than  you  guess,  and  you  will  find  that  out 
line 3527=>before  long.  So  cheer  up  Bilbo  and  don't  look  so  glum.  Cheer  up  Thorin  and 
line 3528=>
line 3529=>####-Company! This  is  your  expedition  after  all. Think  of  the  treasure  at  the  end,  and 
line 3530=>forget the forest and the dragon, at any rate until tomorrow morning!" 
line 3531=>When tomorrow morning came he still said the same. 
line 3532=>So  now  there  was  nothing  left  to  do  but  to  fill  their  water-skins  at  a  clear 
line 3533=>spring they found close to the forest-gate, and unpack the ponies. They distributed 
line 3534=>the  packages  as  fairly  as  they  could,  though  Bilbo  thought  his  lot  was 
line 3535=>wearisomely heavy, and did not at all like  the idea of trudging for miles and miles 
line 3536=>with all that on his back. 
line 3537=>"Don't you worry!" said Thorin. "It will get  lighter all  too soon. Before  long  I 
line 3538=>expect we shall all wish our packs heavier, when the food begins to run short." 
line 3539=>Then  at  last  they  said  good-bye  to  their  ponies  and  turned  their  heads  for 
line 3540=>home.  Off  they  trotted  gaily,  seeming  very  glad  to  put  their  tails  towards  the 
line 3541=>shadow of Mirkwood. As they went away Bilbo could have sworn that a thing like 
line 3542=>a bear left the shadow of the trees and shambled off quickly after them. 
line 3543=>Now Gandalf  too  said  farewell. Bilbo  sat on  the ground  feeling very unhappy 
line 3544=>and wishing he was beside the wizard on his tall horse. He had gone just inside the 
line 3545=>forest  after  breakfast  (a  very  poor  one),  and  it  had  seemed  as  dark  in  there  in  the 
line 3546=>morning  as  at  night,  and  very  secret:  "a  sort  of watching  and waiting  feeling,"  he 
line 3547=>said to himself. 
line 3548=>"Good-bye!"  said  Gandalf  to  Thorin.  "And  good-bye  to  you  all,  good-bye! 
line 3549=>Straight through the forest is your way now. Don't stray off the track!-if you do, it 
line 3550=>is  a  thousand  to one you will never  find  it  again  and never get out of Mirkwood; 
line 3551=>and then I don't suppose I, or any one else, will ever see you again." 
line 3552=>"Do we really have to go through?" groaned the hobbit. 
line 3553=>"Yes, you do!" said the wizard, "if  you want to get to the other side. You must 
line 3554=>either go through or give up your quest. And I am not going to allow you to back 
line 3555=>out  now,  Mr.  Baggins.  I  am  ashamed  of  you  for  thinking  of  it.  You  have  got  to 
line 3556=>look after all these dwarves for me," he laughed. 
line 3557=>"No! no!" said Bilbo. "I didn't mean that. I meant, is there no way round?" 
line 3558=>"There is, if you care to go two hundred miles or so out of your way north, and 
line 3559=>twice  that  south.  But  you  wouldn't  get  a  safe  path  even  then.  There  are  no  safe 
line 3560=>paths  in  this part of  the world. Remember you are over the Edge of the Wild now, 
line 3561=>and in for all sorts of fun wherever you go. Before you could get round Mirkwood 
line 3562=>in  the  North  you  would  be  right  among  the  slopes  of  the  Grey  Mountains,  and 
line 3563=>they  are  simply  stiff  with  goblins,  hobgoblins,  and  rest  of  the  worst  description. 
line 3564=>Before  you  could  get  round  it  in  the  South,  you  would  get  into  the  land  of  the 
line 3565=>Necromancer;  and  even  you.  Bilbo, won't  need me  to  tell  you  tales  of  that  black 
line 3566=>
line 3567=>####-sorcerer. I don't advise you to go anywhere near the places overlooked by his dark 
line 3568=>tower! Stick  to  the  forest-track, keep your spirits up, hope for the best, and with a 
line 3569=>tremendous  slice  of  luck  you  may  come  out  one  day  and  see  the  Long  Marshes 
line 3570=>lying  below  you,  and  beyond  them,  high  in  the East,  the Lonely Mountain where 
line 3571=>dear old Smaug lives, though I hope he is not expecting you." 
line 3572=>"Very  comforting  you  are  to  be  sure,"  growled  Thorin.  "Good-bye!  If  you 
line 3573=>won't come with us, you had better get off without any more talk!" 
line 3574=>"Good-bye  then,  and  really  good-bye!"  said  Gandalf,  and  he  turned  his  horse 
line 3575=>and  rode  down  into  the West.  But  he  could  not  resist  the  temptation  to  have  the 
line 3576=>last word. Before he had passed quite out of hearing he turned and put his hands to 
line 3577=>his mouth  and  called  to  them. They  heard  his  voice  come  faintly:  "Good-bye! Be 
line 3578=>good, take care of yourselves-and DON'T LEAVE THE PATH!" 
line 3579=>Then he galloped away and was soon lost to sight. "O good-bye and go away!" 
line 3580=>grunted  the  dwarves,  all  the  more  angry  because  they  were  really  filled  with 
line 3581=>dismay at losing him. Now began the most dangerous part of all the journey.  
line 3582=>They  each  shouldered  the  heavy  pack  and  the  water-skin  which  was  their 
line 3583=>share, and turned from the light that lay on the lands outside and plunged into the 
line 3584=>forest.  
line 3585=> 
line 3586=>
line 3587=>####-<h4>Chapter 8 </h4> <br>
line 3588=>
line 3589=>Flies and Spiders 
line 3590=>
line 3591=> 
line 3592=>They  walked  in  single  file.  The  entrance  to  the  path  was  like  a  sort  of  arch 
line 3593=>leading  into  a  gloomy  tunnel made  by  two  great  trees  that  leant  together,  too  old 
line 3594=>and  strangled  with  ivy  and  hung  with  lichen  to  bear  more  than  a  few  blackened 
line 3595=>leaves. The  path  itself was  narrow and wound in and out among the trunks. Soon 
line 3596=>the  light  at  the  gate  was  like  a  little  bright  hole  far  behind,  and  the  quiet  was  so 
line 3597=>deep that their feet seemed to thump along while all the trees leaned over them and 
line 3598=>listened. As  theft  eyes  became  used  to  the  dimness  they  could  see  a  little way  to 
line 3599=>either  side  in  a  sort  of  darkened  green  glimmer.  Occasionally  a  slender  beam  of 
line 3600=>sun  that had  the  luck  to slip  in  through some opening  in  the  leaves far above, and 
line 3601=>still  more  luck  in  not  being  caught  in  the  tangled  boughs  and  matted  twigs 
line 3602=>beneath,  stabbed  down  thin  and  bright  before  them.  But  this  was  seldom,  and  it 
line 3603=>soon ceased altogether.  
line 3604=>There were  black  squirrels  in  the wood. As  Bilbo's  sharp  inquisitive  eyes  got 
line 3605=>used  to  seeing  things  he  could  catch  glimpses  of  them whisking  off  the  path  and 
line 3606=>scuttling  behind  tree-trunks.  There  were  queer  noises  too,  grunts,  scufflings,  and 
line 3607=>hurryings  in  the undergrowth, and among  the  leaves  that  lay piled endlessly  thick 
line 3608=>in  places  on  the  forest-floor;  but  what  made  the  noises  he  could  not  see.  The 
line 3609=>nastiest  things  they  saw  were  the  cobwebs:  dark  dense  cobwebs  with  threads 
line 3610=>extraordinarily  thick,  often  stretched  from  tree  to  tree,  or  tangled  in  the  lower 
line 3611=>branches  on  either  side  of  them.  There  were  none  stretched  across  the  path,  but 
line 3612=>whether because some magic kept it clear, or for what other reason they could not 
line 3613=>guess. 
line 3614=>It was not long before they grew to hate the forest as heartily as they had hated 
line 3615=>the tunnels of the goblins, and it seemed to offer even less hope of any ending. But 
line 3616=>they had to go on and on, long after they were sick for a sight of the sun and of the 
line 3617=>sky, and  longed for  the feel of wind on  their faces. There was no movement of air 
line 3618=>down under the forest-roof, and it was everlastingly still and dark and stuffy. Even 
line 3619=>the dwarves felt it, who were used to tunnelling, and lived at times for long whiles 
line 3620=>without the light of the sun; but the hobbit, who liked holes to make a house in but 
line 3621=>not to spend summer days in, felt he was being slowly suffocated. 
line 3622=>The nights were the worst. It then became pitch-dark â€“ not what you call pitch-
line 3623=>dark,  but  really  pitch;  so  black  that  you  really  could  see  nothing.  Bilbo  tried 
line 3624=>flapping his hand in front of his nose, but he could not see it at all. Well, perhaps it 
line 3625=>
line 3626=>####-is  not  true  to  say  that  they  could  see  nothing:  they  could  see  eyes. They  slept  all 
line 3627=>closely  huddled  together,  and  took  it  in  turns  to  watch;  and  when  it  was  Bilbo's 
line 3628=>turn  he  would  see  gleams  in  the  darkness  round  them,  and  sometimes  pairs  of 
line 3629=>yellow  or  red  or  green  eyes  would  stare  at  him  from  a  little  distance,  and  then 
line 3630=>slowly  fade  and  disappear  and  slowly  shine  out  again  in  another  place.  And 
line 3631=>sometimes  they  would  gleam  down  from  the  branches  just  above  him;  and  that 
line 3632=>was most terrifying. But the eyes that he liked the least were horrible pale bulbous 
line 3633=>sort  of  eyes.  "Insect  eyes"  he  thought,  "not  animal  eyes,  only  they  are  much  too 
line 3634=>big." 
line 3635=>Although  it was  not  yet  very  cold,  they  tried  lighting watch-fires at night, but 
line 3636=>they  soon  gave  that  up.  It  seemed  to  bring  hundreds  and  hundreds  of  eyes  all 
line 3637=>round  them,  though  the  creatures,  whatever  they  were,  were  careful  never  to  let 
line 3638=>their bodies show in the little flicker of the flames. Worse still it brought thousands 
line 3639=>of  dark-grey  and  black  moths,  some  nearly  as  big  as  your  hand,  flapping  and 
line 3640=>whirring  round their ears. They could not stand that, nor the huge bats, black as a 
line 3641=>top-hat,  either;  so  they  gave  up  fires  and  sat  at  night  and  dozed  in  the  enormous 
line 3642=>uncanny darkness. 
line 3643=>All  this  went  on  for  what  seemed  to  the  hobbit  ages  upon  ages;  and  he  was 
line 3644=>always  hungry,  for  they were extremely careful with  their provisions. Even  so, as 
line 3645=>days  followed  days,  and  still  the  forest  seemed  just  the  same,  they  began  to  get 
line 3646=>anxious. The  food would not  last  for  ever:  it was  in  fact  already beginning  to get 
line 3647=>low. They tried shooting at the squirrels, and they wasted many arrows before they 
line 3648=>managed  to  bring  one  down  on  the  path.  But  when  they  roasted  it,  it  proved 
line 3649=>horrible to taste, and they shot no more squirrels. 
line 3650=>They  were  thirsty  too,  for  they  had  none  too  much  water,  and  in  all  the  time 
line 3651=>they  had  seen  neither  spring  nor  stream.  This  was  their  state  when  one  day  they 
line 3652=>found their path blocked by a running water. It flowed fast and strong but not very 
line 3653=>wide right across  the way, and  it was black, or  looked  it  in  the gloom. It was well 
line 3654=>that  Beorn  had  warned  them  against  it,  or  they  would  have  drunk  from  it, 
line 3655=>whatever  its  colour,  and  filled  some  of  their  emptied  skins  at  its  bank. As  it was 
line 3656=>they only thought of how to cross it without wetting themselves in its water. There 
line 3657=>had  been  a  bridge  of  wood  across,  but  it  had  rotted  and  fallen  leaving  only  the 
line 3658=>broken posts near the bank. 
line 3659=>Bilbo kneeling on the brink and peering forward cried: "There is a boat against 
line 3660=>the far bank! Now why couldn't it have been this side!" 
line 3661=>"How far away do you think it is?" asked Thorin, for by now they knew Bilbo 
line 3662=>had the sharpest eyes among them. 
line 3663=>
line 3664=>####-"Not at all far. I shouldn't think above twelve yards." 
line 3665=>"Twelve  yards!  I  should  have  thought  it was  thirty  at  least,  but my  eyes  don't 
line 3666=>see  as  well  as  they  used  a  hundred  years  ago.  Still  twelve  yards  is  as  good  as  a 
line 3667=>mile. We can't jump it, and we daren't try to wade or swim." 
line 3668=>"Can any of you throw a rope?" 
line 3669=>"What's the good of that? The boat is sure to be tied up, even if we could hook 
line 3670=>it, which I doubt." 
line 3671=>"I  don't  believe  it  is  tied,"  said Bilbo,  "though of  course  I  can't be  sure  in  this 
line 3672=>light;  but  it  looks  to me  as  if  it was  just  drawn  up  on  the  bank, which  is  low  just 
line 3673=>there where the path goes down into the water." 
line 3674=>"Dori is the strongest, but Fili is the youngest and still  has the best sight," said 
line 3675=>Thorin.  "Come  here  Fili,  and  see  if  you  can  see  the  boat  Mr.  Baggins  is  talking 
line 3676=>about." 
line 3677=>Fili thought he could; so when he had stared a long while to get an idea of the 
line 3678=>direction,  the  others  brought  him  a  rope.  They  had  several with  them, and on  the 
line 3679=>end  of  the  longest  they  fastened  one  of  the  large  iron  hooks  they  had  used  for 
line 3680=>catching  their packs  to  the  straps  about  their  shoulders. Fili  took  this  in his hand, 
line 3681=>balanced it for a moment, and then flung it across the stream. 
line 3682=>Splash  it  fell  in  the  water!  "Not  far  enough!"  said  Bilbo  who  was  peering 
line 3683=>forward.  "A  couple  of  feet  and  you  would  have  dropped  it  on  to  the  boat.  Try 
line 3684=>again.  I don't  suppose  the magic  is  strong  enough  to hurt you,  if you  just  touch  a 
line 3685=>bit of wet rope." 
line 3686=>Fili  picked  up  the  hook when  he  had  drawn  it  back,  rather  doubtfully  all  the 
line 3687=>same. This time he threw it with greater strength. 
line 3688=>"Steady!" said Bilbo, "you have thrown it right into the wood on the other side 
line 3689=>now.  Draw  it  back  gently."  Fili  hauled  the  rope  back  slowly,  and  after  a  while 
line 3690=>Bilbo said: 
line 3691=>"Carefully! It is lying on the boat; let's hope the hook will catch." 
line 3692=>It  did.  The  rope went  taut,  and  Fili  pulled  in  vain. Kili  came  to  his  help,  and 
line 3693=>then  Oin  and  Gloin.  They  tugged  and  tugged,  and  suddenly  they  all  fell  over  on 
line 3694=>their backs. Bilbo was on  the  lockout, however, caught  the rope, and with a piece 
line 3695=>of  stick  fended  off  the  little  black  boat  as  it  came  rushing  across  the  stream. 
line 3696=>"Help!"  he  shouted,  and Balin was  just  in  time  to  seize  the  boat  before  it  floated 
line 3697=>off down the current. 
line 3698=>"It  was  tied  after  all,"  said  he,  looking  at  the  snapped  painter  that  was  still 
line 3699=>dangling  from  it.  "That  was  a  good  pull,  my  lads;  and  a  good  job  that  our  rope 
line 3700=>was the stronger." 
line 3701=>
line 3702=>####-"Who'll cross first?" asked Bilbo. 
line 3703=>"I  shall,"  said Thorin,  "and  you will come with me, and Fili and Balin. That's 
line 3704=>as  many  as  the  boat  will  hold  at  a  time.  After  that  Kili  and  Oin  and  Gloin  and 
line 3705=>Don; next On and Nori, Bifur and Bofur; and last Dwalin and Bombur." 
line 3706=>"I'm  always  last  and  I  don't  like  it,"  said  Bombur.  "It's  somebody  else's  turn 
line 3707=>today." 
line 3708=>"You  should  not  be  so  fat. As  you  are,  you must  be with  the  last  and  lightest 
line 3709=>boatload.  Don't  start  grumbling  against  orders,  or  something  bad  will  happen  to 
line 3710=>you." 
line 3711=>"There  aren't  any  oars.  How  are  you  going  to  push  the  boat  back  to  the  far 
line 3712=>bank?" asked the hobbit. 
line 3713=>"Give me  another  length  of  rope  and  another  hook,"  said  Fili,  and when  they 
line 3714=>had got  it  ready, he cast  into  the darkness ahead and as high as he could  throw  it. 
line 3715=>Since  it did not  fall down again,  they saw  that  it must have stuck in the branches. 
line 3716=>"Get  in now," said Fili, "and one of you haul on  the rope  that  is stuck  in a  tree on 
line 3717=>the other  side. One of  the others must keep hold of  the hook we used  at  first,  and 
line 3718=>when we  are  safe  on  the  other  side  he  can  hook  it  on,  and  you  can draw  the boat 
line 3719=>back." 
line 3720=>In  this  way  they  were  all  soon  on  the  far  bank  safe  across  the  enchanted 
line 3721=>stream.  Dwalin  had  just  scrambled  out  with  the  coiled  rope  on  his  arm,  and 
line 3722=>Bombur  (still  grumbling)  was  getting  ready  to  follow,  when  something  bad  did 
line 3723=>happen. There was a  flying  sound of hooves on  the path ahead. Out of  the gloom 
line 3724=>came suddenly  the shape of a  flying deer.  It charged  into  the dwarves and bowled 
line 3725=>them  over,  then  gathered  itself  for  a  leap.  High  it  sprang  and  cleared  the  water 
line 3726=>with  a  mighty  jump.  But  it  did  not  reach  the  other  side  in  safety. Thorin was  the 
line 3727=>only  one  who  had  kept  his  feet  and  his  wits.  As  soon  as  they  had  landed  he  had 
line 3728=>bent his bow and fitted an arrow in case any hidden guardian of the boat appeared. 
line 3729=>Now he  sent  a  swift  and  sure  shot  into the leaping beast. As it reached the further 
line 3730=>bank  it  stumbled.  The  shadows  swallowed  it  up,  but  they  heard  the  sound  of 
line 3731=>hooves quickly falter and then go still. 
line 3732=>Before  they  could  shout  in  praise  of  the  shot,  however,  a  dreadful  wail  from 
line 3733=>Bilbo  put  all  thoughts  of  venison  out  of  their  minds.  "Bombur  has  fallen  in! 
line 3734=>Bombur is drowning!" he cried. It was only too true. Bombur had only one foot on 
line 3735=>the land when the hart bore down on him, and sprang over him. He had stumbled, 
line 3736=>thrusting the boat away from the bank, and then toppled back into the dark water, 
line 3737=>his  hands  slipping  off  the  slimy  roots  at  the  edge,  while  the  boat  span  slowly  off 
line 3738=>and disappeared. 
line 3739=>
line 3740=>####-They  could  still  see  his  hood  above  the  water  when  they  ran  to  the  bank. 
line 3741=>Quickly  they  flung  a  rope with  a  hook towards him. His hand caught it, and they 
line 3742=>pulled  him  to  the  shore.  He  was  drenched  from  hair  to  boots,  of  course,  but  that 
line 3743=>was  not  the  worst.  When  they  laid  him  on  the  bank  he  was  already  fast  asleep, 
line 3744=>with one hand clutching the rope so tight that they could not get it from his grasp; 
line 3745=>and  fast asleep he  remained  in  spite of all  they could do. They were  still  standing 
line 3746=>over him,  cursing  their  ill  luck,  and Bombur's  clumsiness,  and  lamenting  the  loss 
line 3747=>of  the  boat  which  made  it  impossible  for  them  to  go  back  and  look  for  the  hart, 
line 3748=>when  they became  aware of  the dim blowing of horns  in  the wood  and  the  sound 
line 3749=>as  of  dogs  baying  far  off.  Then  they  all  fell  silent;  and  as  they  sat  it  seemed  they 
line 3750=>could hear  the noise of a great hunt going by  to  the north of  the path, though they 
line 3751=>saw no sign of it. There they sat for a long while and did not dare to make a move. 
line 3752=>Bombur  slept  on with  a  smile  on  his  fat  face,  as  if  he  no  longer  cared  for  all  the 
line 3753=>troubles that vexed them. 
line 3754=>Suddenly  on  the  path  ahead  appeared  some  white  deer,  a  hind  and  fawns  as 
line 3755=>snowy  white  as  the  hart  had  been  dark.  They  glimmered  in  the  shadows.  Before 
line 3756=>Thorin  could  cry  out  three  of  the  dwarves  had  leaped  to  their  feet  and  loosed  off 
line 3757=>arrows  from  their  bows.  None  seemed  to  find  their  mark.  The  deer  turned  and 
line 3758=>vanished  in  the  trees  as  silently  as  they  had  come,  and  in  vain  the  dwarves  shot 
line 3759=>their arrows after them. 
line 3760=>"Stop!  stop!"  shouted  Thorin;  but  it  was  too  late,  the  excited  dwarves  had 
line 3761=>wasted  their  last  arrows,  and  now  the  bows  that  Beorn  had  given  them  were 
line 3762=>useless. 
line 3763=>They  were  a  gloomy  party  that  night,  and  the  gloom  gathered  still  deeper  on 
line 3764=>them in the following days. They had crossed the enchanted stream; but beyond it 
line 3765=>the  path  seemed  to  straggle  on  just  as  before,  and  in  the  forest  they  could  see  no 
line 3766=>change.  Yet  if  they  had  known  more  about  it  and  considered  the  meaning  of  the 
line 3767=>hunt  and  the  white  deer  that  had  appeared  upon  their  path,  they  would  have 
line 3768=>known  that  they  were  at  last  drawing  towards  the  eastern  edge,  and  would  soon 
line 3769=>have  come,  if  they  could  have  kept  up  their  courage  and  their  hope,  to  thinner 
line 3770=>trees and places where the sunlight came again. 
line 3771=>But  they  did  not  know  this,  and  they  were  burdened  with  the  heavy  body  of 
line 3772=>Bombur,  which  they  had  to  carry  along  with  them  as  best  they  could,  taking  the 
line 3773=>wearisome  task  in  turns  of  four  each while  the  others  shared  their  packs.  If  these 
line 3774=>had not become all too light in the last few days, they would never have managed 
line 3775=>it;  but  a  slumbering  and  smiling  Bombur  was  a  poor  exchange  for  packs  filled 
line 3776=>with  food  however  heavy.  In  a  few  days  a  time  came when  there was  practically 
line 3777=>
line 3778=>####-nothing  left  to  eat  or  to  drink. Nothing wholesome  could  they  see  growing  in  the 
line 3779=>woods, only funguses and herbs with pale leaves and unpleasant smell. 
line 3780=>About four days from the enchanted stream they  came to a part where most of 
line 3781=>the trees were beeches. They were at first inclined to be cheered by the change, for 
line 3782=>here  there  was  no  undergrowth  and  the  shadow  was  not  so  deep.  There  was  a 
line 3783=>greenish light about them, and in places they could see some distance to either side 
line 3784=>of  the  path.  Yet  the  light  only  showed  them  endless  lines  of  straight  grey  trunks 
line 3785=>like the pillars of some huge twilight hall. There was a breath of air and a noise of 
line 3786=>wind,  but  it  had  a  sad  sound.  A  few  leaves  came  rustling  down  to  remind  them 
line 3787=>that  outside  autumn was  coming  on.  Their  feet  ruffled  among  the  dead  leaves  of 
line 3788=>countless other  autumns  that drifted over  the banks of  the path  from  the deep  red 
line 3789=>carpets of the forest. 
line 3790=>Still Bombur  slept  and  they grew very weary. At  times  they heard disquieting 
line 3791=>laughter.  Sometimes  there  was  singing  in  the  distance  too.  The  laughter  was  the 
line 3792=>laughter of fair voices not of goblins, and the singing was beautiful, but it sounded 
line 3793=>eerie and  strange, and  they were not comforted,  rather  they hurried on  from  those 
line 3794=>parts with what strength they had left. 
line 3795=>Two  days  later  they  found  their  path  going  downwards  and  before  long  they 
line 3796=>were in a valley filled almost entirely with a mighty growth of oaks. 
line 3797=>"Is there no end to this accursed forest?" said Thorin. 
line 3798=>"Somebody must climb a tree and see if he can get his head above the roof and 
line 3799=>have  a  look  round.  The  only  way  is  to  choose  the  tallest  tree  that  overhangs  the 
line 3800=>path." 
line 3801=>Of course "somebody" meant Bilbo. They chose him because  to be of any use 
line 3802=>the  climber  must  get  his  head  above  the  topmost  leaves,  and  so  he must  be  light 
line 3803=>enough for the highest and slenderest branches to bear him. Poor Mr. Baggins had 
line 3804=>never had much practice in climbing trees, but they hoisted him up into the lowest 
line 3805=>branches of an enormous oak that grew right out into the path, and up he had to go 
line 3806=>as best he could. He pushed his way through the tangled twigs with many a slap in 
line 3807=>the eye; he was greened and grimed from the old bark of the greater boughs; more 
line 3808=>than  once  he  slipped  and  caught  himself  just  in  time; and at  last, after a dreadful 
line 3809=>struggle  in  a  difficult  place  where  there  seemed  to  be  no  convenient  branches  at 
line 3810=>all, he got near the top. All the time he was wondering whether there were spiders 
line 3811=>in the tree, and how he was going to get down again (except by falling). 
line 3812=>In  the  end  he  poked  his  head  above  the  roof  of  leaves,  and  then  he  found 
line 3813=>spiders  all  right.  But  they  were  only  small  ones  of  ordinary  size,  and  they  were 
line 3814=>after  the  butterflies.  Bilbo's  eyes  were  nearly  blinded  by  the  light.  He  could  hear 
line 3815=>
line 3816=>####-the dwarves shouting up at him from far below, but he could not answer, only hold 
line 3817=>on  and  blink.  The  sun  was  shining  brilliantly,  and  it  was  a  long  while  before  he 
