line 3827=>trees  and  the  leaves  in  any  direction.  His  heart,  that  had  been  lightened  by  the 
line 3828=>sight of the sun and the feel of the wind, sank back into his toes: there was no food 
line 3829=>to go back to down below.  
line 3830=>Actually, as I have told you, they were not far off the edge of the forest; and if 
line 3831=>Bilbo had had the sense to see it, the tree that he had climbed, though it was tall in 
line 3832=>itself, was standing near  the bottom of a wide valley, so  that  from  its  top  the  trees 
line 3833=>seemed  to  swell  up  all  round  like  the  edges  of  a  great  bowl,  and  he  could  not 
line 3834=>expect  to  see  how  far  the  forest  lasted.  Still  he  did  not  see  this,  and  he  climbed 
line 3835=>down  full  of  despair.  He  got  to  the  bottom  again  at  last  scratched,  hot,  and 
line 3836=>miserable,  and  he  could  not  see  anything  in  the  gloom  below  when  he  got  there. 
line 3837=>His report soon made the others as miserable as he was. 
line 3838=>"The forest goes on for ever and ever and ever in all directions! Whatever shall 
line 3839=>we do? And what  is  the use of sending a hobbit!"  they cried, as if it was his fault. 
line 3840=>They did not care tuppence about the butterflies, and were only made more angry 
line 3841=>when he told them of the beautiful breeze, which they were too heavy to climb up 
line 3842=>and feel. 
line 3843=> 
line 3844=>That  night  they  ate  their  very  last  scraps  and  crumbs  of  food;  and  next 
line 3845=>morning  when  they  woke  the  first  thing  they  noticed  was  that  they  were  still 
line 3846=>gnawingly  hungry,  and  the  next  thing  was  that  it  was  raining  and  that  here  and 
line 3847=>there  the  drip  of  it  was  dropping  heavily  on  the  forest  floor.  That  only  reminded 
line 3848=>them  that  they  were  also  parchingly  thirsty,  without  doing  anything  to  relieve 
line 3849=>them: you cannot quench a terrible thirst by standing under giant oaks and waiting 
line 3850=>for  a  chance  drip  to  fall  on  your  tongue.  The  only  scrap  of  comfort  there  was, 
line 3851=>came unexpectedly from Bombur.  
line 3852=>
line 3853=>####-He woke  up  suddenly  and  sat  up  scratching  his  head. He  could  not make  out 
line 3854=>where  he  was  at  all,  nor  why  he  felt  so  hungry;  for  he  had  forgotten  everything 
line 3855=>that  had  happened  since  they  started  their  journey  that  May  morning  long  ago. 
line 3856=>The  last  thing  that  he  remembered  was  the  party  at  the  hobbit's  house,  and  they 
line 3857=>had  great  difficulty  in  making  him  believe  their  tale  of  all  the  many  adventures 
line 3858=>they had had since. 
line 3859=>When he heard that there was nothing to eat, he sat down and wept, for he felt 
line 3860=>very  weak  and  wobbly  in  the  legs.  "Why  ever  did  I  wake  up!"  he  cried.  "I  was 
