line 3977=>fainter,  and  though  after  a while  it  seemed  to  him  they  changed  to  yells and cries 
line 3978=>for help  in  the  far distance, all noise at  last died  right away, and he was  left alone 
line 3979=>in complete silence and darkness. 
line 3980=> 
line 3981=>That was  one  of  his most miserable moments. But  he  soon made  up  his mind 
line 3982=>that  it was no good  trying  to do  anything  till  day came with some  little  light, and 
line 3983=>quite  useless  to  go  blundering  about  tiring  himself  out  with  no  hope  of  any 
line 3984=>breakfast to revive him. So he sat himself down with his back to a tree, and not for 
line 3985=>the  last  time  fell  to  thinking  of  his  far-distant  hobbit-hole  with  its  beautiful 
line 3986=>pantries. He was deep in thoughts of bacon and eggs and toast and butter when he 
