line 3995=>free.  He  beat  the  creature  off  with  his  hands-it  was  trying  to  poison  him  to  keep 
line 3996=>him  quiet,  as  small  spiders  do  to  flies-until he  remembered his  sword  and drew  it 
line 3997=>out. Then the spider jumped back, and he had time to cut his legs loose. After that 
line 3998=>it was  his  turn  to  attack.  The  spider  evidently was  not  used  to  things  that carried 
line 3999=>such stings at  their sides, or  it would have hurried away quicker. Bilbo came at  it 
line 4000=>before  it  could  disappear  and  struck  it  with  his  sword  right  in  the  eyes.  Then  it 
line 4001=>went mad  and  leaped  and  danced  and  flung  out  its  legs  in  horrible  jerks, until he 
line 4002=>
line 4003=>####-killed it with another stroke; and then he fell down and remembered nothing more 
line 4004=>for a long while. 
line 4005=>There was  the usual dim grey  light of  the  forest-day about him when he came 
line 4006=>to  his  senses.  The  spider  lay  dead  beside  him,  and  his  sword-blade  was  stained 
line 4007=>black.  Somehow  the  killing  of  the  giant  spider,  all  alone  by  himself  in  the  dark 
line 4008=>without  the  help  of  the  wizard  or  the  dwarves  or  of  anyone  else,  made  a  great 
line 4009=>difference  to Mr. Baggins. He  felt a different person, and much  fiercer and bolder 
line 4010=>in  spite  of  an  empty  stomach,  as  he wiped  his  sword  on  the  grass  and  put  it  back 
line 4011=>into its sheath. 
line 4012=>"I will give you a name," he said to it, "and I shall call you Sting." 
line 4013=>After  that he  set out  to  explore. The  forest was grim  and  silent, but obviously 
line 4014=>he  had  first  of  all  to  look  for  his  friends,  who  were  not  likely  to  be  very  far  off, 
line 4015=>unless they had been made prisoners by the elves (or worse things). 
line 4016=>Bilbo  felt  that  it was unsafe  to  shout,  and he  stood  a  long while wondering  in 
