line 4258=>their own troubles. Balin in particular insisted on having the Gollum story, riddles 
line 4259=>and  all,  told  all  over  again, with  the  ring  in  its  proper  place. But  after  a  time  the 
line 4260=>light  began  to  fail,  and  then  other  questions  were  asked.  Where  were  they,  and 
line 4261=>where was their path, and where was there any food, and what were they going to 
line 4262=>do  next?  These  questions  they  asked  over  and  over  again,  and  it  was  from  little 
line 4263=>Bilbo  that  they seemed  to expect  to get  the answers. From which you can see  that 
line 4264=>they had changed their opinion of Mr. Baggins very much, and had begun to have 
line 4265=>a  great  respect  for  him  (as  Gandalf  had  said  they  would).  Indeed  they  really 
line 4266=>expected  him  to  think  of  some  wonderful  plan  for  helping  them,  and  were  not 
line 4267=>merely  grumbling.  They  knew  only  too  well  that  they  would  soon  all  have  been 
line 4268=>dead, if it had not been for the hobbit; and they thanked him many times. Some of 
line 4269=>them even got up and bowed right to the ground before him, though they fell over 
line 4270=>with  the  effort,  and  could  not  get  on  their  legs  again  for  some  time. Knowing  the 
line 4271=>truth about  the vanishing did not  lessen  their opinion of Bilbo at all;  for  they saw 
line 4272=>that  he  had  some  wits,  as  well  as  luck  and  a  magic  ring-and  all  three  are  very 
line 4273=>useful possessions. In fact they praised him so much that Bilbo began to feel there 
line 4274=>really  was  something  of  a  bold  adventurer  about  himself  after  all,  though  he  I 
line 4275=>would have felt a lot bolder still, if there had been anything to eat. 
line 4276=>But there was nothing, nothing at all; and none of them Were fit to go and look 
line 4277=>for  anything,  or  to  search  for  the  lost  path.  The  lost  path!  No  other  idea  would 
line 4278=>
line 4279=>####-come into Bilbo's tired head. He just sat staring in front of him at the endless trees; 
line 4280=>and  after  a while  they  all  fell  silent  again. All  except Balin. Long  after  the others 
line 4281=>had  stopped  talking  and  shut  their  eyes,  he  kept  on  muttering  and  chuckling  to 
line 4282=>himself. 
line 4283=>"Gollum! Well I'm blest! So that's how he sneaked past me is it? Now I know! 
line 4284=>Just  crept  quietly  along  did  you,  Mr.  Baggins?  Buttons  all  over  the  doorstep? 
line 4285=>Good  old  Bilbo-Bilbo-Bilbo-bo-bo-boâ€“"  And  then  he  fell  asleep,  and  there  was 
line 4286=>complete silence for a long time. 
line 4287=>All  of  a  sudden Dwalin  opened  an  eye,  and  looked  round  at  them.  "Where  is 
line 4288=>Thorin?"  he  asked.  It  was  a  terrible  shock.  Of  course  there  were  only  thirteen of 
line 4289=>them,  twelve dwarves and  the hobbit. Where  indeed was Thorin? They wondered 
line 4290=>what  evil  fate  had  befallen  him,  magic  or  dark  monsters;  and  shuddered  as  they 
line 4291=>lay  lost  in  the  forest. There  they dropped off one by one  into uncomfortable  sleep 
line 4292=>full  of  horrible  dreams,  as  evening wore  to  black  night;  and  there we must  leave 
line 4293=>them for the present, too sick and weary to set guards or take turns watching. 
line 4294=>Thorin  had  been  caught  much  faster  than  they  had.  You  remember  Bilbo 
line 4295=>falling  like  a  log  into  sleep,  as  he  stepped  into  a  circle  of  light?  The  next  time  it 
line 4296=>had  been  Thorin  who  stepped  forward,  and  as  the  lights  went  out  he  fell  like  a 
line 4297=>stone  enchanted.  All  the  noise  of  the  dwarves  lost  in  the  night,  their  cries  as  the 
line 4298=>spiders caught them and bound them, and all the sounds of the battle next day, had 
line 4299=>passed over him unheard. Then the Wood-elves had come to him, and bound him, 
line 4300=>and carried him away. The feasting people were Wood-elves, of course. These are 
line 4301=>not wicked folk. If they have a fault it is distrust of strangers. Though their magic 
line 4302=>was strong, even in those days they were wary. They differed from the High Elves 
line 4303=>of  the West,  and were more  dangerous  and  less wise.  For most  of  them  (together 
line 4304=>with  their  scattered  relations  in  the hills  and mountains) were  descended from the 
line 4305=>ancient  tribes  that never went  to Faerie  in  the West. There  the Light-elves and the 
line 4306=>Deep-elves  and  the  Sea-elves  went  and  lived  for  ages,  and  grew  fairer  and  wiser 
line 4307=>and more learned, and invented their magic and their cunning craft, in the making 
line 4308=>of  beautiful  and marvellous  things,  before  some  came  back  into  the Wide World. 
line 4309=>In  the Wide World  the Wood-elves  lingered  in  the  twilight of  our Sun  and Moon 
line 4310=>but  loved  best  the  stars;  and  they  wandered  in  the  great  forests  that  grew  tall  in 
line 4311=>lands  that  are  now  lost.  They  dwelt  most  often  by  the  edges  of  the  woods,  from 
line 4312=>which they could escape at times to hunt, or to ride and run over the open lands by 
line 4313=>moonlight or starlight; and after the coming of Men they took ever more and more 
line 4314=>to  the  gloaming  and  the  dusk. Still  elves  they were  and  remain,  and  that  is Good 
line 4315=>People. 
line 4316=>
line 4317=>####-In  a  great  cave  some  miles  within  the  edge  of  Mirkwood  on  its  eastern  side 
line 4318=>there  lived  at  this  time  their  greatest  king. Before  his  huge  doors  of  stone  a  river 
line 4319=>ran  out  of  the  heights  of  the  forest  and  flowed on  and out  into  the marshes  at  the 
line 4320=>feet of the high wooded lands. This great cave, from which countless smaller ones 
line 4321=>opened  out  on  every  side,  wound  far  underground  and  had  many  passages  and 
line 4322=>wide  halls;  but  it was  lighter  and more wholesome  than  any  goblin-dwelling, and 
line 4323=>neither so deep nor so dangerous. In fact the subjects of the king mostly lived and 
line 4324=>hunted  in  the  open  woods,  and  had  houses  or  huts  on  the  ground  and  in  the 
line 4325=>branches. The  beeches were  their  favourite  trees. The  king's  cave  was his palace, 
line 4326=>and  the  strong  place  of  his  treasure,  and  the  fortress  of  his  people  against  their 
line 4327=>enemies. 
line 4328=>It was  also  the  dungeon  of  his  prisoners.  So  to  the  cave  they  dragged Thorin-
line 4329=>not  too  gently,  for  they  did  not  love  dwarves,  and  thought  he  was  an  enemy.  In 
line 4330=>ancient days  they had had wars with some of  the dwarves, whom  they accused of 
line 4331=>stealing  their  treasure.  It  is  only  fair  to  say  that  the  dwarves  gave  a  different 
line 4332=>account, and said that they only took what was their due, for the elf-king had bar- 
line 4333=>gained with  them  to  shape  his  raw  gold  and  silver,  and  had  afterwards  refused  to 
line 4334=>give  them  their  pay.  If  the  elf-king had  a weakness  it was  for  treasure,  especially 
line 4335=>for  silver  and  white  gems;  and  though  his  hoard  was  rich,  he  was  ever  eager  for 
line 4336=>more, since he  had not yet  as great  a  treasure  as other  elf-lords of old. His people 
line 4337=>neither mined nor worked metals or jewels, nor did they bother much with trade or 
line 4338=>with  tilling  the  earth.  All  this  was  well  known  to  every  dwarf,  though  Thorin's 
line 4339=>family had had nothing  to do with the old quarrel I have spoken of. Consequently 
line 4340=>Thorin was angry at their treatment of him, when they took their spell off him and 
line 4341=>he came  to his senses; and also he was determined  that no word of gold or  jewels 
line 4342=>should be dragged out of him. 
line 4343=>The  king  looked  sternly  on  Thorin,  when  he  was  brought  before  him,  and 
line 4344=>asked him many questions. But Thorin would only say that he was starving. 
line 4345=>"Why  did  you  and  your  folk  three  times  try  to  attack  my  people  at  their 
line 4346=>merrymaking?" asked the king. 
line 4347=>"We  did  not  attack  them,"  answered  Thorin;  "we  came  to  beg,  because  we 
line 4348=>were starving." 
line 4349=>"Where are your friends now, and what are they doing?" 
line 4350=>"I don't know, but I expect starving in the forest." 
line 4351=>"What were you doing in the forest?" 
line 4352=>"Looking for food and drink, because we were starving." 
line 4353=>"But what brought you into the forest at all?" asked the king angrily.  
line 4354=>
line 4355=>####-At that Thorin shut his mouth and would not say another word. 
line 4356=>"Very well!"  said  the  king.  "Take  him  away  and  keep  him  safe,  until  he  feels 
line 4357=>inclined to tell the truth, even if he waits a hundred years.'" 
line 4358=>Then the elves put thongs on him, and shut him in one of the inmost caves with 
line 4359=>strong wooden doors, and left him. They gave him food and drink, plenty of both, 
line 4360=>if  not  very  fine;  for  Wood-elves  were  not  goblins,  and  were  reasonably  well-
line 4361=>behaved even  to  their worst enemies, when  they captured  them. The giant  spiders 
line 4362=>were the only living things that they had no mercy upon. 
line 4363=>There  in  the  king's  dungeon  poor  Thorin  lay;  and  after  he  had  got  over  his 
line 4364=>thankfulness  for bread  and meat and water, he began to wonder what had become 
line 4365=>of  his  unfortunate  friends.  It  was  not  very  long  before  he  discovered;  but  that 
line 4366=>belongs  to  the  next  chapter  and  the  beginning  of  another  adventure  in  which  the 
line 4367=>hobbit again showed his usefulness. 
line 4368=> 
line 4369=>
line 4370=>####-<h4>Chapter 9 </h4> <br> <br>
line 4371=>
line 4372=>Barrels Out of Bond 
line 4373=>
line 4374=> 
line 4375=>The day  after  the battle with  the  spiders Bilbo  and  the dwarves made one  last 
line 4376=>despairing effort  to find a way out before  they died of hunger and  thirst. They got 
line 4377=>up  and  staggered  on  in  the  direction  which  eight  out  of  the  thirteen  of  them 
line 4378=>guessed to be the one in which the path lay; but they never found out if they were 
line 4379=>right.  Such  day  as  there  ever  was  in  the  forest  was  fading  once  more  into  the 
line 4380=>blackness of night, when  suddenly out  sprang  the  light of many  torches  all  round 
line 4381=>them,  like  hundreds  of  red  stars.  Out  leaped  Wood-elves  with  their  bows  and 
line 4382=>spears and called the dwarves to halt. 
line 4383=>There  was  no  thought  of  a  fight.  Even  if  the  dwarves  had  not  been  in  such  a 
line 4384=>state  that  they  were  actually  glad  to  be  captured,  their  small  knives,  the  only 
line 4385=>weapons  they had, would have been of no use against  the arrows of  the elves  that 
line 4386=>could  hit  a  bird's  eye  in  the  dark. So  they  simply  stopped  dead  and  sat  down  and 
line 4387=>waited-all except Bilbo, who popped on his ring and slipped quickly to one side. 
line 4388=>That  is why, when  the  elves bound  the dwarves  in  a  long  line, one behind  the 
line 4389=>other,  and  counted  them,  they  never  found  or  counted  the  hobbit.  Nor  did  they 
line 4390=>hear  or  feel  him  trotting  along  well  behind  their  torch-light  as  they  led  off  their 
line 4391=>prisoners  into  the  forest.  Each  dwarf  was  blindfold,  but  that  did  not  make  much 
line 4392=>difference,  for  even Bilbo with  the  use  of  his  eyes  could  not  see where  they were 
line 4393=>going,  and  neither  he  nor  the  others  knew  where  they  had  started  from  anyway. 
line 4394=>Bilbo  had  all  he  could  do  to  keep  up with  the  torches,  for  the  elves were making 
line 4395=>the dwarves go  as  fast  as  ever  they  could,  sick  and weary  as  they were. The king 
line 4396=>had ordered them to make haste. Suddenly the torches stopped, and the hobbit had 
line 4397=>just  time  to  catch  them  up  before  they  began  to  cross  the  bridge.  This  was  the 
line 4398=>bridge  that  led  across  the  river  to  the  king's  doors.  The  water  flowed  dark  and 
line 4399=>swift and strong beneath; and at the far end were gates before the mouth of a huge 
line 4400=>cave  that  ran  into  the  side  of  a  steep  slope  covered  with  trees.  There  the  great 
line 4401=>beeches came right down to the bank, till their feet were in the stream. Across this 
line 4402=>bridge the elves thrust their prisoners, but Bilbo hesitated in the rear. He did not at 
line 4403=>all  like  the  look  of  the  cavern-mouth  and  he  only made  up  his mind  not  to desert 
line 4404=>his friends just in time to scuttle over at the heels of the fast elves, before the great 
line 4405=>gates of the king closed behind them with a clang. 
line 4406=>Inside  the  passages  were  lit  with  red  torch-light,  and  the  elf-guards  sang  as 
line 4407=>they marched along  the  twisting, crossing, and echoing paths. These were not like 
line 4408=>
line 4409=>####-those  of  the  goblin-cities:  they  were  smaller,  less  deep  underground,  and  filled 
line 4410=>with  a  cleaner  air.  In  a  great  hall with  pillars  hewn  out  of  the  living  stone  sat  the 
line 4411=>Elvenking on a chair of carven wood. On his head was a crown of berries and red 
line 4412=>leaves,  for  the  autumn  was  come  again.  In  the  spring  he  wore  a  crown  of 
line 4413=>woodland flowers. In his hand he held a carven staff of oak. 
line 4414=>The prisoners were brought before him; and though he looked grimly at them, 
line 4415=>he  told  his  men  to  unbind  them,  for  they  were  ragged  and  weary.  "Besides  they 
line 4416=>need no ropes in here," said he. "There is no escape from my magic doors for those 
line 4417=>who are once brought inside." 
line 4418=>Long and searchingly he questioned the dwarves about their doings, and where 
line 4419=>they were going to, and where they were coming from; but he got little more news 
line 4420=>out  of  them  than  out  of  Thorin.  They  were  surly  and  angry  and  did  not  even 
line 4421=>pretend to be polite. 
line 4422=>"What  have  we  done,  O  king?"  said  Balin,  who  was  the  eldest  left.  "Is  it  a 
line 4423=>crime  to  be  lost  in  the  forest,  to  be  hungry  and  thirsty,  to  be  trapped  by  spiders? 
line 4424=>Are  the  spiders your  tame beasts or your pets,  if killing  them makes you  angry?" 
line 4425=>Such a question of course made the king angrier than ever, and he answered: "It is 
line 4426=>a crime  to wander  in my  realm without  leave. Do you  forget  that you were  in my 
line 4427=>kingdom,  using  the  road  that  my  people  made?  Did  you  not  three  times  pursue 
line 4428=>and  trouble  my  people  in  the  forest  and  '  rouse  the  spiders  with  your  riot  and 
line 4429=>clamour?  After  all  the  disturbance  you  have  made  I  have  a  right  to  know  what 
line 4430=>brings you here, and if you will not tell me now, I will keep you all in prison until 
line 4431=>you have learned sense and manners!" 
line 4432=>Then he ordered  the dwarves  each  to be put  in  a  separate  cell  and  to be given 
line 4433=>food and drink, but not  to be allowed  to pass  the doors of  their  little prisons, until 
line 4434=>one at  least of  them was willing  to  tell him all he wanted  to know. But be did not 
line 4435=>tell  them  that  Thorin  was  also  a  prisoner  with  him.  It  was  Bilbo  who  found  that 
line 4436=>out. 
line 4437=> 
line 4438=>Poor  Mr.  Baggins  â€“  it  was  a  weary  long  time  that  he  lived  in  that  place  all 
line 4439=>alone,  and  always  in  hiding,  never  daring  to  take  off  his  ring,  hardly  daring  to 
line 4440=>sleep,  even  tucked  away  in  the  darkest  and  remotest  comers  he  could  find.  For 
line 4441=>something  to  do  he  took  to wandering  about  the  Elven-king's palace. Magic shut 
line 4442=>the  gates,  but  be  could  sometimes  get  out,  if  he  was  quick.  Companies  of  the 
line 4443=>Wood-elves,  sometimes with  the  king  at  their  head, would  from  time  to  time  ride 
line 4444=>out  to hunt, or  to other business  in  the woods and in the lands to the East. Then if 
line 4445=>Bilbo  was  very  nimble,  he  could  slip  out  just  behind  them;  though  it  was  a 
line 4446=>
line 4447=>####-dangerous  thing  to do. More  than once he was nearly caught  in  the doors, as  they 
line 4448=>clashed  together  when  the  last  elf  passed;  yet  he  did  not  dare  to  march  among 
line 4449=>them  because  of  his  shadow  (altogether  thin  and wobbly  as  it was  in  torch-light), 
line 4450=>or  for  fear  of  being  bumped  into  and  discovered. And when  he  did  go  out, which 
line 4451=>was  not  very  often,  he  did  no  good.  He  did  not  wish  to  desert  the  dwarves, and 
line 4452=>indeed he did not know where in the world to go without them. He could not keep 
line 4453=>up  with  the  hunting  elves  all  the  time  they  were  out,  so  he  never  discovered  the 
line 4454=>ways  out  of  the wood,  and was  left  to wander miserably  in  the  forest,  terrified  of 
line 4455=>losing  himself,  until  a  chance  came  of  returning. He was  hungry  too  outside,  for 
line 4456=>he was  no  hunter;  but  inside  the  caves  he  could  pick  up  a  living  of  some  sort  by 
line 4457=>stealing  food  from  store  or  table  when  no  one  was  at  hand.  "I  am  like  a  burglar 
line 4458=>that  can't  get  away,  but must  go  on miserably  burgling  the  same  house  day  after 
line 4459=>day,"  he  thought.  "This  is  the  dreariest  and  dullest  part  of  all  this  wretched, 
line 4460=>tiresome,  uncomfortable  adventure!  I  wish  I  was  back  in  my  hobbit-hole  by my 
line 4461=>own warm fireside with the lamp shining!" He often wished, too, that he could get 
line 4462=>a message for help sent to the wizard, but that of course was quite impossible; and 
line 4463=>he soon  realized  that  if anything was  to be done,  it would have  to be done by Mr. 
line 4464=>Baggins, alone and unaided. 
line 4465=>Eventually,  after  a week  or  two  of  this  sneaking  sort  of  life,  by watching  and 
line 4466=>following  the  guards  and  taking  what  chances  he  could,  he  managed  to  find  out 
line 4467=>where each dwarf was kept. He found all their twelve cells in different parts of the 
line 4468=>palace,  and  after  a  time  he  got  to  know  his  way  about  very  well.  What  was  his 
line 4469=>surprise one day to overhear some of the guards talking and to learn that there was 
line 4470=>another dwarf in prison too, in a specially deep dark place. He guessed at once, of 
line 4471=>course,  that  that was  Thorin;  and  after  a while he  found  that his guess was  right. 
line 4472=>At  last  after  many  difficulties  he  managed  to  find  the  place  when  no  one  was 
line 4473=>about, and to have a word with the chief of the dwarves. Thorin was too wretched 
line 4474=>to  be  angry  any  longer  at  his  misfortunes,  and  was  even  beginning  to  think  of 
line 4475=>telling the king all about his treasure and his quest (which shows how low-spirited 
line 4476=>he had become), when he heard Bilbo's little voice at his keyhole. He could hardly 
line 4477=>believe  his  ears.  Soon  however  he  made  up  his  mind  that  he  could  not  be 
line 4478=>mistaken, and he came  to  the door and had a  long whispered  talk with  the hobbit 
line 4479=>on the other side. 
line 4480=>So  it was  that Bilbo was  able  to  take  secretly Thorin's message  to  each of  the 
line 4481=>other  imprisoned  dwarves,  telling  them  that  Thorin  their  chief was  also  in prison 
line 4482=>close  at  hand,  and  that  no  one was  to  reveal  their  errand  to  the  long,  not  yet,  not 
line 4483=>before  Thorin  gave  the  word.  For  Thorin  had  taken  heart  again  hearing  how  the 
line 4484=>
line 4485=>####-hobbit  had  rescued  his  companions  from  the  spiders,  and  was  determined  once 
line 4486=>more  not  to  ransom  himself  with  promises  to  the  king  of  a  share  in  the  treasure, 
line 4487=>until  all  hope  of  escaping  in  any  other  way  had  disappeared;  until  in  fact  the 
line 4488=>remarkable Mr. Invisible Baggins (of whom he began to have a very high opinion 
line 4489=>indeed) had altogether failed to think of something clever.  
line 4490=>The  other  dwarves  quite  agreed when  they  got  the message. They  all  thought 
line 4491=>their  own  shares  in  the  treasure  (which  they  quite  regarded  as  theirs,  in  spite  of 
line 4492=>their plight  and  the  still unconquered dragon) would  suffer  seriously if the Wood-
line 4493=>elves  claimed  part  of  it,  and  they  all  trusted  Bilbo.  Just  what  Gandalf  had  said 
line 4494=>would  happen,  you  see.  Perhaps  that  war  part  of  his  reason  for  going  off  and 
line 4495=>leaving them. 
line 4496=>Bilbo,  however,  did  not  feel  nearly  so  hopeful  as  they  did.  He  did  not  like 
line 4497=>being depended on by everyone, and he wished he had the wizard at hand. But that 
line 4498=>was no use: probably all the dark distance of Mirkwood lay between them. He sat 
line 4499=>and  thought  and  thought,  until  his  head  nearly  burst,  but  no  bright  idea  would 
line 4500=>come. One  invisible  ring was  a  very  fine  thing,  but  it was  not much  good  among 
line 4501=>fourteen. But of course, as you have guessed, he did  rescue his  friends  in  the end, 
line 4502=>and  this  is  how  it  happened.  One  day,  nosing  and  wandering  about.  Bilbo 
line 4503=>discovered  a  very  interesting  thing:  the  great  gates  were  not  the  only  entrance  to 
line 4504=>the  caves.  A  stream  flowed  under  part  of  the  lowest  regions  of  the  palace,  and 
line 4505=>joined the Forest River some way further to the east, beyond the steep slope out of 
line 4506=>which  the  main  mouth  opened.  Where  this  underground watercourse  came  forth 
line 4507=>from the hillside there was a water-gate. There the rocky roof came down close to 
line 4508=>the surface of the stream, and from it a portcullis could be dropped right to the bed 
line 4509=>of  the  river  to  prevent  anyone  coming  in  or  out  that way. But  the  portcullis was 
line 4510=>often open,  for a good deal of  traffic went out and  in by  the water-gate. If anyone 
line 4511=>had come in that way, he would have found himself in a dark rough tunnel leading 
line 4512=>deep into the heart of the hill; but at one point where it  passed under the caves the 
line 4513=>roof  had  been  cut  away  and  covered  with  great  oaken  trapdoors.  These  opened 
line 4514=>upwards  into  the  king's  cellars.  There  stood  barrels,  and  barrels,  and  barrels;  for 
line 4515=>the Wood-elves, and especially their king, were very fond of wine, though no vines 
line 4516=>grew in those parts. The wine, and other goods, were brought from far away, from 
line 4517=>their kinsfolk in the South, or from the vineyards of Men in distant lands. 
line 4518=>Hiding  behind  one  of  the  largest  barrels  Bilbo  discovered  the  trapdoors  and 
line 4519=>their  use,  and  lurking  there,  listening  to  the  talk of  the king's  servants, he  learned 
line 4520=>how the wine and other goods came up the rivers, or over land, to the Long Lake. 
line 4521=>It  seemed  a  town of Men  still  throve  there, built out on bridges  far  into  the water 
line 4522=>
line 4523=>####-as  a  protection  against  enemies  of  all  sorts,  and  especially  against  the  dragon  of 
line 4524=>the  Mountain.  From  Lake-town  the  barrels  were  brought  up  the  Forest  River. 
line 4525=>Often they were just tied together like big rafts and poled or rowed up the stream; 
line 4526=>sometimes they were loaded on to flat boats. 
line 4527=>When  the  barrels  were  empty  the  elves  cast  them  through  the  trapdoors, 
line 4528=>opened  the  water-gate,  and  out  the  barrels  floated  on  the  stream,  bobbing  along, 
line 4529=>until they were carried by the current to a place far down the river where the bank 
line 4530=>jutted  out,  near  to  the  very  eastern  edge  of Mirkwood. There  they were  collected 
line 4531=>and  tied  together  and  floated  back  to  Lake-town,  which  stood  close  to  the  point 
line 4532=>where the Forest River flowed into the Long Lake. 
line 4533=> 
line 4534=>For  some  time Bilbo  sat and  thought about  this water-gate, and wondered if it 
line 4535=>could  be  used  for  the  escape  of  his  friends,  and  at  last  he  had  the  desperate 
line 4536=>beginnings of a plan. 
line 4537=>The  evening meal had been  taken  to  the prisoners. The guards were  tramping 
line 4538=>away  down  the  passages  taking  the  torch-light  with  them  and  leaving  everything 
line 4539=>in  darkness.  Then  Bilbo  heard  the  king's  butler  bidding  the  chief  of  the  guards 
line 4540=>good-night. 
line 4541=>"Now come with me," he said, "and taste the new wine that has just come in. I 
line 4542=>shall be hard at work tonight clearing the cellars of the empty wood, so let us have 
line 4543=>a drink first to help the labour." 
line 4544=>"Very good," laughed the chief of the guards. "I'll taste with you, and see if it is 
line 4545=>fit for the king's table. There is a feast tonight and it would not do to send up poor 
line 4546=>stuff!" 
line 4547=> 
line 4548=>When  he  heard  this  Bilbo  was  all  in  a  flutter,  for  he  saw  that  luck  was  with 
line 4549=>him  and  he  had  a  chance  at  once  to  try  his  desperate  plan.  He  followed  the  two 
line 4550=>elves, until  they entered a small cellar and sat down at a  table on which  two  large 
line 4551=>flagons were set. Soon they began to drink and laugh merrily. Luck of an unusual 
line 4552=>kind was with Bilbo  then.  It must be potent wine  to make a wood-elf drowsy; but 
line 4553=>this wine, it would seem, was the heady vintage of the great gardens of Dorwinion, 
line 4554=>not  meant  for  his  soldiers  or  his  servants,  but  for  the  king's  feasts  only,  and  for 
line 4555=>smaller bowls, not for the butler's great flagons. 
line 4556=>Very soon the chief guard nodded his head, then he laid it on the table and fell 
line 4557=>fast asleep. The butler went on talking and laughing to himself for a while without 
line 4558=>seeming to notice, but soon his head too nodded to the table, and he fell asleep and 
line 4559=>snored  beside  his  friend.  Then  in  crept  the  hobbit.  Very  soon  the chief guard had 
line 4560=>
line 4561=>####-no  keys,  but Bilbo was  trotting  as  fast  as  he  could  along  the  passage  towards  the 
line 4562=>cells. The  great  bunch  seemed  very  heavy  to  his  arms,  and  his  heart was  often  in 
line 4563=>his  mouth,  in  spite  of  his  ring,  for  he  could  not  prevent  the  keys  from  making 
line 4564=>every now and then a loud clink and clank, which put him all in a tremble. 
line 4565=>First  he  unlocked  Balin's  door,  and  locked  it  again  carefully  as  soon  as  the 
line 4566=>dwarf was  outside. Balin was most  surprised,  as  you  can  imagine;  but  glad  as  he 
line 4567=>was  to  get  out  of  his  wearisome  little  stone  room,  he  wanted  to  stop  and  ask 
line 4568=>questions, and know what Bilbo was going to do, and all about it. 
line 4569=>"No  time  now!"  said  the  hobbit.  "You  must  follow  me!  We  must  all  keep 
line 4570=>together  and not  risk getting  separated. All of us must  escape or none,  and  this  is 
line 4571=>our  last  chance.  If  this  is  found out, goodness knows where  the king will put you 
line 4572=>next, with chains on your hands and feet  too, I expect. Don't argue,  there's a good 
line 4573=>fellow!" 
line 4574=>Then  off  he went  from  door  to  door,  until  his  following  had  grown  to  twelve-
line 4575=>none  of  them  any  too  nimble,  what  with  the  dark,  and  what  with  their  long 
line 4576=>imprisonment. Bilbo's heart thumped every time one of them bumped into another, 
line 4577=>or  grunted  or  whispered  in  the  dark.  "Drat  this  dwarvish  racket!"  he  said  to 
line 4578=>himself. But all went well, and they met no guards. As a matter of fact there was a 
line 4579=>great  autumn  feast  in  the woods  that night,  and  in  the halls  above. Nearly  all  the 
line 4580=>king's  folks  were  merrymaking.  At  last  after  much  blundering  they  came  to 
line 4581=>Thorin's  dungeon,  far  down  in  a  deep  place  and  fortunately  not  far  from  the 
line 4582=>cellars. 
line 4583=>"Upon my word!"  said Thorin, when Bilbo whispered to him to come out and 
line 4584=>join his  friends,  "Gandalf  spoke  true,  as usual. A pretty  fine burglar you make,  it 
line 4585=>seems,  when  the  time  comes.  I  am  sure  we  are  all  for  ever  at  your  service, 
line 4586=>whatever happens after this. But what comes next?" 
line 4587=>Bilbo saw that the time had come to explain his idea, as far as he could; but he 
line 4588=>did  not  feel  at  all  sure  bow  the  dwarves  would  take  it.  His  fears  were  quite 
line 4589=>justified, for they did not like it a bit, and started grumbling loudly in spite of their 
line 4590=>danger.  
line 4591=>"We  shall  be  bruised  and  battered  to  pieces,  and  drowned  too,  for  certain!" 
line 4592=>they muttered. "We thought you had got some sensible notion, when you managed 
line 4593=>to get hold of the keys. This is a mad idea!" 
line 4594=>"Very well!" said Bilbo very downcast, and also rather annoyed. "Come  along 
line 4595=>back  to  your  nice  cells,  and  I  will  lock  you  all  in  again,  and  you  can  sit  there 
line 4596=>comfortably  and  think  of  a  better  plan-but  I don't suppose  I shall ever get hold of 
line 4597=>the keys again, even if I feel inclined to try." 
line 4598=>
line 4599=>####-"That  was  too  much  for  them,  and  they  calmed  down.  In  the  end,  of  course, 
line 4600=>they had to do just what Bilbo suggested, because it was obviously impossible for 
line 4601=>them  to  try  and  find  their  way  into  the  upper  halls,  or  to  fight  their  way  out  of 
