line 4726=>Now  the  very  last  barrel  was  being  rolled  to  the  doors!  In  despair  and  not 
line 4727=>knowing what  else  to  do,  poor  little Bilbo  caught hold of  it  and was pushed over 
line 4728=>the edge with it. Down into the water he fell, splash! into the cold dark water with 
line 4729=>the  barrel  on  top  of  him. He  came  up  again  spluttering  and  clinging  to  the wood 
line 4730=>like a  rat, but  for all his efforts he could not scramble on top. Every time he tried, 
line 4731=>the  barrel  rolled  round  and  ducked  him  under  again.  It  was  really  empty,  and 
line 4732=>floated light as a cork. Though his ears were full of water, he could hear the elves 
line 4733=>still  singing  in  the  cellar  above.  Then  suddenly  the  trapdoors  fell  to with a boom 
line 4734=>and  their  voices  faded  away. He was  in  the  dark  tunnel,  floating  in  icy water,  all 
line 4735=>alone-for you cannot count friends that are all packed up in barrels. 
line 4736=>Very  soon a grey patch came up  in  the darkness ahead. He heard  the creak of 
line 4737=>the water-gate being hauled up, and he found that he was in the midst of a bobbing 
line 4738=>and  bumping mass  of  casks  and  tubs  all  pressing  together  to  pass  under  the  arch 
line 4739=>and  get  out  into  the  open  stream.  He  had  as  much  as  he  could  do  to  prevent 
line 4740=>himself  from  being  hustled  and  battered  to  bits;  but  at  last  the  jostling  crowd 
line 4741=>began to break up and swing off, one by one, under the stone arch and away. Then 
line 4742=>he saw  that  it would have been no good even  if he had managed  to get astride his 
line 4743=>barrel,  for  there was  no  room  to  spare, not  even  for  a hobbit, between  its  top  and 
line 4744=>the suddenly stooping roof where the gate was. 
line 4745=> 
line 4746=>Out  they  went  under  the  overhanging  branches  of  the  trees  on  either  bank. 
line 4747=>Bilbo  wondered  what  the  dwarves  were  feeling  and  whether  a  lot  of  water  was 
line 4748=>getting  into  their  tubs.  Some  of  those  that  bobbed  along  by  him  in  the  gloom 
line 4749=>seemed pretty low in the water, and he guessed that these had dwarves inside. 
line 4750=>"I do hope  I put  the  lids on  tight enough!" he  thought, but before  long he was 
line 4751=>worrying  too much  about  himself  to remember  the dwarves. He managed  to keep 
line 4752=>his head  above  the water, but he was  shivering with  the  cold,  and he wondered  if 
line 4753=>he would die of  it before  the  luck  turned, and how much  longer he would be able 
line 4754=>to hang on, and whether he should risk the chance of  letting go and trying to swim 
line 4755=>to the bank. 
line 4756=>
line 4757=>####-The  luck  turned  all  right  before  long:  the  eddying  current  carried  several 
line 4758=>barrels  close  ashore  at  one  point  and  there  for  a  while  they  stuck  against  some 
line 4759=>hidden  root.  Then  Bilbo  took  the  opportunity  of  scrambling  up  the  side  of  his 
line 4760=>barrel while it was held steady against another. Up he crawled like a drowned rat, 
line 4761=>and lay on the top spread out to keep the balance as best he could. The breeze was 
line 4762=>cold  but  better  than  the water,  and  he  hoped  he would  not  suddenly  roll off again 
line 4763=>when  they  started  off  once  more.  Before  long  the  barrels  broke  free  again  and 
line 4764=>turned  and  twisted  off  down  the  stream,  and  out  into  the  main  current  Then  he 
line 4765=>found it quite as difficult to stick on as he had feared; but he managed it somehow, 
line 4766=>though  it was miserably uncomfortable. Luckily he was very  light, and  the barrel 
line 4767=>was  a  good  big  one  and  being  rather  leaky  had  now  shipped  a  small  amount  of 
line 4768=>water. All  the  same  it was  like  trying  to  ride, without  bridle  or  stirrups,  a  round-
line 4769=>bellied  pony  that  was  always  thinking  of  rolling  on  the  grass.  In  this  way  at  last 
line 4770=>Mr. Baggins came to a place where the trees on either hand grew thinner. He could 
line 4771=>see the paler sky between them. The dark river opened suddenly wide, and there it 
line 4772=>was  joined  to  the  main  water of  the Forest River  flowing down  in haste  from  the 
line 4773=>king's  great  doors.  There was  a  dim  sheet  of water  no  longer  overshadowed,  and 
line 4774=>on  its  sliding  surface  there were  dancing  and  broken  reflections  of  clouds  and  of 
line 4775=>stars. Then  the hurrying water of  the Forest River swept all the company of casks 
line 4776=>and tubs away to the north bank, in which it had eaten out a wide bay. This had a 
line 4777=>shingly  shore  under  hanging  banks  and  was  walled  at  the  eastern  end  by  a  little 
line 4778=>jutting  cape  of  hard  rock.  On  the  shallow  shore  most  of  the barrels  ran  aground, 
line 4779=>though a few went on to bump against the stony pier.  
line 4780=>There  were  people  on  the  look-out  on  the  banks.  They  quickly  poled  and 
line 4781=>pushed all the barrels together into the shallows, and when they had counted them 
line 4782=>they  roped  them  together and left them till the morning. Poor dwarves! Bilbo was 
line 4783=>not  so  badly  off  now.  He  slipped  from  his  barrel  and  waded  ashore,  and  then 
line 4784=>sneaked  along  to  some huts  that he  could  see near  the water's  edge. He no  longer 
line 4785=>thought  twice  about  picking  up  a  supper  uninvited  if  he  got  the  chance,  he  had 
line 4786=>been  obliged  to  do  it  for  so  long,  and  he  knew  only  too  well  what  it  was  to  be 
line 4787=>really  hungry,  not merely  politely  interested  in  the  dainties  of  a well-filled larder. 
line 4788=>Also he had caught a glimpse of a fire  through  the  trees, and that appealed to him 
line 4789=>with his dripping and ragged clothes clinging to him cold and clammy.  
line 4790=> 
line 4791=>There is no need to tell you much of his adventures that night, for now we are 
line 4792=>drawing  near  the  end  of  the  eastward  journey  and  coming  to  the  last  and  greatest 
line 4793=>adventure,  so  we  must  hurry  on.  Of  course  helped  by  his  magic  ring  he  got  on 
line 4794=>
line 4795=>####-very well  at  first,  but  he was  given  away  in  the  end  by  his wet  footsteps  and  the 
line 4796=>trail of drippings that he left wherever he went or sat; and also he began to snivel, 
line 4797=>and  wherever  he  tried  to  hide  he  was  found  out  by  the  terrific  explosions  of  his 
line 4798=>suppressed  sneezes.  Very  soon  there  was  a  fine  commotion  in  the  village  by  the 
line 4799=>riverside; but Bilbo escaped  into  the woods carrying a  loaf and a  leather bottle of 
line 4800=>wine and a pie that did not belong to him. The rest of the night he had to pass wet 
line 4801=>as he was and far from a fire, but the bottle helped him to do that, and he actually 
line 4802=>dozed a little on some dry leaves, even though the year was getting late and the air 
line 4803=>was chilly.  
line 4804=>He woke again with a specially loud sneeze. It was already grey morning, and 
line 4805=>there was a merry racket down by the river. They were making up a raft of barrels, 
line 4806=>and  the  raft-elves  would  soon  be  steering  it  off  down  the  stream  to  Lake-town. 
line 4807=>Bilbo  sneezed  again.  He  was  no  longer  dripping  but  he  felt  cold  all  over.  He 
line 4808=>scrambled down as  fast as his  stiff  legs would  take him and managed  just  in  time 
line 4809=>to get on to the mass of casks without being noticed in the general bustle. Luckily 
line 4810=>there was  no  sun  at  the  time  to  cast  an  awkward  shadow,  and  for  a mercy he did 
line 4811=>not sneeze again for a good while. 
line 4812=>There  was  a  mighty  pushing  of  poles.  The  elves  that  were  standing  in  the 
line 4813=>shallow  .water  heaved  and  shoved.  The  barrels  now  all  lashed  together  creaked 
line 4814=>and fretted.  . 
line 4815=>"This is a heavy load!" some grumbled. "They float too deep-some of these are 
line 4816=>never  empty.  If  they  had  come  ashore  in  the  daylight, we might  have  had  a  look 
line 4817=>inside," they said. 
line 4818=>"No time now!" cried the raftman. "Shove off!" 
line 4819=>And off they went at last, slowly at first, until they had passed the point of rock 
line 4820=>where other elves stood  to fend  them off with poles, and  then quicker and quicker 
line 4821=>as  they  caught  the  main  stream  and  went  sailing  away  down,  down  towards  the 
line 4822=>Lake. 
line 4823=>They  had  escaped  the  dungeons  of  the  king  and  were  through  the wood,  but 
line 4824=>whether alive or dead still remains to be seen. 
line 4825=> 
line 4826=>
line 4827=>####-<h4>Chapter 10</h4> <br> 
line 4828=>
line 4829=>A Warm Welcome 
line 4830=>
line 4831=> 
line 4832=>The day grew lighter and warmer as they floated along. After a while the river 
line 4833=>rounded  a  steep  shoulder  of  land  that  came  down  upon  their  left. Under  its  rocky 
line 4834=>feet  like  an  inland  cliff  the  deepest  stream  had  flowed  lapping  and  bubbling. 
line 4835=>Suddenly  the  cliff  fell  away. The  shores  sank. The  trees  ended. Then Bilbo  saw  a 
line 4836=>sight: The  lands opened wide  about him,  filled with  the waters of  the  river which 
line 4837=>broke  up  and  wandered  in  a  hundred  winding  courses,  or  halted  in  marshes  and 
line 4838=>pools  dotted  with  isles  on  every  side:  but  still  a  strong  water  flowed  on  steadily 
line 4839=>through  the midst. And  far  away,  its  dark  head  in  a  torn  cloud,  there  loomed  the 
line 4840=>Mountain!  Its  nearest  neighbours  to  the  North-East  and  the  tumbled  land  that 
line 4841=>joined it to them could not be seen. All alone it rose and looked across the marshes 
line 4842=>to  the  forest.  The  Lonely  Mountain!  Bilbo  had  come  far  and  through  many 
line 4843=>adventures to see it, and now he did not like the look of it in the least. 
line 4844=>As  he  listened  to  the  talk  of  the  raftmen  and  pieced  together  the  scraps  of 
line 4845=>information  they  let  fall, he  soon  realized  that he was very  fortunate  ever  to have 
line 4846=>seen  it  at  all,  even  from  this  distance.  Dreary  as  had  been  his  imprisonment and 
line 4847=>unpleasant  as  was  his  position  (to  say  nothing  of  the  poor  dwarves  underneath 
line 4848=>him)  still,  he  had  been  more  lucky  than  he  had  guessed.  The  talk  was  all  of  the 
line 4849=>trade  that  came  and  went  on  the  waterways  and  the  growth  of  the  traffic  on  the 
line 4850=>river, as  the  roads out of  the East  towards Mirkwood vanished or  fell  into disuse; 
line 4851=>and of the bickerings of the Lake-men and the Wood-elves about the upkeep of the 
line 4852=>Forest River and the care of the banks. 
line 4853=>Those  lands  had  changed  much  since  the  days  when  dwarves  dwelt  in  the 
line 4854=>Mountain,  days  which  most  people  now  remembered  only  as  a  very  shadowy 
line 4855=>tradition.  They  had  changed  even  in  recent  years,  and  since  the  last  news  that 
line 4856=>Gandalf  had  had  of  them.  Great  floods  and  rains  had  swollen  the  waters  that 
line 4857=>flowed  east;  and  there had been  an  earthquake or  two  (which  some were  inclined 
line 4858=>to attribute to the dragon-alluding to him chiefly with a curse and an ominous nod 
line 4859=>in  the  direction  of  the  Mountain).  The  marshes  and  bogs  had  spread  wider  and 
line 4860=>wider  on  either  side.  Paths  had  vanished,  and many  a  rider  and wanderer  too,  if 
line 4861=>they  had  tried  to  find  the  lost  ways  across.  The  elf-road  through  the wood which 
line 4862=>the dwarves had followed on the advice of Beorn now came to a doubtful and little 
line 4863=>used  end  at  the  eastern  edge  of  the  forest;  only  the  river offered any  longer a safe 
line 4864=>
line 4865=>####-way  from  the  skirts  of  Mirkwood  in  the  North  to  the  mountain-shadowed plains 
line 4866=>beyond, and the river was guarded by the Wood-elves' king. 
line 4867=>So  you  see Bilbo  had  come  in  the  end  by  the  only  road  that was  any  good.  It 
line 4868=>might have  been  some  comfort  to Mr. Baggins  shivering on  the barrels,  if he had 
line 4869=>known  that  news  of  this  had  reached  Gandalf  far  away  and  given  him  great 
line 4870=>anxiety, and  that he was  in  fact  finishing his other business  (which does not come 
line 4871=>into this tale) and getting ready to come in search of Thorin's company. But Bilbo 
line 4872=>did not know it. 
line 4873=>All he knew was that the river seemed to go on and on and on for ever, and he 
line 4874=>was  hungry,  and  had  a  nasty  cold  in  the  nose,  and  did  not  like  the  way  the 
line 4875=>Mountain seemed to frown at him and threaten him as it drew ever nearer. After a 
line 4876=>while, however,  the  river  took a more southerly course and  the Mountain  receded 
line 4877=>again,  and  at  last,  late  in  the  day  the  shores  grew  rocky,  the  river  gathered  all  its 
line 4878=>wandering  waters  together  into  a  deep  and  rapid  flood,  and  they  swept  along  at 
line 4879=>great speed. 
line 4880=>The  sun had  set when  turning with another  sweep  towards  the East  the  forest-
line 4881=>river  rushed  into  the  Long  Lake.  There  it  had  a  wide  mouth  with  stony  clifflike 
line 4882=>gates at either side whose feet were piled with shingles. The Long Lake! Bilbo had 
line 4883=>never  imagined  that  any  water  that  was  not  the  sea  could  look  so  big.  It  was  so 
line 4884=>wide  that  the  opposite  shores  looked  small  and  far,  but  it  was  so  long  that  its 
line 4885=>northerly end, which pointed towards the Mountain, could not be  seen at all. Only 
line 4886=>from the map did Bilbo know that away up there, where the stars of the Wain were 
line 4887=>already  twinkling,  the  Running  River  came  down  into  the  lake  from  Dale  and 
line 4888=>with  the  Forest  River  filled  with  deep  waters  what  must  once  have  been  a  great 
line 4889=>deep  rocky  valley. At  the  southern  end  the  doubled waters  poured  out  again  over 
line 4890=>high waterfalls  and  ran  away  hurriedly  to  unknown  lands.  In  the  still  evening  air 
line 4891=>the noise of the falls could be heard like a distant roar.  
line 4892=>Not  far  from  the mouth  of  the Forest River was the strange town he heard the 
line 4893=>elves speak of in the king's cellars. It was not built on the shore, though there were 
line 4894=>a  few  huts  and  buildings  there,  but  right  out  on  the  surface  of  the  lake,  protected 
line 4895=>from  the swirl of  the entering river by a promontory of rock which formed a calm 
line 4896=>bay. A great  . bridge made of wood ran out to where on huge piles made of forest 
line 4897=>trees  was  built  a  busy  wooden  town,  not  a  town  of  elves  but  of  Men,  who  still 
line 4898=>dared  to  dwell  here  under  the  shadow  of  the  distant  dragon-mountain. They  still 
line 4899=>throve  on  the  trade  that  came  up  the  great  river  from  the  South  and  was  carted 
line 4900=>past  the  falls  to  their  town;  but  in  the  great  days  of  old,  when  Dale  in  the  North 
line 4901=>was rich and prosperous, they had been wealthy and powerful, and there had been 
line 4902=>
line 4903=>####-fleets  of  boats  on  the  waters,  and  some  were  filled  with  gold  and  some  with 
line 4904=>warriors  in  armour,  and  there  had  been  wars  and  deeds  which  were  now  only  a 
line 4905=>legend.  The  rotting  piles  of  a  greater  town  could  still  be  seen  along  the  shores 
line 4906=>when the waters sank in a drought. 
line 4907=>But men  remembered  little of  all  that,  though  some  still  sang old  songs of  the 
line 4908=>dwarf-kings  of  the Mountain,  Thror  and  Thrain  of  the  race  of  Durin,  and  of  the 
line 4909=>coming of the Dragon, and the fall of the lords of Dale. Some sang too that Thror 
line 4910=>and Thrain would  come  back  one  day  and  gold would  flow  in  rivers  through  the 
line 4911=>mountain-gates, and all that land would be filled with new song and new laughter. 
line 4912=>But this pleasant legend did not much affect their daily business. 
line 4913=> 
line 4914=>As  soon  as  the  raft  of  barrels  came  in  sight boats  rowed out  from  the piles of 
line 4915=>the  town,  and  voices  hailed  the  raft-steerers. Then  ropes were  cast  and oars were 
line 4916=>pulled,  and  soon  the  raft  was  drawn  out  of  the  current  of  the  Forest  River  and 
line 4917=>towed  away  round  the  high  shoulder  of  rock  into  the  little  bay  of  Lake-town. 
line 4918=>There  it  was  moored  not  far  from  the  shoreward  head  of  the  great  bridge.  Soon 
line 4919=>men would come up  from  the South and  take  some of  the casks away, and others 
line 4920=>they would fill with goods they had brought to be taken back up the stream to the 
line 4921=>Wood-elves' home. In the meanwhile the barrels were left afloat while the elves of 
line 4922=>the raft and the boatmen went to feast in Lake-town. 
line 4923=>They would have been surprised, if they could have seen what happened down 
line 4924=>by  the  shore,  after  they  had  gone  and  the  shades  of  night  had  fallen. First  of  all  a 
line 4925=>barrel was  cut  loose  by Bilbo  and  pushed  to  the  shore  and  opened. Groans  came 
line 4926=>from  inside,  and  out  crept  a most  unhappy  dwarf. Wet  straw was  in  his  draggled 
line 4927=>beard;  he  was  so  sore  and  stiff,  so  bruised  and  buffeted  he  could  hardly  stand  or 
line 4928=>stumble through the shallow water to lie groaning on the shore. He had a famished 
line 4929=>and a savage look like a dog that has been chained and forgotten in a kennel for a 
line 4930=>week.  It was Thorin,  but  you  could  only  have  told  it  by his golden chain, and by 
line 4931=>the  colour  of  his  now  dirty  and  tattered  sky-blue  hood  with  its  tarnished  silver 
line 4932=>tassel. It was some time before he would be even polite to the hobbit. 
line 4933=>"Well,  are  you  alive  or  are  you  dead?"  asked  Bilbo  quite  crossly.  Perhaps  he 
line 4934=>had  forgotten  that he had had  at  least one good meal more  than  the dwarves,  and 
line 4935=>also  the use of his  arms  and  legs, not  to  speak of  a greater  allowance of  air.  "Are 
line 4936=>you still in prison, or are you free? If you want food, and if you want to go on with 
line 4937=>this silly adventure- it's yours after all and not mine-you had better slap your arms 
line 4938=>and rub your legs and try and help me get the others out while there is a chance!" 
line 4939=>
line 4940=>####-Thorin  of  course  saw  the  sense  of  this,  so  after  a  few  more  groans  he  got  up 
line 4941=>and  helped  the  hobbit as well as he could.  In  the darkness  floundering  in  the cold 
line 4942=>water  they had a difficult and very nasty  job  finding which were  the  right barrels. 
line 4943=>Knocking  outside  and  calling  only  discovered  about  six  dwarves  that  could 
line 4944=>answer.  They  were  unpacked  and  helped  ashore where  they  sat  or  lay muttering 
line 4945=>and  moaning;  they  were  so  soaked  and  bruised  and  cramped  that  they  could 
line 4946=>hardly yet realize their release or be properly thankful for it. 
line 4947=>Dwalin  and  Balin  were  two  of  the most  unhappy,  and  it  was  no  good  asking 
line 4948=>them  to  help.  Bifur  and  Bofur  were  less  knocked  about  and  drier,  but  they  lay 
line 4949=>down  and  would  do  nothing.  Fili  and  Kili,  however,  who  were  young  (for 
line 4950=>dwarves) and had also been packed more neatly with plenty of  straw  into  smaller 
line 4951=>casks, came out more or less smiling, with only a bruise or two and a stiffness that 
line 4952=>soon wore off. 
line 4953=>"I hope I never smell the smell of apples again!" said Fili. "My tub was full of 
line 4954=>it.  To  smell  apples  everlastingly  when  you  can  scarcely  move  and  are  cold  and 
line 4955=>sick  with  hunger  is  maddening.  I  could  eat  anything  in  the  wide  world  now,  for 
line 4956=>hours on end-but not an apple!" 
line 4957=>With  the willing help of Fili  and Kili, Thorin  and Bilbo  at  last discovered  the 
line 4958=>remainder  of  the  company  and  got  them  out.  Poor  fat  Bombur  was  asleep  or 
line 4959=>senseless; Dori, Nori, Ori, Oin and Gloin were waterlogged and seemed only half 
line 4960=>alive; they all had to be carried one by one and laid helpless on the shore. 
line 4961=>"Well! Here we are!" said Thorin. "And I suppose we ought to thank our stars 
line 4962=>and Mr. Baggins. I am sure he has a right to expect it, though I wish he could have 
line 4963=>arranged  a  more  comfortable  journey.  Still-all  very  much  at  your  service  once 
line 4964=>more, Mr. Baggins. No doubt we shall feel properly grateful, when we are fed and 
line 4965=>recovered. In the meanwhile what next?" 
line 4966=>"I suggest Lake-town," said Bilbo, "What else is there?" Nothing else could, of 
line 4967=>course, be suggested; so leaving the others Thorin and Fili and Kili and the hobbit 
line 4968=>went  along  the  shore  to  the  great  bridge. There were  guards  at  the  head  of  it,  but 
line 4969=>they were  not  keeping very careful watch,  for  it was  so  long  since  there had been 
line 4970=>any  real  need. Except  for  occasional  squabbles  about  river-tolls they were friends 
line 4971=>with the Wood-elves. Other folk were far away; and some of the younger people in 
line 4972=>the town openly doubted the existence of any dragon in the mountain, and laughed 
line 4973=>at  the greybeards and gammers who  said  that  they had  seen him  flying  in  the  sky 
line 4974=>in  their  young  days.  That  being  so  it  is  not  surprising  that  the  guards  were 
line 4975=>drinking  and  laughing  by  a  fire  in  their  hut,  and  did  not  hear  the  noise  of  the 
line 4976=>
line 4977=>####-unpacking  of  the  dwarves  or  the  footsteps  of  the  four  scouts.  Their  astonishment 
line 4978=>was enormous when Thorin Oakenshield stepped in through the door.  
line 4979=>"Who  are  you  and what  do  you want?"  they  shouted  leaping  to  their  feet  and 
line 4980=>gipping for weapons. 
line 4981=>"Thorin son of Thrain son of Thror King under the Mountain!" said the dwarf 
line 4982=>in  a  loud  voice,  and  he  looked  it,  in  spite  of  his  torn  clothes  and  draggled  hood. 
line 4983=>The  gold  gleamed  on  his  neck  and  waist:  his  eyes  were  dark  and  deep.  "I  have 
line 4984=>come back. I wish to see the Master of your town!" 
line 4985=>Then  there  was  tremendous  excitement.  Some  of  the  more  foolish  ran  out  of 
line 4986=>the  hut  as  if  they  expected  the  Mountain  to  go  golden  in  the  night  and  all  the 
line 4987=>waters  of  the  lake  to  turn  yellow  right  away.  The  captain  of  the  guard  came 
line 4988=>forward. 
line 4989=>"And who are these?" he asked, pointing to Fili and: Kili and Bilbo. 
line 4990=>"The sons of my father's daughter," answered Thorin, "Fili and Kili of the race 
line 4991=>of Durin, and Mr. Baggins who has travelled with us out of the West." 
line 4992=>"If you come in peace lay down your arms!" said the captain. 
line 4993=>"We  have  none,"  said  Thorin,  and  it  was  true  enough:  their  knives  had  been 
line 4994=>taken from them by the wood-elves, and the great sword Orcrist too. Bilbo had his 
line 4995=>short sword, hidden as usual, but he said nothing about that. "We have no need of 
line 4996=>weapons,  who  return  at  last  to  our  own  as  spoken  of  old.  Nor  could  we  fight 
line 4997=>against so many. Take us to your master!" 
line 4998=>"He is at feast," said the captain. 
line 4999=>"Then all the more reason for taking us to him," burst in Fili, who was getting 
line 5000=>impatient at these solemnities. "We are worn and famished after our long road and 
line 5001=>we have sick comrades. Now make haste and  let us have no more words, or your 
line 5002=>master may have something to say to you." 
line 5003=>"Follow me  then,"  said  the  captain,  and with  six men  about  them he  led  them 
line 5004=>over  the bridge  through  the gates and  into  the market-place of the town. This was 
line 5005=>a  wide  circle  of  quiet  water  surrounded  by  the  tall  piles  on  which  were  built  the 
line 5006=>greater  houses,  and  by  long  wooden  quays  with  many  steps  and  ladders  going 
line 5007=>down  to  the  surface  of  the  lake. From  one  great  hall  shone many  lights  and  there 
line 5008=>came  the  sound  of many  voices.  They  passed  its  doors  and  stood  blinking  in  the 
line 5009=>light looking at long tables filled with folk. 
line 5010=>"I  am Thorin  son  of Thrain  son of Thror King under the Mountain! I return!" 
line 5011=>cried Thorin in a loud voice from the door, before the captain could say anything. 
line 5012=>All  leaped  to  their  feet.  The Master  of  the  town  sprang  from  his  great  chair.  But 
line 5013=>
line 5014=>####-none  rose  in greater surprise  than  the  raft-men of the elves who were sitting at the 
line 5015=>lower end of the hall. Pressing forward before the Master's table they cried: 
line 5016=>"These  are  prisoners  of  our  king  that  have  escaped,  wandering  vagabond 
line 5017=>dwarves that could not give any good account of themselves, sneaking through the 
line 5018=>woods and molesting our people!" 
line 5019=>"Is  this  true?"  asked  the  Master.  As  a  matter  of  fact  he  thought  it  far  more 
line 5020=>likely than the return of the King under the Mountain, if any such person had ever 
line 5021=>existed. 
line 5022=>"It  is  true  that we were wrongfully waylaid by the Elven-king and imprisoned 
line 5023=>without  cause  as  we  journeyed  back  to  our  own  land,"  answered  Thorin.  "But 
line 5024=>lock  nor  bar  may  hinder  the  homecoming  spoken  of  old.  Nor  is  this  town  in  the 
line 5025=>Wood-elves' realm. I speak to the Master of the town of the Men of the lake, not to 
line 5026=>the raft-men of the king." 
line 5027=>Then  the  Master  hesitated  and  looked  from  one  to  the  other.  The  Elvenking 
line 5028=>was  very  powerful  in  those  parts  and  the Master wished  for  no  enmity with  him, 
line 5029=>nor did he  think much of old songs, giving his mind  to  .trade and tolls, to cargoes 
line 5030=>and  gold,  to  which  habit  he  owed  his  position.  Others  were  of  different  mind, 
line 5031=>however,  and  quickly  the  matter  was  settled  without  him.  The  news  had  spread 
line 5032=>from  the  doors  of  the  hall  like  fire  through  all  the  town.  People  were  shouting 
line 5033=>inside  the  hall  and  outside  it. The  quays were  thronged with  hurrying  feet.  Some 
line 5034=>began  to  sing  snatches  of  old  songs  concerning  the  return  of  the  King  under  the 
line 5035=>Mountain;  that  it was Thror's grandson not Thror himself  that had come back did 
line 5036=>not bother them at all. Others took up the song and it rolled loud and high over the 
line 5037=>lake. 
line 5038=> 
line 5039=>
line 5040=>The King beneath the mountains, 
line 5041=>The King of carven stone, 
line 5042=>The lord of silver fountains 
line 5043=>Shall come into his own! 
line 5044=> 
line 5045=>His crown shall be upholden, 
line 5046=>His harp shall be restrung, 
line 5047=>His halls shall echo golden 
line 5048=>To songs of yore re-sung. 
line 5049=> 
line 5050=>The woods shall wave on mountains 
line 5051=>And grass beneath the sun; 
line 5052=>His wealth shall flow in fountains 
line 5053=>And the rivers golden run. 
line 5054=>
line 5055=>####- 
line 5056=>The streams shall run in gladness, 
line 5057=>The lakes shall shine and burn, 
line 5058=>And sorrow fail and sadness 
line 5059=>At the Mountain -king's return! 
line 5060=> 
line 5061=>So they sang, or very like that, only there was a great deal more of it, and there 
line 5062=>was much  shouting as well as  the music of harps and of  fiddles mixed up with  it. 
line 5063=>Indeed  such  excitement  had  not  been  known  in  the  town  in  the  memory  of  the 
line 5064=>oldest  grandfather. The Wood-elves  themselves began  to wonder greatly and even 
line 5065=>to  be  afraid.  They  did  not  know  of  course  how  Thorin  had  escaped,  and  they 
line 5066=>began to think their king might have made a serious mistake. As for the Master he 
line 5067=>saw  there was nothing else for  it but  to obey  the general clamour, for  the moment 
line 5068=>at any rate, and to pretend to believe that Thorin was what he said. So he gave up 
line 5069=>to  him  his  own  great  chair  and  set  Fili  and  Kili  beside  him  in  places  of  honour.  
line 5070=>Even  Bilbo  was  given  a  seat  at  the  high  table,  and  no  explanation  of  where  he 
line 5071=>came  in-no  songs  had  alluded  to  him  even  in  the  obscurest way-was asked  for  in 
line 5072=>the general bustle. 
line 5073=>Soon afterwards  the other dwarves were brought  into  the  town amid scenes of 
line 5074=>astonishing enthusiasm. They were all doctored and fed and housed and pampered 
line 5075=>in  the  most  delightful  and  satisfactory  fashion.  A  large  house  was  given  up  to 
line 5076=>Thorin  and  his  company;  boats  and  rowers were  put  at  their  service;  and  crowds 
line 5077=>sat outside and sang  songs all day, or cheered if any dwarf showed so much as his 
line 5078=>nose. 
line 5079=>Some of the songs were old ones; but some of them were quite new and spoke 
line 5080=>confidently  of  the  sudden  death  of  the  dragon  and  of  cargoes  of  rich  presents 
line 5081=>coming  down  the  river  to  Lake-town.  These were  inspired  largely  by  the Master 
line 5082=>and  they  did  not  particularly  please  the  dwarves,  but  in  the  meantime  they  were 
line 5083=>well  contented  and  they  quickly  grew  fat  and  strong  again.  Indeed within  a week 
line 5084=>they  were  quite  recovered,  fitted  out  in  fine  cloth  of  their  proper  colours,  with 
line 5085=>beards combed and trimmed, and proud steps. Thorin looked and walked as if his 
line 5086=>kingdom was already regained and Smaug chopped up into little pieces. 
line 5087=>Then,  as he had  said,  the dwarves' good  feeling  towards  the  little hobbit grew 
line 5088=>stronger  every  day.  There  were  no  more  groans  or  grumbles.  They  drank  his 
line 5089=>health, and they patted him on the back, and they made a great fuss of him; which 
line 5090=>was just as well, for he was not feeling particularly cheerful. He had not forgotten 
line 5091=>the  look  of  the  Mountain,  nor  the  thought  of  the  dragon,  and  he  had  besides  a 
line 5092=>
line 5093=>####-shocking  cold.  For  three  days  he  sneezed  and  coughed,  and  he  could  not  go  out, 
line 5094=>and even after that his speeches at banquets were limited to "Thag you very buch." 
line 5095=> 
line 5096=>In the meanwhile the Wood-elves had gone back up the Forest River with their 
line 5097=>cargoes,  and  there  was  great  excitement  in  the  king's  palace.  I  have  never  heard 
line 5098=>what  happened  to  the  chief  of  the  guards  and  the  butler.  Nothing  of  course  was 
line 5099=>ever said about keys or barrels while  the dwarves stayed in Lake-town, and Bilbo 
line 5100=>was careful never to become invisible. Still, I daresay, more was guessed than was 
line 5101=>known, though doubtless Mr. Baggins remained a bit of a mystery. In any case the 
line 5102=>king knew now the dwarves' errand, or thought he did, and he said to himself: 
line 5103=>"Very well! We'll see! No treasure will come back through Mirkwood without 
line 5104=>my having something to say in the matter. But I expect they will all come to a bad 
line 5105=>end, and serve them right!" He at any rate did not believe in dwarves fighting and 
line 5106=>killing  dragons  like  Smaug,  and  he  strongly  suspected  attempted  burglary  or 
line 5107=>something  like  it  which  shows  he  was  a  wise  elf  and  wiser  than  the  men  of  the 
line 5108=>town, though not quite right, as we shall see in the end. He sent out his spies about 
line 5109=>the  shores  of  the  lake  and  as  far northward  towards  the Mountains  as  they would 
line 5110=>go, and waited. 
line 5111=>At  the  end  of  a  fortnight  Thorin  began  to  think  of  departure.  While  the 
line 5112=>enthusiasm  still  lasted  in  the  town was  the  time  to get help.  It would not do  to  let 
line 5113=>everything  cool  down  with  delay.  So  he  spoke  to  the  Master  and  his  councillors 
line 5114=>and said that soon he and his company must go on towards the Mountain. 
line 5115=>Then for  the first  time  the Master was surprised and a  little frightened; and he 
line 5116=>wondered  if  Thorin  was  after  all  really  a  descendant  of  the  old  kings.  He  had 
line 5117=>never  thought  that  the  dwarves  would  actually  dare  to  approach  Smaug,  but 
line 5118=>believed  they were  frauds who would sooner or  later be discovered and be  turned 
line 5119=>out. He was wrong. Thorin, of  course, was  really  the grandson of  the King under 
line 5120=>the  Mountain,  and  there  is  no  knowing  what  a  dwarf  will  not  dare  and  do  for 
line 5121=>revenge or the recovery of his own. But the Master was not sorry at all to let them 
line 5122=>go.  They  were  expensive  to  keep,  and  their  arrival  had  turned  things  into  a  long 
line 5123=>holiday in which business was at a standstill. 
line 5124=>"Let them go and bother Smaug, and see how he welcomes them!" he thought. 
line 5125=>"Certainly,  O  Thorin  Thrain's  son  Thror's  son!"  was  what  he  said.  "You  must 
line 5126=>claim your own. The hour  is at hand, spoken of old. What help we can offer shall 
line 5127=>be yours, and we trust to your gratitude when your kingdom is regained." 
line 5128=>So  one  day,  although  autumn  was  now  getting  far  on,  and  winds  were  cold, 
line 5129=>and  leaves  were  falling  fast,  three  large  boats  left  Lake-town,  laden with  rowers, 
line 5130=>
line 5131=>####-dwarves,  Mr.  Baggins,  and  many  provisions.  Horses  and  ponies  had  been  sent 
line 5132=>round  by  circuitous  paths  to  meet  them  at  their  appointed  landing-place.  The 
line 5133=>Master  and  his  councillors  bade  them  farewell  from  the  great  steps  of  the  town-
line 5134=>hall  that  went  down  to  the  lake.  People  sang  on  the  quays  and  out  of  windows. 
line 5135=>The  white  oars  dipped  and  splashed,  and  off  they  went  north  up  the  lake  on  the 
line 5136=>last stage of their long journey. The only person thoroughly unhappy was Bilbo. 
line 5137=> 
line 5138=>
line 5139=>####-<h4>Chapter 11</h4> <br> 
line 5140=>
line 5141=>On the Doorstep 
line 5142=>
line 5143=> 
line 5144=>In  two  days  going  they  rowed  right up  the Long Lake and passed out  into  the 
line 5145=>River  Running,  and  now  they  could  all  see  the  Lonely  Mountain  towering  grim 
line 5146=>and  tall  before  them.  The  stream was  strong  and  their  going  slow. At  the;  end  of 
line 5147=>the third day, some miles up the river, they drew in to the left or western bank and 
line 5148=>disembarked.  Here  they  were  joined  by  the  horses  with  other  provisions  and 
line 5149=>necessaries and the ponies for their own use that had been sent to meet them. They 
line 5150=>packed what  they  could  on  the  ponies  and  the  rest was made  into  a  store under  a 
line 5151=>tent,  but  none  of  the men  of  the  town would  stay with  them  even  for  the  night  so 
line 5152=>near the shadow of the Mountain. 
line 5153=>"Not  at  any  rate  until  the  songs  have  come  true!"  said  they.  It  was  easier  to 
line 5154=>believe in the Dragon and less easy to believe in Thorin in these wild parts. Indeed 
line 5155=>their stores had no need of any guard, for all  the  land was desolate and empty. So 
line 5156=>their escort  left  them, making off  swiftly down  the  river and  the  shoreward paths, 
line 5157=>although the night was already drawing on. 
line 5158=>They spent a cold and  lonely night and  their spirits  fell. The next day  they set 
line 5159=>out  again. Balin  and Bilbo  rode  behind,  each  leading  another  pony  heavily  laden 
line 5160=>beside  him;  the  others  were  some  way  ahead  picking  out  a  slow  road,  for  there 
line 5161=>were no paths. They made north-west, slanting away from the River Running, and 
line 5162=>drawing ever nearer and nearer to a great spur of the Mountain that was flung out 
line 5163=>southwards towards them. 
line 5164=>It was a weary journey, and a quiet and stealthy one. There was no laughter or 
line 5165=>song or sound of harps, and the pride and hopes which had stirred in their hearts at 
line 5166=>the  singing  of  old  songs  by  the  lake  died  away  to  a  plodding  gloom.  They  knew 
line 5167=>that they were drawing near to the end of their journey, and that it might be a very 
line 5168=>horrible end. The land about them grew bleak and barren, though once, as Thorin 
line 5169=>told  them,  it had been green and fair. There was  little grass, and before  long  there 
line 5170=>was neither bush nor tree, and only broken and blackened stumps to speak of ones 
line 5171=>long  vanished.  They  were  come  to  the  Desolation  of  the  Dragon,  and  they  were 
line 5172=>come at the waning of the year.  
line 5173=> 
line 5174=>They  reached  the  skirts  of  the  Mountain  all  the  same  without  meeting  any 
line 5175=>danger or any sign of the Dragon other than the wilderness he had made about his 
line 5176=>lair.  The Mountain  lay  dark  and  silent  before  them  and  ever  higher  above  them. 
line 5177=>
line 5178=>####-They made  their  first  camp  on  the western  side  of  the  great  southern  spur, which 
line 5179=>ended  in  a  height  called Ravenhill. On  this  there  had  been  an  old watch-post; but 
line 5180=>they dared not climb it yet, it was too exposed. 
line 5181=>Before  setting  out  to  search  the western  spurs  of  the Mountain  for  the  hidden 
line 5182=>door, on which all their hopes rested, Thorin sent out a scouting expedition to spy 
line 5183=>out  the  land  to  the  South  where  the  Front  Gate  stood.  For  this  purpose  he  chose 
line 5184=>Balin  and Fili  and Kili,  and with  them went Bilbo. They marched under  the grey 
line 5185=>and silent cliffs to the feet of Ravenhill. There the river, after winding a wide loop 
line 5186=>over the valley of Dale, turned from the Mountain on its road to the Lake, flowing 
line 5187=>swift and noisily. Its bank was bare and rocky, tall and steep above the stream; and 
line 5188=>gazing  out  from  it  over  the  narrow  water,  foaming  and  splashing  among  many 
line 5189=>boulders,  they  could  see  in  the wide valley  shadowed by  the Mountain's  arms  the 
line 5190=>grey ruins of ancient houses, towers, and walls. 
line 5191=>"There  lies  all  that  is  left  of  Dale,"  said  Balin.  "The  mountain's  sides  were 
line 5192=>green with woods  and  all  the  sheltered  valley  rich  and  pleasant  in  the  days when 
line 5193=>the  bells  rang  in  that  town." He  looked  both  sad  and  grim  as  he  said  this: he had 
line 5194=>been one of Thorin's companions on the day the Dragon came. 
line 5195=>They did not dare to follow the river much further to. wards the Gate; but they 
line 5196=>went on beyond the end of the southern spur, until lying hidden behind a rock they 
line 5197=>could  look  out  and  see  the  dark  cavernous  opening  in  a  great  cliff-wall between 
line 5198=>the  arms  of  the Mountain. Out  of  it  the waters  of  the Running River  sprang;  and 
line 5199=>out  of  it  too  there  came  a  steam  and  a  dark  smoke. Nothing moved  in  the waste, 
line 5200=>save  the  vapour  and  the  water,  and  every  now  and  again  a  black  and  ominous 
line 5201=>crow. The only sound was  the sound of  the stony water, and every now and again 
line 5202=>the harsh croak of a bird. Balin shuddered. 
line 5203=>"Let us return!" he said. "We can do no good here!â€“ And I don't like these dark 
line 5204=>birds, they look like spies of evil." 
line 5205=>"The dragon is still alive and in the halls under the Mountain then-or I imagine 
line 5206=>so from the smoke," said the hobbit. 
line 5207=>"That  does  not  prove  it,"  said Balin,  "though  I  don't  doubt  you  are  right. But 
line 5208=>he might be gone  away  some  time, or  he might be lying out on the mountain-side 
line 5209=>keeping watch, and still I expect smokes and steams would come out of the gates: 
line 5210=>all the halls within must be filled with his foul reek." 
line 5211=> 
line 5212=>With  such  gloomy  thoughts,  followed  ever  by  croaking  crows  above  them, 
line 5213=>they made  their weary way  back  to  the  camp. Only  in  June  they  had  been  guests 
line 5214=>in  the fair house of Elrond, and  though autumn was now crawling  towards winter 
line 5215=>
line 5216=>####-that  pleasant  time  now  seemed  years  ago.  They were  alone  in  the  perilous waste 
line 5217=>without  hope  of  further  help. They were  at  the  end  of  their  journey,  but  as  far  as 
line 5218=>ever, it seemed, from the end of their quest. None of them had much spirit left. 
line 5219=>Now  strange  to  say  Mr.  Baggins  had  more  than  the  others.  He  would  often 
line 5220=>borrow Thorin's map  and  gaze  at  it,  pondering over  the  runes and  the message of 
line 5221=>the  moon-letters  Elrond  had  read.  It  was  he  that  made  the  dwarves  begin  the 
line 5222=>dangerous  search  on  the  western  slopes  for  the  secret  door.  They  moved  their 
line 5223=>camp  then  to  a  long  valley,  narrower  than  the  great  dale  in  the  South where  the 
line 5224=>Gates  of  the  river  stood,  and  walled  with  lower  spurs  of  the  Mountain.  Two  of 
line 5225=>these  here  thrust  forward west  from  the main mass  in  long  steep-sided ridges  that 
line 5226=>fell ever downwards towards the plain. On this western side there were fewer signs 
line 5227=>of  the  dragon's  marauding  feet,  and  there  was  some  grass  for  their  ponies.  From 
line 5228=>this western  camp,  shadowed  all day by  cliff  and wall until  the  sun began  to  sink 
line 5229=>towards  the  forest,  day  by  day  they  toiled  in  parties  searching  for  paths  up  the 
line 5230=>mountain-side. If the map was true, somewhere high above the cliff at the valley's 
line 5231=>head must stand the secret door. Day by day they came back to their camp without 
line 5232=>success. 
line 5233=>But at  last unexpectedly  they  found what  they were seeking. Fili and Kili and 
line 5234=>the  hobbit went  back one day down  the valley and scrambled among  the  tumbled 
line 5235=>rocks  at  its  southern  corner.  About  midday,  creeping  behind  a  great  stone  that 
line 5236=>stood  alone  like  a  pillar,  Bilbo  came  on  what  looked  like  rough  steps  going 
line 5237=>upwards.  Following  these  excitedly  he  and  the dwarves  found  traces of  a narrow 
line 5238=>track,  often  lost,  often  rediscovered,  that  wandered  on  to  the  top  of  the  southern 
line 5239=>ridge and brought them at last to a still narrower ledge, which turned north across 
line 5240=>the  face of  the Mountain. Looking down  they  saw  that they were at the top of the 
line 5241=>cliff  at  the  valley's  head  and  were  gazing  down  on  to  their  own  camp  below. 
line 5242=>Silently, clinging to the rocky wall on their right, they went in single file along the 
line 5243=>ledge,  till  the  wall  opened  and  they  turned  into  a  little  steep-walled  bay,  grassy-
line 5244=>floored,  still  and quiet.  Its  entrance which  they had  found  could not be  seen  from 
line 5245=>below because of  the overhang of  the  cliff, nor  from  further off because  it was  so 
line 5246=>small that it looked like a dark crack and no more. It was not a cave and was open 
line 5247=>to  the  sky  above;  but  at  its  inner  end  a  flat  wall  rose  up  that  in  the  lower  I  part, 
line 5248=>close  to  the  ground,  was  as  smooth  and  upright  as  mason's  work,  but  without  a 
line 5249=>joint or crevice to be seen. 
line 5250=>"No sign was  there of post or  lintel or  threshold, nor any sign of bar or bolt or 
line 5251=>key-hole; yet they did not doubt that they had found the door at last. 
line 5252=>
line 5253=>####-They  beat  on  it,  they  thrust  and  pushed  at  it,  they  implored  it  to  move,  they 
line 5254=>spoke  fragments of broken  spells of opening, and nothing  stirred. At  last  tired out 
line 5255=>they.  rested  on  the  grass  at  its  feet,  and  then  at  evening  began,  their  long  climb 
line 5256=>down. 
line 5257=> 
line 5258=>There was excitement  in  the camp  that night.  In  the morning  they prepared  to 
line 5259=>move  once  more.  Only  Bofur  and  Bombur  were  left  behind  to  guard  the  ponies 
line 5260=>and  such  stores  as  they  had  brought  with  them  from  the  river.  The  others  went 
line 5261=>down  the  valley  and  up  the  newly  found  path,  and  so  to  the  narrow  ledge. Along 
line 5262=>this  they could carry no bundles or packs, so narrow and breathless was  it, with a 
line 5263=>fall  of  a  hundred  and  fifty  feet  beside  them  on  to  sharp  rocks  below;  but  each  of 
line 5264=>them  took a good coil of  rope wound  tight about his waist, and  so at  last without 
line 5265=>mishap they reached the little grassy bay.  
line 5266=>There  they  made  their  third  camp,  hauling  up  what  they  needed  from  below 
line 5267=>with  their ropes. Down  the same way  they were able occasionally  to  lower one of 
line 5268=>the more  active  dwarves,  such  as Kili,  to  exchange  such  news  as  there was,  or  to 
line 5269=>take  a  share  in  the  guard  below,  while  Bofur  was  hauled  up  to  the  higher  camp. 
line 5270=>Bombur would not come up either the rope or the path. 
line 5271=>"I am too fat for such fly-walks," he said. "I should turn dizzy and tread on my 
line 5272=>beard, and then you would be thirteen again. And the knotted ropes are too slender 
line 5273=>for my weight." Luckily for him that was not true, as you will see. 
line 5274=>In  the  meanwhile  some  of  them  explored  the  ledge  beyond  the  opening  and 
line 5275=>found a path  that  led higher and higher on  to  the mountain; but  they did not dare 
line 5276=>to venture very  far  that way, nor was  there much use  in  it. Out up  there  a  silence 
line 5277=>reigned,  broken  by  no  bird  or  sound  except  that  of  the  wind  in  the  crannies  of 
line 5278=>stone. They spoke low and never called or sang, for danger brooded in every rock. 
line 5279=>The  others  who  were  busy  with  the  secret  of  the  door  had  no  more  success. 
line 5280=>They  were  too  eager  to  trouble  about  the  runes  or  the  moon-letters,  but  tried 
line 5281=>without  resting  to  discover where  exactly  in  the  smooth  face  of  the  rock  the  door 
line 5282=>was hidden. They had brought picks and tools of many sorts from Lake-town, and 
line 5283=>at  first  they  tried  to  use  these.  But  when  they  struck  the  stone  the  handles 
line 5284=>splintered and jarred their arms cruelly, and the steel heads broke or bent like lead. 
line 5285=>Mining work,  they  saw  clearly was  no  good  against  the magic  that  had  shut  this 
line 5286=>door; and they grew terrified, too, of the echoing noise. 
line 5287=>Bilbo  found  sitting  on  the  doorstep  lonesome  and  wearisome-there was  not  a 
line 5288=>doorstep, of course, really, but they used to call the little grassy space between the 
line 5289=>wall  and  the  opening  the  "doorstep"  in  fun,  remembering Bilbo's words  long  ago 
line 5290=>
line 5291=>####-at  the  unexpected  party  in  his  hobbit-hole,  when  he  said  they  could  sit  on  the 
line 5292=>doorstep  till  they  thought  of  something.  And  sit  and  think  they  did,  or  wandered 
line 5293=>aimlessly about, and glummer and glummer they became. 
line 5294=>Their  spirits  had  risen  a  little  at  the  discovery  of  the path, but now  they  sank 
line 5295=>into their boots; and yet they would not give it up and go away. The hobbit was no 
line 5296=>longer much brighter than the dwarves. He would do nothing but sit with his back 
line 5297=>to  the  rock-face  and  stare  away west  through  the opening, over  the cliff, over  the 
line 5298=>wide  lands  to  the black wall of Mirkwood,  and  to  the distances beyond,  in which 
line 5299=>he  sometimes  thought  he  could  catch  glimpses  of  the Misty Mountains  small  and 
line 5300=>far. If the dwarves asked him what he was doing he answered: 
line 5301=>"You  said  sitting  on  the  doorstep  and  thinking  would  be  my  job,  not  to 
line 5302=>mention  getting  inside,  so  I  am  sitting  and  thinking." But  I  am  afraid  he was  not 
line 5303=>thinking  much  of  the  job,  but  of  what  lay  beyond  the  blue  distance,  the  quiet 
line 5304=>Western Land  and  the Hill  and  his  hobbit-hole under  it. A  large grey  stone  lay  in 
line 5305=>the centre of the grass and he stared moodily at it or watched the great snails. They 
line 5306=>seemed  to  love  the  little  shut-in  bay  with  its  walls  of  cool  rock,  and  there  were 
line 5307=>many of them of huge size crawling slowly and stickily along its sides. 
line 5308=>"Tomorrow begins the last week of Autumn," said Thorin one day.  
line 5309=>"And winter comes after autumn," said Bifur.  
line 5310=>"And  next  year  after  that,"  said  Dwalin,  "and  our  beards  will  grow  till  they 
line 5311=>hang  down  the  cliff  to  the  valley  before  anything  happens  here.  What  is  our 
line 5312=>burglar doing for us? 
line 5313=>Since  he  has  got  an  invisible  ring,  and  ought  to  be  a  specially  excellent 
line 5314=>performer  now,  I  am  beginning  to  think  he might  go  through  the  Front Gate  and 
line 5315=>spy things out a bit!" 
line 5316=>Bilbo  heard  this-the  dwarves  were  on  the  rocks  just  :  above  the  enclosure 
line 5317=>where  he  was  sitting-and  "Good Gracious!"  he  thought,  "so  that  is what  they  are 
line 5318=>beginning  to  think,  is  it?  It  is  always  poor  me  that  has  to  get  them  out  :  of  their 
line 5319=>difficulties, at least since the wizard left. Whatever am I going to do? I might have 
line 5320=>known  that  something  dreadful  would  happen  to  me  in  the  end.  I  don't  think  I 
line 5321=>could bear to see the unhappy valley of Dale again, and as for that steaming gate! 
line 5322=>! !" 
line 5323=>That  night  he  was  very  miserable  and  hardly  slept.  Next  day  the  dwarves  all 
line 5324=>went  wandering  off  in  various  directions;  some  were  exercising  the  ponies  down 
line 5325=>below,  some  were  roving  about  the  mountain-side. All day Bilbo  sat gloomily  in 
line 5326=>the  grassy  bay  gazing  at  the  stone,  or  out  west  through  the  narrow  opening. He 
line 5327=>
line 5328=>####-had  a  queer  feeling  that  he  was  waiting  for  something.  "Perhaps  the  wizard  will 
line 5329=>suddenly come back today," he thought. 
line 5330=>If  he  lifted  his  head  he  could  see  a  glimpse  of  the  distant  forest.  As  the  sun 
line 5331=>turned west there was a gleam of yellow upon its far roof, as if the light caught the 
line 5332=>last pale  leaves. Soon he  saw  the orange ball of  the  sun  sinking  towards  the  level 
line 5333=>of his eyes. He went  to  the opening and  there pale and faint was a  thin new moon 
line 5334=>above  the  rim  of Earth. At  that  very moment  he  heard  a  sharp crack behind him. 
line 5335=>There on the grey stone in the grass was an enormous thrush, nearly coal black, its 
line 5336=>pale  yellow  breast  freckled  dark  spots.  Crack!  It  had  caught  a  snail  and  was 
line 5337=>knocking it on the stone. Crack! Crack! 
line 5338=>Suddenly  Bilbo  understood.  Forgetting  all  danger  he  stood  on  the  ledge  and 
line 5339=>hailed  the  dwarves,  shouting  and  paying. Those  that were  nearest  came  tumbling 
line 5340=>over the rocks and as fast as they could along the ledge to him, wondering what on 
line 5341=>earth  was  the  matter;  the  others  shouted  to  be  hauled  up  the  ropes  (except 
line 5342=>Bombur, of course: he was asleep). 
line 5343=>Quickly  Bilbo  explained.  They  all  fell  silent:  the  hobbit  standing  by  the  grey 
line 5344=>stone,  and  the  dwarves with wagging  beards watching  impatiently.  The  sun  sank 
line 5345=>lower  and  lower,  and  their  hopes  fell.  It  sank  into  a  belt  of  reddened  cloud  and 
line 5346=>disappeared.  The  dwarves  groaned,  but  still  Bilbo  stood  almost  without  moving. 
line 5347=>The  little  moon  was  dipping  to  the  horizon.  Evening  was  coming  on.  Then 
line 5348=>suddenly  when  their  hope  was  lowest  a  red  ray  of  the  sun  escaped  like  a  finger 
line 5349=>through  a  rent  in  the  cloud.  A  gleam  of  light  came  straight  through  the  opening 
line 5350=>into  the  bay  and  fell  on  the  smooth  rock-face.  The  old  thrush,  who  had  been 
line 5351=>watching from a high perch with beady eyes and head cocked on one side, gave a 
line 5352=>sudden  trill. There was a  loud attack. A  flake of  rock split  from  the wall and  fell. 
line 5353=>A  hole  appeared  suddenly  about  three  feet  from  the  ground.  Quickly,  trembling 
line 5354=>lest the chance should fade, the dwarves rushed to the rock and pushed-in vain. 
line 5355=>"The key! The key!" cried Bilbo. "Where is Thorin?" 
line 5356=>Thorin hurried up. 
line 5357=>"The key!" shouted Bilbo. "The key that went with the map! Try it now while 
line 5358=>there is still time!" 
line 5359=>Then Thorin stepped up and drew the key on its chain from round his neck. He 
line 5360=>put  it  to  the  hole.  It  fitted  and it turned! Snap! The gleam went out, the sun sank, 
line 5361=>the moon was gone, and evening sprang into the sky.  
line 5362=>Now  they  all  pushed  together,  and  slowly  a  part  of  the  rock-wall  gave  way. 
line 5363=>Long straight cracks appeared and widened. A door five feet high and three broad 
line 5364=>was  out-  lined,  and  slowly  without  a  sound  swung  inwards.  It  seemed  as  if 
line 5365=>
line 5366=>####-darkness  flowed  out  like  a  vapour  from  the  hole  in  the  mountain-side,  and  deep 
line 5367=>darkness  in  which  nothing  could  be  seen  lay  before  their  eyes  mouth  leading  in 
line 5368=>and down. 
line 5369=> 
line 5370=>
line 5371=>####-<h4>Chapter 12</h4> <br> 
line 5372=>
line 5373=>Inside Information 
line 5374=>
line 5375=> 
line 5376=>For  a  long  time  the  dwarves  stood  in  the  dark  before  the  door  and  debated, 
line 5377=>until at last Thorin spoke: 
line 5378=>"Now  is  the  time  for  our  esteemed  Mr.  Baggins,  who  has  proved  himself  a 
line 5379=>good  companion  on  our  long  road,  and  a  hobbit  full  of  courage and  resource  far 
line 5380=>exceeding  his  size,  and  if  I may  say  so  possessed  of  good  luck  far  exceeding  the 
line 5381=>usual  allowance-now  is  the  time  for  him  to  perform  the  service  for which  he was 
line 5382=>included in our Company; now is the time for him to earn his Reward." 
line 5383=>You are  familiar with Thorin's style on  important occasions, so  I will not give 
line 5384=>you  any  more  of  it,  though  he  went  on  a  good  deal  longer  than  this.  It  certainly 
line 5385=>was an important occasion, but Bilbo felt impatient. By now he was quite familiar 
