line 5657=>"You  may  indeed!  I  come  from  under  the  hill,  and  under  hills  and  over  the 
line 5658=>hills my paths led. And through the air, I am he that walks unseen." 
line 5659=>"So I can well believe," said Smaug, "but that is hardly our usual name." 
line 5660=>"I am  the clue-finder, the web-cutter, the stinging fly. I as chosen for the lucky 
line 5661=>number." 
line 5662=>"Lovely  titles!"  sneered  the  dragon.  "But  lucky  numbers  don't  always  come 
line 5663=>off." 
line 5664=>"I  am  he  that  buries  his  friends  alive  and  drowns  them  and  draws  them  alive 
line 5665=>again from the water. I came from the end of a bag, but no bag went over me." 
line 5666=>"These don't sound so creditable," scoffed Smaug. 
line 5667=>"I  am  the  friend  of  bears  and  the  guest  of  eagles.  I  am  Ringwinner  and 
line 5668=>Luckwearer;  and  I  am  Barrel-rider," went  on Bilbo  beginning  to  be  pleased with 
line 5669=>his riddling. 
line 5670=>"That's  better!"  said  Smaug.  "But  don't  let  your  imagination  run  away  with 
line 5671=>you!" 
line 5672=> 
line 5673=>
line 5674=>####-This  of  course  is  the way  to  talk  to  dragons,  if  you  don't want  to  reveal  your 
line 5675=>proper  name  (which  is  wise),  and  don't  want  to  infuriate  them  by  a  flat  refusal 
line 5676=>(which is also very wise). No dragon can resist the fascination of riddling talk and 
line 5677=>of wasting time trying to understand it. There was a lot here which Smaug did not 
line 5678=>understand  at  all  (though  I  expect  you  do,  since  you  know  all  about  Bilbo's 
line 5679=>adventures  to which  he was  referring), but he  thought he understood enough, and 
line 5680=>he chuckled in his wicked inside. 
line 5681=>"I  thought so  last night," he smiled  to himself. "Lake-men, some nasty scheme 
line 5682=>of those miserable tub-trading Lake-men, or I'm a lizard. I haven't been down that 
line 5683=>way for an age and an age; but I will soon alter that!" 
line 5684=>"Very  well,  O  Barrel-rider!"  he  said  aloud.  "Maybe  Barrel  was  your  pony's 
