line 5888=>below.  
line 5889=>Darkness  grew  deeper  and  he  grew  ever  more  uneasy.  "Shut  the  door!"  he 
line 5890=>begged them. "I fear that dragon in my marrow. I like this silence far less than the 
line 5891=>uproar of last night. Shut the door before it is too late!" 
line 5892=>Something  in  his  voice  gave  the  dwarves  an  uncomfortable  feeling.  Slowly 
line 5893=>Thorin shook off his dreams and getting up he kicked away the stone that wedged 
line 5894=>the door. Then they thrust upon it, and it closed with a snap and a clang. No trace 
line 5895=>of a keyhole was there left on the inside. They were shut in the Mountain! 
line 5896=>And  not  a  moment  too  soon.  They  had  hardly  gone  any  distance  down  the 
line 5897=>tunnel  when  a  blow  smote  the  side  of  the  Mountain  like  the  crash  of  battering-
line 5898=>rams  made  of  forest  oaks  and  swung  by  giants.  The  rock  boomed,  the  walls 
line 5899=>cracked and stones fell from the roof on their heads. What would have happened if 
line 5900=>
line 5901=>####-the door had still been open I don't like to think. They fled further down the tunnel 
line 5902=>glad to be still alive, while behind them outside they heard the roar and rumble of 
line 5903=>Smaug's  fury.  He  was  breaking  rocks  to  pieces,  smashing  wall  and  cliff  with  the 
line 5904=>lashings  of  his  huge  tail,  till  their  little  lofty  camping ground,  the  scorched grass, 
line 5905=>the thrush's stone, the snail-covered walls, the narrow ledge, and all disappeared in 
line 5906=>a  jumble  of  smithereens,  and  an  avalanche  of  splintered  stones  fell  over  the  cliff 
line 5907=>into the valley below.  
line 5908=>Smaug  had  left  his  lair  in  silent  stealth,  quietly  soared  into  the  air,  and  then 
line 5909=>floated heavy and slow in the dark like a monstrous crow, down the wind towards 
line 5910=>the  west  of  the  Mountain,  in  the  hopes  of  catching  unawares  something  or 
line 5911=>somebody  there,  and  of  spying  the outlet  to  the passage which  the  thief had used. 
line 5912=>This  was  the  outburst  of  his  wrath  when  he  could  find  nobody  and  see  nothing, 
line 5913=>even where he guessed the outlet must actually be. 
line 5914=>After  he  had  let  off  his  rage  in  this  way  he  felt  better  and  he  thought  in  his 
line 5915=>heart that he would not be troubled again from that direction. In-the meanwhile he 
line 5916=>had further vengeance to take. "Barrel-rider!" he snorted. "Your fee came from the 
line 5917=>waterside  and  up  the water  you  came with  out  a  doubt.  I  don't  know  your  smell, 
line 5918=>but if you are not one of those men of the Lake, you had their help. They shall see 
line 5919=>me and remember who is the real King under the Mountain!" 
line 5920=>He rose in fire and went away south towards the Running River.  
