line 5928=>In  the  meanwhile,  the  dwarves  sat  in  darkness,  and  utter  silence  fell  about 
line 5929=>them.  Little  they  ate  and  little  they  spoke.  They  could  not  count  the  passing  of 
line 5930=>time; and  they  scarcely dared  to move,  for  the whisper of  their voices echoed and 
line 5931=>rustled in the tunnel. If they dozed, they woke still to darkness and to silence going 
line 5932=>on unbroken. At last after days and days of waiting, as it seemed, when they were 
line 5933=>becoming  choked  and  dazed  for  want  of  air,  they  could  bear  it  no  longer.  They 
line 5934=>would  almost  have  welcomed  sounds  from  below  of  the  dragon's  return.  In  the 
line 5935=>silence  they  feared  some  cunning  devilry  of  his,  but  they  could  not  sit  there  for 
line 5936=>ever. 
line 5937=>Thorin spoke: "Let us  try  the door!" he said. "I must feel  the wind on my face 
line 5938=>soon  or  die.  I  think  I  would  rather  be  smashed  by  Smaug  in  the  open  than 
line 5939=>suffocate in here!" 
line 5940=>So several of the dwarves got up and groped back to where the door had been. 
line 5941=>But  they  found  that  the  upper  end  of  the  tunnel  had  been  shattered  and  blocked 
line 5942=>with broken  rock. Neither key nor  the magic  it had once obeyed would ever  open 
line 5943=>that door again. 
line 5944=>"We are trapped!" they groaned. "This is the end. We shall die here." 
line 5945=>But  somehow,  just  when  the  dwarves  were  most  despairing,  Bilbo  felt  a 
line 5946=>strange  lightening  of  the  heart,  as  if  a  heavy  weight  had  gone  from  under  his 
line 5947=>waistcoat. 
line 5948=>"Come, come!" he  said.  "While  there's  life  there's hope!" as my  father used  to 
line 5949=>say,  and  'Third  time  pays  for  all.'  I  am  going  down  the  tunnel  once  again.  I  have 
line 5950=>been  that  way  twice,  when  I  knew  there  was  a  dragon  at  the  other  end,  so  I  will 
line 5951=>risk  a  third  visit  when  I  am  no  longer  sure.  Anyway  the  only  way  out  is  down. 
line 5952=>And I think time you had better all come with me." 
line 5953=>In desperation they agreed, and Thorin was the first go forward by Bilbo's side. 
line 5954=>"Now  do  be  careful!"  whispered  the  hobbit,  "and  quiet  as  you  can  be! There 
line 5955=>may be no Smaug at the bottom but then again there may be. Don't let us take any 
line 5956=>unnecessary risks!" 
line 5957=>Down,  down  they  went.  The  dwarves  could  not,  course,  compare  with  the 
line 5958=>hobbit  in  real  stealth,  and  the made  a  deal  of  puffing  and  shuffling which  echoes 
line 5959=>magnified alarmingly; but  though every now and again Bilbo  in  fear  stopped and 
line 5960=>listened,  not  a  sound  stirred  below  Near  the  bottom,  as  well  as  he  could  judge, 
line 5961=>
line 5962=>####-Bilbo slipped on his ring and went ahead. But he did not need it: the darkness was 
line 5963=>complete,  and  they were  all  invisible,  ring  or  no  ring.  In  fact  so  black was  it  that 
line 5964=>the  hobbit  came  to  the  opening  unexpectedly,  put  his  hand  on  air,  stumbled  for 
line 5965=>ward, and rolled headlong into the hall! 
line 5966=>There he  lay face downwards on  the floor and did no dare  to get up, or hardly 
