line 6192=>before  long  came  to  a  deep  dell sheltered among  the rocks;  there  they rested for a 
line 6193=>while and had such a breakfast as they could, chiefly cram and water. (If you want 
line 6194=>to  know  what  cram  is,  I  can  only  say  that  I  don't  know  the  recipe;  but  it  is 
line 6195=>biscuitish,  keeps  good  indefinitely,  is  supposed  to  be  sustaining,  and  is  certainly 
line 6196=>not  entertaining,  being  in  fact  very  uninteresting  except  as  a  chewing  exercise.  It 
line 6197=>was made by the Lake-men for long journeys). 
line 6198=>After  that  they went on again; and now  the road struck westwards and  left  the 
line 6199=>river, and the great shoulder of the south-pointing mountain-spur drew ever nearer. 
line 6200=>At  length  they  reached  the  hill  path.  It  scrambled  steeply  up,  and  they  plodded 
line 6201=>slowly one behind the other, till at last in the late afternoon they came to the top of 
line 6202=>the ridge and saw the wintry sun going downwards to the West. 
line 6203=>Here  they  found  a  flat  place  without  a  wall  on  three  sides,  but  backed  to  the 
line 6204=>North by a  rocky  face  in which  there was an opening  like a door. From  that door 
line 6205=>there was a wide view East and South and West. 
line 6206=>"Here,"  said  Balin,  "in  the  old  days  we  used  always  to  keep  watchmen,  and 
line 6207=>that  door  behind  leads  into  a  rock-hewn  chamber  that  was  made  here  as  a 
line 6208=>guardroom.  There  were  several  places  like  it  round  the  Mountain.  But  there 
line 6209=>seemed small need for watching in the days of our prosperity, and the guards were 
line 6210=>made  over  comfortable,  perhaps  â€“ otherwise we might have had  longer warnings 
line 6211=>of  the coming of  the dragon, and  things might have been different. Still,  "here we 
line 6212=>can now lie hid and sheltered for a while, and can see much without being seen." 
line 6213=>"Not much use, if we have been seen coming here," said Dori, who was always 
line 6214=>looking  up  towards  the Mountain's  peak,  as  if  he  expected  to  see Smaug  perched 
line 6215=>there like a bird on a steeple. 
line 6216=>"We must take our chance of that," said Thorin. "We can go no further to-day." 
line 6217=>"Hear, hear!" cried Bilbo, and flung himself on the ground. 
line 6218=>In the rock-chamber there would have been room for a hundred, and there was 
line 6219=>a  small  chamber  further  in,  more  removed  from  the  cold  outside.  It  was  quite 
line 6220=>deserted; not even wild animals seemed  to have used  it  in all  the days of Smaug's 
line 6221=>dominion. There they laid their burdens; and some threw themselves down at once 
line 6222=>and slept, but the others sat near the outer door and discussed their plans. 
line 6223=>In  all  their  talk  they  came  perpetually  back  to  one  thing: where was  Smaug? 
line 6224=>They  looked West  and  there was  nothing,  and  East  there was  nothing,  and  in  the 
line 6225=>
line 6226=>####-South  there  was  no  sign  of  the  dragon,  but  there  was  a  gathering  of  very  many 
line 6227=>birds. At  that  they gazed and wondered; but they were no nearer understanding it, 
line 6228=>when the first cold stars came out. 
line 6229=>
line 6230=>####-<h4>Chapter 14</h4> <br> 
line 6231=>
line 6232=>Fire and Water 
line 6233=>
line 6234=> 
line 6235=>Now  if you wish,  like  the dwarves,  to hear news of Smaug, you must go back 
line 6236=>again  to  the  evening  when  he  smashed  the  door  and  flew  off  in  rage,  two  days 
line 6237=>before. 
line 6238=>The  men  of  the  lake-town  Esgaroth  were  mostly  indoors,  for  the  breeze  was 
line 6239=>from the black East and chill, but a few were walking on the quays, and watching, 
line 6240=>as they were fond of doing, the stars shine out from the smooth patches of the lake 
line 6241=>as  they  opened  in  the  sky.  From  their  town  the  Lonely  Mountain  was  mostly 
line 6242=>screened  by  the  low  hills  at  the  far  end  of  the  lake,  through  a  gap  in  which  the 
line 6243=>Running  River  came  down  from  the North. Only  its  high  peak  could  they  see  in 
line 6244=>clear weather, and they looked seldom at it, for it was ominous and dreary even in 
line 6245=>the light of morning. Now it was lost and gone, blotted in the dark. 
line 6246=>Suddenly it flickered back to view; a brief glow touched it and faded. 
line 6247=>"Look!"  said  one.  "The  lights  again!  Last  night  the watchmen  saw  them start 
line 6248=>and fade from midnight until dawn. Something is happening up there." 
line 6249=>"Perhaps  the  King  under  the  Mountain  is  forging  gold,"  said  another.  "It  is 
line 6250=>long since he went north. It is time the songs began to prove themselves again." 
line 6251=>"Which  king?"  said  another  with  a  grim  voice.  "As  like  as  not  it  is  the 
line 6252=>marauding  fire  of  the  Dragon,  the  only  king  under  the  Mountain  we  have  ever 
line 6253=>known." 
line 6254=>"You  are  always  foreboding  gloomy  things!"  said  the  others.  "Anything  from 
line 6255=>floods to poisoned fish. Think of something cheerful!" 
line 6256=>Then  suddenly  a  great  light  appeared  in  the  low  place  in  the  hills  and  the 
line 6257=>northern end of the lake turned golden. 
line 6258=>"The King  beneath  the Mountain!"  they  shouted.  "His wealth  is  like  the  Sun, 
line 6259=>his silver like a fountain, his rivers golden run! The  river is running gold from the 
line 6260=>Mountain!"  they  cried,  and  everywhere  windows  were  opening  and  feet  were 
line 6261=>hurrying. 
line 6262=>There was once more a  tremendous excitement and enthusiasm. But  the grim-
line 6263=>voiced fellow ran hotfoot to the Master. "The dragon is coming or I am a fool!" he 
line 6264=>cried. "Cut the bridges! To arms! To arms!" 
line 6265=>Then  warning  trumpets  were  suddenly  sounded,  and  echoed  along  the  rocky 
line 6266=>shores.  The  cheering  stopped  and  the  joy was  turned  to  dread.  So  it was  that  the 
line 6267=>dragon  did  not  find  them  quite  unprepared.  Before  long,  so  great was  his  speed, 
line 6268=>
line 6269=>####-they  could  see  him  as  a  spark  of  fire  rushing  towards  them  and  growing  ever 
line 6270=>huger  and more  bright,  and  not  the most  foolish  doubted  that  the  prophecies  had 
line 6271=>gone  rather wrong. Still  they had a  little  time. Every vessel  in  the town was filled 
line 6272=>with  water,  every  warrior  was  armed,  every  arrow  and  dart  was  ready,  and  the 
line 6273=>bridge  to  the  land  was  thrown  down  and  destroyed,  before  the  roar  of  Smaug's 
line 6274=>terrible  approach  grew  loud,  and  the  lake  rippled  red  as  fire  beneath  the  awful 
line 6275=>beating of his wings. 
line 6276=>Amid  shrieks  and  wailing  and  the  shouts  of  men  he  came  over  them,  swept 
line 6277=>towards the bridges and was foiled! The bridge was gone, and his enemies were on 
line 6278=>an  island  in  deep  water-too  deep  and  dark  and  cool  for  his  liking.  If  he  plunged 
line 6279=>into  it, a vapour and a steam would arise enough  to cover all  the  land with a mist 
line 6280=>for days; but  the  lake was mightier  than he,  it would quench him before he could 
line 6281=>pass through. 
line 6282=>Roaring  he  swept  back  over  the  town.  A  hail  of  dark  arrows  leaped  up  and 
line 6283=>snapped and  rattled on his  scales and  jewels, and  their  shafts  fell back kindled by 
line 6284=>his  breath  burning  and  hissing  into  the  lake.  No  fireworks  you  ever  imagined 
line 6285=>equalled the sights that night. At the twanging of the bows and the shrilling of the 
line 6286=>trumpets  the  dragon's wrath blazed to its height, till he was blind and mad with it. 
line 6287=>No  one  had  dared  to  give  battle  to  him  for  many  an  age;  nor  would  they  have 
line 6288=>dared  now,  if  it  had  not  been  for  the  grim-voiced man  (Bard was his name), who 
line 6289=>ran to and fro cheering on the archers and urging the Master to order them to fight 
line 6290=>to the last arrow.  
line 6291=>Fire leaped from the dragon's jaws. He circled for a while high in the air above 
line 6292=>them lighting all the lake; the trees by the shores shone like copper and like blood 
line 6293=>with  leaping shadows of dense black at their feet. Then down he swooped straight 
line 6294=>through  the  arrow-storm,  reckless  in  his  rage,  taking  no  heed  to  turn  his  scaly 
line 6295=>sides towards his foes, seeking only to set their town ablaze. 
line 6296=>Fire  leaped  from  thatched  roofs  and  wooden  beam-ends  as  he  hurtled  down 
line 6297=>and  past  and  round  again,  though  all  had  been  drenched  with  water  before  he 
line 6298=>came. Once more water was flung by a hundred hands wherever a spark appeared. 
line 6299=>Back  swirled  the  dragon.  A  sweep  of  his  tail  and  the  roof  of  the  Great  House 
line 6300=>crumbled  and  smashed  down.  Flames  unquenchable  sprang  high  into  the  night. 
line 6301=>Another  swoop and another, and another house and  then another  sprang afire and 
line 6302=>fell;  and  still  no  arrow  hindered  Smaug  or  hurt  him  more  than  a  fly  from  the 
line 6303=>marshes.  Already  men  were  jumping  into  the  water  on  every  side.  Women  and 
line 6304=>children  were  being  huddled  into  laden  boats  in  the  market-pool. Weapons were 
line 6305=>flung down. There was mourning and weeping, where but a little time ago the old 
line 6306=>
line 6307=>####-songs  of mirth  to  come  had  been  sung  about  the  dwarves. Now men cursed  their 
line 6308=>names.  The  Master  himself  was  turning  to  his  great  gilded  boat,  hoping  to  row 
line 6309=>away  in  the confusion and save himself. Soon all  the  town would be deserted and 
line 6310=>burned down to the surface of the lake. That was the dragon's hope. They could all 
line 6311=>get  into  boats  for  all  he  cared.  There  he  could  have  fine  sport  hunting  them,  or 
line 6312=>they could stop till they starved. Let them try to get to land and he would be ready. 
line 6313=>Soon  he  would  set  all  the  shoreland  woods  ablaze  and  wither  every  field  and 
line 6314=>pasture.  Just  now  he  was  enjoying  the  sport  of  town-baiting  more  than  he  had 
line 6315=>enjoyed anything for years. But there was still a company of archers that held their 
line 6316=>ground among the burning houses. Their captain was Bard, grim-voiced and grim-
line 6317=>faced,  whose  friends  had  accused  him  of  prophesying  floods  and  poisoned  fish, 
line 6318=>though  they  knew  his  worth  and  courage.  He  was  a  descendant  in  long  line  of 
line 6319=>Girion, Lord of Dale, whose wife and child had escaped down  the Running River 
line 6320=>from  the  ruin  long  ago. Now  he  shot with  a  great yew bow,  till all his arrows but 
line 6321=>one were spent. The flames were near him. His companions were leaving him. He 
line 6322=>bent his bow for  the  last  time. Suddenly out of  the dark something fluttered  to his 
line 6323=>shoulder.  He  started-but  it was  only  an  old  thrush. Unafraid  it perched by his ear 
line 6324=>and it brought him news. Marvelling he found he could understand its tongue, for 
line 6325=>he was of the race of Dale. 
line 6326=>"Wait! Wait!"  it  said  to  him.  "The moon  is  rising.  Look  for  the  hollow  of  the 
line 6327=>left  breast  as  he  flies  and  turns  above  you!" And while Bard paused  in wonder  it 
line 6328=>told  him  of  tidings  up  in  the  Mountain  and  of  all  that  it  had  heard.  Then  Bard 
line 6329=>drew his bow-string to his ear. The dragon was circling back, flying low, and as he 
line 6330=>came the moon rose above the eastern shore and silvered his great wings. 
line 6331=>"Arrow!"  said  the  bowman.  "Black  arrow!  I  have  saved  you  to  the  last.  You 
line 6332=>have never  failed me and always  I have  recovered you.  I had you  from my  father 
line 6333=>and  he  from  of  old.  If  ever  you  came  from  the  forges  of  the  true  king  under  the 
line 6334=>Mountain, go now and speed well!" 
line 6335=>The  dragon  swooped  once more  lower  than  ever,  and  as  he  turned  and  dived 
line 6336=>down his belly glittered white with  sparkling  fires of gems  in  the moon-but not in 
line 6337=>one place. The great bow  twanged. The black arrow sped straight from  the string, 
line 6338=>straight  for  the  hollow  by  the  left  breast  where  the  foreleg  was  flung  wide.  In  it 
line 6339=>smote and vanished, barb, shaft and  feather, so  fierce was  its  flight. With a shriek 
line 6340=>that  deafened men,  felled  trees  and  split  stone,  Smaug  shot  spouting  into  the  air, 
line 6341=>turned over and crashed down from on high in ruin. 
line 6342=>Full on  the  town he  fell. His  last  throes splintered  it  to sparks and gledes. The 
line 6343=>lake roared  in. A vast steam  leaped up, white  in  the sudden dark under  the moon. 
line 6344=>
line 6345=>####-There  was  a  hiss,  a  gushing  whirl,  and  then  silence.  And  that  was  the  end  of 
line 6346=>Smaug  and  Esgaroth,  but  not  of  Bard.  The waxing moon  rose  higher  and  higher 
line 6347=>and the wind grew loud and cold. It twisted the white fog into bending pillars and 
