line 6349=>marshes before Mirkwood. Then the many boats could be seen dotted dark on the 
line 6350=>surface of  the  lake, and down  the wind came  the voices of  the people of Esgaroth 
line 6351=>lamenting  their  lost  town and goods and  ruined houses. But  they had  really much 
line 6352=>to be  thankful  for, had  they  thought of  it,  though  it  could hardly be  expected  that 
line 6353=>they should just then: three quarters of the people of the town had at least escaped 
line 6354=>alive;  their  woods  and  fields  and  pastures  and  cattle  and  most  of  their  boats 
line 6355=>remained undamaged; and the dragon was dead. What that meant they had not yet 
line 6356=>realized. 
line 6357=>They  gathered  in  mournful  crowds  upon  the  western  shores,  shivering  in  the 
line 6358=>cold wind,  and  their  first  complaints  and  anger were  against  the Master, who had 
line 6359=>left the town so soon, while some were still willing to defend it. 
line 6360=>"He  may  have  a  good  head  for  business-especially  his  own  business,"  some 
line 6361=>murmured, "but he  is no good when anything serious happens!" And  they praised 
line 6362=>the courage of Bard and his last mighty shot. "If only he had not been killed," they 
line 6363=>all  said,  "we  would  make  him  a  king.  Bard  the  Dragon-shooter  of  the  line  of 
line 6364=>Girion! Alas that he is lost!" 
line 6365=>And  in  the very midst of  their  talk, a  tall figure stepped from  the shadows. He 
line 6366=>was drenched with water, his black hair hung wet over his face and shoulders, and 
line 6367=>a fierce light was in his eyes. 
line 6368=>"Bard  is  not  lost!"  he  cried.  "He  dived  from  Esgaroth,  when  the  enemy  was 
line 6369=>slain. I am Bard, of the line of Girion; I am the slayer of the dragon!" 
line 6370=>"King  Bard!  King  Bard!"  they  shouted;  but  the Master  ground  his  chattering 
line 6371=>teeth. 
line 6372=>"Girion was lord of Dale, not king of Esgaroth," he said. "In the Lake-town we 
line 6373=>have  always  elected masters  from  among  the old  and wise,  and have not  endured 
line 6374=>the rule of mere fighting men. Let 'King Bard' go back to his own kingdom-Dale is 
line 6375=>now freed by his valour, and nothing binders his return. And any that wish can go 
line 6376=>with  him,  if  they  prefer  the  cold  shores  under  the  shadow  of  the Mountain  to  the 
line 6377=>green shores of the lake. The wise will stay here and hope to rebuild our town, and 
line 6378=>enjoy again in time its peace and riches." 
line 6379=>"We will have King Bard!" the people near at hand shouted in reply. "We have 
line 6380=>had  enough  of  the  old men  and  the money-counters!" And people further off took 
line 6381=>
line 6382=>####-up the cry: "Up the Bowman, and down with Moneybags," till the clamour echoed 
line 6383=>along the shore. 
line 6384=>"I  am  the  last man  to  undervalue  Bard  the  Bowman,"  said  the Master warily 
line 6385=>(for Bard now stood close beside him). "He has tonight earned an eminent place in 
line 6386=>the  roll  of  the  benefactors  of  our  town;  and  he  is  worthy  of  many  imperishable 
line 6387=>songs.  But,  why  O  People?"-and  here  the Master  rose  to  his  feet  and  spoke  very 
line 6388=>loud and clear â€“ "why do I get all your blame? For what fault am I to be deposed? 
line 6389=>Who  aroused  the  dragon  from  his  slumber,  I might  ask? Who obtained of us rich 
line 6390=>gifts  and  ample  help,  and  led  us  to  believe  that  old  songs  could  come  true? Who 
line 6391=>played  on  our  soft  hearts  and  our  pleasant  fancies? What  sort  of  gold  have  they 
line 6392=>sent  down  the  river  to  reward  us?  Dragon-fire  and  ruin!  From  whom  should we 
line 6393=>claim the recompense of our damage, and aid for our widows and orphans?" 
line 6394=>As  you  see,  the Master  had  not  got  his  position  for  nothing.  The  result  of  his 
line 6395=>words  was  that  for  the  moment  the  people  quite  forgot  their  idea  of  a  new  king, 
line 6396=>and  turned  their angry  thoughts  towards Thorin and his company. Wild and bitter 
line 6397=>words were shouted from many sides; and some of those who had before sung the 
line 6398=>old  songs  loudest,  were  now  heard  as  loudly  crying  that  the  dwarves  had  stirred 
line 6399=>the dragon up against them deliberately! 
line 6400=>"Fools!" said Bard. "Why waste words and wrath on those unhappy creatures? 
line 6401=>Doubtless  they  perished  first  in  fire,  before  Smaug  came  to  us."  Then  even  as  he 
line 6402=>was  speaking,  the  thought  came  into  his  heart  of  the  fabled  treasure  of  the 
line 6403=>Mountain lying without guard or owner, and he fell suddenly silent. He thought of 
line 6404=>the Master's  words,  and  of  Dale  rebuilt,  and  filled  with  golden  bells,  if  he  could 
line 6405=>but find the men. 
line 6406=>At  length  he  spoke  again:  "This  is  no  time  for  angry  words.  Master,  or  for 
line 6407=>considering weighty plans of change. There is work to do. I serve you still-though 
line 6408=>after  a  while  I  may  think  again  of  your  words  and  go  North  with  any  that  will 
line 6409=>follow me." 
line 6410=>Then  he  strode  off  to  help  in  the  ordering  of  the  camps  and  in  the  care  of  the 
line 6411=>sick  and  the  wounded.  But  the  Master  scowled  at  his  back  as  he  went,  and 
line 6412=>remained  sitting  on  the  ground. He  thought much  but  said  little,  unless  it was  to 
line 6413=>call  loudly  for  men  to  bring  him  fire  and  food.  Now  everywhere  Bard  went  he 
line 6414=>found  talk  running  like  fire  among  the  people  concerning  the  vast  treasure  that 
line 6415=>was  now  unguarded.  Men  spoke  of  the  recompense  for  all  their  harm  that  they 
line 6416=>would soon get from it, and wealth over and to spare with which to buy rich things 
line 6417=>from  the  South;  and  it  cheered  them  greatly  in  their  plight.  That was as well,  for 
line 6418=>the night was bitter and miserable. Shelters could be contrived for few (the Master 
line 6419=>
line 6420=>####-had one)  and  there was  little  food  (even  the Master went  short). Many  took  ill of 
line 6421=>wet  and  cold  and  sorrow  that  night,  and  afterwards  died,  who  had  escaped 
line 6422=>uninjured from the ruin of the town; and in the days that followed there was much 
line 6423=>sickness and great hunger.  
line 6424=>Meanwhile  Bard  took  the  lead,  and  ordered  things  as  he  wished,  though 
line 6425=>always  in  the  Master's  name,  and  he  had  a  hard  task  to  govern  the  people  and 
line 6426=>direct  the  preparations  for  their  protection  and  housing.  Probably  most  of  them 
line 6427=>would  have  perished  in  the winter  that  now  hurried  after  autumn,  if  help  had  not 
line 6428=>been to hand. But help came swiftly; for Bard at once had speedy messengers sent 
line 6429=>up  the  river  to  the Forest  to ask  the aid of  the King of  the Elves of  the Wood, and 
line 6430=>these messengers had found a host already on the move, although it was then only 
line 6431=>the third day after the fall of Smaug. 
line 6432=>The Elvenking had received news from his own messengers and from the birds 
line 6433=>that  loved  his  folk,  and  already  knew  much  of  what  had  happened.  Very  great 
line 6434=>indeed was  the commotion among all  things with wings  that dwelt on  the borders 
line 6435=>of  the Desolation of  the Dragon. The  air was  filled with  circling  flocks,  and  their 
line 6436=>swift-flying messengers  flew  here  and  there  across  the  sky.  Above  the  borders  of 
line 6437=>the  Forest  there  was  whistling,  crying  and  piping.  Far  over  Mirkwood  tidings 
line 6438=>spread: "Smaug is dead!" Leaves rustled and startled ears were lifted. Even before 
line 6439=>the  Elvenking  rode  forth  the  news  had  passed west  right  to  the  pinewoods  of  the 
line 6440=>Misty Mountains; Beorn had heard it in his wooden house, and the goblins were at 
line 6441=>council in their caves. 
line 6442=>"That  will  be  the  last  we  shall  hear  of  Thorin  Oakenshield,  I  fear,"  said  the 
line 6443=>king. "He would have done better to have remained my guest. It is an ill wind, all 
line 6444=>the  same,"  he  added,  "that  blows  no  one  any  good."  For  he  too  had  not  forgotten 
line 6445=>the legend of the wealth of Thror. So it was that Bard's messengers found him now 
line 6446=>marching  with  many  spearmen  and  bowmen;  and  crows  were  gathered  thick, 
line 6447=>above him,  for  they  thought  that war was awakening again,  such as had not been 
line 6448=>in  those parts  for a  long age. But  the king, when he  received  the prayers of Bard, 
line 6449=>had  pity,  for  he  was  the  lord  of  a  good  and  kindly  people;  so  turning  his march, 
line 6450=>which  had  at  first  been  direct  towards  the  Mountain,  he  hastened  now  down  the 
line 6451=>river  to  the  Long  Lake.  He  had  not  boats  or  rafts  enough  for  his  host,  and  they 
line 6452=>were  forced  to  go  the  slower way  by  foot;  but  great  store  of  goods he sent ahead 
line 6453=>by water. Still elves are lightâ€“footed, and though they were not in these days much 
line 6454=>used  to  the  marches  and  the  treacherous  lands  between  the  Forest  and  the  Lake, 
line 6455=>their going was swift. Only five days after the death of the dragon they came upon 
line 6456=>the  shores and  looked on  the  ruins of  the  town. Their welcome was good, as may 
line 6457=>
line 6458=>####-be expected, and the men and their Master were ready to make any bargain for the 
line 6459=>future in return for the Elvenking's aid. 
line 6460=>Their plans were soon made. With the women and the children, the old and the 
line 6461=>unfit,  the  Master  remained  behind;  and  with  him  were  some  men  of  crafts  and 
line 6462=>many  skilled  elves;  and  they  busied  themselves  felling  trees,  and  collecting  the 
line 6463=>timber  sent  down  from  the  Forest.  Then  they  set  about  raising  many  huts  by  the 
line 6464=>shore  against  the  oncoming  winter;  and  also  under  the  Master's  direction  they 
line 6465=>began  the planning of a new  town, designed more fair and  large even  than before, 
line 6466=>but not  in  the  same place. They  removed northward higher up  the  shore;  for  ever 
line 6467=>after  they  had  a  dread  of  the  water  where  the  dragon  lay.  He  would  never  again 
line 6468=>return to his golden bed, but was stretched cold as stone, twisted upon the floor of 
line 6469=>the  shallows.  There  for  ages  his  huge  bones  could  be  seen  in  calm weather  amid 
line 6470=>the  ruined  piles  of  the old  town. But  few dared  to cross  the cursed spot, and none 
line 6471=>dared  to dive  into  the shivering water or recover  the precious stones  that fell from 
line 6472=>his rotting carcass. 
line 6473=>But  all  the men  of  arms  who  were  still  able,  and  the most  of  the  Elvenking's 
line 6474=>array,  got  ready  to march  north  to  the Mountain.  It  was  thus  that  in  eleven  days 
line 6475=>from the ruin of the town the head of their host passed the rock-gates at the end of 
line 6476=>the lake and came into the desolate lands. 
line 6477=>
line 6478=>####-<h4>Chapter 15</h4> <br> 
line 6479=>
line 6480=>The Gathering of the Clouds 
line 6481=>
line 6482=> 
line 6483=>Now  we  will  return  to  Bilbo  and  the  dwarves.  All  night  one  of  them  had 
line 6484=>watched,  but when morning  came  they  had  not  heard  or  seen  any  sign  of  danger. 
line 6485=>But ever more thickly the birds were gathering. Their companies came flying from 
line 6486=>the  South;  and  the  crows  that  still  lived  about  the Mountain  were  wheeling  and 
line 6487=>crying unceasingly above. 
line 6488=>"Something  strange  is  happening,"  said  Thorin.  "The  time  has  gone  for  the 
line 6489=>autumn  wanderings;  and  these  are  birds  that  dwell  always  in  the  land;  there  are 
line 6490=>starlings  and  flocks  of  finches;  and  far  off  there  are  many  carrion  birds  as  if  a 
line 6491=>battle were afoot!" 
line 6492=>Suddenly Bilbo pointed: "There  is  that old  thrush again!" he cried. "He seems 
line 6493=>to have escaped, when Smaug  smashed  the mountain-side, but I don't suppose the 
line 6494=>snails have!" 
line 6495=>Sure  enough  the  old  thrush was  there,  and  as  Bilbo  pointed,  he  flew  towards 
line 6496=>them  and  perched  on  a  stone  near  by. Then  he  fluttered  his wings  and  sang;  then 
line 6497=>he  cocked  his  head  on  one  side,  as  if  to  listen;  and  again  he  sang,  and  again  he 
line 6498=>listened. 
line 6499=>"I  believe  he  is  trying  to  tell  us  something,"  said  Balin;  "but  I  cannot  follow 
line 6500=>the  speech  of  such  birds,  it  is  very  quick  and  difficult.  Can  you  make  it  out 
line 6501=>Baggins?" 
line 6502=>"Not very well," said Bilbo (as a matter of fact, he could make nothing of it at 
line 6503=>all); "but the old fellow seems .very excited." 
line 6504=>"I only wish he was a raven!" said Balin. 
line 6505=>"I  thought  you  did  not  like  them!  You  seemed  very  shy  of  them,  when  we 
line 6506=>came this way before." 
line 6507=>"Those  were  crows!  And  nasty  suspicious-looking  creatures  at  that,  and  rude 
line 6508=>as  well.  You  must  have  heard  the  ugly  names  they were  calling  after  us. But  the 
line 6509=>ravens  are  different.  There  used  to  be  great  friendship  between  them  and  the 
line 6510=>people  of  Thror;  and  they  often  brought  us  secret  news,  and were  rewarded with 
line 6511=>such bright things as they coveted to hide in their dwellings. 
line 6512=>"They  live many  a  year,  and  their memories  are  long,  and  they  hand  on  their 
line 6513=>wisdom to their children. I knew many among the ravens of the rocks when I was 
line 6514=>a  dwarf-  lad.  This  very  height  was  once  named  Ravenhill,  because  there  was  a 
line 6515=>
line 6516=>####-wise  and  famous  pair,  old  Care  and  his  wife,  that  lived  here  above  the  guard-
line 6517=>chamber. But I don't suppose that any of that ancient breed linger here now." 
line 6518=>No  sooner  had  he  finished  speaking  than  the  old  thrush  gave  a  loud  call,  and 
line 6519=>immediately flew away.  
line 6520=>"We may not understand him, but that old bird understands us, I am sure," said 
line 6521=>Balin. "Keep watch now, and see what happens!" 
line 6522=>Before  long  there  was  a  fluttering  of  wings,  and  back  came  the  thrush;  and 
line 6523=>with him came a most decrepit old bird. He was getting blind, he could hardly fly, 
line 6524=>and  the  top of his head was bald. He was an aged raven of great size. He alighted 
line 6525=>stiffly  on  the  ground  before  them,  slowly  flapped  his wings,  and  bobbed  towards 
line 6526=>Thorin. 
line 6527=>"O  Thorin  son  of  Thrain,  and  Balin  son  of  Fundin,"  he  croaked  (and  Bilbo 
line 6528=>could  understand  what  he  said,  for  he  used  ordinary  language  and  not  bird-
line 6529=>speech).  "I  am  RÃ³ac  son  of  Carc.  Carc  is  dead,  but  he  was  well  known  to  you 
line 6530=>once. It is a hundred years and three and fifty since I came out of the egg, but I do 
line 6531=>not  forget what my  father  told me. Now  I  am  the  chief  of  the  great  ravens  of  the 
line 6532=>Mountain. We are few, but we remember still the king that was of old. Most of my 
line 6533=>people are abroad, for there are great tidings in the South â€“ some are tidings of joy 
line 6534=>to you, and some you will not think so good. 
line 6535=>"Behold! the birds are gathering back again to the Mountain and to Dale from 
line 6536=>South and East and West, for word has gone out that Smaug is dead!" 
line 6537=>"Dead!  Dead?"  shouted  the  dwarves.  "Dead!  Then  we  have  been  in  needless 
line 6538=>fear-and the treasure is ours!" 
line 6539=>They all sprang up and began to caper about for joy.  
line 6540=>"Yes,  dead,"  said RÃ³ac. "The  thrush, may his feathers never fall, saw him die, 
line 6541=>and  we may  trust  his  words.  He  saw  him  fall  in  battle  with  the men  of  Esgaroth 
line 6542=>the third night back from now at the rising of the moon." 
line 6543=>It was some time before Thorin could bring the dwarves to be silent and listen 
