line 6567=>and strong of wing, that you would send messengers to our kin in the mountains of 
line 6568=>the  North,  both  west  from  here  and  east,  and  tell  them  of  our  plight.  But  go 
line 6569=>specially to my cousin Dain in the Iron Hills, for he has many people well-armed, 
line 6570=>and dwells nearest to this place. Bid him hasten!" 
line 6571=>"I  will  not  say  if  this  counsel  be  good  or  bad,"  croaked  RÃ³ac;  "but  I will  do 
line 6572=>what can be done." Then off he slowly flew.  
line 6573=>"Back now to the Mountain!" cried Thorin. "We have little time to lose." 
line 6574=>"And  little  food  to  use!"  cried  Bilbo,  always  practical  on  such  points.  In  any 
line 6575=>case  he  felt  that  the  adventure was, properly speaking, over  .with  the death of  the 
line 6576=>dragon-in  which  he  was  much  mistaken-and  he  would  have  given  most  of  his 
line 6577=>share of the profits for the peaceful winding up of these affairs. 
line 6578=>"Back  to  the  Mountain!"  cried  the  dwarves  as  if  they  had  not  heard  him;  so 
line 6579=>back he had  to go with  them. As you have heard  some of  the  events  already, you 
line 6580=>will  see  that  the  dwarves  still  had  some  days  before  them.  They  explored  the 
line 6581=>caverns  once  more,  and  found,  as  they  expected,  that  only  the  Front  Gate 
line 6582=>remained  open;  all  the  other  gates  (except,  of  course,  the  small  secret  door)  had 
line 6583=>long  ago  been  broken  and  blocked  by  Smaug,  and  no  sign  of  them  remained.  So 
line 6584=>now  they  began  to  labour  hard  in  fortifying  the  main  entrance,  and  in  remaking 
line 6585=>the  road  that  led  from  it.  Tools  were  to  be  found  in  plenty  that  the  miners  and 
line 6586=>quarriers  and  builders  of  old  had  used;  and  at  such  work  the  dwarves  were  still 
line 6587=>very skilled. 
line 6588=>As  they  worked  the  ravens  brought  them  constant  tidings.  In  this  way  they 
line 6589=>learned  that  the  Elvenking  had  turned  aside  to  the  Lake,  and  they  still  had  a 
line 6590=>breathing  space. Better  still,  they heard  that  three of  their ponies had escaped and 
line 6591=>
line 6592=>####-were wandering wild far down the banks of the Running River, not far from where 
line 6593=>the  rest of  their  stores had been  left. So while  the others went on with  their work, 
line 6594=>Fili  and  Kili  were  sent,  guided  by  a  raven,  to  find  the  ponies  and  bring  back  all 
line 6595=>they could. 
line 6596=>They were  four  days  gone,  and  by  that  time  they  knew  that  the  joined  armies 
line 6597=>of  the  Lake-men  and  the  Elves  were  hurrying  towards  the  Mountain.  But  now 
line 6598=>their hopes were higher; for they had food for some weeks with care-chiefly cram, 
line 6599=>of course, and they were very tired of it; but cram is much better than nothing-and 
line 6600=>already the gate was blocked with a wall of squared stones laid dry, but very thick 
line 6601=>and  high  across  the  opening.  There  were  holes  in  the  wall  through  which  they 
line 6602=>could  see  (or  shoot)  but  no  entrance.  They  climbed  in  or  out  with  ladders,  and 
line 6603=>hauled stuff up with ropes. For the issuing of the stream they had contrived a small 
line 6604=>low arch under the new wall; but near the entrance they had so altered the narrow 
line 6605=>bed  that  a wide pool  stretched  from  the mountain-wall to the head of the fall over 
line 6606=>which  the  stream  went  towards  Dale.  Approach  to  the  Gate  was  now  only 
line 6607=>possible, without  swimming,  along  a narrow  ledge of  the  cliff,  to  the  right  as one 
line 6608=>looked  outwards  from  the wall.  The  ponies  they  had  brought  only  to  the  head  of 
line 6609=>the  steps  above  the  old  bridge,  and  unloading  them  there  had  bidden  them  return 
line 6610=>to their masters and sent them back riderless to the South. 
line 6611=>There  came  a  night  when  suddenly  there  were  many  lights  as  of  fires  and 
line 6612=>torches away south in Dale before them. 
line 6613=>"They  have  come!"  called  Balin.  "And  their  camp  is  very  great.  They  must 
line 6614=>have come into the valley under the cover of dusk along both banks of the river." 
line 6615=>That night the dwarves slept little. The morning was still pale when they saw a 
line 6616=>company approaching. From behind  their wall  they watched  them come up  to  the 
line 6617=>valley's head and climb slowly up. Before long they could see that both men of the 
line 6618=>lake  armed  as  if  for  war  and  elvish  bowmen  were  among  them.  At  length  the 
line 6619=>foremost  of  these  climbed  the  tumbled  rocks  and  appeared  at  the  top  of  the  falls; 
line 6620=>and very great was their surprise to see the pool before them and the Gate blocked 
line 6621=>with a wall of new-hewn stone. 
line 6622=>As they stood pointing and speaking to one another Thorin hailed them: "Who 
line 6623=>are  you,"  he  called  in  a  very  loud  voice,  "that  come  as  if  in  war  to  the  gates  of 
line 6624=>Thorin son of Thrain, King under the Mountain, and what do you desire?" 
line 6625=>But  they  answered  nothing.  Some  turned  swiftly  back,  and  the  others  after 
line 6626=>gazing  for  a while  at  the Gate  and  its  defences  soon  followed  them. That  day  the 
line 6627=>camp was moved  and was  brought  right  between  the  arms  of  the Mountain.  The 
line 6628=>rocks echoed then with voices and with song, as they had not done for many a day. 
line 6629=>
line 6630=>####-There was  the  sound,  too,  of  elven-harps and of sweet music; and as  it echoed up 
line 6631=>towards  them  it  seemed  that  the  chill  of  the  air  was  warmed,  and  they  caught 
line 6632=>faintly the fragrance of woodland flowers blossoming in spring. 
line 6633=>Then Bilbo longed to escape from the dark fortress and to go down and join in 
line 6634=>the mirth  and  feasting  by  the  fires.  Some  of  the  younger  dwarves were moved  in 
line 6635=>their  hearts,  too,  and  they  muttered  that  they  wished  things  had  fallen  out 
line 6636=>otherwise and that they might welcome such folk as friends; but Thorin scowled. 
