line 6680=>This song appeared to please Thorin, and he smiled again and grew merry; and 
line 6681=>he began reckoning the distance to the Iron Hills and how long it would be before 
line 6682=>Dain  could  reach  the  Lonely Mountain,  if  he  had  set  out  as  soon  as  the message 
line 6683=>reached  him.  But  Bilbo's  heart  fell,  both  at  the  song  and  the  talk:  they  sounded 
line 6684=>much  too  warlike.  The  next  morning  early  a  company  of  spearmen  was  seen 
line 6685=>crossing  the  river,  and  marching  up  the  valley.  They  bore  with  them  the  green 
line 6686=>banner of the Elvenking and the blue banner of the Lake, and they advanced until 
line 6687=>they stood right before the wall at the Gate. 
line 6688=>Again Thorin hailed  them  in a  loud voice: "Who are you  that come armed for 
line 6689=>war to the gates of Thorin son of Thrain, King under the Mountain?" This time he 
line 6690=>was answered. 
line 6691=>A  tall  man  stood  forward,  dark  of  hair  and  grim  of  face,  and  he  cried:  "Hail 
line 6692=>Thorin! Why do you fence yourself like a robber in his hold? We are not yet foes, 
line 6693=>and  we  rejoice  that  you  are  alive  beyond  our  hope.  We  came  expecting  to  find 
line 6694=>none  living  here;  yet  now  that  we  are  met  there  is  matter  for  a  parley  and  a 
line 6695=>council." 
line 6696=>"Who are you, and of what would you parley?" 
line 6697=>"I am Bard, and by my hand was the dragon slain and your treasure delivered. 
line 6698=>Is that not a matter that concerns you? Moreover I am by right descent the heir of 
line 6699=>Girion of Dale,  and  in your hoard  is mingled much of  the wealth of his halls  and 
line 6700=>town,  which  of  old  Smaug  stole.  Is  not  that  a  matter  of  which  we  may  speak? 
line 6701=>Further  in  his  last  battle  Smaug  destroyed  the  dwellings  of  the men  of  Esgaroth, 
line 6702=>and  I  am  yet  the  servant  of  their Master.  I would  speak  for  him  and  ask whether 
line 6703=>you  have  no  thought  for  the  sorrow  and misery  of  his  people.  They  aided  you  in 
line 6704=>your  distress,  and  in  recompense  you  have  thus  far  brought  ruin  only,  though 
line 6705=>doubtless undesigned." 
line 6706=>Now  these were  fair words and  true,  if proudly and grimly  spoken; and Bilbo 
line 6707=>thought  that Thorin would at once admit what  justice was  in  them. He did not, of 
line 6708=>course,  expect  that  any one would remember that it was he who discovered all by 
line 6709=>himself the dragon's weak spot; and that was just as well, for no one ever did. But 
line 6710=>also he did not reckon with the power that gold has upon which a dragon has long 
line 6711=>
line 6712=>####-brooded,  nor with  dwarvish  hearts. Long hours  in  the past days Thorin had  spent 
line 6713=>in the treasury, and the lust of it was heavy on him. Though he had hunted chiefly 
line 6714=>for  the Arkenstone, yet he had  an  eye  for many  another wonderful  thing  that was 
line 6715=>lying there, about which were wound old memories of the labours and the sorrows 
line 6716=>of his race. 
line 6717=>"You  put  your worst  cause  last  and  in  the  chief  place," Thorin  answered.  "To 
line 6718=>the treasure of my people no man has a claim, because Smaug who stole it from us 
line 6719=>also  robbed  him  of  life  or  home.  The  treasure  was  not  his  that  his  evil  deeds 
line 6720=>should  be  amended  with  a  share  of  it.  The  price  of  the  goods  and  the  assistance 
line 6721=>that we  received of  the Lake-men we will fairly pay-in due time. But nothing will 
line 6722=>we  give,  not  even  a  loaf's  worth,  under  threat  of  force. While  an  armed host  lies 
line 6723=>before our doors, we look on you as foes and thieves. 
line 6724=>"It is in my mind to ask what share of their inheritance you would have paid to 
line 6725=>our kindred, had you found the hoard unguarded and us slain." 
line 6726=>"A just question," replied Bard. "But you are not dead, and we are not robbers. 
line 6727=>Moreover  the  wealthy  may  have  pity  beyond  right  on  the  needy  that  befriended 
line 6728=>them when they were in want. And still my other claims remain unanswered." 
line 6729=>"I will  not  parley,  as  I  have  said, with  armed men  at my  gate. Nor  at all with 
line 6730=>the people of the Elvenking, whom I remember with small kindness. In this debate 
line 6731=>they have no place. Begone now ere our arrows fly! And if you would speak with 
line 6732=>me  again,  first  dismiss  the  elvish  host  to  the  woods  where  it  belongs,  and  then 
line 6733=>return, laying down your arms before you approach the threshold." 
line 6734=>"The Elvenking  is my  friend,  and  he  has  succoured  the  people  of  the Lake  in 
line 6735=>their need, though they had no claim but friendship on him," answered Bard. "We 
line 6736=>will  give  you  time  to  repent  your  words.  Gather  your  wisdom  ere  we  return!" 
line 6737=>Then he departed and went back to the camp. 
line 6738=>Ere  many  hours  were  past,  the  banner-bearers  returned,  and  trumpeters  stood 
line 6739=>forth and blew a blast: 
line 6740=>"In  the  name  of  Esgaroth  and  the  Forest,"  one  cried,  "we  speak  unto  Thorin 
line 6741=>Thrain's  son  Oakenshield,  calling  himself  the  King  under  the  Mountain,  and  we 
line 6742=>bid him consider well  the claims  that have been urged, or be declared our  foe. At 
line 6743=>the  least  he  shall  deliver  one  twelfth  portion  of  the  treasure  unto  Bard,  as  the 
line 6744=>dragon-slayer,  and  as  the  heir  of  Girion.  From  that  portion  Bard  will  himself 
line 6745=>contribute  to  the  aid  of  Esgaroth;  but  if  Thorin  would  have  the  friendship  and 
line 6746=>honour of the lands about, as his sires had of old, then he will give also somewhat 
line 6747=>of his own  for  the comfort of  the men of  the Lake." Then Thorin seized a bow of 
line 6748=>
line 6749=>####-horn  and  shot  an  arrow  at  the  speaker.  It  smote  into  his  shield  and  stuck  there 
line 6750=>quivering. 
line 6751=>'"Since  such  is  your  answer,"  he  called  in  return,  "I  declare  the  Mountain 
line 6752=>besieged. You shall not depart from it, until you call on your side for a truce and a 
line 6753=>parley. We will bear no weapons against you, but we leave you to your gold. You 
line 6754=>may eat that, if you will!" 
line 6755=>With  that  the  messengers  departed  swiftly,  and  the  dwarves  were  left  to 
line 6756=>consider  their  case. So grim had Thorin become, that even if they had wished, the 
line 6757=>others  would  not  have  dared  to  find  fault  with  him;  but  indeed  most  of  them 
line 6758=>seemed  to  share  his mind-except perhaps old fat Bombur and Fili and Kili. Bilbo, 
line 6759=>of course, disapproved of  the whole  turn of affairs. He had by now had more than 
line 6760=>enough of the Mountain, and being besieged inside it was not at all to his taste. 
line 6761=>"The whole place still stinks of dragon," he grumbled to himself, "and it makes 
line 6762=>me sick. And cram is beginning simply to stick in my throat." 
line 6763=>
line 6764=>####-<h4>Chapter 16</h4> <br> 
line 6765=>
line 6766=>A Thief in the Night 
line 6767=>
line 6768=> 
line 6769=>Now the days passed slowly and wearily. Many of the dwarves spent their time 
line 6770=>piling  and  ordering  the  treasure;  and  now  Thorin  spoke  of  the  Arkenstone  of 
line 6771=>Thrain, and bade them eagerly to look for it in every comer.  
line 6772=>"For the Arkenstone of my father," he said, "is worth more than a river of gold 
line 6773=>in  itself,  and  to me  it  is  beyond  price.  That  stone  of  all  the  treasure  I  name  unto 
line 6774=>myself, and I will be avenged on anyone who finds it and withholds it." 
line 6775=>Bilbo heard these words and he grew afraid, wondering what would happen, if 
line 6776=>the stone was found-wrapped in an old bundle of tattered oddments that he used as 
line 6777=>a pillow. All the same he did not speak of it, for as the weariness of the days grew 
line 6778=>heavier, the beginnings of a plan had come into his little head. 
line 6779=>Things had gone on like this for some time, when the ravens brought news that 
line 6780=>Dain and more than five hundred dwarves, hurrying from the Iron Hills, were now 
line 6781=>within about two days' march of Dale, coming from the North-East. 
line 6782=>"But  they  cannot  reach  the  Mountain  unmarked,"  said  RÃ³ac,  "and  I  fear  lest 
line 6783=>there  be  battle  in  the  valley.  I  do  not  call  this  counsel  good.  Though  they  are  a 
line 6784=>grim  folk,  they  are  not  likely  to  overcome  the  host  that  besets  you;  and  even  if 
line 6785=>they  did  so, what will  you gain? Winter and snow is hastening behind them. How 
line 6786=>shall you be  fed without  the  friendship and goodwill of  the  lands about you? The 
line 6787=>treasure is likely to be your death, though the dragon is no more!"' 
line 6788=>But  Thorin  was  not moved.  "Winter  and  snow  will  bite both men and elves," 
line 6789=>he said, "and they may find their dwelling in the Waste grievous to bear. With my 
line 6790=>friends behind  them and winter upon  them,  they will perhaps be  in softer mood  to 
line 6791=>parley with." 
line 6792=>That night Bilbo made up his mind. The sky was black and moonless. As soon 
line 6793=>as  it  was  full  dark,  he  went  to  a  corner  of  an  inner  chamber  just  within  the  gate 
line 6794=>and drew from his bundle a rope, and also the Arkenstone wrapped in a rag. Then 
line 6795=>he  climbed  to  the  top  of  the  wall.  Only  Bombur  was  there,  for  it  was  his  turn to 
line 6796=>watch, and the dwarves kept only one watchman at a time. 
line 6797=>"It is mighty cold!" said Bombur. "I wish we could have a fire up here as they 
line 6798=>have in the camp!" 
line 6799=>"It is warm enough inside," said Bilbo. 
line 6800=>
line 6801=>####-"I  daresay;  but  I  am  bound  here  till  midnight,"  grumbled  the  fat  dwarf.  "A 
line 6802=>sorry  business  altogether.  Not  that  I  venture  to  disagree  with  Thorin,  may  his 
line 6803=>beard grow ever longer; yet he was ever a dwarf with a stiff neck." 
line 6804=>"Not as stiff as my legs," said Bilbo. "I am tired of stairs and stone passages. I 
line 6805=>would give a good deal for the feel of grass at my toes." 
line 6806=>"I would give a good deal for the feel of a strong drink in my throat, and for a 
line 6807=>soft bed after a good supper!" 
line 6808=>"I  can't  give  you  those,  while  the  siege  is  going  on.  But  it  is  long  since  I 
line 6809=>watched,  and  I  will  take  your  turn  for  you,  if  you  like.  There  is  no  sleep  in  me 
line 6810=>tonight." 
line 6811=>  "You  are  a  good  fellow,  Mr.  Baggins,  and  I  will  take  your  offer  kindly.  If 
line 6812=>there  should  be  anything  to  note,  rouse me  first, mind  you!  I will  lie  in  the  inner 
line 6813=>chamber to the left, not far away." 
line 6814=>"Off you go!" said Bilbo. "I will wake you at midnight, and you can wake the 
line 6815=>next watchman." As soon as Bombur had gone, Bilbo put on his ring, fastened his 
line 6816=>rope,  slipped  down  over  the wall,  and was  gone. He  had  about  five  hours  before 
line 6817=>him.  Bombur  would  sleep  (he  could  sleep  at  any  time,  and  ever  since  the 
line 6818=>adventure  in  the  forest he was  always  trying  to  recapture  the beautiful dreams he 
line 6819=>had then); and all the others were busy with Thorin. It was unlikely that any, even 
line 6820=>Fili  or  Kili,  would  come out on  the wall until  it was  their  turn.  It was very dark, 
line 6821=>and  the  road  after  a  while,  when  he  left  the  newly made  path  and  climbed  down 
line 6822=>towards the lower course of the stream, was strange to him. At last he came to the 
line 6823=>bend  where  he  had  to  cross  the  water,  if  he  was  to  make  for  the  camp,  as  he 
line 6824=>wished. The bed of the stream was there shallow but already broad, and fording it 
line 6825=>in the dark was not easy for the little hobbit. He was nearly across when he missed 
line 6826=>his  footing  on  a  round  stone  and  fell  into  the  cold  water  with  a  splash.  He  had 
line 6827=>barely  scrambled  out  on  the  far  bank,  shivering  and  spluttering,  when  up  came 
line 6828=>elves in the gloom with bright lanterns and searched for the cause of the noise. 
line 6829=>"That  was  no  fish!"  one  said.  "There  is  a  spy  about.  Hide  your  lights! They 
line 6830=>will help him more  than us,  if  it  is  that queer  little creature  that  is said  to be  their 
line 6831=>servant." 
line 6832=>"Servant,  indeed!"  snorted  Bilbo;  and  in  the  middle  of  his  snort  he  sneezed 
line 6833=>loudly, and the elves immediately gathered towards the sound. 
line 6834=>"Let's  have  a  light!"  he  said.  "I  am  here,  if  you want me!"  and  he  slipped  off 
line 6835=>his ring, and popped from behind a rock. 
line 6836=>
line 6837=>####-They seized him quickly, in spite of their surprise. "Who are you? Are you the 
line 6838=>dwarves' hobbit? What are you doing? How did you get so far past our sentinels?" 
line 6839=>they asked one after another.  
line 6840=>"I am Mr. Bilbo Baggins," he answered, "companion of Thorin, if you want to 
line 6841=>know. I know your king well by sight, though perhaps he doesn't know me to look 
line 6842=>at. But Bard will remember me, and it is Bard I particularly want to see." 
line 6843=>"Indeed!" said they, "and what may be your business?"  
line 6844=>"Whatever  it  is,  it's my own, my good  elves. But  if you wish  ever  to get back 
line 6845=>to  your  own  woods  from  this  cold  cheerless  place,"  he  answered  shivering,  "you 
line 6846=>will  take me  along  quiet  to a fire, where I can dry-and then you will let me speak 
line 6847=>to your chiefs as quick as may be. I have only an hour or two to spare." 
line 6848=>That is how it came about that some two hours after his escape from the Gate, 
line 6849=>Bilbo  was  sitting  beside  a  warm  fire  in  front  of  a  large  tent,  and  there  sat  too, 
