line 6933=>####-<h4>Chapter 17</h4> <br> 
line 6934=>
line 6935=>The Clouds Burst 
line 6936=>
line 6937=> 
line 6938=>Next  day  the  trumpets  rang  early  in  the  camp. Soon  a  single  runner was  seen 
line 6939=>hurrying  along  the  narrow  path.  At  a  distance  he  stood  and  hailed  them,  asking 
line 6940=>whether Thorin would now listen to another embassy, since new tidings had come 
line 6941=>to hand, and matters were changed. 
line 6942=>"That will be Dain!" said Thorin when he heard. "They will have got wind of 
line 6943=>his  coming.  I  thought  that would  alter  their mood! Bid them come few in number 
line 6944=>and weaponless, and I will hear," he called to the messenger.  
line 6945=>About  midday  the  banners  of  the  Forest  and  the  Lake  were  seen  to  be  borne 
line 6946=>forth  again.  A  company  of  twenty  was  approaching.  At  the  beginning  of  the 
line 6947=>narrow  way  they  laid  aside  sword  and  spear,  and  came  on  towards  the  Gate. 
line 6948=>Wondering, the dwarves saw that among them were both Bard and the Elvenking, 
line 6949=>before whom an old man wrapped in cloak and hood bore a strong casket of iron-
line 6950=>bound wood. 
line 6951=>"Hail Thorin!" said Bard. "Are you still of the same mind?" 
line 6952=>"My mind does not change with the rising and setting of a few suns," answered 
line 6953=>Thorin. "Did you come to ask me idle questions? Still the elf-host has not departed 
line 6954=>as  I  bade! Till  then  you  come  in  vain  to  bargain with me."  "Is  there  then nothing 
line 6955=>for which you would yield any of your gold?" 
line 6956=>"Nothing that you or your friends have to offer." 
line 6957=>"What of the Arkenstone of Thrain?" said he, and at the same moment the old 
line 6958=>man  opened  the  casket  and  held  aloft  the  jewel.  The  light  leapt  from  his  hand, 
line 6959=>bright and white in the morning. 
line 6960=>Then Thorin was stricken dumb with amazement and confusion. No one spoke 
line 6961=>for  a  long while. Thorin  at  length broke  the  silence,  and his voice was  thick with 
line 6962=>wrath. "That stone was my father's, and is mine," he said. "Why should I purchase 
line 6963=>my  own?"  But  wonder  overcame  him  and  he  added:  "But  how  came  you  by  the 
line 6964=>heirloom of my house-if there is need to ask such a question of thieves?" 
line 6965=>"We  are  not  thieves," Bard  answered.  "Your  own we will  give  back  in  return 
line 6966=>for our own." 
line 6967=>'How came you by it?" shouted Thorin in gathering rage. 
line 6968=>"I gave it them!" squeaked Bilbo, who was peeping over the wall, by now, in a 
line 6969=>dreadful fright. 
line 6970=>
line 6971=>####-"You!  You!"  cried  Thorin,  turning  upon  him  and  grasping  him  with  both 
line 6972=>hands.  "You  miserable  hobbit!  You  undersized-burglar!"  he  shouted  at  a  loss  for 
line 6973=>words, and he shook poor Bilbo like a rabbit. 
line 6974=>"By the beard of Durin! I wish I had Gandalf here! Curse him for his choice of 
line 6975=>you! May his beard wither! As for you I will throw you to the rocks!" he cried and 
line 6976=>lifted Bilbo in his arms. 
line 6977=>"Stay! Your wish is granted!" said a voice. The old man with the casket threw 
line 6978=>aside  his  hood  and  cloak.  "Here  is  Gandalf!  And  none  too  soon  it  seems.  If  you 
line 6979=>don't  like my Burglar, please don't damage him. Put him down,  and  listen first  to 
