line 6991=>"I will,"  said Thorin  grimly.  "And  I will  let  you  go  at  that-and may we never 
line 6992=>meet again!" Then he turned and spoke over the wall. "I am betrayed," he said. "It 
line 6993=>was rightly guessed that I could not forbear to redeem the Arkenstone, the treasure 
line 6994=>of my house. For it I will give one fourteenth share of the hoard in silver and gold, 
line 6995=>setting  aside  the  gems;  but  that  shall  be  accounted  the  promised  share  of  this 
line 6996=>traitor, and with that reward he shall depart, and you can divide it as you will. He 
line 6997=>will  get  little  enough,  I  doubt  not.  Take  him,  if  you  wish  him  to  live;  and  no 
line 6998=>friendship of mine goes with him. 
line 6999=>"Get down now to your friends!" he said to Bilbo, "or I will throw you down." 
line 7000=>"What about the gold and silver?" asked Bilbo. 
line 7001=>"That shall follow after, as can be arranged," said he. 
line 7002=>"Get down!" 
line 7003=>"Until then we keep the stone," cried Bard. 
line 7004=>"You are not making a very splendid figure as King under the Mountain," said 
line 7005=>Gandalf. "But things may change yet." 
line 7006=>
line 7007=>####-"They may indeed," said Thorin. And already, so strong was the bewilderment 
line 7008=>of  the  treasure upon him, he was pondering whether by the help of Dain he might 
line 7009=>not recapture the Arkenstone and withhold the share of the reward. 
line 7010=>And  so  Bilbo  was  swung  down  from  the  wall,  and  departed  with  nothing  for 
line 7011=>all his trouble, except the armour which Thorin had given him already. More than 
line 7012=>one of the dwarves 'in their hearts felt shame and pity at his going. 
line 7013=>"Farewell!" he cried to them. "We may meet again as friends." 
line 7014=>"Be  off!"  called  Thorin.  "You  have  mail  upon  you,  which  was  made  by  my 
line 7015=>folk,  and  is  too  good  for  you.  It  cannot  be  pierced  .by  arrows;  but  if  you  do  not 
line 7016=>hasten, I will sting your miserable feet. So be swift!" 
line 7017=>"Not so hasty!" said Bard. "We will give you until tomorrow. At noon we will 
line 7018=>return,  and  see  if  you  have  brought  from  the  hoard  the  portion  that  is  to  be  set 
line 7019=>against  the  stone.  If  that  is  done  without  deceit,  then  we  will  depart,  and  the  elf-
line 7020=>host will go back to the Forest. In the meanwhile farewell!" 
line 7021=>With  that  they  went  back  to  the  camp;  but  Thorin  sent  messengers  by  RÃ³ac 
line 7022=>telling Dain of what had passed, and bidding him come with wary speed. 
line 7023=>That day passed and the night. The next day the wind shifted west, and the air 
line 7024=>was  dark  and  gloomy.  The  morning  was  still  early  when  a  cry  was  heard  in  the 
line 7025=>camp.  Runners  came  in  to  report  that  a  host  of  dwarves  had  appeared  round  the 
line 7026=>eastern spur of  the Mountain and was now hastening  to Dale. Dain had come. He 
line 7027=>had  hurried  on  through  the  night,  and  so  had  come  upon  them  sooner  than  they 
line 7028=>had expected. Each one of his folk was clad in a hauberk of steel mail that hung to 
line 7029=>his  knees,  and  his  legs were  covered with  hose  of  a  fine  and  flexible metal mesh, 
line 7030=>the secret of whose making was possessed by Dain's people. 
line 7031=>The  dwarves  are  exceedingly  strong  for  their  height,  but  most  of  these  were 
line 7032=>strong  even  for  dwarves.  In  battle  they  wielded  heavy  two-handed mattocks;  but 
line 7033=>each of  them had also a  short broad  sword at his  side and a  round  shield  slung at 
line 7034=>his  back.  Their  beards  were  forked  and  plaited  and  thrust  into  their  belts.  Their 
line 7035=>caps  were  of  iron  and  they  were  shod  with  iron,  and  their  faces  were  grim. 
line 7036=>Trumpets  called  men  and  elves  to  arms.  Before  long  the  dwarves  could  be  seen 
line 7037=>coming  up  the  valley  at  a  great  pace.  They  halted  between  the  river  and  the 
line 7038=>eastern  spur;  but  a  few  held  on  their  way,  and  crossing  the  river  drew  near  the 
line 7039=>camp;  and  there  they  laid  down  their weapons  and  held  up  their  hands  in  sign  of 
line 7040=>peace. Bard went out to meet them, and with him went Bilbo. 
line 7041=>"We  are  sent  from  Dain  son  of  Nain,"  they  said  when  questioned.  "We  are 
line 7042=>hastening  to our kinsmen  in  the Mountain, since we learn that the kingdom of old 
line 7043=>is  renewed. But who  are  you  that  sit  in  the  plain  as  foes  before  defended walls?" 
line 7044=>
line 7045=>####-This, of. course, in the polite and rather old-fashioned language of such occasions, 
line 7046=>meant simply: "You have no business  here. We are going on, so make way or we 
line 7047=>shall fight you!" They meant to push on between the Mountain and the loop of the 
line 7048=>river, for the narrow land there did not seem to be strongly guarded. 
line 7049=>Bard,  of  course,  refused  to  allow  the  dwarves  to  go  straight  on  to  the 
line 7050=>Mountain. He was  determined  to wait  until  the  gold  and  silver  had  been  brought 
line 7051=>out in exchange for the Arkenstone: for he did not believe that this would be done, 
line 7052=>if  once  the  fortress  was manned  with  so  large  and  warlike  a  company.  They  had 
line 7053=>brought with  them a great store of supplies; for  the dwarves can carry very heavy 
line 7054=>burdens,  and  nearly  all  of  Dain's  folks,  in  spite  of  their  rapid  march,  bore  huge 
line 7055=>packs  on  their  backs  in  addition  to  their  weapons.  They  would  stand  a  siege  for 
line 7056=>weeks,  and  by  that  time yet more dwarves might  come,  and yet more,  for Thorin 
line 7057=>had many relatives. Also they would be able to reopen and guard some other gate, 
line 7058=>so that the besiegers would have to encircle the whole mountain; and for that they 
line 7059=>had not sufficient numbers. 
line 7060=>These  were,  in  fact,  precisely  their  plans  (for  the  raven-messengers  had  been 
line 7061=>busy between Thorin and Dain); but  for  the moment  the way was barred, so after 
line 7062=>angry  words  the  dwarf-messengers  retired  muttering  in  their  beards.  Bard  then 
line 7063=>sent messengers  at  once  to  the Gate; but  they  found no gold or payment. Arrows 
line 7064=>came forth as soon as they were within shot, and they hastened back in dismay. In 
line 7065=>the  camp  all  was  now  astir,  as  if  for  battle;  for  the  dwarves  of  Dain  were 
line 7066=>advancing along the eastern bank. 
line 7067=>"Fools!"  laughed  Bard,  "to  come  thus  beneath  the  Mountain's  arm!  They  do 
line 7068=>not understand war above ground, whatever they may know of battle in the mines. 
line 7069=>There  are many  of  our  archers  and  spearmen  now  hidden  in  the  rocks  upon  their 
line 7070=>right  flank. Dwarf-mail may  be  good,  but  they will  soon be hard put  to  it. Let us 
line 7071=>set on them now from both sides, before they are fully rested!" 
line 7072=>But  the  Elvenking  said:  "Long will  I  tarry,  ere  I  begin  this war  for  gold.  The 
line 7073=>dwarves cannot press us, unless we will, or do anything  that we cannot mark. Let 
line 7074=>us  hope  still  for  something  that  will  bring  reconciliation.  Our  advantage  in 
line 7075=>numbers will be enough, if in the end it must come to unhappy blows." 
line 7076=>But he reckoned without the dwarves. The knowledge that the Arkenstone was 
line 7077=>in  the  hands  of  the  besiegers  burned  in  their  thoughts;  also  they  guessed  the 
line 7078=>hesitation of Bard and his friends, and resolved to strike while they debated. 
line 7079=>Suddenly  without  a  signal  they  sprang  silently  forward  to  attack.  Bows 
line 7080=>twanged and arrows whistled; battle was about to be joined. 
line 7081=>
line 7082=>####-Still  more  suddenly  a  darkness  came  on  with  dreadful  swiftness!  A  black 
line 7083=>cloud  hurried  over  the  sky. Winter  thunder  on  a wild wind  rolled  roaring  up  and 
line 7084=>rumbled  in  the  Mountain,  and  lightning  lit  its  peak.  And  beneath  the  thunder 
line 7085=>another  blackness  could  be  seen  whirling  forward;  but  it  did  not  come  with  the 
line 7086=>wind,  it  came  from  the  North,  like  a  vast  cloud  of  birds,  so  dense  that  no  light 
line 7087=>could be seen between their wings. 
line 7088=>"Halt!"  cried  Gandalf,  who  appeared  suddenly,  and  stood  alone,  with  arms 
line 7089=>uplifted, between  the advancing dwarves and  the  ranks awaiting  them. "Halt!" he 
line 7090=>called  in  a  voice  like  thunder,  and  his  staff  blazed  forth  with  a  flash  like  the 
line 7091=>lightning.  "Dread  has  come  upon  you  all!  Alas!  it  has  come  more  swiftly  than  I 
line 7092=>guessed. The Goblins  are upon you! Bolg*  of the North is coming. O Dain! whose 
line 7093=>father  you  slew  in  Moria.  Behold!  the  bats  are  above  his  army  like  a  sea  of 
line 7094=>locusts. They ride upon wolves and Wargs are in their train!" 
line 7095=>Amazement  and  confusion  fell  upon  them  all.  Even  as  Gandalf  had  been 
line 7096=>speaking  the  darkness  grew.  The  dwarves  halted  and  gazed  at  the  sky.  The  elves 
line 7097=>cried out with many voices. 
line 7098=>"Come!" called Gandalf.  "There  is yet  time  for council. Let Dain  son of Nain 
line 7099=>come swiftly to us!" 
line 7100=> 
line 7101=>So  began  a  battle  that  none  had  expected; and  it was called  the Battle of Five 
line 7102=>Armies,  and  it  was  very  terrible.  Upon  one  side  were  the  Goblins  and  the  wild 
line 7103=>Wolves, and upon  the other were Elves and Men and Dwarves. This  is how  it  fell 
line 7104=>out.  Ever  since  the  fall  of  the Great Goblin  of  the Misty Mountains  the hatred of 
line 7105=>their  race  for  the  dwarves  had  been  rekindled  to  fury. Messengers  had  passed  to 
line 7106=>and fro between all their cities, colonies and strongholds; for they resolved now to 
line 7107=>win  the  dominion  of  the  North.  Tidings  they  had  gathered  in  secret  ways; and  in 
line 7108=>all  the  mountains  there  was  a  forging  and  an  arming.  Then  they  marched  and 
line 7109=>gathered by hill  and valley, going  ever by  tunnel or under dark, until  around  and 
line 7110=>beneath the great mountain Gundabad of the North, where was their capital, a vast 
line 7111=>host  was  assembled  ready  to  sweep  down  in  time  of  storm  unawares  upon  the 
line 7112=>South. Then  they  learned of  the death of Smaug,  and  joy was  in  their hearts:  and 
line 7113=>they hastened night  after night  through  the mountains,  and  came  thus  at  last on  a 
line 7114=>sudden  from  the  North  hard  on  the  heels  of  Dain.  Not  even  the  ravens  knew  of 
line 7115=>their  coming  until  they  came  out  in  the  broken  lands  which  divided  the  Lonely 
line 7116=>Mountain from the hills behind. How much Gandalf knew cannot be said, but it is 
line 7117=>plain that he had not expected this sudden assault. 
line 7118=>
line 7119=>                                                             
line 7120=>*
line 7121=> Son of Azog 
line 7122=>
line 7123=>####-This is the plan that he made in council with the Elvenking and with Bard; and 
line 7124=>with  Dain,  for  the  dwarf-lord  now  joined  them:  the  Goblins  were  the  foes  of  all, 
line 7125=>and at  their coming all other quarrels were  forgotten. Their only hope was  to  lure 
line 7126=>the  goblins  into  the  valley  between  the  arms  of  the Mountain;  and  themselves  to 
line 7127=>man  the  great  spurs  that  struck  south  and  east. Yet  this would  be  perilous,  if  the 
line 7128=>goblins  were  in  sufficient  numbers  to  overrun  the  Mountain  itself,  and  so  attack 
line 7129=>them also  from behind and above; but there was no time for make any other plan, 
line 7130=>or to summon any help. 
line 7131=>Soon  the  thunder  passed,  rolling  away  to  the  South-East;  but  the  bat-cloud 
line 7132=>came,  flying  lower,  over  the  shoulder  of  the  Mountain,  and  whirled  above  them 
line 7133=>shutting out the light and filling them with dread. 
line 7134=>"To  the  Mountain!"  called  Bard.  "To  the  Mountain!  Let  us  take  our  places 
line 7135=>while there is yet time!" 
line 7136=>On  the Southern spur,  in  its  lower slopes and  in  the  rocks at  its  feet,  the Elves 
line 7137=>were  set;  on  the  Eastern  spur  were men  and  dwarves.  But  Bard  and  some  of  the 
line 7138=>nimblest of men and elves climbed  to  the height of  the Eastern  shoulder  to gain a 
line 7139=>view  to  the North. Soon  they could see  the  lands before  the Mountain's  feet black 
line 7140=>with a hurrying multitude. Ere long the vanguard swirled round the spur's end and 
line 7141=>came  rushing  into  Dale.  These  were  the  swiftest  wolf-riders,  and  already  their 
line 7142=>cries  and  howls  rent  the  air  afar.  A  few  brave  men  were  strung  before  them  to 
line 7143=>make  a  feint  of  resistance,  and many  there  fell  before  the  rest  drew  back  and fled 
line 7144=>to  either  side.  As  Gandalf  had  hoped,  the  goblin  army  had  gathered  behind  the 
line 7145=>resisted  vanguard,  and  poured  now  in  rage  into  the  valley,  driving  wildly  up 
line 7146=>between  the  arms  of  the  Mountain,  seeking  for  the  foe.  Their  banners  were 
line 7147=>countless, black and red, and they came on like a tide in fury and disorder.  
line 7148=>It  was  a  terrible  battle.  The  most  dreadful  of  all  Bilbo's  experiences,  and  the 
line 7149=>one which  at  the  time he hated most  â€“ which is to say it was the one he was most 
line 7150=>proud  of,  and  most  fond  of  recalling  long  afterwards,  although  he  was  quite 
line 7151=>unimportant in it. Actually I must say he put on his ring early in the business, and 
line 7152=>vanished  from  sight,  if  not  from  all  danger.  A  magic  ring  of  that  sort  is  not  a 
line 7153=>complete  protection  in  a  goblin  charge,  nor  does  it  stop  flying  arrows  and  wild 
line 7154=>spears;  but  it  does  help  in  getting  out  of  the way,  and  it  prevents  your  head  from 
line 7155=>being specially chosen for a sweeping stroke by a goblin swordsman. 
line 7156=>The  elves  were  the  first  to  charge.  Their  hatred  for  the  goblins  is  cold  and 
line 7157=>bitter. Their spears and swords shone  in  the gloom with a gleam of chill flame, so 
line 7158=>deadly  was  the  wrath  of  the  hands  that  held  them.  As  soon  as  the  host  of  their 
line 7159=>enemies was dense  in  the valley,  they sent against  it a shower of arrows, and each 
line 7160=>
line 7161=>####-flickered  as  it  fled  as  if with  stinging  fire.  Behind  the  arrows  a  thousand  of  their 
line 7162=>spearmen  leapt  down  and  charged.  The  yells  were  deafening.  The  rocks  were 
line 7163=>stained  black  with  goblin  blood.  Just  as  the  goblins  were  recovering  from  the 
line 7164=>onslaught  and  the  elf-charge was halted,  there  rose  from across  the valley a deep-
line 7165=>throated  roar. With  cries  of  "Moria!"  and  "Dain,  Dain!"  the  dwarves  of  the  Iron 
line 7166=>Hills  plunged  in,  wielding  their  mattocks,  upon  the  other  side;  and  beside  them 
line 7167=>came  the  men  of  the  Lake  with  long  swords.  Panic  came  upon  the Goblins;  and 
line 7168=>even as they turned to meet this new attack, the elves charged again with renewed 
line 7169=>numbers. Already many of  the goblins were  flying back down  the  river  to  escape 
line 7170=>from the trap: and many of their own wolves were turning upon them and rending 
line 7171=>the  dead  and  the  wounded.  Victory  seemed  at  hand,  when  a  cry  rang  out  on  the 
line 7172=>heights above. 
line 7173=>Goblins  had  scaled  the Mountain  from  the  other  side  and  already many were 
line 7174=>on the slopes above the Gate, and others were streaming down recklessly, heedless 
line 7175=>of  those  that  fell  screaming  from  cliff  and  precipice,  to  attack  the  spurs  from 
line 7176=>above. Each of these could be reached by paths that ran down from the main mass 
line 7177=>of  the Mountain  in  the  centre;  and  the  defenders  had  too  few  to  bar  the  way  for 
line 7178=>long. Vi ctory now vanished from hope. They had only stemmed the first onslaught 
line 7179=>of the black tide. 
line 7180=>Day drew on. The goblins gathered again  in  the valley. There a host of Wargs 
line 7181=>came  ravening  and  with  them  came  the  bodyguard  of  Bolg,  goblins  of  huge  size 
line 7182=>with scimitars of steel. Soon actual darkness was coming into a stormy sky; while 
line 7183=>still  the great bats  swirled  about  the heads  and  ears of  elves  and men, or  fastened 
line 7184=>vampire-like  on  the  stricken.  Now  Bard  was  fighting  to  defend  the  Eastern  spur, 
line 7185=>and yet giving slowly back; and the elf-lords were at bay about their king upon the 
line 7186=>southern arm, near to the watch-post on Ravenhill. 
line 7187=>Suddenly  there  was  a  great  shout,  and  from  the  Gate  came  a  trumpet  call. 
line 7188=>They had forgotten Thorin! Part of  the wall, moved by  levers, fell outward with a 
line 7189=>crash  into  the  pool. Out  leapt  the King  under  the Mountain,  and  his  companions 
line 7190=>followed  him.  Hood  and  cloak  were  gone;  they  were  in  shining  armour,  and  red 
line 7191=>light  leapt  from  their  eyes.  In  the  gloom  the  great  dwarf  gleamed  like  gold  in  a 
line 7192=>dying fire. 
line 7193=>Rocks were buried down from on high by the goblins above; but they held on. 
line 7194=>leapt  down  to  the  falls'  foot,  and  rushed  forward  to  battle. Wolf  and  rider  fell  or 
line 7195=>fled before them. Thorin wielded his axe with mighty strokes, and nothing seemed 
line 7196=>to harm him. 
line 7197=>
line 7198=>####-"To  me!  To  me!  Elves  and  Men!  To  me!  O  my  kinsfolk!"  he  cried,  and  his 
line 7199=>voice shook like a horn in the valley.  
line 7200=>Down, heedless of order, rushed all the dwarves of Dain to his help. Down too 
line 7201=>came  many  of  the  Lake-men,  for Bard  could  not  restrain  them;  and out upon  the 
line 7202=>other  side  came many  of  the  spearmen  of  the  elves. Once  again  the  goblins were 
line 7203=>stricken in the valley; and they were piled in heaps till Dale was dark and hideous 
line 7204=>with  their  corpses.  The  Wargs  were  scattered  and  Thorin  drove  right  against  the 
line 7205=>bodyguards  of  Bolg.  But  he  could  not  pierce  their  ranks.  Already  behind  him 
line 7206=>among the goblin dead lay many men and many dwarves, and many a fair elf that 
line 7207=>should  have  lived  yet  long  ages  merrily  in  the  wood.  And  as  the  valley  widened 
line 7208=>his onset grew ever slower. His numbers were too few. His flanks were unguarded. 
line 7209=>Soon  the  attackers  were  attacked,  and  they  were  forced  into  a  great  ring,  facing 
line 7210=>every  way,  hemmed  all  about  with  goblins  and  wolves  returning  to  the  assault. 
line 7211=>The bodyguard of Bolg came howling against them, and drove in upon their ranks 
line 7212=>like waves  upon  cliffs  of  sand.  Their  friends  could  not  help  them,  for  the  assault 
line 7213=>from  the Mountain was  renewed with  redoubled  force,  and  upon  either  side men 
line 7214=>and elves were being slowly beaten down. 
line 7215=>On  all  this  Bilbo  looked  with  misery.  He  had  taken  his  stand  on  Ravenhill 
line 7216=>among  the Elves-partly because  there was more chance of escape from  that point, 
line 7217=>and partly (with the more Tookish part of his mind) because if he was going to be 
line 7218=>in  a  last  desperate  stand,  he  preferred  on  the  whole  to  defend  the  Elvenking. 
line 7219=>Gandalf,  too,  I  may  say,  was  there,  sitting  on  the  ground  as  if  in  deep  thought, 
line 7220=>preparing,  I  suppose,  some  last  blast  of magic  before  the  end.  That  did  not  seem 
line 7221=>far off. "It will not be  long now,"  thought Bilbo, "before the goblins win the Gate, 
line 7222=>and  we  are  all  slaughtered  or  driven  down  and  captured.  Really  it  is  enough  to 
line 7223=>make  one  weep,  after  all  one  has  gone  through.  I  would  rather  old  Smaug  had 
line 7224=>been left with all the wretched treasure, than that these vile creatures should get it, 
line 7225=>and  poor  old Bombur,  and Balin  and  Fili  and Kili  and  all  the  rest  come  to  a  bad 
line 7226=>end;  and  Bard  too,  and  the  Lake-men  and  the  merry  elves.  Misery  me!  I  have 
line 7227=>heard  songs  of  many  battles,  and  I  have  always  understood  that  defeat  may  be 
line 7228=>glorious. It seems very uncomfortable, not to say distressing. I wish I was well out 
line 7229=>of it." 
line 7230=>The  clouds  were  torn  by  the  wind,  and  a  red  sunset  slashed  the West.  Seeing 
line 7231=>the  sudden  gleam  in  the  gloom  Bilbo  looked  round. He  gave  a  great  cry:  he  had 
line 7232=>seen  a  sight  that  made  his  heart  leap,  dark  shapes  small  yet  majestic  against  the 
line 7233=>distant glow.  
line 7234=>"The Eagles! The Eagles!" he shouted. "The Eagles are coming!" 
line 7235=>
line 7236=>####-Bilbo's eyes were seldom wrong. The eagles were coming down the wind, line 
line 7237=>after line, in such a host as must have gathered from all the eyries of the North. 
line 7238=>"The  Eagles!  the  Eagles!"  Bilbo  cried,  dancing  and  waving  his  arms.  If  the 
line 7239=>elves could not see him they could hear him. Soon they too took up the cry, and it 
line 7240=>echoed  across  the  valley. Many wondering  eyes  looked up,  though as yet nothing 
line 7241=>could be seen except from the southern shoulders of the Mountain. 
line 7242=>"The Eagles!" cried Bilbo once more, but at that moment a stone hurtling from 
line 7243=>above smote heavily on his helm, and he fell with a crash and knew no more. 
line 7244=>
line 7245=>####-<h4>Chapter 18</h4> <br> 
line 7246=>
line 7247=>The Return Journey 
line 7248=>
line 7249=> 
line 7250=>When Bilbo came  to himself, he was  literally by himself. He was  lying on  the 
line 7251=>flat stones of Ravenhill, and no one was near. A cloudless day, but cold, was broad 
line 7252=>above him. He was shaking, and as chilled as stone, but his head burned with fire. 
line 7253=>"Now I wonder what has happened?" he said to himself. "At any rate I am not 
line 7254=>yet one of the fallen heroes; but I suppose there is still time enough for that!" 
line 7255=>He  sat  up  painfully.  Looking  into  the  valley  he  could  see  no  living  goblins. 
line 7256=>After  a while as his head cleared a  little, he  thought he could see elves moving  in 
line 7257=>the  rocks  below.  He  rubbed  his  eyes.  Surely  there  was  a  camp  still  in  the  plain 
line 7258=>some  distance  off;  and  there  was  a  coming  and  going  about  the  Gate?  Dwarves 
line 7259=>seemed  to  be  busy  removing  the wall. But  all was deadly  still. There was no  call 
line 7260=>and  no  echo  of  a  song.  Sorrow  seemed  to  be  in  the  air.  "Victory  after  all,  I 
line 7261=>suppose!"  he  said,  feeling  his  aching  head.  "Well,  it  seems  a  very  gloomy 
line 7262=>business." 
line 7263=>Suddenly he was aware of a man climbing up and coming towards him. 
line 7264=>"Hullo there!" he called with a shaky voice. "Hullo there! What news?" 
line 7265=>"What  voice  is  it  that  speaks  among  the  stones?"  said  the  man  halting  and 
line 7266=>peering about him not far from where Bilbo sat. 
line 7267=>Then Bilbo remembered his ring! "Well I'm blessed!" said he. "This invisibility 
line 7268=>has  its  drawbacks  after  all.  Otherwise  I  suppose  I  might  have  spent  a  warm  and 
line 7269=>comfortable night in bed!" 
line 7270=>"It's me, Bilbo Baggins,  companion  of Thorin!"  he  cried,  hurriedly  taking  off 
line 7271=>the ring. 
line 7272=>"It  is  well  that  I  have  found  you!"  said  the  man  striding  forward.  "You  are 
line 7273=>needed and we have looked for you long. You would have been numbered among 
line 7274=>the  dead,  who  are many,  if  Gandalf  the  wizard  had  not  said  that  your  voice  was 
line 7275=>last  heard  in  this  place.  I  have  been  sent  to  look  here  for  the  last  time.  Are  you 
line 7276=>much hurt?" 
line 7277=>"A  nasty  knock  on  the  head,  I  think,"  said  Bilbo.  "But  I  have  a  helm  and  a 
line 7278=>hard skull. All the same I feel sick and my legs are like straws." 
line 7279=>"I  will  carry  you  down  to  the  camp  in  the  valley,"  said  the man,  and  picked 
line 7280=>him lightly up. 
line 7281=>The man was swift and sure-footed. It was not long before Bilbo was set down 
line 7282=>before  a  tent  in Dale;  and  there  stood Gandalf, with  his  arm  in  a  sling.  Even  the 
line 7283=>
line 7284=>####-wizard had not escaped without a wound; and  there were  few unharmed in all the 
line 7285=>host. 
line 7286=>When Gandalf saw Bilbo, he was delighted. "Baggins!" he exclaimed. "Well I 
line 7287=>never! Alive after all â€“ 1 am glad! I began to wonder if even your luck would see 
line 7288=>you through! A terrible business, and it nearly was disastrous. But other news can 
line 7289=>wait. Come!" he said more gravely. "You are called for;" and leading the hobbit he 
line 7290=>took him within the tent. 
line 7291=>"Hail! Thorin," he said as he entered. "I have brought him." 
line 7292=>There  indeed  lay  Thorin  Oakenshield,  wounded  with  many  wounds,  and  his 
line 7293=>rent  armour  and  notched  axe  were  cast  upon  the  floor.  He  looked  up  as  Bilbo 
line 7294=>came beside him. 
line 7295=>"Farewell,  good  thief,"  he  said.  "I  go  now  to  the  halls  of waiting  to  sit  beside 
line 7296=>my  fathers,  until  the world  is  renewed. Since  I  leave  now  all  gold  and  silver,  and 
line 7297=>go  where  it  is  of  little  worth,  I  wish  to  part  in  friendship  from  you,  and  I  would 
line 7298=>take back my words and deeds at the Gate." 
line 7299=>Bilbo  knelt  on  one  knee  filled  with  sorrow.  "Farewell,  King  under  the 
line 7300=>Mountain!"  he  said.  "This  is  a  bitter  adventure,  if  it  must  end  so;  and  not  a 
line 7301=>mountain  of  gold  can  amend  it. Yet  I  am  glad  that  I  have  shared  in  your  perils  â€“ 
line 7302=>that has been more than any Baggins deserves." 
line 7303=>"No!" said Thorin. "There  is more  in you of good  than you know, child of  the 
line 7304=>kindly West. Some  courage  and  some wisdom, blended  in measure.  If more of us 
line 7305=>valued food and cheer and song above hoarded gold, it would be a merrier world. 
line 7306=>But sad or merry, I must leave it now. Farewell!" 
line 7307=>Then Bilbo  turned  away,  and  he went  by  himself,  and  sat  alone wrapped  in  a 
line 7308=>blanket, and, whether you believe it or not, he wept until his eyes were red and his 
line 7309=>voice was hoarse. He was a kindly little soul. Indeed it was long before he had the 
line 7310=>heart to make a joke again. "A mercy it is," he said at last to himself, "that I woke 
line 7311=>up when I did. I wish Thorin were living, but I am glad that we parted in kindness. 
line 7312=>You  are  a  fool,  Bilbo  Baggins,  and  you made  a  great mess  of  that  business with 
line 7313=>the stone; and there was a battle, in spite of all your efforts to buy peace and quiet, 
line 7314=>but I suppose you can hardly be blamed for that." 
line 7315=>All  that  had  happened  after  he  was  stunned,  Bilbo  learned  later;  but  it  gave 
line 7316=>him more sorrow than joy, and he was now weary of his adventure. He was aching 
line 7317=>in  his  bones  for  the  homeward  journey. That,  however, was  a  little  delayed, so  in 
line 7318=>the meantime I will tell something of events. The Eagles had long had suspicion of 
line 7319=>the  goblins'  mustering;  from  their  watchfulness  the  movements  in  the  mountains 
line 7320=>could not be altogether hid. So  they  too had gathered  in great numbers, under  the 
line 7321=>
line 7322=>####-great  Eagle  of  the Misty Mountains;  and  at  length  smelling  battle  from  afar  they 
line 7323=>had come  speeding down  the gale  in  the nick of  time. They  it was who dislodged 
line 7324=>the  goblins  from  the  mountain-slopes,  casting  them  over  precipices,  or  driving 
line 7325=>them down shrieking and bewildered among their foes. It was not long before they 
line 7326=>had  freed  the  Lonely  Mountain,  and  elves  and  men  on  either  side  of  the  valley 
line 7327=>could come at last to the help of the battle below.  
line 7328=>But even with the Eagles they were still outnumbered. 
line 7329=>In  that  last  hour  Beorn  himself  had  appeared  â€“  no  one  knew  how  or  from 
line 7330=>where. He  came  alone,  and  in  bear's  shape;  and  he  seemed  to  have  grown  almost 
line 7331=>to  giant-size  in  his wrath. The  roar  of  his  voice was  like  drums  and  guns;  and  he 
line 7332=>tossed  wolves  and  goblins  from  his  path  like  straws  and  feathers.  He  fell  upon 
line 7333=>their  rear,  and  broke  like  a  clap  of  thunder  through  the  ring.  The  dwarves  were 
line 7334=>making  a  stand  still  about  their  lords  upon  a  low  rounded  hill.  Then  Beorn 
line 7335=>stooped and lifted Thorin, who had fallen pierced with spears, and bore him out of 
line 7336=>the  fray.  Swiftly  he  returned  and  his  wrath  was  redoubled,  so  that  nothing  could 
line 7337=>withstand  him,  and  no  weapon  seemed  to  bite  upon  him.  He  scattered  the 
line 7338=>bodyguard,  and  pulled  down Bolg  himself  and  crushed  him. Then  dismay  fell  on 
line 7339=>the  Goblins  and  they  fled  in  all  directions.  But  weariness  left  their  enemies  with 
line 7340=>the  coming  of  new  hope,  and  they  pursued  them  closely,  and  prevented  most  of 
line 7341=>them from escaping where they could. They drove many of them into the Running 
line 7342=>River, and such as fled south or west they hunted into the marshes about the Forest 
line 7343=>River;  and  there  the  greater  part  of  the  last  fugitives  perished,  while  those  that 
line 7344=>came  hardly  to  the Wood-elves'  realm  were  there  slain,  or  drawn  in  to  die  in  the 
line 7345=>trackless  dark  of  Mirkwood.  Songs  have  said  that  three  parts  of  the  goblin 
line 7346=>warriors of the North perished on that day, and the mountains had peace for many 
line 7347=>a year.  
line 7348=>Victory  had  been  assured  before  the  fall  of  night,  but  the  pursuit  was  still  on 
line 7349=>foot, when  Bilbo  returned  to  the  camp;  and not many were  in  the valley  save  the 
line 7350=>more grievously wounded. 
line 7351=>"Where are  the Eagles?" he asked Gandalf  that evening, as he  lay wrapped  in 
line 7352=>many warm blankets. 
line 7353=>"Some  are  in  the  hunt,"  said  the  wizard,  "but  most  have  gone  back  to  their 
line 7354=>eyries.  They  would  not  stay  here,  and  departed  with  the  first  light  of  morning. 
line 7355=>Dain has crowned their chief with gold, and sworn friendship with them for ever." 
line 7356=>"I  am  sorry.  I  mean,  I  should  have  liked  to  see  them  again,"  said  Bilbo 
line 7357=>sleepily;  "perhaps  I  shall  see  them  on  the  way  home.  I  suppose  I  shall  be  going 
line 7358=>home soon?" 
line 7359=>
line 7360=>####-"As soon as you like," said the wizard. 
line 7361=>Actually it was some days before Bilbo really set out. 
line 7362=>They buried Thorin deep beneath the Mountain, and Bard laid the Arkenstone 
line 7363=>upon his breast. 
line 7364=>"There let it lie till the Mountain falls!" he said. "May it bring good fortune to 
line 7365=>all his  folk  that dwell here after!" Upon his  tomb  the Elvenking  then  laid Orcrist, 
line 7366=>the  elvish  sword  that  had  been  taken  from  Thorin  in  captivity.  It  is  said  in  songs 
line 7367=>that it gleamed ever in the dark if foes approached, and the fortress of the dwarves 
line 7368=>could  not  be  taken  by  surprise.  There  now  Dain  son  of  Nain  took  up  his  abode, 
line 7369=>and  he  became  King  under  the  Mountain,  and  in  time  many  other  dwarves 
line 7370=>gathered  to  his  throne  in  the  ancient  halls.  Of  the  twelve  companions  of  Thorin, 
line 7371=>ten  remained. Fili  and Kili  had  fallen  defending  him with  shield  and  body,  for  he 
line 7372=>was their mother's elder brother. The others remained with Dain; for Dain dealt his 
line 7373=>treasure well. There was,  of  course,  no  longer  any  question of dividing  the hoard 
line 7374=>in  such  shares  as had been planned,  to Balin  and Dwalin,  and Dori  and Nori  and 
line 7375=>Ori,  and  Oin  and  Gloin,  and  Bifur  and  Bofur  and  Bombur-or  to  Bilbo.  Yet  a 
line 7376=>fourteenth  share of  all  the  silver  and gold, wrought  and unwrought, was given up 
line 7377=>to  Bard;  for  Dain  said:  "We  will  honour  the  agreement  of  the  dead,  and  he  has 
line 7378=>now the Arkenstone in his keeping." 
line 7379=>Even  a  fourteenth  share  was  wealth  exceedingly  great,  greater  than  that  of 
line 7380=>many  mortal  kings.  From  that  treasure  Bard  sent  much  gold  to  the  Master  of 
line 7381=>Lake-town; and he rewarded his followers and friends freely. To the Elvenking he 
line 7382=>gave  the  emeralds  of  Girion,  such  jewels  as  he  most  loved,  which  Dain  had 
line 7383=>restored  to  him.  To  Bilbo  he  said:  "This  treasure  is  as  much  yours  as  it  is  mine; 
line 7384=>though  old  agreements  cannot  stand,  since  so  many  have  a  claim  in  its  winning 
line 7385=>and  defence.  Yet  even  though  you  were  willing  to  lay  aside  all  your  claim,  I 
line 7386=>should wish that the words of Thorin, of which he repented, should not prove true: 
line 7387=>that we should give you little. I would reward you most richly of all." 
line 7388=>"Very  kind  of  you,"  said  Bilbo.  "But  really  it  is  a  relief  to me. How  on  earth 
line 7389=>should  I  have  got  all  that  treasure  home  without  war  and  murder  all  along  the 
line 7390=>way,  I  don't  know. And  I  don't  know what  I  should  have done with  it when  I got 
line 7391=>home. I am sure it is better in your hands." 
line 7392=>In  the end he would only  take  two  small chests, one  filled with  silver, and  the 
line 7393=>other with gold, such as one strong pony could carry. "That will be quite as much 
line 7394=>as I can manage," said he. 
line 7395=>At last the time came for him to say good-bye to his friends. "Farewell, Balin!" 
line 7396=>he  said;  "and  farewell,  Dwalin;  and  farewell  Dori,  Nori,  Ori,  Oin,  Gloin,  Bifur, 
line 7397=>
line 7398=>####-Bofur, and Bombur! May your beards never grow  thin!" And  turning  towards  the 
line 7399=>Mountain  he added: "Farewell Thorin Oakenshield! And Fili and Kili! May your 
line 7400=>memory never fade!" 
line 7401=>Then  the  dwarves  bowed  low  before  their  Gate,  but  words  stuck  in  their 
line 7402=>throats.  "Good-bye and good luck, wherever you fare!" said Balin at last. "If ever 
line 7403=>you  visit  us  again,  when  our  halls  are  made  fair  once  more,  then  the  feast  shall 
line 7404=>indeed be splendid!" 
line 7405=>"If  ever  you  are  passing my way,"  said Bilbo,  "don't wait  to  knock!  Tea  is  at 
line 7406=>four; but any of you are welcome at any time!" 
line 7407=>Then he turned away.  
line 7408=>The  elf-host  was  on  the  march;.  and  if  it  was  sadly  lessened,  yet  many  were 
line 7409=>glad,  for  now  the  northern  world  would  be  merrier  for  many  a  long  day.  The 
line 7410=>dragon  was  dead,  and  the  goblins  overthrown,  and  their  hearts  looked  forward 
line 7411=>after winter  to  a  spring  of  joy. Gandalf  and Bilbo  rode behind the Elvenking, and 
line 7412=>beside  them strode Beorn, once again  in man's shape, and he  laughed and sang  in 
line 7413=>a loud voice upon the road. So they went on until they drew near to the borders of 
line 7414=>Mirkwood, to the north of the place where the Forest River ran out. 
line 7415=>Then  they  halted,  for  the  wizard  and  Bilbo  would  not  enter  the  wood,  even 
line 7416=>though the king bade them stay a while in his halls. They intended to go along the 
line 7417=>edge of  the  forest, and  round  its northern end  in  the waste  that  lay between  it and 
line 7418=>the  beginning  of  the  Grey Mountains.  It  was  a  long  and  cheerless  road,  but  now 
line 7419=>that  the goblins were crushed,  it seemed safer  to  them  than  the dreadful pathways 
line 7420=>under the trees. Moreover Beorn was going that way too. 
line 7421=>"Farewell!  O  Elvenking!"  said  Gandalf.  "Merry  be  the  greenwood, while  the 
line 7422=>world is yet young! And merry be all your folk!" 
line 7423=>"Farewell!  O  Gandalf!"  said  the  king.  "May  you  ever  appear  where  you  are 
line 7424=>most  needed  and  least  expected!  The  oftener  you  appear  in  my  halls  the  better 
line 7425=>shall I be pleased!" 
line 7426=>"I beg of  you," said Bilbo stammering and standing on one foot, "to accept this 
line 7427=>gift!" and he brought out a necklace of  silver and pearls  that Dain had given him 
line 7428=>at their parting. 
line 7429=>"In what way have I earned such a gift, O hobbit?" said the king. 
line 7430=>"Well,  er,  I  thought,  don't  you  know,"  said  Bilbo  rather  confused,  "that,  er, 
line 7431=>some  little  return  should  be made  for  your,  er,  hospitality.  I mean  even  a  burglar 
line 7432=>has his feelings. I have drunk much of your wine and eaten much of your bread." 
line 7433=>
line 7434=>####-"I will  take your gift, O Bilbo  the Magnificent!" said the king gravely. "And I 
line 7435=>name  you  elf-friend  and  blessed. May  your  shadow  never  grow  less  (or  stealing 
line 7436=>would be too easy)! Farewell!" 
line 7437=>Then  the  elves  turned  towards  the  Forest,  and  Bilbo  started  on  his  long  road 
line 7438=>home. 
line 7439=>He had many hardships and adventures before he got back. The Wild was still 
line 7440=>the Wild, and there were many other things in it in those days besides goblins; but 
line 7441=>he  was  well  guided  and  well  guarded-the  wizard  was  with  him,  and  Beorn  for 
line 7442=>much  of  the way-and  he was  never  in  great danger again. Anyway by mid-winter 
line 7443=>Gandalf  and Bilbo had  come  all  the way back,  along both  edges of  the Forest,  to 
line 7444=>the  doors  of Beorn's  house;  and  there  for  a while  they  both  stayed. Yule-tide was 
line 7445=>warm  and  merry  there;  and  men  came  from  far  and  wide  to  feast  at  Beorn's 
line 7446=>bidding.  The  goblins  of  the  Misty  Mountains  were  now  few  and  terrified,  and 
line 7447=>hidden  in  the deepest holes  they could  find; and  the Wargs had vanished  from  the 
line 7448=>woods,  so  that men went  abroad without  fear. Beorn  indeed became  a great  chief 
line 7449=>afterwards  in  those  regions  and  ruled  a wide  land between  the mountains  and  the 
line 7450=>wood; and it is said that for many generations the men of his line had the power of 
line 7451=>taking bear's shape, and some were grim men and bad, but most were in heart like 
line 7452=>Beorn,  if  less  in  size  and  strength.  In  their  day  the  last  goblins were  hunted  from 
line 7453=>the  Misty  Mountains  and  a  new  peace  came  over  the  edge  of  the  Wild.  It  was 
line 7454=>spring,  and  a  fair  one  with  mild  weathers  and  a  bright  sun,  before  Bilbo  and 
line 7455=>Gandalf  took  their  leave  at  last  of Beorn,  and  though  he  longed  for  home. Bilbo 
line 7456=>left with regret, for the flowers of the gardens of Beorn were m springtime no less 
line 7457=>marvellous  than  in high summer. At  last  they came up  the  long road, and reached 
line 7458=>the  very  pass  where  the  goblins  had  captured  them before. But  they came  to  that 
line 7459=>high  point  at morning,  and  looking  backward  they  saw  a  white  sun  shining  over 
line 7460=>the  out-stretched  lands.  There  behind  lay  Mirkwood,  blue  in  the  distance,  and 
line 7461=>darkly green at the nearer edge even in the spring. There far away was the Lonely 
line 7462=>Mountain  on  the  edge  of  eyesight.  On  its  highest  peak  snow  yet  unmelted  was 
line 7463=>gleaming pale. 
line 7464=>"So  comes  snow  after  fire,  and  even  dragons  have  their  ending!"  said  Bilbo, 
line 7465=>and he  turned his back on his adventure. The Tookish part was getting very tired, 
line 7466=>and  the  Baggins  was  daily  getting  stronger.  "I  wish  now  only  to  be  in  my  own 
line 7467=>arm-chair!" he said. 
line 7468=>
line 7469=>####-<h4>Chapter 19</h4> <br> 
line 7470=>
line 7471=>The Last Stage 
line 7472=>
line 7473=> 
line 7474=>It was on May the First that the two came back at last to the brink of the valley 
line 7475=>of  Rivendell,  where  stood  the  Last  (or  the  First)  Homely  House.  Again  it  was 
line 7476=>evening,  their  ponies were  tired,  especially  the  one  that  carried  the  baggage;  and 
line 7477=>they all felt in need of rest. As they rode down the steep path, Bilbo heard the elves 
line 7478=>still  singing  in  the  trees,  as  if  they  had  not  stopped  since  he  left;  and  as  soon  as 
line 7479=>their riders came down into the lower glades of the wood they burst into a song of 
line 7480=>much the same kind as before. This is something like it: 
line 7481=> 
line 7482=>
line 7483=>The dragon is withered, 
line 7484=>His bones are now crumbled; 
line 7485=>His armour is shivered, 
line 7486=>His splendour is humbled! 
line 7487=>Though sword shall be rusted, 
line 7488=>And throne and crown perish  
line 7489=>With strength that men trusted 
line 7490=>And wealth that they cherish, 
line 7491=>Here grass is still growing, 
line 7492=>And leaves are yet swinging, 
line 7493=>The white water flowing, 
line 7494=>And elves are yet singing 
line 7495=>Come! Tra-la-la-lally! 
line 7496=>Come back to the valley! 
line 7497=> 
line 7498=>The stars are far brighter 
line 7499=>Than gems without measure, 
line 7500=>The moon is far whiter 
line 7501=>Than silver in treasure: 
line 7502=>The fire is more shining 
line 7503=>On hearth in the gloaming 
line 7504=>Than gold won by mining, 
line 7505=>So why go a -roaming? 
line 7506=>O! Tra-la-la-lally 
line 7507=>Come back to the Valley.  
line 7508=> 
line 7509=>O! Where are you going, 
line 7510=>
line 7511=>####-So late in returning? 
line 7512=>The river is flowing, 
line 7513=>The stars are all burning! 
line 7514=>O! Whither so laden, 
line 7515=>So sad and so dreary? 
line 7516=>Here elf and elf-maiden 
line 7517=>Now welcome the weary 
line 7518=>With Tra-la-la-lally 
line 7519=>Come back to the Va lley,  
line 7520=>Tra-la-la-lally 
line 7521=>Fa-la-la-lally 
line 7522=>Fa-la! 
line 7523=>
line 7524=> 
line 7525=>Then  the  elves  of  the  valley  came  out  and  greeted  them  and  led  them  across 
line 7526=>the  water  to  the  house  of  Elrond.  There  a  warm  welcome  was  made  them,  and 
line 7527=>there  were  many  eager  ears  that  evening  to  hear  the  tale  of  their  adventures. 
line 7528=>Gandalf it was who spoke, for Bilbo was fallen quiet and drowsy. Most of the tale 
line 7529=>he  knew,  for  he  had  been  in  it,  and  had  himself  told much  of  it  to  the  wizard  on 
line 7530=>their homeward way or  in  the house of Beorn; but every now and again he would 
line 7531=>open one eye, and listen, when a part of the story which he did not yet know came 
line 7532=>in. It was in this way that he learned where Gandalf had been to; for he overheard 
line 7533=>the  words  of  the  wizard  to  Elrond.  It  appeared  that  Gandalf  had  been  to  a  great 
line 7534=>council of the white wizards, masters of lore and good magic; and that they had at 
line 7535=>last driven the Necromancer from his dark hold in the south of Mirkwood. 
line 7536=>"Ere  long  now,"  Gandalf  was  saying,  "The  Forest  will  grow  somewhat  more 
line 7537=>wholesome. The North will be freed from that horror for many long years, I hope. 
line 7538=>Yet I wish he were banished from the world!" 
line 7539=>"It would be well  indeed," said Elrond; "but I fear  that will not come about  in 
line 7540=>this age of the world, or for many after." 
line 7541=>When  the  tale  of  their  joumeyings  was  told,  there  were  other  tales,  and  yet 
line 7542=>more  tales,  tales of  long ago, and  tales  . of new  things, and  tales of no  time at all, 
line 7543=>till Bilbo's head fell forward on his chest, and he snored comfortably in a corner.  
line 7544=>He woke to find himself in a white bed, and the moon shining through an open 
line 7545=>window.  Below  it  many  elves  were  singing  loud  and  clear  on  the  banks  of  the 
line 7546=>stream. 
line 7547=> 
line 7548=>
line 7549=>Sing all ye joyful, now sing all together?  
line 7550=>The wind's in the free-top, the wind's in the heather;  
line 7551=>The stars are in blossom, the moon is in flower,  
line 7552=>
line 7553=>####-And bright are the windows of Night in her tower.  
line 7554=> 
line 7555=>Dance all ye joyful, now dance all together! 
line 7556=>Soft is the grass, and let foot be like feather! 
line 7557=>The river is silver, the shadows are fleeting; 
line 7558=>Merry is May-time, and merry our meeting. 
line 7559=> 
line 7560=>Sing we now softly, and dreams let us weave him! 
line 7561=>Wind him in slumber and there let us leave him! 
line 7562=>The wanderer sleepeth. Now soft be his pillow! 
line 7563=>Lullaby! Lullaby! Alder and Willow! 
line 7564=> 
line 7565=>Sigh no more Pine, till the wind of the morn! 
line 7566=>Fall Moon! Dark be the land! 
line 7567=>Hush! Hush! Oak, Ash, and Thorn! 
line 7568=>Hushed be all water, till dawn is at hand! 
line 7569=>
line 7570=> 
line 7571=>"Well, Merry People!" said Bilbo looking out. "What time by the moon is this? 
line 7572=>Your lullaby would waken a drunken goblin! Yet I thank you." 
line 7573=>"And  your  snores  would  waken  a  stone  dragon  â€“  yet  we  thank  you,"  they 
line 7574=>answered  with  laughter.  "It  is  drawing    towards  dawn,  and  you  have  slept  now 
line 7575=>since the night's beginning. Tomorrow, perhaps, you will be cured of weariness." 
line 7576=>"A  little  sleep  does  a  great  cure  in  the  house  of  Elrond,"  said  he;  "but  I  will 
line 7577=>take  all  the  cure  I  can  get.  A  second  good  night,  fair  friends!"  And  with  that  he 
line 7578=>went back to bed and slept till late morning. 
line 7579=>Weariness fell from him soon in that house, and he had many a merry jest and 
line 7580=>dance,  early  and  late,  with  the  elves  of  the  valley.  Yet  even  that  place  could  not 
line 7581=>long  delay  him  now,  and  he  thought  always  of  his  own  home.  After  a  week, 
line 7582=>therefore, he said farewell  to Elrond, and giving him such small gifts as he would 
line 7583=>accept, he  rode  away with Gandalf. Even  as  they  left  the valley  the  sky darkened 
line 7584=>in the West before them, and wind and rain came up to meet them. 
line 7585=>"Merry  is May-time!" said Bilbo, as  the  rain beat  into his  face. "But our back 
line 7586=>is to legends and we are coming home. I suppose this is a first taste of it." 
line 7587=>"There is a long road yet," said Gandalf. 
line 7588=>"But  it  is  the  last  road,"  said  Bilbo.  They  came  to  the  river  that  marked  the 
line 7589=>very  edge  of  the  borderland  of  the Wild,  and  to  the  ford  beneath  the  steep  bank, 
line 7590=>which  you  may  remember.  The  water  was  swollen  both  with  the  melting  of  the 
line 7591=>snows  at  the  approach  of  summer,  and  with  the  daylong  rain;  but  they  crossed 
line 7592=>with some difficulty, and pressed forward, as evening fell, on the last stage of their 
line 7593=>
line 7594=>####-journey.  This  was  much  as  it  had  been  before,  except  that  the  company  was 
line 7595=>smaller,  and  more  silent;  also  this  time  there were  no  trolls. At  each  point  on  the 
line 7596=>road Bilbo  recalled  the  happenings  and  the words  of  a  year  ago-it seemed  to him 
line 7597=>more  like  ten-so  that,  of  course,  he  quickly  noted  the  place  where  the  pony  had 
line 7598=>fallen  in  the  river,  and  they  had  turned  aside  for  their  nasty  adventure with  Tom 
line 7599=>and  Bert  and  Bill. Not  far  from  the  road  they  found  the  gold  of  the  trolls, which 
line 7600=>they had buried,  still hidden  and untouched.  "I have  enough  to  last me my  time," 
line 7601=>said Bilbo, when they had dug it up. "You had better take this, Gandalf. I daresay 
line 7602=>you can find a use for it." 
line 7603=>"Indeed I can!" said the wizard. "But share and share alike! You may find you 
line 7604=>have more needs than you expect." 
line 7605=>So they put the gold in bags and slung them on the ponies, who were not at all 
line 7606=>pleased  about  it.  After  that  their  going  was  slower,  for  most  of  the  time  they 
line 7607=>walked.  But  the  land  was  green  and  there  was  much  grass  through  which  the 
line 7608=>hobbit  strolled  along  contentedly.  He  mopped  his  face  with  a  red  silk 
line 7609=>handkerchief-no!  not  a  single  one  of  his own had  survived, he had borrowed  this 
line 7610=>one from Elrond  â€“for now June had brought summer, and  the weather was bright 
line 7611=>and hot again. 
line 7612=>As  all  things  come  to  an  end,  even  this  story,  a  day  came  at  last  when  they 
line 7613=>were in sight of the country where Bilbo had been born and bred, where the shapes 
line 7614=>of  the  land  and  of  the  trees  were  as  well  known  to  him  as  his  hands  and  toes. 
line 7615=>Coming  to  a  rise  he  could  see  his  own  Hill  in  the  distance,  and  he  stopped 
line 7616=>suddenly and said: 
line 7617=> 
line 7618=>
line 7619=>Roads go ever ever on, 
line 7620=>Over rock and under tree, 
line 7621=>By caves where never sun has shone, 
line 7622=>By streams that never find the sea; 
line 7623=> 
line 7624=>Over snow by winter sown, 
line 7625=>And through the merry flowers of June, 
line 7626=>Over grass and over stone, 
line 7627=>And under mountains in the moon. 
line 7628=> 
line 7629=>Roads go ever ever on 
line 7630=>Under cloud and under star,  
line 7631=>Yet feet that wandering have gone 
line 7632=>Turn at last to home afar.  
line 7633=> 
line 7634=>
line 7635=>####-Eyes that fire and sword have seen 
line 7636=>And horror in the halls of stone 
line 7637=>Look at last on meadows green 
line 7638=>And trees and hills they long have known. 
line 7639=>
line 7640=> 
line 7641=>Gandalf  looked  at  him.  "My  dear  Bilbo!"  he  said.  "Something  is  the  matter 
line 7642=>with you! You are not the hobbit that you were." 
line 7643=>And so they crossed the bridge and passed the mill by the river and came right 
line 7644=>back  to  Bilbo's  own  door.  "Bless  me!  What's  going  on?"  he  cried.  There  was  a 
line 7645=>great  commotion,  and  people  of  all  sorts,  respectable  and  unrespectable,  were 
line 7646=>thick  round  the  door,  and many were  going  in  and  out-not even wiping  their  feet 
line 7647=>on the mat, as Bilbo noticed with annoyance. 
line 7648=>If he was surprised,  they were more surprised still. He had arrived back  in  the 
line 7649=>middle  of an auction! There was a large notice in black and red hung on the gate, 
line 7650=>stating  that  on  June  the  Twenty-second  Messrs.  Grubb,  Grubb,  and  Bun-owes 
line 7651=>would  sell  by  auction  the  effects  of  the  late  Bilbo  Baggins  Esquire,  of  Bag-End, 
line 7652=>Underhill,  Hobbiton.  Sale  to  commence  at  ten  o'clock  sharp.  It  was  now  nearly 
line 7653=>lunch-time,  and most  of  the  things  had  already  been  sold,  for  various  prices  from 
line 7654=>next  to  nothing  to  old  songs  (as  is  not  unusual  at  auctions).  Bilbo's  cousins  the 
line 7655=>Sackville-Bagginses  were,  in  fact,  busy  measuring  his  rooms  to  see  if  their  own 
line 7656=>furniture would  fit.  In  short Bilbo was  "Presumed Dead,"  and not  everybody  that 
line 7657=>said so was sorry to find the presumption wrong. 
line 7658=>The  return  of  Mr.  Bilbo  Baggins  created  quite  a  disturbance,  both  under  the 
line 7659=>Hill  and  over  the Hill, and across  the Water;  it was a great deal more  than a nine 
line 7660=>days' wonder.  The  legal  bother,  indeed,  lasted  for  years.  It was  quite  a  long  time 
line 7661=>before Mr. Baggins was in fact admitted to be alive again. The people who had got 
line 7662=>specially  good  bargains  at  the  Sale  took  a  deal  of  convincing;  and  in  the  end  to 
line 7663=>sav6  time  Bilbo  had  to  buy  back  quite  a  lot  of  his  own  furniture.  Many  of  his 
line 7664=>silver  spoons mysteriously  disappeared  and were  never  accounted  for.  Personally 
line 7665=>he  suspected  the  Sackville-Bagginses.  On  their  side  they  never  admitted  that  the 
line 7666=>returned  Baggins  was  genuine,  and  they  were  not  on  friendly  terms  with  Bilbo 
line 7667=>ever after. They really had wanted to live in his nice hobbit-hole so very much. 
line 7668=>Indeed Bilbo  found he had  lost more  than  spoons  â€“ he had lost his reputation. 
line 7669=>It  is  true  that  for  ever  after  he  remained  an  elf-friend,  and  had  the  honour  of 
line 7670=>dwarves, wizards, and all such folk as ever passed that way; but he was no longer 
line 7671=>quite  respectable.  He  was  in  fact  held  by  all  the  hobbits  of  the  neighbourhood to 
line 7672=>be  'queer'-except by his nephews and nieces on  the Took  side, but even  they were 
line 7673=>not  encouraged  in  their  friendship  by  their  elders.  I  am  sorry  to  say  he  did  not 
line 7674=>
line 7675=>####-mind.  He  was  quite  content;  and  the  sound  of  the  kettle  on  his  hearth  was  ever 
line 7676=>after more musical  than  it had been  even  in  the quiet days before  the Unexpected 
line 7677=>Party. His sword he hung over  the mantelpiece. His coat of mail was arranged on 
line 7678=>a  stand  in  the hall  (until he  lent  it  to  a Museum). His gold  and  silver was  largely 
line 7679=>spent in presents, both useful and extravagant â€“ which to a certain extent accounts 
line 7680=>for  the  affection  of  his  nephews  and  his  nieces.  His  magic  ring  he  kept  a  great 
line 7681=>secret,  for  he  chiefly  used  it  when  unpleasant  callers  came.  He  took  to  writing 
line 7682=>poetry  and  visiting  the  elves;  and  though  many  shook  their  heads  and  touched 
line 7683=>their  foreheads  and  said  "Poor  old Baggins!"  and  though  few  believed  any  of  his 
line 7684=>tales,  he  remained  very  happy  to  the  end  of  his  days,  and  those  were 
line 7685=>extraordinarily long. 
line 7686=>One  autumn  evening  some  years  afterwards  Bilbo  was  sitting  in  his  study 
line 7687=>writing  his  memoirs  â€“  he  thought  of  calling  them  "There  and  Back  Again,  a 
line 7688=>Hobbit's  Holiday"  â€“  when  there  was  a  ring  at  the  door.  It  was  Gandalf  and  a 
line 7689=>dwarf; and the dwarf was actually Balin. 
line 7690=>"Come  in!  Come  in!"  said  Bilbo,  and  soon  they  were  settled  in  chairs  by  the 
line 7691=>fire. If Balin noticed that Mr. Baggins' waistcoat was more extensive (and had real 
line 7692=>gold buttons), Bilbo also noticed that Balm's beard was several inches longer, and 
line 7693=>his jewelled belt was of great magnificence. 
line 7694=>They  fell  to  talking  of  their  times  together,  of  course,  and  Bilbo  asked  how 
line 7695=>things  were  going  in  the  lands  of  the Mountain.  It  seemed  they  were  going  very 
line 7696=>well.  Bard  had  rebuilt  the  town  in  Dale  and  men  had  gathered  to  him  from  the 
line 7697=>Lake  and  from  South  and  West,  and  all  the  valley  had  become  tilled  again  and 
line 7698=>rich, and the desolation was now filled with birds and blossoms in spring and fruit 
line 7699=>and  feasting  in  autumn. And Lake-town was refounded and was more prosperous 
line 7700=>than  ever,  and much wealth went  up  and down the Running River; and there was 
line 7701=>friendship in those parts between elves and dwarves and men. 
line 7702=>The old Master had come to a bad end. Bard had given him much gold for the 
line 7703=>help  of  the  Lake-people,  but  being  of  the  kind  that  easily  catches  such  disease  he 
line 7704=>fell under the dragon-sickness, and took most of the gold and fled with it, and died 
line 7705=>of starvation in the Waste, deserted by his companions. 
line 7706=>"The  new  Master  is  of  wiser  kind,"  said  Balin,  "and  very  popular,  for,  of 
line 7707=>course,  he  gets  most  of  the  credit  for  the  present  prosperity.  They  are  making 
line 7708=>songs which say that in his day the rivers run with gold." 
line 7709=>"Then  the  prophecies  of  the  old  songs  have  turned  out  to  be  true,  after  a 
line 7710=>fashion!" said Bilbo. 
line 7711=>
line 7712=>####-"Of  course!"  said Gandalf.  "And why  should  not  they  prove  true? Surely you 
line 7713=>don't  disbelieve  the  prophecies,  because  you  had  a  hand  in  bringing  them  about 
line 7714=>yourself? You  don't  really  suppose,  do  you,  that  all  your  adventures  and  escapes 
line 7715=>were  managed  by  mere  luck,  just  for  your  sole  benefit?  You  are  a  very  fine 
line 7716=>person,  Mr.  Baggins,  and  I  am  very  fond  of  you;  but  you  are  only  quite  a  little 
line 7717=>fellow in a wide world after all!" 
line 7718=>"Thank goodness!" said Bilbo laughing, and handed him the tobacco-jar.  
