line 7818=>####-Foreword 
line 7819=>
line 7820=> 
line 7821=> 
line 7822=>     This  tale grew in the telling, until it became  a history of the Great 
line 7823=>War of the  Ring and included  many glimpses of the yet more ancient history 
line 7824=>that preceded it. It was begun soon after The  Hobbit was written and before 
line 7825=>its publication in 1937; but I did not go  on with this sequel, for I wished 
line 7826=>first  to complete and set in  order the mythology and  legends of the Elder  
line 7827=>Days, which had then been taking shape for some years. I desired to do  this 
line 7828=>for my own satisfaction,  and  I had little hope that other people would  be 
line 7829=>interested  in  this work, especially  since it was primarily  linguistic in 
line 7830=>inspiration and  was begun  in order to provide  the necessary background of 
line 7831=>'history' for Elvish tongues. 
line 7832=>     When  those  whose advice and opinion I sought corrected little hope to 
line 7833=>no hope, I went back to the sequel, encouraged by  requests from readers for  
line 7834=>more information concerning hobbits and their adventures. But the story  was 
line 7835=>drawn  irresistibly  towards the  older world, and became an account,  as it 
line 7836=>were, of its end and passing away  before its beginning and middle had  been 
line 7837=>told. The process  had begun  in the writing  of The Hobbit, in which  there 
line 7838=>were  already  some  references to the older  matter:  Elrond, Gondolin, the 
line 7839=>High-elves, and the  orcs,  as  well as glimpses that had arisen unbidden of 
line 7840=>things higher or deeper  or darker than its surface: Durin,  Moria, Gandalf, 
line 7841=>the Necromancer,  the  Ring.  The  discovery  of the significance  of  these 
line 7842=>glimpses and of  their relation to  the ancient histories revealed the Third 
line 7843=>Age and its culmination in the War of the Ring. 
line 7844=>     Those who  had asked for  more information about hobbits eventually got  
line 7845=>it, but they had to wait a long time; for the composition of The Lord of the 
line 7846=>Rings went on at intervals during the  years 1936 to 1949, a period in which  
line 7847=>I had  many  duties that  I did not neglect, and  many  other interests as a  
line 7848=>learner and teacher  that often absorbed  me. The delay was, of course, also 
line 7849=>increased by the outbreak of war in 1939, by the end of which  year the tale 
line 7850=>had not yet reached  the  end  of Book  One. In spite of the darkness of the 
line 7851=>next  five years I  found that the story could  not now be  wholly abandoned,  
line 7852=>and  I plodded on, mostly  by night, till I stood  by Balin's tomb in Moria. 
line 7853=>There I halted for a long while. It  was almost a  year later when I went on 
line 7854=>and so came to Lothlurien and the Great River late in 1941. In the next year  
line 7855=>
line 7856=>####-I  wrote the first drafts of the  matter  that now stands as Book Three, and 
line 7857=>the beginnings of  chapters I and III of Book Five; and there as the beacons 
line 7858=>flared in  Anurien  and Thjoden came to Harrowdale I stopped.  Foresight had 
line 7859=>failed and there was no time for thought. 
line 7860=>     It was  during 1944  that, leaving the loose ends and perplexities of a  
line 7861=>war which it was my task to  conduct, or at least to report, 1 forced myself 
line 7862=>to tackle the journey of Frodo  to  Mordor.  These chapters,  eventually  to 
line 7863=>become  Book Four,  were  written  and  sent  out  as  a  serial  to my son, 
line 7864=>Christopher, then in South Africa with the RAF.  Nonetheless it took another 
line 7865=>five  years before the tale was brought to its present end;  in that  time I 
line 7866=>changed my house, my chair,  and my college,  and the days though  less dark 
line 7867=>were no less laborious.  Then when the 'end' had  at last  been reached  the 
line 7868=>whole story had to be revised, and indeed  largely re-written backwards. And 
line 7869=>it had to be typed, and  re-typed: by me; the cost of professional typing by 
line 7870=>the ten-fingered was beyond my means. 
line 7871=>     The Lord of the  Rings has been read by many  people since  it  finally 
line 7872=>appeared in print; and I should like to say something here with reference to 
line 7873=>the many opinions  or guesses that I  have  received or have read concerning 
line 7874=>the motives  and meaning  of  the tale. The prime motive was the desire of a  
line 7875=>tale-teller  to try  his hand at a  really long  story that would  hold  the 
line 7876=>attention  of  readers, amuse them, delight  them, and at times maybe excite 
line 7877=>them or deeply move them. As a guide I had only my own  feelings for what is 
line 7878=>appealing or moving, and for  many the guide  was inevitably often at fault. 
line 7879=>Some who have read the book, or at  any rate have reviewed it, have found it 
line 7880=>boring, absurd, or contemptible; and I have no  cause  to complain, since  I 
line 7881=>have similar opinions of  their works, or of the kinds  of writing that they 
line 7882=>evidently  prefer. But even from the points of view of many who have enjoyed 
line 7883=>my story there is much that fails to please. It is perhaps not possible in a  
line 7884=>long tale to please everybody at  all  points, nor to displease everybody at 
line 7885=>the same points; for I find from the letters that I have  received  that the 
line 7886=>passages or chapters that are to some a blemish  are all by others specially 
line 7887=>approved. The  most critical  reader of all, myself, now finds many defects,  
line 7888=>minor and major, but  being fortunately under no obligation either to review 
line 7889=>the book  or  to write  it again, he will pass over these in  silence, except 
line 7890=>one that has been noted by others: the book is too short. 
line 7891=>     As for any inner meaning or  'message', it has in the intention  of the 
line 7892=>author none. It is neither allegorical nor topical. As the story grew it put 
line 7893=>
line 7894=>####-down roots  (into the past) and threw out unexpected branches: but  its main 
line 7895=>theme was  settled from  the outset by the  inevitable choice of the Ring as 
line 7896=>the link between it and  The Hobbit. The crucial chapter, "The Shadow of the 
line 7897=>Past', is  one of the oldest parts of the tale.  It  was written long before 
line 7898=>the foreshadow  of  1939 had yet become a threat of inevitable disaster, and 
line 7899=>from that  point the  story would have developed along essentially  the same 
line 7900=>lines, if that disaster had been averted. Its sources are things long before 
line 7901=>in mind, or in some  cases already written, and  little or nothing in it was 
line 7902=>modified by the war that began in 1939 or its sequels.  
line 7903=>     The real war  does not resemble the legendary war in its process or its 
line 7904=>conclusion. If it had inspired  or  directed  the development of the legend, 
line 7905=>then certainly the  Ring would have  been seized and used against Sauron; he 
line 7906=>would  not have been annihilated  but enslaved, and Barad-dyr would not have 
line 7907=>been destroyed but occupied. Saruman, failing to get possession of the Ring, 
line 7908=>would m the confusion  and treacheries of the  time have found in Mordor the 
line 7909=>missing links in his own researches into Ring-lore, and before long he would 
line 7910=>have made a Great  Ring  of his  own with which to challenge the self-styled 
line 7911=>Ruler of Middle-earth.  In that conflict both sides would  have held hobbits 
line 7912=>in hatred and contempt: they would not long have survived even as slaves. 
line 7913=>     Other arrangements could be devised according to the tastes or views of 
line 7914=>those  who  like allegory  or  topical reference.  But I  cordially  dislike 
line 7915=>allegory in all its manifestations, and always have done so since I grew old 
line 7916=>and  wary  enough to  detect  its  presence. I  much prefer history, true or  
line 7917=>feigned, with its varied  applicability  to the  thought  and  experience of 
line 7918=>readers. I think that many confuse 'applicability' with 'allegory'; but  the 
line 7919=>one  resides  in the  freedom of the reader, and the  other in  the purposed 
line 7920=>domination of the author. 
line 7921=>     An author cannot of course remain wholly unaffected  by his experience,  
line 7922=>but the ways in which a story-germ uses the soil of experience are extremely  
line 7923=>complex,  and  attempts  to  define  the  process  are at  best guesses from 
line 7924=>evidence  that  is  inadequate  and  ambiguous.  It  is also  false,  though 
line 7925=>naturally  attractive,  when  the  lives  of   an  author  and  critic  have 
line 7926=>overlapped, to  suppose that the movements of thought or the events of times 
line 7927=>common to both were necessarily the most powerful influences. One has 
line 7928=>indeed 
line 7929=>personally to come under the shadow of war to feel fully its oppression; but 
line 7930=>as the years go by it seems now often forgotten that to  be caught  in youth 
line 7931=>
line 7932=>####-by  1914 was no less hideous an experience  than to  be involved in 1939 and 
line 7933=>the  following years. By 1918 all but one of my close  friends were dead. Or  
line 7934=>to  take  a less grievous  matter:  it  has been supposed by some  that 'The 
line 7935=>Scouring of  the Shire' reflects the situation in England at the time when I 
line 7936=>was finishing  my tale. It does  not. It is an  essential  part of the plot, 
line 7937=>foreseen from the outset, though in the event  modified  by the character of 
line 7938=>Saruman as  developed  in  the story  without, need I  say,  any allegorical 
line 7939=>significance or contemporary political reference  whatsoever. It has  indeed 
line 7940=>some basis in experience,  though  slender (for the  economic situation  was 
line 7941=>entirely different),  and much further back. The country in which I lived in 
line 7942=>childhood was  being  shabbily  destroyed before  I was  ten, in  days  when 
line 7943=>motor -cars were  rare objects  (I had  never seen  one) and  men wer e  still 
line 7944=>building suburban railways.  Recently I saw in a paper a picture of the last  
line 7945=>decrepitude of  the once  thriving  corn-mill beside its  pool that long ago 
line 7946=>seemed to me so important.  I never liked the looks of the Young miller, but 
line 7947=>his father,  the Old  miller,  had  a  black  beard,  and he  was  not named 
line 7948=>Sandyman. 
line 7949=>     The  Lord  of  the  Rings is  now  issued in  a  new  edition,  and the 
line 7950=>opportunity  has  been  taken  of  revising  it.  A  number  of  errors  and 
line 7951=>inconsistencies that still rema ined in  the text have been corrected, and an 
line 7952=>attempt has been made to provide information on a few points which attentive 
line 7953=>readers have raised. I have considered all their comments and enquiries, and 
line 7954=>if some seem to have been passed over  that  may be because I have failed to  
line 7955=>keep  my  notes in  order;  but many  enquiries  could only  be answered  by  
line 7956=>additional appendices, or indeed  by the  production  of an accessory volume  
line 7957=>containing  much of  the material that I did not  include  in  the  original 
line 7958=>edition, in particular more detailed linguistic information. In the meantime 
line 7959=>this edition offers this Foreword, an  addition to the Prologue, some notes,  
line 7960=>and an index of the names of persons and places. This index is in  intention 
line 7961=>complete in items  but not in references,  since for the present  purpose it 
line 7962=>has been  necessary to reduce its bulk. A complete index, making full use of 
line 7963=>the  material  prepared  for  me  by Mrs.  N. Smith,  belongs  rather to the 
line 7964=>accessory volume. 
line 7965=> 
line 7966=>
line 7967=>####-* PROLOGUE * 
line 7968=>
line 7969=> 
line 7970=> 
line 7971=>
line 7972=>1. Concerning Hobbits 
line 7973=>
line 7974=> 
line 7975=> 
line 7976=>     This  book  is largely  concerned  with  Hobbits, and from its pages  a  
line 7977=>reader  may discover  much of their character and a little of their history. 
line 7978=>Further information will also be found in the selection from the Red Book of 
line 7979=>Westmarch  that has already been published, under the  title of The  Hobbit. 
line 7980=>That story  was derived  from the earlier chapters of the Red Book, composed 
line 7981=>by  Bilbo himself, the first Hobbit to become famous in  the world at large, 
line 7982=>and called by him There and  Back Again, since they told of his journey into 
line 7983=>the East and his  return: an adventure  which later involved all the Hobbits 
line 7984=>in the great events of that Age that are here related. 
line 7985=>     Many, however, may wish to know more about  this remarkable people 
line 7986=>from 
line 7987=>the outset, whi le some  may not possess the earlier book. For such readers a  
line 7988=>few notes on the more important points are here  collected from Hobbit-lore,  
line 7989=>and the first adventure is briefly recalled. 
line 7990=>     Hobbits are  an  unobtrusive  but  very  ancient  people, more numerous 
line 7991=>formerly than they are today; for they love peace and quiet and  good tilled 
line 7992=>earth: a well-ordered and well-farmed countryside was their favourite haunt. 
line 7993=>They do not and did not understand or like machines more  complicated than a  
line 7994=>forge-bellows, a water -mill, or a  hand-loom, though  they were skilful with  
line 7995=>tools. Even in ancient days they  were, as a rule, shy of 'the Big Folk', as 
line 7996=>they call us, and now  they avoid us with  dismay and are  becoming hard  to  
line 7997=>find. They are quick of hearing and sharp-eyed, and though they are inclined  
line 7998=>to be  fat  and do not hurry unnecessarily, they are nonetheless  nimble and 
line 7999=>deft  in  their  movements.  They  possessed  from  the  first  the  art  of 
line 8000=>disappearing  swiftly and silently, when large folk whom they do not wish to 
line 8001=>meet come blundering by; and this an they have developed until to Men it may 
line 8002=>seem  magical. But Hobbits have never, in  fact,  studied magic of any kind,  
line 8003=>and their elusiveness  is due  solely to a professional skill  that heredity 
line 8004=>and  practice,  and  a  close  friendship  with  the  earth,  have  rendered 
line 8005=>
line 8006=>####-inimitable by bigger and clumsier races.  
line 8007=>     For  they are  a  little people,  smaller  than Dwarves:  less tout and 
line 8008=>stocky, that is, even when they  are not actually much shorter. Their height 
line 8009=>is  variable, ranging between two and  four feet of our measure. They seldom 
line 8010=>now reach three feet; but they hive dwindled, they  say, and in ancient days 
line 8011=>they were  taller. According to the Red Book,  Bandobras Took  (Bullroarer), 
line 8012=>son of Isengrim the Second,  was four foot five and able to ride a  horse. He 
line 8013=>was  surpassed  in all Hobbit records only by two famous characters of  old;  
line 8014=>but that curious matter is dealt with in this book. 
line 8015=>     As for the Hobbits of the  Shire,  with whom these tales are concerned, 
line 8016=>in  the  days  of their peace and prosperity they  were  a  merry folk. They 
line 8017=>dressed in bright colours, being notably fond of yellow and green;  but they 
line 8018=>seldom wore shoes, since  their feet had tough leathery soles  and were clad 
line 8019=>in  a  thick  curling hair, much like  the hair  of  their  heads, which was 
line 8020=>commonly  brown.  Thus,  the  only  craft  little  practised among them  was 
line 8021=>shoe-making; but they had long and skilful fingers and could make many other 
line 8022=>useful and comely  things.  Their faces  were as  a rule good-natured rather  
line 8023=>than  beautiful,  broad,  bright-eyed,  red-cheeked,  with  mouths   apt  to 
line 8024=>laughter,  and to eating and  drinking. And laugh  they  did,  and  eat, and 
line 8025=>drink, often and heartily, being fond  of simple  jests at all times, and of 
line 8026=>six meals  a  day (when  they  could  get them).  They  were  hospitable and 
line 8027=>delighted in  parties, and  in  presents, which  they  gave away freely  and 
line 8028=>eagerly accepted. 
line 8029=>     It  is plain indeed that  in spite  of later  estrangement Hobbits  are 
line 8030=>relatives of ours: far nearer to us than Elves, or even than Dwarves. Of old 
line 8031=>they spoke  the languages  of Men,  after their own fashion,  and liked  and 
line 8032=>disliked much  the same things as Men did. But what exactly our relationship 
line 8033=>is  can no longer be discovered. The  beginning of Hobbits lies  far back in 
line 8034=>the  Elder Days that  are  now  lost and  forgotten.  Only  the Elves  still 
line 8035=>preserve any  records  of  that  vanished  time, and  their  traditions  are 
line 8036=>concerned almost entirely with their own history, in which Men appear seldom 
line 8037=>and Hobbits are not mentioned at  all. Yet it is clear that Hobbits  had, in 
line 8038=>fact, lived quietly in  Middle-earth for  many  long years before other folk  
line 8039=>became  even aware of  them.  And the world being after all  full of strange 
line 8040=>creatures   beyond  count,  these  little  people   seemed  of  very  little 
line 8041=>importance. But in the days of Bilbo, and  of Frodo his  heir, they suddenly 
line 8042=>became, by no wish of  their  own, both important and renowned, and troubled 
line 8043=>
line 8044=>####-the counsels of the Wise and  the Great. 
line 8045=>     Those days,  the Third Age of Middle-earth, are now long past, and  the 
line 8046=>shape  of all lands has  been changed; but the regions in which Hobbits then  
line 8047=>lived were doubtless  the  same  as  those  in which  they still linger: the 
line 8048=>North-West  of the  Old World, east of  the Sea. Of their original home  the 
line 8049=>Hobbits in Bilbo's time preserved no  knowledge. A  love  of learning (other  
line 8050=>than genealogical lore) was far from general among them,  but there remained 
line 8051=>still a few  in  the  older families  who  studied their own books, and even 
line 8052=>gathered reports  of old times and distant lands  from Elves,  Dwarves,  and 
line 8053=>Men. Their own  records  began only  after the settlement of the  Shire, and 
line 8054=>their most ancient  legends hardly looked further  back than their Wandering  
line 8055=>Days. It is clear, nonetheless, from these legends, and from the evidence of 
line 8056=>their peculiar words  and customs, that like many other  folk Hobbits had in 
line 8057=>the distant past moved westward. Their earliest tales seem to glimpse a time 
line 8058=>when they dwelt in the upper vales of Anduin, between the eaves of 
line 8059=>Greenwood 
line 8060=>the Great  and the Misty Mountains. Why they  later undertook  the hard  and 
line 8061=>perilous crossing of the mountains into Eriador is no longer  certain. Their 
line 8062=>own  accounts speak  of the multiplying of Men in  the land, and of a shadow 
line 8063=>that fell on the forest,  so that it became  darkened  and its new  name was 
line 8064=>Mirkwood. 
line 8065=>     Before the  crossing  of the  mountains the Hobbits had  already become 
line 8066=>divided  into  three  somewhat   different  breeds:  Harfoots,  Stoors,  and 
line 8067=>Fallohides. The Harfoots were  browner  of skin, smaller,  and  shorter, and 
line 8068=>they were beardless and bootless; their hands and feet were neat and nimble;  
line 8069=>and they preferred highlands and hillsides. The Stoors were broader, heavier  
line 8070=>in build; their feet  and hands were larger,  and they preferred flat  lands 
line 8071=>and riversides.  The Fallohides  were fairer of  skin and also of  hair, and 
line 8072=>they were taller and slimmer than the others; they were lovers of  trees and 
line 8073=>of woodlands.  
line 8074=>     The  Harfoots had  much  to do  with Dwarves in ancient times, and long 
line 8075=>lived in the  foothills  of  the  mountains. They moved westward early,  and 
line 8076=>roamed over Eriador as far as Weathertop while the  others were still in the 
line 8077=>Wilderland. They were the most normal  and representative variety of Hobbit, 
line 8078=>and  far  the most  numerous. They  were the most inclined to settle  in one 
line 8079=>place, and longest preserved their ancestral habit of living in  tunnels and 
line 8080=>holes. 
line 8081=>
line 8082=>####-     The Stoors lingered long by  the  banks of  the Great River Anduin, and 
line 8083=>were less shy of Men.  They came west after  the  Harfoots and  followed the 
line 8084=>course of the  Loudwater  southwards;  and  there  many of  them  long dwelt 
line 8085=>between Tharbad and the borders of Dunland before they moved north again. 
line 8086=>     The  Fallohides, the least numerous, were a northerly branch. They were 
line 8087=>more friendly with Elves  than the other Hobbits were, and had more skill in 
line 8088=>language  and song than in handicrafts; and of old they preferred hunting to 
line 8089=>tilling.  They  crossed the mountains north of Rivendell  and came  down the  
line 8090=>River Hoarwell. In  Eriador they soon  mingled with the other kinds that had 
line 8091=>preceded them,  but being somewhat  bolder  and more adventurous, they  were 
line 8092=>often found as leaders or chieftains among clans of Harfoots or Stoors. Even 
line 8093=>in Bilbo's time the strong Fallohidish strain could still be noted among the 
line 8094=>greater families, such as the Tooks and the Masters of Buckland. 
line 8095=>     In the  westlands  of Eriador, between  the  Misty  Mountains  and  the 
line 8096=>Mountains of  Lune, the Hobbits found both Men and Elves. Indeed, a  remnant 
line 8097=>still dwelt there of the DÂ®nedain, the kings of Men that  came over the  Sea  
line 8098=>out of  Westernesse; but  they were  dwindling fast and  the  lands of their 
line 8099=>North Kingdom were falling far and  wide into waste. There was  room and  to 
line 8100=>spare for  incomers, and ere long  the Hobbits began  to  settle in  ordered 
line 8101=>communities. Most of their earlier settlements had long disappeared and been 
line 8102=>forgotten in Bilbo's time;  but  one of the  first to become important still 
line 8103=>endured, though reduced in  size; this  was at Bree and in the Chetwood that 
line 8104=>lay round about, some forty miles east of the Shire. 
line 8105=>     It was in these  early days,  doubtless, that the Hobbits learned their 
line 8106=>letters and  began to write  after  the  manner  of the DÂ®nedain, who had in 
line 8107=>their  turn long before learned  the art from  the Elves. And in  those days 
line 8108=>also they  forgot  whatever languages  they had used before,  and spoke ever  
line 8109=>after the  Common  Speech, the  Westron as it  was  named, that was  current 
line 8110=>through all the lands of the kings  from Arnor to  Gondor, and about all the 
line 8111=>coasts of the Sea from Belfalas to Lune. Yet they kept  a few words of their 
line 8112=>own,  as  well as their own names of months  and days, and  a great store of 
line 8113=>personal names out of the past. 
line 8114=>     About this time legend among  the Hobbits first  becomes history with a  
line 8115=>reckoning  of years. For it was in the  one thousand  six hundred  and first  
line 8116=>year of the  Third Age  that the  Fallohide brothers, Marcho and Blanco, set 
line 8117=>out  from  Bree; and having  obtained  permission  from  the  high  king  at 
line 8118=>Fornost1,  they crossed the brown river Baranduin with a  great following of 
line 8119=>
line 8120=>####-Hobbits.  They passed over the Bridge of Stonebows, that had been  built  in 
line 8121=>the  days  of the  power of the North Kingdom,  and they took ail  the  land 
line 8122=>beyond  to  dwell in,  between  the river and  the Far Downs.  All  that was 
line 8123=>demanded of them was  that they should keep the Great Bridge in  repair, and 
line 8124=>all other bridges  and roads,  speed the king's messengers, and  acknowledge 
line 8125=>his lordship. 
line 8126=>     Thus began  the Shire-reckoning, for the year  of  the  crossing of the 
line 8127=>Brandywine (as the  Hobbits turned the name) became  Year One  of the Shire, 
line 8128=>and all later dates were reckoned from it.2 At once the western Hobbits fell 
line 8129=>in love with their new land, and they  remained there, and soon passed  once 
line 8130=>more out  of the history  of Men and of Elves. While there  was still a king 
line 8131=>they  were in name his subjects, but they were, in  fact, ruled by their own 
line 8132=>chieftains  and meddled not at all with events in the world outside. To  the 
line 8133=>last  battle at Fornost with the Witch -lord of Angmar they  sent some bowmen 
line 8134=>to the aid of the king, or so they maintained, though no tales of Men record 
line 8135=>it.  But in that war the North Kingdom ended; and then the  Hobbits took the 
line 8136=>land for their own, and they chose from their own chiefs a Thain to hold the 
line 8137=>authority of the king that  was  gone. There for a thousand years  they were 
line 8138=>little troubled  by wars, and  they prospered and  multiplied after the Dark 
line 8139=>Plague (S.R. 37) until the disaster of  the Long Winter and the famine  that 
line 8140=>followed it. Many thousands then  perished, but the Days of Dearth (1158-60) 
line 8141=>were at the time of this  tale long past and  the Hobbits  had again  become 
line 8142=>accustomed  to plenty. The land  was rich and kindly, and though it had long 
line 8143=>been deserted  when they entered it,  it  had  before been  well tilled, and 
line 8144=>there the king had once had many farms, cornlands, vineyards, and woods.  
line 8145=>     Forty leagues it stretched from the Far Downs to the Brandywine Bridge, 
line 8146=>and fifty from the northern moors to  the marshes in the south. The  Hobbits 
line 8147=>named  it  the Shire, as the region of the  authority of their Thain,  and a  
line 8148=>district of well-ordered  business; and there  in that pleasant  comer of the 
line 8149=>world they plied their well-ordered business of living, and they heeded less 
line 8150=>and less the world outside where dark things moved, until they came to think 
line 8151=>that  peace and  plenty were the rule in Middle-earth and the  right of  all 
line 8152=>sensible folk. They forgot or ignored what little they had ever known of the 
line 8153=>Guardians, and of  the labours of those that made possible the long peace of 
line 8154=>the  Shire. They were, in fact, sheltered, but they had ceased  to  remember  
line 8155=>it. 
line 8156=>     At no  time had Hobbits of any  kind been  warlike, and  they had never  
line 8157=>
line 8158=>####-fought  among  themselves. In olden days  they had, of  course,  been  often 
line 8159=>obliged to fight to maintain themselves in a hard world; but in Bilbo's time 
line 8160=>that was very ancient history. The last battle, before this story opens, and 
line 8161=>indeed the  only  one  that had ever been  fought  within the borders of the 
line 8162=>Shire, was beyond  living memory: the Battle  of  Greenfields, S.R. 1147, in  
line 8163=>which Bandobras Took routed an invasion of Orcs. Even the weathers had 
line 8164=>grown 
line 8165=>milder, and the  wolves  that had once  come ravening  out of the  North  in 
line 8166=>bitter white winters were  now only  a grandfather's tale. So,  though there 
line 8167=>was still  some store of  weapons in the  Shire, these were  used  mostly as 
line 8168=>trophies, hanging above hearths or on  walls, or gathered into the museum at 
line 8169=>Michel Delving. The  Mathom-house it was  called; for  anything that Hobbits 
line 8170=>had  no immediate use for, but were unwilling to throw away,  they  called a  
line 8171=>mathom.  Their dwellings were apt to become rather crowded with mathoms, 
line 8172=>and 
line 8173=>many of the presents that passed from hand to hand were of that son. 
line 8174=>     Nonetheless, ease and peace had left this people still curiously tough. 
line 8175=>They were,  if it came to it, difficult to daunt or to kill; and they  were, 
line 8176=>perhaps,  so unwearyingly fond of  good things not least because they could, 
line 8177=>when put to it, do without them,  and could survive rough handling by grief,  
line 8178=>foe,  or weather in  a way that astonished those who did not know them  well 
line 8179=>and  looked  no further than their bellies and their well-fed  faces. Though 
line 8180=>slow to quarrel, and for sport killing nothing that lived, they were doughty 
line 8181=>at bay,  and  at  need could still handle arms. They shot well with the bow,  
line 8182=>for they were keen-eyed and sure at the mark. Not only with bows and arrows.  
line 8183=>If any Hobbit stooped for a stone,  it was well to get  quickly under cover, 
line 8184=>as all trespassing beasts knew very well. 
line 8185=>     All Hobbits had originally  lived in  holes in the  ground, or  so they 
line 8186=>believed,  and in such dwellings they still  felt most at  home; but  in  the 
line 8187=>course of time they had been obliged to adopt other forms of abode. Actually 
line 8188=>in  the Shire in Bilbo's  days it  was, as a rule, only the richest and  the 
line 8189=>poorest Hobbits  that maintained the old custom. The poorest  went on  living 
line 8190=>in burrows  of the  most  primitive  kind,  mere holes indeed, with only one 
line 8191=>window or  none;  while  the  well-to-do  still constructed  more  luxurious 
line 8192=>versions of the simple diggings of old.  But suitable  sites for these large 
line 8193=>and ramifying tunnels (or smials as they called them) were not everywhere to 
line 8194=>be found; and in the flats and the low-lying districts the Hobbits, as  they 
line 8195=>
line 8196=>####-multiplied, began to  build above ground. Indeed, even in the hilly  regions 
line 8197=>and the older villages, such  as  Hobbiton or Tuckborough,  or in the  chief 
line 8198=>township of the Shire, Michel Delving  on  the White Downs, there  were  now 
line 8199=>many houses  of wood,  brick, or stone. These  were  specially  favoured  by 
line 8200=>millers, smiths, ropers,  and cartwrights, and others of that sort; for even 
line 8201=>when  they  had holes to live in. Hobbits had long been  accustomed to build 
line 8202=>sheds and workshops. 
line 8203=>     The habit of building farmhouses and barns was said to have begun among 
line 8204=>the inhabitants of the Marish  down by the Brandywine.  The  Hobbits of that 
line 8205=>quarter, the Eastfarthing, were rather large and heavy-legged, and they wore 
line 8206=>dwarf-boots in muddy  weather. But they were well known  to  be Stoors in  a 
line 8207=>large part of their blood, as indeed was shown by the down that many grew on 
line 8208=>their chins. No Har foot  or Fallohide had  any trace of a beard. Indeed, the 
line 8209=>folk  of  the Marish,  and  of Buckland,  east  of  the  River,  which  they 
line 8210=>afterwards  occupied, came for the most  part  later into the Shire  up from 
line 8211=>south-away;  and  they still had many peculiar names and strange  words  not 
line 8212=>found elsewhere in the Shire. 
line 8213=>     It is probable that the craft of building, as many other crafts beside, 
line 8214=>was derived from the DÂ®nedain. But  the Hobbits  may  have learned it direct 
line 8215=>from the Elves, the teachers of  Men  in their  youth. For the Elves of  the 
line 8216=>High Kindred had not yet forsaken Middle-earth, and they dwelt still at that 
line 8217=>time at  the Grey Havens away to the west, and in other  places within reach 
line 8218=>of the  Shire. Three  Elf-towers of immemorial age were still to be seen  on 
line 8219=>the  Tower Hills  beyond the  western marches.  They shone far  off  in  the 
line 8220=>moonlight. The tallest was furthest away, standing alone upon a green mound. 
line 8221=>The Hobbits of the Westfarthing said that one could see the Sea from the lop  
line 8222=>of that tower; but  no  Hobbit had ever  been known to climb it. Indeed, few 
line 8223=>Hobbits  had ever  seen or  sailed  upon the Sea, and fewer  still had  ever  
line 8224=>returned to  report  it. Most Hobbits regarded even  rivers  and small boats 
line 8225=>with deep misgivings, and not  many of  them could swim.  And as the days of 
line 8226=>the Shire lengthened  they  spoke  less and  less with  the  Elves, and grew 
line 8227=>afraid  of them, and distrustful of those  that  had dealings with them; and 
line 8228=>the Sea  became  a word  of fear  among them, and a token of death, and they 
line 8229=>turned their faces away from the hills in the west. 
line 8230=>     The craft  of building may have come from Elves or Men, but the Hobbits 
line 8231=>used it in  their own fashion. They did not go in  for  towers. Their houses 
line 8232=>were usually long, low,  and comfortable. The oldest kind  were,  indeed, no 
line 8233=>
line 8234=>####-more than built imitations of smials, thatched with dry  grass or  straw, or  
line 8235=>roofed with turves,  and having walls somewhat  bulged. That stage, however, 
line 8236=>belonged to the early days of the Shire, and hobbit-building had long  since 
line 8237=>been  altered, improved by devices,  learned from Dwarves,  or discovered by 
line 8238=>themselves.  A  preference for round windows, and even round  doors, was the 
line 8239=>chief remaining peculiarity of hobbit -architecture. 
line 8240=>     The houses  and  the  holes   of  Shire-hobbits  were  often  large, and 
line 8241=>inhabited by large families. (Bilbo and Frodo Baggins were as bachelors very 
line 8242=>exceptional,  as they were also in many other ways, such as their friendship 
line 8243=>with the Elves.) Sometimes, as in the case  of the Tooks of Great Smials, or  
line 8244=>the Brandybucks  of  Brandy Hall,  many  generations of  relatives  lived in 
line 8245=>(comparative) peace  together  in one ancestral  and many -tunnelled mansion. 
line 8246=>All Hobbits were, in any case,  clannish and reckoned up their relationships 
line 8247=>with great care. They drew long and elaborate family -trees with  innumerable 
line 8248=>branches. In dealing with Hobbits it is important to remember who is related 
line 8249=>to whom,  and in what degree. It would be impossible in this book to set out 
line 8250=>a  family-tree  that included  even the more  important members of the  more 
line 8251=>important families at  the  time which these tales tell of. The genealogical 
line 8252=>trees  at  the  end  of  the  Red Book of  Westmarch  are  a  small book  in 
line 8253=>themselves,  and all but Hobbits  would find them  exceedingly dull. Hobbits 
line 8254=>delighted in such things, if they  were accurate: they liked  to  have books 
line 8255=>filled with  things that they already knew, set out fair and  square with no 
line 8256=>contradictions.  
line 8257=>
line 8258=>####- 
line 8259=>
line 8260=>2. Concerning Pipe-weed 
line 8261=>
line 8262=> 
line 8263=> 
line 8264=>     There is another astonishing  thing about Hobbits of old  that must  be 
line 8265=>mentioned, an astonishing habit: they imbibed  or inhaled, through pipes  of 
line 8266=>clay or wood, the smoke of the burning leaves of  a herb, which they  called  
line 8267=>pipe-weed or leaf, a variety  probably of Nicotiana. A great deal of mystery 
line 8268=>surrounds the  origin  of this peculiar  custom,  or  'art' as  the  Hobbits 
line 8269=>preferred to call it. All that could be discovered about it in antiquity was 
line 8270=>put together by Meriadoc Brandybuck (later Master of Buckland), and since he 
line 8271=>and  the   tobacco  of the Southfarthing  play  a part in  the  history  that 
line 8272=>follows, his remarks in the introduction to his Herblore of the Shire may be 
line 8273=>quoted. 
line 8274=>     'This,'  he says, 'is the one art that we can certainly claim to be our 
line 8275=>own invention.  When  Hobbi ts  first began  to smoke  is not known,  all the  
line 8276=>legends and family histories take it for granted; for ages folk in the Shire 
line 8277=>smoked various herbs, some fouler, some sweeter. But all accounts agree that 
line 8278=>Tobold Hornblower  of  Longbottom  in the Southfarthing first grew  the true 
line 8279=>pipe-weed in his gardens in  the days of Isengrim the Second, about the year  
line 8280=>1070 of Shire-reckoning. The best home-grown still comes from that district, 
line 8281=>especially the  varieties  now  known  as Longbottom  Leaf,  Old  Toby,  and 
line 8282=>Southern Star. 
line 8283=>     'How Old  Toby came by  the plant is not recorded, for to his dying day 
line 8284=>he would not tell.  He knew much about herbs, but he was no traveller. It is 
line 8285=>said that in his youth he went often to Bree, though he certainly never went 
line 8286=>further fr om the Shire than that.  It is thus quite possible that he learned 
line 8287=>of this plant in Bree, where now, at  any rate,  it grows well on  the south 
line 8288=>slopes of the hill. The  Bree-hobbits  claim to have been the  first  actual 
line 8289=>smokers of the pipe-weed.  They cla im,  of  course, to have done  everything  
line 8290=>before the people of the Shire,  whom they refer  to as "colonists"; but  in 
line 8291=>this case their claim is, I think,  likely to be true. And  certainly it was 
line 8292=>from Bree  that the  art  of smoking  the genuine weed sprea d  in the recent 
line 8293=>centuries among Dwarves and such other folk, Rangers, Wizards, or wanderers,  
line 8294=>as still passed  to and fro through that  ancient road-meeting. The home and 
line 8295=>centre of  the an is thus to be found in  the old inn of  Bree, The Prancing 
line 8296=>
line 8297=>####-Pony, that has been kept by the family of Butterbur from time beyond record. 
line 8298=>     'All the same,  observations  that I have made on my own many  journeys 
line 8299=>south have convinced me that the weed itself  is not  native to our parts of 
line 8300=>the  world,  but  came  northward  from the lower Anduin, whither  it was, I 
line 8301=>suspect, originally brought  over  Sea by the Men  of  Westernesse. It grows 
line 8302=>abundantly  in  Gondor, and  there  is richer and  larger than in the North, 
line 8303=>where it is never found wild, and flourishes  only in  warm sheltered places 
line 8304=>like Longbottom. The Men of Gondor call it sweet galenas, and esteem it only 
line 8305=>for the fragrance of its  flowers. From  that land it must have been carried 
line 8306=>up the Greenway  during the long centuries between the coming of Elendil and 
line 8307=>our own day.  But even the DÂ®nedain of  Gondor allow us this credit: Hobbits 
line 8308=>first put it into pipes.  Not even the Wizards first thought of that  before 
line 8309=>we did.  Though one Wizard that I knew took up the art long ago,  and became 
line 8310=>as skilful in it as in all other things that he put his mind to.' 
line 8311=>
line 8312=>####- 
line 8313=>
line 8314=>3. Of the Ordering of the Shire 
line 8315=>
line 8316=> 
line 8317=> 
line 8318=>     The  Shire was  divided  into  four  quarters,  the  Farthings  already 
line 8319=>referred to.  North,  South, East,  and  West;  and  these again each into a  
line 8320=>number of folklands,  which still bore the names of some of  the old leading  
line 8321=>families, although by the time  of this  history these names were no  longer 
line 8322=>found only in their  proper folklands.  Nearly all Tooks  still lived in the 
line 8323=>Tookland,  but that  was not  true  of  many  other  families,  such  as the 
line 8324=>Bagginses  or  the Boffins.  Outside the  Farthings  were the  East and West 
line 8325=>Marches:  the  Buckland  (see  beginning of Chapter  V,  Book  I);  and  the 
line 8326=>Westmarch added to the Shire in S.R. 1462. 
line 8327=>     The Shire at  this time had hardly any 'government'. Families  for  the 
line 8328=>most part  managed their  own affairs. Growing  food and eating  it occupied  
line 8329=>most of their time. In  other matters they were, as a rule, generous and not 
line 8330=>greedy, but  contented and moderate, so  that estates, farms, workshops, and 
line 8331=>small trades tended to remain unchanged for generations.  
line 8332=>     There  remained,  of course, the  ancient tradition concerning the high 
line 8333=>king at  Fornost, or Norbury as they called it, away north of the Shire. But 
line 8334=>there had been no king for nearly  a thousand years,  and even the ruins  of 
line 8335=>Kings' Norbury  were covered with grass. Yet the Hobbits  still said of wild 
line 8336=>folk and wicked things (such as trolls) that they had not heard of the king. 
line 8337=>For they attributed to the king of old all their essential laws; and usually 
line 8338=>they kept the laws of free will, because they were The Rules (as they said), 
line 8339=>both ancient and just. 
line 8340=>     It is true  that  the Took  family had long  been  pre-eminent; for the 
line 8341=>office  of  Thain had  passed  to them  (from the Oldbucks)  some  centuries 
line 8342=>before,  and the chief  Took had borne that title ever since. The  Thain was 
line 8343=>the  master  of  the  Shire-moot, and captain of  the Shire-muster  and  the 
line 8344=>Hobbitry-in-arms,  but  as  muster  and moot  were only  held  in  times  of 
line 8345=>emergency,  which no  longer occurred, the Thainship  had  ceased to be more 
line 8346=>than  a  nominal dignity. The  Took  family was  still,  indeed,  accorded a  
line 8347=>special respect, for it remained  both numerous and exceedingly wealthy, and 
line 8348=>was  liable  to produce in ever y generation strong  characters  of  peculiar 
line 8349=>habits and even adventurous temperament. The latter qualities, however, were 
line 8350=>
line 8351=>####-now  rather  tolerated (in  the  rich) than  generally  approved. The custom 
line 8352=>endured, nonetheless, of referring to the head of the  family  as The  Took, 
line 8353=>and of  adding  to  his  name, if  required, a number: such  as Isengrim the 
line 8354=>Second, for instance. 
line 8355=>     The only  real official  in the Shire  at  this date  was the Mayor  of 
line 8356=>Michel Delving (or of the Shire), who was  elected every  seven years at the 
line 8357=>Free Fair on the White  Downs at  the Lithe, that is at Midsummer.  As mayor  
line 8358=>almost   his  only  duty   was  to  preside   at  banquets,  given   on  the 
line 8359=>Shire-holidays,  which occurred at  frequent intervals. But  the  offices of 
line 8360=>Postmaster and First Shirriff were attached  to  the  mayoralty, so that  he 
line 8361=>managed  both the  Messenger Service  and  the  Watch.  These were the  only 
line 8362=>Shire-services,  and the Messengers  were the  most  numerous,  and much the 
line 8363=>busier of the two. By no means a ll Hobbits were lettered, but those who were 
line 8364=>wrote constantly to all their friends (and a  selection  of their relations)  
line 8365=>who lived further off than an afternoon's walk. 
line 8366=>     The Shirriffs was the name  that the  Hobbits gave to  their police, or  
line 8367=>the nearest equivalent that they possessed. They had, of course, no uniforms 
line 8368=>(such things being  quite unknown), only  a feather in their caps;  and they 
line 8369=>were  in  practice rather haywards than policemen,  more concerned  with the 
line 8370=>strayings of  beasts than of people. There were in all the Shire only twelve 
line 8371=>of them, three in  each  Farthing,  for  Inside Work. A  rather larger body, 
line 8372=>varying  at need,  was  employed  to  'beat  the  bounds', and to  see  that 
line 8373=>Outsiders of any kind, great or small, did not make themselves a nuisance. 
line 8374=>     At the time  when this story begins the Bounders, as they were  called, 
line 8375=>had been greatly  increased.  There  were  many reports  and  complaints  of 
line 8376=>strange persons  and creatures prowling about the borders, or over them: the 
line 8377=>first  sign  that all  was not  quite as  it  should be, and always had been 
line 8378=>except  in tales and legends of  long ago. Few heeded the sign, and not even  
line 8379=>Bilbo yet had any notion of what it portended. Sixty years  had passed since 
line 8380=>he set out on his  memorable journey, and he was old  even for Hobbits,  who 
line 8381=>reached a hundred  as often as not; but much evidently still remained of the 
line 8382=>considerable  wealth that he  had brought back. How  much or  how  little he 
line 8383=>revealed to no one,  not even to Frodo  his favourite 'nephew'. And he still 
line 8384=>kept secret the ring that he bad found. 
line 8385=>
line 8386=>####- 
line 8387=>
line 8388=>4. Of the Finding of the Ring  
line 8389=>
line 8390=> 
line 8391=> 
line 8392=>     As is  told in The Hobbit, there came one day to Bilbo's door the great 
line 8393=>Wizard, Gandalf the Grey, and thirteen dwarves with him: none other, indeed, 
line 8394=>than Thorin Oakenshield,  descendant  of kings, and his twelve companions in 
line 8395=>exile. With  them he set  out, to his own lasting astonishment, on a morning 
line 8396=>of  April, it being then  the year 1341 Shire-reckoning, on a quest of great 
line 8397=>treasure, the dwarf-hoards of the Kings under the Mountain,  beneath  Erebor 
line 8398=>in Dale, far off in the East. The quest was  successful, and the Dragon that 
line 8399=>guarded the hoard was destroyed. Yet, though before  all  was won the Battle 
line 8400=>of Five Armies was fought, and Thorin was slain, and  many deeds  of  renown 
line 8401=>were done, the matter would scarcely have concerned later history, or earned 
line 8402=>more than a note in the long annals of the Third Age, but for an  'accident' 
line 8403=>by the way.  The  party was assailed by  Orcs in a  high pass  of  the Misty 
line 8404=>Mountains as they went towards Wilderland; and so it happened that Bilbo was 
line 8405=>lost for a while in the black orc-mines deep under the mountains, and there, 
line 8406=>as he groped  in vain in the dark, he put  his hand on  a ring, lying on the 
line 8407=>floor of a tunnel. He put it in h is pocket. It seemed then like mere luck. 
line 8408=>     Trying to find  his way out. Bilbo went on  down to  the  roots  of the 
line 8409=>mountains, until he could go no further.  At the bottom  of the tunnel lay a  
line 8410=>cold lake far  from the light, and on an island  of rock  in the water lived 
line 8411=>Gollum. He was a loathsome little creature: he paddled a small boat with his 
line 8412=>large  flat feet,  peering with pale luminous eyes  and  catching blind fish 
line 8413=>with his long fingers, and eating  them raw.  He ate  any living thing, even 
line 8414=>orc, if  he could catch it and strangle it without a struggle. He possessed a  
line 8415=>secret treasure that had come to him long ages ago,  when he  still lived in 
line 8416=>the light: a ring  of gold  that made its  wearer invisible. It was the  one 
line 8417=>thing he  loved, his 'precious', and he talked to  it, even when it  was not 
line 8418=>with him. For he kept it hidden safe in a hole on his island, except when he 
line 8419=>was hunting or spying on the ores of the mines. 
line 8420=>     Maybe he would have attacked Bilbo at once, if the ring had been on him 
line 8421=>when they met;  but it was  not, and  the hobbit held  in his hand an Elvish 
line 8422=>knife,  which served him as a sword. So to gain time Gollum challenged Bilbo 
line 8423=>to the Riddle-game,  saying that if he  asked a riddle which Bilbo could not 
line 8424=>
line 8425=>####-guess, then  he would kill him and eat him;  but if Bilbo defeated him, then 
line 8426=>he would do as Bilbo wished: he would lead him to a way out of the tunnels.  
line 8427=>     Since he was lost in the dark without hope, and could neither go on nor  
line 8428=>back. Bilbo accepted the challenge; and they asked one another many riddles.  
line 8429=>In the end Bilbo won the game, more by luck (as it seemed) than by wits; for 
line 8430=>he was stumped at last  for a riddle to ask, and cried out, as his hand came 
line 8431=>upon the ring he lad picked up and forgotten:  What  haw I got in my pocket? 
line 8432=>This Gollum failed to answer, though he demanded three guesses. 
line 8433=>     The  Authorities, it is true, differ whether  this last  question was a  
line 8434=>mere  'question' and not  a  'riddle' according to  the strict rules  of the 
line 8435=>Game; but all agree that, after accepting it and trying to guess the answer, 
line 8436=>Gollum was bound by his promise. And Bilbo pressed him to keep his word; 
line 8437=>for 
line 8438=>the  thought  came  to him that  this slimy creature might prove false, even 
line 8439=>though  such  promises  were held sacred, and of old all  but  the wickedest 
line 8440=>things feared to break them. But after ages alone in the dark Gollum's heart 
line 8441=>was black, and  treachery was in it.  He slipped  away, and  returned to the 
line 8442=>island, of which Bilbo knew nothing,  not far off in the dark  water. There, 
line 8443=>he  thought,  lay  his  ring.  He was hungry now,  and angry, and  once  his 
line 8444=>'precious' was with him he would not fear any weapon at all. 
line 8445=>     But the ring was  not on the island; he had  lost it, it was  gone. His 
line 8446=>screech  sent a shiver down Bilbo's back, though he  did not  yet understand 
line 8447=>what  had happened. But Gollum had at last leaped to a guess, too late. What 
line 8448=>has  it got  in its pocketses? he  cried. The light in his eyes  was like  a  
line 8449=>green flame as he sped back to murder the hobbit and recover his 'precious'.  
line 8450=>Just  in  time Bilbo saw his peril,  and he fled blindly up the passage away 
line 8451=>from the water;  and once more he was saved by his luck. For  just as he ran 
line 8452=>he  put  his  hand in his  pocket, and  the ring  slipped  quietly on to his 
line 8453=>finger. So it was that  Gollum passed him  without seeing him, and  went  to  
line 8454=>guard  the  way out, lest the 'thief' should escape.  Warily Bilbo  followed 
line 8455=>him, as he went along, cursing, and talking to himself about his 'precious';  
line 8456=>from which  talk at last even Bilbo guessed the truth,  and hope came to him 
line 8457=>in the darkness: he himself had  found the marvellous  ring and a chance  of 
line 8458=>escape from the orcs and from Gollum. 
line 8459=>     At length they  came to a halt before an unseen opening that led to the 
line 8460=>lower  gates  of  the mines,  on the eastward  side of the mountains.  There 
line 8461=>Gollum  crouched at bay, smelling and listening;  and Bilbo  was  tempted to 
line 8462=>
line 8463=>####-slay him with his sword. But  pity stayed him, and though  he kept the ring, 
line 8464=>in  which  his  only hope lay, he  would not  use  it  to  help him kill the 
line 8465=>wretched creature at a disadvantage. In  the  end, gathering his courage, he 
line 8466=>leaped  over  Gollum in the dark, and fled away down the passage, pursued by 
line 8467=>his enemy's cries  of hate and despair: Thief,  thief! Baggins!  We hates it 
line 8468=>for ever! 
line 8469=>     Now it is a curious fact that this is not the story as Bilbo first told 
line 8470=>it to his companions.  To  them his account was  that Gollum had promised to 
line 8471=>give  him a present, if he  won the game;  but when  Gollum went to fetch it  
line 8472=>from his island he found the treasure was gone: a magic ring, which had been 
line 8473=>given to him long ago on his birthday. Bilbo guessed that this was the  very 
line 8474=>ring  that he  had found, and as he had won the game, it was already  his by 
line 8475=>right. But being in a tight place, he said nothing about it, and made Gollum 
line 8476=>show him  the way out, as a reward instead of  a present. This account Bilbo 
line 8477=>set down in  his memoirs, and he seems never to have altered it himself, not  
line 8478=>even after  the  Council of  Elrond.  Evidently  it  still  appeared in  the 
line 8479=>origina l Red Book, as it  did  in several of the  copies  and abstracts. But 
line 8480=>many copies contain the  true account (as an alternative), derived no  doubt 
line 8481=>from notes by Frodo  or Samwise, both of whom learned the truth, though they 
line 8482=>seem to have been unwilling to delete anything  actually written by the  old 
line 8483=>hobbit himself. 
line 8484=>     Gandalf, however,  disbelieved Bilbo's first story, as soon as he heard 
line 8485=>it,  and he continued  to be very curious about the ring. Eventually he  got 
line 8486=>the true  tale  out  of  Bilbo  after much questioning,  which for  a  while 
line 8487=>strained  their  friendship;  but  the  wizard seemed  to  think  the  truth 
line 8488=>important. Though he did not say so to Bilbo, he also thought  it important, 
line 8489=>and disturbing, to find that the good hobbit had not told the truth from the 
line 8490=>first:  quite contrary to his  habit. The idea of a 'present' was  not  mere 
line 8491=>hobbitlike  invention,  all the  same.  It was  suggested  to Bilbo,  as  he 
line 8492=>confessed, by Gollum's talk that he overheard; for Gollum did, in fact, call 
line 8493=>the  ring  his 'birthday  present', many times.  That also  Gandalf  thought 
line 8494=>strange and suspicious; but he did not discover the truth in  this point for  
line 8495=>many more years, as will be seen in this book. 
line 8496=>     Of  Bilbo's  later adventures little  more need be said here. Wi th  the 
line 8497=>help of the ring he escaped from the orc-guards at the gate and rejoined his 
line 8498=>companions. He  used the ring many times on his  quest, chiefly for the help 
line 8499=>of his  friends; but  he kept it secret from them as long as he could. After  
line 8500=>
line 8501=>####-his return to his home he never spoke  of  it  again to anyone, save Gandalf 
line 8502=>and Frodo;  and no one else  in the  Shire knew of its  existence,  or so he 
line 8503=>believed. Only to Frodo did he show  the account of  his Journey that he was 
line 8504=>writing. 
line 8505=>     His  sword,  Sting, Bilbo hu ng  over his  fireplace,  and  his coat  of 
line 8506=>marvellous mail, the gift of the Dwarves from the Dragon-hoard, he lent to a  
line 8507=>museum, to the Michel Delving Mathom-house in fact. But he kept in a  drawer  
line 8508=>at Bag  End  the old cloak and hood that he had worn on his travels; and the  
line 8509=>ring, secured by a fine chain, remained in his pocket. 
line 8510=>     He returned to his home at Bag End on June the 22nd in his fifty-second 
line 8511=>year (S.R. 1342),  and nothing very notable occurred in the  Shire until Mr. 
line 8512=>Baggins    began    the   pr eparations   for   the   celebration   of    his 
line 8513=>hundred-and-eleventh birthday  (S.R.  1401).  At  this  point  this  History 
line 8514=>begins. 
line 8515=>
line 8516=>####- 
line 8517=>
line 8518=>NOTE ON THE SHIRE RECORDS 
line 8519=>
line 8520=> 
line 8521=> 
line 8522=>     At the end of the Third Age the part played by the Hobbits in the great 
line 8523=>events that led  to  the  inclusion  of  the Shire  in the  Reunited Kingdom 
line 8524=>awakened among them a  more widespread  interest in  their own  history; and 
line 8525=>many of their traditions, up to that time still  mainly oral, were collected 
line 8526=>and Written down. The  greater families were  also concerned with  events in 
line 8527=>the  Kingdom  at  large,  and  many  of  their members  studied its  ancient 
line 8528=>histories and  legends. By the  end of the  first century of the Fourth  Age 
line 8529=>there were already to be found in the Shire several libraries tha t contained 
line 8530=>many historical books and records. 
line 8531=>     The largest of these collections were probably at Undertowers, at Great 
line 8532=>Smials,  and at Brandy Hall.  This  account of the end of  the Third  Age is 
line 8533=>drawn mainly from the Red Book of Westmarch. That most important  source 
line 8534=>for 
line 8535=>the  history  of  the War  of  the Ring was so  called because it  was  long 
line 8536=>preserved  at  Undertowers,  the  home  of the Fairbairns,  Wardens  of  the 
line 8537=>Westmarch.1  It was in origin Bilbo's private diary, which he took with  him 
line 8538=>to Rivendell.  Frodo brought  it back to the Shire, together with many loose 
line 8539=>leaves of notes, and during S.R. 1420-1 he nearly filled its pages  with his 
line 8540=>account of the War.  But annexed to  it  and preserved with it, probably m a  
line 8541=>single red case, were  the three large  volumes, bound in  red leather, that 
line 8542=>Bilbo gave  to him as a parting gift. To these four  volumes there was added  
line 8543=>in Westmarch a fifth containing commentaries, genealogies, and various other  
line 8544=>matter concerning the hobbit members of the Fellowship. 
line 8545=>     The original Red Book has  not been  preserved, but  many  copies  were 
line 8546=>made,  especially of the first volume, for the use of the descendants of the 
line 8547=>children  of  Master  Samwise.  The  most  important  copy, however,  has  a  
line 8548=>different history.  It  was kept at  Great  Smials,  but it  was written  in 
line 8549=>Condor,  probably at  the  request  of the  great-grandson  of Peregrin, and 
line 8550=>completed in S.R. 1592  (F.A. 172). Its southern scribe appended this  note: 
line 8551=>Findegil,  King's Writer, finished this work in IV 172. It  is an exact copy 
line 8552=>in  all details of the Thain's Book  m Minas Tirith.  That book was  a copy, 
line 8553=>made at the request of King Elessar,  of the Red Book of the Periannath, and 
line 8554=>
line 8555=>####-was brought to him by the Thain Peregrin when he retired to Gondor in IV 64 . 
line 8556=>     The Thain's Book was  thus  the first copy made of  the  Red  Book  and 
line 8557=>contained much that was later omitted or lost.  In Minas  Tirith it received 
line 8558=>much  annotation, and  many  corrections, especially  of  names,  words, and 
line 8559=>quotations in the Elvish languages; and there was added to it an abbreviated  
line 8560=>version of those  parts of The  Tale of Aragorn  and Arwen which lie outside 
line 8561=>the  account of the War. The full tale  is  stated  to have been written  by 
line 8562=>Barahir, grandson of the Steward Faramir, some time after the passing of the  
line 8563=>King. But the chief importance of  Findegil's copy is that it alone contains 
line 8564=>the whole  of Bilbo's 'Translations from the  Elvish'. These  three  volumes 
line 8565=>were  found to be a work of great skill and learning in  which, between 1403 
line 8566=>and 1418, he had used all the sources  available to  him  in Rivendell, both 
line 8567=>living and written. But  since they were little used by Frodo, being  almost  
line 8568=>entirely concerned with the Elder Days, no more is said of them here. 
line 8569=>     Since Meriadoc and Peregrin became the  heads  of their great families,  
line 8570=>and  at the  same time kept up their  connexions with Rohan and  Gondor, the 
line 8571=>libraries at Bucklebury and Tuckborough contained much that did  not  appear 
line 8572=>in the Red Book.  In Brandy Hall there were many works dealing  with Eriador  
line 8573=>and the  history of Rohan. Some of these were composed or  begun by 
line 8574=>Meriadoc 
line 8575=>himself, though in the  Shire he was chiefly remembered for  his Herblore of 
line 8576=>the Shire, and for his Reckoning of  Years m which he discussed the relation 
line 8577=>of the calendars of the Shire and Bree  to those of  Rivendell,  Gondor, and 
line 8578=>Rohan. He also wrote a short treatise on Old Words and Names  in the  Shire, 
line 8579=>having special interest  in discovering the kinship with the language of the 
line 8580=>Rohirrim of such 'shire-words' as mathom and old elements in place names. 
line 8581=>     At Great Smials the books were  of less interest to Shire-folk,  though 
line 8582=>more important for larger history. None of them was written by Peregrin, but 
line 8583=>he and  his successors  collected  many manuscripts written  by  scribes  of 
line 8584=>Gondor:  mainly  copies  or  summaries of  histories or legends  relating to 
line 8585=>Elendil  and his heirs. Only  here in the Shire were to  be  found extensive 
line 8586=>materials for  the history  of  NÂ®menor and the  arising of  Sauron.  It was 
line 8587=>probably at Great Smials that The Tale of Years1 was put  together, with the 
line 8588=>assistance of material  collected by Meriadoc. Though  the dates  given  are 
line 8589=>often conjectural, especially for the Second Age, they deserve attention. It 
line 8590=>is   probable  that  Mer iadoc  obtained   assistance  and  information  from 
line 8591=>Rivendell,  which he  visited  more  than  once.  There, though  Elrond  had 
line 8592=>
line 8593=>####-departed, his sons long remained, together with some of the High-elven folk. 
line 8594=>It  is  said  that  Celeborn  went  to  dwell  there after the departure  of 
line 8595=>Galadriel; but there is no record of the day when at last he sought the Grey 
line 8596=>Havens,  and  with  him went the last  living  memory  of the  Elder Days in  
line 8597=>Middle-earth. 
line 8598=>
line 8599=>####-* BOOK I *  
line 8600=>
line 8601=> 
line 8602=> 
line 8603=>
line 8604=>Chapter 1. A Long-expected Party 
line 8605=>
line 8606=> 
line 8607=> 
line 8608=>     When  Mr. Bilbo Baggins of Bag  End announced that  he would shortly be 
line 8609=>celebrating   his   eleventy-first  birthday   with  a   party  of   special 
line 8610=>magnificence, there was much talk and excitement in Hobbiton. 
line 8611=>     Bilbo  was very rich  and very peculiar, and had been the wonder of the 
line 8612=>Shire  for  sixty   years,  ever  since  his  remarkable  disappearance  and 
line 8613=>unexpected return. The riches  he  had brought back from his travels had now 
line 8614=>become  a local legend, and it was popularly believed, whatever the old folk  
line 8615=>might  say,  that  the Hill  at Bag  End was  full  of tunnels  stuffed with 
line 8616=>treasure. And if that was not enough for  fame, there was also his prolonged  
line 8617=>vigour  to marvel at. Time wore on,  but it seemed to  have little effect on 
line 8618=>Mr. Baggins. At ninety he was much the same as at fifty. At ninety-nine they 
line 8619=>began to  call him well-preserved,  but unchanged would have been nearer the 
line 8620=>mark. There were  some that shook their heads and thought  this was too much 
line 8621=>of  a good thing; it seemed unfair that anyone should  possess  (apparently)  
line 8622=>perpetual youth as well as (reputedly) inexhaustible wealth. 
line 8623=>     'It  will  have  to be  paid for,'  they said. 'It  isn't natural,  and 
line 8624=>trouble will come of it!' 
line 8625=>     But so far trouble had not come;  and as Mr. Baggins was  generous with 
line 8626=>his money, most people were willing to forgive him his oddities and his good 
line 8627=>fortune.  He  remained  on visiting  terms with  his  relatives (except,  of 
line 8628=>course, the Sackville-Bagginses), and he had many devoted admirers among 
line 8629=>the 
line 8630=>hobbits of poor and unimportant families. But he had no close friends, until 
line 8631=>some of his younger cousins began to grow up. 
line 8632=>     The eldest of  these,  and Bilbo's favourite,  was young Frodo Baggins. 
line 8633=>When Bilbo was ninety-nine, he adopted Frodo as his heir, and brought him to 
line 8634=>live  at Bag End;  and the  hopes  of the  Sackville-Bagginses were  finally 
line 8635=>dashed. Bilbo and Frodo happened to have the same  birthday, September 
line 8636=>22nd. 
line 8637=>'You had better come and live here, Frodo my lad,' said  Bilbo one day; 'and 
line 8638=>then we  can  celebrate our birthday-parties  comfortably together.' At that 
line 8639=>
line 8640=>####-time Frodo  was still in his tweens, as the hobbits called the irresponsible 
line 8641=>twenties between childhood and coming of age at thirty-three. 
line 8642=>     Twelve more years passed. Each year the Bagginses  had given very lively 
line 8643=>combined  birthday-parties  at  Bag  End;  but  now  it  was understood that 
line 8644=>something  quite  exceptional was being planned  for that autumn.  Bilbo was 
line 8645=>going  to  be  eleventy -one,  111,  a  rather  curious  number  and  a  very 
line 8646=>respectable  age  for a hobbit (the Old Took  himself had only reached 130); 
line 8647=>and Frodo was going to be thirty- three, 33) an important number: the date of 
line 8648=>his 'coming of age'.  
line 8649=>     Tongues began to wag in  Hobbiton and Bywater; and rumour of the coming 
line 8650=>event travelled all  over the Shire. The  history and character of Mr. Bilbo 
line 8651=>Baggins became once again the  chief  topic of  conversation; and the  older  
line 8652=>folk suddenly found their reminiscences in welcome demand. 
line 8653=>     No one  had  a  more attentive audience than old Ham  Gamgee,  commonly 
line 8654=>known as  the  Gaffer. He held forth  at  The Ivy Bush,  a small inn on  the 
line 8655=>Bywater road; and he spoke with some authority, for he had tended the garden 
line 8656=>at Bag End for forty years, and had helped old Holman in the same job befor e 
line 8657=>that. Now that he was himself  growing old  and stiff in the joints, the job 
line 8658=>was mainly  carried on by his youngest son, Sam Gamgee. Both father  and son 
line 8659=>were on very friendly  terms with Bilbo and  Frodo. They  lived  on the Hill  
line 8660=>itself, in Number 3 Bagshot Row just below Bag End. 
line 8661=>     'A very nice  well-spoken  gentlehobbit  is  Mr.  Bilbo, as I've always 
line 8662=>said,' the Gaffer declared. With perfect truth: for Bilbo was very polite to 
line 8663=>him, calling him 'Master Hamfast', and consulting  him  constantly upon  the 
line 8664=>growing  of vegetables  - in the matter of 'roots', especially  potatoes, the 
line 8665=>Gaffer was recognized as the  leading authority  by all in the neighbourhood 
line 8666=>(including himself). 
line 8667=>     'But  what about this Frodo that lives with  him?'  asked Old Noakes of 
line 8668=>Bywater.  'Baggins is his name, but he's more than  half a  Brandybuck, they 
line 8669=>say. It beats me why any Baggins  of  Hobbiton should go looking for a  wife 
line 8670=>away there in Buckland, where folks are so queer.' 
line 8671=>     'And no  wonder they're queer,'  put  in  Daddy  Twofoot  (the Gaffer's 
line 8672=>next-door neighbour),  'if they live  on  the wrong  side of the  Brandywine 
line 8673=>River, and right agin  the Old Forest. That's a dark bad place, if half  the 
line 8674=>tales be true.' 
line 8675=>     'You're right,  Dad!' said  the  Gaffer. 'Not  that  the Brandybucks of 
line 8676=>Buck-land live in the Old Forest; but they're a queer breed, seemingly. They  
line 8677=>
line 8678=>####-fool about  with boats on that big  river   - and that  isn't  natural. Small 
line 8679=>wonder that trouble came of  it,  I say. But be that as it may, Mr. Frodo is 
line 8680=>as nice a young hobbit  as you could wish to meet. Very much like Mr. Bilbo, 
line 8681=>and in  more than  looks.  After all his  father  was  a Baggins.  A  decent 
line 8682=>respectable hobbit was Mr. Drogo  Baggins; there  was never much to tell  of 
line 8683=>him, till he was drownded.' 
line 8684=>     'Drownded?' said several  voices. They  had heard this and other darker  
line 8685=>rumours before, of course; but  hobbits have a passion  for  family history, 
line 8686=>and they were ready to hear  it again. 'Well, so they say,' said the Gaffer. 
line 8687=>'You see: Mr. Drogo, he married poor Miss  Primula Brandybuck.  She  was 
line 8688=>our 
line 8689=>Mr. Bilbo's first cousin on the mother's side (her mother being the youngest 
line 8690=>of the Old Took's  daughters); and Mr.  Drogo  was his second cousin. So Mr. 
line 8691=>Frodo is his first and second cousin, once removed either way, as the saying 
line 8692=>is,  if  you  follow me.  And Mr. Drogo was  staying at Brandy Hall with his 
line 8693=>father -in-law, old Master Gorbadoc, as he often  did after his marriage (him 
line 8694=>being partial to  his vittles,  and old  Gorbadoc keeping  a mighty generous 
line 8695=>table); and he went out boating on the Brandywine River; and he and his wife 
line 8696=>were drownded, and poor Mr. Frodo only a child and all. ' 
line 8697=>     'I've heard they went on the water after dinner in the moonlight,' said 
line 8698=>Old Noakes; 'and it was Drogo's weight as sunk the boat.' 
line 8699=>     'And I heard she pushed him in, and  he pulled her in after him,'  said 
line 8700=>Sandyman, the Hobbiton miller. 
line 8701=>     'You shouldn't listen  to all you hear, Sandyman,' said the Gaffer, who 
line 8702=>did not much like the miller. 'There isn't no  call to go ta lking of pushing 
line 8703=>and pulling. Boats are quite tricky enough for those that sit  still without 
line 8704=>looking  further for the cause of trouble. Anyway: there was this  Mr. Frodo  
line 8705=>left  an  orphan  and  stranded,  as  you  might   say,  among  those  queer  
line 8706=>Bucklanders,  being brought  up anyhow  in Brandy Hall. A regular warren, by 
line 8707=>all accounts. Old Master Gorbadoc never had fewer than  a couple  of hundred 
line 8708=>relations in  the place.  Mr. Bilbo  never did  a kinder  deed  than when he 
line 8709=>brought the lad back to live among decent folk. 
line 8710=>     'But I  reckon it was a nasty shock for those Sackville-Bagginses. They  
line 8711=>thought  they were going to get Bag End,  that time when he went off and was 
line 8712=>thought to be dead.  And then he comes back and orders them off; and he goes 
line 8713=>on living and living, and never looking a day older, bless him! And suddenly 
line 8714=>he  produces  an  heir,  and  has  all  the  papers  made  out  proper.  The 
line 8715=>
line 8716=>####-Sackville-Bagginses won't never  see the inside of Bag End now, or it  is to 
line 8717=>be hoped not.' 
line 8718=>     'There's a tidy bit of money tucked away up there, I hear tell,' said a  
line 8719=>stranger,  a visitor on  business from  Michel Delving in the  Westfarthing. 
line 8720=>'All the top of  your hill is full of tunnels packed with chests of gold and 
line 8721=>silver, and jools, by what I've heard. ' 
line 8722=>     'Then you've heard  more than I  can speak  to,' answered the Gaffer. I 
line 8723=>know nothing about  jools.  Mr. Bilbo is free with  his money, and there seems 
line 8724=>no lack of it; but I know of no tunnel -making. I  saw Mr. Bilbo when he came 
line 8725=>back, a matter of  sixty  years  ago,  when I was a  lad. I'd  not long come 
line 8726=>prentice to old  Holman (him being my dad's cousin), but he had me up at Bag 
line 8727=>End helping  him  to keep folks from trampling and  trapessing  all over the 
line 8728=>garden while the sale was on. And in the middle of it all Mr. Bilbo comes up 
line 8729=>the Hill  with  a pony and some mighty big  bags and a couple  of  chests. I 
line 8730=>don't  doubt  they were mostly full of treasure  he had picked up in foreign 
line 8731=>parts, where there be mountains of gold, they  say;  but there wasn't enough 
line 8732=>to fill tunnels. But  my lad Sam will know  more about that. He's in and out 
line 8733=>of Bag End. Crazy about stories of the old days he is, and he listens to all 
line 8734=>Mr. Bilbo's  tales. Mr. Bilbo has learned him his letters  - meaning no harm, 
line 8735=>mark you, and I hope no harm will come of it. 
line 8736=>     'Elves and Dragons' I says  to him. 'Cabbages and  potatoes are  better 
line 8737=>for me and  you. Don't go getting mixed up in  the business of your betters, 
line 8738=>or you'll land in trouble  too big for you,' I says  to him. And I might say 
line 8739=>it to others,' he added with a look at the stranger and the miller. 
line 8740=>     But the Gaffer did  not convince  his audience. The  legend  of Bilbo's 
line 8741=>wealth was now too  firmly fixed in the minds  of the  younger generation of  
line 8742=>hobbits. 
line 8743=>     'Ah, but he has likely enough been adding to what he brought at first,' 
line 8744=>argued the miller, voicing common  opinion. 'He's often  away from home. And 
line 8745=>look at the outlandish  folk that visit him:  dwarves  coming at night,  and 
line 8746=>that old wandering conjuror, Gandalf,  and  all. You can say  what you like, 
line 8747=>Gaffer, but Bag End's a queer place, and its folk are queerer.' 
line 8748=>     'And you can say what you like, about what you know no more of than you  
line 8749=>do of boating, Mr. Sandyman,' retorted the Gaffer, disliking the miller even 
line 8750=>more  than usual. If  that's being queer, then we could do  with a bit  more 
line 8751=>queerness in these parts. There's  some  not  far away that wouldn't offer a  
line 8752=>pint of beer to a friend, if they  lived  in  a hole with golden  walls. But 
line 8753=>
line 8754=>####-they do things proper at Bag End. Our  Sam says that  everyone's going to be 
line 8755=>invited to the party, and there's  going to be presents, mark you,  presents 
line 8756=>for all - this very month as is.' 
line 8757=>     That very month  was  September, and as fine as you could ask. A day or  
line 8758=>two  later a rumour (probably  started by the knowledgeable Sam)  was spread 
line 8759=>about  that there were going to be fireworks  - fireworks, what is more, such 
line 8760=>as had not been seen in the Shire for nigh  on a  century, not indeed  since 
line 8761=>the Old Took died. 
line 8762=>     Days passed  and The Day drew nearer.  An odd-looking waggon laden with 
line 8763=>odd-looking packages rolled into Hobbiton one evening and toiled up the Hill 
line 8764=>to  Bag End. The startled hobbits peered out of lamplit doors to gape at it. 
line 8765=>It was driven  by outlandish  folk, singing strange songs: dwarves with long 
line 8766=>beards and deep hoods. A few of them remained at Bag End.  At the end of the 
line 8767=>second week in September a cart came in  through Bywater from the  direction 
line 8768=>of the  Brandywine Bridge in  broad daylight. An old  man was driving it all  
line 8769=>alone.  He  wore a tall pointed blue hat,  a  long grey cloak,  and a silver  
line 8770=>scarf. He  had a long white beard and bushy eyebrows  that stuck  out beyond 
line 8771=>the  brim of  his  hat. Small hobbit-children ran after the cart all through 
line 8772=>Hobbiton and right up the hill. It ha d a cargo of fireworks, as they rightly 
line 8773=>guessed. At Bilbo's front door the old man began to unload: there were great 
line 8774=>bundles of fireworks of all sorts and shapes, each labelled with a large red 
line 8775=>G and the elf-rune, . 
line 8776=>     That was Gandalf's mark, of course,  and the  old man  was Gandalf  the 
line 8777=>Wizard,  whose  fame in the Shire  was  due mainly to  his skill with fires,  
line 8778=>smokes, and lights.  His real business was far more difficult and dangerous, 
line 8779=>but  the Shire-folk knew nothing about  it. To them  he was just one  of the 
line 8780=>'attractions'  at the Party. Hence the excitement of the hobbit-children.  'G  
line 8781=>for Grand!' they  shouted, and the old man smiled.  They knew him by  sight, 
line 8782=>though he only appeared in Hobbiton occasionally and never stopped long; but 
line 8783=>neither they nor  any  but  the  oldest of  their elders had seen one of his 
line 8784=>firework displays  - they now belonged to the legendary past. 
line 8785=>     When the old  man,  helped by  Bilbo  and  some  dwarves,  had finished  
line 8786=>unloading. Bilbo gave a few pennies away; but not a single squib or  cracker  
line 8787=>was forthcoming, to the disappointment of the onlookers.  
line 8788=>     'Run  away now!' said  Gandalf.  'You  will  get plenty  when  the time 
line 8789=>comes.' Then he disappeared inside with Bilbo, and the door  was  shut.  The 
line 8790=>young  hobbits  stared at  the door  in vain for a while, and then made off, 
line 8791=>
line 8792=>####-feeling that the day of the party would never come. 
line 8793=>     Inside Bag End, Bilbo and Gandalf were sitting at the open window  of a  
line 8794=>small room looking out west on to the garden.  The late afternoon was br ight  
line 8795=>and   peaceful.  The  flowers  glowed   red  and  golden:  snap-dragons  and 
line 8796=>sun-flowers, and nasturtiums trailing all over the turf walls and peeping in 
line 8797=>at the round windows.  
line 8798=>     'How bright your garden looks!' said Gandalf. 
line 8799=>     'Yes,' said Bilbo. I am very fond indeed of it, and of all the dear old 
line 8800=>Shire; but I think I need a holiday.' 
line 8801=>     'You mean to go on with your plan then?' 
line 8802=>     'I do. I made up my mind months ago, and I haven't changed it.' 
line 8803=>     'Very  well.  It is no good saying any  more.  Stick to your plan  - your 
line 8804=>whole plan, mind  - and I hope it will turn out for the best, for  you,  and 
line 8805=>for all of us.' 
line 8806=>     'I hope  so.  Anyway  I mean to enjoy  myself on Thursday, and  have my 
line 8807=>little joke.' 
line 8808=>     'Who will laugh, I wonder?' said Gandalf, shaking his head. 
line 8809=>     'We shall see,' said Bilbo. 
line 8810=>     The next day more carts rolled up the Hill, and still more carts. There 
line 8811=>might have  been  some grumbling about 'dealing locally', but that very week 
line 8812=>orders began to pour out of Bag End for every  kind of provision, commodity, 
line 8813=>or luxury  that  could be obtained in Hobbiton or Bywater or anywhere in the 
line 8814=>neighbourhood.  People  became enthusiastic; and they began to tick off  the 
line 8815=>days on  the calendar; and they watched eagerly for the  postman, hoping for  
line 8816=>invitations.  
line 8817=>     Before long  the  invitations  began  pouring  out,  and  the  Hobbiton 
line 8818=>post-office  was blocked, and the Bywater post -office  was snowed under, and 
line 8819=>voluntary assistant postmen were called for.  There was a constant stream of 
line 8820=>them going up the Hill, carrying hundreds of polite variations on Thank you, 
line 8821=>I shall certainly come. 
line 8822=>     A notice appeared on the gate at Bag End: NO ADMITTANCE EXCEPT 
line 8823=>ON PARTY 
line 8824=>BUSINESS. Even those  who had, or  pretended  to  have  Party  Business were 
line 8825=>seldom allowed inside. Bilbo  was  busy:  writing invitations,  ticking  off 
line 8826=>answers, packing up presents, and making  some  private preparations  of his 
line 8827=>own. From the time of Gandalf's arrival he remained hidden from view.  
line 8828=>     One morning the hobbits woke to find  the large field,  south of Bilbo's 
line 8829=>
line 8830=>####-front door, covered with ropes and poles for tents  and pavilions. A special 
line 8831=>entrance  was cut into the bank leading to  the road, and wide steps  and  a  
line 8832=>large white gate were built there. The three hobbit-families of Bagshot Row,  
line 8833=>adjoining the field, were intensely  interested  and  generally envied.  Old 
line 8834=>Gaffer Gamgee stopped even pretending to work in his garden. 
line 8835=>     The tents began to  go up. There was a specially large pavilion, so big 
line 8836=>that the tree that grew in the   field was right inside it, and stood proudly 
line 8837=>near one end, at the head of  the chief table. Lanterns were hung on all its 
line 8838=>branches. More  promising still (to the hobbits' mind): an enormous open-air  
line 8839=>kitchen was erected in the  north corner of  the field. A draught  of cooks, 
line 8840=>from every inn and eating-house  for miles around, arrived to supplement the 
line 8841=>dwarves and other odd  folk  that were quartered at Bag End. Excitement rose 
line 8842=>to its height. 
line 8843=>     Then the weather  clouded  over.  That was on Wednesday the  eve of the  
line 8844=>Party.  Anxiety was  intense. Then Thursday,  September  the 22nd,  actually 
line 8845=>dawned. The sun got up, the clouds vanished, flags were unfurled and the fun 
line 8846=>began. 
line 8847=>     Bilbo  Baggins called it  a  party,  but it  was really  a  variety  of 
line 8848=>entertainments  rolled  into one.  Practically  everybody  living  near  was 
line 8849=>invited. A very few were overlooked  by accident, but  as they turned up all 
line 8850=>the same, that did not matter.  Many people  from other parts of  the  Shire 
line 8851=>were also asked; and there were even  a few from outside the  borders. Bilbo  
line 8852=>met the guests (and additions) at the new white gate in person. He gave away 
line 8853=>presents to all and sundry - the latter were  those  who went out again by a  
line 8854=>back way  and came  in  again by  the gate. Hobbits give   presents  to other  
line 8855=>people  on their own birthdays. Not very expensive ones, as a  rule, and not 
line 8856=>so lavishly  as on this  occasion; but it was  not a bad system. Actually in 
line 8857=>Hobbiton  and Bywater every  day in the year it was somebody's  birthday, so 
line 8858=>that every  hobbit  in those parts had a fair chance of at least one present 
line 8859=>at least once a week. But they never got tired of them. 
line 8860=>     On this occasion the presents were unusually  good. The hobbit-children 
line 8861=>were so excited that for a while they almost forgot  about eating. There were 
line 8862=>toys the like  of which they had  never seen before, all beautiful and  some 
line 8863=>obviously magical.  Many of them had indeed been ordered a year before,  and 
line 8864=>had  come  all  the way  from  the Mountain and from Dale, and  were of real 
line 8865=>dwarf-make. 
line 8866=>     When  every guest had been  welcomed  and was finally inside the  gate,  
line 8867=>
line 8868=>####-there were  songs, dances, music, games,  and,  of course,  food  and drink. 
line 8869=>There were  three  official  meals: lunch,  tea, and dinner (or supper). But 
line 8870=>lunch and  tea were marked chiefly by  the fact that at  those times all the 
line 8871=>guests  were sitting  down and eating together. At  other  times  there were 
line 8872=>merely lots  of  people  eating and drinking  -  continuously from elevenses 
line 8873=>until six-thirty, when the fireworks  started. 
line 8874=>     The fireworks were by Gandalf: they were not only brought  by  him, but 
line 8875=>designed and made by  him; and the  special effects, set pieces, and flights 
line 8876=>of rockets were let off by him. But  there was  also a generous distribution 
line 8877=>of  squibs,  crackers,  backarappers,   sparklers,  torches,  dwarf-candles,  
line 8878=>elf-fountains, goblin-barkers  and thunder -claps. They  were all superb. The 
line 8879=>art of Gandalf improved with age. 
line 8880=>     There were  rockets like  a flight  of scintillating birds singing with 
line 8881=>sweet voices. There were green trees with trunks of dark smoke: their leaves  
line 8882=>opened like a whole spring unfolding in a moment, and their shining branches 
line 8883=>dropped glowing flowers down upon the  astonished hobbits, disappearing with 
line 8884=>a  sweet  scent just  before they touched  their  upturned faces. There were 
line 8885=>fountains  of butterflies that flew  glittering into  the trees;  there were 
line 8886=>pillars  of  coloured  fires that rose  and  turned into eagles, or  sailing 
line 8887=>ships,  or  a  phalanx of flying swans; there was a red  thunderstorm  and a  
line 8888=>shower  of  yellow  rain; there was a  forest  of silver spears  that sprang 
line 8889=>suddenly  into the  air with a  yell like an embattled  army, and came  down 
line 8890=>again into the Water with a hiss like a  hundred hot snakes.  And there  was 
line 8891=>also one last surprise,  in  honour of Bilbo,  and  it startled  the hobbits 
line 8892=>exceedingly, as  Gandalf intended. The lights went out. A great  smoke  went 
line 8893=>up. It shaped itself like a mountain seen in the distance, and began to glow 
line 8894=>at  the summit. It spouted green  and scarlet flames. Out flew a  red-golden 
line 8895=>dragon - not life-size, but terribly life-like: fire came from his jaws, his 
line 8896=>eyes glared down; there  was  a  roar, and he whizzed three  times  over the 
line 8897=>heads of the crowd. They all ducked, and  many fell fla t on their faces. The 
line 8898=>dragon passed like an  express train,  turned a  somersault, and  burst over  
line 8899=>Bywater with a deafening explosion. 
line 8900=>     'That is  the  signal for  supper!'  said  Bilbo.  The  pain  and alarm 
line 8901=>vanished at once, and the prostrate hobbits  leaped to their feet. There  was 
line 8902=>a splendid supper for everyone; for everyone, that  is, except those invited 
line 8903=>to the special family dinner -party. This was held in the great pavilion with 
line 8904=>the tree. The invitations were limited to twelve dozen (a number also called 
line 8905=>
line 8906=>####-by the hobbits one Gross, though  the  word was not considered proper to use 
line 8907=>of people); and  the  guests were selected  from  all  the families to which 
line 8908=>Bilbo and Frodo were related, with  the addition of a  few special unrelated 
line 8909=>friends (such as Gandalf). Many young hobbits  were included, and present by 
line 8910=>parental permission; for hobbits were easy-going with their children in  the 
line 8911=>matter  of  sitting up late,  especially when there  was a chance of getting 
line 8912=>them a free meal. Bringing up young hobbits took a lot of provender. 
line 8913=>     There  were  many  Bagginses  and  Boffins,  and also  many  Tooks  and 
line 8914=>Brandybucks;  there  were  various  Grubbs   (relations  of  Bilbo  Baggins' 
line 8915=>grandmother), and various Chubbs (connexions of his Took grandfather); and a 
line 8916=>selection  of  Burrowses,  Bolgers, Bracegirdles,  Brockhouses,  Goodbodies, 
line 8917=>Hornblowers and Proudfoots. Some of these were only very distantly 
line 8918=>connected 
line 8919=>with Bilbo, and  some of them  had hardly ever  been in Hobbiton before,  as 
line 8920=>they lived in remote corners of the Shire. The Sackville-Bagginses  were not 
line 8921=>forgotten.  Otho and his wife Lobelia were present. They disliked Bilbo  and 
line 8922=>detested Frodo,  but  so magnificent  was the invitation  card,  written  in 
line 8923=>golden ink, that  they had felt it was impossible to refuse. Besides,  their 
line 8924=>cousin, Bilbo, had been specializing  in  food for many years and  his table 
line 8925=>had a high reputation. 
line 8926=>     All  the  one hundred  and forty-four guests expected a pleasant feast; 
line 8927=>though they  rather  dreaded  the  after -dinner  speech  of their  host  (an 
line 8928=>inevitable item). He was liable to drag  in bits of  what he  called poetry; 
line 8929=>and sometimes, after  a glass or two, would  allude to the absurd adventures 
line 8930=>of his mysterious journey. The guests were not disappointed: they had a very 
line 8931=>pleasant feast, in fact an engrossing entertainment: rich, abundant, varied, 
line 8932=>and prolonged. The  purchase of provisions fell almost to nothing throughout 
line 8933=>the district in the ensuing weeks; but as Bilbo's catering had  depleted the 
line 8934=>stocks of most stores, cellars and warehouses for miles around, that did not 
line 8935=>matter much. 
line 8936=>     After  the feast (more or less) came the  Speech. Most of  the  company 
line 8937=>were, however, now in a tolerant  mood, at that  delightful stage which they 
line 8938=>called 'filling up  the corners'.  They were sipping their favourite drinks,  
line 8939=>and nibbling at  their favourite  dainties, and their fears  were forgotten. 
line 8940=>They were prepared to listen to anything, and to cheer at every full stop. 
line 8941=>     My dear People, began Bilbo, rising in  his  place. 'Hear! Hear! Hear!' 
line 8942=>they shouted,  and  kept on repeating  it  in chorus,  seeming  reluctant to 
line 8943=>
line 8944=>####-follow their own advice. Bilbo left  his place and went and stood on a chair 
line 8945=>under the illuminated  tree. The  light of the lanterns fell on his  beaming 
line 8946=>face; the golden buttons shone on his embroidered silk waistcoat. They could 
line 8947=>all see  him standing,  waving  one hand in  the air,  the other  was in his 
line 8948=>trouser-pocket. 
line 8949=>     My dear Bagginses and Boffins, he began again;  and my  dear  Tooks and 
line 8950=>Brandybucks, and Grubbs,  and  Chubbs,  and Burrowses,  and Hornblowers, 
line 8951=>and 
line 8952=>Bolgers, Bracegirdles, Goodbodies, Brockhouses and Proudfoots.  
line 8953=>'ProudFEET!' 
line 8954=>shouted  an  elderly  hobbit  from  the back  of the pavilion.  His name, of 
line 8955=>course, was  Proudfoot, and well merited; his feet were large, exceptionally 
line 8956=>furry, and both were on the table. 
line 8957=>     Proudfoots,  repeated Bilbo. Also my  good  Sackville -Bagginses that  I 
line 8958=>welcome  back at last  to  Bag  End. Today  is my  one  hundred and eleventh  
line 8959=>birthday: I am eleventy -one  today! 'Hurray!  Hurray! Many  Happy  Returns!' 
line 8960=>they  shouted, and they  hammered  joyously  on the tables.  Bilbo was doing 
line 8961=>splendidly. This was the sort of stuff they liked: short and obvious.  
line 8962=>     / hope you  are  all  enjoying yourselves as much as  I  am.  Deafening 
line 8963=>cheers. Cries  of  Yes  (and  No). Noises  of trumpets and horns, pipes  and 
line 8964=>flutes,  and  other musical instruments.  There were, as has been said, many 
line 8965=>young hobbits present. Hundreds of musical crackers had been pulled. Most of 
line 8966=>them bore the  mark DALE  on them; which did not  convey much to most of 
line 8967=>the 
line 8968=>hobbits, but they all agreed they were  marvellous crackers.  They contained 
line 8969=>instruments, small, but of perfect make and enchanting tones. Indeed, in one 
line 8970=>corner some of  the young Tooks and  Brandybucks, supposing Uncle  Bilbo  to 
line 8971=>have finished (since he had plainly said all that was necessary), now got up 
line 8972=>an impromptu orchestra, and began a  merry dance-tune.  Master  Everard Took  
line 8973=>and  Miss Melilot Brandybuck  got on a  table  and with bells in their hands 
line 8974=>began to dance the Springle-ring: a pretty dance, but rather vigorous. 
line 8975=>     But Bilbo had not finished. Seizing a horn from a youngster near by, he 
line 8976=>blew  three loud  hoots. The noise subsided. /  shall not keep you  long, he 
line 8977=>cried. Cheers from all the assembly. /  have called  you all  together for a  
line 8978=>Purpose. Something in  the way  that he said this made an impression.  There 
line 8979=>was almost silence, and one or two of the Tooks pricked up their ears. 
line 8980=>     Indeed,  for  Three  Purposes! First of  all,  to  tell  you that  I am 
line 8981=>
line 8982=>####-immensely fond  of  you all, and that eleventy -one years is too short a time 
line 8983=>to live among such  excellent and  admirable hobbits. Tremendous outburst of 
line 8984=>approval. 
line 8985=>     / don't know half of you half as well as I should like; and I like less 
line 8986=>than half of you half as well as you deserve. This was unexpected and rather  
line 8987=>difficult. There  was some scattered clapping, but most of  them were trying 
line 8988=>to work it out and see if it came to a compliment. 
line 8989=>     Secondly,  to  celebrate my birthday.  Cheers again.  / should say: OUR 
line 8990=>birthday.  For it  is, of  course, also the birthday of my  heir and nephew,  
line 8991=>Frodo.  He comes  of  age  and into his inheritance today. Some  perfunctory 
line 8992=>clapping by the  elders;  and some loud  shouts of 'Frodo!  Frodo! Jolly old 
line 8993=>Frodo,' from the juniors. The Sackville-Bagginses scowled, and wondered what 
line 8994=>was  meant by 'coming  into his inheritance'. Together we score one  hundred  
line 8995=>and forty -four.  Your numbers were chosen to  fit this remarkable total: One 
line 8996=>Gross, if I  may use the  expression. No cheers. This was ridiculous. Many of 
line 8997=>his guests, and especially  the Sackville-Bagginses, were insulted,  feeling 
line 8998=>sure they had only been asked to fill up the  required number, like goods in 
line 8999=>a package. 'One Gross, indeed! Vulgar expression.' 
line 9000=>     It is also,  if  I  may be  allowed to  refer to  ancient history,  the 
line 9001=>anniversary of my arrival by barrel at Esgaroth on the Long Lake; though the 
line 9002=>fact that it was  my birthday slipped  my memory on that occasion. I was only  
line 9003=>fifty-one  then,  and birthdays did  not seem so important.  The banquet was  
line 9004=>very splendid, however, though I had a bad cold at the time, I remember, and 
line 9005=>could only say 'thag you very  buch'. I now repeat  it more correctly: Thank 
line 9006=>you  very  much for coming  to my little party. Obstinate  silence. They all  
line 9007=>feared that  a song or some poetry was now imminent;  and they  were getting 
line 9008=>bored. Why couldn't he stop talking and let them drink his health? But Bilbo  
line 9009=>did not sing or recite. He paused for a moment. 
line 9010=>     Thirdly  and finally, he said,  I wish to make an ANNOUNCEMENT. He 
line 9011=>spoke 
line 9012=>this last word so  loudly and suddenly that everyone sat up who still could. 
line 9013=>I regret to announce that - though, as I said, eleventy -one years is far too 
line 9014=>short a time to spend among you - this is the END. I am going. I  am leaving 
line 9015=>NOW. GOOD-BYE! 
line 9016=>     He stepped down and  vanished. There was a blinding flash of light, and 
line 9017=>the guests  all blinked. When they opened their eyes Bilbo was nowhere to be 
line 9018=>seen. One hundred  and forty-four flabbergasted hobbits sat back speechless.  
line 9019=>
line 9020=>####-Old  Odo Proudfoot  removed his feet from the table and stamped. Then  there 
line 9021=>was  a  dead  silence,  until  suddenly, after  several deep breaths,  every 
line 9022=>Baggins,  Boffin,   Took,   Brandybuck,   Grubb,  Chubb,  Burrows,   Bolger, 
