line 9026=>     It  was generally agreed that the joke was  in very bad taste, and more 
line 9027=>food and drink were needed to cure the guests  of shock and annoyance. 'He's 
line 9028=>mad. I always said so,'  was probably  the  most  popular comment.  Even the 
line 9029=>Tooks (with a few exceptions) thought  Bilbo's behaviour was absurd. For the 
line 9030=>moment most of  them took it for granted that his disappearance was  nothing 
line 9031=>more than a ridiculous prank. 
line 9032=>     But old Rory Brandybuck was not  so sure. Neither age  nor an  enormous 
line 9033=>dinner  had clouded his wits, and he said to his daughter -in-law, Esmeralda: 
line 9034=>'There's something fishy in this, my dear! I believe that mad Baggins is off 
line 9035=>again. Silly old fool. But why worry? He hasn't taken the vittles with him.' 
line 9036=>He called loudly to Frodo to send the wine round again. 
line 9037=>     Frodo  was the only one present who had said nothing. For some time  he 
line 9038=>had  sat silent  beside  Bilbo's  empty  chair,  and ignored all remarks and 
line 9039=>questions. He had enjoyed the  joke,  of course, even  though he had been in 
