line 9320=>     This  is  only  a  small  selection of  the assembled presents. Bilbo's 
line 9321=>residence had got rather cluttered up  with things in the course of his long 
line 9322=>
line 9323=>####-life.  It was a  tendency of hobbit-holes to get cluttered up: for which the 
line 9324=>custom of giving so many birthday-presents was largely responsible.  Not, of 
line 9325=>course,  that the  birthday-presents  were always new,  there were one or two 
line 9326=>old mathoms  of forgotten uses that had circulated all around  the district; 
line 9327=>but Bilbo had usually given new presents, and  kept  those that he received. 
line 9328=>The old hole was now being cleared a little. 
line 9329=>     Every  one  of  the various  parting  gifts  had  labels,  written  out 
line 9330=>personally  by Bilbo,  and several had some point,  or  some  joke.  But, of 
line 9331=>course,  most  of the  things were  given where  they  would  be  wanted and 
line 9332=>welcome. The  poorer hobbits, and especially  those of Bagshot Row, did very 
line 9333=>well. Old Gaffer  Gamgee got  two sacks of potatoes, a new spade, a  woollen 
line 9334=>waistcoat,  and  a   bottle  of  ointment  for  creaking  joints.  Old  Rory 
line 9335=>Brandybuck,  in  return  for  much  hospitality, got a dozen  bottles of Old 
line 9336=>Winyards: a strong red wine from the Southfarthing, and now quite mature, as 
line 9337=>it had been laid down by Bilbo's father. Rory quite forgave Bilbo, and voted 
line 9338=>him a capital fellow after the first bottle. 
line 9339=>     There was plenty of everything left for Frodo.  And, of course, all the 
line 9340=>chief  treasures, as well  as  the  books,  pictures, and  more than  enough 
line 9341=>furniture,  were  left  in his possession. There was,  however, no sign  nor  
line 9342=>mention of money or jewellery: not a  penny-piece or  a glass bead was given 
