line 9344=>     Frodo had a  very  trying time that afternoon. A fa lse rumour  that the 
line 9345=>whole household was being distributed free spread like wildfire; and  before 
line 9346=>long  the place was packed with  people who had no business there, but could 
line 9347=>not be kept out. Labels got torn off and mixed, and quarrels broke out. Some  
line 9348=>people tried to do swaps and deals in the hall; and others tried to make off 
line 9349=>with minor  items not  addressed to  them,  or  with  anything  that  seemed 
line 9350=>unwanted  or unwatched.  The road to the gate  was blocked  with barrows and 
line 9351=>handcarts.  
line 9352=>     In the middle of  the  commotion the Sackville-Bagginses arrived. Frodo  
line 9353=>had retired for a while and left his  friend Merry Brandybuck to keep an eye 
line 9354=>on things. When Otho loudly demanded to see Frodo, Merry bowed politely.  
line 9355=>     'He is indisposed,' he said. 'He is resting.' 
line 9356=>     'Hiding, you mean,'  said  Lobelia. 'Anyway we want  to see him and  we 
line 9357=>mean to see him. Just go and tell him so!' 
line 9358=>     Merry left them a long while in the hall, and they had time to discover  
line 9359=>their parting gift  of spoons. It did  not improve their tempers. Eventually 
line 9360=>
line 9361=>####-they were shown into the study. Frodo was sitting at a  table with a lot  of 
line 9362=>papers in front of him. He looked indisposed - to see Sackville-Bagginses at 
line 9363=>any  rate;  and he stood up,  fidgeting with something in his pocket. But he 
line 9364=>spoke quite politely. 
line 9365=>     The Sackville-Bagginses were  rather offensive. They began  by offering 
line 9366=>him  bad  bargain-prices  (as between  friends)  for  various  valuable  and 
line 9367=>unlabelled  things.  When  Frodo  replied  that  only  the  things specially 
line 9368=>directed by Bilbo were being given away, they said the whole affair was very 
line 9369=>fishy. 
line 9370=>     'Only one thing  is clear to me,' said Otho, 'and that  is that you are 
line 9371=>doing exceedingly well out of it. I insist on seeing the will.' 
line 9372=>     Otho would  have been Bilbo's heir, but for  the  adoption of Frodo. He 
line 9373=>read the will carefully and  snorted. It was,  unfortunately, very clear and 
line 9374=>correct (according to the legal customs of hobbits, which demand among other  
line 9375=>things seven signatures of witnesses in red ink). 
line 9376=>     'Foiled again!' he said  to his  wife. 'And after waiting sixty   years.  
line 9377=>Spoons? Fiddlesticks!' He snapped his fingers under Frodo's nose and slumped 
line 9378=>off. But Lobelia was not so easily got rid of. A little later Frodo came out 
line 9379=>of the study  to see how things were going  on and found her still about the 
line 9380=>place, investigating nooks  and comers and  tapping the  floors. He escorted 
line 9381=>her firmly off the premises, after he had relieved her of several small (but 
line 9382=>rather valuable) articles that had somehow fallen inside  her umbrella.  Her  
line 9383=>face looked as if  she was in the throes of thinking out a  really  crushing 
line 9384=>parting remark; but all she found to say, turning round on the step, was:  
line 9385=>     'You'll live to regret  it, young  fellow! Why  didn't you  go too? You  
line 9386=>don't belong here; you're no Baggins  - you - you're a Brandybuck!' 
line 9387=>     'Did you hear that, Merry? That was an insult, if you like,' said Frodo 
line 9388=>as he shut the door on her. 
line 9389=>     'It was a compliment,' said Merry  Brandybuck, 'and so, of  course, not 
line 9390=>true.' 
line 9391=>     Then they went  round the hole,  and  evicted three  young hobbits (two 
line 9392=>Boffins and a Bolger) who were knocking  holes  in the  walls  of one of the 
line 9393=>cellars.  Frodo  also had a  tussle  with young Sancho  Proudfoot  (old  Odo 
line 9394=>Proudfoot's  grandson),  who had  begun an  excavation in the larger pantry, 
line 9395=>where  he thought there was an echo. The legend of Bilbo's gold excited both 
line 9396=>curiosity  and  hope;  for legendary  gold  (mysteriously obtained,  if  not  
line 9397=>positively ill-gotten), is, as every  one  knows, any one's for  the  finding 
line 9398=>
line 9399=>####--unless the search is interrupted. 
line 9400=>     When he had overcome  Sancho and  pushed him out, Frodo  collapsed on a  
line 9401=>chair in the hall. It's time to  close the shop, Merry,'  he said. 'Lock the 
line 9402=>door, and don't open it to anyone today,  not even if they bring a battering 
line 9403=>ram.' Then he went to revive himself with a belated cup of tea. 
line 9404=>     He had hardly sat down, when there came a soft knock at the front-door. 
line 9405=>'Lobelia again most likely,' he thought. 'She must have thought of something 
line 9406=>really nasty, and have come back again to say it. It can wait.' 
line 9407=>     He went on  with his tea.  The knock was repeated,  much louder, but he 
line 9408=>took no notice. Suddenly the wizard's head appeared at the window.  
line 9409=>     'If you don't let me in, Frodo, I  shall blow your door right down your 
line 9410=>hole and out through the hill,' he said. 
line 9411=>     'My dear Gandalf! Half a  minute!' cried Frodo, running out of the room 
line 9412=>to the door. 'Come in! Come in! I thought it was Lobelia.' 
line 9413=>     'Then I  forgive you.  But I saw her some time ago, driving a pony-trap 
line 9414=>towards Bywater with a face that would have curdled new milk.' 
line 9415=>     'She had already nearly curdled me. Honestly, I nearly tried on Bilbo's 
line 9416=>ring. I longed to disappear.' 
line 9417=>     'Don't do that!'  said  Gandalf, sitting down. 'Do be  careful of  that 
line 9418=>ring, Frodo! In fact, it is partly about that that I have come to say a last 
line 9419=>word.' 
line 9420=>     'Well, what about it?' 
line 9421=>     'What do you know already?' 
line 9422=>     'Only  what Bilbo told me. I have heard his story: how he found it, and 
line 9423=>how he used it: on his journey, I mean.' 
line 9424=>     'Which story, I wonder,' said Gandalf.  
line 9425=>     'Oh, not what he told the dwarves and put in his book,' said Frodo. 'He 
line 9426=>told me  the  true story  soon after I  came to live here.  He said  you had 
line 9427=>pestered him till he told you, so I had better know too. "No secrets between 
line 9428=>us,  Frodo,"  he  said;  "but  they are not  to go  any  further. It's  mine 
line 9429=>anyway."' 
line 9430=>     'That's interesting,' said Gandalf.  'Well,  what did  you  think of it 
line 9431=>all?' 
line 9432=>     'If you mean, inventing all that about a "present",  well, I thought the 
line 9433=>true story much more likely, and I  couldn't see the point of altering it at 
line 9434=>all. It was very  unlike Bilbo to do  so,  anyway; and I thought  it  rather  
line 9435=>odd.' 
line 9436=>
line 9437=>####-     'So did I. But odd things may happen to people that have such treasures 
line 9438=>- if  they use them. Let it be a warning to you to be very careful  with it. 
line 9439=>It may have other powers than just making you vanish when you wish to.' 
line 9440=>     'I don't understand,' said Frodo. 
line 9441=>     'Neither do I,'  answered  the wizard. 'I have  merely begun  to wonder  
line 9442=>about the ring,  especially since last night. No need to worry.  But if  you  
line 9443=>take my  advice you will use it very  seldom, or not at  all. At least I beg 
line 9444=>you not  to use it in any way that will cause talk or rouse suspicion. I say 
line 9445=>again: keep it safe, and keep it secret!' 
line 9446=>     'You are very mysterious! What are you afraid of?' 
line 9447=>     'I am not certain, so I  will say no  more. I may  be able to  tell you  
line 9448=>something  when I come back. I am going off at once: so this is good-bye for 
line 9449=>the present.' He got up. 
line 9450=>     'At  once!' cried Frodo.  'Why,  I thought  you were staying  on for at 
line 9451=>least a week. I was looking forward to your help.' 
line 9452=>     'I did mean to  - but I have had to change my mind. I  may be away for a  
line 9453=>good while;  but  I'll come and see you again, as soon  as I  can. Expect me 
line 9454=>when you see me! I shall  slip in quietly.  I  shan't often be visiting  the 
line 9455=>Shire openly again.  I find that I have become rather unpopular. They  say I 
line 9456=>am a  nuisance  and  a  disturber  of the  peace. Some people  are  actually 
line 9457=>accusing me of spiriting Bilbo away, or worse. If you want to know, there is 
line 9458=>supposed to be a plot between you and me to get hold of his wealth.' 
line 9459=>     'Some  people!'  exclaimed Frodo.  'You  mean  Otho  and  Lobelia.  How 
line 9460=>abominable!  I would give  them Bag  End and everything else, if I could get  
line 9461=>Bilbo back  and go off tramping in the country with  him. I  love the Shire. 
line 9462=>But I begin to  wish, somehow, that I had gone too. I wonder if I shall ever  
line 9463=>see him again.' 
line 9464=>     'So do I,' said Gandalf. 'And  I wonder many other things. Good-bye now!  
line 9465=>Take  care  of  yourself!  Look out  for  me, especially at  unlikely times!  
line 9466=>Good-bye!' 
line 9467=>     Frodo saw him to the door. He gave a final wave of his hand, and walked 
line 9468=>off at a surprising pace; but Frodo  thought the  old wizard looked unusually 
line 9469=>bent, almost  as if  he was carrying a great weight. The evening was closing 
line 9470=>in, and his cloaked figure quickly vanished into the twilight. Frodo did not 
line 9471=>see him again for a long time. 
line 9472=> 
line 9473=> 
line 9474=>
line 9475=>####-<h4>Chapter 2.</h4> <br> The Shadow of the Past 
line 9476=>
line 9477=> 
line 9478=> 
line 9479=>     The talk did not die down in nine  or even ninety-nine days. The second 
line 9480=>disappearance of Mr. Bilbo Baggins was discussed in Hobbiton, and indeed all 
line 9481=>over the Shire,  for a year  and a day,  and was remembered much longer than 
line 9482=>that.  It became  a fireside -story for  young  hobbits;  and eventually  Mad 
line 9483=>Baggins,  who used to vanish with a  bang and a flash and reappear with bags 
line 9484=>of jewels and gold, became a favourite character of legend and lived on long  
line 9485=>after all the true events were forgotten. 
line 9486=>     But in the meantime, the general opinion in the  neighbourhood was that 
line 9487=>Bilbo, who  had always been rather cracked, had at  last gone quite mad, and  
line 9488=>had run off into the Blue. There he had  undoubtedly fallen into a pool or a  
line 9489=>river and  come to a tragic,  but  hardly an  untimely, end.  The blame  was 
line 9490=>mostly laid on Gandalf. 
line 9491=>     'If only that  dratted  wizard will leave young  Frodo  alone,  perhaps 
line 9492=>he'll  settle  down  and  grow some  hobbit-sense,'  they said. And  to  all 
line 9493=>appearance the wizard did leave Frodo alone, and he did settle down, but the  
line 9494=>growth of hobbit-sense was not very noticeable. Indeed, he at once  began to  
line 9495=>carry on Bilbo's reputation for oddity. He  refused to go into mourning; and 
line 9496=>the next  year  he gave a party  in  honour of  Bilbo's  hundred-and-twelfth 
line 9497=>birthday, which he  called Hundred-weight Feast. But that was  short  of the 
line 9498=>mark, for twenty guests were invited  and  there were several meals at which  
line 9499=>it snowed food and rained drink, as hobbits say. 
line 9500=>     Some people were rather shocked; but Frodo kept up the custom of giving 
line 9501=>Bilbo's  Birthday Party year after year  until  they got used to it. He said 
line 9502=>that he did not think Bilbo  was dead. When  they asked: 'Where is he then?' 
line 9503=>he shrugged his shoulders. 
line 9504=>     He lived  alone, as Bilbo had done; but he  had  a  good  many friends, 
line 9505=>especially among  the younger hobbits  (mostly descendants  of the Old Took) 
line 9506=>who  had  as children been fond of  Bilbo  and often in and out of Bag  End.  
line 9507=>Folco Boffin and Fredegar  Bolger were two of these; but his closest friends 
line 9508=>were Peregrin Took (usually called Pippin),  and Merry Brandybuck  (his real 
line 9509=>name was Meriadoc, but  that was seldom remembered). Frodo went tramping 
line 9510=>all 
line 9511=>over  the Shire with them; but more often he wandered by himself, and to the 
line 9512=>amazement of  sensible folk he was sometimes  seen far  from home walking in 
line 9513=>
line 9514=>####-the hills and woods under the starlight.  Merry and Pippin suspected that he 
line 9515=>visited the Elves at times, as Bilbo had done. 
line 9516=>     As time went on, people began to notice that Frodo also showed signs of 
line 9517=>good 'preservation':  outwardly he retained the appearance  of a  robust and 
line 9518=>energetic hobbit just out of his tweens. 'Some folk have all the luck,' they 
line 9519=>said;  but it was not until Frodo approached the  usually more  sober age of 
line 9520=>fifty that they began to think it queer. 
line 9521=>     Frodo himself, after the first shock, found  that being his  own master  
line 9522=>and the Mr. Baggins of Bag End  was rather  pleasant. For some  years he was 
line 9523=>quite  happy and did not  worry much about the  future. But half unknown  to 
line 9524=>himself the regret that he had not gone with Bilbo was  steadily growing. He 
line 9525=>found himself  wondering at times,  especially in the autumn, about the wild 
line 9526=>lands, and strange visions of mountains that he had never seen came into his 
line 9527=>dreams. He began to sa y to himself: 'Perhaps I shall cross the  River myself 
line 9528=>one day.' To which the other half of his mind always replied: 'Not yet.' 
line 9529=>     So it  went on,  until his forties were  running  out, and his fiftieth 
line 9530=>birthday  was  drawing  near:  fifty  was a number   that he felt was somehow 
line 9531=>significant (or ominous); it was at any  rate at that age that adventure had 
line 9532=>suddenly  befallen  Bilbo. Frodo began to feel  restless, and the  old paths 
line 9533=>seemed too well-trodden. He  looked at maps, and  wondered  what lay  beyond 
line 9534=>their edges: maps made  in the Shire showed  mostly  white spaces beyond its 
line 9535=>borders.  He took to wandering further afield and more often by himself; and 
line 9536=>Merry and his other friends watched him anxiously. Often he was seen walking 
line 9537=>and talking with the strange  wayfarers that began at this time to appear in 
line 9538=>the Shire. 
line 9539=>     There were rumours of  strange things happening in the  world  outside; 
line 9540=>and as Gandalf had not at that time appeared or sent any message for several 
line 9541=>years, Frodo gathered all the news he could. Elves, who seldom walked in the 
line 9542=>Shire, could  now be seen passing westward through the woods in the evening, 
line 9543=>passing and  not returning; but they were leaving Middle-earth and  were  no  
line 9544=>longer concerned with its troubles. There were, however, dwarves on the road 
line 9545=>in  unusual numbers. The ancient East -West Road ran through the Shire to its 
line 9546=>end at the Grey Havens, and dwarves had always used it on their way to their 
line 9547=>mines in the Blue Mountains. They  were the  hobbits' chief  source of  news 
line 9548=>from distant parts  - if they  wanted any: as a rule  dwarves said little and 
line 9549=>hobbits  asked  no  more.  But now Frodo  often met strange dwarves  of  far  
line 9550=>countries, seeking refuge in the West. They were troubled, and some spoke in 
line 9551=>
line 9552=>####-whispers of the Enemy and of the Land of Mordor. 
line 9553=>     That name  the hobbits  only knew in legends  of the  dark past, like a  
line 9554=>shadow  in  the  background  of their  memories;  but  it  was  ominous  and 
line 9555=>disquieting. It seemed that the  evil power in Mirkwood had been  driven out 
line 9556=>by the White Council  only  to  reappear  in  greater  strength  in the  old 
line 9557=>strongholds of Mordor. The  Dark Tower had been rebuilt,  it was  said. From 
line 9558=>there the  power was spreading far and  wide,  and away far  east  and south 
line 9559=>there were  wars and  growing  fear.  Orcs were  multiplying  again  in  the  
line 9560=>mountains. Trolls were abroad, no longer dull-witted, but  cunning and armed 
line 9561=>with  dreadful  weapons.  And there  were  murmured  hints of creatures more 
line 9562=>terrible than all these, but they had no name. 
line 9563=>     Little of all this,  of  course, reached the ears of  ordinary hobbits. 
line 9564=>But  even the deafest  and most stay-at-home began to hear queer  tales; and 
line 9565=>those whose business  took  them  to  the  borders  saw strange  things. The 
line 9566=>conversation in The  Green Dragon at Bywater,  one evening in the spring  of 
line 9567=>Frodo's  fiftieth year,  showed that  even in the comfortable  heart of  the 
line 9568=>Shire rumours had been heard, though most hobbits still laughed at them. 
line 9569=>     Sam Gamgee was sitting in one  corner near the fire,  and opposite  him 
line 9570=>was Ted  Sandyman, the  miller's son;  and there  were various  other rustic 
line 9571=>hobbits listening to their talk. 
line 9572=>     'Queer things you do hear these days, to be sure,' said Sam. 
line 9573=>     'Ah,'  said  Ted, 'you do, if you listen. But I can hear fireside-tales 
line 9574=>and children's stories at home, if I want to.' 
line 9575=>     'No doubt you can,' retorted Sam, 'and I daresay  there's more truth in 
line 9576=>some of them than you reckon.  Who invented the stories anyway? Take 
line 9577=>dragons 
line 9578=>now.' 
line 9579=>     'No thank 'ee,' said  Ted, 'I won't.  I heard tell of them when I was a  
line 9580=>youngster, but there's no  call to  believe in  them  now. There's  only one 
line 9581=>Dragon in Bywater, and that's Green,' he said, getting a general laugh. 
line 9582=>     'All  right,' said  Sam, laughing with the rest. 'But  what about these 
line 9583=>Tree-men, these giants, as you might call  them? They do say that one bigger 
line 9584=>than a tree was seen up away beyond the North Moors not long back.' 
line 9585=>     'Who's they?' 
line 9586=>     'My cousin Hal for one. He works for Mr. Boffin at Overhill and goes up 
line 9587=>to the Northfarthing for the hunting. He saw one.' 
line 9588=>     'Says he did, perhaps. Your Hal's always saying  he's seen  things; and 
line 9589=>
line 9590=>####-maybe he sees things that ain't there.' 
line 9591=>     'But  this  one was as big  as an elm tree, and walking - walking seven 
line 9592=>yards to a stride, if it was an inch.' 
line 9593=>     'Then I bet it wasn't an inch. What he saw was an elm  tree, as like as 
line 9594=>not.' 
line 9595=>     'But this one was  walking, I tell you; and there  ain't no elm tree on 
line 9596=>the North Moors.' 
line 9597=>     'Then Hal can't have  seen one,' said Ted. There  was some laughing and 
line 9598=>clapping: the audience seemed to think that Ted had scored a point. 
line 9599=>     'All  the same,'  said  Sam,  'you can't deny  that others besides  our 
line 9600=>Halfast have seen  queer  folk crossing the  Shire  - crossing  it, mind you: 
line 9601=>there are more that are turned back at the borders. The Bounders  have never  
line 9602=>been so busy before. 
line 9603=>     'And I've heard tell  that Elves are moving west. They do  say they are 
line 9604=>going to the harbours, out away beyond the  White Towers.' Sam waved his 
line 9605=>arm 
line 9606=>vaguely: neither he nor  any of them knew how far it was to the Sea, past the 
line 9607=>old towers  beyond  the western borders  of the  Shire. But  it was  an  old 
line 9608=>tradition that  away over  there stood the Grey  Havens, from which at times 
line 9609=>elven-ships set sail, never to return. 
line 9610=>     'They are sailing,  sailing, sailing over the Sea,  they are going into 
line 9611=>the West  and  leaving us,' said  Sam, half chanting the words, shaking  his 
line 9612=>head sadly and solemnly. But Ted laughed. 
line 9613=>     'Well,  that isn't anything  new, if you believe the  old tales.   And I 
line 9614=>don't see  what it matters to me or you.  Let  them sail!  But I warrant you  
line 9615=>haven't seen them doing it; nor any one else in the Shire.' 
line 9616=>     'Well I don't  know,' said Sam  thoughtfully. He believed he  had  once 
line 9617=>seen an Elf in the  woods, and still hoped to  see more one  day. Of all the 
line 9618=>legends  that he had heard in his  early  years such fragments of tales  and 
line 9619=>half-remembered  stories  about  the Elves as the hobbits knew,  had  always 
line 9620=>moved him  most deeply. 'There  are some,  even in these parts, as  know the 
line 9621=>Fair Folk and get news  of them,'  he said. 'There's Mr. Baggins now, that I 
line 9622=>work for. He told me  that they were sailing and he knows a bit about Elves.  
line 9623=>And old Mr. Bilbo knew more:  many's the  talk I had with  him  when I was a  
line 9624=>little lad.' 
line 9625=>     'Oh, they're both cracked,' said Ted. 'Leastways old Bilbo was cracked, 
line 9626=>and Frodo's cracking. If that's where  you get your news from, you'll  never  
line 9627=>
line 9628=>####-want for moonshine. Well,  friends,  I'm  off home.  Your  good  health!' He 
line 9629=>drained his mug and  went out noisily. 
line 9630=>     Sam sat silent and said no more. He had a good deal to think about. For  
line 9631=>one thing, there was a lot to do up in the Bag End garden, and he would have 
line 9632=>a busy day tomorrow, if the weather cleared. The grass was growing fast. But 
line 9633=>Sam ha d more on his mind than gardening. After a while he sighed, and got up 
line 9634=>and went out. 
line 9635=>     It was  early April and the sky was now clearing after  heavy rain. The 
line 9636=>sun was down,  and  a cool  pale evening was quietly fading  into night.  He 
line 9637=>walked  home  under  the  early stars  through  Hobbiton and  up  the  Hill, 
line 9638=>whistling softly and thoughtfully. 
line 9639=>     It  was  just at  this  time that  Gandalf  reappeared  after his  long 
line 9640=>absence. For three years  after  the Party he had  been away.  Then he  paid 
line 9641=>Frodo a  brief visit,  and after taking a good look at him he went off again. 
line 9642=>During  the  next  year  or  two  he  had  turned  up  fairly often,  coming 
line 9643=>unexpectedly  after  dusk, and going off without warning before sunrise.  He 
line 9644=>would  not  discuss  his  own  business  and  journeys, and  seemed  chiefly 
line 9645=>interested in small news about Frodo's health and doings. 
line 9646=>     Then suddenly his visits had ceased. It was over nine years since Frodo 
line 9647=>had seen or heard of him, and  he had begun  to think that  the wizard would 
line 9648=>never return and  had given up all interest in hobbits. But that evening, as 
line 9649=>Sam was walking home  and twilight was fading, there came the once  familiar 
line 9650=>tap on the study window.  
line 9651=>     Frodo welcomed  his old friend with  surprise  and great delight.  They 
line 9652=>looked hard at one another. 
line 9653=>     'Ah well eh?' said Gandalf. 'You look the same as ever, Frodo!' 
line 9654=>     'So do you,' Frodo replied; but secretly he thought that Gandalf looked 
line 9655=>older and  more careworn. He pressed him for news of himself and of the wide 
line 9656=>world, and  soon they were  deep in talk, and  they stayed  up far into  the 
line 9657=>night. 
line 9658=>     Next morning after a late breakfast, the  wizard was sitting with Frodo 
line 9659=>by the open  window of the  study. A bright fire was on the hearth,  but the 
line 9660=>sun was warm, and  the  wind was in the  South. Everything looked fresh, and 
line 9661=>the new green of Spring  was shimmering in the fields and on the tips of the  
line 9662=>trees' fingers.  
line 9663=>     Gandalf  was thinking of  a  spring,  nearly  eighty years before, when 
line 9664=>Bilbo  had run out  of Bag End without  a handkerchief. His hair was perhaps 
line 9665=>
line 9666=>####-whiter  than it  had  been  then,  and his  beard  and eyebrows were perhaps 
line 9667=>longer, and  his face more lined with care and  wisdom; but his eyes were as 
line 9668=>bright as ever, and he smoked and blew smoke-rings with the same vigour  and 
line 9669=>delight. 
line 9670=>     He was  smoking  now in  silence, for  Frodo was sitting still, deep in 
line 9671=>thought. Even in the light of morning he felt the dark shadow of the tidings 
line 9672=>that Gandalf had brought. At last he broke the silence. 
line 9673=>     'Last  night  you  began to  tell  me  strange  things  about  my ring, 
line 9674=>Gandalf,' he said. 'And then you stopped, because you said that such matters 
line 9675=>were best left until  daylight. Don't you think  you  had better finish now?  
line 9676=>You  say the ring  is dangerous,  far mor e  dangerous than  I guess. In what 
line 9677=>way?' 
line 9678=>     'In many  ways,' answered  the wizard. It is far  more powerful than  I 
line 9679=>ever dared to think at first, so powerful that in the  end it  would utterly 
line 9680=>overcome anyone of mortal race who possessed it. It would possess him. 
line 9681=>     'In Eregion long  ago many Elven-rings  were made,  magic  rings as you  
line 9682=>call them, and they were, of course, of various  kinds: some more potent and 
line 9683=>some  less.  The lesser rings were only essays  in the craft before  it  was 
line 9684=>full-grown, and to the Elven-smiths they were but  trifles  - yet still to my 
line 9685=>mind dangerous for mortals. But  the Great Rings,  the Rings of Power,  they 
line 9686=>were perilous.  
line 9687=>     'A  mortal, Frodo, who keeps one of the Great  Rings, does not die, but 
line 9688=>he does not  grow  or obtain more life, he merely continues, until  at  last 
line 9689=>every minute is a weariness. And if he often  uses the Ring  to make himself 
line 9690=>invisible,  he fades: he becomes in the end invisible permanently, and walks 
line 9691=>in the twilight under the eye of the  dark power that rules the Rings.  Yes, 
line 9692=>sooner or  later  - later, if he is strong or well-meaning to begin with, but 
line 9693=>neither strength nor good purpose will last  - sooner or later the dark power  
line 9694=>will devour him.' 
line 9695=>     'How terrifying!' said Frodo. There was another long silence. The sound 
line 9696=>of Sam Gamgee cutting the lawn came in from the garden. 
line 9697=>     'How long have you  known this?'  asked Frodo  at length. 'And how much 
