line 10028=>it, or go away and leave it?' 
line 10029=>     'You  ought to  begin to understand, Frodo,  after all you have heard,' 
line 10030=>said Gandalf. 'He  hated it and loved it, as he hated and loved  himself. He 
line 10031=>could not get rid of it. He had no will left in the matter. 
line 10032=>     'A  Ring  of  Power  looks   after  itself,  Frodo.  It  may  slip  off 
line 10033=>treacherously, but its keeper never  abandons it. At most he  plays with the 
line 10034=>idea of handing  it on  to someone else's care  - and  that  only at an early 
line 10035=>stage, when it first  begins  to grip. But  as  far as I know Bilbo alone in 
line 10036=>history has ever gone beyond playing, and  really done it.  He needed all my 
line 10037=>help, too. And even  so he would never  have just  forsaken  it, or  cast it 
line 10038=>aside. It  was not Gollum, Frodo, but the  Ring  itself that decided things.  
line 10039=>The Ring left him.' 
line 10040=>     'What, just in time  to meet Bilbo?' said Frodo. 'Wouldn't an  Orc have 
line 10041=>suited it better?' 
line 10042=>     'It  is no laughing  matter,'  said Gandalf. 'Not for you.  It was  the 
