line 10356=>one ear. 
line 10357=>     'Well, well, bless my beard!' said Gandalf. 'Sam Gamgee is it? Now what 
line 10358=>may you be doing?' 
line 10359=>     'Lor bless  you, Mr. Gandalf, sir!' said Sam. 'Nothing! Leastways I was 
line 10360=>just  trimming the grass-border  under  the window,  if you  follow me.'  He 
line 10361=>picked up his shears and exhibited them as evidence. 
line 10362=>     'I don't,' said Gandalf grimly. It is some time  since I last heard the 
line 10363=>sound of your shears. How long have you been eavesdropping?' 
line 10364=>     'Eavesdropping,  sir? I don't  follow you, begging  your pardon.  There 
line 10365=>ain't no eaves at Bag End, and that's a fact.' 
line 10366=>     'Don't be  a  fool! What  have  you  heard,  and why  did you  listen?' 
line 10367=>Gandalf's eyes flashed and his brows stuck out like bristles.  
line 10368=>     'Mr. Frodo, sir!' cried Sam quaking. 'Don't let him hurt me, sir! Don't  
line 10369=>let  him turn  me  into anything unnatural!  My old  dad would take on so. I 
line 10370=>meant no harm, on my honour, sir!' 
line 10371=>     'He  won't hurt you,' said Frodo,  hardly able to keep  from  laughing, 
line 10372=>although he was himself startled and rather puzzled. 'He knows, as well as I  
line 10373=>do, that you mean no harm. But just you up and answer his questions straight 
line 10374=>away!' 
line 10375=>     'Well, sir,' said Sam dithering a little. 'I heard a deal that I didn't 
line 10376=>rightly  understand,  about an  enemy, and  rings, and  Mr. Bilbo, sir,  and 
line 10377=>dragons, and a  fiery mountain, and - and  Elves, sir. I listened because  I 
line 10378=>couldn't help  myself, if you know what I mean. Lor bless  me, sir, but I do 
line 10379=>love tales of  that sort. And  I believe  them  too,  whatever Ted may  say. 
line 10380=>Elves,  sir! I  would dearly love  to see  them. Cou ldn't you take  me to see 
line 10381=>Elves, sir, when you go?' 
line 10382=>     Suddenly Gandalf laughed. 'Come  inside!' he shouted,  and  putting out 
line 10383=>both his arms he lifted the astonished Sam, shears, grass-clippings and all, 
line 10384=>right through the window and stood him on the floor. 'Take you to see Elves, 
line 10385=>eh?' he  said, eyeing Sam  closely, but with a smile flickering on his face. 
line 10386=>'So you heard that Mr. Frodo is going away?' 
line 10387=>
line 10388=>####-     'I  did,  sir.  And that's why I choked:  which  you heard seemingly. I 
line 10389=>tried not to, sir, but it burst out of me: I was so upset.' 
line 10390=>     'It can't be  helped, Sam,' said  Frodo sadly. He had suddenly realized 
line 10391=>that  flying  from the Shire  would mean  more painful partings than  merely 
line 10392=>saying farewell  to  the familiar comforts of Bag End. 'I shall have to  go. 
line 10393=>But' - and  here he looked  hard at Sam  - 'if you really care about me, you  
line 10394=>will keep that dead secret. See? If you don't, if you even breathe a word of 
line 10395=>what you've heard here, then  I  hope  Gandalf will turn you into a  spotted 
line 10396=>toad and fill the garden full of grass-snakes.' 
line 10397=>     Sam fell on his knees,  trembling. 'Get  up, Sam!' said Gandalf. I have 
line 10398=>thought of something better than  that. Something  to shut your  mouth,  and  
line 10399=>punish you properly for listening. You shall go away with Mr. Frodo!' 
line 10400=>     'Me,  sir!' cried Sam, springing up like a dog invited for a walk.  'Me 
line 10401=>go and see Elves and all! Hooray!' he shouted, and then burst into tears.  
line 10402=> 
line 10403=>
line 10404=>####- 
line 10405=>
line 10406=>Chapter 3. Three is Company 
line 10407=>
line 10408=> 
line 10409=> 
line 10410=>     'You ought to go quietly, and you ought to  go soon,' said Gandalf. Two 
line 10411=>or three weeks had passed, and still Frodo made  no sign of getting ready to 
line 10412=>go. 
line 10413=>     'I know. But it is difficult to do both,' he objected. If I just vanish 
line 10414=>like Bilbo, the tale will be all over the Shire in no time.' 
line 10415=>     'Of course you mustn't vanish!' said Gandalf. 'That wouldn't do at all! 
line 10416=>I said soon, not instantly. If  you can think of any way of slipping out  of 
line 10417=>the  Shire  without  its  being generally known, it will  be  worth a little 
line 10418=>delay. But you must not delay too long.' 
line 10419=>     'What  about the  autumn, on  or after  Our Birthday?' asked  Frodo. 'I  
line 10420=>think I could probably make some arrangements by then.' 
line 10421=>     To tell the truth, he was very reluctant to start, now that it had come 
line 10422=>to  the  point. Bag End seemed a more  desirable residence than  i t  had for 
line 10423=>years, and he wanted to savour as much as he could of his last summer in the 
line 10424=>Shire. When autumn came, he knew that part at least of his heart would think 
line 10425=>more kindly  of journeying, as it always did at that season. He  had  indeed 
line 10426=>privately made up his mind to leave on his  fiftieth birthday:  Bilbo's  one 
line 10427=>hundred and twenty-eighth. It  seemed somehow the proper day on which to set 
line 10428=>out and follow him. Following Bilbo was uppermost in his mind, and  the  one 
line 10429=>thing  that made the thought  of leaving  bearable. He  thought as little as 
line 10430=>possible about the Ring, and where it might lead him in  the end. But he did 
line 10431=>not tell all his  thoughts to Gandalf. What the  wizard  guessed  was always 
line 10432=>difficult to tell. 
line 10433=>     He looked at Frodo and smiled. 'Very well,' he said. 'I think that will 
line 10434=>do -  but  it must not  be any  later. I  am getting  very anxious.  In  the 
line 10435=>mean-while, do take care, and don't let out any hint of where you are going!  
line 10436=>And  see  that Sam Gamgee does not talk. If he does, I really shall turn him 
line 10437=>into a toad.' 
line 10438=>     'As for  where I am going,' said Frodo, 'it would be  difficult to give 
line 10439=>that away, for I have no clear idea myself, yet.' 
line 10440=>     'Don't be absurd!' said Gandalf. 'I  am not warning you against leaving 
line 10441=>an  address  at the post -office!  But you are leaving the  Shire   - and that 
line 10442=>should not be known,  until you  are far away. And  you must go, or at least 
line 10443=>
line 10444=>####-set  out,  either North,  South,  West  or East  -  and  the direction should 
line 10445=>certainly not be known.' 
line 10446=>     'I have been so  taken up with the thoughts of leaving  Bag End, and of 
line 10447=>saying  farewell, that I have  never even  considered  the  direction,' said 
line 10448=>Frodo. 'For where am I to go? And by  what  shall I  steer? What is to be my  
line 10449=>quest? Bilbo went to find a treasure, there and back aga in; but I go to lose 
line 10450=>one, and not return, as far as I can see.' 
line 10451=>     'But you cannot  see very far,' said Gandalf. 'Neither can I. It may be 
line 10452=>your task to find the Cracks of Doom; but that quest may be for others: I do 
line 10453=>not know. At any rate you are not ready for that long road yet.' 
line 10454=>     'No  indeed!' said  Frodo.  'But  in the  meantime what course am I  to 
line 10455=>lake?' 
line 10456=>     'Towards  danger; but not  too  rashly, nor too straight,' answered the 
line 10457=>wizard. 'If you want my advice, make for Rivendell. That journey  should not 
line 10458=>prove too  perilous, though the  Road is less easy than it was, and it  will 
line 10459=>grow worse as the year fails.' 
line 10460=>     'Rivendell!' said  Frodo. 'Very good:  I will go east, and  I will make 
line 10461=>for Rivendell. I will take Sam to visit the Elves; he will be delighted.' He 
line 10462=>spoke lightly;  but his heart was  moved  suddenly with  a desire to see the 
line 10463=>house of Elrond  Halfelven, and  breathe the  air  of that deep valley where 
line 10464=>many of the Fair Folk still dwelt in peace. 
line 10465=>     One summer's evening an astonishing piece of news  reached the Ivy Bush 
line 10466=>and Green Dragon. Giants and other portents on the borders of the Shire were 
line 10467=>forgotten for more important matters: Mr. Frodo was  selling Bag End, indeed 
line 10468=>he had already sold it - to the Sackville-Bagginses!  
line 10469=>     'For a nice bit, loo,' said some.  'At a bargain price,'  said  others,  
line 10470=>'and that's more likely when Mistress Lobelia's  the  buyer.' (Otho had died 
line 10471=>some years before, at the ripe but disappointed age of 102.) 
line 10472=>     Just  why  Mr.  Frodo  was selling  his  beautiful hole was  even  more 
line 10473=>debatable than the price. A  few held the theory - supported by the nods and  
line 10474=>hints  of Mr. Baggins himself  - that Frodo's money was  running out: he  was 
line 10475=>going to leave Hobbiton and live in a  quiet way on the proceeds of the sale 
line 10476=>down  in  Buckland  among   his  Brandybuck  relations.  'As  far  from  the 
line 10477=>Sackville-Bagginses  as may be,'  some added.  But  so firmly fixed  had the 
line 10478=>notion of  the immeasurable wealth  of the Bagginses of Bag End  become that 
line 10479=>most found this  hard to believe, harder than  any  other reason or unreason 
line 10480=>that  their fancy  could suggest:  to  most  it suggested  a  dark  and  yet 
line 10481=>
line 10482=>####-unrevealed plot by Gandalf. Though he kept himself very quiet and did not go 
line 10483=>about by day, it was well known that he was 'hiding up in the  Bag End'. But 
line 10484=>however a removal might  fit in with the  designs of his wizardry, there was 
line 10485=>no doubt about the fact: Frodo Baggins was going back to Buckland. 
line 10486=>     'Yes, I shall be moving  this autumn,' he  said.  'Merry Brandybuck  is 
line 10487=>looking out  for a nice little hole for me, or perhaps a small house.' 
line 10488=>     As a matter of fact with  Merry's help he had already chosen and bought 
line 10489=>a little house  at Crickhollow in the country beyond Bucklebury. To all  but 
line 10490=>Sam he pretended he was going to settle down there permanently. The decision 
line 10491=>to set out eastwards had suggested the idea to him; for Buckland was on  the 
line 10492=>eastern borders  of  the Shire, and as he had lived there  in childhood  his 
line 10493=>going back would at least seem credible. 
line 10494=>     Gandalf  stayed in the Shire for over two months.  Then one evening, at 
line 10495=>the end of  June, soon  after Frodo's  plan  had  been finally  arranged, he 
line 10496=>suddenly  announced that  he was going off  again next morning.  'Only for a 
line 10497=>short  while, I hope,'  he said.  'But  I am  going down beyond the southern 
line 10498=>borders to get some news, if I can. I have been idle longer than I should.' 
line 10499=>     He spoke lightly, but it seemed to Frodo that he looked rather worried. 
line 10500=>'Has anything happened?' he asked. 
line 10501=>     'Well no; but I have heard something that has made me anxious and needs 
line 10502=>looking into. If I think it necessary after all  for you to get off at once, 
line 10503=>I shall come back immediately, or at least send word. In the meanwhile stick  
line 10504=>to your plan; but be more careful than ever, especially of the  Ring.  Let me 
line 10505=>impress on you once more: don't use it!'  
line 10506=>     He  went off at dawn.  'I may be back any day,'  he  said. 'At the very 
line 10507=>latest I shall come back  for  the farewell party. I think after all you may 
line 10508=>need my company on the Road.' 
line 10509=>     At first  Frodo  was a  good deal  disturbed,  and wondered often  what 
line 10510=>Gandalf could  have  heard; but his  uneasiness wore  off, and in  the  fine  
line 10511=>weather  he forgot his  troubles for a  while. The  Shire had seldom seen so 
line 10512=>fair a summer, or so rich an autumn: the trees were laden with apples, honey 
line 10513=>was dripping in the combs, and the corn was tall and full. 
line 10514=>     Autumn was well under  way  before  Frodo began to worry  about Gandalf 
line 10515=>again.  September  was  passing  and there  was  still no  news of him.  The 
line 10516=>Birthday, and the removal, drew  nearer, and still he did not come,  or send 
line 10517=>word.  Bag End began to be busy.  Some of Frodo's friends  came  to stay and 
line 10518=>help  him with the packing: there was Fredegar Bolger and Folco  Boffin, and 
line 10519=>
line 10520=>####-of course his special friends Pippin Took and Merry Brandybuck. Between 
line 10521=>them 
line 10522=>they turned the whole place upside-down. 
line 10523=>     On  September  20th  two  covered  carts  went off  laden  to Buckland, 
line 10524=>conveying  the furniture and goods that Frodo had not  sold to his new home, 
line 10525=>by way of the  Brandywine Bridge. The next day Frodo became  really anxious, 
line 10526=>and kept  a constant look -out  for  Gandalf. Thursday, his birthday morning,  
line 10527=>dawned as fair and  clear  as it had long ago for Bilbo's great party. Still 
line 10528=>Gandalf did not appear. In the evening Frodo gave his farewell feast: it was 
line 10529=>quite small, just  a  dinner  for himself  and his four helpers; but  he was 
line 10530=>troubled and fell in no mood for it. The thought  that he would so soon have 
line 10531=>to part  with his young  friends weighed  on his heart. He  wondered how  he 
line 10532=>would break it to them. 
line 10533=>     The four younger  hobbits were, however, in high spirits, and the party 
line 10534=>soon became very cheerful in spite of Gandalf's absence. The dining-room was 
line 10535=>bare except for a table  and  chairs,  but the food  was good, and there was 
line 10536=>good  wine:  Frodo's  wine  had  not  been  included  in  the  sale  to  the 
line 10537=>Sackville-Bagginses. 
line 10538=>     'Whatever happens to  the rest of my stuff, when the S.-B.s  get  their 
line 10539=>claws on  it, at any rate I have found a good home for this!' said Frodo, as 
line 10540=>he drained his glass. It was the last drop of Old Winyards.  
line 10541=>     When they had sung many songs, and talked of  many things they had done 
line 10542=>together,  they toasted  Bilbo's birthday, and  they  drank his  health  and 
line 10543=>Frodo's together according to Frodo's custom. Then they went out for a sniff 
line 10544=>of air, and glimpse of the stars, and then  they went to bed.  Frodo's party 
line 10545=>was over, and Gandalf had not come. 
line 10546=>     The next morning they were busy packing another cart with the remainder 
line 10547=>of the luggage. Merry took charge of this, and drove off with Fatty (that is 
line 10548=>Fredegar  Bolger).  'Someone must get there and  warm the house  before  you  
line 10549=>arrive,' said Merry.  'Well, see you later - the day  after tomorrow,  if you  
line 10550=>don't go to sleep on the way!' 
line 10551=>     Folco went  home  aft er lunch,  but Pippin remained behind.  Frodo  was 
line 10552=>restless and anxious,  listening in vain for a  sound of Gandalf. He decided 
line 10553=>to  wait until  nightfall. After that,  if  Gandalf wanted him urgently,  he 
line 10554=>would go to Crickhollow, and might even get there first. For Frodo was going 
line 10555=>on foot. His plan - for pleasure and a last look at the Shire as much as any 
line 10556=>other reason  -  was to walk from Hobbiton to  Bucklebury  Ferry, taking  it 
line 10557=>
line 10558=>####-fairly easy. 
line 10559=>     'I shall  get  myself a bit  into  training,  too,' he said, looking at 
line 10560=>himself  in  a dusty mirror in the  half-empty  hall.  He  had  not done any 
line 10561=>strenuous walking for a long time, and the reflection  looked rather flabby, 
line 10562=>he thought. 
line 10563=>     After lunch, the Sackville-Bagginses, Lobelia and her sandy-haired son, 
line 10564=>Lotho, turned  up, much to Frodo's annoyance. 'Ours at last!' said  Lobelia, 
line 10565=>as she stepped inside. It was not polite; nor strictly true, for the sale of 
line 10566=>Bag  End  did not take effect  until  midnight.  But Lobelia  can perhaps be 
line 10567=>forgiven: she had been obliged to wait about seventy-seven years  longer for  
line 10568=>Bag End  than she once hoped, and she was now  a  hundred years old. 
line 10569=>Anyway, 
line 10570=>she had  come to see that nothing she had paid for had been carried off; and 
line 10571=>she wanted the keys. It took a long while to satisfy her, as she had brought 
line 10572=>a complete inventory  with her and went  right through  it. In  the end  she 
line 10573=>departed with Lotho and  the spare  key and  the promise that the  other key 
line 10574=>would  be  left at  the  Gamgees' in Bagshot Row.  She  snorted, and  showed 
line 10575=>plainly that she  thought the Gamgees  capable of plundering the hole during  
line 10576=>the night. Frodo did not offer her any tea. 
line 10577=>     He took his own tea with Pippin and Sam Gamgee  in the  kitchen. It had 
line 10578=>been  officially announced that Sam was coming to Buckland  'to  do for  Mr. 
line 10579=>Frodo and look after his bit of garden'; an arrangement that was approved by 
line 10580=>the Gaffer, though it did not console him for the prospect of having Lobelia  
line 10581=>as a neighbour. 
line 10582=>     'Our  last meal at  Bag End!'  said Frodo, pushing back his chair. They 
line 10583=>left the washing up  for Lobelia.  Pippin  and Sam  strapped  up their three 
line 10584=>packs and piled them in the porch. Pippin went out for a last  stroll in the 
line 10585=>garden. Sam disappeared. 
line 10586=>     The sun went down. Bag End seemed sad and gloomy and dishevelled. 
line 10587=>Frodo 
line 10588=>wandered round the familiar rooms,  and saw the light  of the sunset fade on 
line 10589=>the walls,  and  shadows  creep out  of  the  corners.  It  grew slowly dark 
line 10590=>indoors. He went out and walked down to  the gate at the bottom of the path,  
line 10591=>and then on a short way down the Hill Road. He half expected to  see Gandalf 
line 10592=>come striding up through the dusk. 
line 10593=>     The sky was clear and the stars were growing bright. 'It's going  to be 
line 10594=>a fine night,'  he  said  aloud.  'That's good for a beginning.  I feel like 
line 10595=>
line 10596=>####-walking. I  can't  bear any  more  hanging about. I am going  to start,  and 
line 10597=>Gandalf must follow  me.'  He  turned to go back, and  then  slopped, for he 
line 10598=>heard voices, just round the corner by the end of Bagshot Row. One voice was 
line 10599=>certainly the old Gaffer's;  the other was strange, and  somehow  unpleasant. 
line 10600=>He could not make out what it said, but he heard the Gaffer's answers, which 
line 10601=>were rather shrill. The old man seemed put out. 
line 10602=>     'No, Mr. Baggins has gone away. Went this morning, and my Sam went 
line 10603=>with 
line 10604=>him: anyway all  his stuff went.  Yes, sold out and  gone,  I tell'ee.  Why?  
line 10605=>Why's none of my business, or yours.  Where to?  That ain't no  secret. He's 
line 10606=>moved to Bucklebury or some such place, away down yonder. Yes it is  - a tidy 
line 10607=>way.  I've never been so far myself; they're  queer folks in Buckland. No, I 
line 10608=>can't give no message. Good night to you!' 
line 10609=>     Footsteps went away down the Hill. Frodo wondered vaguely why  the fact 
line 10610=>that they did not  come on up the Hill seemed a  great relief. 'I am sick of 
line 10611=>questions a nd curiosity  about my doings,  I  suppose,' he thought. 'What an 
line 10612=>inquisitive lot they all  are!' He had half a mind to go and ask  the Gaffer  
line 10613=>who the inquirer was; but he thought better (or worse) of it, and turned and 
line 10614=>walked quickly back to Bag End. 
line 10615=>     Pippin was sitting on his pack  in  the porch. Sam was not there. Frodo 
line 10616=>stepped inside the dark door. 'Sam!' he called. 'Sam! Time!' 
line 10617=>     'Coming, sir!' came  the answer  from far within, followed soon by  Sam 
line 10618=>himself, wiping his mouth. He had been saying farewell to the beer -barrel in 
line 10619=>the cellar. 
line 10620=>     'All aboard, Sam?' said Frodo. 
line 10621=>     'Yes, sir. I'll last for a bit now, sir.' 
line 10622=>     Frodo shut and locked the  round door, and  gave the key  to Sam.  'Run 
line 10623=>down with this to your home, Sam!' he said. 'Then cu t along the Row and meet 
line 10624=>us as quick as you can at the gate in the  lane  beyond the meadows.  We are 
line 10625=>not  going  through  the village  tonight.  Too  many ears pricking and eyes 
line 10626=>prying.' Sam ran off at full speed. 
line 10627=>     'Well, now we're off at last!'  said  Frodo. They shouldered their packs 
line 10628=>and took up their sticks, and  walked round the corner to the  west  side of 
line 10629=>Bag End. 'Good-bye!' said Frodo, looking at the dark blank windows. He 
line 10630=>waved 
line 10631=>his hand, and then turned and (following Bilbo, if  he had known it) hurried 
line 10632=>after Peregrin down  the garden-path. They jumped over the low place in  the 
line 10633=>
line 10634=>####-hedge at the bottom and took to the fields, passing into the darkness like a  
line 10635=>rustle in the grasses.  
line 10636=>     At the bottom of the  Hill  on its western  side they came  to  the gate 
line 10637=>opening on to a  narrow lane.  There they  halted and adjusted the straps of 
line 10638=>their packs. Presently  Sam  appeared, trotting quickly and  breathing hard; 
line 10639=>his heavy pack was hoisted high on his shoulders, and he had put on his head 
line 10640=>a tall shapeless fell  bag, which  he called  a hat. In the gloom  he looked 
line 10641=>very much like a dwarf. 
line 10642=>     'I am sure you  have given me all the heaviest stuff,'  said Frodo.  'I  
line 10643=>pity snails, and all that carry their homes on their backs.' 
line 10644=>     'I could take a lot  more yet, sir. My packet is quite light,' said Sam 
line 10645=>stoutly and untruthfully. 
line 10646=>     'No, you  don't,  Sam!' said  Pippin.  'It is  good  for him. He's  got 
line 10647=>nothing except what he ordered us to pack. He's been slack lately, and he'll 
line 10648=>feel the weight less when he's walked off some of his own.' 
line 10649=>     'Be kind to a poor old hobbit!' laughed Frodo. 'I shall be as thin as a  
line 10650=>willow-wand, I'm sure, before I get to Buckland. But I was talking nonsense. 
line 10651=>I suspect you have taken more than your share, Sam, and I shall look into  it 
line 10652=>at our next  packing.'  He  picked  up his  stick  again. 'Well, we all like 
line 10653=>walking  in the dark,' he said,  'so let's put  some miles  behind us before 
line 10654=>bed.' 
line 10655=>     For a short way they followed  the lane westwards. Then leaving it they 
line 10656=>turned left and took quietly to  the  fields again. They went in single file 
line 10657=>along hedgerows and the borders of coppices, and night fell dark about them. 
line 10658=>In their  dark cloaks they were as invisible as if they all had magic rings. 
line 10659=>Since they were  all hobbits, and were  trying  to be silent,  they made  no 
line 10660=>noise that even hobbits would  hear. Even the wild things in  the fields and 
line 10661=>woods hardly noticed their passing. 
line 10662=>     After  some  time they crossed the Water, west of Hobbiton, by a narrow 
line 10663=>plank -bridge.  The stream  was  there no more than  a winding  black ribbon,  
line 10664=>bordered with leaning  alder -trees. A mile or two further south they hastily 
line 10665=>crossed the great  road  from  the Brandywine Bridge; they were  now in  the 
line 10666=>Tookland and  bending south-eastwards they made for the  Green Hill Country. 
line 10667=>As they began to climb its first slopes they looked back and  saw the  lamps  
line 10668=>in Hobbiton far off twinkling in  the gentle  valley of  the  Water. Soon it 
line 10669=>disappeared  in the  folds of the darkened land, and was followed by Bywater 
line 10670=>beside  its grey pool. When the  light of  the  last  farm was  far  behind, 
line 10671=>
line 10672=>####-peeping among the trees, Frodo turned and waved a hand in farewell. 
line 10673=>     'I wonder if  I shall ever  look down into that valley  again,' he said 
line 10674=>quietly. 
line 10675=>     When they  had walked for about three hours they rested. The night  was 
line 10676=>clear,  cool, and starry, but smoke-like wisps of mist were creeping up  the 
line 10677=>hill-sides from the streams and deep  meadows. Thin-clad birches, swaying in 
line 10678=>a light wind  above their heads, made a black net aga inst the pale sky. They 
line 10679=>ate a  very  frugal supper (for hobbits), and  then went on again. Soon they 
line 10680=>struck a narrow road, that  went rolling  up and down,  fading grey into the 
line 10681=>darkness ahead: the road to Woodhall, and  Stock, and the Bucklebury  Ferry. 
line 10682=>It climbed away from the  main road  in the Water-valley, and wound over the 
line 10683=>skirts  of  the  Green  Hills  towards  Woody-End,  a  wild  corner  of  the 
line 10684=>Eastfarthing. 
line 10685=>     After a while  they plunged into  a deeply  cloven  track  between tall 
line 10686=>trees that rustled their dry leaves in the night. It was very dark. At first  
line 10687=>they  talked,  or hummed a  tune  softly together, being  now far  away from 
line 10688=>inquisitive ears. Then they marched  on in silence,  and Pippin began to lag 
line 10689=>behind.  At  last, as  they began to   climb  a  steep slope, he  stopped and 
line 10690=>yawned. 
line 10691=>     'I  am  so sleepy,' he said,  'that soon I shall fall down on the road. 
line 10692=>Are you going to sleep on your legs? It is nearly midnight.' 
line 10693=>     'I thought you liked walking in the dark,' said Frodo. 'But there is no 
line 10694=>great  hurry.  Merry expects  us some time the day after  tomorrow; but that 
line 10695=>leaves us nearly two days more. We'll halt at the first likely spot.' 
line 10696=>     'The  wind's in  the West,' said Sam. 'If  we get to the other  side of 
line 10697=>this hill,  we shall find  a spot  that  is  sheltered and snug  enough, sir. 
line 10698=>There is  a dry fir-wood just ahead,  if  I  remember rightly.' Sam knew the 
line 10699=>land well  within twenty miles of  Hobbiton, but that was  the  limit of his 
line 10700=>geography. 
line 10701=>     Just  over the  top  of  the  hill they came on  the patch of fir-wood. 
line 10702=>Leaving  the  road  they  went into  the deep resin -scented  darkness of the 
line 10703=>trees, and  gathered  dead  sticks and cones to make a fire. Soon they had a  
line 10704=>merry crackle of flame at the foot of a large fir-tree and they sat round it 
line 10705=>for  a while, until they began to nod. Then, each in an  angle  of the great 
line 10706=>tree's roots, they curled  up  in  their cloaks and blankets, and were  soon 
line 10707=>fast asleep. They set no  watch; even Frodo feared  no danger yet,  for they 
line 10708=>were still in  the heart  of the Shire. A few  creatures came and  looked at 
line 10709=>
line 10710=>####-them when the fire had died away. A fox passing through the wood on business 
line 10711=>of his own stopped several minutes and sniffed. 
line 10712=>     'Hobbits!' he thought. 'Well, what next? I have heard of strange doings 
line 10713=>in this land,  but  I have  seldom  heard of a hobbit  sleeping out of doors 
line 10714=>under a tree. Three of them! There's something mighty queer behind this.' He 
line 10715=>was quite right, but he never found out any more about it. 
line 10716=>     The morning came,  pale and clammy. Frodo woke up first, and found that 
line 10717=>a tree-root had made a hole in his back, and that his neck was stiff. 
line 10718=>     'Walking for pleasure! Why didn't  I drive?'  he thought, as he usually 
line 10719=>did at the beginning of an expedition. 'And all  my  beautiful feather  beds 
line 10720=>are sold to the Sackville-Bagginses! These  tree -roots would  do them good.' 
line 10721=>He stretched. 'Wake up, hobbits!' he cried. It's a beautiful morning.' 
line 10722=>     'What's beautiful about it?' said Pippin, peering  over the edge of his 
line 10723=>blanket with one eye. 'Sam! Gel breakfast ready for half-past nine! Have you 
line 10724=>got the bath-water hot?' 
line 10725=>     Sam jumped up,  looking rather  bleary. 'No,  sir, I haven't, sir!'  he 
line 10726=>said. 
line 10727=>     Frodo stripped the blankets from Pippin and  rolled him  over, and then 
line 10728=>walked off to the edge of the wood. Away eastward the sun was rising red out 
line 10729=>of the mists that lay thick  on  the world. Touched  with  gold and red  the 
line 10730=>autumn trees seemed to  be sailing rootless in a shadowy sea. A little below 
line 10731=>him to the left the road ran down steeply into a hollow and disappeared. 
line 10732=>     When  he returned  Sam  and  Pippin had got a good fire going. 'Water!' 
line 10733=>shouted Pippin. 'Where's the water?' 
line 10734=>     'I  don't keep  water in my  pockets,' said  Frodo. 'We thought you had 
line 10735=>gone to find  some,' said Pippin, busy  setting out the food, and cups. 'You  
line 10736=>had better go now.' 
line 10737=>     'You  can come too,'  said  Frodo, 'and  bring  all the water -bottles.' 
line 10738=>There was  a stream at the foot of the hill. They  filled their  bottles and 
line 10739=>the small  camping kettle at a little fall  where the water fell  a few feet 
line 10740=>over an outcrop  of grey stone. It  was  icy cold;  and they spluttered  and 
line 10741=>puffed as they bathed their faces and hands.  
line 10742=>     When their breakfast was over, and their packs all trussed up again, it 
line 10743=>was after  ten o'clock, and the day was beginning to turn fine and hot. They 
line 10744=>went  down the slope, and across the stream where  it  dived under the road,  
line 10745=>and up the next slope, and up and down another shoulder of the hills; and by 
line 10746=>that time their cloaks, blankets, water , food, and other gear already seemed 
line 10747=>
line 10748=>####-a heavy burden. 
line 10749=>     The day's march promised to be warm and tiring  work. After some miles, 
line 10750=>however, the road  ceased to roll up and  down: it climbed  to the  top of a  
line 10751=>steep bank in a weary zig-zagging sort of way, and then prepared to  go down 
line 10752=>for  the last time. In front of  them they saw  the lower lands  dotted with 
line 10753=>small clumps of  trees that melted away in  the distance to a brown woodland 
line 10754=>haze. They were looking across the  Woody End towards  the Brandywine 
line 10755=>River. 
line 10756=>The road wound away before them like a piece of string. 
line 10757=>     'The road goes on  for ever,' said Pippin; 'but I can't without a rest. 
line 10758=>It is  high time for lunch.' He sat down on the bank at the side of the road 
line 10759=>and looked  away east into the haze, beyond which lay the River, and the end 
line 10760=>of the Shire in which he had spent all his life. Sam stood by him. His round 
line 10761=>eyes were wide open  - for he was looking across lands he had never seen to a 
line 10762=>new horizon. 
line 10763=>     'Do Elves live in those woods?' he asked. 
line 10764=>     'Not that I ever  heard,' said Pippin.  Frodo  was silent.  He  too was 
line 10765=>gazing eastward along the road, as if he had never seen it  before. Suddenly 
line 10766=>he spoke, aloud but as if to himself, saying slowly: 
line 10767=>     The Road goes ever on and on  
line 10768=>     Down from the door where it began. 
line 10769=>     Now far ahead the Road has gone, 
line 10770=>     And I must follow, if I can, 
line 10771=>     Pursuing it with weary feet, 
line 10772=>     Until it joins some larger way, 
line 10773=>     Where many paths and errands meet. 
line 10774=>     And whither then? I cannot say. 
line 10775=>     'That sounds  like a bit of old Bilbo's rhyming,' said Pippin. 'Or is it 
line 10776=>one of your imitations? It does not sound altogether encouraging.' 
line 10777=>     'I don't know,' said Frodo. It came to me then, as  if I was making  it 
line 10778=>up; but I  may have heard it long ago. Certainly it reminds  me very much of 
line 10779=>Bilbo in the last years, before he went away. He used often to say there was 
line 10780=>only  one  Road;  that it was like a great river: its  springs were at every 
line 10781=>doorstep,  and every path was  its  tributary. "It's  a dangerous  business,  
line 10782=>Frodo, going out of your door," he used to say. "You step into the Road, and 
line 10783=>if you don't keep your feet,  there is no knowing where  you might  be swept  
line 10784=>off to.  Do you realize  that  this  is the  very  path  that  goes  through 
line 10785=>
line 10786=>####-Mirkwood,  and that if you  let it, it  might take you to the Lonely Mountain 
line 10787=>or  even  further and to worse places?"  He  used to say  that  on  the path 
line 10788=>outside the  front door at  Bag End, especially  after he had been out for a  
line 10789=>long walk.' 
line 10790=>     'Well,  the Road won't sweep me  a nywhere for an  hour  at least,' said 
line 10791=>Pippin, unslinging his pack. The others followed his example,  putting their 
line 10792=>packs against the bank and their  legs out  into the road. After a rest they 
line 10793=>had a good lunch, and then more rest. 
line 10794=>     The sun was beginning to get  low and the light of afternoon was on the 
line 10795=>land as they went down the hill. So far they had not met a soul on the road. 
line 10796=>This way was not much used, being hardly fit for carts, and there was little 
line 10797=>traffic to  the Woody End. They had been jogging along again for an hour  or 
line 10798=>more when Sam  stopped a  moment as  if  listening. They were  now on  level 
line 10799=>ground,  and  the  road  after  much  winding  lay  straight  ahead  through 
line 10800=>grass-land sprinkled with tall trees, outliers of the approaching woods.  
line 10801=>     'I can hear a pony or a horse coming along the road behind,' said Sam. 
line 10802=>     They  looked back, but the turn of the  road prevented them from seeing 
line 10803=>far. 'I wonder if that  is Gandalf coming after us,' said Frodo; but even as 
line 10804=>he said it, he had a feeling  that it was not so, and a sudden desire to hide 
line 10805=>from the view of the rider came over him. 
line 10806=>     'It  may not matter much,' he  said apologetically, 'but I would rather  
line 10807=>not be seen on the  road  - by anyone. I am  sick of my  doings being noticed  
line 10808=>and discussed. And if  it is Gandalf,' he added as  an afterthought, 'we can 
line 10809=>give him  a little surprise, to pay him out for being so late. Let's get out 
line 10810=>of sight!' 
line 10811=>     The other two ran quickly to the left and down into a little hollow not 
line 10812=>far  from the  road. There  they lay  flat. Frodo  hesitated  for  a second: 
line 10813=>curiosity or some other feeling was struggling with his desire  to hide. The 
line 10814=>sound of hoofs drew nearer. Just in time he threw himself down in a patch of 
line 10815=>long grass behind a tree that overshadowed the road. Then he lifted his head 
line 10816=>and peered cautiously above one of the great roots. 
line 10817=>     Round the  corner came  a black horse, no hobbit-pony  but a full-sized 
line 10818=>horse;  and  on  it sat  a large man,  who seemed to  crouch in  the saddle, 
line 10819=>wrapped in a great black  cloak and  hood, so that only his boots in the high 
line 10820=>stirrups showed below; his face was shadowed and invisible. 
line 10821=>     When it reached the  tree and was level with Frodo  the  horse stopped. 
line 10822=>The riding figure sat quite still with its head bowed, as if listening. From 
line 10823=>
line 10824=>####-inside the hood came  a  noise as of  someone sniffing to  catch an  elusive 
line 10825=>scent; the head turned from side to side of the road. 
line 10826=>     A sudden  unreasoning  fear of  discovery laid hold  of Frodo,  and  he 
line 10827=>thought  of his Ring. He hardly dared  to breathe,  and yet the desire to get 
line 10828=>it out of his pocket became so strong that he began slowly to move his hand. 
line 10829=>He felt  that  he had only to  slip  it on, and then he  would  be safe. The 
line 10830=>advice of Gandalf seemed absurd. Bilbo had used the Ring. 'And I am still in 
line 10831=>the Shire,' he thought, as his hand touched the chain on  which  it hung. At  
line 10832=>that moment  the  rider  sat up,  and  shook the  reins.  The  horse stepped 
line 10833=>forward, walking slowly at first, and then breaking into a quick trot. 
line 10834=>     Frodo crawled to  the edge of the road and watched the rider,  until he 
line 10835=>dwindled into the distance. He could not be quite sure, but it seemed to him 
line 10836=>that suddenly, before it  passed out  of sight,  the horse turned aside  and 
line 10837=>went into the trees on the right. 
line 10838=>     'Well, I  call that very queer, and indeed disturbing,' said  Frodo  to 
line 10839=>himself, as he  walked towards his companions. Pippin and  Sam  had remained 
line 10840=>flat  in the  grass, and had seen nothing; so Frodo  described the rider and 
line 10841=>his strange behaviour. 
line 10842=>     'I can't say why, but I felt certain he was looking or smelling for me; 
line 10843=>and also I felt certain that I did  not want him to discover  me. I've never 
line 10844=>seen or fell anything like it in the Shire before.' 
line 10845=>     'But what has  one of the Big  People got  to do with us?' said Pippin. 
line 10846=>'And what is he doing in this part of the world?' 
line 10847=>     'There are some Men about,' said Frodo. 'Down in the Southfarthing they  
line 10848=>have  had trouble  with Big  People,  I believe. But I have  never heard  of 
line 10849=>anything like this rider. I wonder  where he comes from.' 
line 10850=>     'Begging  your  pardon,' put  in Sam  suddenly,  'I know where he comes 
line 10851=>from. It's from Hobbiton that  this here black  rider comes, unless  there's 
line 10852=>more than one. And I know where he's going to.' 
line 10853=>     'What do you mean?' said Frodo sharply, looking at him in astonishment.  
line 10854=>'Why didn't you speak up before?' 
line 10855=>     'I have only just remembered, sir. It was like this: when I got back to 
line 10856=>our  hole yesterday evening with the key, my dad, he says to me: Hello, Sam! 
line 10857=>he says. I thought you were away with Mr. Frodo this morning. There's been a  
line 10858=>strange customer asking for Mr. Baggins of Bag End, and he's only just gone. 
line 10859=>I've sent him on to Bucklebury. Not that I liked the sound of him. He seemed 
line 10860=>mighty put out, when I told him Mr. Baggins had  left his old home for good. 
line 10861=>
line 10862=>####-Hissed at me, he did.  It gave me quite a shudder. What sort of a fellow was  
line 10863=>he? says I to the Gaffer. / don't know,  says he; but he wasn't a hobbit. He 
line 10864=>was tall and black-like, and he  stooped aver me. I reckon it was one of the 
line 10865=>Big Folk from foreign parts. He spoke funny. 
line 10866=>     'I  couldn't stay  to  hear more, sir, since  you were  waiting; and  I 
line 10867=>didn't give much heed to it myself. The Gaffer is getting old, and more than 
line 10868=>a bit blind,  and it  must have been  near dark when this fellow come up the 
line 10869=>Hill  and  found him taking the air at the end of our Row. I hope  he hasn't 
line 10870=>done no harm, sir, nor me.' 
line 10871=>     'The Gaffer can't be blamed anyway,' said Frodo. 'As a matter of fact I 
line 10872=>heard him talking to a  stranger, who  seemed to  be inquiring for me, and I 
line 10873=>nearly went and asked him who it was. I wish I had, or you had told me about 
line 10874=>it before. I might have been more careful on the road.' 
line 10875=>     'Still, there may be no connexion between  this rider and the  Gaffer's 
line 10876=>stranger,' said Pippin. 'We left Hobbiton  secretly enough, and  I don't see 
line 10877=>how he could have followed us.' 
line 10878=>     'What about the smelling, sir?' said Sam. 'And the Gaffer said he was a  
line 10879=>black chap.' 
line 10880=>     'I wish  I had  waited  for  Gandalf,' Frodo  muttered. 'But perhaps it 
line 10881=>would only have made matters worse.' 
line 10882=>     'Then you know  or guess something about this  rider?' said Pippin, who 
line 10883=>had caught the muttered words.  
line 10884=>     'I don't know, and I would rather  not guess,'  said Frodo. 'All right, 
line 10885=>cousin Frodo! You can  keep your  secret for the present,  if you want to be 
line 10886=>mysterious. In the meanwhile what are we to do? I should like a  bite and  a  
line 10887=>sup,  but somehow  I think  we had better move on from here.  Your  talk  of 
line 10888=>sniffing riders with invisible noses has unsettled me.' 
line 10889=>     'Yes, I think we  will move on now,' said Frodo;  'but  not on the road 
line 10890=>-in case  that rider comes back, or another  follows him. We  ought to do  a  
line 10891=>good step more today. Buckland is still miles away.' 
line 10892=>     The shadows  of  the trees  were long and  thin  on the  grass, as they 
line 10893=>started off again. They now kept  a stone's throw to  the left of  the road, 
line 10894=>and kept out of sight of it as much  as they  could. But this hindered them; 
line 10895=>for the grass was thick and  tussocky, and the ground uneven, and the  trees 
line 10896=>began to draw together into thickets.  
line 10897=>     The sun had gone down  red behind the hills at their backs, and evening 
line 10898=>was coming on before they came back to the road at the end of the long level 
line 10899=>
line 10900=>####-over which  it had run straight for  some miles.  At that point it bent left 
line 10901=>and  went down into the lowlands of  the Yale  making for Stock;  but a lane 
line 10902=>branched right, winding  through a  wood of ancient oak-trees on its way  to 
line 10903=>Woodhall. 'That is the way for us,' said Frodo. 
line 10904=>     Not far from the road-meeting they came on the huge hulk  of a tree: it 
line 10905=>was  still alive  and had leaves  on  the small branches that it had put out 
line 10906=>round the  broken  stumps of its long-fallen limbs; but it  was hollow,  and 
line 10907=>could  be entered  by  a great  crack  on the  side  away from the road. The 
line 10908=>hobbits crept inside, and sat there upon a floor  of old leaves and  decayed 
line 10909=>wood.  They rested and had a light  meal, talking quietly and listening from 
line 10910=>time to time. 
line 10911=>     Twilight  was about  them as they crept back to the lane. The West wind 
line 10912=>was sighing in the branches. Leaves were whispering. Soon the  road began to 
line 10913=>fall gently but steadily into the dusk. A  star  came out above the trees in 
line 10914=>the darkening East before them.  They went  abreast  and in step, to keep up 
line 10915=>their spirits.  After  a time, as the stars  grew thicker and  brighter, the 
line 10916=>feeling of disquiet left them, and they no longer listened  for the sound of 
line 10917=>hoofs. They began to hum softly, as hobbits have a way of doing as they walk 
line 10918=>along,  especially  when  they  are drawing near to home at night. With most  
line 10919=>hobbits  it  is  a supper -song  or a bed-song;  but these  hobbits  hummed a  
line 10920=>walking-song (though not, of course, without any mention of supper and bed). 
line 10921=>Bilbo Baggins had made the words, to a tune  that  was as old as  the hills, 
line 10922=>and taught  it to Frodo as they walked in the  lanes of the Water -valley and 
line 10923=>talked about Adventure. 
line 10924=>     Upon the hearth the fire is red, 
line 10925=>     Beneath the roof there is a bed; 
line 10926=>     But not yet weary are our feet, 
line 10927=>     Still round the corner we may meet 
line 10928=>     A sudden tree or standing stone 
line 10929=>     That none have seen but we alone. 
line 10930=>     Tree and flower and leaf and grass, 
line 10931=>     Let them pass! Let them pass! 
line 10932=>     Hill and water under sky, 
line 10933=>     Pass them by! Pass them by! 
line 10934=> 
line 10935=>     Still round the corner there may  wait 
line 10936=>     A new road or a secret gate, 
line 10937=>
line 10938=>####-     And though we pass them by today, 
line 10939=>     Tomorrow we may come this way 
line 10940=>     And take the hidden paths that run 
line 10941=>     Towards the Moon or to the Sun. 
line 10942=>     Apple, thorn, and nut and sloe, 
line 10943=>     Let them go! Let them go! 
line 10944=>     Sand and stone and pool and dell, 
line 10945=>     Fare you well! Fare you well! 
line 10946=> 
line 10947=>     Home is behind, the world ahead, 
line 10948=>     And there are many paths to tread 
line 10949=>     Through shadows to the edge of night, 
line 10950=>     Until the stars are all alight. 
line 10951=>     Then world behind and home ahead, 
line 10952=>     We'll wander back to home and bed. 
line 10953=>     Mist and twilight, cloud and shade, 
line 10954=>     Away shall fade! Away shall fade! 
line 10955=>     Fire and lamp, and meat and bread, 
line 10956=>     And then to bed! And then to bed! 
line 10957=>     The song ended. 'And now to bed! And now to bed!' sang Pippin in a high 
line 10958=>voice. 
line 10959=>     'Hush!' said Frodo. 'I think I hear hoofs again.' 
line 10960=>     They slopped suddenly  and  stood as silent as tree-shadows, listening. 
line 10961=>There was a sound of hoofs in the lane, some way behind, but coming slow and 
line 10962=>clear down the wind. Quickly and quietly they slipped off the path, and  ran 
line 10963=>into the deeper shade under the oak-trees. 
line 10964=>     'Don't let  us go too far!' said Frodo. 'I don't want to be seen, but I 
line 10965=>want to see if it is another Black Rider.' 
line 10966=>     'Very well!' said Pippin. 'But don't forget the sniffing!' 
line 10967=>     The hoofs drew nearer. They had no time to find any hiding-place better  
line 10968=>than the general  darkness under the trees; Sam and Pippin crouched behind a 
line 10969=>large tree-bole, while  Frodo  crept back a few yards  towards  the lane. It 
line 10970=>showed grey and pale, a line  of fading light through the wood. Above it the 
line 10971=>stars were thick in the dim sky, but there was no moon. 
line 10972=>     The sound of hoofs stopped. As Frodo watched he saw something dark pass 
line 10973=>across  the lighter  space between two trees, and then halt. It looked  like 
line 10974=>the  black shade of a horse led by a smaller black  shadow. The black shadow 
line 10975=>
line 10976=>####-stood close  to the point where they had left the  path, and it  swayed from 
line 10977=>side to side. Frodo thought he heard the sound of  snuffling. The shadow bent 
line 10978=>to the ground, and then began to crawl towards him. 
line 10979=>     Once more the desire to slip on the Ring came over Frodo; but this time 
line 10980=>it was stronger than before. So strong that, almost before he  realized what 
line 10981=>he was  doing, his hand was groping  in his pocket. But at that moment there 
line 10982=>came  a sound  like mingled song and laughter. Clear voices rose and fell in  
line 10983=>the starlit air. The black shadow straightened up and retreated.  It climbed 
line 10984=>on to the  shadowy  horse  and  seemed  to  vanish  across the lane into the 
line 10985=>darkness on the other side. Frodo breathed again. 
line 10986=>     'Elves!' exclaimed Sam in a hoarse whisper. 'Elves, sir!' He would have 
line 10987=>burst  out of the trees and dashed off towards  the voices, if they  had not 
line 10988=>pulled him back. 
line 10989=>     'Yes,  it  is Elves,' said  Frodo. 'One can meet them sometimes  in the 
line 10990=>Woody End.  They don't live in the Shire, but they  wander into it in Spring 
line 10991=>and  Autumn,  out  of their own  lands away  beyond the  Tower Hills.  I  am 
line 10992=>thankful that they do! You did not  see, but  that Black  Rider stopped just  
line 10993=>here and was actually crawling towards us when the song began. As soon as he 
line 10994=>heard the voices he slipped away.' 
line 10995=>     'What  about the Elves?'  said  Sam, too  excited  to trouble about the 
line 10996=>rider. 'Can't we go and see them?' 
line 10997=>     'Listen! They are coming this way,' said Frodo. 'We have only to wait.' 
line 10998=>The singing drew nearer. One clear voice rose now above  the others.  It was 
line 10999=>singing in the fair elven-tongue, of which Frodo knew only a little, and the 
line 11000=>others knew nothing. Yet  the sound blending with the melody seemed to shape 
line 11001=>itself  in their thought into words which they only partly understood.  This 
line 11002=>was the song as Frodo heard it: 
line 11003=>     Snow-white! Snow-white! O Lady clear! 
line 11004=>     O Queen beyond the Western Seas! 
line 11005=>     O Light to us that wander here 
line 11006=>     Amid the world of woven trees! 
line 11007=> 
line 11008=>     Gilthoniel! O Elbereth! 
line 11009=>     Clear are thy eyes and bright thy breath! 
line 11010=>     Snow-white! Snow-white! We sing to thee 
line 11011=>     In a far land beyond the Sea. 
line 11012=> 
line 11013=>
line 11014=>####-     O stars that in the Sunless Year 
line 11015=>     With shining hand by her were sawn, 
line 11016=>     In windy fields now bright and clear 
line 11017=>     We see your silver blossom blown! 
line 11018=> 
line 11019=>     O Elbereth! Gilthoniel! 
line 11020=>     We still remember, we who dwell 
line 11021=>     In this far land beneath the trees, 
line 11022=>     Thy starlight on the Western Seas. 
line 11023=>     The  song  ended.  'These  are High  Elves!  They  spoke  the  name  of 
line 11024=>Elbereth!' said Frodo in amazement,  'Few of that fairest folk are ever seen 
line 11025=>in the Shire. Not many now remain in Middle-earth,  east  of the  Great Sea. 
line 11026=>This is indeed a strange chance!' 
line 11027=>     The hobbits  sat in shadow  by the wayside. Before long the Elves  came 
line 11028=>down the lane towards the valley. They  passed slowly, and the hobbits could 
line 11029=>see the starlight glimmering on their hair and  in their  eyes. They bore no  
line 11030=>lights,  yet as they walked a  shimmer, like the light of the moon above the 
line 11031=>rim of the hills before it rises, seemed to fall about their feet. They were 
line 11032=>now silent, and  as the last Elf  passed  he turned  and looked  towards the 
line 11033=>hobbits and laughed. 
line 11034=>     'Hail,  Frodo!' he  cried. 'You  are  abroad  late. Or are  you perhaps 
line 11035=>lost?'  Then he called aloud  to the others, and all the company stopped and 
line 11036=>gathered round. 
line 11037=>     'This  is indeed  wonderful!'  they  said. 'Three hobbits in  a wood at 
line 11038=>night! We  have not seen  such a thing  since Bilbo went away.  What is  the 
line 11039=>meaning of it?' 
line 11040=>     'The meaning of it, fair people,'  said Frodo, 'is simply that  we seem 
line 11041=>to be going the same  way as you are. I like  walking under the stars. But I 
line 11042=>would welcome your company.' 
line 11043=>     'But we have no need of other company, and hobbits are  so  dull,' they 
line 11044=>laughed. 'And how do you know that we go the same way as you, for you do 
line 11045=>not 
line 11046=>know whither we are going?' 
line 11047=>     'And how do you know my name?' asked Frodo in return. 
line 11048=>     'We know many things,'  they said. 'We have seen you often before  with 
line 11049=>Bilbo, though you may not have seen us.' 
line 11050=>     'Who are you, and who is your lord?' asked Frodo. 
line 11051=>
line 11052=>####-     'I am Gildor,' answered their leader, the Elf who had first hailed him. 
line 11053=>'Gildor Inglorion of  the  House  of Finrod. We are Exiles, and most of  our 
line 11054=>kindred have long  ago  departed and  we  too are  now only  tarrying here a  
line 11055=>while, ere we return  over the Great Sea.  But some  of  our kinsfolk  dwell 
line 11056=>still  in peace in Rivendell.  Come now, Frodo, tell us what you  are doing?  
line 11057=>For we see that there is some shadow of fear upon you.' 
line 11058=>     'O Wise  People!' interrupted Pippin eagerly. 'Tell us about  the Black  
line 11059=>Riders!' 
line 11060=>     'Black Riders?' they said  in  low voices. 'Why  do you ask a bout Black  
line 11061=>Riders?' 
line 11062=>     'Because two Black Riders have  overtaken us today,  or one has done so 
line 11063=>twice,' said Pippin;  'only a little while ago  he slipped away as you  drew 
line 11064=>near.' 
line 11065=>     The Elves did not answer at  once, but spoke together  softly  in their 
line 11066=>own tongue.  At length Gildor turned to the  hobbits. 'We  will not speak of 
line 11067=>this here,' he said. 'We think you had  best come now with us. It is not our 
line 11068=>custom, but for this time we will lake you on our road, and  you shall lodge 
line 11069=>with us tonight, if you  will.' 
line 11070=>     'O Fair  Folk!  This is good fortune beyond my hope,' said  Pippin. Sam 
line 11071=>was speechless.  'I  thank you indeed, Gildor Inglorion,' said Frodo bowing. 
line 11072=>'Elen snla lÂ®menn' omentielvo, a star shines on the hour of our meeting,' he 
line 11073=>added in the high-elven speech. 
line 11074=>     'Be careful,  friends!' cried  Gildor laughing. 'Speak no secrets! Here 
line 11075=>is  a  scholar in  the  Ancient  Tongue.  Bilbo  was a  good  master.  Hail, 
line 11076=>Elf-friend!' he said, bowing to Frodo.  'Come now with your friends and join 
line 11077=>our company! You had best walk in the middle so  that you may not stray. You  
line 11078=>may be weary before we halt.' 
line 11079=>     'Why? Where are you going?' asked Frodo. 
line 11080=>     'For tonight we go to the woods on the hills above Woodhall. It is some 
line 11081=>miles, but  you shall have  rest at  the  end of it, and it will shorten your 
line 11082=>journey tomorrow.' 
line 11083=>     They now marched on again in silence, and passed like shadows and faint 
line 11084=>lights: for  Elves  (even  more  than hobbits)  could walk when they  wished  
line 11085=>without sound or footfall.  Pippin soon began  to feel sleepy, and staggered 
line 11086=>once  or twice; but each time a tall Elf at his side  put out  his  arm  and 
line 11087=>saved him from a  fall. Sam walked along at Frodo's side, as if in a  dream, 
line 11088=>with an expression on his face half of fear and half of astonished  joy. 
line 11089=>
line 11090=>####-     The  woods on either side became denser; the trees were now younger and 
line 11091=>thicker;  and as the lane went lower, running down into a fold of the hills, 
line 11092=>there were many deep brakes of hazel on the rising slopes at either hand. At  
line 11093=>last the Elves turned aside from the path.  A  green ride  lay almost unseen 
line 11094=>through the  thickets on the right; and this they  followed as it wound away 
line 11095=>back up the  wooded slopes on to the  top of a shoulder of  the  hills  that 
line 11096=>stood out into the lower land of the river -valley. Suddenly they came out of 
line 11097=>the shadow of  the trees, and  before them lay a  wide space of  grass, grey 
line 11098=>under the night. On three sides the woods  pressed upon it; but eastward the 
line 11099=>ground fell steeply and the tops of the dark trees, growing at the bottom of 
line 11100=>the slope,  were  below their feet. Beyond, the  low lands  lay dim and flat 
line 11101=>under the stars.  Nearer  at hand  a few lights twinkled  in the village  of 
line 11102=>Woodhall. 
line 11103=>     The  Elves sat on  the grass  and spoke  together in  soft voices; they 
line 11104=>seemed to take no further  notice of the hobbits.  Frodo and his  companions 
line 11105=>wrapped themselves in cloaks and blankets, and drowsiness stole  over  them. 
line 11106=>The  night grew  on,  and  the  lights in the valley  went out. Pippin  fell 
line 11107=>asleep, pillowed on a green hillock. 
line 11108=>     Away  high  in the East swung Remmirath,  the Netted Stars,  and slowly 
line 11109=>above  the mists red Borgil rose, glowing like a jewel of fire. Then by some 
line 11110=>shift of airs all the mist was drawn away like a veil, and there leaned  up, 
line 11111=>as  he  climbed  over  the  rim  of the  world, the  Swordsman  of  the  Sky, 
line 11112=>Menelvagor with  his shining  belt. The  Elves all burst into song. Suddenly 
line 11113=>under the trees a fire sprang up with a red light. 
line 11114=>     'Come!' the  Elves called to the hobbits. 'Come!  Now is  the time  for 
line 11115=>speech and merriment!' 
line 11116=>     Pippin sat up and rubbed his eyes. He shivered. 'There is a fire in the 
line 11117=>hall, and food for hungry guests,' said an Elf standing before him. 
line 11118=>     At the south  end of the greensward  there  was an opening.  There  the 
line 11119=>green  floor  ran on into the wood, and formed a  wide  space like  a  hall, 
line 11120=>roofed by the boughs of trees. Their great trunks ran like pillars down each 
line 11121=>side. In the middle there was a wood-fire blazing, and upon the tree-pillars 
line 11122=>torches with lights of gold and silver were burning  steadily. The Elves sat 
line 11123=>round the  fire upon the grass or  upon the  sawn  rings of old trunks. Some 
line 11124=>went  to  and  fro bearing cups and  pouring  drink; others brought  food on 
line 11125=>heaped plates and dishes.  
line 11126=>     'This  is poor fare,' they said  to the hobbits; 'for we are lodging in 
line 11127=>
line 11128=>####-the greenwood far from  our halls. If ever  you are our guests at  home,  we 
line 11129=>will treat you better.' 
line 11130=>     'It seems to me good enough for a birthday-party,' said Frodo. 
line 11131=>     Pippin afterwards recalled little o f either food or drink, for his mind 
line 11132=>was  filled  with the  light upon the elf-faces, and the  sound of voices so 
line 11133=>various and so beautiful that he felt in a waking  dream.  But he remembered  
line 11134=>that there was bread, surpassing the savour of a fair white  loaf to one who 
line 11135=>is starving;  and fruits  sweet  as  wildberries  and richer than the tended 
line 11136=>fruits of gardens; he drained a cup that was filled with a fragrant draught, 
line 11137=>cool as a clear fountain, golden as a summer afternoon. 
line 11138=>     Sam could never describe in words, nor picture clearly to himself, what 
line 11139=>he felt or thought that  night, though it remained in  his  memory as one of 
line 11140=>the chief  events of his life.  The  nearest he  ever got was to say: 'Well, 
line 11141=>sir, if I could grow  apples like that, I would call  myself a gardener. But 
line 11142=>it was the singing that went to my heart, if you know what I mean.' 
line 11143=>     Frodo sat, eating, drinking, and talking with delight; but his mind was 
line 11144=>chiefly on the words spoken. He knew a little of the elf-speech and listened 
line 11145=>eagerly. Now and again he spoke to those that served him and thanked them in 
line 11146=>their own language. They smiled at  him  and said laughing: 'Here is a jewel 
line 11147=>among hobbits!' 
line 11148=>     After a while Pippin fell fast asleep, and was lifted up and borne away 
line 11149=>to a bower under the trees; there he was laid upon a soft bed and  slept the 
line 11150=>rest  of the night away. Sam refused to  leave  his  master. When Pippin had 
line 11151=>gone, he came and sat curled up at Frodo's feet, where at last he nodded and 
line 11152=>closed his eyes. Frodo remained long awake, talking with Gildor. 
line 11153=>     They  spoke of many things, old  and new,  and Frodo questioned  Gildor  
line 11154=>much about happenings  in the wide world outside the Shire. The tidings were 
line 11155=>mostly  sad and ominous: of  gathering  darkness, the wars  of Men,  and the 
line 11156=>flight of the Elves. At last Frodo asked  the question  that  was nearest to 
line 11157=>his heart: 
line 11158=>     'Tell me, Gildor, have you ever seen Bilbo since he left us?' 
line 11159=>     Gildor  smiled.  'Yes,' he answered.  'Twice. He said farewell to us on 
line 11160=>this very  spot. But I saw  him once again, far  from here.' He would say no 
line 11161=>more about Bilbo, and Frodo fell silent. 
line 11162=>     'You do not ask me or tell me much that concerns yourself, Frodo,' said 
line 11163=>Gildor. 'But I already know a little, and I  can read more in your  face and 
line 11164=>in the thought behind your questions. You are leaving the Shire, and yet you  
line 11165=>
line 11166=>####-doubt that you will find  what you seek, or accomplish what  you intend,  or  
line 11167=>that you will ever return. Is not that so?' 
line 11168=>     'It is,' said Frodo; 'but I thought my going was a secret known only to 
line 11169=>Gandalf and my faithful Sam.' He looked down at Sam, who was snoring 
line 11170=>gently. 
line 11171=>     'The secret will not reach the Enemy from us,' said Gildor. 
line 11172=>     'The Enemy?' said Frodo. 'Then you know why I am leaving the Shire?' 
line 11173=>     'I  do not know  for what  reason the Enemy is pursuing you,'  answered 
line 11174=>Gildor; 'but I perceive that he is  - strange indeed though that seems to me. 
line 11175=>And I warn  you  that peril is now both before you  and behind you, and upon 
line 11176=>either side.' 
line 11177=>     'You  mean the Riders? I feared  that  they were servants of the Enemy. 
line 11178=>What are the Black Riders?' 
line 11179=>     'Has Gandalf told you nothing?' 
line 11180=>     'Nothing about such creatures.' 
line 11181=>     'Then I think it  is not  for me to say more  - lest terror should keep 
line 11182=>you from your journey. For it seems to me that you  have set out only just in 
line 11183=>time, if  indeed you are in time. You must now make  haste, and neither stay 
line 11184=>nor turn back; for the Shire is no longer any protection to you.' 
line 11185=>     'I cannot  imagine what information could be more terrifying  than your 
line 11186=>hints  and warnings,' exclaimed Frodo. 'I knew  that  danger lay  ahead,  of 
line 11187=>course; but I did not expect to  meet it in  our  own Shire.  Can't a hobbit 
line 11188=>walk from the Water to the River in peace?' 
line 11189=>     'But  it is not your own Shire,' said Gildor. 'Others dwelt here before 
line 11190=>hobbits were; and others will dwell here again when hobbits are no more. The 
line 11191=>wide world is all about you: you can fence yourselves in, but you cannot for  
line 11192=>ever fence it out.' 
line 11193=>     'I know - and yet it has always seemed so safe and familiar. What can I 
line 11194=>do  now?  My  plan was  to  leave  the Shire  secretly, and  make my  way to 
line 11195=>Rivendell; but now my footsteps are dogged, before ever I get to Buckland.' 
line 11196=>     'I  think you should still follow that  plan,'  said Gildor.  'I do not 
line 11197=>think the Road  will prove too  hard for  your courage. But  if  you  desire 
line 11198=>clearer counsel, you should ask  Gandalf. I do not know the reason  for your  
line 11199=>flight, and therefore I do not know by what means your  pursuers will assail  
line 11200=>you. These things Gandalf must know. I suppose that you  will see him before 
line 11201=>you leave the Shire?' 
line 11202=>     'I hope so. But that is another  thing that  makes  me anxious. I  have 
line 11203=>
line 11204=>####-been expecting Gandalf for many days. He was to have come to Hobbiton at 
line 11205=>the 
line 11206=>latest two  nights  ago; but he has  never appeared. Now I am wondering what 
line 11207=>can have happened. Should I wait for him?' 
line 11208=>     Gildor  was silent for a moment. 'I do not like this news,' he said  at 
