line 11210=>not meddle  in  the  affairs  o f Wizards, for they  are subtle  and quick to  
line 11211=>anger. The choice is yours: to go or wait.' 
line 11212=>     'And  it  is also  said,'  answered  Frodo:  'Go not  to the  Elves for 
line 11213=>counsel, for they will say both no and yes.' 
line 11214=>     'Is it  indeed?' laughed Gildor. 'Elves  seldom give  unguarded advice, 
line 11215=>for advice is a  dangerous gift,  even from  the  wise to the wise, and  all 
line 11216=>courses may run ill. But what would you? You have not told me all concerning 
line 11217=>yourself; and how then shall  I choose better  than you? But if  you  demand  
line 11218=>advice, I will for friendship's sake give it.  I think you  should now go at 
line 11219=>once, without delay; and if Gandalf does not come before you set out, then I  
line 11220=>also advise  this:  do not  go  alone. Take such friends  as are trusty  and 
line 11221=>willing. Now you should be grateful, for I do  not give this counsel gladly. 
line 11222=>The Elves have their  own labours and their own sorrows, and they are little  
line 11223=>concerned  with the ways of  hobbits,  or of any other creatures upon earth. 
line 11224=>Our  paths cross theirs seldom, by chance or purpose. In this meeting  there 
line 11225=>may be more than chance; but the purpose  is not clear to  me, and I fear to 
line 11226=>say too much.' 
line 11227=>     'I am  deeply grateful,' said  Frodo;  'but  I  wish you would  tell me 
line 11228=>plainly what the  Black  Riders  are. If I  take your  advice I may not  see 
line 11229=>Gandalf for  a  long while,  and I ought to know what  is  the  danger  that 
line 11230=>pursues me.' 
line 11231=>     'Is  it not  enough to  know  that they  are servants  of  the  Enemy?' 
