line 11254=>Chapter 4. A Short Cut to Mushrooms 
line 11255=>
line 11256=> 
line 11257=> 
line 11258=>     In the morning Frodo woke refreshed. He was lying in  a bower made by a 
line 11259=>living tree  with branches laced  and drooping to the ground; his bed was of 
line 11260=>fern and grass,  deep and soft  and  strangely fragrant. The sun was shining 
line 11261=>through  the fluttering leaves,  which were still green  upon the  tree.  He 
line 11262=>jumped up and went out. 
line 11263=>     Sam  was  sitting  on the grass near the  edge  of the wood. Pippin was 
line 11264=>standing studying the sky and weather. There was no sign of the Elves.  
line 11265=>     'They have left us fruit  and drink, and bread,' said Pippin. 'Come and 
line 11266=>have your breakfast. The bread tastes almost as good as it did last night. I 
line 11267=>did not want to leave you any, but Sam insisted.' 
line 11268=>     Frodo  sat  down  beside  Sam and began  to eat. 'Wha t is the  plan for  
line 11269=>today?' asked Pippin. 
line 11270=>     'To  walk  to Bucklebury as  quickly as possible,'  answered Frodo, and 
line 11271=>gave his attention to the food. 
line 11272=>     'Do you think  we shall see  anything  of  those Riders?' asked  Pippin 
line 11273=>cheerfully. Under  the  morning  sun the prospect of seeing a whole troop of 
line 11274=>them did not seem very alarming to him. 
line 11275=>     'Yes, probably,' said Frodo, not liking  the reminder. 'But  I  hope to 
line 11276=>get across the river without their seeing us.' 
line 11277=>     'Did you find out anything about them from Gildor?' 
line 11278=>     'Not much  - only hints and riddles,' said Frodo evasively. 'Did you ask  
line 11279=>about the sniffing?' 
line 11280=>     'We didn't discuss it,' said Frodo with his mouth full. 
line 11281=>     'You should have. I am sure it is very important.' 
line 11282=>     'In that case I am sure Gildor would have refused  to explain it,' said 
line 11283=>Frodo sharply. 'And now leave me in peace  for a bit! I don't want to answer  
line 11284=>a string of questions while I am eating. I want to think!' 
line 11285=>     'Good heavens!' said Pippin. 'At breakfast?' He walked away towards the 
line 11286=>edge of the green. 
line 11287=>     From Frodo's mind the bright morning - treacherously bright, he thought  
line 11288=>- had not banished the fear of pursuit; and he pondered the words of Gildor. 
line 11289=>The merry voice of Pippin came to him. He was running  on the green turf and 
line 11290=>singing. 
line 11291=>
line 11292=>####-     'No!  I could  not!' he said  to  himself.  'It is one thing to take my 
line 11293=>young friends walking over the Shire with me, until we are hungry and weary, 
line 11294=>and food  and  bed are  sweet.  To  take them into exile,  where  hunger and 
line 11295=>weariness may ha ve  no cure,  is quite another  - even if they are willing to 
line 11296=>come. The inheritance  is mine  alone.  I don't think I  ought  even to take 
line 11297=>Sam.' He looked at Sam Gamgee, and discovered that Sam was watching him. 
line 11298=>     'Well, Sam!' he said. 'What about it? I am leaving the Shire as soon as 
line 11299=>ever I  can - in fact I  have made up my mind now not even to wait  a day at 
line 11300=>Crickhollow, if it can be helped.' 
line 11301=>     'Very good, sir!' 
line 11302=>     'You still mean to come with me?' 
line 11303=>     'I do.' 
line 11304=>     'It  is going to be very dangerous, Sam. 'It is already dangerous. Most  
line 11305=>likely neither of us will come back.' 
line 11306=>     'If you don't come back, sir, then I shan't, that's certain,' said Sam. 
line 11307=>'Don't you leave him! they said to me. Leave him! I said. I never mean to. I 
line 11308=>am  going  with  him, if   he climbs to the Moon,  and if  any of those Black 
line 11309=>Rulers try to stop him, they'll have Sam Gamgee to reckon with, I said. They 
line 11310=>laughed.' 
line 11311=>     'Who are they, and what are you talking about?' 
line 11312=>     'The  Elves, sir. We had some talk last night; and  they seemed to know 
line 11313=>you were going away, so I didn't see the use of denying  it. Wonderful folk, 
line 11314=>Elves, sir! Wonderful!' 
line 11315=>     'They are,' said Frodo.  'Do you like  them still,  now  you have had a  
line 11316=>closer view?' 
line 11317=>     'They  seem a bit above my likes and dislikes,  so  to speak,' answered 
line 11318=>Sam slowly. 'It don't seem to matter what I think about them. They are quite 
line 11319=>different from what I expected - so old and young, and so gay and sad, as it 
line 11320=>were.' 
line 11321=>     Frodo looked at Sam rather startled, half expecting to see some  outward 
line 11322=>sign of the odd change that seemed  to have come  over him. It did not sound 
line 11323=>like the voice of the old Sam Gamgee that he thought he  knew. But it looked 
line 11324=>like the old  Sam Gamgee sitting  there, except that  his face was unusually 
line 11325=>thoughtful. 
line 11326=>     'Do  you feel any  need to  leave the Shire now  - now that your wish to 
line 11327=>see them has come true already?' he asked. 
line 11328=>     'Yes,  sir. I  don't  know how to  say it, but after last night  I feel 
line 11329=>
line 11330=>####-different. I seem to see ahead, in a kind  of way.  I know  we are going  to 
line 11331=>take a very long road, into darkness; but I know I can't turn back. It isn't  
line 11332=>to see Elves now, nor dragons, nor mountains, that  I want  - I don't rightly 
line 11333=>know what I  want: but I  have something to do before the end, and  it  lies 
line 11334=>ahead, not  in the Shire. I must see it through, sir, if you understand me.' 
line 11335=>     'I don't  altogether.  But I  understand  that Gandalf chose me a  good 
line 11336=>companion. I am content. We will go together.' 
line 11337=>     Frodo finished his  breakfast in silence.  Then standing  up he  looked 
line 11338=>over the land ahead, and called to Pippin. 
line 11339=>     'All ready to start?' he said as Pippin ran up. 'We must be getting off 
line 11340=>at once. We slept late; and there are a good many miles to go.' 
line 11341=>     'You slept  late, you mean,' said Pippin. 'I was up long before; and we 
line 11342=>are only waiting for you to finish eating and thinking.' 
line 11343=>     'I  have finished both now. And I am going to make for Bucklebury Ferry 
line 11344=>as quickly  as possible. I am not  going out of the way, back to the road we 
line 11345=>left last night: I am going to  cut straight across country from here.' 
line 11346=>     'Then you are going to fly,'  said Pippin.  'You  won't cut straight on 
line 11347=>foot anywhere in this country.' 
line 11348=>     'We  can  cut  straighter than the road anyway,'  answered  Frodo. 'The 
line 11349=>Ferry is east from Woodhall;  but the hard road curves away to the left  -you  
line 11350=>can see a bend of it away north over there. It goes round  the north  end of 
line 11351=>the Marish so as to  strike  the causeway from  the  Bridge above Stock. But 
line 11352=>that is miles out of the way.  We could save a quarter  of the distance if we 
line 11353=>made a line for the Ferry from where we stand.' 
line 11354=>     'Short cuts make  long delays,' argued  Pippin. 'The  country  is rough 
line 11355=>round  here, and  there are bogs and  all  kinds of difficulties down in the 
line 11356=>Marish -I know the land  in these parts. And if you are worrying about Black 
line 11357=>Riders, I can't  see that it is any worse meeting  them on  a road than in a  
line 11358=>wood or a field.' 
line 11359=>     'It is  less  easy  to find people in the  woods and  fields,' answered 
line 11360=>Frodo. 'And if you are supposed to be on the road, there is some chance that 
line 11361=>you will be looked for on the road and not off it.' 
line 11362=>     'All right!' said Pippin. 'I will follow  you into every bog and ditch. 
line 11363=>But it is  hard! I had counted  on  passing the Golden Perch at Stock before 
line 11364=>sundown. The best beer in the Eastfarthing, or used to be: it is a long time 
line 11365=>since I tasted it.' 
line 11366=>     'That settles it!'  said Frodo. 'Short cuts  make delays, but inns make 
line 11367=>
line 11368=>####-longer  ones. At all costs we must  keep  you away from the Golden Perch. We 
line 11369=>want to get to Bucklebury before dark. What do you say, Sam?' 
line 11370=>     'I  will go  along with you, Mr. Frodo,' said Sam (in spite of  private 
line 11371=>misgiving and a deep regret for the best beer in the Eastfarthing). 
line 11372=>     'Then  if we are going to toil  through bog and briar, let's  go  now!' 
line 11373=>said Pippin. 
line 11374=>     It was  already nearly as hot as it had been the day before; but clouds 
line 11375=>were  beginning  to come up from the West. It looked likely to turn to rain. 
line 11376=>The hobbits scrambled down a steep  green  bank and  plunged into the  thick 
line 11377=>trees below. Their course  had been chosen to  leave Woodhall to their left, 
line 11378=>and  to cut slanting through the woods that clustered along the eastern side 
line 11379=>of  the  hills,  until they reached the flats  beyond. Then they  could make 
line 11380=>straight  for the Ferry over country that was open, except for a few ditches 
line 11381=>and fences. Frodo reckoned they had eighteen miles to go in a straight line. 
line 11382=>     He soon found that the thicket was closer and more tangled than it  had 
line 11383=>appeared. There were no paths  in the  undergrowth, and they did not  get on 
line 11384=>very  fast.  When they had struggled to the bottom of the bank, they found a  
line 11385=>stream  running  down from  the hills behind in a deeply dug bed with  steep 
line 11386=>slippery sides overhung with brambles. Most inconveniently it cut across the 
line 11387=>line they had chosen. They could  not jump over it, nor indeed get across it 
line 11388=>at  all without  getting wet, scratched, and muddy.  They  halted, wondering  
line 11389=>what to do.  'First check!' said Pippin, smiling grimly. 
line 11390=>     Sam Gamgee  looked back.  Through an opening  in  the trees he caught a 
line 11391=>glimpse of the top of the green bank from which they had climbed down. 
line 11392=>     'Look!'  he said, clutching  Frodo by the  arm. They all looked, and on 
line 11393=>the edge high above  them they saw against the sky a horse  standing. Beside 
line 11394=>it stooped a black figure. 
line 11395=>     They  at once gave  up any  idea of going back. Frodo led  the way, and 
line 11396=>plunged quickly into the  thick bushes beside the stream. 'Whew!' he said to  
line 11397=>Pippin. 'We were both right! The short cut has gone crooked already; but   we 
line 11398=>got under  cover only just in time. You've got sharp ears, Sam: can you hear  
line 11399=>anything coming?' 
line 11400=>     They  stood still,  almost holding  their breath as  they listened; but 
line 11401=>there was  no sound  of pursuit. 'I  don't fancy  he  would try bringing his 
line 11402=>hor se down that bank,' said Sam. 'But I guess he  knows we came down it.  We 
line 11403=>had better be going on.' 
line 11404=>     Going  on was  not altogether easy.  They had packs  to carry,  and the 
line 11405=>
line 11406=>####-bushes and  brambles were reluctant to  let  them through. They were cut off  
line 11407=>from the wind by  the ridge behind, and the air  was still  and stuffy. When 
line 11408=>they forced their way at last into more open ground, they were hot and tired 
line 11409=>and very scratched, and they were also no longer certain of the direction in 
line 11410=>which they  were  going.  The banks of  the stream sank,  as it reached  the 
line 11411=>levels and  became broader  and shallower,  wandering off towards the Marish 
line 11412=>and the River. 
line 11413=>     'Why,  this  is  the Stock-brook!' said Pippin. 'If we are going to try 
line 11414=>and get back on to our course, we must  cross at once and bear right.' 
line 11415=>     They waded  the  stream, and hurried over a wide open space, rush-grown 
line 11416=>and treeless, on the  further side. Beyond that they came again to a belt of 
line 11417=>trees: tall oaks, for the most part, with here  and there an elm tree or  an 
line 11418=>ash. The ground was fairly level, and  there was little undergrowth; but the 
line 11419=>trees were loo close for them to see far  ahead.  The leaves blew upwards in 
line 11420=>sudden gusts of wind, and spots of rain began to fall from the overcast sky. 
line 11421=>Then the wind died  away and the rain came streaming down. They trudged 
line 11422=>along 
line 11423=>as fast as they could, over patches of grass, and through  thick  drifts  of 
line 11424=>old leaves; and all about them the rain pattered  and trickled. They did not 
line 11425=>talk, but kept glancing back, and from side to side. 
line 11426=>     After  half an hour Pippin said: 'I hope  we  have not turned  too much 
line 11427=>towards the south, and are not walking longwise through this wood! It is not  
line 11428=>a very broad belt --I should  have said  no more than a mile at the widest  - 
line 11429=>and we ought to have been through it by now.' 
line 11430=>     'It is no good our starting to go in zig-zags,' said Frodo. 'That won't  
line 11431=>mend  matters. Let us keep on as we  are going! I am not sure that I want to 
line 11432=>come out into the open yet.' 
line 11433=>     They  went on for perhaps another couple of miles. Then the sun gleamed 
line 11434=>out of ragged clouds  again and the rain  lessened. It was now past mid-day,  
line 11435=>and they felt it was high time for lunch. They halted under an elm tree: its 
line 11436=>leaves  though fast turning yellow were still thick, and the  ground at  its 
line 11437=>feel  was fairly dry and sheltered. When  they came to make their meal, they 
line 11438=>found that  the  Elves had  filled their bottles  with  a  clear drink, pale 
line 11439=>golden in colour: it had the scent of a honey made  of many flowers, and was 
line 11440=>wonderfully  refreshing. Very soon they  were  laughing, and snapping  their  
line 11441=>fingers at rain, and at Black Riders.  The last few  miles, they felt, would 
line 11442=>soon be behind them. 
line 11443=>
line 11444=>####-     Frodo propped his back against the tree-trunk, and closed his eyes. Sam 
line 11445=>and Pippin sat near, and they began to hum, and then to sing softly: 
line 11446=>     Ho! Ho! Ho! to the bottle I go 
line 11447=>     To heal my heart and drown my woe. 
line 11448=>     Rain may fall and wind may blow,  
line 11449=>     And many miles be still to go, 
line 11450=>     But under a tall tree I will lie, 
line 11451=>     And let the clouds go sailing by. 
line 11452=>     Ho! Ho! Ho! they began again louder. They stopped short suddenly. Frodo 
line 11453=>sprang to his feet. A long-drawn wail came  down the wind, like  the  cry of 
line 11454=>some evil  and  lonely  creature.  It  rose and fell, and  ended  on  a high 
line 11455=>piercing  note. Even as  they sat and stood, as  if suddenly frozen,  it was 
line 11456=>answered by another  cry, fainter and further off, but no less  chilling  to 
line 11457=>the blood. There was then a silence, broken only by the sound of the wind in 
line 11458=>the leaves. 
line 11459=>     'And what do you think that was?' Pippin asked at last, trying to speak 
line 11460=>lightly, but quavering a little. 'If it was a bird, it was  one that I never  
line 11461=>heard in the Shire before.' 
line 11462=>     'It was not bird or beast,' said Frodo. 'It was a call, or  a signal -- 
line 11463=>there were words in that cry, though  I  could not catch them. But no hobbit 
line 11464=>has such a voice.' 
line 11465=>     No more was said about it. They were all thinking of the Riders, but no 
line 11466=>one  spoke of them. They  were now reluctant either to  stay  or go  on; but 
line 11467=>sooner or  later they had got to  get across the  open country to the Ferry, 
line 11468=>and  it was best to go  sooner  and  in daylight.  In a few moments they had 
line 11469=>shouldered their packs again and were off. 
line 11470=>     Before long the wood came  to a  sudden end. Wide grass-lands stretched 
line 11471=>before them. They now saw that  they had, in  fact, turned too much  to  the 
line 11472=>south.  Away over  the  flats  they could glimpse the low hill of Bucklebury 
line 11473=>across the River, but it was now to their left. Creeping cautiously out from 
line 11474=>the edge of the trees,  they set off  across  the  open  as  quickly as they 
line 11475=>could. 
line 11476=>     At first they felt afraid, away from the shelter of  the wood. Far back  
line 11477=>behind them stood the  high place  where  they had  breakfasted.  Frodo half 
line 11478=>expected to see the small distant  figure of  a horseman on  the ridge  dark 
line 11479=>against  the sky; but there was  no sign of  one. The  sun escaping from the 
line 11480=>breaking clouds, as it sank towards the hills they had left, was now shining 
line 11481=>
line 11482=>####-brightly again. Their fear left them, though they still felt uneasy. But the 
line 11483=>land  became  steadily  more  tame and  well-ordered.  Soon they  came  into  
line 11484=>well-tended fields and meadows: there were  hedges  and gates  and dikes for 
line 11485=>drainage. Everything seemed quiet and peaceful, just an  ordinary corner  of 
line 11486=>the Shire. Their spirits rose with every step. The  line  of  the River grew 
line 11487=>nearer; and the Black Riders began  to seem  like phantoms of  the woods now 
line 11488=>left far behind. 
line 11489=>     They passed along the edge of a huge turnip-field, and  came to a stout 
line 11490=>gate.  Beyond it a  rutted  lane ran between low well-laid hedges towards  a  
line 11491=>distant clump of trees. Pippin stopped. 
line 11492=>     'I know these fields and this gate!' he said. 'This is Bamfurlong,  old 
line 11493=>Farmer Maggot's land. That's his farm away there in the trees.' 
line 11494=>     'One trouble after  another!' said Frodo, looking nearly as much alarmed 
line 11495=>as if Pippin  had declared the lane was the slot leading to  a dragon's den. 
line 11496=>The others looked at him in surprise. 
line 11497=>     'What's wrong with  old Maggot?' asked Pippin.  'He's a good  friend to 
line 11498=>all the  Brandy  bucks.  Of course he's  a terror to trespassers, and  keeps 
line 11499=>ferocious  dogs  - but after all, folk down here are near the border and have 
line 11500=>to be more on their guard.' 
line 11501=>     'I  know,' said  Frodo. 'But all the same,' he added with  a shamefaced 
line 11502=>laugh,  'I am  terrified of  him and his dogs. I have avoided  his  farm for  
line 11503=>years and  years. He  caught me  several times trespassing after  mushrooms,  
line 11504=>when I was a youngster at Brandy Hall. On the last occasion he beat  me, and 
line 11505=>then took  me  and showed  me to his dogs. "See, lads," he  said, "next time 
line 11506=>this young varmint sets foot on my land, you can eat  him. Now see him off!" 
line 11507=>They chased me all the way to the Ferry. I have never got over the  fright  - 
line 11508=>though I  daresay  the beasts knew their business and  would not really have 
line 11509=>touched me.' 
line 11510=>     Pippin laughed. 'Well, it's time you  made it up. Especially if you are 
line 11511=>coming back to live  in Buckland. Old Maggot is really  a stout fellow -  if 
line 11512=>you leave his mushrooms alone. Let's get into the lane and then we shan't be 
line 11513=>trespassing. If we meet him, I'll do the talking. He is a friend of Merry's,  
line 11514=>and I used to come here with him a good deal at one time.' 
line 11515=>     They went along the lane, until they saw the  thatched roofs of a large 
line 11516=>house and farm-buildings peeping ou t among the trees ahead. The Maggots, 
line 11517=>and 
line 11518=>the Puddifoots of  Stock, and most of  the  inhabitants of  the Marish, were 
line 11519=>
line 11520=>####-house-dwellers; and this farm was stoutly built of brick and had a high wall 
line 11521=>all round it. There was a wide wooden gate opening out of the  wall into the  
line 11522=>lane. 
line 11523=>     Suddenly  as they drew nearer  a terrific baying and barking broke out, 
line 11524=>and a loud voice was heard shouting: 'Grip! Fang! Wolf! Come on, lads!' 
line 11525=>     Frodo and Sam stopped dead, but Pippin walked  on a few paces. The gate 
line 11526=>opened and  three  huge dogs came  pelting  out  into  the  lane, and dashed 
line 11527=>towards the travellers, barking fiercely. They took no notice of Pippin; but 
line 11528=>Sam shrank  against the wall, while  two wolvish-looking dogs sniffed at him 
line 11529=>suspiciously, and snarled if he moved. The largest and most ferocious of the 
line 11530=>three halted in front of Frodo, bristling and growling. 
line 11531=>     Through the gate there now appeared  a broad  thick -set  hobbit  with a  
line 11532=>round  red  face. 'Hallo! Hallo!  And who may you  be, and what  may you  be 
line 11533=>wanting?' he asked. 
line 11534=>     'Good afternoon, Mr. Maggot!' said Pippin. 
line 11535=>     The farmer looked at  him closely. 'Well, if it  isn't Master Pippin   - 
line 11536=>Mr. Peregrin Took, I should say!' he cried, changing from a scowl to a grin. 
line 11537=>'It's a long time since I saw you round here. It's lucky for you that I know 
line 11538=>you. I was just going out to  set my dogs  on  any strangers. There are some 
line 11539=>funny things going  on today. Of course, we do get queer folk  wandering  in  
line 11540=>these parts at times. Too near the River,' he said, shaking his  head.  'But 
line 11541=>this fellow was the most outlandish I have ever set eyes  on. He won't cross 
line 11542=>my land without leave a second time, not if I can stop it.' 
line 11543=>     'What fellow do you mean?' asked Pippin. 
line 11544=>     'Then you haven't  seen him?' said  the  farmer. 'H e  went up the  lane 
line 11545=>towards the  causeway not  a  long while back. He  was a funny  customer and 
line 11546=>asking funny questions. But perhaps you'll come along inside, and we'll pass 
line 11547=>the news more comfortable. I've a  drop  of good ale on tap, if you and your  
line 11548=>friends are willing, Mr. Took.' 
line 11549=>     It seemed plain that the  farmer would tell them more, if allowed to do 
line 11550=>it in his own time and  fashion, so they all accepted  the invitation. 'What 
line 11551=>about the dogs?' asked Frodo anxiously. 
line 11552=>     The farmer laughed.  'They  won't harm you - not unless I  tell 'em to. 
line 11553=>Here, Grip! Fang! Heel!' he cried. 'Heel, Wolf!'  To the relief of Frodo and 
line 11554=>Sam, the dogs walked away and let them go free. 
line 11555=>     Pippin introduced  the other two to the farmer. 'Mr. Frodo Baggins,' he 
line 11556=>said.  'You may not remember him, but he used to live at Brandy Hall.' At the 
line 11557=>
line 11558=>####-name Baggins the farmer started, and gave Frodo a sharp glance. For a moment 
line 11559=>Frodo thought that the memory of stolen mushrooms had been aroused, and 
line 11560=>that 
line 11561=>the dogs would be  told  to see him   off. But Farmer Maggot took him by  the 
line 11562=>arm. 
line 11563=>     'Well, if that isn't queerer than ever?'  he exclaimed. 'Mr. Baggins is 
line 11564=>it? Come inside! We must have a talk.' 
line 11565=>     They went  into the farmer's  kitchen, and sat by  the wide fire-place. 
line 11566=>Mrs. Maggot brought out  beer in  a huge jug, and filled four large mugs. It 
line 11567=>was a good brew,  and Pippin found himself more than compensated for 
line 11568=>missing 
line 11569=>the  Golden  Perch.  Sam  sipped his  beer  suspiciously.  He had a  natural 
line 11570=>mistrust of the inhabitants of other parts of the Shire; and also he was not 
line 11571=>disposed to be quick  friends with anyone who had beaten his master, however  
line 11572=>long ago. 
line 11573=>     After  a few remarks about  the weather and the agricultural  prospects 
line 11574=>(which were no worse than usual), Farmer Maggot put down his  mug and 
line 11575=>looked 
line 11576=>at them all in turn. 
line 11577=>     'Now, Mr.  Peregrin,' he  said,  'where  might you  be coming from, and 
line 11578=>where might you be going  to?  Were you coming to visit' me? For, if so, you 
line 11579=>had gone past my gate without my seeing you.' 
line 11580=>     'Well, no, '  answered Pippin.  'To tell  you the truth, since  you have 
line 11581=>guessed  it, we got into the lane from the other end: we had come  over your  
line 11582=>fields. But that was quite by accident.  We  lost our way in the woods, back  
line 11583=>near Woodhall, trying to take a short cu t to the Ferry.' 
line 11584=>     'If you were  in a hurry,  the road would have served you better,' said 
line 11585=>the farmer. 'But I wasn't worrying about  that. You have  leave to walk over  
line 11586=>my land, if you have a  mind, Mr.  Peregrin. And you, Mr. Baggins  - though I 
