line 11590=>just heard the name Baggins before  you  turned up.  What do you think  that 
line 11591=>funny customer asked me?' 
line 11592=>     They  waited anxiously for  him to go on. 'Well,' the farmer continued, 
line 11593=>approaching his point with slow relish, 'he came riding on a big black horse 
line 11594=>in at  the  gate, which  happened  to be open, and right up to my door.  All 
line 11595=>
line 11596=>####-black he was  himself, too, and cloaked and hooded up, as if he did not want 
line 11597=>to be known. "Now what  in the Shire  can  he want?" I thought to myself. We 
line 11598=>don't see many of the Big Folk over the border; and anywa y I had never heard 
line 11599=>of any like this black fellow. 
line 11600=>     ' "Good-day to you!" I says,  going  out to him. "This  lane don't lead 
line 11601=>anywhere,  and wherever  you may be going, your quickest way will be back to 
line 11602=>the road." I didn't like the looks of  him; and when  Grip came out, he took  
line 11603=>one sniff and  let out a  yelp as if he had been slung: he put down his tail 
line 11604=>and bolted off howling. The black fellow sat quite still. 
line 11605=>     ' "I come  from yonder," he  said,  slow  and stiff-like, pointing back  
