line 11607=>queer voice,  and bent  down towards  me. I could not see any face,  for his 
line 11608=>hood fell down so low; and I felt a sort of shiver down  my back. But  I did 
line 11609=>not see why he should come riding over my land so bold. 
line 11610=>     ' "Be off!" I said. "There are no Bagginses  here.  You're in the wrong 
line 11611=>part of the Shire. You had better go back west to Hobbiton  - but you can  go 
line 11612=>by road this time." 
line 11613=>     ' "Baggins has  left,"  he answered in a whisper. "He is coming. He  is 
line 11614=>not far away. I wish to find him. If he passes will you tell me? I will come 
line 11615=>back with gold." 
line 11616=>     ' "No you won't," I said.  "You'll  go back  where you  belong,  double 
line 11617=>quick. I give you one minute before I call all my dogs." 
line 11618=>     'He gave a sort  of hiss. It might have been laughing, and it might not. 
line 11619=>Then he spurred  his great  horse right  at me, and I jumped  out of the way 
line 11620=>only just in time. I called the dogs, but he swung off, and rode through the 
line 11621=>gate  and up the lane  towards the causeway like a bolt  of thunder. What do  
line 11622=>you think of that?' 
line 11623=>     Frodo sat for a moment looking at  the fire,  but  his only thought was 
line 11624=>how on earth would they  reach the Ferry. 'I don't  know what  to think,' he 
line 11625=>said at last. 
line 11626=>     'Then I'll tell you what to think,' said Maggot. 'You should never have 
line 11627=>gone  mixing yourself up with Hobbiton folk, Mr. Frodo.  Folk  are queer  up 
line 11628=>there.'  Sam  stirred in  his  chair,  and  looked  at  the  farmer  with an 
line 11629=>unfriendly  eye. 'But you were always a  reckless lad. When  I heard you had 
line 11630=>left the Brandybucks  and  gone  off  to that old Mr. Bilbo, I said that you  
line 11631=>were going to find trouble. Mark my words, this  all comes of those  strange 
line 11632=>doings of Mr. Bilbo's. His money was got in some strange fashion  in foreign 
line 11633=>
line 11634=>####-parts, they  say. Maybe there is some that want  to know what has  become of 
line 11635=>the gold and jewels that he buried in the hill of Hobbiton, as I hear?' 
line 11636=>     Frodo said  nothing:  the  shrewd  guesses of  the farmer  were  rather  
line 11637=>disconcerting. 
line 11638=>     'Well, Mr. Frodo,' Maggot went  on, 'I'm glad that you've had the sense 
line 11639=>to come back to Buckland. My  advice is: stay  there! And don't get mixed up 
line 11640=>with these outlandish folk.  You'll have  friends  in these parts. If any of 
line 11641=>these black  fellows come after you  again,  I'll  deal with  them. I'll say 
line 11642=>you're dead, or have left the Shire, or anything you like. And that might be 
line 11643=>true enough; for as like as not it is old Mr. Bilbo they want news of.' 
line 11644=>     'Maybe you're right,' said Frodo, avoiding the farmer's eye and staring 
line 11645=>at the fire. 
line 11646=>     Maggot looked at him thoughtfully. 'Well, I see  you have ideas of your 
line 11647=>own,' he said. 'It is as plain as my  nose that no  accident brought you and 
line 11648=>that rider here on the same afternoon; and maybe my  news was no  great news 
line 11649=>to you, after all.  I am not asking you to tell me anything you  have a mind 
line 11650=>to keep to yourself; but I see you are in some kind  of trouble. Perhaps you  
line 11651=>are thinking it won't be too easy to get to the Ferry without being caught?' 
line 11652=>     'I was thinking so,' said Frodo. 'But we have got to try and get there; 
line 11653=>and  it won't  be  done by sitting  and thinking. So I am afraid we must  be 
line 11654=>going.  Thank you very much indeed for your kindness! I've been in terror of 
line 11655=>you and your dogs for over thirty years, Farmer Maggot, though you may laugh 
line 11656=>to hear it. It's a pity: for I've missed a good friend. And now I'm sorry to 
line 11657=>leave so soon. But I'll come back, perhaps, one day  - if I get a chance.' 
line 11658=>     'You'll be welcome when you come,' said Maggot. 'But now I've a notion. 
line 11659=>It's near  sundown  already,  and we are going to  have our  supper; for  we 
line 11660=>mostly go to bed  soon after the Sun. If you and Mr. Peregrin and  all could 
line 11661=>stay and have a bite with us, we would be pleased!' 
line 11662=>     'And so should we!' said  Frodo. 'But  we  must  be going at once,  I'm 
line 11663=>afraid. Even now it will be dark before we can reach the Ferry.' 
line 11664=>     'Ah! but wait a minute! I was going to say: after a bit of supper, I'll 
line 11665=>gel out a small waggon,  and I'll drive you all to the Ferry. That will save 
line 11666=>you a good step, and it might also save you trouble of another sort.' 
line 11667=>     Frodo  now accepted the invitation gratefully, to the relief  of Pippin 
line 11668=>and  Sam. The sun  was  already behind the  western hills, and the light was 
line 11669=>failing.  Two  of  Maggot's  sons  and his  three  daughters came in, and  a  
line 11670=>generous  supper was  laid  on the large table.  The kitchen  was  lit  with 
line 11671=>
line 11672=>####-candles and the fire was mended. Mrs. Maggot  hustled in and out. One or two 
line 11673=>other  hobbits  belonging to the farm-household came in.  In  a short  while 
line 11674=>fourteen  sat  down to eat. There  was beer in plenty,  and a mighty dish of 
line 11675=>mushrooms  and bacon, besides much other solid farmhouse fare. The  dogs lay 
line 11676=>by the fire and gnawed rinds and cracked bones. 
line 11677=>     When they had finished, the farmer and his sons went out with a lantern 
line 11678=>and got the waggon ready. It was dark in the yard, when the guests came out. 
line 11679=>They  threw their  packs  on board  and  climbed in. The farmer sat  in  the 
line 11680=>driving-seat,  and whipped up his two stout  ponies. His  wife stood  in the 
line 11681=>light of the open door. 
line 11682=>     'You  be  careful  of yourself. Maggot!' she called. 'Don't  go arguing 
line 11683=>with any foreigners, and come straight back!' 
line 11684=>     'I will!' said he, and drove out  of the gate. There was  now no breath 
line 11685=>of wind stirring; the night was still and quiet, and a chill was in the air. 
line 11686=>They went without  lights and took it  slowly. After  a mile or two the lane 
line 11687=>came to an end, crossing a deep dike,  and climbing a short slope up  on  to 
line 11688=>the high-banked causeway. 
line 11689=>     Maggot got down and took a good look  either way, north and  south, but 
line 11690=>nothing could  be  seen  in the darkness, and  there was not a sound in  the 
line 11691=>still  air.  Thin  strands  of river -mist  were hanging above the dikes, and 
line 11692=>crawling over the fields.  
line 11693=>     'It's going  to be thick,' said Maggot; 'but  I'll not light my lantern 
line 11694=>till I turn for home. We'll hear anything on the road long before we meet it 
line 11695=>tonight.' 
line 11696=>     It was five miles or more from Maggot's lane to the Ferry. The  hobbits 
line 11697=>wrapped themselves  up, but their ears were strained for any sound above the 
line 11698=>creak  of  the wheels and the  slow clop of  the ponies' hoofs.  The  waggon 
line 11699=>seemed slower than a snail to Frodo. Beside him  Pippin was  nodding towards 
line 11700=>sleep; but Sam was staring forwards into the rising fog. 
line 11701=>     They reached the  entrance to the Ferry lane at last. It was marked  by 
line 11702=>two tall white posts  that suddenly loomed up  on their right. Farmer Maggot 
line 11703=>drew  in his  ponies  and the  waggon creaked  to a  halt.  They  were  just 
line 11704=>beginning  lo scramble out, when suddenly they heard what  they had all been 
line 11705=>dreading: hoofs on the road ahead. The sound was coming towards them. 
line 11706=>     Maggot  jumped  down  and stood holding the  ponies' heads, and peering 
line 11707=>forward into the gloom. Clip-clop, clip-clop came the approaching rider. The 
line 11708=>fall of the hoofs sounded loud in the still, foggy air. 
line 11709=>
line 11710=>####-     'You'd better be hidden, Mr. Frodo,' said  Sam anxiously. 'You get down 
line 11711=>in the waggon and cover up with  blankets, and we'll send this  rider to the 
line 11712=>rightabouts!'  He climbed out  and went to the  farmer's side.  Black Riders 
line 11713=>would have to ride over him to get near the waggon. 
line 11714=>     Clop-clop, clop-clop. The rider was nearly on them. 
line 11715=>     'Hallo there!' called Farmer Maggot. The advancing hoofs stopped short.  
line 11716=>They thought they could dimly guess a dark cloaked shape in the mist, a yard 
line 11717=>or two ahead. 'Now then!'  said the  farmer, throwing the  reins to  Sam and 
line 11718=>striding forward. 'Don't you come a step nearer! What do you want, and where 
line 11719=>are you going?' 
line 11720=>     'I want Mr. Baggins. Have you seen him?' sa id a muffled voice - but the 
line 11721=>voice was  the voice of Merry Brandybuck.  A dark lantern was uncovered, and 
line 11722=>its light fell on the astonished face of the farmer. 
line 11723=>     'Mr. Merry!' he cried. 
line 11724=>     'Yes, of course! Who  did you think it was?' said Merry coming forward.  
line 11725=>As  he came out of the mist and their fears subsided, he seemed suddenly  to 
line 11726=>diminish to  ordinary  hobbit-size. He was  riding a pony, and a  scarf  was 
line 11727=>swathed round his neck and over his chin to keep out the fog. 
line 11728=>     Frodo  sprang  out of  the waggon to greet  him. 'So  there you are  at 
line 11729=>last!'  said Merry.  'I was beginning to wonder if you would  turn up at all 
line 11730=>today, and I was just going back to supper. When it grew foggy I came across 
line 11731=>and rode up  towards Stock to see if you had fallen in  any ditches. But I'm 
line 11732=>blest  if  I  know  which way  you  have come. Where did you  find them, Mr. 
line 11733=>Maggot? In your duck-pond?' 
line 11734=>     'No,  I  caught 'em trespassing,'  said the farmer, 'and nearly set  my 
line 11735=>dogs on  'em;  but they'll tell  you all the story,  I 've no doubt.  Now, if 
line 11736=>you'll excuse  me, Mr. Merry and Mr. Frodo and  all, I'd best be turning for  
line 11737=>home. Mrs. Maggot will be worriting with the night getting thick.' 
line 11738=>     He backed the waggon into the lane and turned it. 'Well, good  night to 
line 11739=>you all,' he said. 'It's been a queer day, and no mistake. But all's well as 
line 11740=>ends well; though perhaps  we should not say  that  until  we reach  our own 
line 11741=>doors. I'll not deny that I'll be glad now when I  do.' He lit his lanterns,  
line 11742=>and got up.  Suddenly he produced a large basket from under the seat.  'I was 
line 11743=>nearly forgetting,' he said. 'Mrs. Maggot put this up  for Mr. Baggins, with 
line 11744=>her compliments.'  He handed  it down and moved off, followed by a chorus of 
line 11745=>thanks and good-nights. 
line 11746=>     They  watched  the  pale  rings  of  light  round his lanterns as  they 
line 11747=>
line 11748=>####-dwindled  into  the  foggy night. Suddenly  Frodo laughed: from the  covered 
line 11749=>basket he held, the scent of mushrooms was rising. 
line 11750=> 
line 11751=>
line 11752=>####- 
line 11753=>
line 11754=>Chapter 5. A Conspiracy Unmasked 
line 11755=>
line 11756=> 
line 11757=> 
line 11758=>     'Now we had  better get home  ourselves,' said  Merry. There's something 
line 11759=>funny about all this, I see; but it must wait till we get in.' 
line 11760=>     They turned down  the Ferry lane, which was straight and well-kept  and  
line 11761=>edged with  large white-washed stones. In a hundred yards  or so  it brought  
line 11762=>them to  the  river -bank,  where there was a broad wooden  landing-stage.  A 
line 11763=>large  flat  ferry-boat was  moored beside it.  The white  bollards near the 
line 11764=>water's edge glimmered in the light of two lamps on high posts. Behind  them 
line 11765=>the mists in the flat fields were now above the hedges; but the water before 
line 11766=>them was dark,  with only  a few curling wisps like steam among the reeds by 
line 11767=>the bank. There seemed to be less fog on the further side. 
line 11768=>     Merry  led the pony  over a gangway  on to  the ferry,  and the  others 
line 11769=>followed.  Merry  then  pushed slowly off with  a  long pole. The Brandywine 
line 11770=>flowed slow and broad before them. On the other side the bank was steep, and 
line 11771=>up it a  winding path climbed from the further landing. Lamps were twinkling 
line 11772=>there. Behind loomed  up the Buck Hill; and out of it, through stray shrouds 
line 11773=>of mist, shone many  round windows, yellow and red. They were the windows 
line 11774=>of 
line 11775=>Brandy Hall, the ancient home of the Brandybucks.  
line 11776=>     Long  ago Gorhendad Oldbuck,  head of the  Oldbuck family,  one of  the 
line 11777=>oldest  in  the Marish or indeed in the Shire, had crossed  the river, which 
line 11778=>was the original  boundary of  the land  eastwards. He built (and excavated)  
line 11779=>Brandy  Hall, changed his name to Brandybuck,  and settled  down  to  become 
line 11780=>master of  what was virtually  a small independent country. His  family grew 
line 11781=>and grew,  and after his days  continued to grow, until Brandy Hall occupied 
line 11782=>the whole of the low hill, and had three large front-doors, many side-doors,  
line 11783=>and about a hundred windows. The  Brandybucks and  their numerous 
line 11784=>dependants 
line 11785=>then  began  to burrow, and later to  build,  all round about. That was  the 
line 11786=>origin  of Buckland, a thickly inhabited strip between the river and the Old 
line 11787=>Forest, a sort  of colony from the Shire. Its  chief village was Bucklebury, 
line 11788=>clustering in the banks and slopes behind Brandy Hall. 
line 11789=>     The people in the Marish were  friendly with the Bucklanders,  and  the 
line 11790=>authority of the Master  of the  Hall (as the head of the Brandybuck  family 
line 11791=>
line 11792=>####-was called) was still acknowledged by the farmers between Stock  and Rushey. 
line 11793=>But  most of the folk of the old Shire regarded the Bucklanders as peculiar, 
line 11794=>half foreigners as it were. Though, as a matter  of fact, they were not very 
line 11795=>different from the other hobbits of the Four Farthings. Except in one point: 
line 11796=>they were fond of boats, and some of them could swim. 
line 11797=>     Their land  was originally unprotected from the East; but on  that side 
line 11798=>they had built a hedge: the High Hay. It had been  planted many  generations 
line 11799=>ago, and was now thick and  tail, for it  was constantly tended. It  ran all 
line 11800=>the  way from Brandywine Bridge, in a big loop  curving away from the river, 
line 11801=>to  Haysend  (where  the  Withywindle flowed  out  of  the Forest  into  the 
line 11802=>Brandywine): well over twenty miles from end to  end. But, of course,  it was 
line 11803=>not  a complete  protection.  The Forest  drew  close  to the hedge in  many 
line 11804=>places.  The Bucklanders kept their doors locked after  dark,  and that also 
line 11805=>was not usual in the Shire. 
line 11806=>     The  ferry-boat moved slowly  across the water. The Buckland shore drew 
line 11807=>nearer. Sam was the only member of the party who had not been over the river  
line 11808=>before. He had a strange feeling as the slow gurgling stream slipped by: his 
line 11809=>old life lay behind  in the mists, dark adventure lay in front. He scratched 
line 11810=>his head, and for a moment had a passing wish that Mr. Frodo could have gone 
line 11811=>on living quietly at Bag End. 
line 11812=>     The four  hobbits stepped off the ferry.  Merry was  tying  it up,  and 
line 11813=>Pippin  was already leading  the pony up the  path, when Sam  (who had  been 
line 11814=>looking ba ck, as if to take farewell of the Shire) said in a hoarse whisper: 
line 11815=>     'Look back, Mr. Frodo! Do you see anything?' 
line 11816=>     On the far stage, under the distant lamps, they could just  make  out a  
line 11817=>figure: it looked like a  dark black bundle left behind. But a s they  looked 
line 11818=>it seemed to move and sway this way and that, as if searching the ground. It  
line 11819=>then crawled, or went crouching, back into the gloom beyond the lamps.  
line 11820=>     'What in the Shire is that?' exclaimed Merry. 
line 11821=>     'Something that is following us,' said Frodo. 'But don't ask  any  more 
line 11822=>now!  Let's get away  at once!' They hurried up the path to the top  of  the 
line 11823=>bank,  but when  they  looked  back  the far shore was shrouded in mist, and 
line 11824=>nothing could be seen. 
line 11825=>     'Thank goodness you don't keep any boats on the west -bank!' said Frodo.  
line 11826=>'Can horses cross the river?' 
line 11827=>     'They  can go twenty miles north to Brandywine  Bridge - or they  might 
line 11828=>swim,'  answered  Merry. 'Though  I  never heard of any horse  swimming  the 
line 11829=>
line 11830=>####-Brandywine. But what have  horses to do with it?' I'll tell you later. Let's 
line 11831=>get indoors and then we can talk.' 
line 11832=>     'All right! You and Pippin know your way; so I'll just ride on and tell 
line 11833=>Fatty Bolger that you are coming. We'll see about supper and things.' 
line 11834=>     'We had our supper early with Farmer Maggot,' said Frodo;  'but we could 
line 11835=>do with another.' 
line 11836=>     'You shall have it! Give  me that basket!' said  Merry, and  rode ahead 
line 11837=>into the darkness.  
line 11838=>     It  was some distance from  the  Brandywine  to  Frodo's new  house  at 
line 11839=>Crickhollow. They passed Buck Hill and Brandy Hall on their left, and on the 
line 11840=>outskirts of Bucklebury struck the main road of Buckland that ran south from 
line 11841=>the Bridge. Half a mile northward  along this they came to a lane opening on  
line 11842=>their  right. This they followed for a couple of miles as it  climbed up and 
line 11843=>down into the country. 
line 11844=>     At last  they  came to a narrow gate in a thick hedge. Nothing could be 
line 11845=>seen  of the house in the dark: it stood back from the lane in the middle of 
line 11846=>a wide  circle of  lawn surrounded by  a belt of  low trees inside the outer  
line 11847=>hedge. Frodo had chosen it, because it stood in an  out-of-the-way corner of 
line 11848=>the country, and there were  no other dwellings close  by.  You could get in 
line 11849=>and out  without being noticed. It had been built a long while before by the 
line 11850=>Brandybucks, for the use  of guests, or members of the family that wished to 
line 11851=>escape  from  the  crowded  life  of  Brandy  Hall  for a  time.  It  was an 
line 11852=>old-fashioned  countrified house, as much like a hobbit -hole as possible: it 
line 11853=>was long and low,  with no  upper storey; and it had a roof  of  turf, round 
line 11854=>windows, and a large round door. 
line 11855=>     As they walked lip the green path  from  the gate no light was visible; 
line 11856=>the  windows  were dark and shuttered.  Frodo knocked on the door, and Fatty 
line 11857=>Bolger opened it . A friendly light streamed out. They slipped in quickly and 
line 11858=>shut themselves and the light inside. They were in a wide hall with doors on 
line 11859=>either side; in  front  of them a  passage ran back  down the  middle of the 
line 11860=>house. 
line 11861=>     'Well, what do you think of it?' asked Merry coming up the passage. 'We 
line 11862=>have  done our  best in  a short time to make it  look  like home. After all 
line 11863=>Fatty and I only got here with the last cart-load yesterday.' 
line 11864=>     Frodo looked  round.  It did  look like home. Many of his own favourite 
line 11865=>things -  or Bilbo's things (they  reminded  him sharply of him in their new 
line 11866=>selling) - were arranged as nearly as possible as they had been  at Bag End. 
line 11867=>
line 11868=>####-It  was  a  pleasant,  comfortable,  welcoming  place;  and he found himself 
line 11869=>wishing  that he was really coming  here to settle down in quiet retirement. 
line 11870=>It  seemed unfair  to have put his friends  to  all  this  trouble;  and  he 
line 11871=>wondered again how he was going to break the news to them that he must leave 
line 11872=>them so soon, indeed at  once. Yet that  would  have  to be  done  that very 
line 11873=>night, before they all went to bed. 
line 11874=>     'It's delightful!' he said with an effort. 'I  hardly feel that I  have 
line 11875=>moved at all.' 
line 11876=>     The  travellers hung  up their  cloaks,  and piled  their packs  on the 
line 11877=>floor. Merry led them down the passage and threw open a door at the far end. 
line 11878=>Firelight came out, and a puff of steam. 
line 11879=>     'A bath!' cried Pippin. 'O blessed Meriadoc!' 
line 11880=>     'Which order  shall we  go in?' said Frodo. 'Eldest  first, or quickest 
line 11881=>first? You'll be last either way, Master Peregrin.' 
line 11882=>     'Trust me to arrange things  better than that!'  said Merry.  'We can't 
line 11883=>begin life  at Crickhollow with a quarrel over baths. In that room there are 
line 11884=>three tubs, and  a copper full of boiling water. There are also towels, mats 
line 11885=>and soap. Get inside, and be quick!' 
line 11886=>     Merry and Fatty went into the kitchen on the other side of the passage, 
line 11887=>and  busied  themselves  with  the  final  preparations  for  a late supper. 
line 11888=>Snatches of competing songs came  from the bathroom mixed  with the sound 
line 11889=>of 
