line 11922=>     They had supper in the kitchen on a table near the fire. 'I suppose you  
line 11923=>three won't want mushrooms again?' said Fredegar without much hope. 
line 11924=>     'Yes we shall!' cried Pippin. 
line 11925=>     'They're mine!'  said Frodo. 'Given to me  by Mrs. Maggot, a queen among 
line 11926=>farmers' wives. Take your greedy hands away, and I'll serve them.' 
line 11927=>     Hobbits have a passion  for mushrooms,  surpassing  even  the greediest  
line 11928=>likings  of Big  People.  A  fact  which  partly explains young Frodo's long 
line 11929=>expeditions  to  the renowned fields of the Marish,  and the  wrath  of  the 
line 11930=>injured Maggot. On this occasion there was plenty for all, even according to 
line 11931=>hobbit standards. There were also many other things to follow, and when they 
line 11932=>had  finished even Fatty Bolger heaved  a sigh  of content. They pushed back 
line 11933=>the table, and drew chairs round the fire. 
line 11934=>     'We'll clear up later,' said Merry. 'Now tell me all  about it! I guess 
line 11935=>that you have been having adventures, which was not quite fair without me. I 
line 11936=>want a full account; and most of all I want to know what was the matter with 
line 11937=>old Maggot, and why he spoke to me like that. He sounded almost as if he was 
line 11938=>scared, if that is possible.' 
line 11939=>     'We  have all been  scared,' said Pippin after a pause,  in which Frodo 
line 11940=>stared at the fire and did not speak. 'You would have been,  too, if you had 
line 11941=>been chased for two days by Black Riders.' 
line 11942=>     'And what are they?' 
line 11943=>
line 11944=>####-     'Black figures  riding  on black horses,'  answered Pippin.  'If  Frodo 
line 11945=>won't talk, I will tell you the whole tale from the beginning.' He then gave 
line 11946=>a  full account of their journey from the time  when they left Hobbiton. Sam 
line 11947=>gave various supporting nods and exclamations. Frodo remained silent. 
line 11948=>     'I should  think you were making it all up,'  said Merry, 'if I had not 
line 11949=>seen  that black shape on  the landing-stage - and heard the queer  sound in 
line 11950=>Maggot's voice. What do you make of it all, Frodo?' 
line 11951=>     'Cousin Frodo has been very close,' said Pippin. 'But the time has come 
line 11952=>for  him to open  out. So far we have been given nothing  more to go on than 
line 11953=>Farmer  Maggot's  guess  that  it  has  something  to  do  with  old Bilbo's 
