line 11968=>silence, and exchanged meaning glances among themselves. 
line 11969=>     'It's coming out in a minute,' whispered Pippin to Merry. Merry nodded. 
line 11970=>     'Well!' said Frodo at  last, sitting  up and straightening his back, as 
line 11971=>if he had made  a  decision.  'I can't keep it dark any  longer.  I have got 
line 11972=>something to tell you all. But I don't know quite how to begin.' 
line 11973=>     'I think I could help you,' said Merry quietly, 'by telling you some of 
line 11974=>it myself.' 
line 11975=>     'What do you mean?' said  Frodo, looking  at him anxiously. 'Just this, 
line 11976=>my  dear old  Frodo: you  are miserable, because you don't know how  to  say 
line 11977=>good-bye.  You  meant to leave the Shire, of course. But danger has come  on 
line 11978=>you sooner  than you expected, and now you are  making up your mind to go at 
line 11979=>once. And you don't want to. We are very sorry for you.' 
line 11980=>     Frodo opened his mouth  and shut it again. His  look of surprise was so 
line 11981=>
line 11982=>####-comical that they laughed. 'Dear  old  Frodo!' said Pippin.  'Did you really 
line 11983=>think you had thrown dust in  all our eyes? You have not been nearly careful 
line 11984=>or clever enough for that! You have obviously been planning to go and saying 
line 11985=>farewell  to  all your haunts all this  year since April. We have constantly 
line 11986=>heard you  muttering:  "Shall  I  ever   look  down into that valley again, I 
