line 12080=>     'I don't deny it,' said Frodo, looking at Sam, who was now grinning. 'I 
line 12081=>don't  deny it, but I'll never believe you  are  sleeping again, whether you  
line 12082=>snore or not. I shall kick you hard to make sure. 
line 12083=>     'You are a set  of deceitful  scoundrels!'  he  said,  turning  to  the 
line 12084=>others.  'But bless you!' he laughed, getting up and waving his arms, 'I give 
line 12085=>in. I will take Gildor's  advice.  If the danger were not  so dark, I should 
line 12086=>dance for joy. Even so,  I cannot  help feeling  happy; happier than I  have 
line 12087=>felt for a long time. I had dreaded this evening.' 
line 12088=>     'Good!  That's  settled. Three cheers  for  Captain Frodo and company!' 
line 12089=>they shouted;  and  they  danced round him. Merry and  Pippin  began a song, 
line 12090=>which they had apparently got ready for the occasion. 
line 12091=>     It was made on  the model of the dwarf-song that started Bilbo  on  his 
line 12092=>adventure long ago, and went to the same tune: 
line 12093=>     Farewell we call to hearth and hall! 
line 12094=>     Though wind may blow and rain may fall, 
line 12095=>
line 12096=>####-     We must away ere break of day 
line 12097=>     Far over wood and mountain tall. 
line 12098=> 
line 12099=>     To Rivendell, where Elves yet dwell 
line 12100=>     In glades beneath the misty fell, 
line 12101=>     Through moor and waste we ride in haste, 
line 12102=>     And whither then we cannot tell. 
line 12103=> 
line 12104=>     With foes ahead, behind us dread, 
line 12105=>     Beneath the sky shall be our bed, 
line 12106=>     Until at last our toil be passed, 
line 12107=>     Our journey done, our errand sped. 
line 12108=> 
line 12109=>     We must away! We must away! 
line 12110=>     We ride before the break of day! 
line 12111=>     'Very good!' said Frodo. 'But in that case there are a lot of things to 
line 12112=>do before we go to bed - under a roof, for  tonight at any rate.' 
line 12113=>     'Oh! That was poetry!' said Pippin. 'Do you really mean to start before 
line 12114=>the break of day?' 
line 12115=>     'I don't know,' answered  Frodo. 'I fear those  Black Riders, and  I am 
line 12116=>sure it is unsafe to stay in one place long, especially in  a place to which 
line 12117=>it is known  I was going. Also Gildor advised me  not to wait. But I  should 
line 12118=>very  much like  to see  Gandalf. I could see that even Gildor was disturbed 
line 12119=>when  he heard that Gandalf  had never  appeared. It really  depends  on two 
line 12120=>things.  How soon could the Riders get to Bucklebury? And how  soon could 
line 12121=>we 
line 12122=>get off? It will take a good deal of preparation.' 
line 12123=>     'The answer to the  second question,' said Merry, 'is that we could get 
line 12124=>off in an hour. I have prepared practically everything. There are six ponies 
line 12125=>in a stable across the fields; stores and tackle are all packed, except  for  
line 12126=>a few extra clothes, and the perishable food.' 
line 12127=>     'It seems to have been  a  very efficient conspiracy,' said Frodo. 'But 
line 12128=>what about the Black Riders? Would it be safe to wait one day for Gandalf?' 
line 12129=>     'That all depends on  what you think the Riders would do, if they found 
line 12130=>you here,' answered Merry. 'They could  have reached here  by now, of course, 
line 12131=>if they were not stopped at the North-gate, where the Hedge runs down to the 
line 12132=>river -bank, just this side of the Bridge. The gate-guards would not let them 
line 12133=>
line 12134=>####-through by night, though they might break through. Even in the daylight they 
line 12135=>would try  to keep them out, I think, at any  rate until  they got a message 
line 12136=>through to the Master of the Hall  - for they would not like the  look of the 
line 12137=>Riders, and would certainly be  frightened by them. But, of course, Buckland 
line 12138=>cannot resist a determined attack for  long. And it  is possible that in the 
line 12139=>morning even a Black Rider that rode  up  and asked for Mr. Baggins would be 
line 12140=>let through. It is pretty generally known that you are coming back  to  live 
line 12141=>at Crickhollow.' 
line 12142=>     Frodo  sat for  a while in thought. 'I have made  up  my mind,' he said 
line 12143=>finally. 'I am starting tomorrow, as soon as it is light. But I am not going 
line 12144=>by road: it  would be safer  to  wait here than  that.  If  I go through the 
line 12145=>North-gate my departure from  Buckland  will  be  known at once, instead  of 
line 12146=>being secret for  several days at least,  as it might be. And  what is more, 
line 12147=>the Bridge and the  East Road  near the  borders  will certainly be watched, 
line 12148=>whether  any Rider gets into  Buckland or not. We don't know  how many there 
line 12149=>are; but there are at least  two, and possibly more. The only thing to do is 
line 12150=>to go off in a qu ite unexpected direction.' 
line 12151=>     'But that  can only mean going  into  the  Old  Forest!'  said Fredegar 
line 12152=>horrified. 'You can't be thinking of doing that. It is quite as dangerous as 
line 12153=>Black Riders.' 
line 12154=>     'Not quite,' said Merry. It sounds very  desperate, but I believe Frodo 
line 12155=>is right. It is the only way of getting off without being followed  at once. 
line 12156=>With luck we might gel a considerable start.' 
line 12157=>     'But you won't have any luck in the Old Forest,' objected Fredegar. 'No 
line 12158=>one ever has luck in there. You'll gel lost. People don't go in there.' 
line 12159=>     'Oh yes they  do!'  said  Merry. 'The Brandybucks go in   - occasionally 
line 12160=>when the fit takes  them. We have  a  private entrance. Frodo  went in once, 
line 12161=>long ago. I have been in several times: usually in daylight, of course, when 
line 12162=>the trees are sleepy and fairly quiet.' 
line 12163=>     'Well, do  as you think best!' said Fredegar. 'I am more afraid of  the 
line 12164=>Old  Forest  than of anything I  know about:  the  stories  about  it  are a  
line 12165=>nightmare; but  my  vote hardly counts,  as I am  not going on the  journey. 
line 12166=>Still, I am very glad  someone is stopping behind, who can tell Gandalf what 
line 12167=>you have done, when he turns up, as I am sure he will before long.' 
line 12168=>     Fond as he was of Frodo, Fatty Bolger had no desire to leave the Shire, 
line 12169=>nor to see what lay  outside it. His family came from the Eastfarthing, from 
line 12170=>Budgeford in Bridgefields in fact, but he had never been over the Brandywine 
line 12171=>
line 12172=>####-Bridge.  His task, according to the original plans  of the conspirators, was 
line 12173=>to stay  behind and deal with inquisitive folk,  and  to keep up as long  as 
line 12174=>possible the  pretence that Mr. Baggins  was still living at Crickhollow. He 
line 12175=>had even brought along some old clothes of  Frodo's to help  him  in playing  
line 12176=>the part. They little thought how dangerous that part might prove. 
line 12177=>     'Excellent!' said Frodo,  when he understood the  plan. 'We  could  not  
line 12178=>have  left  any  message behind for Gandalf otherwise.  I don't know whether 
line 12179=>these Riders can read or not, of course, but I should not have dared to risk  
line 12180=>a written message, in case they got in and  searched the house. But if Fatty 
line 12181=>is willing to hold the fort, and I can be sure of Gandalf knowing the way we 
line 12182=>have gone, that  decides me. I am going  into  the Old  Forest  first  thing 
line 12183=>tomorrow.' 
line 12184=>     'Well, that's that,' said Pippin. 'On the whole I would rather have our 
line 12185=>job than Fatty's - waiting here till Black Riders come.' 
line 12186=>     'You wait till you are well inside  the Forest,' said Fredegar. 'You'll 
line 12187=>wish you were back here with me before this time tomorrow.' 
line 12188=>     'It's no  good arguing about it any more,' said Merry.  'We have  still 
line 12189=>got  to tidy up and put the finishing touches to  the packing, before we get 
line 12190=>to bed. I shall call you all before the break of day.' 
line 12191=>     When at last he  had got to bed, Frodo could not sleep for  some  time. 
line 12192=>His  legs ached. He. was  glad that he was riding in the morning. Eventually 
line 12193=>he fell into a  vague dream, in which he seemed to be looking  out of a high 
line 12194=>window over  a dark  sea of tangled trees.  Down below among the roots there 
line 12195=>was the sound of creatures  crawling and snuffling.  He felt sure they would  
line 12196=>smell him out sooner or later. 
line 12197=>     Then  he heard a noise in the distance.  At first he thought  it  was a  
line 12198=>great wind  coming over the leaves of the forest. Then  he knew  that it was 
line 12199=>not leaves, but the sound of the  Sea far-off; a sound he had never heard in 
line 12200=>waking life, though it  had often  troubled his dreams. Suddenly he found he 
line 12201=>was out in the open. There were no trees after all. He was on  a dark heath, 
line 12202=>and there was a strange salt smell in  the air. Looking up he saw before him 
line 12203=>a tall white tower, standing alone on a high ridge. A great desire came over  
line 12204=>him to climb the tower and see the Sea. He started to struggle  up the ridge 
line 12205=>towards the  tower:  but  suddenly a light came in  the sky, and there was a  
line 12206=>noise of thunder. 
line 12207=> 
line 12208=> 
line 12209=>
line 12210=>####-<h4>Chapter 6.</h4> <br> The Old Forest 
line 12211=>
line 12212=> 
line 12213=> 
line 12214=>     Frodo woke suddenly. It was still dark in  the room. Merry was standing 
line 12215=>there with a candle  in one hand, and banging  on the  door with the  other. 
line 12216=>'All right! What is it?' said Frodo, still shaken and bewildered. 
line 12217=>     'What is it!' cried Merry. 'It is  time to get up. It is half past four 
line 12218=>and very foggy. Come on! Sam is already getting breakfast ready. Even Pippin 
line 12219=>is up. I am just going to saddle the ponies, and fetch the one that is to be 
line 12220=>the  baggage-carrier. Wake that sluggard Fatty! At least he must get up  and  
line 12221=>see us off.' 
line 12222=>     Soon after  six o'clock the  five  hobbits were  ready  to start. Fatty 
line 12223=>Bolger was still yawning. They stole quietly out of the house. Merry went in 
line 12224=>front leading a laden pony, and took his way along a path that  went through 
line 12225=>a spinney behind  the house, and then  cut across several fields. The leaves 
line 12226=>of  trees were  glistening, and every twig  was dripping; the grass was grey 
line 12227=>with  cold dew. Everything was  still,  and far-away  noises seemed near and 
line 12228=>clear:  fowls chattering  in a yard,  someone closing a  door of  a  distant 
line 12229=>house. 
line 12230=>     In their shed they found the ponies;  sturdy  little beasts of the kind 
line 12231=>loved by hobbits, not speedy, but good for  a long day's work. They mounted, 
line 12232=>and  soon  they  were  riding off  into  the  mist,  which  seemed  to  open 
line 12233=>reluctantly before them and close forbiddingly behind them. After riding for  
line 12234=>about  an  hour,  slowly  and without talking,  they  saw  the Hedge looming  
line 12235=>suddenly ahead. It was tall and netted over  with silver cobwebs.  'How  are 
line 12236=>you  going to get  through  this?'  asked Fredegar. 'Follow me!' said Merry, 
line 12237=>'and you will see.' He turned to the  left  along  the Hedge, and  soon they 
line 12238=>came to a point  wher e it bent inwards, running along the lip of a hollow. A 
line 12239=>cutting  had been made, at  some distance from the  Hedge, and  went sloping 
line 12240=>gently down into the ground. It had walls of brick at  the sides, which rose 
line 12241=>steadily,  until suddenly  they arched  over a nd formed a  tunnel that dived 
line 12242=>deep under the Hedge and came out in the hollow on the other side. 
line 12243=>     Here Fatty Bolger halted. 'Good-bye, Frodo!' he  said.  'I wish you were 
line 12244=>not going into the Forest. I only hope you will not need rescuing before the 
line 12245=>day is out. But good luck to you - today and every day!' 
line 12246=>     'If there  are no worse things ahead  than  the Old Forest, I  shall be 
line 12247=>lucky,'  said  Frodo. 'Tell Gandalf to hurry along the  East Road: we  shall 
line 12248=>
line 12249=>####-soon be back on it and going as fast as we can.'  'Good-bye!' they cried, and 
line 12250=>rode down the slope and disappeared from Fredegar's sight into the tunnel. 
line 12251=>     It  was  dark and  damp. At the far  end it  was  closed  by  a gate of 
line 12252=>thick -set iron bars. Merry got down and unlocked the gate, and when they had 
line 12253=>all passed through he pushed it to again. It shut with a clang, and the lock  
line 12254=>clicked. The sound was ominous. 
line 12255=>     'There!' said Merry. 'You have left the Shire, and are now outside, and 
line 12256=>on the edge of the Old Forest.' 
line 12257=>     'Are the stories about it true?' asked Pippin. 
line 12258=>     'I don't know what  stories you mean,' Merry answered. 'If you mean the 
line 12259=>old bogey-stories Fatty's nurses  used to tell him, about goblins and wolves 
line 12260=>and things of that sort, I should say no. At any rate I  don't believe them. 
line 12261=>But the  Forest is queer. Everything in it  is very  much more  alive,  more 
line 12262=>aware of what is going on, so to  speak, than things  are in the  Shire. And 
line 12263=>the  trees do not like strangers. They watch  you. They  are usually content 
line 12264=>merely to  watch  you,  as  long  a s  daylight  lasts,  and  don't  do much. 
line 12265=>Occasionally the most unfriendly ones may drop a  branch,  or  stick  a root 
line 12266=>out,  or grasp at you with a long trailer. But at  night things  can be most  
line 12267=>alarming,  or so I am  told. I have  only once or twice  been in here  after  
line 12268=>dark, and then only near the hedge. I thought all the  trees were whispering 
line 12269=>to each  other,  passing news and plots along in an unintelligible language; 
line 12270=>and the branches swayed and groped without any wind. They  do  say the trees 
line 12271=>do  actually move, and can surround strangers and hem them in. In  fact long  
line 12272=>ago they  attacked the Hedge: they came and  planted themselves right by it,  
line 12273=>and leaned over it. But the hobbits came and cut down hundreds of trees, and 
line 12274=>made a great  bonfire in the  Forest, and  burned all the  ground in  a long 
line 12275=>strip east of the Hedge. After that the  trees gave up the attack,  but they 
line 12276=>became very unfriendly.  There  is  still a wide  bare  space not far inside 
line 12277=>where the bonfire was made.' 
line 12278=>     'Is it only the trees that are dangerous?' asked Pippin. 
line 12279=>     'There are  various queer things living deep  in the Forest, and on the 
line 12280=>far  side,' said Merry, 'or at least I have heard so; but I have never  seen 
line 12281=>any of them. But something makes paths. Whenever  one comes inside one 
line 12282=>finds 
line 12283=>open tracks; but they seem to shift and change from time  to time in a queer 
line 12284=>fashion.  Not far from  this tunnel there is, or was for  a  long time,  the 
line 12285=>beginning of quite  a broad path leading to the Bonfire  Glade,  and then on 
line 12286=>
line 12287=>####-more  or less in our direction, east and a little  north. That is the path I 
line 12288=>am going to try and find.' 
line 12289=>     The hobbits now left the tunnel -gate and rode across  the  wide hollow.  
line 12290=>On the far side was a faint path leading up on to the floor of the Forest, a  
line 12291=>hundred yards a nd more beyond  the Hedge;  but it  vanished  as  soon as  it 
line 12292=>brought them under the trees.  Looking back they could see the  dark line of 
line 12293=>the  Hedge  through  the stems of trees  that were already thick about them. 
line 12294=>Looking  ahead  they  could  see  only tree-trunks of innumerable sizes  and  
line 12295=>shapes: straight  or bent,  twisted, leaning,  squat  or slender, smooth  or  
line 12296=>gnarled and branched;  and all the stems were green  or grey with  moss  and  
line 12297=>slimy, shaggy growths.  
line 12298=>     Merry alone  seemed fairly cheerful.  'You had  better lead  on and find 
line 12299=>that path,'  Frodo  said to him.  'Don't  let us lose one another, or forget 
line 12300=>which way the Hedge lies!' 
line 12301=>     They picked a  way  among the trees, and  their  ponies plodded  along, 
line 12302=>carefully  avoiding the many  writhing  and interlacing roots. There  was no 
line 12303=>undergrowth. The ground was  rising  steadily,  and as they went  forward it  
line 12304=>seemed  that the trees became  taller, darker,  and  thicker. There  was  no 
line 12305=>sound,  except  an occasional drip  of  moisture falling  through  the still 
line 12306=>leaves.  For  the  moment  there  was no  whispering  or movement  among the 
line 12307=>branches; but  they  all got  an uncomfortable feeling that they were  being 
line 12308=>watched with disapproval, deepening to dislike and even enmity.  The feeling 
line 12309=>steadily  grew, until they found  themselves looking up quickly, or glancing 
line 12310=>back over their shoulders, as if they expected a sudden blow.  
line 12311=>     There was not  as  yet  any  sign  of  a path,  and  the  trees  seemed 
line 12312=>constantly to bar their way. Pippin suddenly  felt that he could not bear it 
line 12313=>any longer, and without warning let out  a shout. 'Oi! Oi!' he  cried. 'I am 
line 12314=>not going to do anything. Just let me pass through, will you!' 
line 12315=>     The others halted startled; but the  cry  fell as if muffled by a heavy 
line 12316=>curtain. There was no echo or answer though the wood  seemed to  become 
line 12317=>more 
line 12318=>crowded and more watchful than before. 
line 12319=>     'I should not shout, if I were you,' said Merry. It does more harm than 
line 12320=>good.' 
line 12321=>     Frodo began to wonder if it were possible to find a way through, a nd if 
line 12322=>he had been right  to make  the others come into this abominable wood. Merry 
line 12323=>was looking from side to side, and seemed already uncertain which way to go. 
line 12324=>
line 12325=>####-Pippin noticed it. 'It  has not taken you long to lose  us,' he said. But at 
line 12326=>that moment Merry gave a whistle of relief and pointed ahead. 
line 12327=>     'Well, well!'  he  said. 'These trees do  shift.  There is the  Bonfire 
line 12328=>Glade in front of  us (or I hope so), but the path to it seems to have moved 
line 12329=>away!' 
line 12330=>     The light grew clearer as they  went forward. Suddenly they came out of 
line 12331=>the trees and found themselves in a wide circular space. There was sky above 
line 12332=>them, blue and clear to  their surprise, for down under the Forest -roof they 
line 12333=>had not been able to see the rising morning and the lifting of the mist. The 
line 12334=>sun  was  not,  however,  high  enough  yet to shine down into the clearing, 
line 12335=>though its light was on  the  tree-tops. The  leaves  were  all  thicker and 
line 12336=>greener about  the edges of  the  glade, enclosing  it with  an almost solid 
line 12337=>wall. No tree grew there,  only rough grass and many tall plants: stalky  and 
line 12338=>faded hemlocks  and wood-parsley,  fire-weed seeding into fluffy ashes,  and 
line 12339=>rampant nettles and  thistles.  A dreary place: but it seemed a charming and 
line 12340=>cheerful garden after the close Forest. 
line 12341=>     The hobbits  felt encouraged, and looked up hopefully at the broadening 
line 12342=>daylight in the  sky. At the far side  of the glade there was a break in the 
line 12343=>wall of trees, and a clear path beyond it. They could see it running on into 
line 12344=>the wood, wide  in places  and open  above, though  every  now and again the 
line 12345=>trees drew in and overshadowed it with their dark boughs. Up this path  they 
line 12346=>rode. They were  still climbing gently, but they now  went much quicker, and 
line 12347=>with better heart;  for it seemed to them that the  Forest had relented, and 
line 12348=>was going to let them pass unhindered after all. 
line 12349=>     But after a while the air began to get  hot and stuffy. The  trees drew 
line 12350=>close again  on either side, and they  could  no longer  see far ahead.  Now 
line 12351=>stronger than ever they  felt again  the ill will  of  the  wood pressing on 
line 12352=>them.  So silent was it that  the fall of their ponies'  hoofs, rustling  on 
line 12353=>dead leaves and  occasionally  stumbling on hidden roots, seemed to thud  in 
line 12354=>their ears. Frodo tried to sing a song to encourage them, but his voice sank  
line 12355=>to a murmur. 
line 12356=>     O! Wanderers in the shadowed land 
line 12357=>     despair not! For though dark they stand, 
line 12358=>     all woods there be must end at last, 
line 12359=>     and see the open sun go past: 
line 12360=>     the setting sun, the rising sun, 
line 12361=>     the day's end, or the day begun. 
line 12362=>
line 12363=>####-     For east or west all woods must fail... 
line 12364=>     Fail - even as he said the word his voice faded  into  silence. The air 
line 12365=>seemed  heavy and the making  of  words wearisome. Just behind them  a large 
line 12366=>branch fell from an  old overhanging tree with  a crash into  the  path. The 
line 12367=>trees seemed to close in before them. 
line 12368=>     'They  do not  like all that about ending and failing,' said  Merry. 'I  
line 12369=>should not sing any  more  at present. Wait till we do  get to the edge, and 
line 12370=>then we'll turn and give them a rousing chorus!' 
line 12371=>     He spoke cheerfully, and if  he felt any great anxiety, he did not show 
line 12372=>it. The  others did not  answer.  They were depressed.  A heavy  weight  was 
line 12373=>settling steadily  on  Frodo's  heart, and he regretted now with every  step 
line 12374=>forward that he had ever thought of challenging the menace  of the trees. He 
line 12375=>was, indeed,  just  about  to stop and propose going back (if that was still 
line 12376=>possible), when  things took  a  new  turn. The  path  stopped climbing, and 
line 12377=>became for a while nearly  level. The dark trees drew aside, and  ahead they 
line 12378=>could see  the path  going  almost  straight forward.  Before them, but some 
line 12379=>distance off, there stood a  green  hill-top, treeless, rising  like a  bald 
line 12380=>head out of the  encircling wood. The  path seemed to be making directly for  
line 12381=>it. 
line 12382=>     They now hurried forward again,  delighted with the thought of climbing 
line 12383=>out  for  a  while above the roof  of the Forest. The path dipped, and  then 
line 12384=>again began  to climb upwards, leading them at last to the foot of the steep 
line 12385=>hillside.  There  it left the trees and faded into the turf.  The wood stood 
line 12386=>all round the hill like  thick  hair that ended sharply in  a circle round a  
line 12387=>shaven crown. 
line 12388=>     The hobbits  led their  ponies up, winding  round and  round until they 
line 12389=>reached the top. There they stood and gazed about them. The air was gleaming 
line 12390=>and sunlit, but hazy; and they could not see to any great distance. Near  at 
line 12391=>hand the mist was now almost gone;  though here and there it lay  in hollows 
line 12392=>of the wood, and to  the south  of  them, out of a deep  fold cutting  right 
line 12393=>across the Forest, the fog still rose like steam or wisps of white smoke. 
line 12394=>     'That,'  said Merry, pointing  with his hand, 'that  is the line of the 
line 12395=>Withywindle. It comes down out of the Downs and flows south-west through 
line 12396=>the 
line 12397=>midst of the  Forest to join the  Brandywine below Haysend. We don't want to 
line 12398=>go that way! The Withywindle valley is said to be  the  queerest part of the 
line 12399=>whole wood  - the centre from which all the queerness comes, as it were.' 
line 12400=>
line 12401=>####-     The others looked in the  direction  that  Merry  pointed out, but they 
line 12402=>could see little but mists over the damp and  deep-cut valley; and beyond it 
line 12403=>the southern half of the Forest faded from view.  
line 12404=>     The sun on the hill-lop was now  getting  hot. It must  have been a bout 
line 12405=>eleven o'clock; but the autumn haze still prevented them from seeing much in 
line 12406=>other directions. In the west they could not make out either the line of the 
line 12407=>Hedge  or  the  valley of  the Brandywine  beyond  it. Northward, where they 
line 12408=>looked most hopefully, they could see nothing that might be the line of  the 
line 12409=>great East Road, for which they were making. They were on an island in a sea  
line 12410=>of trees, and the horizon was veiled. 
line 12411=>     On the south-eastern  side  the ground fell very  steeply,  as  if  the 
line 12412=>slopes  of  the  hill   were  continued  far  down  under  the  trees,  like 
line 12413=>island-shores that really  are the  sides  of a mountain rising  out of deep 
line 12414=>waters. They sat on the green edge and looked out over the woods below them, 
line 12415=>while they ate their  mid-day meal. As  the sun rose  and  passed  noon they 
line 12416=>glimpsed far  off  in  the east the grey-green lines  of the Downs  that lay 
line 12417=>beyond  the Old Forest on that side. That cheered them greatly; for  it  was 
line 12418=>good to see a sight of anything beyond the  wood's border s,  though they did  
line 12419=>not mean to go  that way,  if  they  could help it: the Barrow-downs  had as 
line 12420=>sinister a reputation in hobbit -legend as the Forest itself.  
line 12421=>     At length they made up their minds  to go on again. The path  that  had 
line 12422=>brought them to the hill reappeared on  the northward side; but they had not  
line 12423=>followed it far before they became aware that it was bending steadily to the 
line 12424=>right.  Soon it  began  to descend  rapidly and they  guessed  that  it must 
line 12425=>actually be heading towards the Withywindle va lley: not at all the direction 
line 12426=>they  wished  lo  take. After some  discussion  they decided to  leave  this 
line 12427=>misleading path and strike northward; for although they had not been able to 
line 12428=>see it  from the hill-top, the Road  must lie that way, and it  could not be 
line 12429=>many miles off. Also northward, and to the left of the path, the land seemed  
line 12430=>lo  be drier  and more  open,  climbing up to slopes  where  the  trees were 
line 12431=>thinner,  and pines and firs replaced the oaks and ashes  and other  strange 
line 12432=>and nameless trees  of the denser wood. 
line 12433=>     At first  their  choice  seemed  to  be good: they got along  at a fair 
line 12434=>speed, though whenever they got  a glimpse of the sun  in an open glade they 
line 12435=>seemed  unaccountably to have veered eastwards. But  after a time the  trees 
line 12436=>began to close in again,  just where they had appeared from a distance to be 
line 12437=>thinner and  less tangled. Then  deep  folds  in  the ground were discovered 
line 12438=>
line 12439=>####-unexpectedly, like the ruts of great  giant-wheels or  wide moats and sunken 
line 12440=>roads long disused and choked with  brambles. These lay usually right across 
line 12441=>their  line  of march, and could only be crossed  by scrambling down and out 
line 12442=>again, which was troublesome and difficult with their ponies. Each time they 
line 12443=>climbed down they found the  hollow  filled  with  thick bushes  and  matted 
line 12444=>undergrowth, which somehow would not  yield to the  left, but only  gave way 
line 12445=>when they turned to the right; and they  had to go some  distance along  the 
line 12446=>bottom before they could find a  way up  the  further bank.  Each  time they 
line 12447=>clambered out, the trees seemed deeper and  darker;  and always  to the left 
line 12448=>and upwards it was most difficult to find a way, and they were forced to the  
line 12449=>right and downwards.  
line 12450=>     After an hour or two they had lost all clear sense of direction, though 
line 12451=>they knew well enough that they had long ceased to go northward at all. They 
line 12452=>were being headed off,  and were simply following a course chosen for them - 
line 12453=>eastwards and southwards, into the heart of the Forest and not out of it. 
line 12454=>     The afternoon was wearing away when they scrambled and stumbled  into a  
line 12455=>fold that was  wider and  deeper than any they had yet met. It  was so sleep 
line 12456=>and  overhung that  it proved  impossible  to climb out  of it again, either  
line 12457=>forwards  or  backwards, without  leaving  their ponies  and  their  baggage 
line 12458=>behind. All  they could do  was to  follow  the fold - downwards. The ground 
line 12459=>grew soft, and in places boggy; springs appeared in the banks, and soon they  
line 12460=>found themselves following a brook that trickled and babbled through a weedy 
line 12461=>bed. Then the ground began to fall rapidly, and the brook growing strong and 
line 12462=>noisy, flowed and leaped swiftly downhill. They were in a deep dim-lit gully 
line 12463=>over -arched by trees high above them. 
line 12464=>     After stumbling along for some way along  the  stream, they came  quite 
line 12465=>suddenly out of the gloom. As if through a gate they saw the sunlight before 
line 12466=>them.  Coming  to the opening they found  that they had  made their way down 
line 12467=>through a cleft in a high sleep bank, almost a cliff. At its feet was a wide 
line 12468=>space of grass and reeds; and in the distance could be glimpsed another bank  
line 12469=>almost as  steep. A golden  afternoon  of  late sunshine lay warm and drowsy 
line 12470=>upon  the hidden land between. In the midst of it there wound lazily a  dark 
line 12471=>river  of brown  water,  bordered with ancient  willows,  arched  over  with 
line 12472=>willows, blocked  with fallen willows,  and flecked with thousands  of faded 
line 12473=>willow-leaves.  The  air was thick  with  them, fluttering  yellow from  the 
line 12474=>branches;  for there  was a  warm  and gentle breeze blowing  softly   in the  
line 12475=>valley, and the reeds were rustling, and the willow-boughs were creaking. 
line 12476=>
line 12477=>####-     'Well, now I have at  least some  notion  of where we are!' said Merry. 
line 12478=>'We have come almost in the opposite direction to which we intended. This is 
line 12479=>the River Withywindle! I will go on and explore.' 
line 12480=>     He passed out into the sunshine and disappeared into the  long grasses.  
line 12481=>After a while he reappeared, and reported that there was fairly solid ground 
line 12482=>between the cliff-foot and the river; in  some places firm turf went down to 
line 12483=>the water's edge. 'What's more,' he  said, 'there seems to be something like 
line 12484=>a footpath  winding  along on  this side  of the river. If  we turn left and 
line 12485=>follow it, we  shall be bound to  come out on the  east side of  the  Forest 
line 12486=>eventually.' 
line 12487=>     'I dare say!' said Pippin. 'That  is, if the  track goes on so far, and 
line 12488=>does not simply lead us into a bog and leave us there.  Who made  the track, 
line 12489=>do you suppose, and why?  I am sure it was not for our benefit. I am getting  
line 12490=>very suspicious  of this Forest and everything in it, and I begin to believe 
line 12491=>all  the stories about it. And have you any idea how far eastward we  should  
line 12492=>have to go?' 
line 12493=>     'No,' said Merry, 'I  haven't. I don't  know in the  least how far down 
line 12494=>the Withywindle we are, or who could possibly come here often enough to 
line 12495=>make 
line 12496=>a path along it. But there is no other way out that I can see or think of.' 
line 12497=>     There being nothing  else for it, they filed out, and Merry led them to 
line 12498=>the path that he had discovered. Everywhere the reeds and  grasses were lush 
line 12499=>and tall, in places far above their heads; but once found, the path was easy 
line 12500=>to  follow, as it  turned  and twisted, picking out the sounder ground among 
line 12501=>the bogs and pools. Here and there it passed  over other rills, running down 
line 12502=>gullies into the Wi thywindle  out of the higher  forest -lands,  and at these 
line 12503=>points there were tree-trunks or bundles of brushwood laid carefully across.  
line 12504=>     The  hobbits began to feel very hot. There were armies of flies  of all 
line 12505=>kinds buzzing round their  ears, and the afternoon sun was burning  on their 
line 12506=>backs.  At last they  came suddenly into a thin shade;  great grey  branches 
line 12507=>reached across  the  path. Each step forward became more  reluctant than the 
line 12508=>last. Sleepiness seemed to be creeping out of the ground and up their  legs, 
line 12509=>and falling softly out of the air upon their heads and eyes. 
line 12510=>     Frodo  felt his  chin go down and  his head nod. Just in front  of  him 
line 12511=>Pippin fell forward on to his knees.  Frodo halted. 'It's no good,' he heard 
line 12512=>Merry saying. 'Can't go another step  without rest. Must have nap. It's cool 
line 12513=>under the willows. Less flies!' 
line 12514=>
line 12515=>####-     Frodo did not like the sound of this. 'Come  on!' he  cried. 'We  can't  
line 12516=>have a  nap yet. We must get clear of the Forest first.' But the others were 
line 12517=>too far gone to care. Besi de them Sam stood yawning and blinking stupidly.  
