line 13051=>than 
line 13052=>enough, for it was not comfortable lore. Tom's words laid bare the hearts of 
line 13053=>trees and their thoughts, which were often dark and strange, and filled with 
line 13054=>a  hatred of things that go free upon the  earth, gnawing, biting, breaking, 
line 13055=>hacking, burning: destroyers and usurpers. It was not called  the Old Forest  
line 13056=>without reason,  for  it  was indeed ancient,  a survivor  of vast forgotten 
line 13057=>woods;  and  in it there  lived  yet, ageing no quicker than the hills,  the 
line 13058=>fathers of the fathers of trees, remembering times when they were lords. The  
line 13059=>countless  years  had  filled  them with pride  and rooted wisdom,  and with 
line 13060=>malice.  But none were more dangerous  than the Great Willow:  his heart was 
line 13061=>rotten, but his strength was  green; and  he was cunning,  and  a master  of 
line 13062=>winds, and his song and thought ran through the woods  on both sides  of the  
line 13063=>river.  His grey  thirsty spirit drew power out of the earth and spread like 
line 13064=>fine root-threads in the ground, and invisible twig-fingers in the air, till 
line 13065=>it had under its dominion nearly all the trees of the Forest  from the Hedge 
line 13066=>to the Downs.  
line 13067=>
line 13068=>####-     Suddenly  Tom's talk  left  the woods and  went leaping  up  the  young 
line 13069=>stream, over  bubbling  waterfalls,  over  pebbles and worn rocks, and among 
line 13070=>small flowers in close  grass and wet crannies, wandering at  last up  on to 
