line 13107=>     'Who are you, Master?' he asked. 
line 13108=>     'Eh, what?' said  Tom sitting up,  and  his eyes glinting in the gloom. 
line 13109=>'Don't you know my name yet? That's the only  answer. Tell me,  who are you, 
line 13110=>alone, yourself and nameless? But you are young and I am old. Eldest, that's 
line 13111=>what I am. Mark my words, my friends: Tom was here before  the river and the 
line 13112=>trees;  Tom remembers the first raindrop and the first  acorn. He made paths 
line 13113=>before  the Big  People,  and saw  the  little People arriving.  He was here 
line 13114=>before the Kings and the graves and the Barrow-wights. When the Elves passed 
line 13115=>westward, Tom was here already, before the  seas were bent. He knew the dark 
line 13116=>under  the stars when it  was  fearless  -  before  the Dark  Lord came  from 
line 13117=>Outside.' 
line 13118=>     A shadow seemed to pass by the  window, and the hobbits glanced hastily 
line 13119=>through  the  panes.  When they  turned again, Goldberry stood  in the  door  
line 13120=>behind,  framed in  light. She held a  candle, shielding its flame  from the 
line 13121=>draught  with her hand;  and the  light  flowed through  it,  like  sunlight 
line 13122=>through a white shell. 
line 13123=>     'The  rain has ended,' she said; 'and new waters are running  downhill, 
line 13124=>under the stars. Let us now laugh and be glad!' 
line 13125=>     'And let us have  food and drink!' cried Tom. 'Long tales are  thirsty. 
line 13126=>And long listening's hungry work, morning, noon,  and evening!' With that he 
line 13127=>jumped  out  of  his  chair,  and  with  a  bound took  a  candle  from  the 
line 13128=>chimney-shelf and lit it  in the flame that Goldberry held;  then he  danced 
line 13129=>about the table. Suddenly he hopped through the door and disappeared. 
line 13130=>     Quickly  he returned, bearing a  large and laden  tray.  Then  Tom  and 
line 13131=>Goldberry  set the table; and  the  hobbits sat  half in  wonder and half in 
line 13132=>laughter: so  fair  was  the grace  of Goldberry  and so  merry and odd  the 
line 13133=>caperings of Tom. Yet in some fashion they  seemed to  weave a single dance, 
line 13134=>neither hindering the other, in  and out of  the  room, and  round about the 
line 13135=>table; and with great speed food and vessels and  lights were set  in order. 
line 13136=>The boards blazed with candles, white and yellow.  Tom bowed to his  guests.  
line 13137=>'Supper is ready,'  said Goldberry; and now the  hobbits  saw that  she  was 
line 13138=>clothed all in silver with  a white girdle, and her  shoes were like fishes' 
line 13139=>mail. But Tom was all in clean blue, blue as rain -washed forget-me-nots, and 
line 13140=>he had green stockings.  
line 13141=>     It was a supper even better than before. The hobbits under the spell of 
line 13142=>
line 13143=>####-Tom's words may have  missed one meal or many,  but when the food was 
line 13144=>before 
line 13145=>them it seemed at  least a week  since they had eaten. They did not  sing or  
line 13146=>even speak much for a while, and paid close attention to business. But after  
line 13147=>a time their hearts and spirit rose high again, and their voices rang out in 
line 13148=>mirth and laughter. 
line 13149=>     After they had eaten,  Goldberry  sang many songs for them, songs  that 
line 13150=>began  merrily  in the  hills and fell softly down into  silence; and in the 
line 13151=>silences they saw in their minds pools and  waters wider  than any  they had 
line 13152=>known, and looking into them they  saw the sky below them and the stars like 
line 13153=>jewels in the  depths. Then  once more she wished them  each  good night and 
line 13154=>left them by the fireside. But Tom now seemed wide awake and plied them 
line 13155=>with 
line 13156=>questions.  
line 13157=>     He appeared already to know much about them and all their families, and  
line 13158=>indeed  to know much of  all the history  and doings of  the Shire down from  
line 13159=>days hardly remembered among the hobbits  themselves. It  no longer surprised 
line 13160=>them; but he  made no secret that he owed  his  recent knowledge  largely to 
line 13161=>Farmer Maggot, whom he seemed to regard as a person of more  importance 
line 13162=>than 
line 13163=>they had imagined.  'There's earth under  his  old  feet, and  clay  on  his 
line 13164=>fingers; wisdom in his bones, and both  his eyes are open,' said Tom. It was 
line 13165=>also clear that Tom  had dealings with the Elves, and it seemed that in some  
line 13166=>fashion, news had reached him from Gildor concerning the flight of Frodo. 
line 13167=>     Indeed  so much did Tom know, and so cunning  was his questioning, that 
line 13168=>Frodo found himself telling him more about Bilbo and his own hopes and fears 
line 13169=>than he  had told before even to  Gandalf. Tom wagged  his head up and down, 
line 13170=>and there was a glint in his eyes when he heard of the Riders. 
line 13171=>     'Show me  the  precious  Ring!'  he said suddenly  in the  midst of the 
line 13172=>story: and  Frodo, to his  own astonishment,  drew  out the chain  from  his 
line 13173=>pocket, and unfastening the Ring handed it at once to Tom. 
line 13174=>     It  seemed  to  grow  larger  as  it  lay  for  a  moment  on  his  big 
line 13175=>brown-skinned hand. Then suddenly he put it  to his eye  and laughed.  For a  
line 13176=>second the  hobbits had a vision, both comical and  alarming, of his  bright 
line 13177=>blue  eye gleaming through a circle of gold. Then Tom put the Ring round the 
line 13178=>end of his little finger and held it up to the candlelight. For a moment the 
line 13179=>hobbits noticed nothing strange about this.  Then they gasped. There was  no  
line 13180=>
line 13181=>####-sign of Tom disappearing!  
line 13182=>     Tom  laughed again,  and then he  spun  the Ring in  the  air  - and it 
line 13183=>vanished with a flash. Frodo  gave a cry - and Tom leaned forward and handed 
line 13184=>it back to him with a smile. 
line 13185=>     Frodo looked at it closely, and rather  suspiciously (like one  who has 
line 13186=>lent a trinket to a juggler). It was the same Ring, or looked  the same  and 
line 13187=>weighed  the same:  for that  Ring had  always  seemed  to  Frodo  to  weigh 
line 13188=>strangely heavy in the hand. But something prompted him to make sure. He 
line 13189=>was 
line 13190=>perhaps a trifle annoyed with Tom for seeming to make so  light of what even 
line 13191=>Gandalf thought so perilously important. He waited  for an opportunity, when 
line 13192=>the talk was going again, and Tom  was telling an absurd story about badgers 
line 13193=>and their queer ways  - then he slipped the Ring on. 
line 13194=>     Merry turned towards him to say something and gave a start, and checked 
line 13195=>an exclamation.  Frodo was delighted (in a  way):  it was  his own ring  all 
line 13196=>right, for Merry was staring blankly  at his  chair, and obviously could not 
line 13197=>see him. He  got up and  crept  quietly away from  the  fireside towards the 
line 13198=>outer door. 
line 13199=>     'Hey there!' cried Tom, glancing towards him with a most seeing look in 
line 13200=>his shining eyes. 'Hey!  Come  Frodo, there!  Where be you  a -going? Old Tom 
line 13201=>Bombadil's not as blind  as that yet. Take off your golden ring! Your hand's 
line 13202=>more fair without it. Come back! Leave your game and  sit down beside me! 
line 13203=>We 
line 13204=>must  talk a while more, and  think about the  morning.  Tom  must teach the  
line 13205=>right road, and keep your feet from wandering.' 
line 13206=>     Frodo laughed (trying to feel pleased), and taking off the Ring he came 
line 13207=>and  sat down  again. Tom now told them that he reckoned the Sun would shine 
line 13208=>tomorrow, and it would be a glad morning, and setting  out would be hopeful. 
line 13209=>But they  would do well to start early; for weather in  that  country was  a  
line 13210=>thing  that  even Tom could  not be sure  of  for long, and it would  change 
line 13211=>sometimes quicker than he could change his jacket.  'I am no weather -master,' 
line 13212=>he said; 'nor is aught that goes on two legs.' 
line 13213=>     By his  advice  they  decided to make nearly  due North from his house, 
line 13214=>over the western and lower slopes of the Downs: they might hope  in that way 
line 13215=>to strike  the East Road in a day's journey, and avoid the  Barrows. He told 
line 13216=>them not to be afraid  - but to mind their own business.  
line 13217=>     'Keep to  the green grass. Don't you go  a -meddling  with old stone  or  
line 13218=>
line 13219=>####-cold Wights or prying in their houses, unless you be strong folk with hearts 
line 13220=>that never falter!' He said this more than once; and he advised them to pass 
line 13221=>barrows  by on the west-side, if  they  chanced to stray near  one.  Then he 
line 13222=>taught them a rhyme to sing, if they should by ill -luck fall into any danger  
line 13223=>or difficulty the next day. 
line 13224=>     Ho! Tom Bombadil, Tom Bombadillo! 
line 13225=>     By water, wood and hill, by the reed and willow,  
line 13226=>     By fire, sun and moon, harken now and hear us! 
line 13227=>     Come, Tom Bombadil, for our need is near us! 
line 13228=>     When they had sung this  altogether after him, he  clapped them each on 
line 13229=>the shoulder with  a  laugh,  and taking  candles  led them  back  to  their 
line 13230=>bedroom. 
line 13231=>
line 13232=>####- 
line 13233=> 
line 13234=>
line 13235=>Chapter 8. Fog on the Barrow-Downs 
line 13236=>
line 13237=> 
line 13238=> 
line 13239=>     That night  they heard no noises.  But either in his  dreams or  out of 
line 13240=>them,  he could not tell which,  Frodo heard a sweet singing running  in his 
line 13241=>mind;  a  song  that  seemed  to  come  like  a  pale  light behind  a  grey 
line 13242=>rain-curtain, and growing stronger to turn the veil all to glass and silver, 
line 13243=>until at last it was rolled back, and a  far green country opened before him 
line 13244=>under a swift sunrise. 
line 13245=>     The vision  melted  into  waking; and  there  was  Tom whistling like a  
line 13246=>tree-full of birds;  and the  sun was already  slanting  down the  hill  and 
line 13247=>through the open window. Outside everything was green and pale gold. 
line 13248=>     After breakfast, which they  again  ate  alone,  they made ready to say 
line 13249=>farewell, as nearly heavy of heart as was possible on such  a morning: cool, 
line 13250=>bright, and clean under a washed autumn sky of thin blue. The air came fresh 
line 13251=>from the  North-west. Their quiet  ponies were almost  frisky,  sniffing and 
line 13252=>moving  restlessly. Tom came out  of the house and  waved his hat and danced 
line 13253=>upon the doorstep, bidding the hobbits to get up and be off and go with good  
line 13254=>speed. 
line 13255=>     They rode off along a path  that  wound away from behind the house, and  
line 13256=>went slanting  up towards the north  end  of  the hill-brow  under which  it 
line 13257=>sheltered. They had just dismounted to lead their  ponies up the last  steep 
line 13258=>slope, when suddenly Frodo stopped. 
line 13259=>     'Goldberry!' he cried. 'My fair lady, clad all in silver green! We have 
line 13260=>never said  farewell  to her, nor seen  her  since the evening!' He  was  so 
line 13261=>distressed tha t he turned  back;  but at  that  moment  a  clear  call  came 
line 13262=>rippling down. There on the  hill-brow she stood beckoning to them: her hair 
line 13263=>was flying loose,  and as it caught the sun it shone and  shimmered. A light 
line 13264=>like the glint  of  water on dewy grass  flashed from under her  feet as she 
line 13265=>danced. 
line 13266=>     They hastened up the  last slope, and stood breathless beside her. They 
line 13267=>bowed, but with a wave of her arm she bade them look round; and they  looked 
line 13268=>out from the hill-top  over lands under the morning. It was now as clear and  
line 13269=>far-seen as it  had been veiled and misty  when they stood upon the knoll in 
line 13270=>the  Forest,  which could now be seen rising pale and green out of  the dark 
line 13271=>trees in the West. In that direction the land rose in  wooded ridges, green, 
line 13272=>
line 13273=>####-yellow,  russet under  the sun, beyond which lay hidden the  valley  of  the 
line 13274=>Brandywine. To the South, over  the  line of  the Withywindle,  there was  a  
line 13275=>distant glint like pale glass where  the Brandywine River  made a great loop  
line 13276=>in the  lowlands  and  flowed   away  out of  the  knowledge of the  hobbits.  
line 13277=>Northward  beyond  the dwindling  downs  the land  ran  away  in  flats  and 
line 13278=>swellings of grey  and green and pale earth -colours, until it  faded  into a  
line 13279=>featureless and  shadowy  distance.  Eastward  the Barrow-downs  rose, ridge 
line 13280=>behind ridge into the morning, and vanished out of eyesight into a guess: it 
line 13281=>was no more  than a guess of  blue and a remote  white glimmer blending with 
line 13282=>the hem of the sky,  but it spoke to them, out of  memory  and old tales, of 
line 13283=>the high and distant mountains. 
line 13284=>     They  took a deep draught  of  the air, and felt that a skip and  a few 
line 13285=>stout strides would  bear  them wherever they wished. It seemed fainthearted  
line 13286=>to go jogging aside over the crumpled skirts of the downs  towards the Road, 
line 13287=>when they  should be leaping,  as lusty as Tom, over the stepping  stones of 
line 13288=>the hills straight towards the Mountains.  
line 13289=>     Goldberry spoke  to them  and recalled their eyes and thoughts.  'Speed 
line 13290=>now, fair guests!'  she said. 'And hold to your purpose! North with the wind 
line 13291=>in  the left eye and a blessing on your footsteps! Make haste while the  Sun 
line 13292=>shines!'  And  to Frodo  she  said:  'Farewell,  Elf-friend, it was a  merry 
line 13293=>meeting!' 
line 13294=>     But Frodo found no words to answer. He bowed low, and mounted his pony, 
line 13295=>and followed by his friends jogged slowly down the gentle slope  behind  the 
line 13296=>hill. Tom Bombadil's house and the valley, and the Forest were lost to view.  
line 13297=>The  air  grew warmer between the green walls of hillside  and hillside, and 
line 13298=>the scent of turf rose strong and sweet as they breathed. Turning back, when 
line 13299=>they reached  the bottom  of the green hollow, they saw Goldberry, now small 
line 13300=>and slender like  a sunlit flower  against the  sky: she  was standing still 
line 13301=>watching them, and her hands were stretched out towards them. As they looked 
line 13302=>she gave a  clear  call,  and lifting  up  her hand she turned  and vanished 
line 13303=>behind the hill. 
line 13304=>     Their way wound along the floor of the hollow, and round the green feet 
line 13305=>of a steep hill into  another deeper and  broader  valley, and then over the 
line 13306=>shoulder of further hills, and down their long  limbs, and  up  their smooth 
line 13307=>sides again, up on to  new hill -tops and down into new valleys. There was no 
line 13308=>tree  nor any visible water: it  was a country  of  grass  and short springy 
line 13309=>turf, silent  except for the whisper of the air over the edges  of the land, 
line 13310=>
line 13311=>####-and high lonely cries of  strange birds.  As they journeyed the sun mounted,  
line 13312=>and grew hot. Each time they climbed a ridge the breeze seemed to have grown 
line 13313=>less. When they caught a  glimpse of the country westward the distant  Forest 
line 13314=>seemed to be  smoking, as if the fallen rain was steaming up again from leaf 
line 13315=>and root and mould.  A shadow now lay round the edge of  sight, a dark  haze 
line 13316=>above which the upper sky was like a blue cap, hot and heavy. 
line 13317=>     About mid-day  they  came to  a hill whose top  was wide and flattened, 
line 13318=>like a shallow  saucer with a  green mounded rim. Inside  there was  no  air 
line 13319=>stirring,  and the sky seemed near their heads. They rode  across and looked  
line 13320=>northwards. Then  their hearts rose,  for it seemed plain that they had come 
line 13321=>further already than they had expected. Certainly the distances  had now all 
line 13322=>become hazy and deceptive, but there could  be no doubt that  the Downs were 
line 13323=>coming to  an end. A  long valley  la y below  them winding  away northwards,  
line 13324=>until it  came  to  an opening  between two  steep shoulders. Beyond,  there 
line 13325=>seemed  to be  no more hills. Due north  they faintly glimpsed  a  long dark 
line 13326=>line. That is a line  of trees,' said Merry, 'and that must mark  the  Road. 
line 13327=>All  along it for many leagues  east of the Bridge there are  trees growing. 
line 13328=>Some say they were planted in the old days.' 
line 13329=>     'Splendid!'  said Frodo. 'If we make as good going this afternoon as we 
line 13330=>have done this morning, we shall have left  the Downs before the Sun sets and 
line 13331=>be jogging on in search of a camping place.'  But even as he spoke he turned 
line 13332=>his glance eastwards, and he saw that on that side the hills were higher and 
line 13333=>looked down  upon them; and all those hills were crowned with green  mounds,  
line 13334=>and on some were standing  stones, pointing upwards like jagged teeth out of 
line 13335=>green gums.  
line 13336=>     That view was somehow disquieting; so they  turned  from  the sight and  
line 13337=>went down into  the hollow circle. In  the  midst of it there stood a single 
line 13338=>stone, standing  tall  under  the  sun above,  and at this hour  casting  no 
line 13339=>shadow. It was shapeless and yet significant: like a landmark, or a guarding 
line 13340=>finger, or more like  a  warning. But they were now hungry, and the sun  was 
line 13341=>still at the fearless noon; so they set their backs against the east side of 
line 13342=>the stone. It was cool,  as if the sun had  had no power to warm  it; but at 
line 13343=>that time this seemed pleasant. There they took food and drink,  and made as 
line 13344=>good a noon-meal under the open sky as anyone could wish; for  the food came 
line 13345=>from 'down under Hill'. Tom had provided them with plenty for the comfort of 
line 13346=>the day. Their ponies unburdened strayed upon the grass.  
line 13347=>     Riding over  the hills,  and eating  their fill, the warm  sun and  the 
line 13348=>
line 13349=>####-scent  of  turf,  lying a little  too long, stretching  out  their legs  and 
line 13350=>looking at the sky above their noses: these things are,  perhaps,  enough to 
line 13351=>explain  what  happened.  However,  that  may  be:  they  woke  suddenly and 
line 13352=>uncomfortably from a sleep they had never meant  to take. The standing stone 
line 13353=>was cold, and it cast a long pale shadow that stretched eastward  over them. 
line 13354=>The sun, a pale and watery yellow, was gleaming  through the mist just above 
line 13355=>the  west wall  of the  hollow  in which  they lay; north, south, and  east, 
line 13356=>beyond the wall the fog was thick, cold and white. The air was silent, heavy 
line 13357=>and  chill. Their ponies  were standing  crowded together  with their  heads 
line 13358=>down. 
line 13359=>     The hobbits sprang to their feet in alarm,  and ran to the western rim. 
line 13360=>They found that they were upon an island in the fog. Even as they looked out 
line 13361=>in  dismay  towards the setting sun, it sank before their  eyes into a white 
line 13362=>sea, and a cold grey shadow sprang up in the East behind. The fog  rolled up 
line 13363=>to the walls and rose above them, and as it mounted it bent over their heads 
line 13364=>until  it  became a roof: they were shut  in a  hall of  mist  whose central 
line 13365=>pillar was the standing stone. 
line 13366=>     They felt as if a trap was closing about them; but  they did  not quite 
line 13367=>lose heart. They still remembered  the hopeful view they had had of the line  
line 13368=>of the Road ahead,  and they still knew in  which direction it  lay. In  any 
line 13369=>case, they now had so great a dislike for that hollow place  about the stone 
line 13370=>that no  thought  of remaining there  was in their minds.  They packed up as 
line 13371=>quickly as their chilled fingers would work. 
line 13372=>     Soon  they were leading their ponies  in single file  over the  rim and 
line 13373=>down the long northward slope of  the hill,  down into a foggy sea. As  they 
line 13374=>went down the mist  became colder  and damper, and their hair hung lank  and 
line 13375=>dripping  on  their foreheads. When they reached the bottom it  was so  cold  
line 13376=>that  they halted  and got out cloaks and  hoods, which soon became  bedewed 
line 13377=>with  grey drops. Then, mounting  their ponies,  they went  sl owly on again,  
line 13378=>feeling their way by the rise and fall of the ground. They were steering, as 
line 13379=>well as they could guess, for the gate-like opening at the far northward end 
line 13380=>of  the  long valley which  they  had  seen in the  morning.  Once they were 
line 13381=>through the  gap, they had only lo keep on in  anything like a straight line 
line 13382=>and they were bound in the end to strike the Road. Their thoughts did not go 
line 13383=>beyond that, except for a vague hope  that  perhaps  away  beyond the  Downs 
line 13384=>there might be no fog. 
line 13385=>     Their going  was  very slow.  To  prevent their  getting separated  and 
line 13386=>
line 13387=>####-wandering in different directions they went in file, with Frodo leading. Sam 
line 13388=>was behind him, and after him came Pippin, and then Merry. The valley 
line 13389=>seemed 
line 13390=>to stretch on endlessly. Suddenly Frodo saw a hopeful sign.  On  either side 
line 13391=>ahead a darkness began  to loom  through  the mist; and he guessed that they 
line 13392=>were  at  last  approaching  the gap in  the hills,  the north-gate  of  the 
line 13393=>Barrow-downs. If they could pass that, they would be free. 
line 13394=>     'Come on! Follow me!' he called back over  his shoulder, and he hurried 
line 13395=>forward.  But  his  hope soon  changed  to bewilderment and alarm. The  dark 
line 13396=>patches  grew darker, but they shrank; and suddenly he saw, towering ominous 
line 13397=>before him and leaning  slightly towards one another like the pillars  of  a  
line 13398=>headless door, two huge  standing  stones. He could not remember having seen 
line 13399=>any sign  of  these in the  valley, when  he looked out from the hill in the 
line 13400=>morning. He had passed  between them almost before he was aware: and even 
line 13401=>as 
line 13402=>he did so  darkness seemed to  fall round him. His pony  reared and snorted,  
line 13403=>and he  fell off. When he looked back he found that he was alone: the others 
line 13404=>had not followed him. 'Sam!' he  called.  'Pippin!  Merry! Come  along!  Why 
line 13405=>don't you keep up?' 
line 13406=>     There was no answer. Fear  took him,  and he ran back  past the  stones 
line 13407=>shouting  wildly: 'Sam!  Sam! Merry! Pippin!' The pony bolted into  the mist  
line 13408=>and vanished. From some way off, or so it seemed, he thought he heard a cry: 
line 13409=>'Hoy!  Frodo! Hoy!' It was away eastward, on his left as he stood  under the 
line 13410=>great  stones, staring and straining into the gloom. He plunged off  in  the 
line 13411=>direction of the call, and found himself going steeply uphill. 
line 13412=>     As he struggled  on he called again,  and kept on calling more and more 
line 13413=>frantically; but he heard no answer for some time, and then it  seemed faint 
line 13414=>and far ahead  and high above him. 'Frodo! Hoy!' came the thin voices out of 
line 13415=>the  mist:  and then  a cry that sounded  like  help, help!  often repeated, 
line 13416=>ending  with a  last help!  that trailed off into a  long wail  suddenly cut 
line 13417=>short.  He stumbled forward  with all the speed he could towards  the cries;  
line 13418=>but the light was now gone, and clinging night had closed about him, so that 
line 13419=>it was impossible to be sure of any direction. He seemed all the time  to be 
line 13420=>climbing up and up. 
line 13421=>     Only the change in the level of the ground at his feet told him when he  
line 13422=>at last came to the top of a ridge or hill. He was  weary, sweating  and yet 
line 13423=>chilled. It was wholly dark. 
line 13424=>
line 13425=>####-     'Where are you?' he cried out miserably. 
line 13426=>     There was no reply. He stood listening. He was suddenly aware  that  it 
line 13427=>was getting very cold, and that up here a wind was beginning to blow, an icy  
line 13428=>wind. A change was coming in the weather. The mist  was flowing  past him 
line 13429=>now 
line 13430=>in shreds and  tatters. His breath was smoking, and  the darkness  was  less 
line 13431=>near and  thick. He looked up  and saw with  surprise  that faint stars were 
line 13432=>appearing  overhead amid the  strands of hurrying cloud  and  fog.  The wind 
line 13433=>began to hiss over the grass.  
line 13434=>     He imagined suddenly that he  caught a muffled cry, and he made towards 
line 13435=>it; and even as he went forward the mist was rolled up and thrust aside, and 
line 13436=>the  starry sky  was  unveiled.  A glance showed him  that he was now  facing 
line 13437=>southwards and was on a round hill-top, which he must  have climbed from the 
line 13438=>north.  Out  of the east  the  biting wind was blowing. To his  right  there 
line 13439=>loomed against the westward stars a dark  black  shape. A great barrow stood 
line 13440=>there. 
line 13441=>     'Where are you?' he cried again, both angry and afraid. 
line 13442=>     'Here!'  said a voice, deep and cold,  that seemed  to come out of  the 
line 13443=>ground. 'I am waiting for you!' 
line 13444=>     'No!' said Frodo; but  he did not run away. His knees gave, and he fell 
line 13445=>on the ground. Nothing happened, and there was no sound. Trembling he 
line 13446=>looked 
line 13447=>up,  in time to see a tall dark  figure like a shadow against the stars.  It 
line 13448=>leaned over him. He thought there were two eyes, very cold though lit with a 
line 13449=>pale light  that seemed to come from  some  remote  distance.  Then  a  grip 
line 13450=>stronger and colder than iron seized him. The icy touch froze his bones, and 
line 13451=>he remembered no more. 
line 13452=>     When  he came to  himself again, for a  moment he could  recall nothing 
line 13453=>except a sense  of  dread. Then  suddenly  he  knew  that he was imprisoned, 
line 13454=>caught hopelessly; he was in a barrow. A  Barrow-wight had taken him, and he 
line 13455=>was probably already under the  dreadful  spells of  the Barrow-wights about 
line 13456=>which whispered tales spoke. He dared not move, but lay as he found himself: 
line 13457=>flat on his back upon a cold stone with his hands on his breast. 
line 13458=>     But though his fear was so great that it seemed to be part  of the very 
line 13459=>darkness that was round him, he found himself as he lay thinking about Bilbo 
line 13460=>Baggins and his stories, of their jogging along together in the lanes of the 
line 13461=>Shire and  talking about roads and adventures.  There  is  a seed of courage 
line 13462=>
line 13463=>####-hidden (often deeply, it is true) in the heart of the fattest and most timid 
line 13464=>hobbit, wailing for some final  and desperate danger to  make it grow. Frodo 
line 13465=>was neither  very  fat nor very  timid; indeed,  though he did not  know it, 
line 13466=>Bilbo (and Gandalf) had thought him the best hobbit in the Shire. He thought 
line 13467=>he had come to the end of his adventure, and a terrible end, but the thought 
line 13468=>hardened him.  He found himself stiffening,  as if for a final spring; he no 
line 13469=>longer felt limp like a helpless prey. 
line 13470=>     As he lay there, thinking and getting a hold of himself, he noticed all 
line 13471=>at once  that the darkness was slowly giving way:  a pale greenish light was 
line 13472=>growing round him. It did not  at first show him what kind of a place he was 
line 13473=>in, for the light  seemed to be  coming out of himself,  and from  the floor  
line 13474=>beside  him, and had not yet reached the roof or wall. He  turned, and there 
line 13475=>in  the  cold glow he saw lying beside him Sam, Pippin, and Merry. They were 
line 13476=>on their backs, and their faces looked deathly pale;  and they were  clad in 
line 13477=>white. About them lay many treasures, of  gold maybe,  though in that  light  
line 13478=>they  looked cold and unlovely.  On their  heads  were circlets, gold  chains 
line 13479=>were about their waists, and on their fingers were many rings. Swords lay by  
line 13480=>their sides, and shields were  at their feet. But across their  three  necks 
line 13481=>lay one long naked sword. 
line 13482=>     Suddenly a  song began: a cold  murmur, rising and  falling.  The voice 
line 13483=>seemed far away and immeasurably dreary, sometimes high in the air and thin, 
line 13484=>sometimes like a low moan from the ground. Out of the formless stream of sad 
line 13485=>but horrible sounds, strings  of words would now and again shape  themselves:  
line 13486=>grim,  hard,  cold  words,  heartless and miserable. The night  was  railing 
line 13487=>against the morning of  which it was bereaved,  and the cold was cursing the 
line 13488=>warmth for which it hungered. Frodo was chilled to the marrow. After a while 
line 13489=>the song became clearer, and  with  dread in  his heart he perceived that it 
line 13490=>had changed into an incantation: 
line 13491=>     Cold be hand and heart and bone, 
line 13492=>     and cold be sleep under stone: 
line 13493=>     never mare to wake on stony bed, 
line 13494=>     never, till the Sun fails and the Moon is dead. 
line 13495=>     In the black wind the stars shall die, 
line 13496=>     and still on gold here let them lie, 
line 13497=>     till the dark lord lifts his hand 
line 13498=>     over dead sea and withered land. 
line 13499=>     He heard behind his head a creaking and scraping sound. Raising himself 
line 13500=>
line 13501=>####-on one arm he looked, and saw now in the pale light that they were in a kind 
line 13502=>of  passage which  behind them turned a corner. Round the corner a long  arm 
line 13503=>was groping, walking on its fingers towards Sam, who was lying nearest,  and 
line 13504=>towards the hilt of the sword that lay upon him. 
line 13505=>     At first Frodo felt as if he  had indeed been turned into stone by  the 
line 13506=>incantation.  Then a wild thought  of escape came to him. He wondered if  he 
line 13507=>put on the Ring, whether the Barrow-wight  would miss him, and he might find 
line 13508=>some way ou t.  He thought  of himself running free  over the grass, grieving 
line 13509=>for Merry, and Sam,  and Pippin,  but free and alive  himself. Gandalf would  
line 13510=>admit that there had been nothing else he could do. 
line 13511=>     But the courage that had been  awakened in  him was now   too strong: he 
line 13512=>could not  leave his friends so easily.  He wavered, groping  in his pocket, 
line 13513=>and then fought with himself again; and as he did so  the arm  crept nearer. 
line 13514=>Suddenly  resolve  hardened  in him,  and  he seized a  short sword that lay 
line 13515=>beside him, and kneeling he stooped  low over the bodies of  his companions.  
line 13516=>With what strength he had he hewed  at the crawling  arm near the wrist, and 
line 13517=>the hand broke off; but at the  same moment the sword  splintered up to  the  
line 13518=>hilt.  There  was a shriek and the light vanished. In  the  dark there was a  
line 13519=>snarling noise. 
line 13520=>     Frodo fell  forward over Merry, and Merry's face felt cold. All at once 
line 13521=>back  into  his mind, from which it had disappeared with the first coming of 
line 13522=>the  fog,  came the  memory  of the house down  under the Hill,  and  of Tom 
line 13523=>singing. He remembered  the rhyme  that  Tom  had taught  them. In  a  small 
line 13524=>desperate voice  he began: Ho!  Tom  Bombadil!  and with that name his voice 
line 13525=>seemed to grow  strong: it had a full and lively sound, and the dark chamber  
line 13526=>echoed as if to drum and trumpet. 
line 13527=>     Ho! Tom Bombadil, Tom Bombadillo! 
line 13528=>     By water, wood and hill, by the reed and willow,  
line 13529=>     By fire, sun and moon, harken now and hear us! 
line 13530=>     Come, Tom Bombadil, for our need is near us! 
line 13531=>     There  was a sudden deep  silence, in which Frodo could hear his  heart 
line 13532=>beating. After a long slow moment he heard plain, but far away, as if it was 
line 13533=>coming down through the  ground or through thick walls,  an  answering voice 
