line 13810=> 
line 13811=>     The Prancing Pony 
line 13812=>     Bree was the chief village of  the Bree-land, a small inhabited region, 
line 13813=>like an island in the empty  lands round about. Besides  Bree  itself, there 
line 13814=>was Staddle on the  other side of the hill, Combe  in a deep valley a little 
line 13815=>further eastward,  and  Archet  on  the  edge of  the Chetwood.  Lying round 
line 13816=>Bree-hill and the  villages was a small country of fields and tamed woodland  
line 13817=>only a few miles broad. 
line 13818=>     The Men of Bree were brown-haired, broad,  and  rather  short, cheerful 
line 13819=>and independent: they belonged to  nobody but themselves; but they were more 
line 13820=>friendly and familiar with Hobbits, Dwarves, Elves, and other inhabitants of 
line 13821=>the world  about them than was (or  is)  usual with Big People. According to 
line 13822=>their own tales  they were the original inhabitants and wer e the descendants 
line 13823=>of the first Men that ever wandered  into the West of the  middle-world. Few 
line 13824=>had survived the turmoils of  the Elder  Days; but  when the  Kings returned 
line 13825=>again over the  Great Sea  they had found the Bree-men still there, and they 
line 13826=>were st ill there now, when the memory  of  the  old Kings had faded into the 
line 13827=>grass. 
line 13828=>     In those days no other Men had settled dwellings so far west, or within 
line 13829=>a hundred leagues of the Shire. But in the wild lands beyond Bree there were 
line 13830=>mysterious wanderers. The Bree-folk called them Rangers, and knew nothing 
line 13831=>of 
line 13832=>their origin. They  were  taller and darker  than the  Men of Bree  and were 
line 13833=>believed  to have strange powers of sight and hearing, and to understand the 
line 13834=>languages of beasts and birds. They roamed at will southwards, and eastwards 
line 13835=>even as far as  the Misty  Mountains; but they were now few and rarely seen. 
line 13836=>When  they appeared they brought news from afar, and told strange  forgotten 
line 13837=>tales which were eagerly listened to; but the Bree-folk did not make friends 
line 13838=>of them. 
line 13839=>     There were  also many families  of hobbits  in the  Bree-land  and they 
line 13840=>claimed to be  the oldest  settlement of Hobbits in the world, one that  was 
line 13841=>founded long before even the Brandywine was crossed and the Shire colonized. 
line 13842=>They  lived  mostly  in  Staddle though  there were  some  in  Bree  itself,  
line 13843=>especially on the  higher slopes of the hill, above the  houses of  the Men. 
line 13844=>
line 13845=>####-The  Big  Folk and  the  Little Folk  (as they  called one another) were  on  
line 13846=>friendly  terms,  minding their  own affairs in  their own  ways,  but  both 
line 13847=>rightly regarding  themselves as  necessary parts of the Bree-folk.  Nowhere 
line 13848=>else in the world was this peculiar (but excellent) arrangement to be found. 
line 13849=>     The Bree-folk, Big and Little, did  not themselves travel much; and the 
line 13850=>affairs  of the  four villages  were their  chief concern. Occasionally  the 
line 13851=>Hobbits  of Bree went as far as  Buckland, or the  Eastfarthing; but  though 
line 13852=>their  link land  was not  much  further  than a  day's  riding  east of the 
line 13853=>Brandywine Bridge,  the  Hobbits  of the Shire  now seldom  visited  it.  An 
line 13854=>occasional Bucklander or  adventurous Took would come  out to  the Inn for a  
line 13855=>night  or  two, but  even  that  was  becoming  less  and  less  usual.  The 
line 13856=>Shire-hobbits referred to those of Bree, and to any others that lived beyond 
line 13857=>the  borders,   as  Outsiders,  and  took  very  little  interest  in  them, 
line 13858=>considering them dull  and uncouth. There were probably  many more 
line 13859=>Outsiders 
line 13860=>scattered about in the West  of the World in those days than  the  people of 
line 13861=>the Shire imagined. Some, doubtless, were no  better than  tramps, ready  to  
line 13862=>dig a hole in any bank and  stay only as long as it suited them.  But in the 
line 13863=>Bree-land, at any rate, the hobbits were decent and  prosperous, and no more 
line 13864=>rustic tha n most of their distant relatives Inside. It was not yet forgotten 
line 13865=>that there had been a time when there was much coming and going  between 
line 13866=>the 
line 13867=>Shire and Bree. There was Bree-blood in the Brandybucks by all accounts.  
line 13868=>     The village of Bree had some  hundred  stone houses  of  the Big  Folk, 
line 13869=>mostly above the Road, nestling  on the hillside with  windows looking west. 
line 13870=>On that side, running in  more  than half a circle from the hill and back to 
line 13871=>it, there was a deep dike with a thick hedge on the  inner side.   Over  this 
line 13872=>the Road crossed by a causeway; but where it pierced the hedge it was barred 
line 13873=>by a great gate. There was another gate in the southern comer where the Road 
line 13874=>ran out of the village. The  gates were closed at nightfall; but just inside 
line 13875=>them were small lodges for the gatekeepers.  
line 13876=>     Down on  the Road, where it swept to the right to  go round the foot of 
line 13877=>the hill, there was a large inn. It had been built long ago when the traffic 
line 13878=>on the roads had been far greater. For Bree stood at an old meeting of ways;  
line 13879=>another ancient road  crossed  the  East  Road  just outside (he dike at the 
line 13880=>western end of the village, and in former days Men and other folk of various 
line 13881=>sorts had travelled much on it. Strange as News from Bree was still a saying 
line 13882=>
line 13883=>####-in the  Eastfarthing, descending from  those days,  when  news  from  North, 
line 13884=>South, and East could be heard in the inn,  and when  the Shire-hobbits used 
line 13885=>to go more often to hear it.  But the Northern Lands had long been desolate,  
line 13886=>and  the  North  Road  was now  seldom  used: it was  grass-grown,  and  the 
line 13887=>Bree-folk called it the Greenway. 
line 13888=>     The Inn  of Bree  was still  there, however, and  the  innkeeper was an 
line 13889=>important person. His house was a meeting place for the idle, talkative, and 
line 13890=>inquisitive  among the inhabitants, large and  small, of the four  villages;  
line 13891=>and a resort of Rangers and other wanderers, and for such travellers (mostly 
line 13892=>dwarves) as still journeyed on the East Road, to and from the Mountains.  
line 13893=>     It  was  dark,  and  white  stars  were  shining,  when  Frodo and  his 
line 13894=>companions came at last to the Greenway-crossing and drew near the  village. 
line 13895=>They came to the West -gate and found it shut, but  at the door  of the lodge 
line 13896=>beyond it, there was a man sitting. He jumped up and  fetched a lantern  and 
line 13897=>looked over  the gate at them in surprise. 
line 13898=>     'What do you want, and where do you come from?' he asked gruffly. 
line 13899=>     'We are making for  the inn here,' answered Frodo.  'We are  journeying 
line 13900=>east and cannot go further tonight.' 
line 13901=>     'Hobbits! Four  hobbits! And what's more,  out  of  the Shire  by their 
line 13902=>talk,' said the gatekeeper, softly as if  speaking to himself. He  stared at 
line 13903=>them darkly for a moment, and then slowly  opened the gate and let them ride 
line 13904=>through. 
line 13905=>     'We don't  often see Shire-folk riding on the Road  at  night,' he went 
line 13906=>on, as they halted  a moment by his door. 'You'll pardon  my wondering  what 
line 13907=>business takes you away east of Bree! What may your names be, might I ask?' 
line 13908=>     'Our names and our business are our own,  and this does not seem a good  
line 13909=>place  to  discuss them,' said Frodo, not liking the look of  the man or  the 
line 13910=>tone of his voice. 
line 13911=>     'Your  business is  your  own, no doubt,'  said  the man; 'but it's  my 
line 13912=>business to ask questions after nightfall.' 
line 13913=>     'We  are hobbits  from Buckland, and we have a  fancy to travel and  to 
line 13914=>stay at the  inn here,' put  in Merry. 'I am  Mr. Brandybuck. Is that enough 
line 13915=>for  you?  The Bree-folk used  to be fair-spoken to travellers,  or so I had 
line 13916=>heard.' 
line 13917=>     'All right, all right!' said the man.  'I  meant no offence. But you'll 
line 13918=>find  maybe that more  folk  than old Harry  at the  gate will be asking you  
line 13919=>questions. There's queer folk about. If you go  on to  The Pony, you'll find 
line 13920=>
line 13921=>####-you're oat the only guests.' 
line 13922=>     He wished  them  good night, and they said no more; but Frodo could see 
line 13923=>in  the lantern-light  that the  man was still eyeing them curiously. He was 
line 13924=>glad to  hear  the gate clang  to  behind  them,  as they rode  forward.  He 
line 13925=>wondered why the man was  so suspicious, and whether any one had been 
line 13926=>asking 
line 13927=>for news of a party of hobbits. Could  it have been Gandalf? He  might  have 
line 13928=>arrived, while they  were delayed in the Forest and the Downs. But there was 
line 13929=>something in the look and the voice of the gatekeeper that made him uneasy.  
line 13930=>     The man stared after the hobbits for a moment, and then he went back to  
line 13931=>his house. As soon as his  back was turned, a dark figure climbed quickly in  
line 13932=>over the gate and melted into the shadows of the village street. 
line 13933=>     The  hobbits rode on up a  gentle slope, passing a few detached  houses, 
line 13934=>and  drew up outside the  inn. The houses looked large  and strange to them.  
line 13935=>Sam stared up at the inn  with its three  storeys and many windows, and felt 
line 13936=>his  heart sink. He  had imagined  himself meeting giants taller than trees, 
line 13937=>and other creatures  even more terrifying, some time or other  in the course 
line 13938=>of his journey; but at the moment he was finding his first sight of  Men and 
line 13939=>their tall houses quite enough, indeed too much for the dark end of a tiring 
line 13940=>day. He  pictured  black horses standing all  saddled in  the shadows of the 
line 13941=>inn-yard, and Black Riders peering out of dark upper windows. 
line 13942=>     'We  surely aren't going  to stay here for the night,  are we, sir?' he 
line 13943=>exclaimed. 'If there are hobbit-folk  in these  pans, why  don't we look for  
line 13944=>some  that would be willing to take us in? It would be more homelike.' 
line 13945=>     'What's wrong with the inn?' said Frodo. 'Tom Bombadil  recommended it. 
line 13946=>I expect it's homelike enough inside.' 
line 13947=>     Even from the outside the inn looked a pleasant house to familiar eyes. 
line 13948=>It had a front on  the Road, and two wings running  back on land partly  cut 
line 13949=>out  of the lower  slopes of the hill, so  that at the rear the second-floor 
line 13950=>windows were level  with the  ground.  There  was a wide  arch  leading to a  
line 13951=>courtyard between the two wings, and on the left under the arch there was  a  
