line 14115=>showing high boots of supple leather that fitted him well, but had seen much 
line 14116=>wear and were now caked with mud. A travel-stained cloak of heavy dark-
line 14117=>green 
line 14118=>cloth was  drawn  close  about him, and in spite of the heat of the room  he 
line 14119=>wore a hood  that overshadowed his  face; but the gleam of his eyes could be 
line 14120=>seen as he watched the hobbits. 
line 14121=>     'Who is that?' Frodo asked, when he  got  a chance  to  whisper  to Mr. 
line 14122=>Butterbur. 'I don't think you introduced him?' 
line 14123=>     'Him?' said  the  landlord in  an  answering whisper,  cocking  an  eye 
line 14124=>without  turning his head. 'I don't rightly know. He is one of the wandering 
line 14125=>folk -Rangers we call them. He seldom talks: not but what he can tell a rare 
line 14126=>tale when he has the mind. He disappears for a month, or a year, and then he 
line 14127=>pops  up again. He was in and out  pretty  often last spring; but I  haven't  
line 14128=>seen  him about lately. What his  right name is I've  never  heard: but he's 
line 14129=>known round here as Strider. Goes  about at a great pace on his long shanks;  
line 14130=>though  he  don't  tell nobody what cause  he has to hurry.  But there's  no 
line 14131=>accounting for East and West, as we say in Bree, meaning the Rangers and the 
line 14132=>Shire-folk, begging your pardon. Funny you  should  ask about  him.' But  at 
line 14133=>that moment Mr. Butterbur was called away  by a demand for more ale  and his 
line 14134=>last remark remained unexplained. 
line 14135=>     Frodo found that Strider was now looking at him, as if he  had heard or  
