line 14144=>     'Well, Master Underhill,' said Strider,  'if I were  you, I should stop 
line 14145=>your  young friends  from talking too much. Drink , fire,  and chance-meeting 
line 14146=>are pleasant enough, but, well - this  isn't the Shire. There are queer folk  
line 14147=>about. Though I  say it as shouldn't, you may  think,'  he  added with a wry 
line 14148=>
line 14149=>####-smile, seeing Frodo's glance. 'And  there have been even stranger travellers 
line 14150=>through Bree lately,' he went on, watching Frodo's face. 
line 14151=>     Frodo returned his  gaze but said nothing; and Strider made no  further  
line 14152=>sign.  His  attention  seemed  suddenly to be fixed on Pippin.  To his alarm 
line 14153=>Frodo became aware that the ridiculous young Took, encouraged by his success 
line 14154=>with  the fat  Mayor of  Michel  Delving, was  now actually  giving a  comic 
line 14155=>account of Bilbo's farewell party. He was already giving an imitation of the 
line 14156=>Speech, and was drawing near to the astonishing Disappearance. 
line 14157=>     Frodo was annoyed. It was a harmless enough tale for most  of the local 
line 14158=>hobbits, no doubt: just a  funny story about  those funny people away beyond 
line 14159=>the River;  but some (old Butterbur, for instance)  knew a thing or two, and 
line 14160=>had probably heard rumours long ago about  Bilbo's vanishing. It would bring 
line 14161=>the name of Baggins to their minds,  especially  if there had been inquiries 
line 14162=>in Bree after that name. 
line 14163=>     Frodo  fidgeted,  wondering  what to  do.  Pippin  was  evidently  much 
line 14164=>enjoying  the attention he was getting,  and had  become  quite forgetful of 
line 14165=>their danger. Frodo had a sudden fear that in his present mood he might even 
line 14166=>mention the Ring; and that might well be disastrous.  
line 14167=>     'You had better do something quick!' whispered Strider in his ear. 
line 14168=>     Frodo jumped up and stood on a table, and began to  talk. The attention 
line 14169=>of Pippin's audience was disturbed. Some of the  hobbits looked at Frodo and 
line 14170=>laughed and clapped, thinking that  Mr. Underhill  had taken as  much ale as 
line 14171=>was good for him. 
line 14172=>     Frodo  suddenly felt very foolish,  and found himself (as was his habit 
line 14173=>when making a speech) fingering  the things in his pocket. He felt the  Ring  
line 14174=>on its chain, and quite unaccountably the desire came over him to slip it on 
line 14175=>and vanish out of the silly  situation. It seemed to him,  somehow, as if me 
line 14176=>suggestion came to him from outside,  from someone or  something a the room. 
line 14177=>He resisted the  temptation firmly, and clasped  the Ring in his hand, as if 
line 14178=>to keep a hold on it and prevent it from escaping or doing any mischief.  At 
line 14179=>any rate it  gave him no inspiration. He spoke  'a  few suitable  words', as 
line 14180=>they  would have said  in the  Shire: We  are all  very much gratified by the 
line 14181=>kindness of your reception, and  I  venture to hope that my brief visit will 
line 14182=>help to  renew  the old ties of  friendship between the Shire and Bree;  and 
line 14183=>then he hesitated and coughed. 
line 14184=>     Everyone in the room was now  looking at him. 'A song!' shouted one  of 
line 14185=>the hobbits.  'A song! A song!' shouted all the others.  'Come on now, master, 
line 14186=>
line 14187=>####-sing us something that we haven't heard before!' 
line 14188=>     For  a  moment  Frodo  stood gaping. Then  in  desperation he  began  a  
line 14189=>ridiculous song tha t Bilbo had been rather  fond of (and indeed rather proud 
line 14190=>of, for he had made up the words himself). It was about an inn; and that  is 
line 14191=>probably why it came into Frodo's mind just then. Here it is in full. Only a  
line 14192=>few words of it are now, as a rule, remember ed. 
line 14193=>     There is an inn, a merry old inn 
line 14194=>     beneath an old grey hill, 
line 14195=>     And there they brew a beer so brown  
line 14196=>     That the Man in the Moon himself came down  
line 14197=>     one night to drink his fill. 
line 14198=> 
line 14199=>     The ostler has a tipsy cat 
line 14200=>     that plays a five-stringed fiddle; 
line 14201=>     And up and down he runs his bow,  
line 14202=>     Now squeaking high, now purring low,  
line 14203=>     now sawing in the middle. 
line 14204=> 
line 14205=>     The landlord keeps a little dog 
line 14206=>     that is mighty fond of jokes; 
line 14207=>     When there's good cheer among the guests, 
line 14208=>     He cocks an ear at all the jests 
line 14209=>     and laughs until he chokes. 
line 14210=> 
line 14211=>     They also keep a horned cow 
line 14212=>     as proud as any queen; 
line 14213=>     But music turns her head like ale, 
line 14214=>     And makes her wave her tufted tail 
line 14215=>     and dance upon the green. 
line 14216=> 
line 14217=>     And O! the rows of silver dishes 
line 14218=>     and the store of silver spoons! 
line 14219=>     For Sunday* there's a special pair, 
line 14220=>     And these they polish up with care 
line 14221=>     on Saturday afternoons. 
line 14222=> 
line 14223=>     The Man in the Moon was drinking deep, 
line 14224=>
line 14225=>####-     and the cat began to wail; 
line 14226=>     A dish and a  spoon on the table danced, 
line 14227=>     The cow in the garden madly pranced, 
line 14228=>     and the little dog chased his tail. 
line 14229=> 
line 14230=>     The Man in the Moon took another mug, 
line 14231=>     and then rolled beneath his chair; 
line 14232=>     And there he dozed and dreamed of ale, 
line 14233=>     Till in the sky the stars were pale, 
line 14234=>     and dawn was in the air. 
line 14235=> 
line 14236=>     Then the ostler said to his tipsy cat: 
line 14237=>     'The white horses of the Moon, 
line 14238=>     They neigh and champ their silver bits; 
line 14239=>     But their master's been and drowned his wits, 
line 14240=>     and the Sun'll be rising soon!'  
line 14241=> 
line 14242=>     So the cat on his fiddle played hey-diddle-diddle, 
line 14243=>     a jig that would wake the dead: 
line 14244=>     He squeaked and sawed and quickened the tune, 
line 14245=>     While the landlord shook the Man in the Moon: 
line 14246=>     'It's after three!' he said. 
line 14247=> 
line 14248=>     They rolled the Man slowly up the hill 
line 14249=>     and bundled him into the Moon, 
line 14250=>     While his horses galloped up in rear, 
line 14251=>     And the cow came capering like a deer, 
line 14252=>     and a dish ran up with the spoon. 
line 14253=> 
line 14254=>     Now quicker the fiddle went deedle -dum-diddle; 
line 14255=>     the dog began to roar, 
line 14256=>     The cow and the horses stood on their heads; 
line 14257=>     The guests all bounded from their beds 
line 14258=>     and danced upon the floor. 
line 14259=> 
line 14260=>     With a ping and a pong the fiddle -strings broke! 
line 14261=>     the cow jumped over the Moon, 
line 14262=>
line 14263=>####-     And the little dog laughed to see such fun, 
line 14264=>     And the Saturday dish went off at a run 
line 14265=>     with the silver Sunday spoon. 
line 14266=> 
line 14267=>     The round Moon rolled behind the hill 
line 14268=>     as the Sun raised up her head. 
line 14269=>     She* hardly believed her fiery eyes; 
line 14270=>     For though it was day, to her surprise 
line 14271=>     they all went back to bed! 
line 14272=>     There was loud and long applause. Frodo had a  good voice, and the song  
line 14273=>tickled their fancy.  'Where's old Barley?' they  cried. 'He ought  to  hear 
line 14274=>this. Bob  ought to learn his cat  the fiddle, and then we'd have a  dance.' 
line 14275=>They called for more ale, and  began to shout: 'Let's have it again, master! 
line 14276=>Come on now! Once more!' 
line 14277=>     They made  Frodo have another drink,  and then  begin his  song  again, 
line 14278=>while many of them  joined  in; for the tune was  well known, and  they were 
line 14279=>quick at picking up  words.  It  was now Frodo's turn to feel  pleased  with 
line 14280=>himself. He capered  about on the table; and when he came  a second  time to 
line 14281=>the cow jumped over the Moon, he leaped in the air. Much too vigorously; for  
line 14282=>he came down,  bang, into a  tray full of mugs, and slipped, and  rolled off 
line 14283=>the table with  a crash, clatter, and bump!  The audience  all opened  their 
line 14284=>mouths wide for laughter, and stopped short a gaping silence; for the singer  
line 14285=>disappeared. He simply  vanished, as  if he had  gone slap through the floor  
line 14286=>without leaving a hole!  
line 14287=>     The  local hobbits  stared in  amazement, and then sprang to their feet 
line 14288=>and shouted for Barliman. All the company drew away from Pippin and Sam, 
line 14289=>who 
line 14290=>found themselves left alone in a comer, and eyed darkly and  doubtfully from 
line 14291=>a  distance.  It was  plain  that many  people  regarded  them  now  as  the 
line 14292=>companions of a travelling magician of unknown powers and purpose. But 
line 14293=>there 
line 14294=>was one  swarthy Bree-lander, who stood looking at them with  a knowing  and 
line 14295=>half-mocking expression that made them feel very uncomfortable. Presently he 
line 14296=>slipped out of the door, followed by the squint-eyed southerner: the two had 
line 14297=>been  whispering  together  a  good  deal  during  the  evening.  Harry  the 
line 14298=>gatekeeper also went out just behind them.. 
line 14299=>     Frodo felt  a fool. Not knowing what else  to do, he crawled away under  
line 14300=>
line 14301=>####-the tables to the  dark comer by Strider, who sat unmoved, giving no sign of 
line 14302=>his thoughts. Frodo leaned back  against the wall and took off the Ring. How 
line 14303=>it came to be on his finger he could not tell. He could only suppose that he 
line 14304=>had  been handling it in his pocket while he sang, and  that somehow  it had 
line 14305=>slipped on  when he stuck out  his hand with a jerk to save his  fall. For a  
line 14306=>moment he wondered if the Ring itself had not played him a trick; perhaps it 
line 14307=>had tried to reveal itself in response to some wish or command that was felt 
line 14308=>in the room. He did not like the looks of the men that had gone out. 
line 14309=>     'Well?' said Strider, when he rea ppeared.  'Why did you do that?  Worse 
line 14310=>than anything your friends could have said! You have put your foot in it! Or  
line 14311=>should I say your finger?' 
line 14312=>     'I don't know what you mean,' said Frodo, annoyed and alarmed. 
line 14313=>     'Oh yes, you do,' answered Strider; 'but  we had better wait  until the 
line 14314=>uproar has  died down. Then, if you  please, Mr.  Baggins, I should  like  a  
line 14315=>quiet word with you.' 
line 14316=>     'What about?' asked Frodo, ignoring the sudden use of his proper name. 
line 14317=>     'A matter of  some importance  -  to us both,' answered Strider, looking 
line 14318=>Frodo in the eye. 'You may hear something to your advantage.' 
line 14319=>     'Very  well,' said Frodo,  trying to appear unconcerned. 'I'll talk  to 
line 14320=>you later.' 
line 14321=>     Meanwhile an argument was going on by the  fireplace. Mr. Butterbur had 
line 14322=>come trotting  in, and  he was now  trying  to listen to several conflicting 
line 14323=>accounts of the event at the same time. 
line 14324=>     'I saw him, Mr.  Butterbur,' said a hobbit;  'or leastways I didn't see 
line 14325=>him, if you take my meaning. He just vanished  into thin air, in a manner of 
line 14326=>speaking.' 
line 14327=>     'You don't say, Mr. Mugwort!' said the landlord, looking puzzled. 
line 14328=>     'Yes I do!' replied Mugwort. 'And I mean what I say, what's more.' 
line 14329=>     'There's some  mistake  somewhere,' said  Butterbur,  shaking his head. 
line 14330=>There was  too much of  that Mr. Underhill to go vanishing  into thin air; or  
line 14331=>into thick air, as is more likely in this room.' 
line 14332=>     'Well, where is he now?' cried several voices.  
line 14333=>     'How should I  know?  He's welcome to go  where he will, so long as  he  
line 14334=>pays in the  morning. There's Mr. Took, now: he's not vanished.' 
line 14335=>     'Well,  I  saw what I  saw,  and  I saw what I  didn't,'  said  Mugwort 
line 14336=>obstinately. 
line 14337=>     'And I say there's  some mistake,' repeated  Butterbur,  picking up the 
line 14338=>
line 14339=>####-tray and gathering up the broken crockery. 
line 14340=>     'Of course there's a mistake!' said Frodo. 'I haven't vanished. Here  I 
line 14341=>am! I've just been having a few words with Strider in the comer.' 
line 14342=>     He  came forward into  the  firelight;  but most of the company  backed 
line 14343=>away,, even more perturbed than before. They were not in the least satisfied 
line 14344=>by his explanation that he had crawled away quickly  under the  tables after  
line 14345=>he  had fallen. Most of the  Hobbits  and the Men of Bree went off then  and 
line 14346=>there in a huff, having no fancy for further entertainment that evening. One 
line 14347=>or two gave Frodo a black look and departed muttering among themselves.  
line 14348=>The 
line 14349=>Dwarves and the two or three strange Men that still remained got up and said 
line 14350=>good night to the landlord, but not to Frodo and his friends. Before long no 
line 14351=>one was left but Strider, who sat on, unnoticed, by the wall. 
line 14352=>     Mr. Butterbur did  not seem  much put out. He reckoned,  very probably,  
line 14353=>that his house would be full again on many future  nights, until the present 
line 14354=>mystery had been  thoroughly discussed. 'N ow what have  you been doing,  Mr. 
line 14355=>Underhill?'  he asked.  'Frightening  my customers and breaking up my crocks 
line 14356=>with your acrobatics!' 
line 14357=>     'I am very sorry to have caused any trouble,' said Frodo. 'It was quite 
line 14358=>unintentional, I assure you. A most unfortunate accident.' 
line 14359=>     'All right, Mr. Underhill! But if you're going to do any more tumbling, 
line 14360=>or conjuring, or whatever it was, you'd best warn folk beforehand  - and warn 
line 14361=>me. We're a bit suspicious round here of anything  out of  the way -uncanny,  
line 14362=>if you understand me; and we don't take to it all of a sudden.' 
line 14363=>     'I shan't be doing anything of the sort again, Mr. Butterbur, I promise 
line 14364=>you.  And now  I think I'll be getting  to bed. We shall be  making an early 
line 14365=>start. Will you see that our ponies are ready by  eight o'clock?' 
line 14366=>     'Very  good! But  before  you go, I  should like  a  word  with you  in 
line 14367=>private, Mr. Underhill. Something has just come back to my mind that I ought 
line 14368=>to tell you. I hope that you'll not take it amiss. When I've seen to a thing 
line 14369=>or two, I'll come along to your room, if you're willing.' 
line 14370=>     'Certainly!'  said Frodo; but his  heart  sank.  He wondered  how  many 
line 14371=>private talks  he would have before  he  got to  bed,  and  what  they would 
line 14372=>reveal. Were  these people  all in league against him?  He  began to suspect 
line 14373=>even old Butterbur's fat face of concealing dark designs. 
line 14374=> 
line 14375=> 
line 14376=>
line 14377=>####-<h4>Chapter 10</h4> <br>. Strider 
line 14378=>
line 14379=> 
line 14380=> 
line 14381=>     Frodo, Pippin, and Sam made their way back to the parlour. There was no 
line 14382=>light. Merry was not there, and the  fire had burned low.  It  was not until 
line 14383=>they had puffed up the embers into a blaze and thrown on a couple of faggots 
line 14384=>that they discovered Strider had come with them. There he was calmly sitting 
line 14385=>in a chair by the door! 
line 14386=>     'Hallo!' said Pippin. 'Who are you, and what do you want?' 
line 14387=>     'I  am called Strider,' he answered: 'and  though he may have forgotten 
line 14388=>it, your friend promised to have a quiet talk with me.' 
line 14389=>     'You  said  I  might  hear something to my advantage, I  believe,' said 
line 14390=>Frodo. 'What have you to say?' 
line 14391=>     'Several things,' a nswered Strider. 'But, of course, I have my price.' 
line 14392=>     'What do you mean?' asked Frodo sharply. 
line 14393=>     'Don't be alarmed! I mean just this: I will tell you  what I  know, and 
line 14394=>give you some good advice  - but I shall want a reward.' 
line 14395=>     'And what will that be, pray?' said Frodo. He suspected now that he had 
line 14396=>fallen in with a rascal, and he thought uncomfortably  that  he had  brought 
line 14397=>only a little money with him. All of it would hardly satisfy a rogue, and he 
line 14398=>could not spare any of it. 
line 14399=>     'No more than  you  can afford,' answered  Strider with a slow smile, as 
line 14400=>if he guessed Frodo's thoughts. 'Just this: you must take me along with you, 
line 14401=>until I wish to leave you.' 
line 14402=>     'Oh, indeed!' replied Frodo, surprised, but not much relieved. 'Even if 
line 14403=>I wanted another  companion, I should  not  agree to any such thing, until I 
line 14404=>knew a good deal more about you, and your business.' 
line 14405=>     'Excellent!' exclaimed  Strider,  crossing  his legs  and sitting  back  
line 14406=>comfortably. 'You seem to be coming to your senses again, and that is all to 
line 14407=>the good. You have been much too careless so far. Very well! I will tell you  
line 14408=>what I know, and leave the reward to  you. You may be glad to grant it, when 
line 14409=>you have heard me.' 
line 14410=>     'Go on then!' said Frodo. 'What do you know?' 
line 14411=>     'Too much; too many dark things,' said Strider grimly. 'But as for your 
line 14412=>business --' He got  up and went to the door,  opened it quickly  and looked 
line 14413=>out.  Then  he shut it quietly and  sat  down again. 'I have quick ears,' he 
line 14414=>went  on, lowering his voice, 'and  though I cannot disappear, I have hunted 
line 14415=>
line 14416=>####-many  wild  and wary  things and I can usually avoid being  seen, if I wish. 
line 14417=>Now, I was behind the hedge this evening on the Road west of Bree, when four 
line 14418=>hobbits  came out  of the Downlands. I need not repeat all that they said to 
line 14419=>old  Bombadil  or  to  one  another, but  one  thing interested  me.  Please 
line 14420=>remember, said one of them,  that the name Baggins  must not be mentioned. I 
line 14421=>am Mr. Underhill, if any name must be given. That interested me so much that 
line 14422=>I followed them here.  I slipped  over the gate just behind them.  Maybe Mr.  
line 14423=>Baggins  has  an  honest reason  for  leaving his name  behind; but if so, I 
line 14424=>should advise him and his friends to be more careful.' 
line 14425=>     'I don't see what interest my name has for any one in Bree,' sa id Frodo 
line 14426=>angrily,  'and I have still to  learn why  it interests you. Mr. Strider may 
line 14427=>have an honest reason  for spying  and eavesdropping;  but  if so,  I should 
line 14428=>advise him to explain it.' 
line 14429=>     'Well answered!' said Strider laughing. 'But the explanation is simple: 
line 14430=>     I was looking for  a Hobbit called Frodo Baggins. I wanted  to find him 
line 14431=>quickly. I had learned that he was carrying out of the Shire, well, a secret 
line 14432=>that concerned me and my friends.  
line 14433=>     'Now, don't mistake me!' he cried, as Frodo rose from his seat, and Sam 
line 14434=>jumped up  with a scowl. 'I shall take more care of  the secret than you do. 
line 14435=>And care  is  needed!' He leaned forward  and  looked at them. 'Watch  every 
line 14436=>shadow!' he said in a  low  voice. 'Black horsemen have passed through Bree. 
line 14437=>On  Monday one came down the Greenway, they say; and another appeared 
line 14438=>later, 
line 14439=>coming up the Greenway from the south.' 
line 14440=>     There was a silence. At last Frodo spoke to Pippin and Sam: 'I ought to 
line 14441=>have guessed  it from the way the gatekeeper greeted us,' he said.  'And  the 
line 14442=>landlord  seems  to  have heard something. Why did  he press us to join  the 
line 14443=>company?  And  why  on  earth  did we  behave so foolishly: we ought to have 
line 14444=>stayed quiet in here.' 
line 14445=>     'It would  have been better,' said Strider. 'I would  have stopped your 
line 14446=>going into  the  common-room, if I could; but the innkeeper would not let me 
line 14447=>in to see you, or take a message.' 
line 14448=>     'Do you think he------' began Frodo. 
line 14449=>     'No,  I  don't  think any  harm  of old Butterbur.  Only  he  does  not 
line 14450=>altogether like  mysterious vagabonds  of my sort.' Frodo gave him a puzzled 
line 14451=>look. 'Well, I have rather a rascally look, have I not?' said Strider with a  
line 14452=>curl of his lip and a  queer gleam in  his eye. 'But I  hope we shall get to 
line 14453=>
line 14454=>####-know one another better.  When we do, I hope you will explain  what happened 
line 14455=>at the end of your song. For that little prank ------' 
line 14456=>     'It was sheer accident!' interrupted Frodo. 
line 14457=>     'I wonder,' said Strider. 'Accident, then. That  accident has made your 
line 14458=>position dangerous.' 
line 14459=>     'Hardly more than it  was already,' said Frodo.  'I knew these horsemen 
line 14460=>were pursuing me;  but now  at any rate they seem to  have  missed me and to 
line 14461=>have gone away.' 
line 14462=>     'You  must not count on that!' said Strider sharply. 'They will return. 
line 14463=>And more  are  coming. There are others. I know their  number. I know  these 
line 14464=>Riders.' He paused,  and his  eyes were cold and hard. 'And there  are  some 
line 14465=>folk  in Bree who  are  not to be  trusted,'  he went on.  'Bill  Ferny, for  
line 14466=>instance. He  has an evil name in the Bree-land,  and queer folk call at his 
line 14467=>house.  You  must  have  noticed him among the  company:  a swarthy sneering 
line 14468=>fellow.  He  was very close with  one  of  the Southern  strangers, and they 
line 14469=>slipped  out   together  just  after  your  "accident".  Not  all  of  those 
line 14470=>Southerners mean well; and as for Ferny, he would sell anything  to anybody; 
line 14471=>or make mischief for amusement.' 
line 14472=>     'What  will Ferny sell,  and what has my accident got to do  with him?' 
line 14473=>said Frodo, still determined not to understand Strider's hints.  
line 14474=>     'News  of you,  of  course,'  answered  Strider.  'An  account of  your 
line 14475=>performance would  be very interesting to certain  people.  After that  they 
line 14476=>would hardly  need to be told your real name. It seems to me only too likely  
line 14477=>that they will hear of it befor e this night is over. Is that enough? You can 
line 14478=>do as you like  about my  reward: take me as a guide  or  not. But I may say 
line 14479=>that I know all the lands  between the Shire and  the Misty Mountains, for I 
line 14480=>have  wandered over  them for many years. I  am  older than  I look. I might  
line 14481=>prove useful. You will  have to leave the  open  road after tonight; for the 
line 14482=>horsemen will  watch  it  night and  day. You may  escape from  Bree, and be 
line 14483=>allowed to  go forward while the Sun is up;  but you won't go far. They will 
line 14484=>come on you in the wild, in some dark  place where  there is no help. Do you 
line 14485=>wish them to find you? They are terrible!' 
line 14486=>     The  hobbits looked at him,  and  saw  with surprise that  his face was 
line 14487=>drawn  as if with pain, and  his hands clenched the arms of  his  chair. The 
line 14488=>room was very quiet and still, and the light seemed to have grown dim. For a 
line 14489=>while he sat with unseeing eyes as if walking in distant memory or listening  
line 14490=>to sounds in the Night far away. 
line 14491=>
line 14492=>####-     'There!' he  cried  after  a moment, drawing his hand  across his brow.  
line 14493=>'Perhaps I know  more about these pursuers than you  do.  You fear them, but 
line 14494=>you do not fear them enough,  yet. Tomorrow you will  have to escape, if you 
line 14495=>can. Strider can take  you by paths that  are  seldom trodden. Will you have 
line 14496=>him? ' 
line 14497=>     There was a heavy silence. Frodo made no answer, his mind was  confused 
line 14498=>with doubt and fear. Sam frowned,  and looked at his  master; and at last he 
line 14499=>broke out: 
line 14500=>     'With  your leave,  Mr. Frodo, I'd  say no! This Strider here, he warns 
line 14501=>and he says take care; and  I say  yes to that, and let's begin with him. He 
line 14502=>comes out  of  the Wild, and I  never heard no good  of such  folk. He knows 
line 14503=>something, that's  plain,  and more  than  I like; but it's no reason why we 
line 14504=>should let him go leading us out into  some dark place  far from help, as he 
line 14505=>puts it.' 
line 14506=>     Pippin fidgeted and looked uncomfortable. Strider did not reply to Sam, 
line 14507=>but turned his keen eyes  on Frodo. Frodo caught his glance and looked away. 
line 14508=>'No,' he said slowly. 'I don't agree. I think, I think you are not really as 
line 14509=>you  choose to  look. You began  to talk to me like the Bree-folk,  but your 
line 14510=>voice has changed. Still Sam seems right in this: I don't see why you should 
line 14511=>warn us to take care, and yet ask us to take you on trust. Why the disguise?  
line 14512=>Who are  you? What do you really know about - about my business; and how  
line 14513=>do 
line 14514=>you know it?' 
line 14515=>     'The lesson in caution has been well learned,' said Strider with a grim 
line 14516=>smile. 'But caution is one thing and wavering is another. You will never get 
line 14517=>to Rivende ll now on your own, and to trust me is your only chance. You  must  
line 14518=>make up your  mind. I will answer some of your  questions, if that will help 
line 14519=>you to do so.  But  why should you believe  my story, if you do not trust me 
line 14520=>already? Still here it is------' 
line 14521=>     At that  moment  there  came a  knock at the  door.  Mr. Butterbur  had 
