line 14854=>     'Well Masters,' said  Nob, 'I've ruffled up  the clothes  and  put in a  
line 14855=>bolster down the  middle of  each bed.  And I made a  nice imitation of your  
line 14856=>head  with a brown woollen mat, Mr. Bag  - Underhill,  sir,' he added with  a  
line 14857=>grin. 
line 14858=>     Pippin laughed. 'Very life-like!'  he said. 'But  wha t will happen when 
line 14859=>they have penetrated the disguise?' 
line 14860=>     'We shall  see,'  said  Strider.  'Let us hope  to hold the  fort  till 
line 14861=>morning.' 
line 14862=>     'Good  night to  you,' said Nob, and went off to take  his part in  the 
line 14863=>watch on the doors.  
line 14864=>     Their bags and gear they piled on the parlour -floor. They pushed a  low 
line 14865=>chair against the door and shut the window. Peering  out, Frodo saw that the 
line 14866=>night was still clear. The Sickle was swinging bright above the shoulders of  
line 14867=>Bree-hill. He then closed and barred  the heavy inside shutters and drew the  
line 14868=>curtains together. Strider built up the fire and blew out all the candles.  
line 14869=>     The  hobbits lay  down  on their blankets  with their feet  towards the 
line 14870=>hearth; but  Strider settled himself  in the chair against  the  door .  They 
line 14871=>
line 14872=>####-talked for a little, for Merry still had several questions to ask. 
line 14873=>     'Jumped over  the Moon!'  chuckled  Merry as he rolled himself  in  his 
line 14874=>blanket. 'Very ridiculous of you, Frodo! But I wish I had been there to see. 
line 14875=>The worthies of Bree will be discussing it a hundred years hence.' 
line 14876=>     'I  hope so,' said Strider. Then  they all fell  silent, and one by one 
line 14877=>the hobbits dropped off to sleep. 
line 14878=> 
line 14879=>
line 14880=>####- 
line 14881=>
line 14882=>Chapter 11. A Knife in the Dark 
line 14883=>
line 14884=> 
line 14885=> 
line 14886=>     As  they prepared  for sleep  in  the  inn at  Bree,  darkness  lay  on 
line 14887=>Buckland; a mist strayed in the dells and along the river -bank. The house at 
line 14888=>Crickhollow stood silent. Fatty Bolger opened the door cautiously and peered 
line 14889=>out. A feeling of fear had been growing on him all day, and he was unable to 
line 14890=>rest or go to bed: there was a brooding threat  in the breathless night-air. 
line 14891=>As he  stared out into the gloom, a black shadow moved under the trees;  the 
line 14892=>gate  seemed  to open  of its own  accord and close again without  a  sound. 
line 14893=>Terror seized him. He  shrank  back,  and for a moment he stood trembling in 
line 14894=>the hall. Then he shut and locked the door. 
line 14895=>     The night  deepened.  There  came  the  soft  sound of horses  led with 
line 14896=>stealth  along the  lane.  Outside  the gate  they stopped, and three  black  
line 14897=>figures entered,  like shades of night  creeping across the ground. One went 
line 14898=>to the door, one to the corner of the house on  either side; and there  they 
line 14899=>stood, as  still as the shadows of  stones, while night went slowly on.  The 
line 14900=>house and the quiet trees seemed to be waiting breathlessly. 
line 14901=>     There was a faint stir  in the leaves, and  a cock crowed far away. The 
line 14902=>cold hour before dawn was passing. The figure by the door moved. In the dark 
line 14903=>without moon or stars a drawn blade gleamed,  as  if a chill light had  been 
line 14904=>unsheathed.  There was a blow, soft but heavy, and the door shuddered. 
line 14905=>     'Open, in the name of Mordor!' said a voice thin and menacing. 
line 14906=>     At a second blow the door yielded and fell back, with timbers burst and 
line 14907=>lock broken. The black figures passed swiftly in. 
line 14908=>     At that moment, among the trees nearby,  a  horn rang out.  It rent the 
line 14909=>night like fire on a hill-top. 
line 14910=>     AWAKE! FEAR! FIRE! FOES! AWAKE! 
line 14911=>     Fatty Bolger had not been idle. As soon as he saw the dark shapes creep 
line 14912=>from the garden, he knew that he must run for it, or perish. And run he did, 
line 14913=>out  of the  back door, through  the garden,  and over the  fields.  When he 
line 14914=>reached  the  nearest  house,  more  than a mile  away, he  collapsed on the 
line 14915=>doorstep. 'No, no, no!'  he was  crying. 'No,  not me! I haven't got it!' It 
line 14916=>was  some time  before anyone could make out what he  was babbling about. 
line 14917=>At 
line 14918=>last they got the idea that enemies were in Buckland, some strange  invasion 
line 14919=>
line 14920=>####-from the Old Forest. And then they lost no more time. 
line 14921=>     FEAR! FIRE! FOES! 
line 14922=>     The Brandybucks were blowing  the Horn-call of  Buckland,  that had not 
line 14923=>been sounded for  a hundred years, not  since the white wolves came  in  the 
line 14924=>Fell Winter, when the Brandywine was frozen over. 
line 14925=>     AWAKE! AWAKE! 
line 14926=>     Far-away answering horns were heard. The alarm was spreading. The black  
line 14927=>figures fled from the house.  One  of them  let fall a  hobbit-cloak  on the 
line 14928=>step, as he ran. In the lane the noise  of hoofs broke out, and gathering to 
line 14929=>a gallop, went hammering away into the darkness. All about Crickhollow there 
line 14930=>was the sound  of horns blowing, and voices crying and feet running. But the 
line 14931=>Black Riders rode like a gale to the North-gate. Let the little people blow!  
line 14932=>Sauron  would deal  with them later. Meanwhile they had another errand: they 
line 14933=>knew now that the house  was empty and the Ring had gone. They rode down 
line 14934=>the 
line 14935=>guards at the gate and vanished from the Shire. 
line 14936=>     In  the early night  Frodo woke from deep  sleep, suddenly, as if  some 
line 14937=>sound or presence  had disturbed  him. He saw that Strider was sitting alert 
line 14938=>in his  chair: his  eyes gleamed in  the light of the  fire, which had  been 
line 14939=>tended and was burning brightly; but he made no sign or movement. 
line 14940=>     Frodo soon went to sleep again; but his dreams were again troubled with  
line 14941=>the noise  of wind and of ga lloping  hoofs.  The wind  seemed to be  curling  
line 14942=>round the house and shaking it; and far off  he heard a horn blowing wildly.  
line 14943=>He  opened his  eyes,  and  heard a  cock  crowing  lustily in the inn-yard. 
line 14944=>Strider  had  drawn the  curtains and pushed back the shutters with a clang. 
line 14945=>The  first  grey light of day  was in the room, and  a  cold  air was coming 
line 14946=>through the open window.  
line 14947=>     As soon  as  Strider  had roused them  all,  he led  the  way  to their 
line 14948=>bedrooms. When they  saw them they were glad that they had taken his advice: 
line 14949=>the windows had been forced  open and were  swinging, and  the curtains were 
line 14950=>flapping; the beds  were tossed about,  and the bolsters  slashed and  flung 
line 14951=>upon the floor; the brown mat was torn to pieces. 
line 14952=>     Strider  immediately  went  to fetch the landlord. Poor  Mr.  Butterbur 
line 14953=>looked sleepy and frightened. He had hardly closed his eyes all night (so he 
line 14954=>said), but he had never heard a sound. 
line 14955=>     'Never has such  a thing happened  in my  time!' he cried,  raising his 
line 14956=>hands in horror. 'Guests unable to sleep in  their beds,  and good  bolsters 
line 14957=>
line 14958=>####-ruined and all! What are we coming to?' 
line 14959=>     'Dark times,' said  Strider. 'But for  the present you  may be left  in 
line 14960=>peace,  when you have got rid of us. We will leave at once. Never mind about 
line 14961=>breakfast: a drink  and a bite standing will have to do. We shall be  packed 
line 14962=>in a few minutes.' 
line 14963=>     Mr. Butterbur hurried off to see that their ponies were  got ready, and 
line 14964=>to fetch them a 'bite'. But very soon he came back in dismay. The ponies had 
line 14965=>vanished!  The stable-doors had all  been opened in the night, and they were 
line 14966=>gone: not only Merry's ponies, but every other horse and beast in the place. 
line 14967=>     Frodo was  crushed by the news. How  could they hope to reach Rivendell 
line 14968=>on foot, pursued  by  mounted enemies? They might as  well  set  out for the 
line 14969=>Moon. Strider sat silent for a while, looking at the hobbits,  as if he  was 
line 14970=>weighing up their strength and courage. 
line 14971=>     'Ponies would  not help  us to  escape  horsemen,'  he  said  at  last, 
line 14972=>thoughtfully, as if he guessed  what Frodo  had in  mind. 'We should  not go 
line 14973=>much slower on foot, not  on the roads that I mean to take.  I was  going to 
line 14974=>walk in any case. It is the food and stores that trouble me. We cannot count 
line 14975=>on getting anything to  eat between here and Rivendell, except  what we take 
line 14976=>with  us; and we ought to take plenty  to spare; for we  may be delayed,  or  
line 14977=>forced  to  go round-about, far out  of  the direct way.  How much  are  you  
line 14978=>prepared to carry on your backs?' 
line 14979=>     'As  much as we must,' said Pippin with  a sinking heart, but trying to 
line 14980=>show that he was tougher than he looked (or felt). 
line 14981=>     'I can carry enough for two,' said Sam defiantly. 
line 14982=>     'Can't  anything be done,  Mr. Butterbur?' asked Frodo. 'Can't we get a  
line 14983=>couple of  ponies in the vi llage, or even one  just for the baggage? I don't  
line 14984=>suppose we  could  hire  them, but we might be able to buy them,' he  added,  
line 14985=>doubtfully, wondering if he could afford it. 
line 14986=>     'I  doubt  it,'  said   the  landlord  unhappily.  'The  two  or  three 
line 14987=>riding-ponies that there were in Bree were stabled  in  my yard, and they're 
line 14988=>gone.  As for other animals, horses or ponies for draught or what not, there 
line 14989=>are very few of them in Bree, and they won't be for sale. But I'll do what I 
line 14990=>can. I'll rout out Bob and send him round as soon as may be.' 
line 14991=>     'Yes,' said Strider reluctantly, 'you  had better do that. I am  afraid 
line 14992=>we  shall have to try  to get  one pony at least. But so ends  all  hope  of 
line 14993=>starting early,  and  slipping away quietly! We might as  well have  blown a  
line 14994=>horn to announce our departure. That was part of their plan, no doubt.' 
line 14995=>
line 14996=>####-     'There is one crumb of comfort,' said Merry, 'and more than a  crumb, I 
line 14997=>hope: we  can have  breakfast while we wait  - and sit down to it.  Let's get 
line 14998=>hold of Nob!' 
line 14999=>     In the end there was more  than three hours'  delay. Bob came back with 
line 15000=>the  report  that  no horse or pony was to be got for love  or  money in the 
line 15001=>neighbourhood - except one: Bill Ferny had  one that he might possibly sell.  
line 15002=>'A poor old half-starved creature it is,'  said Bob; 'but he won't part with 
line 15003=>it for less than thrice its worth, seeing how  you're placed, not if I knows 
line 15004=>Bill Ferny.' 
line 15005=>     'Bill  Ferny?'  said Frodo. 'Isn't there some trick? Wouldn't the beast  
line 15006=>bolt back to him with all our stuff, or help in tracking us, or something?' 
line 15007=>     'I wonder,' said Strider. 'But I cannot imagine any animal running home 
line 15008=>to him, once  it got  away.  I  fancy this  is only an  afterthought of kind 
line 15009=>Master  Ferny's: just a  way of increasing his profits  from the affair. The 
line 15010=>chief  danger is that the poor beast is probably at  death's door. But there 
line 15011=>does not seem any choice. What does he want for it?' 
line 15012=>     Bill Ferny's price was twelve  silver pennies; and  that  was indeed at 
line 15013=>least  three times the pony's value in those pans. It  proved to  be a bony, 
line 15014=>underfed, and dispirited  animal; but  it did  not look like dying just yet. 
line 15015=>Mr. Butterbur paid for it himself, and offered Merry  another eighteen pence 
line 15016=>as  some  compensation  for  the  lost animals. He was an  honest  man,   and 
line 15017=>well-off as things were reckoned  in Bree;  but thirty silver pennies was  a  
line 15018=>sore blow to him, and being cheated by Bill Ferny made it harder to bear. 
line 15019=>     As a matter of fact he came out on the right side in the end. It turned 
line 15020=>out later that only one  horse had been actually stolen. The others had been 
line 15021=>driven off, or  had  bolted in terror, and were found wandering in different 
line 15022=>corners  of  the  Bree-land.  Merry's  ponies  had  escaped altogether,  and 
line 15023=>eventually (having a good deal of sense) they made their way to the Downs in 
line 15024=>search of Fatty Lumpkin. So they came under  the care  of Tom Bombadil for a  
line 15025=>while, and were well-off. But when  news of the events at Bree came to Tom's 
line 15026=>ears, he sent them to Mr. Butterbur, who thus got five good beasts at a very 
line 15027=>fair price. They had  to work harder in Bree, but  Bob treated them well; so 
line 15028=>on the whole  they were lucky: they missed a dark and dangerous journey. But 
line 15029=>they never came to Rivendell. 
line 15030=>     However, in the meanwhile for all Mr. Butterbur knew his money was gone 
line 15031=>for  good, or  for bad.  And he had other troubles. For  there  was a  great 
line 15032=>commotion as soon as  the remaining  guests were astir and heard news of the 
line 15033=>
line 15034=>####-raid  on the inn. The southern travellers had lost several horses and blamed 
line 15035=>the innkeeper loudly, until it became known that one of their own number had 
line 15036=>also  disappeared  in the  night,  none  other than Bill Ferny's squint-eyed 
line 15037=>companion. Suspicion fell on him at once. 
line 15038=>     'If you pick up with  a  horse-thief, and  bring him to my house,' said 
line 15039=>Butterbur angrily, 'you ought to pay  for all the damage yourselves and  not 
line 15040=>come shouting at me. Go and ask Ferny where your handsome friend is!' But it 
line 15041=>appeared that he was nobody's friend, and nobody could recollect when he had 
line 15042=>joined their party. 
line 15043=>     After  their  breakfast the  hobbits had to re-pack,  and get  together  
line 15044=>further  supplies for  the  longer  journey  they were now expecting. It was 
line 15045=>close on ten o'clock before they at last got off. By  that time the whole of 
line 15046=>Bree was buzzing with excitement. Frodo's vanishing trick; the appearance of 
line 15047=>the black  horsemen; the robbing of the stables; and not least the news that 
line 15048=>Strider  the Ranger  had joined the  mysterious hobbits, made such a tale as 
line 15049=>would last for  many  uneventful years. Most of  the inhabitants of Bree and  
line 15050=>Staddle, and many  even  from Combe and Archet, were crowded in the  road 
line 15051=>to 
line 15052=>see the travellers start. The other  guests in  the inn were at the doors or  
line 15053=>hanging out of the windows. 
line 15054=>     Strider had changed his mind, and  he decided  to leave Bree by the main 
line 15055=>road. Any attempt to set  off across country at once would only make matters 
line 15056=>worse: half the inhabitants would follow them,  to see what they were up to,  
line 15057=>and to prevent them from trespassing. 
line 15058=>     They said farewell to Nob and Bob, and took leave of Mr. Butterbur with 
line 15059=>many thanks. 'I  hope we shall  meet again some  day, when things are  merry 
line 15060=>once more,' said Frodo. 'I  should like nothing better than  to stay in your 
line 15061=>house in peace for a while.' 
line 15062=>     They tramped off, anxious and downhearted, under the eyes of the crowd. 
line 15063=>Not  all  the faces were friendly, nor all the words that were shouted.  But 
line 15064=>Strider seemed to be held in awe by most of the Bree-landers, and those that 
line 15065=>he stared at shut their mouths and drew away. He walked in  front with Frodo; 
line 15066=>next came  Merry  and Pippin; and last came Sam leading the pony,  which was 
line 15067=>laden with as much  of their baggage as  they  had the heart to give it; but 
line 15068=>already it looked less dejected,  as  if  it approved of the  change in  its 
line 15069=>fortunes.  Sam  was chewing an  apple thoughtfully. He had a pocket full  of 
line 15070=>them:  a parting  present from Nob and  Bob. 'Apples for walking, and a pipe 
line 15071=>
line 15072=>####-for sitting,' he said. 'But I reckon I'll miss them both before long.' 
line 15073=>     The hobbits took no notice of the inquisitive heads that peeped  out of 
line 15074=>doors,  or  popped over walls and fences,  as they passed. But as they  drew 
line 15075=>near to  the further gate, Frodo saw a  dark  ill-kept  house behind a thick  
line 15076=>hedge: the  last  house  in the village.  In one of the  windows he caught a  
line 15077=>glimpse of a sallow face with sly, slanting eyes; but it vanished at once. 
line 15078=>     'So that's where that southerner is hiding!' he thought. 'He looks more 
line 15079=>than half like a goblin.' 
line 15080=>     Over the hedge  another  man  was  staring boldly.  He  had heavy black  
line 15081=>brows, and  dark scornful eyes; his large mouth curled in  a  sneer.  He was 
line 15082=>smoking a  short black pipe. As they approached he took it out  of his mouth 
line 15083=>and spat. 
line 15084=>     'Morning,  Longshanks!' he  said.  'Off  early?  Found some  friends at 
line 15085=>last?' Strider nodded, but did not answer.  'Morning, my little friends!' he 
line 15086=>said  to the  others. 'I suppose you know who you've taken  up  with? That's 
line 15087=>Stick -at-naught  Strider,  that is!  Though  I've  heard other names not  so 
line 15088=>pretty.  Watch out tonight! And you,  Sammie, don't  go ill-treating my poor  
line 15089=>old pony! Pah!' He spat again. 
line 15090=>     Sam turned quickly. 'And you.  Ferny,' he said, 'put your ugly face out 
line 15091=>of sight, or it will get  hurt.' With a sudden flick, quick as lightning, an 
line 15092=>apple left his hand and hit Bill square on the nose. He ducked too late, and 
line 15093=>curses  came from  behind  the  hedge.  'Waste  of a  good apple,'  said Sam 
line 15094=>regretfully, and strode on. 
line 15095=>     At last  they  left  the  village  behind. The  escort of children  and 
line 15096=>stragglers  that  had  followed  them  got  tired  and  turned  back at  the 
line 15097=>South-gate. Passing through, they kept on along the Road for some  miles. It  
line 15098=>bent to the left, curving back into its eastward line as it rounded the feet 
line 15099=>of  Bree-hill,  and  then  it  began to run  swiftly downwards  into  wooded 
line 15100=>country. To their left they could see some of the houses and hobbit-holes of 
line 15101=>Staddle on the  gentler  south-eastern  slopes of  the hill; down in  a deep 
line 15102=>hollow away north of the Road there were wisps of rising  smoke  that showed 
line 15103=>where Combe lay; 
line 15104=>     Archet was hidden in the trees beyond. 
line 15105=>     After the  Road had run down some way, and  had left Bree-hill standing 
line 15106=>tall and brown behind, they came on a narrow track that led off towards  the 
line 15107=>North. 'This is where we leave  the open and take to cover,' said Strider. 
line 15108=>     'Not a "short cut", I hope,' said  Pippin.  'Our last short cut through 
line 15109=>
line 15110=>####-woods nearly ended in disaster.' 
line 15111=>     'Ah, but you had not  got me with you then,' laughed Strider. 'My cuts,  
line 15112=>short  or long, don't go wrong.' He took a look up and down the Road. No one 
line 15113=>was in sight; and he led the way quickly down towards the wooded valley. 
line 15114=>     His  plan, as  far as  they  could understand  it without  knowing  the 
line 15115=>country, was to go towards Archet at first, but to bear right and pass it on 
line 15116=>the  east, and then to steer as straight as he could over the wild lands  to 
line 15117=>Weathertop Hill. In that way they  would, if all went well,  cut off a great 
line 15118=>loop of the Road,  which  further on bent southwards to avoid the Midgewater  
line 15119=>Marshes.  But,  of  course, they  would have  to  pass  through  the marshes 
line 15120=>themselves, and Strider's description of them was not encouraging. 
line 15121=>     However,  in the meanwhile, walking was not unpleasant.  Indeed, if  it 
line 15122=>had not been for the disturbing events  of the night before, they would have 
line 15123=>enjoyed this pan of the journey better than any up to that time. The sun was 
line 15124=>shining, clear but not too hot. The woods in the valley were still leafy and 
line 15125=>full  of  colour, and  seemed  peaceful  and wholesome. Strider   guided them 
line 15126=>confidently among the many crossing paths, although left  to themselves they 
line 15127=>would soon have  been at  a loss. He was taking a wandering course with many 
line 15128=>turns and doublings, to put off any pursuit. 
line 15129=>     'Bill Ferny will have watched where we left the Road, for certain,'  he 
line 15130=>said;  'though I don't think he  will follow  us himself. He  knows the land 
line 15131=>round here well enough, but he knows he is not a  match for me in a wood. It 
line 15132=>is what he may tell others that I am afraid of. I don't suppose they are far 
line 15133=>away. If they think we have made for Archet, so much the better.' 
line 15134=>     Whether because  of Strider's skill or for some other reason,  they saw 
line 15135=>no sign and heard no  sound of any other living thing all  that day: neither  
line 15136=>two-footed,  except  birds;  nor  four-footed,  except  one  fox  and  a  few 
line 15137=>squirrels. The next day  they began to steer a steady  course eastwards; and 
line 15138=>still all was quiet and  peaceful. On  the third day out from Bree they came  
line 15139=>out of  the  Chetwood. The  land  had been falling steadily, ever since they 
line 15140=>turned aside from the  Road,  and they  now  entered a wide flat expanse  of 
line 15141=>country, much more difficult to manage. They were  far beyond the borders of 
line 15142=>the Bree-land,  out in the  pathless  wilderness, and  drawing  near  to the 
line 15143=>Midge-water Marshes.  
line 15144=>     The ground now became damp, and in places boggy and here and there they 
line 15145=>came  upon pools, and  wide  stretches of reeds  and rushes filled with  the 
line 15146=>warbling of little hidden  birds. They  had to pick their  way  carefully to 
line 15147=>
line 15148=>####-keep  both  dry-footed and  on  their  proper  course.  At  first  they made 
line 15149=>fan-progress,  but as  they  went on, their passage  became slower  and more 
line 15150=>dangerous.  The marshes were bewildering and  treacherous, and there was  no 
line 15151=>permanent trail even for Rangers  to find through their shifting  quagmires.  
line 15152=>The  flies began  to torment them, and the air was full  of  clouds of  tiny 
line 15153=>midges that crept up their sleeves and breeches and into their hair. 
line 15154=>     'I  am being eaten alive!'  cried  Pippin. 'Midgewater!  There are more 
line 15155=>midges than water!' 
line 15156=>     'What  do  they live  on  when  they  can't  get  hobbit?'  asked  Sam, 
line 15157=>scratching his neck. 
line 15158=>     They spent a miserable day in this lonely and unpleasant country. Their 
line 15159=>camping-place  was  damp, cold,  and uncomfortable;  and the  biting insects 
line 15160=>would not let  them sleep. There were also abominable creatures haunting the 
line 15161=>reeds  and tussocks that from  the sound  of them were evil relatives of the 
line 15162=>cricket.  There  were  thousands  of  them,  and  they  squeaked all  round, 
line 15163=>neek-breek,  breek-neek, unceasingly all the night, until the  hobbits  were 
line 15164=>nearly frantic. 
line 15165=>     The  next day,  the fourth, was little  better, and the night almost as 
line 15166=>comfortless. Though  the Neekerbreekers (as Sam called them)  had been  left  
line 15167=>behind, the midges still pursued them. 
line 15168=>     As Frodo lay, tired but unable to close his eyes, it seemed to him that 
line 15169=>far away  there came  a light in the eastern sky: it  flashed and faded many 
line 15170=>times. It was not the dawn, for that was still some hours off.  
line 15171=>     'What is the  light?'  he said  to  Strider,  who had  risen,  and  was 
line 15172=>standing, gazing ahead into the night. 
line 15173=>     'I do  not know,' Strider answered. 'It is too distant to make  out. It 
line 15174=>is like lightning that leaps up from the hill -tops.' 
line 15175=>     Frodo lay down again, but for a long while he could still see the white 
line 15176=>flashes, and against them the tall dark figure  of Strider,  standing silent 
line 15177=>and watchful. At last he passed into uneasy sleep. 
line 15178=>     They had not  gone  far  on  the  fifth day  when  they  left  the last  
line 15179=>straggling pools and  reed-beds of the marshes  behind them. The land before 
line 15180=>them began steadily  to rise again. Away in the distance eastward they could 
line 15181=>now  see a line of hills. The highest of them was at the  right of  the line 
line 15182=>and  a little  separated from the  others. It  had a  conical top,  slightly 
line 15183=>flattened at the summit. 
line 15184=>     'That  is Weathertop,' said Strider. 'The Old Road,  which we have left  
line 15185=>
line 15186=>####-far  away on our right, runs to the south  of it and passes not far from its 
line 15187=>foot. We  might  reach it by noon tomorrow, if we  go straight towards it. I 
line 15188=>suppose we had better do so.' 
line 15189=>     'What do you mean?' asked Frodo. 
line 15190=>     'I mean: when we do get there, it is not certain what we shall find. It 
line 15191=>is close to the Road.' 
line 15192=>     'But surely we wer e hoping to find Gandalf there?' 
line 15193=>     'Yes; but the hope is faint.  If he comes  this way at  all, he may not 
line 15194=>pass through  Bree, and so  he may not know  what we  are doing. And anyway, 
line 15195=>unless by luck we arrive almost together, we shall miss one another; it will 
line 15196=>not be safe for him or for us to wait there long. If the Riders fail to find 
line 15197=>us in the wilderness,  they are likely to make for Weathertop themselves. It 
line 15198=>commands a wide view all round. Indeed, there  are many birds and  beasts in 
line 15199=>this country that  could see us,  as we stand here, from that hill-top.  Not 
line 15200=>all the  birds are to be trusted,  and there are other spies more  evil than 
line 15201=>they are.' 
line 15202=>     The hobbits looked  anxiously at  the distant hills. Sam looked up into 
line 15203=>the pale sky, fearing to see hawks  or eagles hovering over them with bright  
line 15204=>unfriendly eyes. 'You do make me feel uncomfortable  and lonesome, Strider!' 
