line 15584=>     That in his arms lay glistening. 
line 15585=> 
line 15586=>     As Beren looked into her eyes 
line 15587=>     Within the shadows of her hair, 
line 15588=>     The trembling starlight of the skies 
line 15589=>     He saw there mirrored shimmering. 
line 15590=>     TinÂ®viel the elven-fair, 
line 15591=>     Immortal maiden elven-wise, 
line 15592=>     About him cast her shadowy hair 
line 15593=>     And arms like silver glimmering. 
line 15594=> 
line 15595=>     Long was the way that fate them bore, 
line 15596=>     O'er stony mountains cold and grey, 
line 15597=>     Through halls of iron and darkling door, 
line 15598=>     And woods of nightshade morrowless. 
line 15599=>     The Sundering Seas between them lay, 
line 15600=>     And yet at last they met once more, 
line 15601=>     And long ago they passed away 
line 15602=>     In the forest singing sorrowless. 
line 15603=>
line 15604=>####-     Strider sighed and paused before he spoke again.  'That is a song,'  he 
line 15605=>said, 'in the mode that  is called ann-thennath  among the Elves, but is hard 
line 15606=>to render in our Common Speech, and this is  but a rough echo of it. It tells 
line 15607=>of the meeting of Beren son  of  Barahir and  LÂ®thien TinÂ®viel. Beren was  a 
line 15608=>mortal man,  but LÂ®thien was the daughter of Thingol,  a King  of Elves upon 
line 15609=>Middle-earth when the world was young; and  she was the fairest  maiden that 
line 15610=>has ever been among all  the children of this world. As  the stars above the 
line 15611=>mists  of  the Northern  lands was her loveliness,  and  in her  face  was a  
line 15612=>shining light. In those days  the Great Enemy, of  whom Sauron of Mordor was 
line 15613=>but a servant, dwelt  in Angband  in the North,  and the  Elves of the  West 
line 15614=>coming back to Middle-earth made  war upon him to regain the Silmarils which 
line 15615=>he had  stolen; and  the fathers of Men aided the Elves. But the  Enemy  was 
line 15616=>victorious  and Barahir  was slain,  and Beren escaping through great  peril 
line 15617=>came over the Mountains of Terror into the hidden Kingdom of Thingol in  the 
line 15618=>forest of Neldoreth.  There he beheld LÂ®thien singing and dancing in a glade 
line 15619=>beside the enchanted  river Esgalduin; and  he named  her TinÂ®viel,  that is 
line 15620=>Nightingale in the language of old. Many sorrows befell them afterwards, and 
line 15621=>they  were parted long. TinÂ®viel rescued Beren from  the dungeons of Sauron, 
line 15622=>and together they passed through great dangers, and cast down even the Great 
line 15623=>Enemy  from  his  throne, and took  from  his  iron  crown one of the  three 
line 15624=>Silmarils, brightest of  all jewels, to  be  the  bride-price of LÂ®thien  to 
line 15625=>Thingol her father. Yet  at the last  Beren  was slain by the Wolf that came 
line 15626=>from  the gates  of  Angband, and he died in  the arms of TinÂ®viel.  But she 
line 15627=>chose mortality, and to die from  the world,  so that  she might follow him; 
line 15628=>and it  is sung that they met again beyond the Sundering  Seas, and  after a  
line 15629=>brief time walking alive once more in the green woods, together they passed, 
line 15630=>long ago, beyond the confines of this  world. So it is that LÂ®thien TinÂ®viel 
line 15631=>alone of the Elf-kindred has died indeed and left  the  world, and they have 
line 15632=>lost her  whom they most loved. But from her the lineage of the Elf-lords of 
line 15633=>old descended among  Men.  There live  still those of whom  LÂ®thien  was the 
line 15634=>foremother,  and  it  is  said  that  her line shall  never fail.  Elrond of 
line 15635=>Rivendell is of that Kin. For of  Beren and LÂ®thien  was born Dior Thingol's 
line 15636=>heir;  and of him Elwing  the White whom Edrendil wedded, he that sailed his 
line 15637=>ship out of the mists of the world into the seas of heaven with the Silmaril 
line 15638=>upon  his brow.  And  of  Edrendil  came  the  Kings  of  NÂ®menor,  that  is 
line 15639=>Westernesse.' 
line 15640=>     As Strider was speaking  they watched his strange eager face, dimly lit 
line 15641=>
line 15642=>####-in the red glow of the wood-fire. His eyes shone, and his voice was rich and 
line 15643=>deep. Above him was a black starry  sky. Suddenly a pale light appeared over  
line 15644=>the crown  of Weathertop behind  him. The  waxing  moon  was climbing 
line 15645=>slowly 
line 15646=>above  the  hill that  overshadowed  them, and the  stars above the hill-top 
line 15647=>faded. 
line 15648=>     The  story ended. The hobbits moved and stretched. 'Look!' said  Merry. 
line 15649=>'The Moon is rising: it must be getting late.' 
line 15650=>     The others looked up. Even as they did so, they saw on the  top of  the 
line 15651=>hill something small and dark  against  the  glimmer of the moonrise. It was 
line 15652=>perhaps only a large stone or jutting rock shown up by the pale light. 
line 15653=>     Sam  and Merry  got up and walked away from the fire. Frodo  and Pippin 
line 15654=>remained seated in silence.  Strider was watching the moonlight on  the hill 
line 15655=>intently.  All seemed quiet and still, but Frodo felt  a cold dread creeping 
line 15656=>over his heart,  now that Strider was  no longer speaking. He huddled closer  
line 15657=>to the fire. At that moment Sam came running back from the edge of the dell. 
line 15658=>     'I don't  know what it is,'  he  said, 'but  I suddenly felt afraid.  I 
line 15659=>durstn't  go  outside this dell  for any money;  I felt that  something  was 
line 15660=>creeping up the slope.' 
line 15661=>     'Did you see anything?' asked Frodo, springing to his feet. 
line 15662=>     'No, sir. I saw nothing, but I didn't stop to look.' 
line 15663=>     'I  saw something,' said Merry; 'or  I thought  I did  -  away westwards 
line 15664=>where  the moonlight was  falling  on  the  flats  beyond the  shadow of the 
line 15665=>hill-tops, I thought there were two or three black shapes. They seemed to be 
line 15666=>moving this way.' 
line 15667=>     'Keep close to the  fire, with your faces outward!' cried Strider. 'Get 
line 15668=>some of the longer sticks ready in your hands!' 
line 15669=>     For a breathless  time  they sat there, silent  and  alert, with  their 
line 15670=>backs  turned to the  wood-fire, each gazing into the shadows that encircled 
line 15671=>them. Nothing happened. There was no sound or  movement in the night.  
line 15672=>Frodo 
line 15673=>stirred,  feeling that he must break the silence:  he longed  to  shout  out 
line 15674=>aloud. 
line 15675=>     'Hush!' whispered Strider.  'What's  that?' gasped Pippin at  the  same 
line 15676=>moment. 
line 15677=>     Over the  lip of the little dell, on the side away  from the hill, they 
line 15678=>felt, rather  than saw, a shadow  rise,  one  shadow or  more than one. They 
line 15679=>
line 15680=>####-strained their eyes, and the shadows  seemed to grow. Soon there could be no 
line 15681=>doubt: 
line 15682=>     three or four  tall black  figures  were standing  there  on the slope, 
line 15683=>looking down  on  them. So black were they that they seemed like black holes 
line 15684=>in the deep shade behind them. Frodo  thought that he heard  a faint hiss as 
line 15685=>of venomous breath  and felt a thin  piercing chill. Then the  shapes slowly 
line 15686=>advanced. 
line 15687=>     Terror overcame Pippin and Merry, and they threw themselves flat on the 
line 15688=>ground. Sam shrank to Frodo's side. Frodo was hardly less terrified than his 
line 15689=>companions; he  was quaking  as  if he was bitter cold,  but his  terror was 
line 15690=>swallowed  up in  a sudden temptation  to put on the Ring. The  desire to do  
line 15691=>this laid hold of him, and he could think of nothing else. He did not forget 
line 15692=>the Barrow,  nor  the  message  of  Gandalf;  but  something  seemed  to  be 
line 15693=>compelling  him to disregard  all warnings, and he longed to yield. Not with  
line 15694=>the hope of escape, or of doing anything, either good or bad: he simply felt 
line 15695=>that he must take the Ring and put  it on his finger. He could not speak. He 
line 15696=>felt Sam looking at him, as if  he knew  that  his  master was in some great 
line 15697=>trouble, but  he could not turn  towards him. He shut his eyes and struggled 
line 15698=>for a while; but  resistance became unbearable, and at  last he  slowly drew 
line 15699=>out the chain, and slipped the Ring on the forefinger of his left hand. 
line 15700=>     Immediately, though everything  else remained as before,  dim and dark, 
line 15701=>the shapes became  terribly clear. He was able to  see beneath  their  black  
line 15702=>wrappings. There were  five  tall  figures: two standing on the lip  of  the 
line 15703=>dell, three advancing. In their white faces burned  keen and merciless eyes;  
line 15704=>under their mantles were long grey robes;  upon  their grey hairs were helms 
line 15705=>of silver; in their haggard hands  were  swords of steel. Their eyes fell on 
line 15706=>him and pierced him, as they rushed towards him. Desperate, he  drew his own 
line 15707=>sword, and it seemed to him that it flickered red, as if it was a firebrand. 
line 15708=>Two of the figures  halted. The   third was taller than  the others: his hair 
line 15709=>was long and gleaming and  on his  helm was  a crown.  In one hand he held a  
line 15710=>long sword, and in the other a knife;  both the knife and the hand that held 
line 15711=>it glowed with a pale light. He sprang forward and bore down on Frodo. 
line 15712=>     At that moment Frodo threw himself forward on  the ground, and he heard 
line 15713=>himself crying aloud: O  Elbereth! Gilthoniel! At the same time he struck at 
line 15714=>the feet of his enemy. A shrill  cry rang  out in the night;  and he felt  a  
line 15715=>pain  like  a  dart  of  poisoned ice  pierce his left shoulder. Even  as he 
line 15716=>swooned he caught, as through a swirling mist,  a glimpse of Strider leaping 
line 15717=>
