line 15725=>Chapter 12. Flight to the Ford 
line 15726=>
line 15727=> 
line 15728=> 
line 15729=>     When Frodo came to himself he was still clutching the Ring desperately.  
line 15730=>He was lying by the fire, which was now piled high and burning br ightly. His 
line 15731=>three companions were bending  over  him.  'What has happened? Where is  the 
line 15732=>pale  king?' he  asked wildly. They were too overjoyed to  hear him speak to  
line 15733=>answer  for  a  while; nor did they  understand  his question.  At length he 
line 15734=>gathered from  Sam that they had seen nothing  but the vague shadowy  shapes 
line 15735=>coming towards them.  Suddenly to his  horror Sam found  that his master had 
line 15736=>vanished; and at that moment a black shadow rushed past him, and he fell. He 
line 15737=>heard  Frodo's  voice, but it seemed to  come from a great distance, or from 
line 15738=>under the earth, crying out strange words. They saw nothing more, until they  
line 15739=>stumbled over the body of Frodo, lying as  if  dead,  face downwards  on the 
line 15740=>grass  with his sword  beneath  him. Strider ordered them to pick him up and 
line 15741=>lay  him near the fire, and then he disappeared. That was now  a  good while 
line 15742=>ago. 
line 15743=>     Sam plainly was beginning to have doubts again about Strider; but while  
line 15744=>they were talking he returned, appearing suddenly out  of the  shadows. They 
line 15745=>started, and Sam drew his sword and stood over Frodo; but Strider knelt down 
line 15746=>swiftly at his side. 
line 15747=>     'I  am not a Black  Rider,  Sam,' he said  gently, 'nor in league  with 
line 15748=>them. I  have been  trying to discover  something of  their movements; but I 
line 15749=>have  found nothing. I cannot  think  why  they have gone and do  not attack  
line 15750=>again. But there is no feeling of their presence anywhere at hand.' 
line 15751=>     When he heard what Frodo had  to tell, he became full  of concern,  and 
line 15752=>shook his head  and sighed. Then he ordered Pippin and Merry to heat as much 
line 15753=>water as they could in their small kettles, and to bathe the wound with  it. 
line 15754=>'Keep the fire going well, and keep Frodo warm!' he said. Then he got up and 
line 15755=>walked  away, and called  Sam to him.  'I think I  understand  things better 
line 15756=>now,' he said in  a low voice.  'There  seem only to  have  been five of the 
line 15757=>enemy. Why they were not all here,  I  don't know;  but I  don't  think they 
line 15758=>expected to  be resisted.  They have drawn off for the  time being. But  not 
line 15759=>far,  I fear. They will come again another night, if we cannot escape.  They 
line 15760=>are  only  waiting,  because  they  think  that   their  purpose  is  almost  
line 15761=>accomplished, and that the  Ring  cannot fly much further. I fear, Sam, that 
line 15762=>
line 15763=>####-they believe  your  master has a deadly  wound that will subdue him to their  
line 15764=>will. We  shall see!' Sam choked with tears. 'Don't  despair!' said Strider. 
line 15765=>'You  must trust  me  now. Your  Frodo is made of sterner  stuff  than I had 
line 15766=>guessed, though Gandalf  hinted that it might prove so. He is not slain, and 
line 15767=>I think he will  resist the evil power of the wound longer  than his enemies 
line 15768=>expect. I will do all I can to help and heal him. Guard him well, while I am 
line 15769=>away!' He hurried off and disappeared again into the darkness. 
line 15770=>     Frodo  dozed, though the  pain  of his wound was slowly growing,  and a  
line 15771=>deadly  chill  was spreading  from  his  shoulder to  his arm  and side. His 
line 15772=>friends watched  over him, warming him,  and bathing  his  wound.  The night 
line 15773=>passed  slowly  and wearily.  Dawn was growing in the sky, and the  dell was 
line 15774=>filling with grey light, when Strider at last returned. 
line 15775=>     'Look!' he cried; and stooping he lifted from the  ground a black cloak 
line 15776=>that had lain there hidden by the darkness. A foot above the lower hem there 
line 15777=>was a slash. 'This was  the stroke of Frodo's sword,' he said. 'The only hurt 
line 15778=>that it did to his enemy, I fear; for it is unharmed, but  all blades perish 
line 15779=>that pierce  that  dreadful  King.  More  deadly  to  him  was  the name  of 
line 15780=>Elbereth.' 
line 15781=>     'And  more  deadly to Frodo was this!' He stooped again and lifted up a  
line 15782=>long thin knife. There was a cold gleam in it. As Strider raised it they saw 
line 15783=>that near the end  its edge was notched and  the  point was broken  off. But 
line 15784=>even as he  held it up in the growing light, they gazed in astonishment, for  
line 15785=>the blade seemed to melt, and vanished like a smoke in the air, leaving only  
line 15786=>the hilt in  Strider's hand. 'Alas!' he  cried. 'It was this accursed  knife 
line 15787=>that gave the wound. Few now have the  skill in  healing to match  such evil  
line 15788=>weapons. But I will do what I can.' 
line 15789=>     He sat down on the  ground, and taking  the dagger -hilt laid it  on his 
line 15790=>knees, and he  sang over it a slow song in a strange tongue. Then setting it 
line 15791=>aside, he turned to Frodo  and in  a soft tone  spoke words the others could 
line 15792=>not catch.  From  the pouch at  his  belt he drew  out the  long leaves of a  
line 15793=>plant. 
line 15794=>     'These  leaves,' he said, 'I have  walked far to  find; for  this plant 
line 15795=>does not grow in the bare hills;  but in the thickets away south of the Road 
line 15796=>I found it in the  dark by the scent of its leaves.' He crushed a leaf in his 
line 15797=>fingers,  and it gave out  a  sweet and pungent fragrance. 'It  is fortunate 
line 15798=>that  I could find it, for it is  a healing plant that the  Men of  the West 
line 15799=>brought to Middle-earth. Athelas they  named it,  and it grows  now sparsely 
line 15800=>
line 15801=>####-and only near places where they dwelt or camped of old;  and it is not known 
line 15802=>in the  North, except to some of those who wander in the Wild. It  has great 
line 15803=>virtues, but over such a wound as this its healing powers may be small.' 
line 15804=>     He threw the leaves into boiling water and bathed Frodo's shoulder. The 
line 15805=>fragrance of the steam was refreshing, and those that were unhurt felt their 
line 15806=>minds calmed and cleared. The herb had  also some  power over the wound, for  
line 15807=>Frodo felt the pain   and also the  sense of  frozen cold lessen in his side; 
line 15808=>but the life did not return to his arm, and  he could not  raise or  use his 
line 15809=>hand.  He  bitterly  regretted his  foolishness, and reproached himself  for  
line 15810=>weakness of will; for he now perceived that in putting on the Ring he obeyed 
line 15811=>not his own desire but the commanding wish of his enemies. He wondered if he 
line 15812=>would  remain maimed for  life,  and how they would now  manage to  continue 
line 15813=>their journey. He fell too weak to stand. 
line 15814=>     The others were discussing this very question. They  quickly decided to 
line 15815=>leave Weathertop as soon as possible. 'I think now,' said Strider, 'that the 
line 15816=>enemy has been watching this place for some days. If Gandalf ever came here, 
line 15817=>then he  must have been forced to ride away, and  he will not return. In any 
line 15818=>case we are in great peril here after  dark, since the attack of last night, 
line 15819=>and we can hardly meet greater danger wherever we go.' 
line 15820=>     As  soon  as  the  daylight  was  full, they had some hurried food  and 
line 15821=>packed. It was impossible for Frodo  to  walk, so  they divided the  greater  
line 15822=>part of their baggage among the four of them, and put Frodo  on the pony. In 
line 15823=>the last few days the poor beast had improved wonderfully; it already seemed 
line 15824=>fatter and stronger, and had begun to show an a ffection for its new masters, 
line 15825=>especially for Sam. Bill Ferny's treatment must  have been very hard for the 
line 15826=>journey in the wild to seem so much better than its former life. 
line 15827=>     They started off in a southerly direction. This would mean crossing the 
line 15828=>Road,  but. it was the  quickest way to more wooded country. And they needed 
line 15829=>fuel; for Strider said  that Frodo must be kept warm,  especially at  night, 
line 15830=>while fire would be some protection  for them all. It  was also his  plan to 
line 15831=>shorten their journey by cutting  across another great loop of the Road: east  
line 15832=>beyond Weathertop it changed its course and took a wide bend northwards. 
line 15833=>     They made  their  way slowly  and  cautiously  round the  south-western 
line 15834=>slopes  of the  hill, and came in a  little while to the  edge of the  Road. 
line 15835=>There was no sign of the Riders. But  even as they were hurrying across they 
line 15836=>heard far away two  cries: a cold voice calling and  a cold voice answering. 
line 15837=>Trembling they sprang forward, and made for the thickets that lay ahead. The 
line 15838=>
line 15839=>####-land before them  sloped  away  southwards, but  it was  wild  and pathless; 
line 15840=>bushes and  stunted trees  grew in dense patches with wide barren  spaces in 
line 15841=>between.  The grass was scanty, coarse,  and grey;  and  the leaves  in  the 
line 15842=>thickets were faded and falling. It was  a cheerless land, and their journey 
line 15843=>was slow and gloomy. They spoke  little as they trudged along. Frodo's heart 
line 15844=>was grieved as he watched them walking beside him with their heads down, 
line 15845=>and 
line 15846=>their  backs bowed  under  their  burdens.  Even  Strider  seemed  tired and 
line 15847=>heavy-hearted. 
line 15848=>     Before the first day's march was over Frodo's pain began to grow again, 
line 15849=>but he did not speak of it for  a long time. Four  days passed,  without the 
line 15850=>ground or the scene changing much, except that behind them Weathertop 
line 15851=>slowly 
line 15852=>sank,  and  before  them the distant mountains loomed a  little nearer.  Yet 
line 15853=>since that far cry they had seen and heard no sign that the enemy had marked 
line 15854=>their  flight or followed them.  They dreaded the dark hours, and kept watch 
line 15855=>in pairs by night, expecting at any time to see black shapes stalking in the 
line 15856=>grey night, dimly lit by the cloud-veiled  moon; but they  saw nothing,  and 
line 15857=>heard no sound but the sigh of withered leaves and grass. Not once  did they 
line 15858=>feel the sense of present  evil that  had assailed them before the attack in 
line 15859=>the dell. It seemed too much to hope that the Riders had already  lost their 
line 15860=>trail again. Perhaps  they  were waiting  to  make  some ambush in  a narrow 
line 15861=>place? 
line 15862=>     At the end of  the fifth day the ground began once more  to rise slowly 
line 15863=>out of the wide  shallow valley into which  they had  descended. Strider now  
line 15864=>turned their course again north-eastwards, and on the sixth day they reached 
line 15865=>the top of a long slow-climbing slope, and saw far  ahead a huddle of wooded 
line 15866=>hills. Away below them they could see the Road sweeping round  the  feet  of 
line 15867=>the hills;  and  to  their  right  a  grey river  gleamed  pale in the  thin 
line 15868=>sunshine. In the  distance they glimpsed yet another river in a stony valley 
line 15869=>half-veiled in mist. 
line 15870=>     "I am  afraid we must  go back  to  the Road  here for  a while,'  said 
line 15871=>Strider.  'We have  now  come to  the  River Hoarwell,  that the Elves  call 
line 15872=>Mitheithel. It  flows down out  of the Ettenmoors, the troll-fells  north of 
line 15873=>Rivendell,  and joins  the Loudwater away in the  South.  Some  call  it the 
line 15874=>Greyflood after that. It is a great water before it finds the  Sea. There is 
line 15875=>no way over  it  below  its sources  in the Ettenmoors, except by  the  Last  
line 15876=>
line 15877=>####-Bridge on which the Road crosses.' 
line 15878=>     'What is that other river we can see far away there?' asked Merry. 
line 15879=>     'That is Loudwater,  the Bruinen of Rivendell,'  answered Strider. 'The 
line 15880=>Road runs along the edge of  the hills for many miles from the Bridge to the 
line 15881=>Ford of Bruinen. But I have  not yet thought how  we shall cross that water. 
line 15882=>One river at a time! We shall be fortunate indeed if we do not find the Last  
line 15883=>Bridge held against us.' 
line 15884=>     Next day, early in  the morning, they came down again to the borders of 
line 15885=>the Road.  Sam  and  Strider  went  forward, but they found no  sign of  any 
line 15886=>travellers or riders. Here under the shadow of the hills there had been some 
line 15887=>rain. Strider judged that it had fallen two days before, and had washed away 
line 15888=>all footprints. No horseman had passed since then, as far as he could see. 
line 15889=>     They hurried along with all the speed they could make, and after a mile 
line 15890=>or two they saw the Last Bridge ahead, at the bottom of a short steep slope. 
line 15891=>They dreaded  to see black figures waiting there, but they saw none. Strider 
line 15892=>made them take cover  in a  thicket at  the side of the Road, while  he went 
line 15893=>forward to explore. 
line 15894=>     Before long he came hurrying back. 'I can see no sign of the enemy,' he 
line 15895=>said,  'and I wonder very much what that  means. But  I have found something 
line 15896=>very strange.' 
line 15897=>     He held out his hand, and showed a single pale-green jewel. 'I found it 
line 15898=>in  the  mud in  the  middle of the  Bridge,' he said. 'It  is  a beryl,  an 
line 15899=>elf-stone.  Whether it was set  there, or  let fall by chance, I cannot say; 
line 15900=>but  it brings  hope to  me. I will take it as a sign that we may  pass  the 
line 15901=>Bridge; but beyond that I dare not keep  to  the Road, without some  clearer  
line 15902=>token.' 
line 15903=>     At once they went on again. They crossed  the Bridge in safety, hearing 
line 15904=>no sound  but  the water  swirling  against its three great  arches. A  mile 
line 15905=>further on they came to a narrow ravine that led away northwards through the 
line 15906=>steep  lands  on  the left of the Road.  Here Strider turned aside, and soon 
line 15907=>they were lost in a sombre  country of dark trees winding among the feet  of 
line 15908=>sullen hills. 
line 15909=>     The hobbits were glad  to leave  the  cheerless lands and the  perilous 
line 15910=>Road behind them; but this new country seemed threatening and unfriendly. As 
line 15911=>they went forward the hills about them steadily rose. Here  and  there  upon 
line 15912=>heights  and ridges they caught glimpses of ancient walls  of stone, and the 
line 15913=>ruins of towers: they had an ominous look. Frodo,  who was  not walking, had 
line 15914=>
