line 15916=>and the  threatening towers on  the hills north of  the Road, in the country 
line 15917=>near the Troll's wood where his first serious adventure had  happened. Frodo 
line 15918=>guessed that they were  now in the  same  region, and wondered if by  chance 
line 15919=>they would pass near the spot. 
line 15920=>     'Who lives  in this land?'  he asked.  'And  who built these  towers? Is 
line 15921=>this troll-country?' 
line 15922=>     'No!' said Strider. 'Trolls do  not  build. No one lives in  this land. 
line 15923=>Men once dwelt  here, ages ago;  but  none remain  now. They  became an evil 
line 15924=>people, as legends  tell, for they fell under  the shadow of Angmar. But all 
line 15925=>were destroyed  in the war that  brought the North Kingdom to  its  end. But 
line 15926=>that is now so long ago that the hills  have forgotten them, though a shadow  
line 15927=>still lies on the land.' 
line 15928=>     'Where  did you learn  such  tales,  if  all  the  land  is  empty  and 
line 15929=>forgetful?' asked Peregrin. 'The  birds and beasts do not tell tales of that 
line 15930=>son.' 
line 15931=>     'The  heirs  of Elendil do not forget all  things past,'  said Strider; 
line 15932=>'and  many more things than  I can tell are remembered in  Rivendell.'  'Have  
line 15933=>you often  been to Rivendell?' said  Frodo. 'I have,' said Strider. 'I dwelt 
line 15934=>there once, and still I return when I may. 
line 15935=>     There my heart is;  but  it is not my fate to sit in peace, even in the 
line 15936=>fair house of Elrond.' 
line 15937=>     The hills now began to shut them in. The Road behind held on its way to  
line 15938=>the River Bruinen, but both were  now hidden  from view. The travellers came 
line 15939=>into a long valley; narrow, deeply cloven, dark  and silent.  Trees with old 
line 15940=>and twisted roots hung over cliffs, and piled up behind into mounting slopes 
line 15941=>of pine-wood. 
line 15942=>     The hobbits grew very weary. They advanced slowly, for they had to pick 
line 15943=>their way through a pathless country, encumbered by fallen trees and tumbled 
line 15944=>rocks. As long as they could they avoided  climbing  for  Frodo's  sake, and 
line 15945=>because it was in fact difficult to find any way up out of the narrow dales.  
line 15946=>They had been two days in this country when the weather turned wet. The wind 
line 15947=>began  to blow steadily  out  of  the West and pour the water of the distant 
line 15948=>seas  on the  dark  heads of the hills in fine  drenching rain. By nightfall 
line 15949=>they  were all soaked,  and their camp was cheerless, for they could not get 
line 15950=>any  fire  to burn. The next  day the  hills rose still  higher  and steeper  
line 15951=>before  them, and  they were forced to  turn away  northwards out  of  their 
line 15952=>
line 15953=>####-course. Strider seemed to  be getting anxious: they were nearly ten days out 
line 15954=>from Weathertop, and their stock of  provisions was beginning to run low. It  
line 15955=>went on raining. 
line 15956=>     That night they camped on  a stony shelf with a rock -wall  behind them, 
line 15957=>in which  there was a shallow cave,  a  mere scoop in the  cliff.  Frodo was 
line 15958=>restless. The  cold and wet had  made his wound more painful  than ever, and 
line 15959=>the ache and sense of deadly chill took  away all sleep.  He lay tossing and 
line 15960=>turning and listening fearfully to the stealthy night-noises: wind in chinks 
