line 16268=>journeying  in  your land  beyond the  Baranduin,* learned  that things were 
line 16269=>amiss, and sent  messages as swiftly as they could. They  said that the Nine 
line 16270=>were abroad,  and  that  you  were  astray bearing a  great  burden  without 
line 16271=>guidance, for Gandalf had not returned. There are few even in Rivendell that 
line 16272=>can ride openly  against  the Nine; but such as there were, Elrond  sent out 
line 16273=>north,  west, and south.  It was thought  that you  might  turn far aside to 
line 16274=>avoid pursuit, and become lost in the Wilderness.  
line 16275=>     'It  was  my  lot  to  take the Road,  and  I  came to  the  Bridge  of 
line 16276=>Mitheithel, and  left a  token  there, nigh  on seven days ago. Three of the 
line 16277=>servants of  Sauron were upon the  Bridge, but  they withdrew  and I pursued 
line 16278=>them westward. I came also  upon two others, but they turned away southward. 
line 16279=>Since then I have  searched  for your  trail. Two days  ago I found  it, and 
line 16280=>followed it over the Bridge; and today I marked where you descended from the 
line 16281=>hills again. But come! There is no time for further news. Since you are here 
line 16282=>we must  risk the peril of  the Road and go. There  are five behind us,  and 
line 16283=>when  they find your trail upon the Road  they will   ride after us  like the 
line 16284=>wind.  And they are not all. Where the  other four may be, I  do not know. I 
line 16285=>fear that we may find the Ford is already held against us.' 
line 16286=>     While Glorfindel was speaking  the  shades of evening  deepened.  Frodo 
line 16287=>felt a great weariness come over him. Ever  since the sun began to  sink the 
line 16288=>mist before his eyes had  darkened,  and he  felt  that a  shadow was coming 
line 16289=>between him and the faces of his friends. Now pain assailed him, and he felt  
line 16290=>cold. He swayed, clutching at Sam's arm. 
line 16291=>     'My master  is  sick and  wounded,' said Sam angrily. 'He  can't go  on 
line 16292=>riding after nightfall. He needs rest.' 
line 16293=>     Glorfindel caught Frodo as he sank to the ground, and taking him gently 
line 16294=>
line 16295=>####-in his arms he looked in his face with grave anxiety. 
line 16296=>     Briefly Strider told of the attack  on their camp under Weathertop, and 
line 16297=>of  the deadly knife. He drew out the hilt, which he had kept, and handed it 
line 16298=>to the Elf. Glorfindel shuddered as he  took  it, but he looked  intently at 
line 16299=>it. 
line 16300=>     'There  are evil things written  on  this hilt,' he said; 'though maybe 
line 16301=>your  eyes  cannot see  them.  Keep it, Aragorn,  till we reach the house of 
line 16302=>Elrond! But be wary, and handle it as little as you may! Alas! the wounds of 
line 16303=>this weapon are beyond my skill to heal. I will do what I can -  but all the 
line 16304=>more do I urge you now to go on without rest.' 
line 16305=>     He searched the  wound on Frodo's shoulder with  his  fingers, and  his 
line 16306=>face grew graver, as  if what he learned disquieted  him. But Frodo felt the 
line 16307=>chill lessen in  his  side  and arm;  a little  warmth crept  down from  his 
line 16308=>shoulder to his hand, and the pain grew easier. The  dusk of evening  seemed  
line 16309=>to grow lighter  about him, as if  a cloud  had been  withdrawn.  He saw his  
line 16310=>friends'  faces more clearly  again, and a  measure of new hope and strength 
line 16311=>returned. 
line 16312=>     'You  shall  ride my  horse,'  said  Glorfindel.  'I will  shorten  the 
line 16313=>stirrups  up to the saddle-skins, and  you must sit as tight as you can. But 
line 16314=>you need not fear: my horse  will not let any rider  fall that I command him 
line 16315=>to bear. His pace is light and smooth;  and if  danger presses  too near, he 
line 16316=>will  bear  you away with a  speed that even  the black steeds of  the enemy 
line 16317=>cannot rival.' 
line 16318=>     'No, he will not!' said  Frodo. 'I  shall  not ride him, if I am to  be 
line 16319=>carried off  to  Rivendell  or anywhere else, leaving  my friends behind  in 
line 16320=>danger.' 
line 16321=>     Glorfindel smiled. 'I doubt very much,' he said, 'if your friends would 
line 16322=>be  in danger if you were  not  with them! The pursuit  would follow you and 
line 16323=>leave  us in  peace, I  think. It is you, Frodo, and that which you bear that 
line 16324=>brings us all in peril.' 
line 16325=>     To that Frodo had no answer, and he was persuaded to mount Glorfindel's 
line 16326=>white  horse.  The pony  was laden instead with a great part  of the others' 
line 16327=>burdens, so that they   now marched lighter, and  for a time made good speed; 
line 16328=>but the hobbits  began  to find it hard to keep up  with the swift  tireless 
line 16329=>feet of the Elf.  On he led them, into the  mouth of darkness,  and still on 
line 16330=>under the deep clouded night. There was neither  star nor moon. Not until the  
line 16331=>grey of dawn did he allow them to halt. Pippin, Merry, and Sam were  by that 
line 16332=>
line 16333=>####-time nearly asleep on their stumbling legs; and  even Strider seemed  by the  
line 16334=>sag of his shoulders to be weary. Frodo sat upon the horse in a dark dream. 
line 16335=>     They  cast  themselves  down  in  the  heather  a  few  yards  from the 
line 16336=>road-side,  and  fell asleep immediately. They seemed hardly to  have closed 
line 16337=>their eyes when Glorfindel, who  had set himself to watch  while they slept, 
line 16338=>awoke  them again.  The sun had  now climbed far into the  morning, and  the 
line 16339=>clouds and mists of the night were gone. 
line 16340=>     'Drink  this!'  said  Glorfindel  to  them, pouring for  each in turn a  
line 16341=>little liquor from his silver -studded flask  of leather.  It  was  clear  as 
line 16342=>spring  water and  had no taste, and it did not feel either  cool or warm in 
line 16343=>the mouth; but  strength  and vigour seemed to flow into all their limbs  as 
line 16344=>they  drank  it. Eaten after that draught the stale  bread  and dried  fruit 
line 16345=>(which was now all that they had left) seemed to satisfy their hunger better  
line 16346=>than many a good breakfast in the Shire had done. 
line 16347=>     They had rested rather less than five hours when they  took to the Road 
line 16348=>again. Glorfindel  still  urged them  on, and  only allowed two brief  halts 
line 16349=>during the day's  march. In this way they covered almost twenty miles before 
line 16350=>nightfall, and  came  to  a  point where the Road bent  right  and  ran down 
line 16351=>towards the  bottom of the valley,  now making  straight for the Bruinen. So  
line 16352=>far there had been no sign or sound of pursuit that the hobbits could see or  
line 16353=>hear; but often  Glorfindel would  halt and  listen  for  a moment, if  they 
line 16354=>lagged behind,  and a look of anxiety  clouded  his face. Once or  twice  he 
line 16355=>spoke to Strider in the elf-tongue. 
line 16356=>     But  however  anxious  their  guides might be,  it  was plain  that the 
line 16357=>hobbits could go no further that night. They were stumbling along dizzy with 
line 16358=>weariness, and unable to think of anything but their feet and legs.  Frodo's 
line 16359=>pain had redoubled, and during the day things about him faded to shadows  of 
line 16360=>ghostly grey.  He almost welcomed the coming of  night,  for  then the world 
line 16361=>seemed less pale and empty. 
line 16362=>     The  hobbits  were still  weary,  when  they  set out  again early next 
line 16363=>morning. There were many miles yet to go between them and the Ford, and 
line 16364=>they 
line 16365=>hobbled forward at the best pace they could manage. 
line 16366=>     'Our  peril  will  be  greatest just  ere  we  reach the  river,'  said 
line 16367=>Glorfindel; 'for my heart warns me that the pursuit is now swift behind  us,  
line 16368=>and other danger may be waiting by the Ford.' 
line 16369=>     The  Road  was still running steadily downhill,  and there  was now  in 
line 16370=>
line 16371=>####-places much  grass  at either side, in which  the  hobbits walked when  they 
line 16372=>could, to ease  their tired feet. In the late afternoon they came to a  place 
line 16373=>where the  Road went  suddenly under the dark shadow of tall pine-trees, and 
line 16374=>then plunged into a deep cutting with steep moist walls of red stone. Echoes 
line 16375=>ran  along as they hurried  forward; and there seemed to  be a sound of many  
line 16376=>footfalls following their own.  All at once, as if through a  gate of light, 
line 16377=>the Road ran  out again from the end of the tunnel into  the open.  There at 
line 16378=>the bottom  of a sharp incline  they saw before  them a long  flat mile, and 
line 16379=>beyond that  the  Ford of Rivendell. On  the  further side was a steep brown 
line 16380=>bank,  threaded  by  a  winding  path;  and behind  that the tall  mountains 
line 16381=>climbed, shoulder above shoulder, and peak beyond peak, into the fading sky. 
line 16382=>     There was still an  echo as  of following feet  in  the cutting   behind 
line 16383=>them;  a  rushing noise as  if  a wind were  rising and pouring  through the 
line 16384=>branches of the  pines. One moment Glorfindel turned  and  listened, then he 
line 16385=>sprang forward with a loud cry. 
line 16386=>     'Fly!' he called. 'Fly! The enemy is upon us!' 
line 16387=>     The white  horse  leaped  forward.  The  hobbits ran  down  the  slope. 
line 16388=>Glorfindel and  Strider followed  as  rear -guard.  They were only  half  way 
line 16389=>across the flat, when suddenly there was a noise of horses galloping. Out of 
line 16390=>the gate in the  trees that they had just left rode a Black Rider. He reined 
line 16391=>his horse  in, and halted,  swaying in his saddle. Another followed him, and 
line 16392=>then another; then again two more. 
line 16393=>     'Ride forward! Ride!' cried Glorfindel to Frodo. 
line 16394=>     He did not obey at  once, for a strange reluctance seized him. Checking 
line 16395=>the horse to  a  walk,  he turned and looked  back. The Riders seemed to sit 
line 16396=>upon  their  great steeds  like  threatening  statues  upon a hill, dark and 
line 16397=>solid, while all the woods and land about them  receded as  if into a  mist. 
line 16398=>Suddenly he knew  in  his heart that they were  silently commanding  him  to 
line 16399=>wait. Then at  once  fear  and hatred awoke in him. His hand left the bridle 
line 16400=>and gripped the hilt of his sword, and with a red flash he drew it. 
line 16401=>     'Ride on! Ride on!' cried Glorfindel, and then loud and clear he called 
line 16402=>to the horse in the elf-tongue: noro lim, noro lim, Asfaloth! 
line 16403=>     At once the  white horse sprang away  and  sped like the wind along the 
line 16404=>last lap of  the Road. At the same moment the  black horses leaped  down the 
line 16405=>hill in pursuit, and from  the Riders came a terrible cry, such as Frodo had 
line 16406=>heard filling  the woods with  horror in the Eastfarthing  far away.  It was 
line 16407=>answered; and to the dismay of Frodo and his friends  out from the trees and 
line 16408=>
