line 16410=>Frodo: two  galloped madly towards  the Ford  to  cut  off  his escape. They 
line 16411=>seemed to him to run like the wind and to grow swiftly larger and darker, as 
line 16412=>their courses converged with his.  
line 16413=>     Frodo looked  back for  a moment over  his shoulder. He could no longer  
line 16414=>see  his friends. The Riders  behind  were  falling  back:  even their great 
line 16415=>steeds  were no match  in  speed for the  white elf-horse of  Glorfindel. He 
line 16416=>looked forward again, and hope fa ded. There seemed no chance of reaching the 
line 16417=>Ford before he  was cut off by  the others that had lain in ambush. He could 
line 16418=>see them clearly now: they appeared to have cast aside their hoods and black  
line 16419=>cloaks, and they were robed in  white and  grey. Swords were  naked in their  
line 16420=>pale hands; helms were on their heads. Their cold eyes  glittered,  and they 
line 16421=>called to him with fell voices.  
line 16422=>     Fear now filled all Frodo's mind. He thought no longer of his sword. No 
line 16423=>cry came from him. He shut his eyes  and clung to the horse's mane. The wind 
line 16424=>whistled in his ears, and the bells upon the harness rang wild and shrill. A 
line 16425=>breath of deadly cold pierced him like a spear, as with a last spurt, like a  
line 16426=>flash of  white fire, the  elf-horse  speeding as  if on wings, passed right 
line 16427=>before the face of the foremost Rider. 
line 16428=>     Frodo heard  the splash of water. It foamed about his feet. He felt the 
line 16429=>quick heave and surge as the horse left the river and struggled up the stony 
line 16430=>path. He was climbing the steep bank. He was across the Ford. 
line 16431=>     But the pursuers were close behind. At  the  top of  the bank the horse 
line 16432=>halted and turned  about neighing  fiercely. There were  Nine  Riders at the 
line 16433=>water's edge below, and Frodo's spirit quailed before  the  threat  of their 
line 16434=>uplifted faces. He knew of nothing that would  prevent them from crossing as 
line 16435=>easily as he had done; and he felt that it was useless to try to escape over  
line 16436=>the long uncertain path from the Ford to the edge  of Rivendell, if once the 
line 16437=>Riders crossed. In any case he felt that  he was commanded urgently to halt.  
line 16438=>Hatred again stirred in him, but he had no longer the strength to refuse. 
line 16439=>     Suddenly the foremost  Rider  spurred  his horse forward. It checked at 
line 16440=>the water and  reared  up.  With  a  great  effort  Frodo  sat  upright  and 
line 16441=>brandished his sword. 
line 16442=>     'Go back!' he cried. 'Go  back to  the Land of Mordor, and follow me no 
line 16443=>more! '  His voice sounded  thin and shrill  in his  own  ears.  The  Riders 
line 16444=>halted, but Frodo had not  the power of Bombadil. His enemies laughed at him 
line 16445=>with  a harsh and chilling laughter. 'Come back! Come back!' they called. 'To 
line 16446=>
line 16447=>####-Mordor we will take you!' 
line 16448=>     'Go back!' he whispered. 
line 16449=>     'The Ring! The  Ring!'  they cried with  deadly voices; and immediately 
line 16450=>their leader urged his horse forward into the water, followed closely by two 
line 16451=>others. 
line 16452=>     'By Elbereth  and LÂ®thien  the Fair,' said Frodo  with  a last  effort, 
line 16453=>lifting up his sword, 'you shall have neither the Ring nor me!' 
line 16454=>     Then the leader, who was now half across the Ford, stood up menacing in 
line 16455=>his  stirrups, and raised up his hand.  Frodo was stricken dumb. He felt his 
line 16456=>tongue  cleave to  his mouth,  and  his heart labouring. His sword broke and  
line 16457=>fell out of his shaking hand. The elf-horse reared and snorted. The foremost  
line 16458=>of the black horses had almost set foot upon the shore. 
line 16459=>     At that moment there  came a roaring and  a rushing: a  noise  of  loud 
line 16460=>waters rolling many stones. Dimly  Frodo saw the river below him  rise,  and 
line 16461=>down along its course there  came a  plumed cavalry of  waves.  White flames 
line 16462=>seemed to Frodo to  flicker on their crests  and he half fancied that he saw 
line 16463=>amid the water white riders upon white horses with frothing manes. The three 
line 16464=>Riders  that  were still in  the midst of  the  Ford were  overwhelmed: they 
line 16465=>disappeared, buried su ddenly under angry  foam.  Those that were behind drew 
line 16466=>back in dismay. 
line 16467=>     With his  last failing senses Frodo  heard cries,  and it seemed to him 
line 16468=>that he saw, beyond the Riders that hesitated on the shore, a shining figure 
line 16469=>of white light;  and behind it ran small shadowy forms  waving flames,  that 
line 16470=>flared red in the grey mist that was falling over the world. 
line 16471=>     The  black  horses were  filled  with madness, and leaping  forward  in 
line 16472=>terror  they bore their riders  into the rushing flood. Their piercing cries 
line 16473=>were drowned in the roaring of the river as it carried them away. Then Frodo 
line 16474=>felt himself  falling,  and  the  roaring and  confusion seemed  to rise and 
line 16475=>engulf him together with his enemies. He heard and saw no more. 
