line 16486=> 
line 16487=>     Frodo woke and found himself lying in bed. At first he thought that  he 
line 16488=>had slept late, after a long unpleasant dream that still hovered on the edge 
line 16489=>of memory. Or  perhaps he  had been ill? But  the ceiling looked strange; it 
line 16490=>was flat, and it had dark beams richly carved. He lay  a little while longer  
line 16491=>looking at patches of sunlight on the wall, and listening to the  sound of a  
line 16492=>waterfall. 
line 16493=>     `Where am  I, and what is the time?' he said aloud to the  ceiling. 'In 
line 16494=>the  House of Elrond, and it is ten o'clock in  the morning.' said  a voice. 
line 16495=>`It is the morning of October the twenty -fourth, if you want to know.' 
line 16496=>     `Gandalf!'  cried  Frodo, sitting up. There was the old wizard, sitting 
line 16497=>in a chair by the open window.  
line 16498=>     `Yes,' he said, `I am here.  And you  are lucky  to be here, too, after  
line 16499=>all the absurd  things you  have done since  you left home.' Frodo lay  down 
line 16500=>again. He felt too comfortable and peaceful to argue, and in any case he did 
line 16501=>not think he would get the better of  an argument.  He  was fully awake now,  
line 16502=>and  the memory of  his  journey  was returning: the  disastrous `short cut' 
line 16503=>through the Old Forest the `accident' at The Prancing Pony;  and his madness 
line 16504=>in putting  on the Ring  in the dell under Weathertop. While he was thinking 
line 16505=>of all these  things and trying  in  vain to  bring  his memory down to  his 
line 16506=>arriving  in  Rivendell, there  was a long  silence, broken only by the soft  
line 16507=>puffs of Gandalf's pipe, as he blew white smoke-rings out of the window.  
line 16508=>     'Where's Sam?' Frodo asked at length. 'And are the others all right?' 
line 16509=>     'Yes, they are  all  safe  and sound,' answered Gandalf.  `Sam was here 
line 16510=>until I sent him off to get some rest, about half an hour ago.' 
line 16511=>     `What happened at the Ford?' said Frodo. `It all seemed so dim somehow; 
line 16512=>and it still does.' 
line 16513=>     'Yes,  it  would.  You were beginning to fade,' answered  Gandalf. 'The 
line 16514=>wound was overcoming you at last. A few more hours and you  would have  
line 16515=>been 
line 16516=>beyond  our aid.  But you have some strength in you, my dear  hobbit! As you 
line 16517=>showed in the  Barrow. That was touch and  go: perhaps  the  most  dangerous 
line 16518=>
line 16519=>####-moment of all. I wish you could have held out at Weathertop.' 
line 16520=>     'You seem to know a great deal already,' said Frodo. `I have not spoken 
line 16521=>to the others about the Barrow. At first it was too horrible; and afterwards 
line 16522=>there were other things to think about. How do you know about it?' 
line 16523=>     'You have talked long  in your sleep, Frodo,' said Gandalf gently, 'and 
line 16524=>it  has not been hard  for me to  read  your mind and memory. Do not  worry! 
line 16525=>Though I said  "absurd" just now, I did not mean it. I think well of you-and 
line 16526=>of the others. It is  no small  feat to have come so far,  and  through such 
line 16527=>dangers, still bearing the Ring.' 
line 16528=>     'We should  never  have done it  without Strider,' said Frodo. `But  we 
line 16529=>needed you. I did not know what to do without you.' 
line 16530=>     'I was delayed,'  said Gandalf, `and that  nearly proved our  ruin. And 
line 16531=>yet I am not sure; it may have been better so.' 
line 16532=>     'I wish you would tell me what happened!' 
line 16533=>     'All in good time! You are not supposed to talk or worry about anything 
line 16534=>today, by Elrond's orders.' 
line 16535=>     `But  talking would stop me thinking and wondering,  which are quite as 
line 16536=>tiring,' said Frodo.  'I am wide awake  now, and  I remember so many  things 
line 16537=>that want explaining. Why  were you delayed?  You  ought to tell me that  at 
line 16538=>least.' 
line 16539=>     'You will soon hear all you wish to know,' said Gandalf. 'We shall have 
line 16540=>a Council, as soon as you are  well enough. At the  moment  I will only  say 
line 16541=>that I was held captive.' 
line 16542=>     'You?' cried Frodo. 
line 16543=>     'Yes, I, Gandalf the Grey,'  said the wizard solemnly.  'There are many 
line 16544=>powers  in  the world,  for good  or for evil. Some are  greater  than I am. 
line 16545=>Against  some  I  have not  yet been measured. But my  time  is  coming. The 
line 16546=>Morgul-lord and his Black Riders have come forth. War is preparing!' 
line 16547=>     `Then you knew of the Riders already -before I met them?' 
line 16548=>     'Yes, I knew of them. Indeed I spoke of them once to you; for the Black  
line 16549=>Riders are the Ringwraiths, the Nine Servants of the Lord of the Rings.  But 
line 16550=>I did not know  that they had arisen again or I should have fled with you at 
line 16551=>once. I heard news  of them only after  I left you in  June; but that  story 
line 16552=>must wait. For the moment we have been saved from disaster, by Aragorn.' 
line 16553=>     'Yes,'  said Frodo, `it was Strider that saved  us. Yet I was afraid of 
line 16554=>him at first. Sam never quite trusted him. I think, not at any rate until we 
line 16555=>met Glorfindel.' 
line 16556=>
line 16557=>####-     Gandalf smiled. `I have heard all about  Sam,' he said. 'He has no more 
line 16558=>doubts now.' 
line 16559=>     'I am glad,' said Frodo. 'For I have become very fond of Strider. Well, 
line 16560=>fond is not the right word.  I mean he is dear to me; though he  is strange, 
line 16561=>and grim  at times. In fact, he reminds  me often of you. I didn't know that 
line 16562=>any of the Big People were  like that.  I thought, well, that  they were just 
line 16563=>big, and rather stupid: kind and stupid like Butterbur; or stupid and wicked 
line 16564=>like  Bill Ferny. But then we don't know much about Men in the Shire, except 
line 16565=>perhaps the Breelanders.' 
line 16566=>     `You  don't know  much  even  about them, if you  think old Barliman is 
line 16567=>stupid,' said Gandalf. 'He is wise enough on his  own ground. He thinks less 
line 16568=>than  he talks, and slower; yet he can see through a brick wall  in time (as 
line 16569=>they say in Bree). But there are few left in  Middle-earth  like Aragorn son 
line 16570=>of Arathorn. The race of the Kings from over the Sea is nearly at an end. It 
line 16571=>may be that this War of the Ring will be their last adventure.' 
line 16572=>     'Do  you  really  mean that  Strider is one  of the people of  the  old 
line 16573=>Kings?' said Frodo in wonder.  `I thought  they had all vanished long ago. I 
line 16574=>thought he was only a Ranger.' 
line 16575=>     'Only a Ranger!' cried Gandalf. `My dear Frodo,  that  is just what the 
line 16576=>Rangers are: the last  remnant in the North  of the great people, the Men of 
line 16577=>the  West.  They have helped  me  before; and I shall need their help in the 
line 16578=>days  to come;  for we  have reached Rivendell, but the Ring is  not yet  at 
line 16579=>rest.' 
line 16580=>     'I suppose not,' said Frodo. 'But  so far my  only thought has been  to 
line 16581=>get here; and  I  hope I  shan't have to go any further. It is very pleasant 
line 16582=>just to rest. I have had a month of exile and adventure, and I find that has 
line 16583=>been as much as I want.' 
line 16584=>     He fell silent and shut his eyes. After a while he spoke again. 'I have 
line 16585=>been reckoning,' he said, `and I can't bring  the  total up  to October  the 
line 16586=>twenty-fourth. It ought to  be  the  twenty-first. We  must have reached the 
line 16587=>Ford by the twentieth.' 
line 16588=>     'You have talked and reckoned more than is good for you,' said Gandalf.  
line 16589=>`How do the side and shou lder feel now?' 
line 16590=>     'I don't know.' Frodo  answered. 'They don't feel at all: which  is  an 
line 16591=>improvement, but'--he made  an  effort--'I can move my  arm again a  little. 
line 16592=>Yes, it is coming back to life. It is not cold,' he added, touching his left  
line 16593=>hand with  his right. 
line 16594=>
line 16595=>####-     `Good!'  said  Gandalf.  `It is  mending  fast. You will soon be  sound 
line 16596=>again. Elrond has cured you: he has tended you for days, ever since you were 
line 16597=>brought in.' 
line 16598=>     'Days?' said Frodo. 
line 16599=>     `Well, four nights and three days,  to be  exact. The Elves brought you  
line 16600=>from this where you lost  count.  We have been terribly anxious, and Sam has 
line 16601=>hardly left  your  side, day or night, except to run  messages. Elrond is  a  
line 16602=>master of healing, but the weapons of  our Enemy are deadly. To tell you the 
line 16603=>truth, I had very little hope; for  I suspected that there was some fragment 
line 16604=>of the blade still in the closed wound. But it could not be found until last  
line 16605=>night.  Then Elrond  removed a  splinter. It  was deeply  buried. and it was 
line 16606=>working inwards.' 
line 16607=>     Frodo shuddered, remembering the cruel knife  with notched  blade  that 
line 16608=>had vanished in Strider's  hands. `Don't be alarmed!' said Gandalf.  `It  is 
line 16609=>gone  now.  It  has  been  melted.  And  it  seems  that  Hobbits fade  very 
line 16610=>reluctantly.  I  have known strong  warriors of  the Big  People  who  would 
line 16611=>quickly have  been overcome by  that splinter, which you bore  for seventeen 
