line 16942=>     Gluin looked at Frodo and smiled. 'You were very fond of Bilbo were you 
line 16943=>not?' he asked. 
line 16944=>     `Yes,' answered Frodo. 'I would rather see him than all  the towers and 
line 16945=>palaces in the world.' 
line 16946=>     At length the feast came to an end. Elrond and Arwen rose and went down 
line 16947=>the hall, and the company followed them in due  order. The doors were thrown 
line 16948=>open, and they went across a  wide passage and through other doors, and came 
line 16949=>into a further hall.  In it were no tables, but a bright fire was burning in 
line 16950=>a great hearth between the carven pillars upon either side. 
line 16951=>     Frodo found himself  walking with  Gandalf. `This  is the Hall of Fire' 
line 16952=>said the wizard.  `Here you will hear many songs and  tales-if you  can keep 
line 16953=>awake. But except on high days it usually stands empty and quiet, and people 
line 16954=>come here who wish for peace,  and thought. There is always a fire here, all  
line 16955=>the year round, but there is little other light.' 
line 16956=>     As Elrond entered and  went towards  the seat prepared for  him, elvish 
