line 18671=> 
line 18672=>     Later that day the hobbits held a meeting of their own in Bilbo's room. 
line 18673=>Merry  and Pippin were indignant when they heard that Sam had crept into the 
line 18674=>Council, and had been chosen as Frodo's companion. 
line 18675=>     `It's most  unfair,' said  Pippin. `Instea d of  throwing  him out,  and 
line 18676=>clapping him in chains, Elrond goes and rewards him for his cheek!' 
line 18677=>     `Rewards!'  said Frodo.  'I can't imagine a more severe punishment. You  
line 18678=>are not  thinking what  you  are saying:  condemned  to  go on this hopeless 
line 18679=>journey, a  reward? Yesterday I dreamed that my  task  was done, and I could 
line 18680=>rest here, a long while, perhaps for good.' 
line 18681=>     'I don't wonder,' said Merry, 'and I wish you could. But we are envying 
line 18682=>Sam, not you. If you have to go, then it will be  a punishment for any of us 
line 18683=>to  be left behind, even in Rivendell. We have  come a long way with you and 
line 18684=>been through some stiff times. We want to go on.' 
line 18685=>     `That's  what  I  meant,'  said  Pippin. `We  hobbits  ought  to  stick  
line 18686=>together, and  we will. I shall go,  unless they chain me up.  There must be 
line 18687=>someone with intelligence in the party.' 
line 18688=>     'Then  you certainly will not  be chosen, Peregrin Took!' said Gandalf, 
line 18689=>looking in through  the window, which was  near the ground. `But you are all 
line 18690=>worrying yourselves unnecessarily. Nothing is decided yet.' 
line 18691=>     `Nothing  decided!' cried Pippin. 'Then what  were  you  all doing? You  
line 18692=>were shut up for hours.' 
line 18693=>     "Talking,' said Bilbo. `There was a deal  of  talk, and everyone had an 
line 18694=>eye-opener. Even old Gandalf.  I think  Legolas's  bit  of news  about Gollum 
line 18695=>caught even him on the hop, though he passed it off.' 
line 18696=>     `You were wrong,'  said Gandalf. 'You  were  inattentive. I had already 
line 18697=>heard of it from Gwaihir. If you want to know, the only real eye-openers, as 
line 18698=>you put  it,  were you  and Frodo;  and  I was  the  only  one  that was not 
line 18699=>surprised.' 
line 18700=>     `Well,  anyway,'  said Bilbo, 'nothing was decided beyond choosing poor  
line 18701=>Frodo  and Sam. I was  afraid all  the time that it might come to that, if I 
line 18702=>was let off. But if you ask me, Elrond will send out a fair number, when the 
line 18703=>reports come in. Have they started yet, Gandalf?' 
line 18704=>     'Yes,' said the wizard. `Some of the scouts have been sent out already. 
line 18705=>
line 18706=>####-More will go  tomorrow.  Elrond is sending Elves, and they will get in touch 
line 18707=>with the Rangers, and maybe  with  Thranduil's folk in Mirkwood. And 
line 18708=>Aragorn 
line 18709=>has gone with Elrond's  sons. We shall have to scour the lands all round for  
line 18710=>many long  leagues before any  move is  made. So cheer  up, Frodo! You  will 
line 18711=>probably make quite a long stay here.' 
line 18712=>     'Ah!' said  Sam gloomily.  'We'll  just wait long enough for  winter to 
line 18713=>come.' 
line 18714=>     'That can't be  helped,' said Bilbo.  'It's your fault partly, Frodo my 
line 18715=>lad: insisting on waiting  for my  birthday. A  funny way of honouring it, I 
line 18716=>can't help thinking. Not the day I should have chosen for letting the S.-B .s 
line 18717=>into Bag End. But there it is: you can't wait now fill spring; and you can't  
line 18718=>go till the reports come back. 
line 18719=>     When winter first begins to bite  
line 18720=>     and stones crack in the frosty night, 
line 18721=>     when pools are black and trees are bare, 
line 18722=>     'tis evil in the Wild to fare. 
line 18723=>     But that I am afraid will be just your luck.' 
line 18724=>     'I am  afraid  it  will,' said Gandalf. 'We  can't start until  we have 
line 18725=>found out about the Riders.' 
line 18726=>     `I thought they were all destroyed in the flood,' said Merry. 
line 18727=>     'You cannot destroy Ringwraiths like that,' said Gandalf. `The power of 
line 18728=>their master  is in them, and  they stand or fall by  him. We hope that they 
line 18729=>were all unhorsed and unmasked, and so made  for a while less dangerous;  but 
line 18730=>we must find out for certain. In the meantime you should try and forget your  
line 18731=>troubles, Frodo. I do not know if I can do anything to  help you; but I will 
line 18732=>whisper this in your ears. Someone said that intelligence would be needed in  
