line 18739=>     `How long  do you  think I  shall have here?' said  Frodo to Bilbo when 
line 18740=>Gandalf had gone. 
line 18741=>     `Oh,  I don't know. I can't count  days in Rivendell,' said Bilbo. 'But 
line 18742=>quite long, I should think. We can have many a good talk. What about helping 
line 18743=>
line 18744=>####-me with my book, and making a  start  on the next?  Have you  thought of  an 
line 18745=>ending?' 
line 18746=>     'Yes, several, a nd all are dark and unpleasant,' said Frodo. 
line 18747=>     'Oh, that won't do!' said Bilbo. `Books ought to have good endings. How 
line 18748=>would this do:  and they all  settled  down and  lived together happily ever 
line 18749=>after?' 
line 18750=>     `It will do well, if it ever comes to that,' said Frodo. 
line 18751=>     'Ah!' said Sam. 'And where will they live? That's what I often wonder.' 
line 18752=>     For a while the hobbits continued to talk and think of the past journey 
line 18753=>and of the perils  that  lay ahead; but such  was the  virtue of the land of 
line 18754=>Rivendell that soon all  fear  and anxiety was lifted  from their minds. The 
line 18755=>future, good or  ill, was not forgotten, but ceased to have  any  power over  
line 18756=>the present. Health and hope grew strong in them, and they were content with 
line 18757=>each good day as it came, taking plea sure in every  meal,  and in every word 
line 18758=>and song. 
line 18759=>     So the days slipped away, as  each morning dawned  bright and fair, and 
line 18760=>each evening followed cool and clear. But autumn was waning fast; slowly the 
line 18761=>golden light  faded to pale silver, and the  lingering leaves fell  from the 
line 18762=>naked trees. A wind began to  blow  chill  from  the  Misty Mountains to the 
line 18763=>east. The Hunter's Moon waxed round in the  night sky, and put to flight all 
line 18764=>the  lesser stars. But low  in the South one star shone red. Every night, as 
line 18765=>the  Moon  waned  again,  it shone brighter and brighter. Frodo could see it 
line 18766=>from his window, deep in the heavens burning like a watchful eye that glared 
line 18767=>above the trees on the brink of the valley. 
line 18768=>     The hobbits had been nearly  two  months  in the House  of  Elrond, and 
line 18769=>November  had  gone by  with the  last  shreds  of autumn, and  December was 
line 18770=>passing, when the scouts  began to  return. Some  had  gone north beyond the 
line 18771=>springs of the Hoarwell into the Ettenmoors;  and others had gone west,  and  
line 18772=>with the help of Aragorn and the Rangers had searched the lands far down the 
line 18773=>Greyflood, as far as Tharbad, where the old North Road crossed  the river by 
