line 18927=>     'Don't try!' said the old hobbit, turning round and slapping him on the 
line 18928=>back.  `Ow!' he cried. `You are  too  hard  now  to slap! But there you are: 
line 18929=>Hobbits must stick together, and especially  Bagginses. All I  ask in return 
line 18930=>is: take  as much care of yourself as you can. and  bring  back all the news 
line 18931=>you can, and  any old  songs and  tales you can come by. I'll do  my best to 
line 18932=>finish my book before you return. I should like to write the second book, if 
line 18933=>
line 18934=>####-I am spared.' He broke off and turned to the window again, singing softly. 
line 18935=> 
line 18936=>     I sit beside the fire and think 
line 18937=>     of all that I have seen, 
line 18938=>     of meadow-flowers and butterflies 
line 18939=>     in summers that have been; 
line 18940=> 
line 18941=>     Of yellow leaves and gossamer 
line 18942=>     in autumns that there were, 
line 18943=>     with morning mist and silver sun 
line 18944=>     and wind upon my hair. 
line 18945=> 
line 18946=>     I sit beside the fire and think 
line 18947=>     of how the world will be 
line 18948=>     when winter comes without a spring 
line 18949=>     that I shall ever see. 
line 18950=> 
line 18951=>     For still  there are so many things 
line 18952=>     that I have never seen: 
line 18953=>     in every wood in every spring 
line 18954=>     there is a different green. 
line 18955=> 
line 18956=>     I sit beside the fire and think 
line 18957=>     of people long ago, 
line 18958=>     and people who will see a world  
line 18959=>     that I shall never know.  
line 18960=> 
line 18961=>     But all the while I sit and think 
line 18962=>     of times there were before, 
line 18963=>     I listen for returning feet 
line 18964=>     and voices at the door. 
line 18965=> 
line 18966=>     It was  a  cold grey  day near the end of  December.  The East Wind was 
line 18967=>streaming through  the  bare branches of the trees, and seething in the dark 
line 18968=>pines on the hills. Ragged clouds  were hurrying overhead,  dark and low. As 
line 18969=>the cheerless shadows  of the early evening began  to  fall the Company made 
line 18970=>ready to set out. They were to start at dusk, for Elrond  counselled them to 
line 18971=>
line 18972=>####-journey  under cover  of night as often as  they could,  until they were far 
line 18973=>from Rivendell. 
line 18974=>     `You should fear the many eyes  of the servants of Sauron,' he said. 'I  
line 18975=>do not doubt that news of the discomfiture of the Riders has already reached 
line 18976=>him,  and he will be filled with wrath. Soon now his spies on foot  and  wing  
line 18977=>will be abroad in the northern lands. Even of the  sky above you must beware 
line 18978=>as you go on your way.' 
line 18979=>     The Company took little gear of war,  for their hope was in secrecy not 
line 18980=>in battle. Aragorn had AndÂ®ril  but no other weapon, and he went  forth clad 
line 18981=>only in rusty green and brown. as a  Ranger of the wilderness. Boromir had a 
line 18982=>long sword,  in fashion like AndÂ®ril but of less  lineage and he bore also a  
line 18983=>shield and his war-horn. 
line 18984=>     'Loud and  clear it sounds  in the valleys of the hills,' he said, `and 
line 18985=>then  let all the foes  of Gondor  flee!' Putting  it to  his lips he blew a  
line 18986=>blast, and the echoes leapt from rock to rock, and all that heard that voice 
line 18987=>in Rivendell sprang to their feet. 
line 18988=>     Slow  should you  be to  wind  that  horn again,  Boromir, said Elrond. 
line 18989=>'until you stand once more on the  borders of your land, and dire need is on 
line 18990=>you.' 
line 18991=>     `Maybe,' said Boromir.  'But always I have let my  horn cry  at setting 
line 18992=>forth, and though thereafter we may walk in the shadows, I will not go forth 
line 18993=>as a thief in the night.' 
line 18994=>     Gimli the  dwarf alone wore  openly  a short shirt of steel-rings,  for  
line 18995=>dwarves make  light  of burdens;  and in  his  belt was a  broad-bladed axe. 
line 18996=>Legolas had  a bow and a  quiver,  and  at his belt a long  white knife. The 
line 18997=>younger  hobbits wore the swords that they had  taken  from the  barrow; but 
line 18998=>Frodo took only Sting;  and his mail-coat, as Bilbo wished, remained hidden. 
line 18999=>Gandalf bore his staff, but girt at his side was  the elven-sword Glamdring, 
line 19000=>the mate of Orcrist that lay now upon  the breast of Thorin under the Lonely 
line 19001=>Mountain. 
line 19002=>     All were well furnished by Elrond with thick warm clothes, and they had 
line 19003=>jackets and cloaks lined with  fur. Spare food and clothes  and blankets and 
line 19004=>other needs were laden on a  pony, none other  than the poor beast that they 
line 19005=>had brought from Bree. 
line 19006=>     ?he stay  in Rivendell had  worked a  great wonder of change on him: he 
line 19007=>was  glossy and seemed  to  have  the vigour of youth.  It  was  Sam who had 
line 19008=>insisted on choosing him, declaring that Bill (as he called him) would pine, 
line 19009=>
line 19010=>####-if he did not come. 
line 19011=>     `That  animal can nearly talk,' he said, `and  would talk, if he stayed 
line 19012=>here  much longer. He gave me a  look as plain as Mr. Pippin could speak it: 
line 19013=>if you don't  let me go  with you, Sam, I'll follow  on my own.' So Bill was 
line 19014=>going as the beast of burden, yet he was the only member of the Company that 
line 19015=>did not seem depressed. 
line 19016=>     Their  farewells had been  said in the great hall by the  fire, and they 
line 19017=>were only waiting now for  Gandalf, who had not yet come out of the house. A 
line 19018=>gleam of firelight came from the open doors, and soft lights were glowing in 
line 19019=>many windows. Bilbo  huddled in a cloak stood silent  on the doorstep beside 
line 19020=>Frodo.  Aragorn sat with his head bowed to his knees; only Elrond knew fully 
line 19021=>what this hour meant to him. The others could be seen as grey  shapes in the 
line 19022=>darkness.  
line 19023=>     Sam was  standing by the  pony, sucking  his teeth, and staring moodily 
line 19024=>into  the  gloom  where  the  river  roared  stonily below;  his  desire for  
line 19025=>adventure was at its lowest ebb. 
line 19026=>     `Bill,  my lad,' he said,  `you oughtn't to have took up  with us.  You  
line 19027=>could have stayed here and et the best hay  till the  new grass comes.' Bill 
line 19028=>swished his tail and said nothing. 
line 19029=>     Sam  eased the pack on  his shoulders, and  went over anxiously  in his 
line 19030=>mind all the things that he had stowed in it,  wondering if he had forgotten 
line 19031=>anything: his chief treasure, his cooking gear; and the  little  box of salt 
line 19032=>that he  always carried  and  refilled  when he  could;  a  good  supply  of 
line 19033=>pipe-weed (but not near enough,  I'll  warrant); flint  and tinder;  woollen 
line 19034=>hose:  linen;  various  small  belongings  of his  master's that  Frodo  had 
line 19035=>forgotten and Sam had  stowed to  bring them out in  triumph when they  were 
line 19036=>called for. He went through them all. 
line 19037=>     'Rope!'  he  muttered. `No  rope!  And  only  last night  you  said  to 
line 19038=>yourself: "Sam, what about a bit of rope? You'll want it, if you haven't got 
line 19039=>it:" Well, I'll wa nt it. I can't get it now.' 
line 19040=>     At that moment Elrond came out with  Gandalf, and he called the Company 
line 19041=>to him. 'This is my last  word,' he said in a low voice. 'The Ring-bearer is 
line 19042=>setting  out on the Quest  of  Mount Doom. On him  alone is any charge laid: 
line 19043=>neither to cast away the Ring, nor to deliver it to any servant of the Enemy 
line 19044=>nor  indeed to  let any  handle  it,  save  members of  the Company  and the 
line 19045=>Council,  and  only then in  gravest need. The others  go  with him  as free 
line 19046=>companions,  to help him on his way.  You may tarry,  or come back, or  turn 
line 19047=>
line 19048=>####-aside into other paths, as chance allows. The further you  go, the less easy 
line 19049=>will it be  to  withdraw; yet  no oath or bond is  laid on you to go further  
line 19050=>than you will. For you do not yet know the strength of  your hearts, and you  
line 19051=>cannot foresee what each may meet upon the road.' 
line 19052=>     `Faithless is he that says farewell when the road darkens,' said Gimli. 
line 19053=>     'Maybe,' said Elrond, `but let him not vow to walk in the dark, who has 
line 19054=>not seen the nightfall. ' 
line 19055=>     'Yet sworn word may strengthen quaking heart,' said Gimli. 
line 19056=>     `Or  break it,' said Elrond. `Look  not too far ahead! But  go now with 
line 19057=>good hearts!  Farewell, and may the  blessing of Elves and Men and  all Free 
line 19058=>Folk go with you. May the stars shine upon your faces!' 
line 19059=>     'Good . . . good luck!' cried Bilbo, stuttering with the cold. 'I don't 
line 19060=>suppose you will be able to keep a diary, Frodo my lad, but I shall expect a  
line 19061=>full account when you get back. And don't be too long! Farewell!' 
line 19062=>     Many other s of Elrond's household stood in the shadows and watched them 
line 19063=>go, bidding them farewell  with soft  voices. There was no laughter, and  no  
line 19064=>song or music. At last they turned away and faded silently into the dusk. 
line 19065=>     They crossed  the bridge and wound slowly up the long steep paths  that 
line 19066=>led out of the cloven vale of Rivendell; and they came at length to the high 
line 19067=>moor where the wind hissed through the  heather. Then with one glance at the 
line 19068=>Last Homely House twinkling below them they strode away far into the night. 
line 19069=>     At  the  Ford of Bruinen they left the Road and turning southwards went 
line 19070=>on  by  narrow paths  among the folded lands. Their purpose was to hold this 
line 19071=>course west of the Mountains  for many  miles and days. The country was 
line 19072=>much 
line 19073=>rougher  and  mor e barren  than  in  the  green vale of the  Great River  in 
line 19074=>Wilderland  on the other side of the range,  and  their going would be slow;  
line 19075=>but  they hoped  in  this way to  escape the notice of unfriendly  eyes. The 
line 19076=>spies of Sauron had hitherto seldom been seen in this empty country, and the 
line 19077=>paths were little known except to the people of Rivendell.  
line 19078=>     Gandalf walked in front, and with him went Aragorn, who knew this  land 
line 19079=>even  in the dark.  The  others were in file behind, and  Legolas whose eyes 
line 19080=>were keen was the rearguard.  The first  part of their  journey was hard and 
line 19081=>dreary, and Frodo remembered little  of it, save the wind. For many  sunless 
line 19082=>days an icy blast came from the Mountains in the east, and no garment seemed 
line 19083=>able  to keep out its searching fingers.  Though the Company was  well clad, 
line 19084=>they  seldom felt warm, either moving or at rest. They slept uneasily during 
line 19085=>
line 19086=>####-the middle of  the day,  in some  hollow of the land,  or  hidden under  the 
line 19087=>tangled  thorn-bushes  that  grew in  thickets in many places. In  the  late 
line 19088=>afternoon they were roused by the watch, and took their chief meal: cold and 
line 19089=>cheerless as  a rule, for they could seldom risk the lighting of a  fire. In 
line 19090=>the  evening  they went on again, always  as nearly  southward as they could 
line 19091=>find a  way. 
line 19092=>     At  first  it seemed  to  the hobbits  that  although  they walked  and 
line 19093=>stumbled until  they were weary, they were creeping forward like snails, and  
line 19094=>getting nowhere. Each  day  the land looked much the same as  it had the day 
line 19095=>before. Yet steadily the  mountains were drawing nearer. South  of Rivendell 
line 19096=>they rose ever higher, and bent westwards; and about the  feet  of the  main 
line 19097=>range there was tumbled an ever  wider land of bleak hills, and deep valleys 
line 19098=>filled with turbulent waters. Paths were few and winding, and led them often  
line 19099=>only to the edge of some sheer fall, or down into treacherous swamps.  
line 19100=>     They had been a fortnight on the way when the weather changed. The wind 
line 19101=>suddenly fell and then  veered round to  the south. The swift -flowing clouds 
line 19102=>lifted and melted away, and the sun came out,  pale and bright. There came a 
line 19103=>cold clear dawn  at the  end of a long stumbling night-march. The travellers 
line 19104=>reached a low ridge crowned with ancient holly -trees whose grey-green trunks 
line 19105=>seemed to have  been  bu ilt  out of the very  stone of the hills. Their dark 
line 19106=>leaves shone and their berries glowed red in the light of the rising sun. 
line 19107=>     Away  in the  south Frodo could  see the  dim shapes of lofty mountains 
line 19108=>that seemed now to stand across the path that the Company was taking. At the 
line 19109=>left of this high  range rose three peaks; the  tallest and nearest stood up 
line 19110=>like a tooth tipped with snow; its great, bare, northern precipice was still 
line 19111=>largely  in the  shadow, but where the sunlight slanted upon  it,  it glowed 
line 19112=>red. 
line 19113=>     Gandalf stood  at Frodo's side and  looked out under his hand. `We have 
line 19114=>done well,' he said.  `We have reached the borders of the country  that  Men 
line 19115=>call Hollin; many Elves lived here  in happier  days,  when Eregion was  its 
line 19116=>name.  Five-and-forty leagues as the crow flies we  have come,  though  many 
line 19117=>long miles further our feet  have walked. The land and the weather  will  be 
line 19118=>milder now, but perhaps all the more dangerous.' 
line 19119=>     `Dangerous or  not, a  real sunrise  is  mighty  welcome,'  said Frodo, 
line 19120=>throwing back his hood and letting the morning light fall on his face. 
line 19121=>     'But the mountains  are ahead of us,' said Pippin. `We must have turned 
line 19122=>eastwards in the night.' 
line 19123=>
line 19124=>####-     'No,'  said Gandalf. 'But you  see further ahead in  the  clear  light. 
line 19125=>Beyond those peaks the range bends round south-west. There are  many maps 
line 19126=>in 
line 19127=>Elrond's house, but I suppose you never thought to look at them?' 
line 19128=>     `Yes I did, sometimes,' said Pippin, `but I don't remember them.  Frodo 
line 19129=>has a better head for that sort of thing.' 
line 19130=>     `I need no map,' said  Gimli, who  had come  up  with Legolas,  and was 
