line 19164=>     'That is true,' said Legolas. `But  the Elves of  this land  were of  a  
line 19165=>race strange to  us  of the  silvan folk, and the trees and the grass do not 
line 19166=>now remember them: Only I hear the stones  lament them: deep they delved us, 
line 19167=>fair  they wrought  us,  high they  builded us;  but they are gone. They are 
line 19168=>gone. They sought the Havens long ago.' 
line 19169=>     That morning they lit a fire in a deep  hollow shrouded by great bushes 
line 19170=>of holly, and their supper -breakfast was merrier than it had been since they 
line 19171=>set out. They did not hurry to bed afterwards, for they expected to have all 
line 19172=>the  night  to sleep  in, and they  did not  mean to go  on again until  the 
line 19173=>evening of the next day. Only Aragorn was silent and restless. After a while 
line 19174=>he left the Company  and  wandered on  to the ridge; there he stood  in  the 
line 19175=>shadow of a tree, looking out southwards and  westwards, with his head posed 
line 19176=>as if he was listening. Then he returned to the brink of the dell and look ed 
line 19177=>down at the others laughing and talking. 
line 19178=>     `What  is the  matter, Strider?' Merry called up. 'What are you looking 
line 19179=>for? Do you miss the East Wind?' 
line 19180=>     'No  indeed,' he answered. `But I miss  something. I  have been in  the 
line 19181=>country  of  Hollin in many seasons. No folk  dwell here now, but many other  
line 19182=>creatures live here at  all times, especially birds. Yet now all  things but 
line 19183=>you are silent. I  can feel it.  There is no sound for miles about  us,  and 
line 19184=>your voices seem to make the ground echo. I do not understand it.' 
line 19185=>     Gandalf looked  up with  sudden interest. `But what do you guess is the 
line 19186=>reason?' he asked.  `Is  there  more  in  it  than  surprise  at seeing four 
line 19187=>hobbits, not to mention  the rest of us, where people are so seldom seen  or  
line 19188=>heard?' 
line 19189=>     `I  hope  that  is  it,'  answered Aragorn.  `But I  have  a  sense  of 
line 19190=>watchfulness, and of fear, that I have never had here before.' 
line 19191=>     "Then we  must be more careful,' said Gandalf.  'If you bring a  Ranger  
line 19192=>with you, it  is well  to pay attention to  him, especially if the Ranger is 
line 19193=>Aragorn. We must stop talking aloud, rest quietly, and set the watch.' 
line 19194=>     It was Sam's turn that day  to take the first watch, but Aragorn joined 
line 19195=>him. The others  fell asleep. Then the silence grew until even  Sam felt it. 
line 19196=>The breathing  of  the  sleepers could be  plainly heard.  The swish  of the 
line 19197=>pony's tail and the occasional movements of his feet became loud noises. Sam 
line 19198=>could hear his own joints creaking, if  he  stirred. Dead silence was around 
line 19199=>
