line 19344=>Aragorn only a pace or two ahead could hardly be seen. 
line 19345=>     'I don't like this at all,' panted Sam  just behind.  'Snow's all right 
line 19346=>on a fine morning,  but I like to be in  bed while it's falling. I wish this 
line 19347=>lot would  go off to Hobbiton! Folk  might  welcome  it there.' Except on the 
line 19348=>high moors of the Northfarthing a heavy fall was rare in the Shire,  and was 
line 19349=>regarded as  a pleasant event and  a chance for fun. No  living hobbit (save 
line 19350=>
line 19351=>####-Bilbo) could remember the Fell Winter of 1311, when the white wolves 
line 19352=>invaded 
line 19353=>the Shire over the frozen Brandywine. 
line 19354=>     Gandalf  halted. Snow  was  thick on  his  hood and  shoulders;  it was 
line 19355=>already ankle-deep about his boots.  
line 19356=>     "This is what I feared,' he said. `What do you say now, Aragorn?' 
line 19357=>     'That I feared  it too,' Aragorn answered, `but less than other things. 
line 19358=>I knew the  risk of  snow, though it seldom falls heavily so far south, save 
line 19359=>high up in the mountains. But we are not  high yet;  we are still  far down, 
line 19360=>where the paths are usually open all the winter.' 
line 19361=>     'I wonder if this  is a contrivance  of the Enemy,' said Boromir. "They 
line 19362=>say in my land that he can govern the storms in the Mountains of Shadow that 
line 19363=>stand upon the borders of Mordor. He has strange powers and many allies.' 
line 19364=>     'His arm  has grown long indeed,' said Gimli, `if he can draw snow down 
line 19365=>from the North to trouble us here three hundred leagues away.' 
line 19366=>     'His arm has grown long,' said Gandalf. 
line 19367=>     While  they  were halted,  the wind died  down, and the snow  slackened 
line 19368=>until  it almost ceased. They tramped on again.  But they had not  gone more 
line 19369=>than a  furlong when the storm returned with fresh  fury. The  wind whistled 
