line 20028=>     `The words are in  the elven-tongue of the West of  Middle-earth in the 
line 20029=>Elder Days,' answered Gandalf.  'But they do not say anything  of importance 
line 20030=>to us.  They say only: The Doors of Durin, Lord of Moria. Speak, friend, and 
line 20031=>enter.  And  underneath  small and faint  is written:  I, Narvi,  made them. 
line 20032=>Celebrimbor of Hollin drew these signs.' 
line 20033=>     `What does it mean by speak, friend, and enter?' asked Merry. 
line 20034=>     'That is plain enough,'  said  Gimli. `If  you are a friend,  speak the 
line 20035=>password, and the doors will open, and you can enter.' 
line 20036=>     'Yes,' said Gandalf, 'these doors are probably  governed by words. Some 
line 20037=>dwarf-gates will open only at special times, or for  particular persons; and 
line 20038=>some have locks and keys that  are still needed when all necessary times and  
line 20039=>words are known. These doors have no key. In the days of Durin they were not 
line 20040=>secret. They usually  stood  open  and doorwards sat here. But  if they were 
line 20041=>shut, any who  knew the opening word could speak it and pass in. At lea st so 
line 20042=>it is recorded, is it not, Gimli? ' 
line 20043=>     'It is,' said the dwarf. `But what the  word  was  is  not  remembered. 
line 20044=>Narvi and his craft and all his kindred have vanished from the earth.' 
line 20045=>     'But do not you know the word, Gandalf? ' asked Boromir in surprise. 
line 20046=>     `No! ' said the wizard. 
line 20047=>     The others looked  dismayed;  only  Aragorn,  who  knew  Gandalf  well, 
