line 20366=>     It was  Gandalf who roused them all from sleep. He  had sat and watched 
line 20367=>all alone for  about six hours, and had let  the others  rest.  `And  in the 
line 20368=>watches I have  made up my mind,' he  said. `I  do  not  like the feel of the 
line 20369=>middle way; and  I do not like the smell of the left-hand way: there is foul 
line 20370=>air down there, or I am no guide. I shall take the right -hand passage. It is 
line 20371=>time we began to climb up again.' 
line 20372=>     For eight dark hours, not counting two brief  halts,  they marched  on;  
line 20373=>and they met no  danger, and heard nothing, and  saw nothing  but the  faint 
line 20374=>gleam  of  the wizard's  light, bobbing like  a will-o'-the-wisp in front of 
line 20375=>them. The passage  they  had  chosen wound steadily upwards. As  far as they 
line 20376=>could judge it went in great mounting curves, and as it rose it grew loftier  
line 20377=>and wider.  There  were  now no openings  to  other galleries or  tunnels on 
line 20378=>either side, and the floor  was level  and sound,  without  pits or  cracks. 
line 20379=>Evidently  they had struck  what once had  been an important road; and  they 
line 20380=>went forward quicker than they had done on their first march. 
line 20381=>     In this way they advanced some fifteen miles, measured in a direct line 
line 20382=>east, though  they must have actually walked twenty miles  or  more. As  the 
line 20383=>road climbed  upwards`  Frodo's spirits rose  a little;  but he  still  felt 
line 20384=>oppressed, and still at times he heard, or thought he heard, away behind the 
line 20385=>Company and beyond the fall and patter of  their feet, a following  footstep 
line 20386=>that was not an echo. 
line 20387=>     They had marched as far as the hobbits could endure without a rest, and 
line 20388=>all were thinking of a place where they could sleep, when suddenly the walls 
line 20389=>to  right and left vanished. They seemed to have passed through some  arched 
line 20390=>doorway into a black and empty space. There  was  a great draught of  warmer  
line 20391=>air behind them, and before  them the darkness was cold on their faces. They 
line 20392=>halted and crowded anxiously together. 
line 20393=>     Gandalf seemed pleased. `I chose the right way,'  he said.  `At  last we 
line 20394=>
line 20395=>####-are  coming to the habitable parts, and I guess that we are not far now from 
line 20396=>the eastern side. But we are  high up, a good deal higher than  the  Dimrill 
line 20397=>Gate, unless I am mistaken. From the feeling of the air we must be in a wide 
line 20398=>hall. I will now risk a little real light.' 
line 20399=>     He  raised his staff,  and for a  brief instant there was blaze  like a  
line 20400=>flash  of lightning. Great shadows sprang up and fled, and for a second they  
line 20401=>saw a vast roof  far above their heads upheld by many mighty pillars hewn of 
line 20402=>stone. Before them and on either side stretched a huge empty hall; its black  
line 20403=>walls, polished  and smooth  as  glass, flashed and glittered.  Three  other  
line 20404=>entrances  they saw, dark black  arches: one straight before them eastwards,  
line 20405=>and one on either side. Then the light went out. 
line 20406=>     `That  is all that I shall venture on for the  present,' said  Gandalf. 
line 20407=>'There used to be great windows on the mountain-side, and shafts leading out 
line 20408=>to the light in the upper reaches of the Mines. I think we have reached  them 
line 20409=>now, but it is  night outside again, and we  cannot tell until morning. If I 
line 20410=>am right, tomorrow we may  actually see  the morning peeping  in. But in the 
line 20411=>meanwhile we had better go  no further. Let  us rest, if we can. Things have 
line 20412=>gone well  so far, and the greater part of the dark road is over. But we are 
line 20413=>not through yet, and it is a long way down to the  Gates  that open  on  the 
line 20414=>world.' 
line 20415=>     The Company spent that night in the great cavernous hall, huddled close 
line 20416=>together  in a corner  to escape  the draught:  there seemed  to be a steady 
line 20417=>inflow of chill air through the eastern archway. All about them as  they lay 
line 20418=>hung the darkness,  hollow and  immense,  and  they  were  oppressed by  the 
line 20419=>loneliness and vastness of  the dolven halls and endlessly branching  stairs 
line 20420=>and passages. The wildest imaginings  that dark rumour had ever suggested to 
line 20421=>the hobbits fell altogether short of the actual dread and wonder of Moria. 
line 20422=>     `There must have been a mighty crowd of dwarves here at one time ' said 
line 20423=>Sam; `and every one  of them busier  than badgers for five  hundred years to 
line 20424=>make all this, and most in hard rock too! What did they do it all for?  They 
line 20425=>didn't live in these darksome holes surely? ' 
line 20426=>     `These are not holes,' said Gimli. `This is the great realm and city of 
line 20427=>the Dwarrowdelf. And  of  old  it was  not  darksome, but  full of light and 
line 20428=>splendour, as is still remembered in our songs.' 
line 20429=>     He rose  and standing in the dark he  began to  chant in a  deep voice, 
line 20430=>while the echoes ran away into the roof.  
line 20431=>     The world was young, the mountains green, 
line 20432=>
line 20433=>####-     No stain yet on the Moon was seen, 
line 20434=>     No words were laid on stream or stone 
line 20435=>     When Durin woke and walked alone. 
line 20436=>     He named the nameless hills and dells; 
line 20437=>     He drank from yet untasted wells; 
line 20438=>     He stooped and looked in Mirrormere, 
line 20439=>     And saw a crown of stars appear, 
line 20440=>     As gems upon a silver thread, 
line 20441=>     Above the shadow of his head. 
line 20442=> 
line 20443=>     The world was fair, the mountains tall, 
line 20444=>     In Elder Days before the fall 
line 20445=>     Of mighty kings in Nargothrond 
line 20446=>     And Gondolin, who now beyond 
line 20447=>     The Western Seas have passed away: 
line 20448=>     The world was fair in Durin's Day. 
line 20449=> 
line 20450=>     A king he was on carven throne 
line 20451=>     In many-pillared halls of stone 
line 20452=>     With golden roof and silver floor, 
line 20453=>     And runes of power upon the door. 
