line 20473=> 
line 20474=>     The world is grey, the mountains old, 
line 20475=>     The forge's fire is ashen-cold  
line 20476=>     No harp is wrung, no hammer falls: 
line 20477=>     The darkness dwells in Durin's halls 
line 20478=>     The shadow lies upon his tomb 
line 20479=>     In Moria, in Khazad-dym. 
line 20480=>     But still the sunken stars appear 
line 20481=>     In dark and windless Mirrormere; 
line 20482=>     There lies his crown in water deep, 
line 20483=>     Till Durin wakes again from sleep. 
line 20484=>     `I like  that! ' said Sam. `I  should  like  to learn it. In Moria,  in  
line 20485=>Khazad-dym!  But it makes the darkness seem heavier, thinking  of all  those  
line 20486=>lamps. Are there piles of jewels and gold lying about here st ill?  ' 
line 20487=>     Gimli was silent. Having sung his song he would say no more. 
line 20488=>     `Piles  of jewels? ' said  Gandalf. `No. The Orcs have often  plundered 
line 20489=>Moria; there is nothing left in the upper halls. And since the dwarves fled, 
line 20490=>no one dares to seek the shafts and treasuries down in the deep places: they 
line 20491=>are drowned in water --or in a shadow of fear.' 
line 20492=>     `Then what do the dwarves want to come back for? ' asked Sam. 
line 20493=>     'For mithril,' answered  Gandalf. `The  wealth of Moria was not in gold 
line 20494=>and jewels, the toys of the Dwarves; nor in iron, their servant. Such things 
line 20495=>they found here, it is true, especially iron; but they did not need to delve 
line 20496=>for  them:  all things that they  desired they could obtain in  traffic. For  
line 20497=>here alone in the world was found Moria -silver, or true-silver as some  have 
line 20498=>called it: mithril is the Elvish name. The Dwarves have a name which they do 
line 20499=>not tell. Its worth was  ten times that of gold, and now it is beyond price; 
line 20500=>for little is left above  ground, and even the Orcs dare not  delve here for 
line 20501=>it. The lodes lead away  north towards  Caradhras, and down to darkness. The 
line 20502=>Dwarves  tell  no tale;  but  even as  mithril  was the  foundation of their 
line 20503=>wealth, so  also it was their destruction: they delved too greedily and  too 
line 20504=>deep,  and disturbed that from which they fled,  Durin's  Bane. Of what they 
line 20505=>brought to light the Orcs  have gathered nearly all, and given it in tribute 
line 20506=>to Sauron, who covets it. 
line 20507=>     `Mithril!  All  folk desired it.  It could be  beaten  like copper, and 
line 20508=>
line 20509=>####-polished like glass; and the Dwarves could make of it a metal, light and yet 
line 20510=>harder  than tempered steel. Its beauty  was like to  that of common silver, 
line 20511=>but  the  beauty  of mithril  did not tarnish  or grow dim.  The Elves dearly 
line 20512=>loved it, and among many uses they  made of it ithildin , starmoon, which you 
line 20513=>saw  upon  the doors. Bilbo had a  corslet of mithril-rings that Thorin gave 
line 20514=>him. I wonder what has become of it? Gathering dust  still in Michel Delving 
line 20515=>Mathom-house, I suppose.' 
line 20516=>     `What?  ' cried  Gimli,  startled  out of  his  silence. `A  corslet of 
line 20517=>Moria -silver? That was a kingly gift! ' 
line 20518=>     'Yes,' said  Gandalf. `I never told him, but its worth was greater than 
line 20519=>the value of the whole Shire and everything in it.' 
line 20520=>     Frodo said nothing, but he put his hand under his tunic and touched the 
line 20521=>rings of his mail-shirt. He felt staggered to think that he had been walking 
line 20522=>about with the price of the Shire under his jacket. Had Bilbo known? He felt 
line 20523=>no doubt that Bilbo knew quite  well.  It was indeed a kingly gift. But  now 
line 20524=>his thoughts  had been carried away  from the dark  Mines, to  Rivendell, to 
line 20525=>Bilbo,  and to Bag  End in  the days while Bilbo was  still there. He wished 
line 20526=>with  all his  heart  that he was back  there, and in those days, mowing the  
line 20527=>lawn, or pottering among the flowers, and that he had never heard  of Moria, 
line 20528=>or mithril --  or the Ring. 
line 20529=>     A deep silence fell.  One by one the others  fell  asleep. Frodo was on 
line 20530=>guard. As if it were a breath that came in through unseen doors  out of deep 
line 20531=>places,  dread  came  over him. His hands were cold  and his  brow  damp. He 
line 20532=>listened. All his mind was given to listening and  nothing else for two slow 
line 20533=>hours; but he heard no sound, not even the imagined echo of a footfall. 
line 20534=>     His  watch  was nearly over, when, far  off  where he guessed  that the 
line 20535=>western  archway stood,  he  fancied  that he could  see two pale points  of 
line 20536=>light, almost  like  luminous eyes. He started. His head had nodded. `I must  
line 20537=>have  nearly fallen asleep on guard,' he thought. `I  was on  the edge  of a 
line 20538=>dream.' He stood up and rubbed his eyes, and remained standing, peering into 
line 20539=>the dark, until he was relieved by Legolas. 
line 20540=>     When he lay down  he quickly went to  sleep, but  it seemed to him that 
line 20541=>the  dream went on: he  heard whispers, and saw the two pale points of light  
