line 21705=>     'You will have no claim,' said  Haldir. `I shall lead you well, and the 
line 21706=>paths are smooth and straight.' 
line 21707=>     `Alas for  the  folly  of these  days! '  said Legolas.  'Here  all  are 
line 21708=>
line 21709=>####-enemies of the one Enemy, and yet I must  walk blind, while the sun is merry 
line 21710=>in the woodland under leaves of gold!  ' 
line 21711=>     `Folly it  may seem,' said Haldir. 'Indeed  in nothing is the power  of 
line 21712=>the Dark Lord more clearly shown  than in the estrangement that  divides all  
line 21713=>those who still oppose him.  Yet so little faith and trust do we find now in 
line 21714=>the world beyond Lothlurien, unless maybe in  Rivendell, that we dare not by 
line 21715=>our own  trust  endanger our  land. We live  now  upon  an island  amid many 
line 21716=>perils, and our hands are more often upon the bowstring than upon the harp.  
line 21717=>     `The rivers long defended us, but they are a sure guard no more for the 
line 21718=>Shadow has crept northward  all about  us. Some speak of departing, yet  for  
line 21719=>that it already seems too  late. The mountains to the west are growing evil; 
line 21720=>to the east the lands are waste, and full of Sauron's creatures; and  it  is 
line 21721=>rumoured  that we cannot  now safely pass southward  through  Rohan, and the 
line 21722=>mouths of the Great River are watched by the Enemy. Even if we could come 
line 21723=>to 
line 21724=>the shores of the Sea, we  should  find no  longer any shelter there. It  is 
line 21725=>said that there are still havens of. the High Elves, but they are  far north 
line 21726=>and west, beyond the land of  the Halflings.  But where  that may be, though 
line 21727=>the Lord and Lady may know, I do not.' 
line 21728=>     `You ought  at  least to guess,  since you have seen  us,' said  Merry. 
line 21729=>`There are Elf-havens west of my land, the Shire where Hobbits live.' 
line 21730=>     `Happy folk  are  Hobbits to dwell  near  the shores of the sea! ' said 
line 21731=>Haldir. 'It is long indeed since any of my folk have looked on it, yet still 
line 21732=>we remember it in song. Tell me of these havens as we walk.' 
line 21733=>     `I cannot,' said Merry. `I have never seen them.  I have never been out 
line 21734=>of my own la nd before. And if I had known what the world outside was like. I 
line 21735=>don't think I should have had the heart to leave it.' 
line 21736=>     `Not even to see fair Lothlurien? '  said Haldir.  'The world is indeed 
line 21737=>full of peril, and in it there are many dark places; but still there is much 
line 21738=>that is fair, and  though in all lands love is  now  mingled with  grief, it 
line 21739=>grows perhaps the greater. 
line 21740=>     `Some there are among us  who sing that  the Shadow  will draw back and 
line 21741=>peace shall come again.  Yet I do not believe  that  the world about us will 
line 21742=>ever again be as it was of old, or the light of the Sun as it was aforetime. 
line 21743=>For the Elves, I fear, it will prove at best a truce, in which they may pass 
line 21744=>to  the  Sea  unhindered  and  leave the Middle-earth  for  ever.  Alas  for  
line 21745=>Lothlurien that I  love! It would be a  poor life in a land where no mallorn 
line 21746=>
line 21747=>####-grew.  But  if  there  are  mallorn-trees beyond  the Great Sea,  none  have 
line 21748=>reported it.' 
line 21749=>     As they spoke  thus, the  Company filed slowly along the  paths  in the 
line 21750=>wood, led by Hald ir, while the other Elf walked behind. They felt the ground 
line 21751=>beneath their  feet smooth and  soft, and  after  a while they  walked  more 
line 21752=>freely, without fear of hurt or  fall. Being deprived of sight, Frodo  found 
line 21753=>his hearing and  other senses  sharpened. He could smell the  trees and  the 
line 21754=>trodden  grass.  He could hear many  different notes in  the  rustle  of the 
line 21755=>leaves overhead, the river murmuring away on  his right, and  the thin clear 
line 21756=>voices of birds in  the sky. He  felt the sun upon his face  and hands  when 
line 21757=>they passed through an open glade. 
line 21758=>     As  soon  as he  set  foot  upon the  far  bank of Silverlode a strange 
line 21759=>feeling had come upon  him, and it  deepened as he walked on into the Naith: 
line 21760=>it seemed to him that  he had stepped over a bridge of time into a corner of 
line 21761=>the  Elder Days, and  was  -now walking  in  a world that  was  no  more.  In 
line 21762=>Rivendell  there was memory of  ancient things; in Lurien the ancient things 
line 21763=>still lived on  in the waking world. Evil had been  seen  and  heard  there, 
line 21764=>sorrow had been known; the Elves  feared and  distrusted the world  outside: 
line 21765=>wolves  were howling on  the wood's borders: but  on  the land  of Lurien no 
line 21766=>shadow lay. 
line 21767=>     All that day the  Company marched on, until  they felt the cool evening 
line 21768=>come and heard  the early night-wind whispering among many leaves. Then 
line 21769=>they 
line 21770=>rested and slept without fear upon the ground;  for  their guides would  not 
line 21771=>permit  them to unbind their eyes, and they could  not climb. In the morning 
line 21772=>they went  on again,  walking without  hast e. At noon they halted, and Frodo  
line 21773=>was aware that they had  passed out under the shining Sun. Suddenly he heard 
line 21774=>the sound of many voices all around him. 
line 21775=>     A marching host of Elves  had  come up silently:  they  were  hastening 
line 21776=>toward the northern borders to guard against any attack from Moria; and they 
line 21777=>brought news,  some of  which Haldir reported. The marauding orcs  had  been 
line 21778=>waylaid and  almost all destroyed; the remnant had fled westward towards the 
line 21779=>mountains, and were being pursued.  A strange creature also  had  been seen, 
line 21780=>running with bent back and  with hands near the ground, like a beast and yet  
line 21781=>not of beast-shape. It  had eluded  capture, and  they had not  shot it, not 
line 21782=>knowing whether it was good or ill, and  it had vanished down the Silverlode 
line 21783=>southward. 
line 21784=>
line 21785=>####-     `Also,' said Haldir, `they bring me a message from the Lord and Lady of 
line 21786=>the Galadhrim. You are all to walk free, even the dwarf Gimli. It seems that 
line 21787=>the  Lady knows who and what is each member of  your  Company.  New 
line 21788=>messages 
line 21789=>have come from Rivendell perhaps.' 
line 21790=>     He  removed the  bandage  first from Gimli's eyes.  'Your pardon! '  he 
line 21791=>said, bowing low. `Look on  us now with friendly eyes! Look and be glad, for  
line 21792=>you are the  first  dwarf to behold the  trees of the Naith of  Lurien since 
line 21793=>Durin's Day! ' 
line 21794=>     When  his eyes were in  turn uncovered, Frodo looked up  and caught his 
line 21795=>breath.  They were  standing  in an  open  space. To the  left stood a great 
line 21796=>mound, covered with  a sward of grass as  green as Spring-time in the  Elder  
line 21797=>Days.  Upon it , as a double crown, grew two circles of trees: the  outer had 
line 21798=>bark  of  snowy white,  and  were leafless  but  beautiful in  their shapely 
line 21799=>nakedness;  the inner were mallorn-trees of great height,  still arrayed  in 
line 21800=>pale  gold. High  amid  the branches of a  towering  tree that stood in  the 
line 21801=>centre of all there gleamed a white flet. At the feet of  the trees, and all 
line 21802=>about  the  green hillsides the grass was studded with small golden  flowers 
line 21803=>shaped  like  stars.  Among them,  nodding  on  slender  stalks,  were  other  
line 21804=>flowers, white and palest green: they glimmered  as a mist amid the rich hue 
line 21805=>of  the  grass. Over all the sky was blue, and  the sun  of afternoon glowed 
line 21806=>upon the hill and cast long green shadows beneath the trees.  
line 21807=>     'Behold! You  are come to Cerin Amroth,' said Haldir. `For this is  the 
line 21808=>heart  of the ancient realm  as it  was long ago, and here is the  mound  of 
line 21809=>Amroth, where in  happier days his high house was built. Here ever bloom the 
line 21810=>winter  flowers  in the  unfading grass:  the  yellow  elanor, and the  pale 
line 21811=>niphredil. Here we will stay awhile, and  come  to the city of the Galadhrim 
line 21812=>at dusk.' 
line 21813=>     The  others  cast themselves down  upon the  fragrant grass,  but Frodo 
line 21814=>stood  awhile still lost in wonder.  It seemed  to him that  he  had stepped 
line 21815=>through a high window  that looked on a vanished world. A light was  upon it 
line 21816=>for which his language  had no  name.  All that  he saw was shapely, but the 
line 21817=>shapes  seemed at once clear cut, as  if they had  been first conceived  and 
line 21818=>drawn at the uncovering of  his eyes, and ancient as if they had endured for  
line 21819=>ever. He saw no colour but those he knew, gold and white and blue and green, 
line 21820=>but  they were  fresh  and poignant,  as if  he  had  at  that  moment first  
line 21821=>
line 21822=>####-perceived them and made for them names new and wonderful. In winter  here 
line 21823=>no 
line 21824=>heart  could  mourn for summer  or  for spring.  No  blemish  or sickness or  
line 21825=>deformity could be seen in anything that grew upon the earth. On the land of 
line 21826=>Lurien there was no stain. 
line 21827=>     He  turned  and saw that Sam was now standing beside him, looking round 
line 21828=>with a  puzzled expression, and rubbing his eyes as  if he was not sure that 
line 21829=>he was  awake. `It's  sunlight  and bright  day, right enough,'  he said. `I  
line 21830=>thought that Elves were all for moon and stars: but this is more elvish than 
line 21831=>anything I ever heard tell of. I feel as if I was  inside a song. if you take 
line 21832=>my meaning.' 
line 21833=>     Haldir looked at them, and he seemed indeed to take the meaning of both 
line 21834=>thought  and  word.  He  smiled. `You  feel the  power of  the  Lady of  the 
line 21835=>Galadhrim,' he said. `Would it please you  to climb with me up Cerin Amroth?  
line 21836=>' 
line 21837=>     They followed  him  as  he stepped lightly up  the  grass-clad  slopes.  
line 21838=>Though he walked and  breathed, and about him living leaves and flowers were 
line 21839=>stirred by the same cool wind as fanned his face, Frodo felt that  he was in 
line 21840=>a timeless land that did not fade or change or fall into forgetfulness. When 
line 21841=>he had gone and passed again into  the outer world, still Frodo the wanderer  
line 21842=>from the Shire would walk there, upon the  grass among  elanor and niphredil 
line 21843=>in fair Lothlurien. 
line 21844=>     They entered the circle of white trees. As they did so the  South  Wind 
line 21845=>blew  upon Cerin Amroth and  sighed among the  branches. Frodo  stood still, 
line 21846=>hearing far off_ great seas upon beaches that had long ago been washed away, 
line 21847=>and sea -birds crying whose race had perished from the earth. 
line 21848=>     Haldir  had gone on and was  now  climbing to the high  flet. As  Frodo 
line 21849=>prepared to follow him,  he laid his hand  upon the  tree beside the ladder: 
line 21850=>never before had  he been  so  suddenly and so keenly aware of the  feel and 
line 21851=>texture of a tree's skin and of the life within  it. He  felt  a  delight in 
line 21852=>wood and  the touch of it, neither  as forester nor as carpenter; it was the 
line 21853=>delight of the living tree itself. 
line 21854=>     As he stepped out at last upon the lofty platform, Haldir took his hand 
line 21855=>and turned him toward the South. `Look this way first! ' he said. 
line 21856=>     Frodo looked  and saw, still at some  distance, a  hill of many  mighty 
line 21857=>trees, or a city of green towers: which it was he could not tell. Out of it, 
line 21858=>it seemed  to him that the  power and light came that held all the  land  in 
line 21859=>
line 21860=>####-sway. He longed suddenly to fly like a bird to rest in the  green city. Then  
line 21861=>he looked  eastward and  saw all the land of Lurien running down to  the pale  
line 21862=>gleam of Anduin, the Great  River.  He lifted his  eyes across the river and 
line 21863=>all the light went out, and he  was back again in the world he knew.  Beyond 
line 21864=>the river  the land  appeared flat and empty,  formless and vague, until far 
line 21865=>away  it  rose  again  like  a  wall, dark  and drear.  The sun that lay  on 
line 21866=>Lothlurien had no power to enlighten the shadow of that distant height. 
line 21867=>     `There  lies  the fastness of  Southern  Mirkwood,' said Haldir. `It is 
line 21868=>clad in a forest of dark fir, where the trees strive one against another and 
line 21869=>their branches rot and wither. In the midst upon a  stony height  stands Dol 
line 21870=>Guldur, where long the hidden Enemy had his dwelling. We fear that now it is 
line 21871=>inhabited again,  and with power sevenfold. A black cloud lies often over it 
line 21872=>of  late. In this high place you may see the two powers that are opposed one  
line 21873=>to another;  and ever  they  strive now  in thought,  but whereas the  light 
line 21874=>perceives  the very  heart of  the darkness,  its  own  secret has not  been 
line 21875=>discovered. Not yet.' He turned and climbed swiftly down, and  they followed 
line 21876=>him. 
line 21877=>     At the hill's foot Frodo found Aragorn, standing still  and silent as a  
line 21878=>tree; but in his hand was a small golden bloom of elanor, and a light was in 
line 21879=>his eyes. He was wrapped in some fair memory: and as Frodo looked  at him he 
line 21880=>knew that he beheld things as they once had been in this same place. For the 
line 21881=>grim years were removed from the  face of Aragorn, and he  seemed clothed in 
line 21882=>white, a  young lord  tall and fair; and he spoke words in the Elvish tongue 
line 21883=>to one whom Frodo could not see . Arwen vanimelda, nambril! he said, and then 
line 21884=>he drew a breath, and returning  out  of his thought  he looked at Frodo and 
line 21885=>smiled. 
line 21886=>     `Here  is the  heart of Elvendom on earth,' he said, `and here my heart 
line 21887=>dwells  ever,  unless there  be a light beyond the dark roads that  we still 
line 21888=>must tread, you and I. Come with  me!  ' And taking Frodo's hand in  his, he 
