line 22102=>     All  of them, it seemed, had fared  alike:  each  had felt that  he was 
line 22103=>offered a choice between a shadow full of fear that lay ahead, and something 
line 22104=>that he greatly  desired: clear before his mind it lay, and to get it he had 
line 22105=>only to  turn  aside from the road and  leave the Quest and  the war against 
line 22106=>Sauron to others.  
line 22107=>     `And it seemed  to me, too,'  said Gimli, `that my choice  would remain 
line 22108=>secret and known only to myself.' 
line 22109=>     'To me it seemed exceedingly strange,' said Boromir. `Maybe it was only 
line 22110=>a test,  and she thought to read our thoughts  for her own good purpose; but 
line 22111=>almost I  should  have said that she was tempting us, and offering  what she 
line 22112=>pretended to have the power to give. It  need not be  said that I refused to 
line 22113=>listen. The Men of Minas Tirith are true to their word.' But what he thought 
line 22114=>that the Lady had offered him Boromir did not tell. 
line 22115=>     And as for Frodo, he would  not speak, though  Boromir pressed him with 
line 22116=>questions. `She held you long in her gaze, Ring-bearer,' he said. 
line 22117=>     `Yes,'  said Frodo; `but whatever  came into my  mind  then I will keep 
line 22118=>there.' 
line 22119=>     `Well, have a care!  ' said  Boromir.  `I do not feel too sure  of this 
line 22120=>Elvish Lady and her purposes.' 
line 22121=>
line 22122=>####-     `Speak no evil of the Lady Galadriel! ' said Aragorn sternly. 'You know 
line 22123=>not what you say.  There is in her  and in  this land no evil, unless a  man 
line 22124=>bring  it  hither himself.  Then let him beware!  But  tonight I shall sleep 
line 22125=>without  fear  for the first time  since  I left Rivendell. And may  I sleep 
line 22126=>deep, and forget for a while my grief! I am weary in body and in  heart.' He 
line 22127=>cast himself down upon his couch and fell at once into a long sleep. 
line 22128=>     The others soon did the same, and no sound  or  dream  disturbed  their 
line 22129=>slumber. When they woke they found that the light of day  was broad upon the 
line 22130=>lawn before the pavilion.  and  the fountain rose and fell glittering in the 
line 22131=>sun. 
line 22132=>     They remained some  days in Lothlurien, so  far as they could  tell  or 
line 22133=>remember. All the while that they dwelt there the sun  shone clear, save for  
line 22134=>a gentle  rain that fell at times, and passed away leaving all  things fresh 
line 22135=>and clean. The air was cool and  soft, as if it were  early spring, yet they 
line 22136=>felt about them the deep  and thoughtful quiet of winter.  It seemed to them 
line 22137=>that they did little but  eat and drink and  rest, and walk among the trees;  
line 22138=>and it was enough. 
line 22139=>     They had not seen  the Lord and Lady  again, and they had little speech 
line 22140=>with the Elven-folk; for few of these  knew or would use the Westron tongue. 
line 22141=>Haldir  had  bidden them  farewell and gone back again to the  fences of the 
line 22142=>North, where great watch was  now kept since the tidings of Moria  that  the 
line 22143=>Company had  brought. Legolas  was away much among the Galadhrim,  and 
line 22144=>after 
line 22145=>the  first  night  he  did not sleep with  the  other companions,  though he 
line 22146=>returned  to  eat and talk with them. Often he  took Gimli with him  when he 
line 22147=>went abroad in the land, and the others wondered at this change. 
line 22148=>     Now as the companions sat or walked together they spoke of Gandalf, and 
line 22149=>all  that  each had  known and seen of  him came clear before their minds. As 
line 22150=>they  were healed of hurt and weariness of body the grief of their loss grew 
line 22151=>more keen. Often they heard nearby Elvish voices singing, and knew that they 
line 22152=>were making songs  of  lamentation  for his fall,  for they caught  his name 
line 22153=>among the sweet sad words that they could not understand. 
line 22154=>     Mithrandir, Mithrandir  sang  the Elves, O Pilgrim Grey!  For  so  they 
line 22155=>loved  to  call  him.  But if Legolas was with  the  Company,  he would  not 
line 22156=>interpret the songs for them, saying that he had not the skill, and that for  
line 22157=>him the grief was still too near, a matter for tears and not yet for song. 
line 22158=>     It was Frodo who first put something of his sorrow into  halting words.  
line 22159=>
line 22160=>####-He was seldom moved to make song or rhyme; even in Rivendell he had 
line 22161=>listened 
line 22162=>and had not sung himself, though his memory was stored with many things that 
line 22163=>others had made before him. But now as he sat beside the  fountain in Lurien 
line 22164=>and heard  about  him the  voices of the Elves, his thought took shape  in a  
line 22165=>song that seemed fair to him;  yet  when he  tried to repeat it to Sam  only 
line 22166=>snatches remained, faded as a handful of withered leaves. 
line 22167=>     When evening in the Shire was grey 
line 22168=>     his footsteps on the Hill were heard; 
line 22169=>     before the dawn he went away 
line 22170=>     on journey long without a word. 
line 22171=> 
line 22172=>     From Wilderland to Western shore, 
line 22173=>     from northern waste to southern hill, 
line 22174=>     through dragon-lair and hidden door 
line 22175=>     and darkling woods he walked at will. 
line 22176=> 
line 22177=>     With Dwarf and Hobbit, Elves and Men, 
line 22178=>     with mortal and immortal folk, 
line 22179=>     with bird on bough and beast in den, 
line 22180=>     in their own secret tongues he spoke. 
line 22181=> 
line 22182=>     A deadly sword, a healing hand, 
line 22183=>     a back that bent beneath its load; 
line 22184=>     a trumpet-voice, a burning brand, 
line 22185=>     a weary pilgrim on the road. 
line 22186=> 
line 22187=>     A lord of wisdom throned he sat, 
line 22188=>     swift in anger, quick to laugh; 
line 22189=>     an old man in a battered hat 
line 22190=>     who leaned upon a thorny staff. 
line 22191=> 
line 22192=>     He stood upon the bridge alone 
line 22193=>     and Fire and Shadow both defied; 
line 22194=>     his staff was broken on the stone, 
line 22195=>     in Khazad-dym his wisdom died. 
line 22196=>     `Why, you'll be beating Mr. Bilbo next! ' said Sam. 
line 22197=>
line 22198=>####-     'No, I am afraid not,' said Frodo. 'But that is the best I can do yet.' 
line 22199=>     'Well, Mr. Frodo, if  you  do have another go, I hope you'll say a word 
line 22200=>about his fireworks,' said Sam. `Something like this:  
line 22201=>     The finest rockets ever seen: 
line 22202=>     they burst in stars of blue and green, 
line 22203=>     or after thunder golden showers 
line 22204=>     came falling like a rain of flowers. 
line 22205=>     Though that doesn't do them justice by a long road.' 
line 22206=>     `No,  I'll  leave that  to  you,  Sam. Or perhaps to Bilbo. But-well. I 
line 22207=>can't talk of  it any more. I can't bear to think  of bringing  the news  to 
line 22208=>him.' 
line 22209=>     One  evening Frodo and Sam were walking  together in the cool twilight.  
line 22210=>Both of them  felt restless again. On  Frodo suddenly the  shadow of parting  
line 22211=>had fallen: he  knew somehow that the time was very near when  he must leave 
line 22212=>Lothlurien. 
line 22213=>     `What do you think of Elves now, Sam?  ' he said. `I asked you the same 
line 22214=>question once before-it   seems a very long while ago; but you have seen more 
line 22215=>of them since then.' 
line 22216=>     'I  have  indeed!  ' said Sam. 'And I reckon  there's  Elves and Elves.  
line 22217=>They're  all  elvish enough,  but they're not all the same. Now  these  folk  
line 22218=>aren't wanderers or homeless, and seem a bit nearer to the likes of us: they 
line 22219=>seem to belong here, more even than Hobbits do in the Shire. Whether they've 
line 22220=>made the land, or  the  land's  made them, it's hard to say,  if you take my 
line 22221=>meaning. It's  wonderfully  quiet here.  Nothing seems to  be going on,  and 
line 22222=>nobody  seems to  want it to. If  there's any magic  about,  it's right down 
line 22223=>deep, where I can't lay my hands on it, in a manner of speaking.' 
line 22224=>     'You can see and feel it everywhere,' said Frodo. 
line 22225=>     'Well,' said Sam, 'you can't  see nobody working  it. No  fireworks like 
line 22226=>poor Gandalf used to  show. I  wonder  we  don't see nothing of the Lord and 
line 22227=>Lady in all these days. I fancy now that she could do some wonderful things, 
line 22228=>if she had a mind. I'd dearly love to see some Elf-magic, Mr. Frodo!  ' 
line 22229=>     'I  wouldn't,' said Frodo.  `I am content.  And I don't  miss Gandalf's 
line 22230=>fireworks, but his bushy eyebrows, and his quick temper, and his voice.' 
line 22231=>     `You're right,'  said  Sam.  `And don't think I'm  finding  fault. I've 
line 22232=>often wanted to  see a  bit of magic like what it tells of in old tales, but 
line 22233=>I've never heard of a  better land than this. It's like being at home and on 
line 22234=>a holiday at the same time, if you understand me. I don't want to leave. All 
line 22235=>
line 22236=>####-the same,  I'm beginning to feel that if we've got to go on,  then we'd best 
line 22237=>get it over. 
line 22238=>     'It's the  job that's never started as takes longest  to finish, as  my 
line 22239=>old gaffer used to say. And I don't reckon that these folk  can do much more 
line 22240=>to  help us, magic or no. It's  when we leave  this land that we shall  miss 
line 22241=>Gandalf worse, I'm thinking.' 
line 22242=>     'I  am afraid that's only too  true, Sam,' said Frodo. `Yet I hope very 
line 22243=>much that before we leave we shall see the Lady of the Elves again.' 
line 22244=>     Even as he spoke, they saw,  as if she  came in answer to their  words,  
