line 22462=>were talking about.  I  saw a star through your finger. But if you'll pardon 
line 22463=>
line 22464=>####-my speaking  out,  I think my master was right. I  wish you'd take his Ring. 
line 22465=>You'd  put things  to  rights.  You'd  stop them digging up the  gaffer  and 
line 22466=>turning him adrift. You'd make some folk pay for their dirty work.' 
line 22467=>     `I would,' she said. `That is how it would begin. Bu t it would not stop 
line 22468=>with that, alas! We will not speak more of it. Let us go!' 
line 22469=>
line 22470=>####- 
line 22471=> 
line 22472=>
line 22473=>Chapter 8. Farewell to Lurien 
line 22474=>
line 22475=> 
line 22476=> 
line 22477=>     That  night  the Company was again summoned to the chamber of Celeborn, 
line 22478=>and there the Lord and Lady greeted them with fair words. At length Celeborn 
line 22479=>spoke of their departure. 
line 22480=>     `Now is the time,' he  said, `when those who wish to continue the Quest  
line 22481=>must harden their hearts to leave this land.  Those who no longer wish to go  
line 22482=>forward may remain here, for a while. But whether they stay or go, none  can 
line 22483=>be sure of  peace.  For we are come now to  the edge of doom. Here those who 
line 22484=>wish  may await  the oncoming of the hour till either the ways of  the world 
line 22485=>lie open again. or we summon them to the  last need of Lurien. Then they may 
line 22486=>return to their own lands, or else go to the long home of those that fall in 
line 22487=>battle.' 
line 22488=>     There was a silence. `They all resolved to  go forward,' said Galadriel 
line 22489=>looking in their eyes. 
line 22490=>     `As for me,' said Boromir, `my way home lies onward and not back.' 
line 22491=>     `That is true,' said Celeborn, `but is all this Company  going with you  
line 22492=>to Minas Tirith? ' 
line 22493=>     `We have not decided our course,' said Aragorn. 'Beyond Lothlurien I do 
line 22494=>not know what Gandalf intended to do. Indeed I do not think that even he had 
line 22495=>any clear purpose. ' 
line 22496=>     `Maybe not,' said  Celeborn, `yet when you leave this land, you  can no 
line 22497=>longer  forget  the Great  River.  As  some of you  know well, it  cannot be 
line 22498=>crossed  by travellers with baggage between Lurien and Gondor, save by boat. 
line 22499=>And are not the bridges  of Osgiliath broken down  and all the landings held 
line 22500=>now by the Enemy?  
line 22501=>     `On which side will you journey? The way to Minas Tirith lies upon this 
line 22502=>side, upon  the  west; but the straight road of the Quest  lies east of  the 
line 22503=>River, upon the darker shore. Which shore will you now take?  ' 
line 22504=>     `If my advice  is heeded, it will be the western shore,  and the way to 
line 22505=>Minas Tirith,' answered Boromir.  `But I  am not the leader of the Company.' 
line 22506=>The others said nothing, and Aragorn looked doubtful and troubled. 
line 22507=>     `I see that you do not yet know  what to do,' said Celeborn. `It is not 
line 22508=>my  part to choose for you; but I will help you as  I  may.  There are  some 
line 22509=>
line 22510=>####-among  you who can handle  boats: Legolas, whose folk know  the swift Forest  
line 22511=>River; and Boromir of Gondor; and Aragorn the traveller.' 
line 22512=>     `And  one Hobbit! ' cried Merry. `Not all of us look on  boats as  wild 
line 22513=>horses. My people live by the banks of the Brandywine.' 
line 22514=>     `That is  well,' said Celeborn. `Then I will furnish  your Company with 
line 22515=>boats. They must be small and light, for  if you go far  by water, there are 
line 22516=>places where you will be forced to  carry them. You will come to  the rapids 
line 22517=>of Sarn  Gebir,  and maybe at  last to the  great falls of  Rauros where the 
line 22518=>River thunders down from Nen Hithoel; and there  are other perils. Boats may 
line 22519=>make your journey less toilsome for  a while.  Yet they  will  not  give you  
line 22520=>counsel:  in the  end  you must leave  them and the River, and turn  west -or 
line 22521=>east.' 
line 22522=>     Aragorn  thanked  Celeborn  many times. The gift of boats comforted him 
line 22523=>much, not least because there would now be no  need to decide his course for 
line 22524=>some days. The others, too, looked more hopeful. Whatever perils  lay ahead, 
line 22525=>it seemed better to float down the broad tide of Anduin to meet them than to 
line 22526=>plod   forward  with  bent backs. Only Sam was doubtful: he at any rate still 
line 22527=>thought boats as bad as wild horses, or worse, and not  all the dangers that 
line 22528=>he had survived made him think better of them. 
line 22529=>     `All shall be prepared for you and await you  at the  haven before noon 
line 22530=>tomorrow,'  said  Celeborn.  'I will send my people to you in the morning to 
line 22531=>help you make ready for the journey. Now we will  wish  you all a fair night  
line 22532=>and untroubled sleep.' 
line 22533=>     'Good  night,  my friends!  ' said Galadriel.  'Sleep in peace! Do  not 
line 22534=>trouble your  hearts overmuch with thought of  the road tonight.  Maybe  the 
line 22535=>paths that  you each  shall tread are  already laid before your feet, though 
line 22536=>you do not see them. Good night! ' 
line 22537=>     The  Company  now  took  their leave  and  returned to their  pavilion. 
line 22538=>Legolas  went with them, for this  was to be their last night in Lothlurien, 
line 22539=>and in spite of the words of Galadriel they wished to take counsel together. 
line 22540=>     For a  long time they debated what they should do, and  how it would be 
line 22541=>best to attempt the fulfilling of their purpose with the Ring: but they came 
line 22542=>to no decision. It was plain that most of them desired to go  first to Minas 
line 22543=>Tirith, and to  escape at least for a while from  the  terror of  the Enemy. 
line 22544=>They would have been willing to follow a leader  over the River and into the  
line 22545=>shadow of Mordor; but Frodo spoke  no word, and Aragorn was still divided in 
line 22546=>his mind. 
line 22547=>
line 22548=>####-     His  own  plan, while Gandalf remained with  them, had been to go  with 
line 22549=>Boromir, and with his sword help to deliver Gondor. For he believed that the 
line 22550=>message of the dreams was a summons, and that the hour had come at last 
line 22551=>when 
line 22552=>the  heir of  Elendil  should  come  forth and  strive with  Sauron  for the 
line 22553=>mastery. But in Moria  the burden of Gandalf had been laid  on  him; and  he  
line 22554=>knew that he could not now forsake the Ring, if Frodo refused in  the end to  
line 22555=>go with  Boromir. And  yet what help could he or any of the Company give  to 
line 22556=>Frodo, save to walk blindly with him into the darkness?  
line 22557=>     `I shall go to Minas Tirith,  alone if need be, for it is my duty,' said 
line 22558=>Boromir; and after  that he was  silent  for a while,  sitting with his eyes 
line 22559=>fixed  on Frodo, as if  he was trying  to  read the Halfling's thoughts.  At 
line 22560=>length he spoke  again, softly, as if he was debating  with himself. `If you  
line 22561=>wish only to destroy  the Ring,' he said,  `then there is little use in  war 
line 22562=>and weapons; and the Men of Minas  Tirith  cannot  help.  But if you wish to  
line 22563=>destroy the armed might  of the  Dark Lord,  then it is folly  to go without 
line 22564=>force into his domain; and folly  to throw away.' He  paused suddenly, as if 
line 22565=>he had  become aware that he was  speaking his thoughts aloud. `It  would be 
line 22566=>folly  to  throw  lives away,  I  mean,' he ended. `It is  a choice  between 
line 22567=>defending a  strong place  and   walking openly  into the arms  of death.  At  
line 22568=>least, that is how I see it.' 
line 22569=>     Frodo caught something  new  and strange  in  Boromir's glance, and  he 
line 22570=>looked hard at  him.  Plainly Boromir's thought was different from his final 
line 22571=>words. It would be folly to throw away: what? The Ring of Power? He had said 
line 22572=>something like this  at the Council, but then he had accepted the correction 
line 22573=>of Elrond. Frodo looked at Aragorn,  but he seemed  deep in  his own thought 
line 22574=>and made no sign that he  had  heeded Boromir's wor ds.  And so  their debate 
line 22575=>ended. Merry and Pippin were  already asleep, and Sam was nodding. The 
line 22576=>night 
line 22577=>was growing old. 
line 22578=>     In the  morning, as they were  beginning  to  pack their slender goods,  
line 22579=>Elves that could speak their tongue came to them and brought them many gifts 
line 22580=>of food and clothing for the  journey.  The food was  mostly in the  form of 
line 22581=>very thin cakes, made of a meal that was baked a light brown on the outside, 
line 22582=>and inside  was  the colour of  cream. Gimli took  up one  of  the cakes and 
line 22583=>looked at it with a doubtful eye. 
line 22584=>     `Cram,' he said  under his breath,  as he broke off a crisp corner  and 
line 22585=>
line 22586=>####-nibbled at it. His expression quickly changed, and  he ate  all the rest  of 
line 22587=>the cake with relish. 
line 22588=>     `No more,  no  more!' cried the  Elves laughing.  `You have eaten enough 
line 22589=>already for a long day's march.' 
line 22590=>     `I thought  it was  only a kind of cram, such as  the Dale-men make for 
line 22591=>journeys in the wild,' said the Dwarf.  
line 22592=>     `So it is,' they answered.  `But we call it   lembas or waybread, and it 
line 22593=>is mor e strengthening than any food made  by Men, and  it  is more  pleasant  
line 22594=>than cram, by all accounts.' 
line 22595=>     `Indeed it is,' said Gimli.  'Why it is better than  the honey-cakes of 
line 22596=>the Beornings,  and  that  is great praise,  for the Beornings  are the best 
line 22597=>bakers that I know of; but they are none too willing to deal out their cakes 
line 22598=>to travellers in these days. You are kindly hosts! ' 
line 22599=>     'All the same, we bid you spare the food,' they  said. 'Eat little at a  
line 22600=>time,  and only at need. For these things  are given to  serve  you when all  
line 22601=>else fails.  The  cakes  will keep sweet  for  many many  days, if  they are 
line 22602=>unbroken and left in their leaf-wrappings, as we have brought them. One will 
line 22603=>keep a traveller on his feet for a day of  long labour, even if he be one of 
line 22604=>the tall Men of Minas Tirith.' 
line 22605=>     The  Elves next unwrapped  and gave to each  of the Company the clothes 
line 22606=>they  had  brought.  For  each they  had  provided a  hood  and cloak,  made 
line 22607=>according to his size, of the light but warm silken stuff that the Galadhrim 
line 22608=>wove. It was  hard to say of what  colour they were:  grey with  the hue  of 
line 22609=>twilight under  the trees they seemed  to be; and yet if they were moved, or  
line 22610=>set in another light, they were green as shadowed leaves, or brown as fallow 
line 22611=>fields by  night, dusk -silver  as  water under  the  stars. Each  cloak  was 
line 22612=>fastened about the neck with a brooch like a green leaf veined with silver. 
line 22613=>     `Are these magic cloaks? ' asked Pippin, looking at them with wonder. 
line 22614=>     `I do  not  know what you mean by  that,' answered  the  leader  of the 
line 22615=>Elves. `They are fair garments, and the web is good, for it was made in this 
line 22616=>land. They are elvish robes certainly, if that is what  you  mean. Leaf  and  
line 22617=>branch, water and  stone: they have the hue and beauty  of all  these things 
line 22618=>under the twilight of Lurien that we  love; for  we  put the thought of  all 
line 22619=>that we love into all that  we make. Yet they  are garments, not armour, and 
line 22620=>they  will not turn shaft or blade. But they should serve you well: they are 
line 22621=>light to wear, and warm enough  or cool enough at  need.  And  you will find 
line 22622=>them a great aid in keeping out of the sight of unfriendly eyes, whether you  
line 22623=>
line 22624=>####-walk among the stones or the trees. You are indeed high in the favour of the 
line 22625=>Lady! For she herself and her maidens wove this stuff; and never before have 
line 22626=>we clad strangers in the garb of our own people.' 
line 22627=>     After  their morning meal the Company said farewell to  the lawn by the 
line 22628=>fountain.  Their  hearts  were  heavy;  for it was a fair  place, and it had 
line 22629=>become like home to  them,  though they could not count the days and  nights 
line 22630=>that they had passed there. As they stood for a moment looking at the  white 
line 22631=>water in the sunlight, Haldir came walking towards them over the green grass 
line 22632=>of the glade. Frodo greeted him with delight. 
line 22633=>     'I have  returned from the  Northern  Fences,'  said the Elf, `and I am 
line 22634=>sent  now  to be your guide again.  The Dimrill Dale is  full of vapour  and 
line 22635=>clouds of  smoke,  and the  mountains are troubled. There are noises in  the 
line 22636=>deeps  of the  earth. If any of you had thought  of returning northwards  to 
line 22637=>your homes, you would not have been able to pass  that  way. But come!  Your 
line 22638=>path now goes south.' 
line 22639=>     As they walked through Caras Galadhon the green ways were empty; but in 
line 22640=>the trees above them many voices were murmuring and singing. They 
line 22641=>themselves 
line 22642=>went  silently. At last Haldir  led them down the  southward  slopes  of the 
line 22643=>hill, and they came again  to  the great  gate hung with  lamps, and to  the 
line 22644=>white  bridge; and so they  passed out and left the city of the Elves.  Then 
line 22645=>they turned  away from the paved road  and took  a path that went off into a  
line 22646=>deep  thicket  of  mallorn-trees,  and passed  on,  winding through  rolling 
line 22647=>woodlands  of  silver  shadow,  leading   them  ever  down,  southwards  and 
line 22648=>eastwards, towards the shores of the River. 
line 22649=>     They had gone  some ten miles and noon  was at hand when they came on a  
line 22650=>high green  wall. Passing through  an opening they came  suddenly out of the 
line 22651=>trees. Before them  lay a  long  lawn of shining grass, studded  with golden 
line 22652=>elanor  that  glinted  in the sun.  The lawn ran  out  into a narrow  tongue 
line 22653=>between  bright margins:  on  the  right  and  west  the  Silverlode  flowed 
line 22654=>glittering; on the left and  east the Great River  rolled its broad  waters, 
line 22655=>deep and  dark.  On  the  further  shores the  woodlands  still  marched  on 
line 22656=>southwards as far as the eye could see, but  all the banks  were  bleak  and 
line 22657=>bare. No mallorn lifted its gold-hung boughs beyond the Land of Lurien. 
line 22658=>     On  the bank of the Silverlode, at some distance up from the meeting of 
line 22659=>the  streams,  there was a hythe of white stones and  white wood. By it were 
line 22660=>moored many boats and  barges.  Some were  brightly painted, and shone  with 
line 22661=>
line 22662=>####-silver and gold  and green, but most were either  white or grey. Three small 
line 22663=>grey boats had been made ready for  the travellers, and  in  these the Elves 
line 22664=>stowed their goods. And they added  also coils of rope, three  to each boat. 
line 22665=>Slender they looked, but strong,  silken  to the touch, grey of hue like the 
line 22666=>elven-cloaks.  
line 22667=>     `What  are  these?  '  asked  Sam,  handling  one  that  lay  upon  the 
line 22668=>greensward. 
line 22669=>     `Ropes indeed! ' answered an Elf  from the  boats.  'Never  travel  far 
line 22670=>without  a rope! And one that is long and strong and light. Such  are these. 
line 22671=>They may be a help in many needs.' 
line 22672=>     'You don't  need to  tell me  that! ' said Sam. `I came without any and 
line 22673=>I've been worried ever since. But I was wondering  what these  were made of,  
line 22674=>knowing a bit about rope -making: it's in the family as you might say.' 
line 22675=>     `They are made of hithlain ,' said the Elf, `but there is no time now to 
line 22676=>instruct  you  in  the  art of their making. Had we  known that  this  craft  
line 22677=>delighted  you, we  could  have taught  you  much. But  now alas! unless you 
line 22678=>should at some time return hither, you must be content with our gift. May it 
line 22679=>serve you well! ' 
line 22680=>     `Come! ' said Haldir.  `All is now ready  for you. Enter the boats! But 
line 22681=>take care at first! ' 
line 22682=>     'Heed the words! ' said the other  Elves. 'These boats are light-built, 
line 22683=>and they are crafty and  unlike the boats of other folk. They will not sink, 
line 22684=>lade them as you will; but they are wayward if mishandled. It would be  wise 
line 22685=>if you accustomed yourselves to stepping  in and out,  here where there is a  
line 22686=>landing-place, before you set off downstream.' 
line 22687=>     The Company  was  arranged in this way: Aragorn, Frodo, and Sam were in 
line 22688=>one boat; Boromir,  Merry,  and Pippin  in another; and  in the  third  were 
line 22689=>Legolas and Gimli, who  had now become fast friends. In this last boat  most 
line 22690=>of  the goods and packs were  stowed. The boats were moved and  steered with 
line 22691=>short-handled paddles that had broad leaf-shaped blades. When all  was ready 
line 22692=>Aragorn led them  on a trial up  the Silverlode. The current  was  swift and 
line 22693=>they went  forward slowly. Sam sat  in the  bows,  clutching the  sides, and 
line 22694=>looking back wistfully to  the  shore. The sunlight  glittering on the water  
line 22695=>dazzled his eyes.  As they passed beyond the green field of the Tongue,  the 
line 22696=>trees  drew down to the  river's  brink. Here and there golden lea ves tossed 
line 22697=>and floated on the  rippling stream.  The air was very bright and still, and 
line 22698=>there was a silence, except for the high distant song of larks. 
line 22699=>
line 22700=>####-     They turned a sharp bend in  the river, and there, sailing proudly down 
line 22701=>the stream toward them, they saw a  swan of great size. The water rippled on  
line 22702=>either  side of the white  breast beneath its curving neck. Its  beak  shone 
line 22703=>like burnished gold, and its eyes glinted like jet set in yellow stones; its 
line 22704=>huge white wings  were half lifted.  A music came down the river as it  drew 
line 22705=>nearer; and suddenly they perceived that it was  a ship, wrought  and carved 
line 22706=>with elven-skill in the likeness of  a bird. Two elves clad in white steered 
line 22707=>it  with  black paddles. In the midst of the vessel sat Celeborn, and behind 
line 22708=>him  stood Galadriel, tall and white; a circlet of golden flowers was in her  
line 22709=>hair, and in her hand she held a harp, and  she sang. Sad and  sweet was the 
line 22710=>sound of her voice in the cool clear air: 
line 22711=>     I sang of leaves, of leaves of gold, and leaves of gold  there grew:  
line 22712=>     Of wind I sang, a wind there came and in the branches blew.  
line 22713=>     Beyond the Sun, beyond the Moon, the foam was on the Sea, 
line 22714=>     And by the strand of Ilmarin there grew a golden Tree. 
line 22715=>     Beneath the stars of Ever-eve in Eldamar it shone, 
line 22716=>     In Eldamar beside the walls of Elven Tirion. 
line 22717=>     There long the golden leaves have grown upon the branching years, 
line 22718=>     While here beyond the Sundering Seas now fall the Elven-tears. 
line 22719=>     O Lurien! The Winter comes, the bare and leafless Day; 
line 22720=>     The leaves are falling in the stream, the River flows away. 
line 22721=>     O Lurien! Too long I have dwelt upon this Hither Shore 
line 22722=>     And in a fading crown have twined the golden elanor. 
line 22723=>     But if of ships I now should sing, what ship would come to me, 
line 22724=>     What ship would bear me ever back across so wide a Sea? 
line 22725=>     Aragorn stayed his boat as the Swan-ship drew alongside. The Lady ended 
line 22726=>her  song and greeted them. `We have come to bid you our last farewell,' she 
line 22727=>said, `and to speed you with blessings from our land . ' 
line 22728=>     `Though  you have  been our guests,'  said Celeborn, `you have  not yet 
line 22729=>eaten with  us, and we  bid you, therefore, to a parting feast, here between 
line 22730=>the flowing waters that will bear you far from Lurien.' 
line 22731=>     The Swan passed on slowly to the hythe, and they turned their boats and 
line 22732=>followed it. There in the last  end  of  Egladil  upon  the  green grass the 
line 22733=>parting feast was held;  but Frodo ate  and drank  little,  heeding only the 
line 22734=>beauty of the Lady and her voice. She seemed no longer perilous or terrible,  
line 22735=>nor  filled with hidden power. Already she seemed to him, as by men of later 
line 22736=>days Elves still  at times are seen: present and yet remote, a living vision 
line 22737=>
line 22738=>####-of that  which has already been left far behind by  the  flowing  streams of 
line 22739=>Time. 
line 22740=>     After they had eaten and drunk,  sitting upon the grass, Celeborn spoke 
line 22741=>to them again of their journey, and lifting his hand he pointed south to the 
line 22742=>woods beyond the Tongue. 
line 22743=>     `As you go down the water,' he said, `you will find that the trees will 
line 22744=>fail, and you  will come to a barren country. There the River flows in stony 
line 22745=>vale amid  high moors, until at last after many leagues it comes to the tall 
line 22746=>island  of the Tindrock,  that we call Tol Brandir. There it casts its  arms 
line 22747=>about the steep shores of the  isle, and falls then  with a  great noise and 
line 22748=>smoke  over the cataracts of Rauros down into the Nindalf, the Wetwang as it 
line 22749=>is called in your  tongue.  That  is a wide region of sluggish fen where the 
line 22750=>stream becomes tortuous and much divided. There the Entwash flows in by 
line 22751=>many 
line 22752=>mouths from the Forest of  Fangorn  in the west. About that stream, on  this 
line 22753=>side of the Great River, lies Rohan. On the further side are the bleak hills 
line 22754=>of the Emyn Muil. The wind blows from the East there, for they look out over  
line 22755=>the Dead Marshes and the Noman-lands to Cirith Gorgor and the black gates of 
line 22756=>Mordor. 
line 22757=>     'Boromir, and any  that go with him seeking  Minas Tirith, will do well 
line 22758=>to leave the Great River  above Rauros and cross the Entwash before it finds 
line 22759=>the marshes.  Yet  they  should  not  go too far  up  that  stream, nor risk  
line 22760=>becoming entangled in the  Forest of Fangorn. That is a strange land, and is 
line 22761=>now  little  known. But  Boromir  and Aragorn  doubtless  do  not  need this 
line 22762=>warning.' 
line 22763=>     'Indeed we have heard  of Fangorn in  Minas Tirith,' said Boromir. `But 
line 22764=>what I have heard seems to me for the most part old wives' tales, such as we  
line 22765=>tell to our children. All that lies north of Rohan is now  to us so far away 
line 22766=>that fancy can wander freely there. Of old Fangorn lay  upon the  borders of 
line 22767=>our realm; but it is now many lives of men since  any of  us  visited it, to 
line 22768=>prove or disprove the legends that have come down from distant years. 
line 22769=>     `I have myself  been at whiles in Rohan, but I have  never  crossed  it 
line 22770=>northwards. When I  was sent out as a messenger, I passed through the Gap by 
line 22771=>the skirts  of the White Mountains,  and crossed the Isen  and the Greyflood  
line 22772=>into Northerland.  A  long and wearisome  journey.  Four  hundred  leagues I 
line 22773=>reckoned it, and it took me many  months; for  I lost my horse at Tharbad, at 
line 22774=>the fording  of  the  Greyflood. After that  journey,  and  the road  I have 
line 22775=>
line 22776=>####-trodden  with  this Company, I  do  not much doubt  that I shall find a  way 
line 22777=>through Rohan, and Fangorn too, if need be.' 
line 22778=>     `Then  I need say no more,' said Celeborn. 'But do not despise the lore 
line 22779=>that has come down from distant years; for oft it may chance  that old wives 
line 22780=>keep in memory word of things that once were needful for the wise to know.' 
line 22781=>     Now Galadriel rose  from the grass, and taking a  cup  from one  of her  
line 22782=>maidens she filled it with white mead and gave it to Celeborn. 
line 22783=>     'Now it is time  to drink the cup of  farewell,' she said. `Drink, Lord 
line 22784=>of  the Galadhrim!  And let not your heart be  sad though night  must follow 
line 22785=>noon, and already our evening draweth nigh.' 
line 22786=>     Then  she brought  the  cup to each of the Company, and bade them drink  
line 22787=>and farewell. But when they had drunk she commanded them to sit again on the 
line 22788=>grass,  and  chairs were set  for her and  for Celeborn.  Her maidens   stood 
line 22789=>silent about her, and a while  she looked upon her guests. At last she spoke 
line 22790=>again. 
line 22791=>     'We have drunk  the cup of  parting,' she  said, `and the  shadows fall 
line 22792=>between us. But  before you go,  I have brought in  my ship gifts  which the 
line 22793=>Lord and Lady of the Galadhrim now offer  you in memory of Lothlurien.' 
line 22794=>Then 
line 22795=>she called to each in turn. 
line 22796=>     `Here is  the gift  of Celeborn  and  Galadriel to the  leader  of your 
line 22797=>Company,' she  said to Aragorn, and she gave him a sheath that had been made 
line 22798=>to fit his sword.  It was  overlaid  with  a  tracery of flowers  and leaves 
line 22799=>wrought of silver and gold, and on it were set in elven runes formed of many 
line 22800=>gems the name AndÂ®ril and the lineage of the sword. 
line 22801=>     `The  blade  that  is  drawn from  this  sheath shall  not be stained or  
line 22802=>broken  even in  defeat,' she said. `But is there aught else that you desire 
line 22803=>of me at our parting? For  darkness will flow between us, and it may be that 
line 22804=>we shall  not meet  again, unless it be far  hence upon  a  road that has no 
line 22805=>returning.' 
line 22806=>     And Aragorn answered: 'Lady, you know  all my desire, and  long held in 
line 22807=>keeping the only  treasure that I seek. Yet it is not yours to give me, even 
line 22808=>if you would; and only through darkness shall I come to it.' 
line 22809=>     `Yet maybe this will lighten  your heart,' said Galadriel;  `for it was 
line 22810=>left in my care to be given to you, should you pass through this land.' Then 
line 22811=>she lifted from  her lap  a  great stone  of a clear green, set in  a silver  
line 22812=>brooch that  was wrought in the likeness of an eagle with  outspread  wings;  
line 22813=>
line 22814=>####-and as  she held  it  up  the gem flashed  like the sun shining through  the 
line 22815=>leaves  of spring. `This  stone I  gave to Celebrnan my daughter, and she to 
line 22816=>hers; and now it comes to you as a token of hope. In this hour take the name 
line 22817=>that was foretold for you, Elessar, the Elfstone of the house of Elendil! ' 
line 22818=>     Then Aragorn took  the stone and pinned the brooch upon his breast, and 
line 22819=>those  who  saw  him wondered; for they  had  not marked before how tall and 
line 22820=>kingly  he stood, and it seemed to  them that many years of toil  had  fallen 
line 22821=>from his shoulders. `For the  gifts that you have  given me I thank you,' he 
line 22822=>said, 'O Lady of  Lurien of whom were sprung Celebrnan  and Arwen  
line 22823=>Evenstar. 
line 22824=>What praise could I say more? ' 
line 22825=>     The Lady bowed her hea d, and she turned then to Boromir, and to him she 
line 22826=>gave a belt of gold; and to  Merry  and Pippin  she gave small silver belts, 
line 22827=>each  with a  clasp wrought like a golden flower. To Legolas she  gave a bow 
line 22828=>such as  the Galadhrim used,  longer and  stouter than the bows of Mirkwood, 
line 22829=>and strung with a string of elf-hair. With it went a quiver of arrows.  
line 22830=>     `For you little gardener and lover of trees,' she said to  Sam, `I have 
line 22831=>only a small gift.' She put into his hand a little box of plain  grey  wood, 
line 22832=>unadorned save for  a single silver rune upon the lid.  `Here  is set  G for  
line 22833=>Galadriel,' she said; `but  also it may stand  for garden in your tongue. In 
line 22834=>this box there is earth from my orchard, and such blessing  as Galadriel has 
line 22835=>still to bestow  is upon it. It will not keep  you on your  road, nor defend 
line 22836=>you  against any peril; but if you keep it and see your  home again at last, 
line 22837=>then perhaps it may reward  you.  Though you should find all barren and laid 
line 22838=>waste, there will be  few gardens in  Middle-earth that will bloom like your 
line 22839=>garden, if you sprinkle this earth there. Then you may  remember  Galadriel, 
line 22840=>and catch a glimpse  far off  of Lurien,  that you  have  seen  only  in our 
line 22841=>winter.  For our spring and our summer are gone  by,  and they will never be 
line 22842=>seen  on earth again save in memory.' 
line 22843=>     Sam  went  red  to  the  ears  and muttered something inaudible, as  he 
line 22844=>clutched the box and bowed as well as he could. 
line 22845=>     `And what gift would a Dwarf ask of the Elves? ' said Galadriel turning 
line 22846=>to Gimli. 
line 22847=>     `None,   Lady,' answered Gimli. `It is  enough for  me  to have seen the 
line 22848=>Lady of the Galadhrim, and to have heard her gentle words.' 
line 22849=>     `Hear all ye Elves! ' she cried to those about her. `Let none say again 
line 22850=>that Dwarves  are grasping  and ungracious! Yet surely, Gimli son of  Gluin, 
line 22851=>
line 22852=>####-you desire something that I could give? Name it, I bid you! You shall not be 
line 22853=>the only guest without a gift.' 
line 22854=>     `There  is  nothing,  Lady  Galadriel,'  said  Gimli,  bowing  low  and 
line 22855=>stammering. `Nothing, unless it might be-unless it is permitted to ask. nay, 
line 22856=>to name a single strand of your hair, which  surpasses the gold of the earth 
line 22857=>as the stars surpass the gems of the mine. I do not ask for such a gift. But 
line 22858=>you commanded me to name my desire.' 
line 22859=>     The Elves stirred and murmured with astonishment, and Celeborn gazed at 
line 22860=>the Dwarf in wonder, but the Lady smiled. 'It is said that the  skill of the 
line 22861=>Dwarves is in their hands rather than in their tongues ' she said; `yet that 
line 22862=>is not true of Gimli. For  none have ever  made to me a request  so bold and 
line 22863=>yet so  courteous. And  how shall I  refuse, since I commanded him to speak? 
line 22864=>But tell me, what would you do with such a gift? ' 
line 22865=>     `Treasure it, Lady,' he answered, `in memory of your words to me at our 
line 22866=>first meeting. And if ever I return to the  smithies of my home, it shall be 
line 22867=>set in imperishable crystal to  be an heirloom of my house, and a  pledge of 
line 22868=>good will between the Mountain and the Wood until the end of days.' 
line 22869=>     Then the  Lady unbraided  one  of her long tresses, and  cut o ff  three 
line 22870=>golden hairs, and laid them in Gimli's hand. `These words shall  go with the 
line 22871=>gift,' she said. `I do not foretell, for all foretelling is now vain: on the 
line 22872=>one hand lies darkness, and on the other only hope. But if  hope  should not 
line 22873=>fail, then I sa y to you, Gimli son of Gluin, that your hands shall flow with 
line 22874=>gold, and yet over you gold shall have no dominion. 
line 22875=>     `And you, Ring-bearer,' she said, turning to Frodo. `I come to you last 
line 22876=>who are not last in my thoughts. For you I have prepared  this.'  She held up 
line 22877=>a small crystal phial: it glittered as she moved it, and rays of white light 
line 22878=>sprang from  her hand.  'In this  phial,' she said, `is  caught the light of 
line 22879=>Edrendil's  star,  set amid  the  waters of my fountain. It will shine still 
line 22880=>brighter when night is  about you. May it be a  light to you in dark places, 
line 22881=>when all other lights go out. Remember Galadriel and her Mirror! ' 
line 22882=>     Frodo took the phial, and for a moment as it shone between them, he saw 
line 22883=>her  again  standing  like a  queen,  great and  beautiful,  but  no  longer  
line 22884=>terrible. He bowed, but found no words to say. 
line 22885=>     Now the Lady arose, and Celeborn led them back to  the  hythe. A yellow 
line 22886=>noon lay  on the  green land  of  the Tongue, and  the water  glittered with 
line 22887=>silver. All at last was  made  ready. The Company took  their places in  the 
line 22888=>boats as  before. Crying farewell, the Elves of Lurien with long  grey poles 
line 22889=>
line 22890=>####-thrust them out into the flowing stream, and  the rippling waters bore  them 
line 22891=>slowly  away. The  travellers  sat still  without moving or speaking. On the 
line 22892=>green  bank near to the very point  of the Tongue  the  Lady Galadriel stood 
line 22893=>alone and silent. As they passed her they  turned and their eyes watched her  
line 22894=>slowly  floating away  from  them.  For  so it seemed  to  them:  Lurien was 
line 22895=>slipping  backward, like a bright ship masted with enchanted trees,  sailing 
line 22896=>on to forgotten shores, while they sat  helpless upon the margin of the grey 
line 22897=>and leafless world. 
line 22898=>     Even as they gazed,  the Silverlode passed out into the currents of the 
line 22899=>Great River, and their boats turned  and began to speed southwards. Soon the 
line 22900=>white form of the Lady  was small and  distant. She  shone like a window  of 
line 22901=>glass  upon a far hill in the westering sun, or as a remote lake seen from a  
line 22902=>mountain: a  crystal fallen in the lap of the land. Then  it seemed to Frodo 
line 22903=>that she lifted her arms in a  final farewell, and far but piercing-clear on 
