line 22944=>     The travellers  now  turned their faces  to  the journey;  the  sun was 
line 22945=>before  them, and their  eyes were dazzled, for all were  filled with tears. 
line 22946=>Gimli wept openly. 
line 22947=>     `I have  looked  the  last  upon that which was  fairest,' he  said  to 
line 22948=>Legolas his companion. `Henceforward I will call  nothing fair, unless it be 
line 22949=>her gift.' He put his hand to his breast. 
line 22950=>     `Tell me,  Legolas, why  did I  come on this Quest?  Little did I  know 
line 22951=>where  the  chief peril  lay!  Truly Elrond spoke, saying that we  could not 
line 22952=>foresee what we might meet upon our road. Torment in the dark was the danger 
line 22953=>that I feared, and it did not hold me back. But I would not have come, had I 
line 22954=>known the  danger of light and joy. Now I have taken my worst wound in  this 
line 22955=>parting, even if I were to go this night straight to the Dark Lord. Alas for 
line 22956=>Gimli son of Gluin! ' 
line 22957=>     `Nay! ' said Legolas. `Alas for us all! And for all that walk the world 
line 22958=>in these after -days. For  such is the  way of  it:  to find and lose,  as it 
line 22959=>seems to those whose boat is on the running stream. But I count you blessed, 
line 22960=>Gimli son of Gluin: for your loss you suffer of your own  free will, and you  
line 22961=>might have chosen otherwise. But you have not forsaken  your companions, 
line 22962=>and 
line 22963=>the least reward that you shall have is that  the memory of Lothlurien shall 
line 22964=>remain ever clear  and unstained in your heart, and  shall neither  fade nor  
line 22965=>
line 22966=>####-grow stale.' 
line 22967=>     `Maybe,' said  Gimli;  `and  I  thank you  for  your words.  True words 
line 22968=>doubtless; yet all  such  comfort  is cold.  Memory  is not  what  the heart 
line 22969=>desires. That is only a mirror, be it clear as Kheled-zvram. Or  so says the 
line 22970=>heart  of Gimli  the Dwarf. Elves  may see  things otherwise.  Indeed I have 
line 22971=>heard that for them memory is more like to the waking world than to a dream. 
line 22972=>Not so for Dwarves.  
line 22973=>     'But let us talk no more of it. Look to the boat! She is too low in the 
line 22974=>water with all this baggage, and  the Great River is swift. I do not wish to 
line 22975=>drown my grief in cold water.' He took up  a paddle, and steered towards the 
line 22976=>western bank, following Aragorn's boat ahead, which had already moved out of 
line 22977=>the middle stream. 
line 22978=>     So the  Company went on their long way, down the wide  hurrying waters,  
line 22979=>borne ever  southwards. Bare woods stalked along either bank, and they could 
line 22980=>not see any glimpse of the lands behind. The breeze died  away and the River 
line 22981=>flowed without a sound. No voice  of  bird broke the silence.  The  sun grew 
line 22982=>misty as the day grew old, until it gleamed in a pale sky  like a high white 
line 22983=>pearl. Then it faded into the West, and dusk came  early, followed by a grey 
line 22984=>and  starless night. Far into the dark quiet hours they  floated on, guiding 
line 22985=>their boats under the overhanging shadows  of the western woods. Great trees 
line 22986=>passed  by like ghosts, thrusting their twisted thirsty  roots  through  the 
line 22987=>mist down into the water. It was dreary and cold. Frodo sat and  listened to 
line 22988=>the  faint lap and  gurgle  of  the River fretting among the  tree-roots and 
line 22989=>driftwood near the shore, until  his  head nodded and he fell into an uneasy 
line 22990=>sleep. 
