line 22995=>Chapter 9. The Great River 
line 22996=>
line 22997=> 
line 22998=> 
line 22999=>     Frodo  was roused  by Sam. He found  that  he was  lying, well wrapped,  
line 23000=>under tall grey-skinned trees in a quiet corner of the woodlands on the west 
line 23001=>bank of the  Great River, Anduin. He had slept the night  away, and the grey 
line 23002=>of morning was dim among the bare branches. Gimli was busy with a small fire 
line 23003=>near at hand. 
line 23004=>     They started  again  before   the day  was broad.  Not that most of  the 
line 23005=>Company were eager to hurry southwards: they were content that the decision, 
line 23006=>which they must make at  latest  when they came  to  Rauros and the Tindrock  
line 23007=>Isle, still lay some days ahead; and they let the River  bear them on at its 
line 23008=>own  pace,  having no desire to hasten  towards  the perils that lay beyond, 
line 23009=>whichever course they  took in  the end. Aragorn  let  them  drift with  the 
line 23010=>stream as they wished, husbanding their  strength against weariness to come.  
line 23011=>But he insisted that at least they should  start early  each day and journey 
line 23012=>on  far into the evening; for he felt  in his heart that  time was pressing, 
line 23013=>and he  feared that the Dark Lord  had not been idle while  they lingered in 
line 23014=>Lurien. 
line 23015=>     Nonetheless  they saw no sign of  an enemy that  day, nor the next. The 
line 23016=>dull grey hours passed without event. As the third  day of their voyage wore 
line 23017=>on the lands changed slowly: the trees  thinned and  then failed altogether. 
line 23018=>On  the eastern bank to their left  they saw long formless slopes stretching 
line 23019=>up and away toward the sky; brown and withered they  looked, as  if fire had 
line 23020=>passed  over them, leaving no  living  blade of green:  an  unfriendly waste 
line 23021=>without even a broken tree or a  bold  stone to relieve the  emptiness. They 
line 23022=>had come to  the Brown Lands  that lay, vast and  desolate, between Southern 
line 23023=>Mirkwood and the hills of the Emyn Muil. What pestilence or war or evil deed 
line 23024=>of the Enemy had so blasted all that region even Aragorn could not tell. 
line 23025=>     Upon the west to their  right the land was treeless  also,  but it  was 
line 23026=>flat, and  in many places green  with wide plains of grass. On this side  of 
line 23027=>the River they passed forests of great reeds, so tall that they shut out all 
line 23028=>view to  the  west,  as  the  little  boats  went   rustling by  along  their 
line 23029=>fluttering borders. Their dark withered plumes bent and tossed in  the light 
line 23030=>cold airs, hissing softly and sadly. Here and there through  openings  Frodo 
line 23031=>could catch sudden  glimpses of rolling meads, and far  beyond them hills in 
line 23032=>
line 23033=>####-the  sunset, and  away on  the edge of sight a dark line, where marched  the 
line 23034=>southernmost ranks of the Misty Mountains.  
line 23035=>     There was no sign of living moving  things,  save birds. Of these there 
line 23036=>were many: small  fowl whistling  and  piping in  the reeds,  but  they were 
line 23037=>seldom seen.  Once  or  twice the  travellers  heard  the rush  and whine of 
line 23038=>swan-wings, and looking up they saw a great phalanx streaming along the sky. 
line 23039=>     `Swans! ' said Sam. `And mighty big ones too! ' 
line 23040=>     `Yes,' said Aragorn, 'and they are black swans.' 
line 23041=>     `How wide and empty and mournful all this country looks! '  said Frodo.  
line 23042=>`I  always imagined  that as one journeyed  south it got warmer and merrier,  
line 23043=>until winter was left behind for ever.' 
line 23044=>     'But we  have not journeyed  far south yet,'  answered Aragorn. `It  is 
line 23045=>still winter, and we are far from the sea. Here the world  is cold until the 
line 23046=>sudden spring, and we  may yet have snow again. Far away down in the Bay  of 
line 23047=>Belfalas, to which Anduin runs, it is warm and merry, maybe, or would be but 
line 23048=>for the  Enemy. But here we are  not above sixty  leagues, I guess, south of 
line 23049=>the Southfarthing away in your Shire, hundreds of long miles yonder. You are 
line 23050=>looking now south-west across the north  plains of the Riddermark, Rohan the 
line 23051=>land of the Horse-lords. Ere long we shall come to the mouth of the Limlight 
line 23052=>that runs  down from Fangorn to join  the  Great  River. That  is  the north 
line 23053=>boundary  of Rohan; and  of old all that lay between  Limlight and the White 
line 23054=>Mountains belonged to the Rohirrim. It  is a rich and pleasant land, and its 
line 23055=>grass has no rival; but in these evil days folk do not dwell by the River or  
line 23056=>ride often  to its shores.  Anduin  is  wide, yet  the orcs  can shoot their 
line 23057=>arrows  far across  the stream; and of late, it is said,  they have dared to 
line 23058=>cross the water and raid the herds and studs of Rohan.' 
line 23059=>     Sam looked from bank to  bank  uneasily. The trees had  seemed  hostile 
line 23060=>before, as if they harboured secret eyes and  lurking dangers; now he wished  
line 23061=>that  the trees were still  there. He felt  that the  Company was too naked, 
line 23062=>afloat in  little open  boats  in  the midst of shelterless  lands, and on a  
line 23063=>river that was the frontier of war. 
line 23064=>     In  the  next day  or two, as they went on, borne  steadily southwards, 
line 23065=>this feeling  of insecurity grew  on  all the Company. For  a whole day they 
line 23066=>took to  their  paddles  and  hastened forward. The banks  slid by. Soon the 
line 23067=>River broadened and grew more shallow; long stony beaches lay upon the east, 
line 23068=>and  there were  gravel-shoals  in  the water, so that  careful steering was 
line 23069=>needed. The Brown Lands rose into bleak wolds, over which flowed a chill air 
line 23070=>
line 23071=>####-from  the  East. On  the  other  side the meads had  become rolling downs of 
line 23072=>withered grass amidst a land of fen and tussock. Frodo shivered, thinking of 
line 23073=>the lawns and fountains, the clear sun and gentle rains of Lothlurien. There 
line 23074=>was little speech and  no laughter  in any of  the boats. Each member of the 
line 23075=>Company was busy with his own thoughts.  
line 23076=>     The heart of  Legolas was running under  the stars of a summer night in 
line 23077=>some  northern glade amid  the beech-woods; Gimli  was fingering gold in his 
line 23078=>mind, and wondering if it were  fit to be  wrought into the  housing  of the 
line 23079=>Lady's gift.  Merry and  Pippin in the middle  boat  were  ill at  ease, for  
line 23080=>Boromir sat muttering  to himself, sometimes biting his nails,  as  if  some 
line 23081=>restlessness or doubt consumed him, sometimes  seizing a paddle and  driving 
line 23082=>the boat  close behind Aragorn's. Then Pippin, who sat  in  the bow  looking 
line 23083=>back, caught a queer gleam in his eye, as he peered forward gazing at Frodo.  
line 23084=>Sam had  long  ago  made up his mind  that,  though boats were maybe  not as 
line 23085=>dangerous  as  he  had been  brought  up  to  believe,  they were  far  more 
line 23086=>uncomfortable  than even  he had  imagined. He was   cramped  and  miserable, 
line 23087=>having nothing to do but stare at the winter -lands crawling by and the  grey 
line 23088=>water on either side of him. Even when the paddles were in use they  did not 
line 23089=>trust Sam with one. 
line 23090=>     As dusk drew down on the fourth day, he was looking back over the bowed 
line 23091=>heads of Frodo and Aragorn and the following boats; he was drowsy and 
line 23092=>longed 
line 23093=>for camp and the feel of earth under his toes. Suddenly something caught his 
line 23094=>sight: at first he stared  at it listlessly, then  he sat  up and rubbed his 
line 23095=>eyes; but when he looked again he could not see it any more. 
line 23096=>     That night they camped  on a small eyot close to  the western bank. Sam 
line 23097=>lay rolled  in  blankets  beside Frodo. `I had a funny dream an hour or  two 
line 23098=>before we  stopped, Mr.  Frodo,' he said. `Or maybe it wasn't a dream. Funny 
line 23099=>it was anyway.' 
line 23100=>     `Well,  what was it? ' said  Frodo,  knowing that  Sam would not settle 
line 23101=>down until he had told his tale, whatever it was. 'I haven't seen or thought 
line 23102=>of anything to make me smile since we left Lothlurien.' 
line 23103=>     `It wasn't funny that way, Mr. Frodo.  It was  queer.  All wrong, if it 
line 23104=>wasn't a dream. And you had best hear it. It was like this: I saw a log with 
line 23105=>eyes!  ' 
line 23106=>     `The log's  all right,' said Frodo.  `There are  many in the River. But 
line 23107=>leave out the eyes!  ' 
line 23108=>
line 23109=>####-     `That I won't,'  said Sam. ` 'Twas  the eyes as made me sit  up,  so to 
line 23110=>speak. I saw what I took to be a log floating along in the half-light behind 
line 23111=>Gimli's boat; but I didn't  give much heed to it. Then  it seemed as if  the 
line 23112=>log  was slowly  catching us  up. And  that  was peculiar, as you might say, 
line 23113=>seeing as we were all  floating on  the stream together. Just then I saw the 
line 23114=>eyes: two pale sort of points, shiny-like, on a hump at the  near end of the 
line 23115=>log. What's  more, it  wasn't a  log, for it had  paddle-feet, like a swan's 
line 23116=>almost, only they seemed bigger, and kept dipping in and out of the water. 
line 23117=>     'That's when  I sat right up  and rubbed  my  eyes,  meaning  to give a  
line 23118=>shout,  if  it was still there  when I had rubbed the drowse out of my head.  
line 23119=>For the whatever -it-was was coming along fast now and  getting close  behind 
line 23120=>Gimli. But whether those two lamps spotted me moving and staring, or whether 
line 23121=>I came to my senses, I don't know. When I looked again, it wasn't there. Yet  
line 23122=>I  think I caught a glimpse with  the tail  of-my eye, as the saying  is, of 
line 23123=>something dark shooting under the shadow of the bank. I couldn't see no more 
line 23124=>eyes though. 
line 23125=>     `I said to myself: "dreaming again, Sam Gamgee," I said: and  I said no 
line 23126=>more just then. But  I've been  thinking since. and now I'm not so sure. What 
line 23127=>do you make of it, Mr. Frodo? ' 
line 23128=>     'I  should make nothing of it  but a log and the dusk and sleep in your 
line 23129=>eyes Sam, said  Frodo, if this was the  first  time that those eyes had been 
line 23130=>seen. But it isn't. I saw them away back north before we reached Lurien. And 
line 23131=>I saw  a strange creature with eyes climbing to the  flet that night. Haldir 
line 23132=>saw it too. And do you remember the report of the  Elves that went after the  
line 23133=>orc-band?  ' 
line 23134=>     `Ah,'  said  Sam. `I  do;  and  I remember  more too.  I don't  like my 
line 23135=>thoughts; but thinking of one thing and another, and Mr. Bilbo's stories and 
line 23136=>all, I fancy I  could put a name on the creature,  at a guess. A nasty name. 
line 23137=>Gollum, maybe?  ' 
line 23138=>     `Yes, that  is what  I  have feared for  some  time,' said  Frodo. `Ever  
line 23139=>since  the night on the flet. I suppose he was lurking in Moria, and  picked 
line 23140=>up our trail then;  but I hoped that our stay in Lurien would throw  him off 
line 23141=>the scent again. The miserable creature must  have  been hiding in the woods 
line 23142=>by the Silverlode, watching us start off! ' 
line 23143=>     `That's about it,'  said Sam. `And  we'd better be a  bit more watchful 
line 23144=>ourselves,  or we'll  feel some  nasty fingers  round our necks one of these 
line 23145=>nights, if we ever wake up to feel anything. And   that's what I  was leading 
line 23146=>
line 23147=>####-up to. No need to trouble  Strider or the others tonight. I'll keep watch. I 
line 23148=>can sleep tomorrow, being no more than luggage in a boat, as you might say.' 
line 23149=>     `I might,' said Frodo, `and I might say "luggage with eyes".  You shall 
line 23150=>watch; but only if  you promise  to  wake me  halfway  towards  morning,  if 
line 23151=>nothing happens before then.' 
line 23152=>     In the  dead hours Frodo came out  of a  deep dark  sleep  to find  Sam 
