line 23470=>made the journey, before all was brought safe to the southern landing. 
line 23471=>     There the portage-way, turning back  to the water -side, ran gently down 
line 23472=>to the shallow edge of a little pool. It seemed to have been  scooped in the 
line 23473=>river -side, not by hand,  but by the  water  swirling  down  from Sarn Gebir 
line 23474=>against a low pier of  rock that jutted out some way into the stream. Beyond  
line 23475=>it the shore rose sheer into a grey  cliff, and there was no further passage 
line 23476=>for those on foot. 
line 23477=>     Already the short afternoon was past, and a dim cloudy dusk was closing 
line 23478=>in. They sat beside the water listening to the confused rush and roar of the 
line 23479=>Rapids hidden in the mist; they wer e tired and sleepy, and their hearts were 
line 23480=>as gloomy as the dying day. 
line 23481=>     'Well, here we are, and here we must pass another night,' said Boromir. 
line 23482=>`We need sleep, and even if Aragorn had a mind to pass the Gates of Argonath 
line 23483=>by night, we are all too tired-except, no doubt, our sturdy dwarf.' 
line 23484=>     Gimli made no reply: he was nodding as he sat. 
line 23485=>     `Let us rest as much  as  we can now,' said  Aragorn. `Tomorrow we must 
line 23486=>journey by day again. Unless the weather changes once more and cheats us, we 
line 23487=>shall have  a good chance  of slipping through, unseen  by any eyes  on  the 
line 23488=>
line 23489=>####-eastern shore. But tonight two must watch together in turns: three hours off 
line 23490=>and one on guard.' 
line 23491=>     Nothing happened that night  worse than a brief drizzle of rain an hour 
line 23492=>before dawn. As soon as it was fully light they started. Already the fog was 
line 23493=>thinning. They kept as  close as they could  to  the western  side, and they 
line 23494=>could see the dim shapes of the low cliffs rising ever higher, shadowy walls 
line 23495=>with  their  feet in the hurrying river. In the mid-morning the  clouds drew 
line 23496=>down  lower,  and it began to rain heavily. They drew  the  skin-covers over  
line 23497=>their boats to prevent them from being flooded, and drifted on: little could 
line 23498=>be seen before them or about them through the grey falling curtains. 
line 23499=>     The rain,  however, did  not  last  long.  Slowly  the  sky above  grew 
line 23500=>lighter,  and  then  suddenly the clouds broke,  and  their draggled fringes 
line 23501=>trailed away northward up the  River. The  fogs and mists were  gone. Before 
line 23502=>the travellers  lay  a wide ravine, with  great rocky sides to which  clung, 
line 23503=>upon  shelves  and in narrow crevices, a few thrawn  trees. The channel grew 
line 23504=>narrower and the River swifter. Now  they were speeding  along  with  little  
line 23505=>hope of stopping or turning, whatever they might meet ahead. Over them was a  
line 23506=>lane of pale-blue sky, around them  the dark overshadowed  River, and before 
line 23507=>them  black, shutting out  the  sun,  the hills of  Emyn Muil, in  which  no 
line 23508=>opening could be seen. 
line 23509=>     Frodo peering  forward saw in the distance two great rocks approaching:  
line 23510=>like  great pinnacles or pillars  of stone  they seemed.  Tall and sheer and 
line 23511=>ominous they stood upon either  side of the  stream. A  narrow  gap appeared 
line 23512=>between them, and the River swept the boats towards it. 
line 23513=>     `Behold the Argonath, the Pillars  of  the Kings! ' cried  Aragorn. `We 
line 23514=>shall pass them soon. Keep the boats  in  line, and as far apart as you can!  
line 23515=>Hold the middle of the stream! ' 
line 23516=>     As Frodo was  borne towards them the great  pillars rose like towers to 
line 23517=>meet  him.  Giants  they  seemed  to  him,  vast  grey  figures  silent  but 
line 23518=>threatening. Then  he saw that they were  indeed shaped and  fashioned:  the 
line 23519=>craft and power  of  old had  wrought  upon them,  and  still they preserved 
line 23520=>through the suns and rains of forgotten years the mighty likenesses in which 
line 23521=>they  had been hewn. Upon great pedestals founded  in the deep  waters stood 
line 23522=>two great kings  of stone: still with blurred eyes and  crannied  brows they 
line 23523=>frowned upon  the North. The left hand of each  was raised  palm outwards in 
line 23524=>gesture of  warning;  in each  right  hand there  was an axe; upon each head 
line 23525=>there  was a crumbling helm  and crown. Great  power and majesty they  still 
line 23526=>
line 23527=>####-wore, the silent wardens  of a long-vanished kingdom. Awe and fear fell upon 
line 23528=>Frodo,  and he  cowered down, shutting his eyes and not daring to look up as 
line 23529=>the boat drew  near. Even Boromir bowed  his head  as  the boats whirled by. 
line 23530=>frail and  fleeting  as little  leaves,  under  the  enduring  shadow of the 
line 23531=>sentinels of NÂ®menor. So they passed into the dark chasm of the Gates. 
line 23532=>     Sheer rose the dreadful cliffs to unguessed heights on either side. Far 
line 23533=>off was the dim sky. The black waters roared and echoed, and a wind screamed 
line 23534=>over them.  Frodo crouching over his knees heard Sam in front  muttering and 
line 23535=>groaning: `What a place! What a horrible place! Just let me get out of  this 
line 23536=>boat, and I'll never wet my toes in a puddle again, let alone a river! ' 
line 23537=>     `Fear  not! ' said a  strange voice behind him.  Frodo  turned and  saw 
line 23538=>Strider, and  yet  not Strider; for  the  weatherworn Ranger  was  no longer  
line 23539=>there.  In the  stern  sat Aragorn son of Arathorn, proud and erect, guiding 
line 23540=>the boat with skilful strokes; his hood was cast back, and his dark hair was 
line 23541=>blowing in the wind, a light was in his eyes:  a king returning from exile to 
line 23542=>his own land. 
line 23543=>     'Fear not!  ' he said. `Long have I desired to look upon the likenesses 
line 23544=>of  Isildur and Anbrion, my sires of old.  Under  their shadow  Elessar, the 
line 23545=>Elfstone son of  Arathorn of the House  of  Valandil  Isildur's  son heir of 
line 23546=>Elendil, has nought to dread! ' 
line 23547=>     Then the light of  his eyes faded, and he spoke to himself: `Would that 
line 23548=>Gandalf were  here! How my  heart yearns  for Minas Anor and the walls of my 
line 23549=>own city! But whither now shall I go? ' 
line 23550=>     The  chasm was long and  dark,  and filled  with the noise of wind  and 
line 23551=>rushing water and echoing stone. It  bent somewhat  towards the west so that 
line 23552=>at first all was dark  ahead; but soon Frodo  saw a tall gap of light before 
line 23553=>him,  ever  growing.  Swiftly it  drew  near,  and  suddenly the  boats shot 
line 23554=>through, out into a wide clear light. 
line 23555=>     The sun, already long fallen from the noon, was shining in a windy sky. 
line 23556=>The pent  waters spread out into a long oval lake, pale  Nen Hithoel, fenced 
line 23557=>by  steep grey hills whose sides were clad with trees, but  their heads were 
line 23558=>bare,  cold-gleaming in  the sunlight. At  the far  southern end  rose three 
line 23559=>peaks.  The midmost stood somewhat forward from the others and sundered 
line 23560=>from 
line 23561=>them, an island  in the waters,  about  which   the flowing River  flung pale 
line 23562=>shimmering arms. Distant but deep there came up on the wind a  roaring sound 
line 23563=>like the roll of thunder heard far away. 
line 23564=>
line 23565=>####-     `Behold Tol Brandir! ' said Aragorn,  pointing south to  the tall peak. 
line 23566=>'Upon the left stands Amon Lhaw, and upon the right is Amon Hen the Hills of 
line 23567=>Hearing and of Sight. In the days  of the  great kings there were high seats 
line 23568=>upon  them, and watch was kept there. But it is said that no foot of  man or 
line 23569=>beast has ever been set upon Tol Brandir. Ere  the shade of  night  falls we 
line 23570=>shall come to them. I hear the endless voice of Rauros calling.' 
line 23571=>     The Company rested now for a while,  drifting south on the current that 
line 23572=>flowed through the middle  of  the lake. They  ate  some food, and then they 
line 23573=>took  to their paddles and  hastened on their way. The sides of the westward 
line 23574=>hills fell into shadow, and  the Sun  grew round and  red.  Here and there a  
line 23575=>misty  star peered out. The three peaks loomed before  them, darkling in the 
line 23576=>twilight. Rauros was roaring with a grea t voice.  Already  night was laid on 
line 23577=>the flowing waters when the travellers came at  last under the shadow of the 
line 23578=>hills. 
line 23579=>     The tenth  day of their journey  was over.  Wilderland was behind them. 
line 23580=>They could go no further without choice between the  east -way and  the west. 
line 23581=>The last stage of the Quest was before them. 
