line 23589=> 
line 23590=>     Aragorn led them to  the right  arm of the River. Here upon its western 
line 23591=>side under the shadow of Tol Brandir a green lawn ran down to the water from 
line 23592=>the feet of Amon Hen.  Behind it rose the first gentle  slopes  of  the hill 
line 23593=>clad with trees, and trees marched away westward along the curving shores of 
line 23594=>the lake. A little spring fell tumbling down and fed the grass.  
line 23595=>     'Here  we will rest tonight,' said Aragorn. `This is the lawn  of Parth 
line 23596=>Galen: a fair place in the summer days of old. Let us hope  that no evil has 
line 23597=>yet come here.' 
line 23598=>     They drew up their boats on the green banks, and  beside them they made  
line 23599=>their camp.  They set  a watch, but had no sight nor sound of their enemies.  
line 23600=>If Gollum had contrived  to follow  them,  he  remained  unseen and unheard. 
line 23601=>Nonetheless as the night  wore on Aragorn grew uneasy, tossing often in  his 
line 23602=>sleep and waking. In the small hours he got up and came to Frodo, whose turn 
line 23603=>it was to watch. 
line 23604=>     `Why are you waking? ' asked Frodo. `It is not your watch.' 
line 23605=>     `I do  not know,' answered Aragorn; `but a shadow and a threat has been 
line 23606=>growing in my sleep. It would be well to draw your sword.' 
line 23607=>     `Why? ' said Frodo. `Are enemies at hand? ' 
line 23608=>     `Let us see what Sting may show,' answered Aragorn. 
line 23609=>     Frodo  then drew the elf-blade from its sheath. To his dismay the edges 
line 23610=>gleamed  dimly in  the night. `Orcs! ' he said. `Not very  near, and yet too 
line 23611=>near, it seems.' 
line 23612=>     `I feared as much,' said Aragorn. `But maybe they are  not on this side 
line 23613=>of the River. The light of  Sting is faint, and it may point to no more than 
line 23614=>spies of Mordor  roaming on the  slopes  of  Amon  Lhaw.  I have never heard 
line 23615=>before of Orcs  upon Amon Hen. Yet who  knows what may happen in  these 
line 23616=>evil 
line 23617=>days, now  that Minas Tirith no longer holds secure the passages of  Anduin.  
line 23618=>We must go warily tomorrow.' 
line 23619=>     The day came like fire and smoke. Low in the East there were black bars 
line 23620=>of cloud  like the fumes of a great burning. The  rising  sun  lit them from 
line 23621=>beneath  with flames of  murky red; but  soon  it climbed above  them into a  
line 23622=>clear sky. The summit of Tol Brandir was tipped with  gold. Frodo looked out 
line 23623=>
line 23624=>####-eastward and  gazed at the tall island.  Its  si des  sprang sheer out of the 
line 23625=>running  water. High up above the  tall cliffs were  steep slopes upon which 
line 23626=>trees climbed, mounting  one  head above another; and  above them again were 
line 23627=>grey  faces of inaccessible rock, crowned by  a great spire  of  stone. Many 
line 23628=>birds were  circling  about it, but no sign of  other living things could be 
line 23629=>seen. 
line 23630=>     When they had eaten, Aragorn called the Company together. `The  day has 
line 23631=>come at last,' he said: 'the day of choice which we have  long delayed. What 
line 23632=>shall  now become  of our Company that has  travelled  so far in fellowship?  
line 23633=>Shall we turn  west with  Boromir and go to the wars of Gondor; or turn east  
line 23634=>to the Fear and Shadow; or shall we break our fellowship and go this way and 
line 23635=>that as each may choose? Whatever  we do  must  be done soon. We  cannot 
line 23636=>long 
line 23637=>halt here. The  enemy is on the eastern shore, we know; but I  fear that the 
line 23638=>Orcs may already be on this side of the water.' 
line 23639=>     There was a long silence in which no one spoke or moved. 
line 23640=>     'Well,  Frodo,'  said Aragorn at last. `I fear that  the burden is laid 
line 23641=>upon  you. You are the  Bearer  appointed by the  Council. Your  own way you  
line 23642=>alone  can choose. In this matter I cannot advise you. I am not Gandalf, and 
line 23643=>though I have tried to  bear his part, I do not know what design or hope  he 
line 23644=>had  for this hour,  if indeed he had any. Most  likely it seems that if  he 
line 23645=>were here now the choice would still wait on you. Such is your fate.' 
line 23646=>     Frodo did not answer at once. Then he spoke slowly. `I  know that haste 
line 23647=>is needed, yet I cannot choose. The burden is heavy. Give me an hour longer, 
line 23648=>and I will speak. Let me be alone! ' 
line 23649=>     Aragorn looked  at  him with  kindly  pity. `Very  well,  Frodo  son of 
line 23650=>Drogo,' he  said. `You shall have an hour, and  you  shall be alone. We will 
