line 23800=>far  away, leaping  blindly up  the path to the hill -top. Terror  and  grief 
line 23801=>shook  him, seeing in  his thought the  mad fierce face of Boromir,  and his 
line 23802=>burning eyes. 
line 23803=>     Soon  he came out alone on the summit of Amon Hen, and halted,  gasping 
line 23804=>for breath. He saw as through a mist a  wide  flat circle, paved with mighty 
line 23805=>flags, and surrounded with  a crumbling battlement;  and in the middle,  set 
line 23806=>upon four carven pillars, was a high seat, reached by a stair of many steps. 
line 23807=>Up  he went and sat upon the ancient chair, feeling like  a lost  child that 
line 23808=>had clambered upon the throne of mountain-kings.  
line 23809=>     At first he could see little. He seemed  to be in a  world of  mist  in 
line 23810=>which  there were only shadows: the Ring  was upon him.  Then here and there 
line 23811=>the mist gave way and he saw  many visions: small and clear as if they  were 
line 23812=>
line 23813=>####-under his eyes upon a table, and yet remote. There was no sound, only bright 
line 23814=>living images.  The world  seemed to have shrunk  and  fallen silent. He was 
line 23815=>sitting upon the Seat of Seeing, on Amon Hen, the Hill of the Eye of the Men 
line 23816=>of  NÂ®menor. Eastward he looked into  wide uncharted lands, nameless plains,  
line 23817=>and forests unexplored. Northward he looked, and the Great  River lay like a 
line 23818=>ribbon beneath him, and the  Misty Mountains stood small and hard  as broken 
line 23819=>teeth. Westward he looked and saw  the broad pastures of Rohan; and Orthanc, 
line 23820=>the pinnacle of Isengard, like a black spike. Southward he looked, and below 
line 23821=>his very feet the  Great River curled  like a toppling wave and plunged over 
line 23822=>the falls of Rauros into a foaming pit; a glimmering rainbow played upon the 
line 23823=>fume. And Ethir Anduin he saw, the mighty delta of the River, and myriads of 
line 23824=>sea -birds whirling like a white dust  in the  sun, and  beneath them a green 
line 23825=>and silver sea, rippling in endless lines.  
line 23826=>     But everywhere he looked he saw  the signs of  war. The Misty Mountains 
line 23827=>were  crawling  like anthills:  orcs were  issuing out  of a thousand holes.  
line 23828=>Under the  boughs of  Mirkwood there was  deadly strife of Elves and Men and 
line 23829=>fell  beasts. The  land of the Beornings was aflame; a cloud was over Moria; 
line 23830=>smoke rose on the borders of Lurien. 
line 23831=>     Horsemen  were  galloping on  the grass of  Rohan;  wolves poured  from  
line 23832=>Isengard. From the  havens of Harad ships of war  put out to sea; and out of 
line 23833=>the East Men were moving endlessly: swordsmen, spearmen, bowmen upon 
line 23834=>horses, 
line 23835=>chariots of chieftains  and laden wains. All  the power of the Dark Lord was 
line 23836=>in  motion. Then turning south  again  he  beheld Minas Tirith. Far away  it 
line 23837=>seemed. and beautiful: white-walled,  many-towered, proud  and fair upon its 
line 23838=>mountain-seat;  its battlements  glittered with  steel, and its turrets were 
line 23839=>bright with many banners. Hope leaped in his heart. But against Minas Tirith 
line 23840=>was  set  another  fortress,  greater and more  strong.  Thither,  eastward, 
line 23841=>unwilling his eye was drawn.  It passed the ruined bridges of Osgiliath, the 
line 23842=>grinning  gates of  Minas Morgul. and the  haunted Mountains, and it  looked 
line 23843=>upon Gorgoroth,  the  valley of terror  in the  Land  of Mordor. Darkness lay 
line 23844=>there under the Sun. Fire glowed amid the smoke. Mount Doom was burning, 
line 23845=>and 
line 23846=>a  great  reek  rising.  Then at last  his  gaze was held: wall  upon  wall, 
line 23847=>battlement  upon  battlement, black, immeasurably strong,  mountain of iron, 
line 23848=>gate of steel, tower of adamant, he saw  it: Barad-dyr,  Fortress of Sauron. 
line 23849=>All hope left him. 
line 23850=>
line 23851=>####-     And suddenly he felt the  Eye. There was an eye  in the Dark Tower that 
line 23852=>did not sleep. He knew that it had become aware of his gaze.  A fierce eager  
line 23853=>will  was there.  It leaped  towards him; almost  like a finger he  felt it, 
line 23854=>searching for him. Very soon it would nail him down, know just exactly where 
line 23855=>he was. Amon  Lhaw it touched. It glanced  upon Tol Brandir he threw himself 
line 23856=>from the seat, crouching, covering his head with his grey hood. 
line 23857=>     He heard himself crying out: Never, never! Or was it: Verily I  come, I 
line 23858=>come to  you? He could not tell. Then  as a flash  from some other point  of 
line 23859=>power there  came  to  his mind another thought: Take it off!  Take  it off! 
line 23860=>Fool, take it off! Take off the Ring! 
line 23861=>     The two powers strove in him. For a moment,  perfectly balanced between 
line 23862=>their piercing  points,  he  writhed,  tormented. Suddenly  he was aware  of 
line 23863=>himself  again. Frodo, neither  the  Voice nor the Eye: free to choose,  and 
line 23864=>with  one  remaining  instant in  which to  do so. He  took the Ring off his 
line 23865=>finger. He  was kneeling in clear  sunlight before  the  high  seat. A black  
line 23866=>shadow seemed to  pass like an arm above him; it  missed Amon Hen and 
line 23867=>groped 
line 23868=>out west,  and faded. Then all the sky was  clean and blue and birds sang in 
line 23869=>every tree. 
line 23870=>     Frodo rose to his feet. A great weariness was on him,  but his will was 
line 23871=>firm and his heart lighter. He spoke aloud to himself. `I  will do now what I 
line 23872=>must,' he said.  'This at least is plain: the evil of the Ring is already at 
line 23873=>work even in the Company,  and the Ring must leave them before it  does more 
line 23874=>harm. I will go alone. Some I cannot  trust, and  those I  can trust are too 
line 23875=>dear  to me: poor old  Sam,  and Merry and  Pippin. Strider,  too: his heart 
line 23876=>yearns for Minas Tirith, and he will be needed there, now Boromir has fallen 
line 23877=>into evil. I will go alone. At once.' 
line 23878=>     He went quickly  down the path and came back to the lawn where  Boromir 
line 23879=>had found him. Then he halted, listening. He thought he could hear cries and  
line 23880=>calls from the woods near the shore below.  
line 23881=>     'They'll be hunting  for  me,' he  said. `I wonder how long I have been 
line 23882=>away. Hours, I should think.' He hesitated. 'What can  I  do? ' he muttered. 
line 23883=>'I must go now or I shall never go.  I shan't  get  a  chance  again. I hate 
line 23884=>leaving them, and like  this without  any explanation. But surely  they will 
line 23885=>understand. Sam will. And what else can I do?' 
line 23886=>     Slowly he  drew out the Ring and put it  on  once more. He vanished and  
line 23887=>passed down the hill, less than a rustle of the wind. 
line 23888=>
line 23889=>####-     The others remained long by the river -side. For some time they had been 
line 23890=>silent, moving restlessly about; but now they  were sitting in a circle, and 
