line 24127=> * BOOK III *  
line 24128=>
line 24129=>Chapter 1. The Departure of Boromir 
line 24130=>
line 24131=> 
line 24132=> 
line 24133=>     Aragorn sped on up the hill. Every now and again he bent to the ground. 
line 24134=>Hobbits go light, and  their  footprints are not  easy  even for a Ranger to 
line 24135=>read, but not  far from the top a spring  crossed  the path, and in the  wet 
line 24136=>earth he saw what he was seeking. 
line 24137=>     'I read the  signs  aright,'  he  said  to himself. 'Frodo  ran  to the 
line 24138=>hill-top. I wonder what he  saw there? But he returned by  the same way, and 
line 24139=>went down the hill again.' 
line 24140=>     Aragorn hesitated. He desired to go to the high seat himself, hoping to 
line 24141=>see there something that  would guide him in his perplexities; but  time was 
line 24142=>pressing. Suddenly he leaped  forward, and  ran to the  summit,  across  the 
line 24143=>great flag-stones, and up the steps. Then sitting in the high seat he looked 
line 24144=>out. But the  sun seemed darkened,  and the world dim and remote.  He turned 
line 24145=>from the North back again to North, and saw nothing save  the distant hills,  
line 24146=>unless it were  that far away he could see again  a great bird like an eagle 
line 24147=>high in the air, descending slowly in wide circles down towards the earth. 
line 24148=>     Even as he  gazed his  quick ears caught sounds in the woodlands below,  
line 24149=>on the west  side  of the River. He stiffened.  There were  cries, and among 
line 24150=>them, to  his  horror, he  could distinguish the harsh voices of  Orcs. Then 
line 24151=>suddenly with  a deep-throated call a great horn blew, and the  blasts of it 
line 24152=>smote the hills and  echoed  in the hollows, rising  in a mighty shout above 
line 24153=>the roaring of the falls. 
line 24154=>     'The horn of  Boromir!' he cried. 'He is  in need!' He  sprang down the 
line 24155=>steps and away, leaping down the path. 'Alas! An ill fate is on me this day, 
line 24156=>and all that I do goes amiss. Where is Sam?' 
line 24157=>     As he ran the cries  came louder, but fainter  now and  desperately the 
line 24158=>horn was blowing. Fierce and shrill rose the yells of the Orcs, and suddenly 
line 24159=>the horn-calls  ceased.  Aragorn  raced  down the last slope,  but before he 
line 24160=>could reach  the hill's foot, the sounds died away;  and as he turned to the 
line 24161=>left and ran towards them  they  retreated, until at last he could hear them 
line 24162=>no more. Drawing  his bright sword and crying Elendil!  Elendil!  he crashed 
line 24163=>through the trees.  
line 24164=>
line 24165=>####-     A mile, maybe, from Parth Galen in a little glade not far from the lake 
line 24166=>he found Boromir. He was sitting with his back to a great tree, as if he was 
line 24167=>resting.  But  Aragorn saw  that he was pierced  with  many  black -feathered 
line 24168=>arrows; his sword  was still in his hand, but it  was  broken near the hilt; 
line 24169=>his horn cloven in two was at his side. Many Orcs lay slain, piled all about 
line 24170=>him and at his feet. 
line 24171=>     Aragorn knelt beside him.  Boromir opened his eyes and strove to speak. 
line 24172=>At last slow  words came. 'I tried to take the Ring from Frodo ' he said. 'I  
line 24173=>am sorry. I have paid.' His glance strayed to his fallen enemies;  twenty at 
line 24174=>least lay there. 'They have gone: the Halflings: the Orcs have taken them. I 
line 24175=>think they  are  not  dead. Orcs bound them.' He paused and  his eyes closed 
line 24176=>wearily. After a moment he spoke again. 
line 24177=>     'Farewell, Aragorn!  Go to  M inas Tirith  and  save my  people!  I have 
line 24178=>failed.' 
line 24179=>     'No!'  said  Aragorn,  taking his hand and kissing  his brow. 'You have 
line 24180=>conquered. Few  have gained such a  victory. Be at peace! Minas Tirith shall  
line 24181=>not fall!' 
line 24182=>     Boromir smiled. 
line 24183=>     'Which way did they go? Was Frodo there?' said Aragorn. 
line 24184=>     But Boromir did not speak again. 
line 24185=>     'Alas!' said  Aragorn. 'Thus  passes the  heir of Denethor, Lord of the 
line 24186=>Tower of Guard! This is a bitter end. Now the Company is all  in ruin. It is 
line 24187=>I that  have failed. Vain was Gandalf's  trust in me.  What  shall I do now?  
line 24188=>Boromir has laid it on  me  to go  to Minas Tirith, and my heart desires it; 
line 24189=>but where are the  Ring and the Bearer? How shall I  find them  and save the  
line 24190=>Quest from disaster?' 
line 24191=>     He knelt for a while, bent with weeping, still clasping Boromir's hand. 
line 24192=>So it  was  that Legolas  and  Gimli  found him.  They came from the western 
line 24193=>slopes of the hill, silently, creeping  through  the  trees as if  they were 
line 24194=>hunting. Gimli had  his axe in hand,  and  Legola s  his long knife:  all his 
line 24195=>arrows were spent. When  they came into the  glade they halted in amazement; 
line 24196=>and  then they stood a moment with heads bowed  in  grief,  for it seemed to 
line 24197=>them plain what had happened. 
line 24198=>     'Alas!'  said Legolas, coming to  Aragorn's  side. 'We have  hunted and 
line 24199=>slain many  Orcs in the woods, but we should have been of more use  here. We 
line 24200=>came when we heard the horn-but too late, it  seems. I  fear  you have taken 
line 24201=>deadly hurt.' 
line 24202=>
line 24203=>####-     'Boromir  is dead,' said Aragorn. 'I am unscathed,  for  I was not here 
line 24204=>with him. He fell defending the hobbits, while I was away upon the hill.' 
line 24205=>     'The hobbits!' cried Gimli 'Where are they then? Where is Frodo?' 
line 24206=>     'I do not know,' answered Aragorn wearily. 'Before he died Boromir told 
line 24207=>me that the Orcs had  bound them;  he  did not think that they were  dead. I 
line 24208=>sent him  to follow  Merry and Pippin; but I did not ask him if Frodo or Sam 
line 24209=>were with him: not until it was too  late.  All  that I have done  today has 
line 24210=>gone amiss. What is to be done now?' 
line 24211=>     'First  we must tend the fallen,'  said Legolas. 'We  cannot  leave him 
line 24212=>lying like carrion among these foul Orcs.' 
line 24213=>     'But we must be swift,' said Gimli. 'He would not wish us to linger. We 
line 24214=>must follow the Orcs, if there is hope  that  any of our Company are  living 
line 24215=>prisoners.' 
line 24216=>     'But we do not know whether the Ring-bearer is with them  or not ' said 
line 24217=>Aragorn.  'Are we to abandon him? Must we not seek him first? An evil choice 
line 24218=>is now before us!' 
line 24219=>     'Then let us do first what we must do,' said  Legolas. 'We have not the 
line 24220=>time or the tools to bury our comrade fitly, or to raise a mound over him. A 
line 24221=>cairn we might build.' 
line 24222=>     'The labour would be hard and long:  there are no stones that we  could 
line 24223=>use nearer than the water -side,' said Gimli. 
line 24224=>     'Then  let us lay him in a boat with his weapons, and the weapons of his 
line 24225=>vanquished foes,' said Aragorn. 'We will send him to the Falls of Rauros and  
line 24226=>give him to Anduin. The River of Gondor will take care at least that no evil 
line 24227=>creature dishonours his bones.' 
line 24228=>     Quickly  they searched the bodies of  the Orcs, gathering  their swords 
line 24229=>and cloven helms and shields into  a  heap. 'See!' cried  Aragorn. 'Here  we 
line 24230=>find  tokens!' He picked  out  from the  pile  of grim weapons  two  knives,  
line 24231=>leaf-bladed, damasked  in go ld and red;  and searching further he found also 
line 24232=>the sheaths,  black, set with small red gems. 'No orc-tools these!' he said. 
line 24233=>'They were  borne by  the hobbits.  Doubtless the  Orcs despoiled them,  but 
line 24234=>feared  to keep  the knives,  knowing  them  for  wha t  they  are:  work  of 
line 24235=>Westernesse, wound about with spells  for the  bane of Mordor. Well, now, if 
line 24236=>they still  live,  our  friends are  weaponless. I will  take these  things,  
line 24237=>hoping against hope, to give them back.' 
line 24238=>     'And  I,' said Legolas,  'will take all the arrows that I can find, for  
line 24239=>my quiver is empty.' He  searched  in the  pile  and on the ground about and 
line 24240=>
line 24241=>####-found not a few that were undamaged and longer in the shaft than such arrows 
line 24242=>as the Orcs were accustomed to use. He looked at them closely. 
line 24243=>     And  Aragorn looked on the slain, and he said: 'Here  lie many that are 
line 24244=>not folk of Mordor. Some are from the North, from the Misty  Mountains, if I 
line 24245=>know  anything of Orcs and their kinds.  And here are others  strange to me.  
line 24246=>Their gear is not after the manner of Orcs at all!' 
line 24247=>     There were four goblin-soldiers of greater  stature, swart, slant-eyed, 
line 24248=>with thick  legs and  large hands. They  were armed with short  broad-bladed 
line 24249=>swords, not with  the curved scimitars usual with Orcs: and they had bows  of 
line 24250=>yew, in length and shape like the bows of Men.  Upon their shields they bore 
line 24251=>a strange device: a small white hand in the centre of a black field; on  the 
line 24252=>front of their iron helms was set an S-rune, wrought of some white metal. 
line 24253=>     'I have not seen  these tokens  before,'  said Aragorn.  'What  do they 
line 24254=>mean?' 
line 24255=>     'S is for Sauron,' said Gimli. 'That is easy to read.' 
line 24256=>     'Nay!' said Legolas. 'Sauron does not use the Elf-runes.' 
line 24257=>     'Neither  does he  use  his right name,  nor permit it  to be  spelt or 
line 24258=>spoken,' said Aragorn. 'And he does  not use white. The  Orcs in the service 
line 24259=>of Barad-dyr use the sign of the Red Eye.' He stood for a moment in thought. 
line 24260=>'S is for Saruman, I  guess,'  he  said at length. 'There  is evil afoot  in 
line 24261=>Isengard,  and the West is no longer safe. It is  as Gandalf feared: by some 
line 24262=>means the traitor Saruman has had news of our journey. It is likely too that 
line 24263=>he  knows  of  Gandalf's  fall.  Pursuers  from Moria may  have escaped  the 
line 24264=>vigilance of Lurien, or they may have avoided that land and come to Isengard 
line 24265=>by other  paths. Orcs travel  fast.  But  Saruman has many  ways of learning 
line 24266=>news. Do you remember the birds?' 
line 24267=>     'Well,  we  have no time to ponder riddles,' said  Gimli. 'Let us  bear 
line 24268=>Boromir away!' 
line 24269=>     'But  after that  we  must guess  the riddles, if we  are to choose our 
line 24270=>course rightly,' answered Aragorn. 
line 24271=>     'Maybe there is no right choice,' said Gimli. 
line 24272=>     Taking his axe the  Dwarf now  cut  several branches. These they lashed 
line 24273=>together with bowstrings, and spread their  cloaks upon the frame. Upon this 
line 24274=>rough bier they carried the  body of  their companion to the shore, together  
line 24275=>with such trophies of  his last battle as they chose to send forth with him. 
line 24276=>It was only a short way, yet they found it no easy task, for  Boromir was  a  
line 24277=>man both tall and strong. 
line 24278=>
line 24279=>####-     At the water -side Aragorn  remained, watching the  bier. while  Legolas 
line 24280=>and Gimli hastened back on foot to Parth  Galen. It was  a mile or more, and 
line 24281=>it was some time before they came back, paddling two boats swiftly along the 
line 24282=>shore. 
line 24283=>     'There is a strange tale  to tell!'  said Legolas. 'There are  only two 
line 24284=>boats upon the bank. We could find no trace of the other.' 
line 24285=>     'Have Orcs been there?' asked Aragorn. 
line 24286=>     'We saw no signs of  them,' answered Gimli. 'And Orcs  would have taken 
line 24287=>or destroyed all the boats, and the baggage as well.' 
line 24288=>     'I will look at the ground when we come there,' said Aragorn. 
line 24289=>     Now they laid  Boromir  in the middle of the boat that  was to bear him 
line 24290=>away. The grey hood and elven-cloak they folded and placed beneath his head. 
line 24291=>They combed his long dark hair and arrayed it upon his shoulders. The golden 
line 24292=>belt of Lurien gleamed  about  his waist. His helm they set beside  him, and 
line 24293=>across  his lap  they laid the  cloven horn and  the hilts and shards of his 
line 24294=>sword; beneath his  feet  they put the swords of his enemies. Then fastening  
line 24295=>the  prow to the stern of the other boat,  they drew him out into the water. 
line 24296=>They rowed sadly along the shore, and turning into the swift -running channel 
line 24297=>they passed the green sward of Parth Galen. The steep  sides of  Tol Brandir  
line 24298=>were  glowing:  it  was now  mid-afternoon.  As they  went south the fume of 
line 24299=>Rauros rose and  shimmered before them, a haze of gold. The rush and thunder 
line 24300=>of the falls shook the windless air . 
line 24301=>     Sorrowfully  they  cast loose  the funeral  boat:  there  Boromir  lay, 
line 24302=>restful, peaceful, gliding upon  the bosom of the  flowing water. The stream 
line 24303=>took him while they  held their own boat back with their paddles. He floated 
line 24304=>by  them, and slowly  his  boat departed, waning to  a dark spot against the 
line 24305=>golden  light;  and then suddenly it vanished. Rauros  roared on unchanging. 
line 24306=>The River  had taken Boromir  son of Denethor,  and he was not seen again in 
line 24307=>Minas  Tirith,  standing as he used to  stand  upon  the  White Tower in the 
line 24308=>morning. But  in Gondor in after -days it long  was said that  the elven-boat 
line 24309=>rode  the falls  and the foaming pool, and bore him down  through Osgiliath, 
line 24310=>and  past the many mouths of Anduin, out  into the Great Sea at night  under  
line 24311=>the stars. 
line 24312=>     For a  while  the three companions remained  silent,  gazing after him. 
line 24313=>Then  Aragorn spoke. 'They will look for him from the White Tower,' he said, 
line 24314=>'but he will not return from mountain or from  sea.' Then slowly he began to 
line 24315=>sing: 
line 24316=>
line 24317=>####-     Through Rohan over fen and field where the long grass grows 
line 24318=>     The West Wind comes walking, and about the walls it goes. 
line 24319=>     'What news from the West, O wandering wind, do you bring to me tonight?  
line 24320=>     Have you seen Boromir the Tall by moon or by starlight?' 
line 24321=>     'I saw him ride over seven streams, over waters wide and grey; 
line 24322=>     I saw him walk in empty lands, until he passed away 
line 24323=>     Into the shadows of the North. I saw him then no more. 
line 24324=>     The North Wind may have heard the horn of the son of Denethor.'  
line 24325=>     'O Boromir! From the high walls westward I looked afar, 
line 24326=>     But you came not from the empty lands where no men are.'  
line 24327=>      
line 24328=>Then Legolas sang: 
line 24329=> 
line 24330=>     From the mouths of the Sea the South Wind flies, from the sandhills and the stones; 
line 24331=>     The wailing of the gulls it bears, and at the gate it moans. 
line 24332=>     'What news from the South, O sighing wind, do you bring to me at eve? 
line 24333=>     Where now is Boromir the Fair? He tarries and I grieve.'  
line 24334=>     'Ask not of me where he doth dwell-so many bones there lie 
line 24335=>     On the white shores and the dark shores under the stormy sky; 
line 24336=>     So many have passed down Anduin to find the flowing Sea. 
line 24337=>     Ask of the North Wind news of them the North Wind sends to me!'  
line 24338=>     'O Boromir! Beyond the gate the seaward road runs south, 
line 24339=>     But you came not with the wailing gulls from the grey sea's mouth.'  
line 24340=>     Then Aragorn sang again: 
line 24341=>     From the  Gate  of Kings  the  North Wind rides,  and past the  roaring falls;  
line 24342=>     And clear and cold about the tower its loud horn calls. 
line 24343=>     'What news from the North, O mighty wind, do you bring to me today? 
line 24344=>     What news of Boromir the Bold? For he is long away.'  
line 24345=>     'Beneath Amon Hen I heard his cry. There many foes he fought. 
line 24346=>     His cloven shield, his broken sword, they to the water brought. 
line 24347=>     His head so proud, his face so fair, his limbs they laid to rest; 
line 24348=>     And Rauros, golden Rauros-falls, bore him upon its breast.'  
line 24349=>     'O Boromir! The Tower of Guard shall ever northward gaze 
line 24350=>     To Rauros, golden Rauros-falls, until the end o f days.'  
line 24351=> 
line 24352=>     So they ended. Then they  turned  their boat and drove it with all  the 
line 24353=>speed they could against the stream back to Parth Galen. 
line 24354=>     'You left the  East Wind to  me,' said Gimli, 'but I will say naught of 
line 24355=>it.' 
line 24356=>     'That is as it should be,' said Aragorn. 'In  Minas Tirith  they endure 
line 24357=>the East Wind, but they do not ask it for tidings. But now Boromir has taken 
line 24358=>
line 24359=>####-his road. and we must make haste to choose our own.' 
line 24360=>     He surveyed the green  lawn, quickly but  thoroughly, stooping often to 
line 24361=>the earth. 'The Orcs have been on this ground,' he  said. 'Otherwise nothing 
line 24362=>can be made  out for certain. All  our  footprints  are  here, crossing  and 
line 24363=>re-crossing. I cannot  tell  whether any of the hobbits have come back since 
line 24364=>the search for  Frodo  began.'  He returned  to the bank, close to where the 
line 24365=>rill  from the  spring  trickled  out into  the River. 'There are some clear 
line 24366=>prints here,' he  said. 'A hobbit waded out into the water and  back; but  I 
line 24367=>cannot say how long ago.' 
line 24368=>     'How then do you read this riddle?' asked Gimli. 
line 24369=>     Aragorn did not answer at once, but went back to the  camping-place and 
line 24370=>looked  at  the baggage. 'Two  packs  are  missing.' he  said, 'and  one  is 
line 24371=>certainly Sam's:  it was rather large and heavy.  This  then  is the answe r: 
line 24372=>Frodo  has gone by boat, and his servant has  gone with him. Frodo must have 
line 24373=>returned while we were all away. I met Sam going up the hill and told him to 
line 24374=>follow me;  but plainly he  did  not do so. He guessed his master s mind and  
line 24375=>came  back here before Frodo had gone. He did  not find it easy to leave Sam 
line 24376=>behind!' 
line 24377=>     'But why should  he leave  us behind, and without  a word?' said Gimli. 
line 24378=>'That was a strange deed!' 
line 24379=>     'And a  brave deed,' said Aragorn. 'Sam was right,  I think.  Frodo did 
line 24380=>not wish to  lead any friend to death with him in Mordor. But he knew that he 
line 24381=>must go himself. Something happened after he left us that  overcame his fear 
line 24382=>and doubt.' 
line 24383=>     'Maybe hunting Orcs came on him and he fled,' said Legolas.  
line 24384=>     'He fled, certainly,' said Aragorn, 'but not, I think, from Orcs.' What 
line 24385=>he  thought was  the cause of Frodo's  sudden resolve and flight Aragorn did  
line 24386=>not say. The last words of Boromir he long kept secret. 
line 24387=>     'Well,  so much  at  least  is now clear,'  said Legolas:  'Frodo is no 
line 24388=>longer on this side of the  River:  only he can have taken the boat. And Sam 
line 24389=>is with him; only he would have taken his pack.' 
line 24390=>     'Our  choice then,' said Gimli, 'is either to take the  remaining  boat 
line 24391=>and follow Frodo, or else to follow  the Orcs on foot. There is little  hope 
line 24392=>either way. We have already lost precious hours.' 
line 24393=>     'Let me  think!' said Aragorn. 'And now  may I make a  right choice and 
line 24394=>change the  evil fate of this unhappy day!' He stood silent for a moment. 'I  
line 24395=>will follow the Orcs,' he said at last. 'I would have guided Frodo to Mordor  
line 24396=>
line 24397=>####-and  gone with  him to the end; but if I  seek him now  in the wilderness, I 
line 24398=>must abandon the captives to torment  and death.  My heart speaks clearly at 
line 24399=>last: the fate  of the Bearer  is in  my  hands no  longer .  The Company has 
line 24400=>played  its part. Yet we that  remain cannot forsake our companions while we 
line 24401=>have strength left.  Come!  We  will go  now. Leave  all  that can be spared 
line 24402=>behind! We will press on by day and dark!' 
line 24403=>     They drew up the  last  boat  and carried  it to  the trees.  They laid 
line 24404=>beneath  it such of their goods  as  they did not  need  and could not carry 
line 24405=>away. Then they left Parth Galen. The afternoon was fading as they came back  
line 24406=>to the glade where Boromir had fallen. There they picked up the trail of the 
line 24407=>Orcs. It needed little skill to find. 
line 24408=>     'No other folk  make such  a trampling,' said Legolas. 'It seems  their 
line 24409=>delight to slash and beat down  growing  things that are not even  in  their 
line 24410=>way.' 
line 24411=>     'But they go with a great  speed for all that,' said Aragorn, 'and they 
line 24412=>do not  tire. And later we  may have  to  search for our  path  in hard bare 
line 24413=>lands.' 
line 24414=>     'Well, after  them!' said Gimli. 'Dwarves too can  go swiftly, and they 
line 24415=>do not tire sooner  than Orcs. But it will be a long chase: they have a long 
line 24416=>start.' 
line 24417=>     'Yes,' said Aragorn, 'we  shall all need the endurance of  Dwarves. But 
line 24418=>come! With hope or without hope we will follow the trail of our enemies. And 
line 24419=>woe to them, if we prove the swifter! We  will make such a chase as shall be  
line 24420=>accounted a marvel among the Three Kindreds Âµ Elves. Dwarves, and Men. 
line 24421=>Forth 
line 24422=>the Three Hunters!' 
line 24423=>     Like a deer he sprang away. Through the trees he sped. On and on he led 
line 24424=>them,  tireless and swift, now that his mind  was at last made up. The woods 
line 24425=>about the lake they left behind. Long slopes  they climbed, dark, hard-edged 
line 24426=>against the  sky already red with sunset. Dusk came. They passed away,  grey 
line 24427=>shadows in a stony land. 
line 24428=> 
line 24429=>
line 24430=>####- 
line 24431=>
line 24432=>Chapter 2. The Riders of Rohan 
line 24433=>
line 24434=> 
line 24435=> 
line 24436=>     Dusk deepened. Mist lay behind them among the trees below, and  brooded 
line 24437=>on  the pale margins of the Anduin, but the  sky was clear. Stars  came out. 
line 24438=>The waxing  moon  was riding in the West, and the shadows of the rocks  were 
line 24439=>black. They had come to  the feet of stony hills, and their pace was slower, 
line 24440=>for the trail was no longer easy to  follow. Here the highlands of the  Emyn 
line 24441=>Muil ran from North to South in two long tumbled ridges. The western side of 
line 24442=>each ridge was steep  and difficult, but  the  eastward slopes were gentler, 
line 24443=>furrowed  with  many  gullies  and  narrow  ravines.  All  night  the  three 
line 24444=>companions scrambled in  this bony land, climbing to the  crest of the first  
line 24445=>and tallest ridge, and down again into the darkness of a deep winding valley 
line 24446=>on the other side. 
line 24447=>     There in the still cool hour before dawn they rested for a brief space. 
line 24448=>The moon had long gone down before them, the stars glittered above them; the 
line 24449=>first light  of day had not  yet come over the dark  hills behind.  For  the 
line 24450=>moment Aragorn was at a loss:  the  orc-trail had descended into the valley, 
line 24451=>but there it had vanished. 
line 24452=>     'Which way would they turn, do you  think?' said Legolas. 'Northward to 
line 24453=>take a straighter road to Isengard,  or Fangorn, if that is their aim as you  
line 24454=>guess? Or southward to strike the Entwash?' 
line 24455=>     'They will not make  for  the  river,  whatever mark they aim at'' said 
line 24456=>Aragorn. 'And unless there is much amiss  in Rohan and  the power of Saruman 
line 24457=>is greatly increased;  they will take  the  shortest way that they  can find 
line 24458=>over the fields of the Rohirrim. Let us search northwards!' 
line 24459=>     The  dale  ran like  a stony  trough between  the  ridged  hills, and a  
line 24460=>trickling stream flowed among the boulders  at the  bottom. A cliff  frowned 
line 24461=>upon their right; to their left rose  grey  slopes, dim  and shadowy in  the 
line 24462=>late night.  They  went  on  for  a  mile  or  more northwards. Aragorn  was 
line 24463=>searching. bent towards  the ground,  among the folds and gullies leading up 
line 24464=>into  the western ridge. Legolas was some way ahead. Suddenly the Elf gave a  
line 24465=>cry and the others came running towards him. 
line 24466=>     'We have already overtaken some of those that we are hunting,' he said. 
line 24467=>'Look!' He pointed, and they saw that  what they had  at  first  taken to be 
line 24468=>boulders lying at the foot of the slope were huddled  bodies. Five dead Orcs 
line 24469=>
line 24470=>####-lay there. They had  been hewn  with many  cruel strokes, and  two had  been 
line 24471=>beheaded. The ground was wet with their dark blood. 
line 24472=>     'Here is another riddle!' said Gimli.  'But it needs the light  of  day 
line 24473=>and for that we cannot wait.' 
line 24474=>     'Yet however you  read it,  it  seems  not  unhopeful,'  said  Legolas.  
line 24475=>'Enemies  of the  Orcs  are  likely to  be our friends. Do any folk dwell in 
line 24476=>these hills?' 
line 24477=>     'No,' said Aragorn. 'The Rohirrim seldom come  here, and it is far from 
line 24478=>Minas Tirith. It might be that some  company of  Men  were  hunting here for 
line 24479=>reasons that we do not know. Yet I think not.' 
line 24480=>     'What do you think?' said Gimli. 
line 24481=>     'I think that  the  enemy  brought his  own enemy  with  him,' answered 
line 24482=>Aragorn. 'These are Northern Orcs from far away. Among the slain are none of 
line 24483=>the great  Orcs with the strange badges. There was a quarrel, I guess: it is 
line 24484=>no uncommon thing with these foul  folk. Maybe there was some  dispute about 
line 24485=>the road.' 
line 24486=>     'Or about the  captives,' said  Gimli. 'Let us hope that they, too, did 
line 24487=>not meet their end here.' 
line 24488=>     Aragorn  searched the ground in a wide  circle,  but no other traces of 
line 24489=>the fight could be found. They went on. Already the eastward sky was turning 
line 24490=>pale; the  stars were fading, and a grey light was  slowly growing. A little 
line 24491=>further  north they  came  to  a fold  in which a tiny stream,  falling  and 
line 24492=>winding, had cut a stony path down into  the valley. In it some bushes grew,  
line 24493=>and there were patches of grass upon its sides. 
line 24494=>     'At last!'  said Aragorn.  'Here are  the tracks that  we seek! Up this 
line 24495=>water -channel: this is the way that the Orcs went after their debate.' 
line 24496=>     Swiftly now the pursuers turned and followed the new path.  As if fresh 
line 24497=>from a  night's rest they sprang  from stone to stone. At last  they reached 
line 24498=>the  crest of  the  grey hill,  and a  sudden breeze blew in  their hair and 
line 24499=>stirred their cloaks: the chill wind of dawn. 
line 24500=>     Turning  back they saw across  the  River  the  far hills kindled.  Day 
line 24501=>leaped into the sky. The red rim of the  sun rose over  the shoulders of the 
