line 25167=>us go free. Or seek to carry  out your law. If you do so there will be fewer  
line 25168=>to return to your war or to your king.' 
line 25169=>     Jomer was silent for a  moment,  then he  spoke. 'We both have need  of 
line 25170=>haste,' he said. 'My  company chafes to be away, and every hour lessens your 
line 25171=>hope. This  is my choice.  You  may go;  and  what  is more, I will lend you  
line 25172=>horses. This  only I ask: when  your quest is achieved, or  is  proved vain, 
line 25173=>return  with  the horses over the  Entwade  to Meduseld,  the high house  in 
line 25174=>Edoras  where Thjoden now sits. Thus you shall prove to him that I  have not 
line 25175=>misjudged. In this I place myself, and maybe my very life, in the keeping of 
line 25176=>your good faith. Do not fail.' 
line 25177=>     'I will not,' said Aragorn. 
line 25178=>     There  was great wonder, and many dark  and doubtful glances, among his 
line 25179=>men, when Jomer gave orders that  the  spare horses were to be  lent to  the 
line 25180=>strangers; but only Jothain dared to speak openly. 
line 25181=>     'It  may be  well enough  for this lord  of the race of Gondor,  as  he 
line 25182=>claims,' he said, 'but who has heard of a horse of the Mark being given to a  
line 25183=>Dwarf?' 
line 25184=>     'No one,' said Gimli. 'And do not trouble: no one will ever hear of it. 
line 25185=>I would sooner  walk  than si t  on the back  of any beast so great,  free or 
line 25186=>begrudged.' 
line 25187=>     'But you must ride now, or you will hinder us,' said Aragorn. 
line 25188=>     'Come, you shall sit  behind me, friend  Gimli, said Legolas.  Then all 
line 25189=>will be well, and you need neither borrow a horse nor be troubled by one.' 
line 25190=>     A great dark-grey horse  was  brought to  Aragorn, and  he  mounted it. 
line 25191=>
line 25192=>####-'Hasufel is  his name,'  said  Jomer.  'May he bear  you well and to  better  
