line 25379=>     Pippin lay in a dark and troubled dream:  it seemed that he could  hear 
line 25380=>his own small  vo ice  echoing in black tunnels,  calling  Frodo, Frodo!  But 
line 25381=>instead of Frodo hundreds of hideous  orc-faces grinned  at  him  out of the 
line 25382=>shadows, hundreds of hideous arms grasped at him from  every side. Where 
line 25383=>was 
line 25384=>Merry? 
line 25385=>     He  woke. Cold air blew on his  face. He was lying on his back. Evening  
line 25386=>was coming and  the sky above was growing dim. He turned and found that  the 
line 25387=>dream  was little worse than  the  waking. His wrists, legs, and ankles were 
line 25388=>tied with cords.  Beside him Merry lay,  white-faced, with a  dirty rag bound  
line 25389=>across his brows. All about them sat or stood a great company of Orcs. 
line 25390=>     Slowly in Pippin's aching head memory pieced itself together and became 
line 25391=>separated from dream-shadows. Of course: he and  Merry had run off into  the 
line 25392=>woods. What had come over them? Why had they dashed off like that, taking 
line 25393=>no 
line 25394=>notice  of  old  Strider? They  had  run a  long  way shouting--he could not 
line 25395=>remember how far or how long; and then suddenly they had crashed  right into 
line 25396=>a  group  of Orcs: they  were standing listening, and they did not appear to 
line 25397=>see Merry and Pippin until they were  almost in their arms. Then they yelled 
line 25398=>and  dozens of other goblins had sprung out  of the  trees. Merry and he had 
line 25399=>drawn their swords, but the  Orcs did not wish to fight, and had tried  only 
line 25400=>to lay  hold of them, even when Merry had cut off several  of their arms and 
line 25401=>hands. Good old Merry!  
line 25402=>     Then  Boromir  had come  leaping through  the  trees. He had made  them 
line 25403=>fight. He slew many of them and the rest fled.  But they had not gone far on  
line 25404=>the way back when they were attacked again. by a hundred Orcs at least, some 
line 25405=>of  them very large, and they shot  a rain of  arrows:  always  at  Boromir. 
line 25406=>Boromir had blown his great horn till the woods rang,  and at first the Orcs 
line 25407=>had  been dismayed and  had  drawn back; but when no  answer but the  echoes 
line 25408=>came, they had attacked more fierce  than ever. Pippin did not remember much 
line 25409=>more.  His last memo was of Boromir  leaning against a tree, plucking out an 
line 25410=>arrow; then darkness fell suddenly. 
line 25411=>     'I suppose I was knocked on the head,' he said to himself. 'I wonder if 
line 25412=>
