line 26049=> 
line 26050=>     Meanwhile the hobbits went with  as much speed as  the dark and tangled  
line 26051=>forest allowed, following  the line of the  running  stream, westward and up 
line 26052=>towards the slopes of the mountains, deeper and deeper into  Fangorn. Slowly 
line 26053=>their fear of the Orcs died away, and their pace slackened. A queer stifling 
line 26054=>feeling came  over  them,  as  if the air were  too thin or too  scanty  for  
line 26055=>breathing. 
line 26056=>     At last Merry halted.  'We can't go on like this,' he  panted.  'I want 
line 26057=>some air.' 
line 26058=>     'Let's have  a  drink  at any rate,'  said  Pippin. 'I'm  parched.'  He 
line 26059=>clambered on to a  great tree-root that  wound  down  into the  stream,  and 
line 26060=>stooping drew up some water in his cupped hands. It was clear and  cold, and 
line 26061=>he  took many draughts.  Merry followed  him.  The water refreshed them  and 
line 26062=>seemed  to cheer their hearts; for a while they sat together on the brink of 
line 26063=>the  stream,  dabbling  their  sore feet and legs, and peering round at  the 
line 26064=>trees that  stood silently about them, rank upon rank, until they faded away 
line 26065=>into grey twilight in every direction. 
line 26066=>     'I suppose you  haven't  lost us already?'  said  Pippin,  leaning back  
line 26067=>against  a great tree-trunk.  'We  can  at  least follow the  course of this 
line 26068=>stream, the Entwash or whatever you call  it, and get  out again  the way we 
line 26069=>came.' 
line 26070=>     'We could, if  our legs  would  do it,' said  Merry;  'and if  we could 
line 26071=>breathe properly.' 
line 26072=>     'Yes, it is  all  very  dim,  and stuffy,  in   here,' said Pippin.  'It 
line 26073=>reminds me, somehow, of the  old room in the  Great Place of  the Tooks away 
line 26074=>back in the  Smials at Tuckborough:  a huge place,  where  the furniture has 
line 26075=>never been moved or changed for generations. They say  the Old Took lived in 
line 26076=>it  year  after  year,  while  he  and  the  room  got  older  and  shabbier  
line 26077=>together -and  it has  never changed since  he  died, a century ago.  And Old 
line 26078=>Gerontius was my great-great-grandfather: that  puts it back a bit. But that 
line 26079=>is  nothing  to the old feeling of  this  wood.  Look at  all those weeping, 
line 26080=>trailing,  beards and whiskers of lichen! And  most of the trees seem  to be 
line 26081=>half covered with ragged dry  leaves that have never fallen. Untidy. I can't  
line 26082=>imagine what spring  would look  like here, if  i t ever comes; still  less a  
line 26083=>spring-cleaning.' 
line 26084=>
line 26085=>####-     'But the Sun at any  rate must peep in sometimes.' said Merry. 'It does 
line 26086=>not look or feel at all like Bilbo's  description of Mirkwood.  That was all 
line 26087=>dark and black,  and the home  of dark black  things. This is just dim,  and 
line 26088=>frightfully  tree-ish.  You  can't imagine animals  living here  at all,  or 
line 26089=>staying for long.' 
line 26090=>     'No, nor hobbits,' said Pippin. 'And I don't like the thought of trying 
line 26091=>to get through  it  either.  Nothing to cat  for a  hundred  miles, I should 
line 26092=>guess. How are our supplies?' 
line 26093=>     'Low,'  said Merry.  'We ran  off  with nothing but a  couple of  spare 
line 26094=>packets  of  lembas, and  left everything else behind.' They  looked at what 
line 26095=>remained of the  elven-cakes:  broken  fragments for abou t five meagre days, 
line 26096=>that  was all. 'And not a wrap or a blanket,' said Merry.  'We shall be cold 
line 26097=>tonight, whichever way we go.' 
line 26098=>     'Well, we'd  better decide on  the way now,' said  Pippin. 'The morning 
line 26099=>must be getting on.' 
line 26100=>     Just then they became  aware of a yellow light that  had appeared, some 
line 26101=>way further  on into the  wood: shafts  of sunlight seemed  suddenly to have  
line 26102=>pierced the forest -roof. 
line 26103=>     'Hullo!' said Merry.  'The Sun must have run into a cloud  while  we've 
line 26104=>been under these  trees, and now she  has  run  out  again; or  else she has 
line 26105=>climbed high enough to look down through some opening. It isn't far let's go 
line 26106=>and investigate!' 
line 26107=>     They  found  it was  further than  they thought. The  ground was rising 
line 26108=>steeply  still,  and  it was becoming  increasingly stony.  The  light  grew 
line 26109=>broader as they went on, and soon they saw that there was a rock -wall before 
line 26110=>them: the side of a hill, or the abrupt end of  some long root thrust out by 
line 26111=>the distant mountains.  No trees grew on it, and the sun was falling full on 
line 26112=>its stony face. The twigs of the trees at  its foot were stretched out stiff 
line 26113=>and still, as if reaching out to the warmth. Where  all had looked so shabby 
line 26114=>and grey before, the wood now gleamed with rich browns, and with the  
line 26115=>smooth 
line 26116=>black-greys  of bark  like polished leather.  The boles of the trees  glowed 
line 26117=>with a soft green like young grass: early spring or  a fleeting vision of it 
line 26118=>was about them. 
line 26119=>     In the face of the stony wall there was something like a stair: natural 
line 26120=>perhaps, and  made by the weathering  and splitting  of the rock, for it was 
line 26121=>rough and uneven. High up, almost level with the tops of forest -trees, there 
line 26122=>
line 26123=>####-was a shelf under a cliff. Nothing grew there but a few grasses and weeds at 
line 26124=>its edge, and  one old stump of a tree  with only two bent branches left: it 
line 26125=>looked almost  like the figure  of some gnarled  old  man,  standing  there, 
line 26126=>blinking in the morning-light. 
line 26127=>     'Up  we go!' said Merry joyfully. 'Now for a breath of air, and a sight 
line 26128=>of the land!' 
line 26129=>     They climbed  and scrambled up the rock. If the  stair had been made it 
line 26130=>was for bigger feet and longer legs than theirs. They were  too eager to  be 
line 26131=>surprised at the  remarkable  way  in  which the  cuts  and  sores of  their 
line 26132=>captivity  had healed and their  vigour had returned. They came at length to 
line 26133=>the edge  of the shelf almost at the feet of the old stump; then they sprang 
line 26134=>up  and  turned  round  with their backs  to the  hill, breathing  deep, and 
line 26135=>looking  out eastward. They saw  that they had  only come some three or four 
line 26136=>miles  into the  forest:  the heads  of the  trees marched  down  the slopes 
line 26137=>towards the  plain. There, near the fringe  of  the forest,  tall spires  of 
line 26138=>curling black smoke went up, wavering and floating towards them. 
line 26139=>     'The wind's changing,'  said Merry.  'It's  turned east again. It feels 
line 26140=>cool up here.' 
line 26141=>     'Yes,'  said Pippin; 'I'm  afraid this is only a passing  gleam, and it 
line 26142=>will  all go grey  again. What a  pity! This  shaggy  old  forest  looked so 
line 26143=>different in the sunlight. I almost felt I liked the place.' 
line 26144=>     'Almost felt you liked the  Forest! That's good! That's uncommonly kind 
line 26145=>of you,' said  a strange voice.  'Turn round and let  me have a look at your 
line 26146=>faces. I almost feel that  I dislike you  both, but do  not let us be hasty. 
line 26147=>Turn round!' A large knob-knuckled hand was laid on each of their shoulders,  
line 26148=>and they  were twisted round,  gently but irresistibly; then  two great arms 
line 26149=>lifted them up. 
line 26150=>     They  found that they  were looking  at a  most extraordinary face.  It 
line 26151=>belonged to a  large  Man-like, almost Troll-like, figure, at least fourteen 
line 26152=>foot high,  very sturdy, with a tall  head,  and hardly any neck. Whether it 
line 26153=>was clad in stuff like green  and grey  bark, or  whether that was its hide, 
line 26154=>was  difficult to say. At any  rate the  arms, at a short distance from  the 
line 26155=>trunk, were not wrinkled,  but covered  with a brown smooth skin.  The large 
line 26156=>feet had seven toes each. The lower part of the long face was covered with a  
line 26157=>sweeping grey beard, bushy, almost twiggy  at the roots,  thin and mossy  at 
line 26158=>the  ends. But  at  the moment the hobbits noted little but the eyes.  These 
line 26159=>deep  eyes  were now  surveying them, slow and solemn, but very penetrating. 
line 26160=>
line 26161=>####-They were brown, shot  with a green light. Often  afterwards Pippin tried to 
line 26162=>describe his first impression of them. 
line 26163=>     'One felt  as if there was an enormous well behind them, filled up with 
line 26164=>ages of  memory  and long, slow,  steady  thinking;  but  their surface  was 
line 26165=>sparkling with  the present: like sun shimmering on the  outer  leaves of  a  
line 26166=>vast tree, or on the ripples of a very deep lake.  I don't know but it  felt 
line 26167=>as  if  something  that grew  in the  ground-asleep, you might say, or  just  
line 26168=>feeling itself  as  something between  roof-tip  and leaf-tip, between  deep 
line 26169=>earth  and sky had suddenly waked up, and was  considering you with the same 
line 26170=>slow care that it had given to its own inside affairs for endless years.' 
