line 26508=>were clear  at  any rate that  UglÂ®k and  his troop  came from Isengard, and 
line 26509=>spoke of Saruman as their master. 
line 26510=>     'Hm, hoom!'  said  Treebeard,  when at last  their story  had wound and 
line 26511=>wandered  down to the battle of the Orcs  and  the Riders  of Rohan.  'Well, 
line 26512=>well! That is a bundle of news and no mistake. You have not told me  all, no 
line 26513=>indeed, not by a long way. But I do not doubt that you a re  doing as Gandalf 
line 26514=>would wish. There is something very  big going on, that I can see, and  what 
line 26515=>it is maybe I shall learn  in good time, or in bad time. By  root  and twig, 
line 26516=>but  it  is a strange business: up sprout a  little folk that are not in the 
line 26517=>old lists,  and behold  the Nine forgotten Riders reappear to hunt them, and 
line 26518=>Gandalf takes them  on a great journey, and Galadriel harbours them in Caras 
line 26519=>Galadhon, and Orcs pursue them down all the  leagues  of Wilderland:  indeed 
line 26520=>they seem to be caught up in a great storm. I hope they weather it!' 
line 26521=>     'And what about yourself?' asked Merry. 
line 26522=>     'Hoom, hm, I have not troubled  about the  Great Wars,' said Treebeard; 
line 26523=>'they mostly concern Elves and Men. That is the business of Wizards: Wizards 
line 26524=>are always troubled  about the future.  I  do not like  worrying  about  the 
line 26525=>future. I am not  altogether on anybody's side, because nobody is altogether  
line 26526=>on my  side, if you understand me: nobody cares  for the woods as I care for  
line 26527=>them, not even  Elves nowadays. Still,  I  take more kindly to Elves than  to 
line 26528=>others: it was the Elves that cured us of  dumbness long ago, and that was a  
line 26529=>great gift that cannot be forgotten, though our  ways have parted since. And 
line 26530=>there are  some things, of  course, whose side I am altogether not  on; I am 
line 26531=>against  them altogether: these -- burbrum' (he again  made a deep rumble of 
line 26532=>disgust)' -- these Orcs, and their masters.  
line 26533=>     'I  used to  be  anxious  when the shadow lay on Mirkwood, but when  it 
line 26534=>removed to Mordor, I did not trouble for a while : Mordor is a long way away. 
line 26535=>But it seems that the wind is setting  East,  and the withering of all woods 
line 26536=>may  be  drawing near.  There is naught that an old Ent can  do to hold back  
line 26537=>that storm: he must weather it or crack. 
line 26538=>     'But Saruman now! Saruman is a neighbour: I cannot overlook him. I must  
line 26539=>do something. I suppose. I have often wondered lately what I should do about 
line 26540=>
line 26541=>####-Saruman.' 
line 26542=>     'Who is  Saruman?'  asked  Pippin.  'Do  you know  anything  about  his 
line 26543=>history?'  'Saruman is  a  Wizard,' answered Treebeard.  'More  than  that I 
line 26544=>cannot say. I do not know the history of Wizards. They  appeared first after  
line 26545=>the Great Ships came over the Sea; but if they came with  the Ships  I never  
line 26546=>can tell. Saruman was  reckoned great among them.  I  believe.  He  gave  up 
line 26547=>wandering  about and minding the  affairs of Men and Elves, some time ago -- 
line 26548=>you would call it a very long time ago: and he settled down at Angrenost, or  
line 26549=>Isengard  as the Men of Rohan call  it. He was very quiet to begin with, but 
line 26550=>his fame began to gr ow. He was  chosen to be head of the White Council, they 
line 26551=>say; but that did not turn out too well. I wonder now  if even  then Saruman 
line 26552=>was not turning to evil ways. But at any  rate he used to give no trouble to 
line 26553=>his neighbours. I used to talk to him.  There was a time when  he was always 
line 26554=>walking about my woods. He was polite in  those days, always asking my leave 
line 26555=>(at  least when he  met me); and always  eager  to  listen. I told him  many 
line 26556=>things that he would never have found out by himself; but he never repaid me 
line 26557=>in like kind. I  cannot remember that he ever told.  me anything. And he got 
line 26558=>more and more like that; his face, as I remember  it-I  have not seen it for  
line 26559=>many  a  day-became  like windows  in  a stone  wall: windows with  shutters 
line 26560=>inside. 
line 26561=>     'I think  that I now understand  what he is  up  to. He  is plotting to 
line 26562=>become a Power. He has a mind of metal and wheels;  and he does not care for  
line 26563=>growing things, except as far as they serve him for the  moment.  And now it 
line 26564=>is clear that he is a  black traitor. He has taken up  with  foul folk, with 
line 26565=>the Orcs. Brm,  hoom! Worse than that: he  has been doing something to them; 
line 26566=>something dangerous. For these Isengarders are more like wicked Men. It is a 
line 26567=>mark of evil things that came in the Great  Darkness  that they cannot abide 
