line 26569=>what he has done? Are they Men he has ruined, or has he blended the races of 
line 26570=>Orcs and Men? That would be a black evil!' 
line 26571=>     Treebeard  rumbled for a moment, as if he  were pronouncing some  deep, 
line 26572=>subterranean Entish malediction. 'Some  time ago I began to wonder  how Orcs 
line 26573=>dared to pass  through my woods so  freely,'  he went on. 'Only lately did I 
line 26574=>guess that  Saruman was to blame, and that  long ago he had been spying  out 
line 26575=>all the ways, and discovering  my secrets. He and his  foul folk are  making 
line 26576=>havoc now. Down on the borders  they are  felling  trees-good trees. Some of 
line 26577=>the trees they just cut down and leave to rot -- orc-mischief that; but most  
line 26578=>
line 26579=>####-are hewn up and  carried off to feed  the fires of Orthanc. There is always a  
line 26580=>smoke rising from Isengard these days.  
line 26581=>     'Curse  him, root and branch!  Many  of those  trees  were  my  friends 
line 26582=>creatures I had known from nut and acorn; many had voices of their  own that 
line 26583=>are lost for ever now. And there are wastes of stump  and bramble where once 
line 26584=>there were singing groves. I have been idle. I have let things slip. It must 
line 26585=>stop!' 
line 26586=>     Treebeard raised  himself  from  his  bed  with a jerk,  stood  up, and 
line 26587=>thumped his hand on the table. The vessels of light trembled and sent up two  
