line 26634=>said. We lost them and we cannot find them.' He sighed. 'I thought most folk  
line 26635=>knew that. There were songs about the hunt of the Ents for the Entwives sung 
line 26636=>among  Elves  and  Men  from  Mirkwood  to  Gondor.  They  cannot  be  quite 
line 26637=>forgotten.' 
line 26638=>     'Well, I  am  afraid the songs have not come west over the Mountains to 
line 26639=>the Shire,'  said Merry. 'Won't you tell us some more, or sing us one of the 
line 26640=>songs?' 
line 26641=>     'Yes, I will indeed,' said Treebeard, seeming pleased with the request. 
line 26642=>'But  I  cannot  tell it properly, only in short; and then  we  must end our 
line 26643=>talk: tomorrow we have councils to call, and work to do, and maybe a journey 
line 26644=>to begin.' 
line 26645=>     'It is rather a strange and sad story,' he went on after a pause. 'When 
line 26646=>the  world  was young, and the woods were  wide  and wild,  the Ents and the 
line 26647=>Entwives  --  and  there  were  Entmaidens  then:  ah!   the  loveliness  of 
line 26648=>Fimbrethil, of Wandlimb the  lightfooted, in the days of our  youth! -- they 
line 26649=>walked  together  and they  housed together.  But our  hearts did not  go on 
line 26650=>growing in the same way: the Ents gave their love to things that they met in 
line 26651=>the world, and the Entwives gave their thought to other things, for the Ents 
line 26652=>loved the great trees; and the wild woods, and the slopes of the high hills; 
line 26653=>and they drank of the mountain-streams, and ate only such fruit as the trees 
line 26654=>
line 26655=>####-let fall in their path;  and they learned of  the Elves and  spoke  with the 
line 26656=>Trees. But  the Entwives gave their  minds to the  lesser trees, and to  the 
line 26657=>meads in the sunshine  beyond the feet of the forests; and they saw the sloe 
line 26658=>in the thicket, and  the wild apple and the cherry blossoming in spring, and 
line 26659=>the green herbs in the waterlands in summer, and the seeding grasses in  the 
line 26660=>autumn  fields. They  did  not desire  to  speak with these things; but they 
line 26661=>wished  them to  hear and obey what was said to  them. The  Entwives ordered 
line 26662=>them to  grow  according to  their wishes, and bear leaf and fruit to  their 
line 26663=>liking; for the Entwives desired order, and plenty, and peace (by which they 
line 26664=>meant that things should remain  where they had set them).  So the  Entwives 
line 26665=>made gardens to live in. But  we Ents went on wandering, and we only came to 
line 26666=>the gardens  now and again. Then when the  Darkness came  in  the North, the 
line 26667=>Entwives crossed  the Great  River, and made new  gardens,  and  tilled  new 
line 26668=>fields, and  we saw  them more seldom. After the Darkness was overthrown the 
line 26669=>land of the Entwives blossomed richly,  and their  fields were full of corn. 
line 26670=>Many men learned the crafts of  the  Entwives and honoured them greatly; but 
line 26671=>we were only a legend to them, a secret in the heart of the forest. Yet here 
line 26672=>we still are,  while  all  the gardens of the Entwives are  wasted: Men call 
line 26673=>them the Brown Lands now. 
line 26674=>     'I remember it was  long ago --  in the time of  the war between Sauron 
