line 26747=>     Treebeard ended  his song.  'That  is  how it goes,'  he  said.  'It is 
line 26748=>Elvish, of course: lighthearted, quickworded, and soon over. I daresay it is 
line 26749=>fair  enough. But the Ents could say  more on their side,  if they had time! 
line 26750=>But now I am going to stand  up  and  take  a little sleep.  Where  will you  
line 26751=>stand?' 
line 26752=>     'We usually  lie down to  sleep,' said Merry.  'We  shall  be all right 
line 26753=>where we are.' 
line 26754=>     'Lie down to sleep!' said Treebeard. 'Why of course you do! Hm, hoom: I  
line 26755=>was  forgetting:  singing that song  put  me in mind  of  old times;  almost  
line 26756=>thought that I was talking to young Entings, I did. Well, you can lie on the 
line 26757=>bed. I am going to stand in the rain. Good night!' 
line 26758=>     Merry  and Pippin climbed on to the bed and curled up in the soft grass 
line 26759=>and fern. It was fresh,  and sweet-scented, and warm. The lights died  down, 
line 26760=>and the glow of the trees faded; but outside  under  the arch they could see 
line 26761=>old Treebeard standing, motionless, with his arms raised above his head. The 
line 26762=>bright stars peered out of the sky, and lit the falling water as  it spilled 
line 26763=>on to his fingers  and head,  and  dripped, dripped, in  hundreds  of silver 
line 26764=>drops on to  his  feet. Listening to the tinkling of  the drops  the hobbits 
