line 26799=>Treebeard  did   not  talk  to  them.  He   hummed  to  himself  deeply  and 
line 26800=>thoughtfully,  but Merry and Pippin caught no proper words: it sounded  like 
line 26801=>boom, boom, rumboom, boorar, boom, boom, dahrar boom boom, dahrar 
line 26802=>boom,  and 
line 26803=>so on with  a constant change of note and rhythm. Now and again they thought 
line 26804=>they heard an answer, a hum or a quiver of sound, that seemed  to come out of 
line 26805=>the earth, or  from boughs above  their heads, or perhaps  from the boles of 
line 26806=>
line 26807=>####-the trees; but Treebeard did not stop or turn his head to either side. 
line 26808=>     They had been going for a  long while  -- Pippin had tried to keep count 
line 26809=>of the 'ent-strides' but had failed, getting lost at about three thousand -- 
line 26810=>when  Treebeard  began to  slacken his pace. Suddenly he  stopped,  put  the 
line 26811=>hobbits down, and raised his curled  hands to his mouth so that they  made a  
line 26812=>hollow tube; then he blew or called through them. A great hoom, hom rang out 
line 26813=>like a deep-throated horn in the woods, and seemed  to echo  from the trees.  
line 26814=>Far off there came from  several directions  a similar  hoom, hom, hoom that 
line 26815=>was not an echo but an answer. 
line 26816=>     Treebeard  now perched Merry and Pippin on his shoulders  and strode on 
line 26817=>again, every now and then sending out another horn-call,  and each time  the 
line 26818=>answers came louder and nearer. In this way they came at last to what looked 
line 26819=>like an impenetrable  wall of dark evergreen trees, trees of a kind that the 
line 26820=>hobbits had never seen  before:  they branched out right from the roots, and 
line 26821=>were densely clad in dark glossy leaves like thornless holly, and  they bore 
line 26822=>many stiff upright flower -spikes with large shining olive-coloured buds.  
line 26823=>     Turning to the  left and skirting this huge hedge  Treebeard  came in a  
line 26824=>few strides to a  narrow entrance. Through it a  worn path passed  and dived 
line 26825=>suddenly down  a long steep slope. The hobbits saw that they were descending 
line 26826=>into a great  dingle, almost as round as a bowl, very wide and deep, crowned  
line 26827=>at the rim with the high dark evergreen hedge. It  was smooth and  grassclad 
line 26828=>inside,  and  there were no  trees  except  three  very tall  and  beautiful 
line 26829=>silver -birches that stood at the  bottom  of the bowl.  Two  other paths led 
line 26830=>down into the dingle: from the west and from the east. 
line 26831=>     Several Ents had already arrived.  More were coming  in down the  other  
line 26832=>paths, and  some were now following Treebeard. As they drew near the hobbits 
line 26833=>gazed  at them.  They had expected to see a number of creatures as much like 
line 26834=>Treebeard as  one hobbit is like another (at any  rate to a stranger's eye); 
line 26835=>and they were very much surprised to see nothing of the  kind. The Ents were 
line 26836=>as different from  one another as trees from trees: some as different as one 
line 26837=>tree  is  from  another of the  same  name  but  quite  different growth and 
line 26838=>history; and some as different  as one tree-kind from another, as birch from 
line 26839=>beech; oak from fir. There were a few older Ents,  bearded and gnarled  like 
line 26840=>hale  but  ancient trees (though none looked  as ancient as Treebeard);  and 
line 26841=>there   were  tall  strong  Ents,   clean-limbed  and  smooth-skinned   like 
line 26842=>forest -trees  in  their  prime; but  there were no young Ents, no  saplings. 
line 26843=>Altogether there were about two  dozen standing on the wide grassy  floor of 
line 26844=>
line 26845=>####-the dingle, and as many more were marching in. 
line 26846=>     At first Merry and Pippin were struck chiefly by the variety  that they 
line 26847=>saw: the many shapes, and colours, the differences in girth; and height, and 
line 26848=>length of leg and arm; and in the number of toes  and fingers (anything from 
line 26849=>three to nine). A few seemed more or less related to Treebeard, and reminded 
line 26850=>them of beech-trees  or oaks. But  there were other kinds. Some recalled the 
line 26851=>chestnut: brown-skinned Ents with large splayfingered hands, and short thick 
line 26852=>legs. Some recalled  the  ash:  tall straight grey  Ents  with many-fingered 
line 26853=>hands and long legs; some  the fir (the tallest Ents), and others the birch, 
line 26854=>the  rowan, and the linden.  But when the Ents all gather ed round Treebeard, 
line 26855=>bowing their  heads  slightly, murmuring in  their  slow musical voices, and 
line 26856=>looking long  and intently at the strangers, then the hobbits saw  that they 
line 26857=>were all of the same kindred, and all had  the same eyes: not all so old  or  
line 26858=>so  deep  as Treebeard's,  but  all  with the  same slow, steady, thoughtful 
line 26859=>expression, and the same green flicker. 
line 26860=>     As soon as the  whole company was assembled,  standing in a wide circle  
line 26861=>round  Treebeard, a curious and unintelligible conversation began.  The Ents 
line 26862=>began to murmur slowly: first  one joined and then  another, until they were 
line 26863=>all chanting together in a long rising and falling rhythm, now louder on one 
line 26864=>side  of  the ring, now dying away there and rising to a great boom  on  the 
line 26865=>other  side. Though he could not catch or  understand any of the words  -- he 
line 26866=>supposed the language was Entish  -- Pippin found the  sound very pleasant to 
line 26867=>listen to at first;  but gradually his attention wavered.  After a long time 
line 26868=>(and the  chant showed no signs  of  sla ckening) he found himself wondering, 
line 26869=>since  Entish  was  such  an 'unhasty'  language,  whether they had yet  got 
line 26870=>further than Good Morning; and if  Treebeard  was to call the roll, how many 
line 26871=>days it would take to sing all their names. 'I wonder what the Entish is for  
line 26872=>yes or no,' he thought. He yawned. 
line 26873=>     Treebeard  was immediately  aware  of him. 'Hm, ha, hey, my Pippin!' he 
line 26874=>said,  and the other Ents all stopped their chant. 'You are a hasty folk,  I 
line 26875=>was forgetting; and anyway it is  wearisome listening to a speech you do not 
line 26876=>understand. You may get down now. I have told your names to the Entmoot, 
line 26877=>and 
line 26878=>they have seen you, and they have agreed that you are not Orcs, and  that  a  
line 26879=>new line shall be put in the old lists. We have got no further yet, but that 
line 26880=>is quick work for an Entmoot. You and Merry  can stroll about in the dingle, 
line 26881=>if you like.  There is  a well of  good water, if you  need refreshing, away 
line 26882=>
line 26883=>####-yonder in the north bank.  There are still  some  words  to speak before the 
line 26884=>Moot really begins.  I will come  and see you again, and tell you how things 
line 26885=>are going.' 
line 26886=>     He put the hobbits down. Before they walked away, they bowed  low. This 
line 26887=>feat  seemed  to amuse  the Ents very much, to judge by the  tone  of  their 
line 26888=>murmurs, and the flicker of their  eyes; but they soon turned  back to their 
line 26889=>own  business. Merry  and Pippin  climbed up the path that came in from  the 
line 26890=>west, and looked  through the opening in the  great  hedge.  Long  tree-clad 
line 26891=>slopes  rose  from  the  lip of  the dingle, and away beyond them, above the 
line 26892=>fir-trees of the furthest  ridge there rose, sharp and white, the peak of  a  
line 26893=>high  mountain.  Southwards to their left they could see the forest  falling 
line 26894=>away  down  into  the  grey distance. There far  away there was a pale green 
line 26895=>glimmer that Merry guessed to be a glimpse of the plains of Rohan. 
line 26896=>     'I wonder where Isengard is?' said Pippin. 
line 26897=>     'I  don't  know quite where  we are,'  said  Merry;  'but that peak  is 
line 26898=>probably Methedras. and as far  as I can remember the  ring of Isengard lies 
line 26899=>in a  fork or deep cleft  at the end of the  mountains. It  is probably down 
line 26900=>behind this  great ridge. There seems to be a smoke or haze over there, left 
line 26901=>of the peak, don't you think?' 
line 26902=>     'What  is Isengard like?' said Pippin. 'I wonder what Ents can do a bout 
line 26903=>it anyway.'  'So do I,' said Merry.  'Isengard is a sort of ring of rocks or  
line 26904=>hills, I think, with a flat space inside and an island or pillar of rock  in 
line 26905=>the  middle, called Orthanc. Saruman has  a tower  on  it. There  is a gate, 
line 26906=>perhaps  more  than   one, in the encircling wall,  and I  believe there is a  
line 26907=>stream running  through it; it  comes  out  of  the  mountains, and flows on 
line 26908=>across the Gap  of  Rohan. It does not seem the  sort  of place for  Ents to 
line 26909=>tackle.  But I  have an odd feeling  about these Ents: somehow I don't think  
line 26910=>they are quite as safe and, well funny as  they seem. They seem slow, queer, 
line 26911=>and  patient, almost  sad; and yet I believe  they could  be roused.  If that 
line 26912=>happened, I would rather not be on the other side.' 
line 26913=>     'Yes!' said  Pippin.  'I  know  what you mean.  There might be  all the 
line 26914=>difference between an old cow sitting and  thoughtfully chewing, and a  bull  
line 26915=>charging; and the change might come  suddenly.  I wonder  if  Treebeard will 
line 26916=>rouse them. I am sure he means to  try.  Bu t they don't like  being  roused. 
line 26917=>Treebeard got roused himself last night, and then bottled it up again.' 
line 26918=>     The hobbits turned back.  The voices of the Ents were still  rising and 
line 26919=>falling in their  conclave. The sun had now risen high  enough to look  over 
line 26920=>
line 26921=>####-the high hedge: it gleamed on the tops of  the birches and lit the northward 
line 26922=>side of the  dingle  with  a  cool yellow  light.  There they  saw  a little 
line 26923=>glittering fountain. They walked along the rim of the great bowl at the feet 
line 26924=>of the evergreens-it was pleasant to feel cool grass about their toes again, 
line 26925=>and  not to  be in a hurry-and then they climbed down  to the gushing water.  
line 26926=>They drank a little,  a clean, cold, sharp  draught, and sat down on a mossy 
line 26927=>stone,  watching the  patches of  sun  on the grass and the shadows  of  the 
line 26928=>sailing clouds passing over the  floor of the dingle. The murmur of the Ents 
line 26929=>went on. It seemed a very strange and remote place, outside their world, and 
line 26930=>far from everything  that had ever  happened  to  them. A great longing  came 
line 26931=>over them for the faces and voices of their companions. especially for Frodo 
line 26932=>and Sam, and for Strider. 
line 26933=>     At last there came  a pause in the  Ent-voices; and looking up they saw 
line 26934=>Treebeard coming towards them. with another Ent at his side. 
line 26935=>     'Hm, hoom, here I am again,' said Treebeard. 'Are you getting weary, or 
line 26936=>feeling  impatient,  hmm,  eh? Well, I  am  afraid  that  you  must  not get 
line 26937=>impatient yet. We have finished the first stage now; but I have still got to 
line 26938=>explain things again to those that live a  long  way off, far from Isengard, 
line 26939=>and those that I could not get round to before the Moot, and  after that  we 
line 26940=>shall have to decide  what to do. However, deciding what to do does not take 
line 26941=>Ents so  long as going over all the facts  and events that  they have to make 
line 26942=>up their  minds  about. Still, it is no use denying, we shall be here a long 
line 26943=>time yet: a couple of  days very likely. So I  have brought you a companion.  
line 26944=>He  has an ent-house nearby.  Bregalad  is his  Elvish name. He says  he has 
line 26945=>already made up his mind and does not need to remain at the Moot. Hm, hm, he 
line 26946=>is the nearest thing among us to a hasty Ent. You ought  to get on together. 
line 26947=>Good-bye!' Treebeard turned and left them. 
line 26948=>     Bregalad  stood for some  time surveying the hobbits solemnly; and they  
line 26949=>looked at him, wondering when he would show any signs of 'hastiness'. He was 
line 26950=>tall, and seemed to be one of the  younger Ents;  he had smooth shining skin 
line 26951=>on  his arms and legs; his lips  were ruddy, and his hair was grey-green. He 
line 26952=>could bend and  sway like a slender tree in the wind. At last  he spoke, and 
line 26953=>his voice though resonant was higher and clearer than Treebeard's.  
line 26954=>     'Ha, hmm, my friends, let us go  for a walk!' he said. 'I  am Bregalad, 
line 26955=>that  is Quickbeam in your language. But it is on ly  a  nickname, of course. 
line 26956=>They have called me that ever since I said yes to an elder Ent before he had 
line 26957=>finished his question. Also I drink quickly, and go out while some are still 
line 26958=>
line 26959=>####-wetting their beards. Come with me!' 
line 26960=>     He reached down two shapely arms and gave a long -fingered hand to  each 
line 26961=>of  the hobbits. All that day  they  walked  about in  the  woods with  him, 
line 26962=>singing, and laughing; for Quickbeam  often  laughed. He laughed if the  sun 
line 26963=>came out from  behind  a cloud, he laughed  if  they came upon a  stream  or  
line 26964=>spring: then  he stooped  and  splashed  his  feet  and head with water;  he 
line 26965=>laughed sometimes  at some sound or whisper in  the trees. Whenever he saw a  
line 26966=>rowan-tree he halted a  while  with  his  arms stretched out,  and sang, and 
line 26967=>swayed as he sang. 
line 26968=>     At  nightfall  he  brought  them to his ent-house:  nothing more than a  
line 26969=>mossy stone set upon turves under a green bank. Rowan-trees grew in a circle 
line 26970=>about it, and there was water  (as in all ent-houses), a spring bubbling out 
line 26971=>from the bank. They  talked for a while as darkness fell on  the forest. Not 
line 26972=>far away  the voices of  the Entmoot  could be heard still going on; but now 
line 26973=>they seemed deeper and less  leisurely,  and every  now  and again one great 
line 26974=>voice would rise in a high and  quickening music,  while all the others died 
line 26975=>away.  But beside them Bregalad  spoke gently  in their  own  tongue, almost 
line 26976=>whispering; and they learned that  he belonged to Skinbark's people, and the  
line 26977=>country where they had lived had been ravaged. That  seemed  to the  hobbits 
line 26978=>quite enough to explain his 'hastiness', at least in the matter of Orcs. 
line 26979=>     'There were rowan-trees in my home,'  said Bregalad,  softly and sadly, 
line 26980=>'rowan-trees that took root when I was an Enting, many many years ago in the 
line 26981=>quiet of the  world. The  oldest were planted by the Ents to try  and please 
line 26982=>the Entwives;  but  they looked at them and smiled and  said  that they knew 
line 26983=>where  whiter blossom and richer fruit were growing. Yet there are no  trees 
line 26984=>of all  that race, the people of the Rose, that are  so beautiful to me. And 
line 26985=>these trees grew and grew, till the  shadow of each  was like a  green hall, 
line 26986=>and  their red  berries in the  autumn  were  a burden,  and a beauty  and a  
line 26987=>wonder. Birds used to flock there. I like birds, even when they chatter; and 
line 26988=>the  rowan has enough  and  to  spare. But  the birds became  unfriendly and 
line 26989=>greedy  and tore at the trees, and threw  the fruit down and did not eat it. 
line 26990=>Then  Orcs came  with axes and cut down my trees. I came  and called them by 
line 26991=>their long names, but they did not quiver, they did not hear or answer: they 
line 26992=>lay dead. 
line 26993=>     O Orofarnl, Lassemista, Carnimnril! 
line 26994=>     O rowan fair, upon your hair how white the blossom lay! 
line 26995=>     O rowan mine, I saw you shine upon a summer's day, 
line 26996=>
line 26997=>####-     Your rind so bright, your leaves so light, your voice so cool and soft: 
line 26998=>     Upon your head how golden-red the crown you bore aloft! 
line 26999=>     O rowan dead, upon your head your hair is dry and grey; 
line 27000=>     Your crown is spilled, your voice is stilled for ever and a day. 
line 27001=>     O Orofarnl, Lassemista, Carnimnril! 
line 27002=>     The hobbits  fell asleep to the sound of  the soft singing of Bregalad, 
line 27003=>that seemed to lament in many tongues the fall of trees that he had loved. 
line 27004=>     The next day they spent also in his company,  but they  did not  go far 
line 27005=>from his 'house'. Most of the time they sat silent under the shelter  of the 
line 27006=>bank; for  the wind was colder, and  the clouds closer and greyer; there was 
line 27007=>little sunshine,  and in the  distance the voices  of  the Ents at the  Moot 
