line 27061=>Indeed I have not seen them roused like this for many an age. We Ents do not 
line 27062=>like being roused; and we never are roused unless it is clear to us that our 
line 27063=>trees  and our  lives  are in  great  danger. That has not happened  in this 
line 27064=>Forest since the wars of Sauron and the Men of the Sea.  It is the orc-work, 
line 27065=>the wanton hewing  -- rbrum --  without even the  bad excuse of  feeding the 
line 27066=>fires, that has so angered us; and the  treachery of a neighbour, who should 
line 27067=>have helped us. Wizards ought to know better: they do know  better. There is 
line 27068=>no curse in  Elvish, Entish, or  the  tongues  of Men bad  enough  for  such 
line 27069=>treachery. Down with Saruman!' 
line 27070=>     'Will you really break the doors of Isengard?' asked Merry. 
line 27071=>     'Ho, hm, well, we could, you know! You do not know, perhaps. how strong 
line 27072=>
line 27073=>####-we are. Maybe you have heard  of Trolls? They  are mighty strong. But Trolls 
line 27074=>are only counterfeits. made by the  Enemy in the Great  Darkness, in mockery 
line 27075=>of Ents, as Orcs were of Elves. We are stronger than Trolls.  We are made of 
line 27076=>the  bones  of  the earth. We can split stone like  the roots of trees, only 
line 27077=>quicker, far quicker, if our minds are roused!  If we  are not hewn down, or  
line 27078=>destroyed  by  fire  or blast  of  sorcery,  we could  split  Isengard  into 
