line 27094=>     'Of course, it  is likely  enough, my friends,' he said slowly, 'likely 
line 27095=>enough that we are going to  our doom: the last march of the Ents. But if we 
line 27096=>stayed at home  and did noth ing, doom would find us anyway, sooner or later. 
line 27097=>That thought has long been  growing in our hearts;  and that is  why we  are 
line 27098=>marching now. It was not a hasty resolve. Now at least the last march of the 
line 27099=>Ents may  be worth a song.  Aye,'  he sighed, 'we may help the other peoples 
line 27100=>before we pass away. Still, I should have liked to see the  songs come  true 
line 27101=>about the Entwives. I should dearly have liked to  see Fimbrethil again. But 
line 27102=>there, my friends, songs  like trees bear fruit  only  in their own time and 
line 27103=>their own way: and sometimes they are withered untimely.' 
line 27104=>     The Ents  went  striding  on at a great pace. They had descended into a  
line 27105=>long fold of the land that fell away southward;  now they began to climb up,  
line 27106=>and up, on to the high western  ridge. The woods fell  away and they came to 
line 27107=>scattered groups of birch, and  then  to bare slopes where only  a few gaunt 
line 27108=>pine-trees grew. The sun  sank behind the dark hill -back in front. Grey dusk  
