line 27128=>Chapter 5. The White Rider 
line 27129=>
line 27130=> 
line 27131=> 
line 27132=>     'My very bones are chilled,' said Gimli, flapping his arms and stamping 
line 27133=>his  feet.  Day  had  come at last.  At dawn  the companions  had made  such 
line 27134=>breakfast as they could; now in the growing light they were getting ready to  
line 27135=>search the ground again for signs of the hobbits. 
line 27136=>     'And do not forget that old man!' said Gimli. 'I should be happier if I 
line 27137=>could see the print of a boot.' 
line 27138=>     'Why would that make you happy?' said Legolas.  
line 27139=>     'Because an old man with feet that leave marks might be no more than he 
line 27140=>seemed,' answered the Dwarf.  
line 27141=>     'Maybe,' said the Elf; 'but a heavy boot might leave no print here: the 
line 27142=>grass is deep and springy.' 
line 27143=>     'That would not  baffle a Ranger,' said Gimli.  'A bent blade is enough 
line 27144=>for Aragorn to read.  But I do not expect  him to find any traces. It was an 
line 27145=>evil phantom of Saruman that we saw last night.  I am sure of it, even under  
line 27146=>the light of morning. His eyes are looking out on us from Fangorn even  now,  
line 27147=>maybe.' 
line 27148=>     'It is likely enough,' said  Aragorn; 'yet I am not sure. I am thinking 
line 27149=>of the horses. You said last night, Gimli, that they were scared away. Bu t I 
line 27150=>did not think so. Did  you hear  them, Legolas? Did they  sound to you  like 
line 27151=>beasts in terror?' 
line 27152=>     'No,' said Legolas. 'I heard them clearly. But for the darkness and our 
line 27153=>own  fear I should have guessed that they  were beasts wild with some sudden 
line 27154=>gladness.  They spoke as horses will when they meet a friend  that they have 
line 27155=>long missed.' 
line 27156=>     'So I thought,'  said  Aragorn; 'but I  cannot  read the riddle, unless 
line 27157=>they return. Come! The  light  is growing fast. Let  us look first and guess 
line 27158=>later! We should  begin here,  near  to  our own  camping-ground,  searching  
line 27159=>carefully all about, and working  up  the slope  towards the forest. To find 
line 27160=>the  hobbits is  our  errand, whatever we may think of  our  visitor in  the 
line 27161=>night. If  they  escaped by some chance,  then they  must have hidden in the 
line 27162=>trees, or they would have been seen. If we find nothing between here and the 
line 27163=>eaves of the wood, then we will make a last search upon the battle-field and  
line 27164=>among the ashes. But there  is little hope there:  the horsemen  of Rohan did 
line 27165=>
line 27166=>####-their work too well.' 
line 27167=>     For some  time the companions crawled and groped upon  the  ground. The 
line 27168=>tree stood  mournfully above  them, its  dry  leaves now hanging  limp,  and  
line 27169=>rattling in the chill  easterly wind. Aragorn moved  slowly away. He came to  
line 27170=>the ashes of the watch-fire  near the river -bank, and then  began to retrace 
line 27171=>the ground back towards the knoll where the battle had been fought. Suddenly 
line 27172=>he stooped and bent low with his face almost in the grass. Then he called to 
line 27173=>the others. They came running up. 
line 27174=>     'Here at  last we find  news!' said Aragorn. He lifted up a broken leaf 
line 27175=>for them  to see,  a large  pale leaf of golden  hue, now fading and turning 
line 27176=>brown. 'Here is a mallorn-leaf  of Lurien, and there are small crumbs on it, 
line 27177=>and a  few more crumbs in the grass.  And  see! there are  some pieces of cut 
line 27178=>cord lying nearby!' 
line 27179=>     'And here is  the knife that cut them!' said Gimli. He stooped and drew 
