line 27182=>orc-weapon,'  he said,  holding it gingerly, and looking with disgust at the 
line 27183=>carved handle: it  had been shaped like  a hideous  head with squinting eyes 
line 27184=>and leering mouth. 
line 27185=>     'Well, here is  the strangest riddle that we have yet found!' exclaimed 
line 27186=>Legolas.  'A  bound  prisoner  escapes  both from  the  Orcs  and  from  the 
line 27187=>surrounding horsemen.  He  then stops, while still in the open, and cuts his 
line 27188=>bonds with an orc-knife. But how and why?  For if his legs were tied, how did 
line 27189=>he walk? And if his arms were tied, how did he use the knife? And if neither  
line 27190=>were tied, why did he cut the cords at all? Being pleased with his skill, he 
line 27191=>then sat down and quietly ate some waybread! That at least is enough to show 
line 27192=>that he was a hobbit, without the mallorn-leaf. After that,  I  suppose,  he 
line 27193=>turned his arms into  wings and flew away singing into the trees. It  should 
line 27194=>be easy to find him: we only need wings ourselves!' 
