line 28526=>have 
line 28527=>reached Isengard by now,  bearing a great prize. Not indeed that prize which  
line 28528=>Saruman desires  above all else, but at the least two members of my Company, 
line 28529=>sharers of a  secret hope, of  which even  to you,  lord, I cannot yet speak 
line 28530=>openly. Dare you think of what they might now be  suffering, or what Saruman 
line 28531=>might now have learned to our destruction?' 
line 28532=>     'I owe much to  Jomer,' said Thjoden. 'Faithful heart  may have forward 
line 28533=>tongue.' 'Say also,' said  Gandalf,  'that to crooked  eyes truth may wear a  
line 28534=>wry face.' 
line 28535=>     'Indeed my eyes were almost blind,' said Thjoden. 'Most of all I owe to 
line 28536=>you, my guest. Once again you have come in time. I would give you a gift ere 
line 28537=>we  go, at your own  choosing. You  have only to name aught  that is mine. I 
line 28538=>reserve now only my sword!' 
line 28539=>     'Whether I came in time or not is yet  to be  seen,' said Gandalf. 'But 
line 28540=>as for your gift, lord, I will choose  one that will fit my need: swift  and 
line 28541=>sure. Give me Shadowfax! He was  only lent  before, if loan we may  call it.  
line 28542=>But now shall ride  him into great hazard,  setting silver against  black: I 
line 28543=>would not risk anything that is not my own.  And already there is  a bond of 
line 28544=>love between us.' 
line 28545=>     'You choose  well,' said Thjoden; 'and I give him now gladly. Yet it  is 
line 28546=>a great  gift. There  is none like  to Shadowfax. In him  one of  the mighty 
line 28547=>steeds of old  has returned. None  such shall  return again. And  to you  my 
line 28548=>other guests I  will offer such things as may be found in my armoury. Swords 
line 28549=>you  do  not need,  but there  are helms and coats  of mail of cunning work, 
line 28550=>
line 28551=>####-gifts to my fathers out of Gondor. Choose from these ere we go, and may they 
line 28552=>serve you well!' 
line 28553=>     Now men came bearing  raiment  of  war from  the  king's hoard and they 
line 28554=>arrayed Aragorn and Legolas in shining mail. Helms too they chose, and round 
line 28555=>shields: their bosses were  overlaid with gold and set with gems,  green and 
line 28556=>red  and white.  Gandalf took no armour; and Gimli needed no coat of  rings, 
line 28557=>even if one had been found to match his stature, for there was no hauberk in 
line 28558=>the hoards of Edoras  of  better make than his short corslet forged  beneath 
line 28559=>the Mountain  in the North.  But he  chose a  cap of iron  and leather  that 
line 28560=>fitted well upon his  round head; and  a small  shield he also took. It bore 
line 28561=>the  running  horse,  white upon green, that was the emblem of  the House of 
line 28562=>Eorl. 
line 28563=>     'May it keep you well!' said Thjoden.  'It was made for me in Thengel's 
line 28564=>day, while still I was a boy.' 
line 28565=>     Gimli bowed.  'I am proud, Lord  of the Mark, to bear your  device,' he 
line 28566=>said. 'Indeed  sooner would I bear a  horse than be borne by one. I  love my 
line 28567=>feet better. But, maybe, I shall come yet where I can stand and fight.' 
line 28568=>     'It may well be so,' said Thjoden. 
line 28569=>     The king now rose, and at once Jowyn came forward bearing wine.  'Ferthu 
line 28570=>Thjoden hbl!' she  said. 'Receive  now this  cup  and drink  in happy  hour. 
line 28571=>Health be with thee at thy going and coming!' 
line 28572=>     Thjoden drank from the cup, and she then proffered it to the guests. As 
