line 28672=>
line 28673=>Chapter 7. Helm's Deep 
line 28674=>
line 28675=> 
line 28676=> 
line 28677=>     The sun was  already westering as they rode  from Edoras, and the light 
line 28678=>of it was in their eyes, turning all the rolling fields of Rohan to a golden 
line 28679=>haze. There was  a beaten way,  north-westward  along the foot-hills  of the 
line 28680=>White Mountains,  and  this they  followed, up and  down in a green country, 
line 28681=>crossing small swift streams by many fords. Far ahead and to their right the 
line 28682=>Misty Mountains  loomed; ever darker  and taller they grew as the miles went 
line 28683=>by. The sun went slowly down before them. Evening came behind. 
line 28684=>     The  host rode on. Need drove them. Fearing to come too late, they rode 
line 28685=>with all the speed they  could, pausing seldom. Swift and  enduring were the 
line 28686=>steeds of Rohan, but there were many leagues to go. Forty  leagues  and more 
line 28687=>it was,  as  a bird flies, from Edoras to the fords of  the Isen, where they 
line 28688=>hoped to find the king's men that held back the hosts of Saruman. 
line 28689=>     Night closed about them. At last they  halted  to make their camp. They 
line 28690=>had ridden for some five hours and  were far out upon the western plain, yet  
line 28691=>more than half their journey lay still before them. In a great circle, under  
line 28692=>the starry sky and the waxing moon, they now made their bivouac. They lit no 
line 28693=>fires, for they  were  uncertain  of events; but they set a ring of  mounted 
line 28694=>guards about them, and  scouts  rode out far ahead, passing like shadows  in  
line 28695=>the folds  of  the land. The  slow night passed without tidings or alarm. At  
line 28696=>dawn the horns sounded, and within an hour they took the road again. 
line 28697=>     There were no clouds overhead yet,  but a  heaviness was in the air; it 
line 28698=>was hot for the season of the year. The rising sun was  hazy, and behind it, 
line 28699=>following it slowly up the sky, there was a growing darkness, as of a  great 
line 28700=>storm moving out of the East. And   away in the North-west there seemed to be 
line 28701=>another  darkness brooding about  the feet of the Misty Mountains,  a shadow 
line 28702=>that crept down slowly from the Wizard's Vale. 
line 28703=>     Gandalf dropped back to where Legolas rode beside Jomer.  'You have the 
line 28704=>keen  eyes  of  your fair  kindred, Legolas,' he said; 'and they  can tell  a  
line 28705=>sparrow from a finch a league off. Tell me, can you sec anything away yonder  
line 28706=>towards Isengard?' 
line 28707=>     'Many miles  lie between,' said Legolas, gazing thither and shading his 
line 28708=>eyes with his long hand. 'I can see a darkness. There  are shapes moving  in 
line 28709=>it,  great shapes  far away upon the bank of the river; but  what they are I 
line 28710=>
line 28711=>####-cannot tell. It  is  not  mist  or  cloud that defeats  my  eyes: there is a  
line 28712=>veiling shadow that  some power lays upon   the  land, and  it marches slowly 
line 28713=>down  stream.  It  is as  if the twilight under  endless trees were  flowing 
line 28714=>downwards from the hills.' 
line 28715=>     'And behind us comes a very storm of Mordor,' said Gandalf. 'It will be 
line 28716=>a black night.' 
line 28717=>     As  the second day  of their riding drew on, the  heaviness in the  air 
line 28718=>increased. In the afternoon the dark clouds began to overtake them: a sombre 
line 28719=>canopy with great billowing  edges flecked with dazzling light. The sun went 
line 28720=>down, blood-red in a smoking haze. The spears of  the Riders were tipped with 
line 28721=>fire as  the  last shafts of light kindled the steep  faces  of the peaks of 
line 28722=>Thrihyrne: now very near they stood  on the  northernmost arm of  the  White 
line 28723=>Mountains, three jagged horns staring at  the  sunset. In the last red  glow 
line 28724=>men in the vanguard saw a black speck, a horseman  riding back towards them. 
line 28725=>They halted awaiting him. 
line 28726=>     He came, a  weary man  with dinted helm  and cloven shield.  Slowly  he 
line 28727=>climbed from his horse and stood there a while gasping. At  length he spoke.  
line 28728=>'Is  Jomer  here?' he asked. 'You come at last, but too late,  and with  too 
line 28729=>little strength. Things have gone evilly since Thjodred fell. We were driven 
line 28730=>back yesterday over the Isen with great loss; many perished at the crossing. 
line 28731=>Then at  night fresh   forces  came  over  the river  against  our camp.  All 
line 28732=>Isengard  must  be  emptied;  and Saruman has  armed the  wild  hillmen  and 
line 28733=>herd-folk of Dunland beyond the rivers, and these also he loosed upon us. We 
line 28734=>were overmastered. The  shield-wall was  broken. Erkenbrand of  Westfold has 
line 28735=>drawn off those men he could gather towards his fastness in Helm's Deep. The 
line 28736=>rest are scattered. 
line 28737=>     'Where is Jomer? Tell him there is no hope ahead.  He should  return to 
line 28738=>Edoras  before  the wolves of Isengard come there.' Thjoden  had sat silent, 
line 28739=>hidden from  the  man's sight behind his  guards; now  he  urged  his  horse 
line 28740=>forward. 'Come, stand before me, Ceorl!'  he said. 'I am here. The last host  
line 28741=>of the Eorlingas has ridden forth. It will not return without battle.' 
line 28742=>     The man's face lightened with joy and wonder.  He drew himself up. Then 
line 28743=>he knelt,  offering his  notched sword to the king. 'Command  me, lord!'  he 
line 28744=>cried. 'And pardon me! I thought--' 
line 28745=>     'You thought I remained  in Meduseld bent like an old tree under winter  
line 28746=>snow. So  it was  when you  rode  to war. But  a  west  wind has shaken  the  
