line 29200=>     'Here at least you are guarded in the  strongest fastness of the Mark,' 
line 29201=>said Aragorn.  'More  hope we  have to defend you  in  the Hornburg than  in 
line 29202=>Edoras, or even at Dunharrow in the mountains.' 
line 29203=>     'It  is said  that the Hornburg  has  never  fallen  to  assault,' said 
line 29204=>
line 29205=>####-Thjoden; 'but now my heart is doubtful. The world changes, and all that once 
line 29206=>was strong now proves unsure. How shall any tower withstand such numbers 
line 29207=>and 
line 29208=>such reckless  hate? Had I known that the strength  of Isengard was grown so 
line 29209=>great, maybe  l should  not so rashly have ridden forth to  meet it, for all 
line 29210=>the arts of Gandalf. His counsel  seems  not now so good as it did under the 
line 29211=>morning sun.' 
line 29212=>     'Do not judge  the counsel  of  Gandalf, until all is over, lord,' said 
line 29213=>Aragorn. 
line 29214=>     'The  end will not be  long,'  said the king. 'But I will not end here, 
line 29215=>taken like an old badger  in a trap. Snowmane and Hasufel  and the horses of 
line 29216=>my guard are  in the inner court.  When  dawn comes, I  will bid  men  sound 
line 29217=>Helm's horn,  and I  will ride forth.  Will  you ride  with me then, son  of 
line 29218=>Arathorn? Maybe we shall cleave a road, or make such an end as will be worth 
line 29219=>a song-if any be left to sing of us hereafter.' 
line 29220=>     'I will ride with you,' said Aragorn. 
line 29221=>     Taking  his leave, he returned to the walls, and passed round all their 
line 29222=>circuit, enheartening the men, and lending aid wherever the assault was hot.  
line 29223=>Legolas  went with  him.  Blasts of  fire leaped up from  below  shaking the 
line 29224=>stones. Grappling-hooks were hurled, and ladders raised. Again and again the 
line 29225=>Orcs gained the  summit of the outer wall, and again the defenders cast them 
line 29226=>down. 
line 29227=>     At last Aragorn stood above the great gates, heedless  of the darts  of 
line 29228=>the  enemy. As  he  looked forth he  saw the eastern sky grow  pale. Then he 
line 29229=>raised his empty hand, palm outward in token of parley. 
line 29230=>     The Orcs yelled and jeered. 'Come down! Come down!' they cried. 'If you 
line 29231=>wish  to speak  to us, come down! Bring out your  king!  We are the fighting 
line 29232=>Uruk-hai.  We will fetch him from his hole,  if  he does not come. Bring out 
line 29233=>your skulking king!' 
line 29234=>     'The king stays or comes at his own will,' said Aragorn. 
line 29235=>     'Then what are you doing here?' they answered. 'Why do you look out? Do 
line 29236=>you wish to see the greatness of our army? We are the fighting Uruk-hai.' 
line 29237=>     'I looked out to see the dawn,' said Aragorn. 
line 29238=>     'What of the dawn?' they jeered. 'We are the Uruk-hai:  we  do not stop  
line 29239=>the fight for night or day, for fair  weather or for storm. We come to kill, 
line 29240=>by sun or moon. What of the dawn?' 
line 29241=>     'None knows what the  new day shall bring him,' said  Aragorn. 'Get you  
line 29242=>
line 29243=>####-gone, ere it turn to your evil.' 
line 29244=>     'Get down or  we will shoot you from the wall,' they cried. 'This is no 
line 29245=>parley. You have nothing to say.' 
line 29246=>     'I have still this to say,' answered Aragorn. 'No  enemy has  yet taken 
line 29247=>the Hornburg. Depart, or not one of you will be spared. Not one will be left 
line 29248=>alive to take back tidings to the North. You do not know your peril.' 
line 29249=>     So great a power and royalty was revealed in Aragorn, as he stood there 
line 29250=>alone  above the ruined gates before  the host of  his  enemies, that many of 
line 29251=>the wild men paused, and looked back over their shoulders to the valley, and  
