line 29253=>and a  hail of darts and arrows whistled over  the  wall, as  Aragorn leaped 
line 29254=>down. 
line 29255=>     There  was a roar and a blast of  fire. The archway  of the gate  above 
line 29256=>which he had stood a moment before crumbled and crashed  in smoke  and 
line 29257=>dust. 
line 29258=>The  barricade was  scattered as if  by  a thunderbolt. Aragorn  ran to  the 
line 29259=>king's tower. 
line 29260=>     But even as the gate fell, and the Orcs  about it yelled,  preparing to 
line 29261=>charge, a murmur arose behind them. like a wind in the distance, and it grew 
line 29262=>to a clamour of many voices crying strange news  in the dawn.  The Orcs upon 
line 29263=>the Rock, hearing the  rumour of dismay, wavered and looked back.  And then, 
line 29264=>sudden and terrible, from the  tower above, the sound  of the great horn  of 
line 29265=>Helm rang out. 
line 29266=>     All that heard that sound trembled. Many of the Orcs cast themselves on 
line 29267=>their faces and covered their ears  with their claws. Back from the Deep the 
line 29268=>echoes came, blast upon blast, as if on every cliff and hill a mighty herald 
line 29269=>stood. But on the walls men looked up, listening with wonder; for the echoes 
line 29270=>did not die. Ever the  horn-blasts wound on among the hills; nearer now  and  
line 29271=>louder they answered one to another, blowing fierce and free. 
line 29272=>     'Helm!  Helm!' the Riders  shouted.  'Helm is arisen  and comes back to 
line 29273=>war. Helm for Thjoden King!' 
line 29274=>     And with that shout the king came. His horse  was white as snow, golden 
line 29275=>was  his shield,  and his  spear was long. At his  right  hand  was Aragorn, 
line 29276=>Elendil's  heir, behind him rode the lords of the  House of Eorl the  Young. 
line 29277=>Light sprang in the sky. Night departed. 
line 29278=>     'Forth Eorlingas!' With a cry and a great noise they charged. Down from 
line 29279=>the gates they roared, over the causeway they swept, and they drove  through 
line 29280=>
line 29281=>####-the hosts of Isengard as a wind among grass. Behind them  from the Deep came 
line 29282=>the stern cries of' men issuing from the caves, driving forth the enemy. Out 
line 29283=>poured  all the men that were left upon  the Rock.  And  ever the  sound  of 
line 29284=>blowing horns echoed in the hills.  
line 29285=>     On they rode, the king and his companions. Captains  and champions fell  
line 29286=>or fled before them. Neither orc nor man withstood them. Their backs were to 
line 29287=>the swords  and  spears of the Riders and their  faces to  the  valley. They 
line 29288=>cried  and  wailed,  for fear and great wonder had  come upon  them with the  
line 29289=>rising of the day. 
line 29290=>     So King Thjoden rode from Helm's Gate and clove his path to  the  great 
line 29291=>Dike. There the company  halted. Light grew bright about them. Shafts of the 
line 29292=>sun flared above the  eastern hills and  glimmered on their spears. But they 
line 29293=>sat silent on their horses, and they gazed down upon the Deeping-coomb. 
line 29294=>     The land had changed. Where before the green dale had  lain, its grassy 
line 29295=>slopes lapping  the ever -mounting hills,  there  now a forest  loomed. Great 
line 29296=>trees, bare and  silent,  stood, rank on  rank, with tangled bough and hoary 
line 29297=>head;  their twisted roots were buried in the long green grass. Darkness was 
line 29298=>under them. Between the  Dike and the eaves of that  nameless wood only  two 
line 29299=>open furlongs lay.  There now cowered  the proud hosts of Saruman, in terror 
line 29300=>of the  king and in terror of the trees. They streamed down from Helm's Gate 
line 29301=>until all above the Dike was  empty  of them, but below it they were  packed 
line 29302=>like swarming flies.  Vainly they crawled and clambered about  the walls  of 
line 29303=>the coomb. seeking to escape.  Upon the  east  too sheer and stony  was  the 
line 29304=>valley's side; upon the left, from the west, their final doom approached. 
line 29305=>     There suddenly upon a ridge appeared a rider, clad in white, shining in 
line 29306=>the rising  sun.  Over  the low hills  the horns were  sounding. Behind him, 
line 29307=>hastening down the long slopes,  were a  thousand  men on foot; their swords 
line 29308=>were in their hands. Amid them strode a man tall and strong.  His shield was 
line 29309=>red. As he came to the valley's brink, he set to his lips a great black horn 
line 29310=>and blew a ringing blast. 
line 29311=>     'Erkenbrand!' the Riders shouted. 'Erkenbrand!' 
line 29312=>     'Behold the White Rider!' cried Aragorn. 'Gandalf is come again!' 
line 29313=>     'Mithrandir, Mithrandir!' said Legolas. 'This is wizardry indeed! Come!  
line 29314=>I would look on this forest, ere the spell changes.' 
line 29315=>     The  hosts  of Isengard roared, swaying this way and that, turning from 
line 29316=>fear to fear. Again the horn sounded from the tower. Down through the breach 
line 29317=>of  the  Dike  charged  the  king's  company.  Down  from  the hills  leaped 
line 29318=>
line 29319=>####-Erkenbrand, lord  of Westfold. Down leaped Shadowfax, like a  deer that runs 
line 29320=>surefooted  in  the mountains. The White Rider was upon them, and the terror  
line 29321=>of  his coming filled  the enemy with  madness. The  wild men fell on  their 
