line 29333=> 
line 29334=>     So it was that in the  light of a fair morning King Thjoden and Gandalf 
line 29335=>the White Rider met again  upon the green  grass beside the  Deeping -stream. 
line 29336=>There was also Aragorn son of Arathorn, and Legolas  the Elf, and Erkenbrand 
line 29337=>of Westfold, and the lords of the Golden House. About them were gathered the 
line 29338=>Rohirrim, the Riders of  the Mark: wonder overcame their joy in victory, and 
line 29339=>their eyes were turned towards the wood. 
line 29340=>     Suddenly there was a great shout, and down from the Dike came those who 
line 29341=>had been driven back into the  Deep. There came  Gamling  the Old, and Jomer  
line 29342=>son of Jomund, and  beside them walked Gimli the dwarf. He had  no helm, 
line 29343=>and 
line 29344=>about his head was a linen band stained  with blood; but his voice  was loud 
line 29345=>and strong. 
line 29346=>     'Forty-two,  Master Legolas!' he cried. 'Alas! My  axe is  notched: the 
line 29347=>forty-second had an iron collar on his neck. How is it with you?' 
line 29348=>     'You have passed my  score  by  one,' answered Legolas. 'But  I  do not  
line 29349=>grudge you the game, so glad am I to see you on your legs!' 
line 29350=>     'Welcome, Jomer, sister -son!' said Thjoden. 'Now that I see you safe, I 
line 29351=>am glad indeed.' 
line 29352=>     'Hail, Lord  of the Mark!' said Jomer. 'The dark night has  passed  and 
line 29353=>day has come again. But  the day has brought strange tidings.' He turned and 
line 29354=>gazed in wonder, first at the  wood and then at Gandalf. 'Once more you come 
line 29355=>in the hour of need, unlooked-for,' he said. 
line 29356=>     'Unlooked-for?' said Gandalf. 'I said that I would return and  meet you  
line 29357=>here.' 
line 29358=>     'But you did not name the hour, nor foretell the manner of your coming. 
line 29359=>Strange help you bring. You are mighty in wizardry, Gandalf the White!' 
line 29360=>     'That may be. But if so, I have not shown it yet. I have but given good 
line 29361=>counsel in peril, and made  use of the  speed of Shadowfax. Your  own valour 
line 29362=>has done more, and  the stout legs of the Westfold-men  marching through the 
line 29363=>night.' 
line 29364=>     Then  they all gazed  at Gandalf with still greater wonder. Some glanced 
line 29365=>darkly  at the wood,  and  passed their  hands  over their brows, as if they 
line 29366=>thought their eyes saw otherwise than his.  
line 29367=>
line 29368=>####-     Gandalf laughed long and merrily. 'The trees?' he said. 'Nay, I see the 
line 29369=>wood as plainly as do you. But that is no deed of mine. It is a thing beyond 
line 29370=>the counsel of the wise. Better than my design, and better even than my hope 
line 29371=>the event has proved.' 
line 29372=>     'Then  if  not  yours,  whose  is  the  wizardry?'  said Thjoden.   'Not 
line 29373=>Saruman's, that is plain. Is there some mightier sage, of  whom  we have yet 
line 29374=>to learn?' 
line 29375=>     'It is  not  wizardry, but a power far older,' said  Gandalf:  'a power  
line 29376=>that walked the earth, ere elf sang or hammer rang. 
line 29377=>     Ere iron was found or tree was hewn, 
line 29378=>     When young was mountain under moon; 
line 29379=>     Ere ring was made, or wrought was woe, 
line 29380=>     It walked the forests long ago.' 
line 29381=>     'And what may be the answer to your riddle?' said Thjoden. 
line 29382=>     'If you  would  learn  that,  you  should come  with me  to  Isengard ' 
line 29383=>answered Gandalf.  
line 29384=>     'To Isengard?' they cried. 
line 29385=>     'Yes,'  said Gandalf. 'I shall  return to  Isengard, and those who will 
line 29386=>may come with me. There we may see strange things.' 
line 29387=>     'But  there  are  not men  enough  in  the Mark,  not if  they were all 
