line 29443=>
line 29444=>####-     The Orcs  were piled in great heaps, away  from the mounds  of Men, not 
line 29445=>far  from  the eaves of the forest. And the people  were  troubled in  their 
line 29446=>minds; for the  heaps of carrion were too great  for burial or for  burning. 
line 29447=>They had little wood for firing, and none would have dared to take an axe to 
line 29448=>the strange trees, even if Gandalf had not warned them to hurt  neither bark 
line 29449=>nor bough at their great peril. 
line 29450=>     'Let the Orcs lie,' said Gandalf. 'The morning may bring new counsel.' 
line 29451=>     In  the  afternoon the King's company prepared  to depart.  The work of 
line 29452=>burial was then but beginning; and Thjoden mourned for the loss of Hbma, his 
line 29453=>captain,  and cast the first earth upon  his grave. 'Great injury indeed has 
line 29454=>Saruman  done  to me and all  this land,' he said; 'and  I will remember it, 
line 29455=>when we meet.' 
line 29456=>     The sun was already drawing near the hills upon the west  of the Coomb,  
line 29457=>when  at last  Thjoden and Gandalf and their companions  rode down from  the 
line 29458=>Dike. Behind them were gathered a great host,  both of the Riders and of the 
line 29459=>people of Westfold, old and young, women and children, who had come out 
line 29460=>from 
line 29461=>the caves. A song of victory they sang with clear voices; and then they fell 
