line 29471=>through  it  Gandalf passed,  and they followed him. Then to their amazement 
line 29472=>they  found that the road ran on, and the Deeping-stream  beside it; and the 
line 29473=>sky was open above  and  full of golden light. But on either side the  great 
line 29474=>aisles  of the  wood  were  already  wrapped in  dusk,  stretching away into 
line 29475=>impenetrable shadows; and there  they  heard the  creaking  and  groaning of  
line 29476=>boughs, and far cries, and a rumour of  wordless  voices, murmuring angrily.  
line 29477=>No Orc or other living creature could be seen. 
line 29478=>     Legolas  and  Gimli were now riding  together  upon one horse; and they  
line 29479=>kept close beside Gandalf, for Gimli was afraid of the wood. 
line 29480=>     'It is hot in  here,'  said Legolas  to Gandalf. 'I feel  a great wrath 
line 29481=>
line 29482=>####-about me. Do you not feel the air throb in your ears?' 
line 29483=>     'Yes,' said Gandalf.  
line 29484=>     'What has become of the miserable Orcs?' said Legolas.  
line 29485=>     'That, I think, no one will ever know,' said Gandalf. 
line 29486=>     They  rode  in silence for a while; but  Legolas was ever glancing from 
line 29487=>side to side, and would often have halted  to  listen to  the  sounds of the 
line 29488=>wood, if Gimli had allowed it. 
line 29489=>     'These are the strangest trees that ever I saw,'  he said; 'and  I have 
line 29490=>seen many  an  oak grow from acorn  to ruinous age.  I wish that  there were 
line 29491=>leisure now to walk among  them: they have voices, and  in time I might come 
line 29492=>to understand their thought.' 
line 29493=>     'No, no!'  said  Gimli.  'Let  us leave  them!  I guess  their  thought 
line 29494=>already: hatred of all that go on two legs; and their  speech is of crushing 
line 29495=>and strangling.' 
line 29496=>     'Not of all that go on two legs,' said  Legolas. 'There I think you are 
line 29497=>wrong.  It is Orcs that they hate.  For they  do not  belong  here and  know 
line 29498=>little of Elves and  Men. Far away  are the valleys where they sprang.  From 
line 29499=>the deep dales of Fangorn, Gimli, that is whence they come, I guess.' 
line 29500=>     'Then that is the most  perilous wood in Middle-earth,'  said Gimli. 'I  
line 29501=>should  be grateful for  the part they have played, but I  do not love them. 
line 29502=>You may think them wonderful, but I have seen a greater wonder in this land, 
line 29503=>more beautiful than any grove or glade that  ever   grew: my  heart  is still 
line 29504=>full of ft. 'Strange are the ways of Men, Legolas! Here they have one of the 
line 29505=>marvels of the Northern  World, and what do they say of it? Caves, they say! 
line 29506=>Caves! Holes to fly to in time of  war, to store fodder in! My good Legolas, 
line 29507=>do you  know that the caverns of Helm's Deep  are vast and beautiful?  There 
line 29508=>would  be an  endless pilgrimage of Dwarves, merely to gaze at them, if such 
line 29509=>things  were known  to be. Aye indeed, they would pay pure gold  for a brief 
line 29510=>glance!' 
line 29511=>     'And I would give  gold to be excused,' said Legolas; 'and double to be 
line 29512=>let out, if I strayed in!' 
line 29513=>     'You have not seen, so I forgive your jest,' said Gimli. 'But you speak 
line 29514=>like a fool. Do you think those halls are fair, where your King dwells under  
line 29515=>the hill in Mirkwood, and Dwarves helped in their making long  ago? They are 
line 29516=>but hovels compared with  the caverns I have  seen here: immeasurable halls, 
line 29517=>filled with an everlasting music  of  water that tinkles into pools, as fair 
line 29518=>as Kheled-zvram in the starlight. 
line 29519=>
line 29520=>####-     'And, Legolas,  when the torches are kindled and men walk  on the sandy  
line 29521=>floors  under  the echoing domes, ah! then, Legolas,  gems  and crystals and  
line 29522=>veins of  precious ore  glint  in the polished  walls; and  the  light glows 
line 29523=>through folded marbles, shell-like, translucent as the living hands of Queen 
line 29524=>Galadriel.  There are  columns of white and saffron and dawn-rose,  Legolas, 
line 29525=>fluted  and twisted into dreamlike forms;  they spring up from many-coloured 
line 29526=>floors to meet the glistening pendants  of  the roof:  wings, ropes, curtains 
line 29527=>fine as  frozen  clouds; spears,  banners, pinnacles  of suspended  palaces!  
line 29528=>Still lakes mirror them: a glimmering world looks up from dark pools covered 
line 29529=>with clear glass;  cities.  such as  the  mind  of Durin  could  scarce have 
line 29530=>imagined in his sleep,  stretch  on through avenues and pillared  courts, on 
line 29531=>into  the dark recesses  where no light can come.  And  plink! a silver drop 
line 29532=>falls,  and the round wrinkles in  the glass make all  the  towers  bend and 
line 29533=>waver like weeds and corals in a grotto of the sea. Then evening comes: they 
line 29534=>fade  and twinkle out; the torches pass on into another  chamber and another  
line 29535=>dream. There is chamber after chamber, Legolas;  hall opening  out of  hall, 
line 29536=>dome after  dome,  stair beyond  stair; and still  the winding paths lead on 
line 29537=>into the mountains' heart.  Caves! The Caverns of Helm's Deep! Happy was the 
line 29538=>chance that drove me there! It makes me weep to leave them.' 
line 29539=>     'Then I  will wish you this fortune for your  comfort, Gimli,' said the 
line 29540=>Elf, 'that you may come safe from war and return to  see  them again. But do 
line 29541=>not tell all your kindred! There seems little left for them to do, from your 
line 29542=>account. Maybe the men of  this land  are wise  to say little: one family of 
line 29543=>busy dwarves with hammer and chisel might mar more than they made.' 
line 29544=>     'No, you do not understand,' said Gimli. 'No dwarf could be  unmoved by 
line 29545=>such loveliness. None  of Durin's race would mine those  caves for stones or  
line 29546=>ore, not if diamonds and gold could be got there.  Do you cut down groves  of 
line 29547=>blossoming trees in the spring-time for firewood? We would tend these glades 
line 29548=>of flowering  stone, not  quarry them. With cautious skill, tap  by tap  -- a 
line 29549=>small  chip of rock and no  more, perhaps, in a whole  anxious  day  -- so we 
line 29550=>could work,  and  as the  years went  by, we  should open  up new  ways, and 
line 29551=>display far chambers that  are still dark, glimpsed  only as a  void  beyond 
line 29552=>fissures in the rock. And lights, Legolas! We should make lights, such lamps 
line 29553=>as once shone  in Khazad-dym; and when  we  wished  we  would drive away 
line 29554=>the 
line 29555=>night  that has  lain there  since the hills were made; and when we  desired 
line 29556=>rest, we would let the night return.' 
line 29557=>
line 29558=>####-     'You  move me, Gimli,' said Legolas. 'I have never heard you speak like 
line 29559=>this  before. Almost you make  me regret that  I  have not seen these caves.  
line 29560=>Come! Let us make this bargain-if we both return safe out of the perils that 
line 29561=>await us, we will journey for a while together. You shall visit Fangorn with 
line 29562=>me, and then I will come with you to see Helm's Deep.' 
line 29563=>     'That would not be the way of return that I should choose,' said Gimli. 
line 29564=>'But I will endure Fangorn, if I have your promise to come back to the caves 
line 29565=>and share their wonder with me.' 
line 29566=>     'You have  my promise,' said Legolas. 'But  alas!  Now  we  must  leave 
line 29567=>behind both cave and wood for a while: See! We  are coming to the end of the 
line 29568=>trees. How far is it to Isengard, Gandalf?' 
line 29569=>     'About fifteen leagues, as the crows of Saruman make it.' said Gandalf:  
line 29570=>'five from the mouth of Deeping-coomb to  the Fords: and ten more from there 
line 29571=>to the gates of Isengard. But we shall not ride all the way this night.' 
line 29572=>     'And  when we come there,  what shall  we see?'  asked Gimli. 'You  may 
line 29573=>know, but I cannot guess.' 
line 29574=>     'I do  not know myself for certain,'  answered the wizard. 'I was there 
line 29575=>at  nightfall yesterday, but much may have happened since. Yet  I think that 
line 29576=>you will not say that the journey was  in vain  -- not though the Glittering 
line 29577=>Caves of Aglarond be left behind.' 
line 29578=>     At last the company passed  through  the trees, and found that they had 
line 29579=>come to the bottom of the Coomb, where  the road from Helm's  Deep 
line 29580=>branched, 
line 29581=>going one way east to  Edoras,  and the other north to the Fords of Isen. As 
line 29582=>they  rode from under the eaves of the wood, Legolas  halted and looked back 
line 29583=>with regret. Then he gave a sudden cry. 
line 29584=>     'There are eyes!' he said.  'Eyes looking out  from the shadows  of the 
line 29585=>boughs! I never saw such eyes before.' 
line 29586=>     The others,  surprised  by  his cry,  halted  and turned;  but  Legolas 
line 29587=>started to ride back. 
line 29588=>     'No, no!' cried Gimli. 'Do  as  you please in your madness,  but let me 
line 29589=>first get  down  from  this horse! I wish  to see  no eyes!' 'Stay,  Legolas 
line 29590=>Greenleaf!' said Gandalf. 'Do not go back into the wood, not yet! Now is not 
line 29591=>your time.' 
line 29592=>     Even as he spoke,  there came forward out of  the  trees three  strange 
line 29593=>shapes.  As  tall as trolls they were, twelve feet  or more in height; their 
line 29594=>strong bodies, stout as  young trees, seemed to be clad with raiment or with 
line 29595=>
line 29596=>####-hide of close-fitting grey and br own. Their limbs were long, and their hands 
line 29597=>had many fingers; their hair was stiff, and their beards grey-green as moss.  
line 29598=>They gazed out with solemn  eyes, but they were not  looking at the  riders:  
line 29599=>their eyes were bent northwards.  Suddenly they  lifted their long  hands to 
line 29600=>their  mouths, and  sent forth ringing calls, clear as notes  of a horn, but 
line 29601=>more musical and various.  The calls  were answered; and turning  again, the  
line 29602=>riders  saw other creatures of the same  kind approaching, striding  through 
line 29603=>the grass. They came swiftly from the North, walking  like wading herons  in 
line 29604=>their gait,  but not in their speed; for their legs in their long paces beat 
line 29605=>quicker than the heron's  wings.  The riders cried aloud in wonder, and some 
line 29606=>set their hands upon their swor d-hilts. 
line 29607=>     'You need no  weapons,' said Gandalf. 'These are but herdsmen. They are 
line 29608=>not enemies, indeed they are not concerned with us at all.' 
line 29609=>     So  it  seemed to be;  for  as  he spoke the tall creatures,  without a  
line 29610=>glance at the riders, strode into the wood and vanished. 
line 29611=>     'Herdsmen!'  said  Thjoden. 'Where  are their  flocks? What  are  they, 
line 29612=>Gandalf? For it is plain that to you, at any rate, they are not strange.' 
line 29613=>     'They are the shepherds of the trees,' answered Gandalf. 'Is it so long 
line 29614=>since you listened to tales by the fireside? There are children in your land 
line 29615=>who, out  of the twisted  threads of story, could pick the  answer  to  your 
line 29616=>question. You have seen  Ents, O King, Ents out of  Fangorn Forest, which in 
line 29617=>your tongue you call the Entwood. Did you think that the name was given only 
line 29618=>in  idle  fancy?  Nay, Thjoden,  it is otherwise: to  them  you are  but the 
line 29619=>passing tale;  all the years from Eorl the Young to Thjoden  the  Old are of 
line 29620=>little count to them; and all the deeds of your house but a small matter.' 
line 29621=>     The king was silent. 'Ents!' he said at  length. 'Out of the shadows of 
line 29622=>legend I  begin a little to  understand the marvel  of the trees, I think. I 
line 29623=>have  lived  to see  strange  days. Long  we have tended our beasts  and our 
line 29624=>fields, built our houses, wrought  our tools, or ridden away to help in  the 
line 29625=>wars  of  Minas Tirith. And that we called  the life of Men,  the way of the 
line 29626=>world. We cared little for what lay beyond the borders of our land. Songs we 
line 29627=>have that  tell of these things, but we are forgetting them,  teaching  them 
line 29628=>only  to children, as  a careless custom. And now  the  songs have come down 
line 29629=>among us out of strange places, and walk visible under the Sun.' 
line 29630=>     'You should  be  glad, Thjoden  King,' said Gandalf. 'For not only  the 
line 29631=>little  life  of Men is  now endangered, but the  life also of  those things 
line 29632=>which you have deemed the matter of legend. You are not without allies, even 
line 29633=>
line 29634=>####-if you know them not.' 
line 29635=>     'Yet  also I should  be sad,' said Thjoden. 'For however the fortune of 
line 29636=>war shall go, may it not so end  that much that was fair and wonderful shall 
line 29637=>pass for ever out of Middle-earth?' 
line 29638=>     'It may,' said Gandalf. 'The evil of Sauron cannot be wholly cured, nor  
line 29639=>made as if it had not been. But to such days we are doomed. Let us now go on 
line 29640=>with the journey we have begun!' 
line 29641=>     The company turned then away from the  Coomb and from the wood and 
line 29642=>took  
line 29643=>the  road  towards the Fords. Legolas followed reluctantly. The sun had set, 
line 29644=>already  it had sunk behind the rim of the world; but  as they rode out from 
line 29645=>the shadow of  the  hills  and looked west to the  Gap  of Rohan the sky was 
line 29646=>still  red, and a burning light was under the  floating clouds. Dark against  
line 29647=>it there wheeled and flew many black -winged birds. Some passed overhead 
line 29648=>wi th 
line 29649=>mournful cries, returning to their homes among the rocks. 
line 29650=>     'The carrion-fowl have been busy about the battle-field,' said Jomer. 
line 29651=>     They rode now at an easy pace and dark came  down upon the plains about 
line 29652=>them. The slow moon mounted,  now  waxing towards the full, and  in its cold 
line 29653=>silver light the swelling grass-lands  rose and fell  like a wide  grey sea. 
line 29654=>They  had ridden for  some four  hours from  the branching of the roads when 
line 29655=>they drew near to the Fords. Long slopes ran swiftly down to where the river  
line 29656=>spread  in stony shoals  between high grassy terraces. Borne upon  the  wind 
line 29657=>they heard the howling of  wolves. Their hearts were heavy,  remembering the 
line 29658=>many men that had fallen in battle in this place. 
line 29659=>     The  road dipped between rising turf-banks, carving its way through the 
line 29660=>terraces to the river's edge, and up again upon the further side. There were 
line 29661=>three  lines of flat stepping-stones  across  the  stream,  and between them 
line 29662=>fords for horses, that went from either brink to a  bare  eyot in the midst. 
line 29663=>The riders looked down upon the crossings,  and  it seemed strange to  them;  
line 29664=>for the Fords had ever been a place full  of the rush  and  chatter of water  
line 29665=>upon stones; but now they  were  silent. The beds of the  stream were almost  
line 29666=>dry, a bare wast e of shingles and grey sand. 
line 29667=>     'This  is  become  a  dreary  place,'  said Jomer. 'What  sickness  has 
line 29668=>befallen the river? Many fair things Saruman has  destroyed: has he devoured 
line 29669=>the springs of Isen too?' 'So it would seem,' said Gandalf. 
line 29670=>     'Alas!'  said Thjoden. 'Must we pass this way,  where the carrion-beasts 
line 29671=>
line 29672=>####-devour so many good Riders of the Mark?' 
line 29673=>     'This is our way,' said Gandalf. 'Grievous is the fall of your men; but 
line 29674=>you shall see that at least the wolves  of the mountains do not devour them. 
line 29675=>It is with their friends, the Orcs, that they hold their feast:  such indeed 
line 29676=>is the friendship of their kind. Come!' 
line 29677=>     They rode down to the river,  and as  they came the wolves ceased their 
line 29678=>howling and  slunk away. Fear  fell on them seeing Gandalf in the moon,  and 
line 29679=>Shadowfax his horse shining like  silver.  The  riders  passed  over to  the 
line 29680=>islet, and glittering eyes watched them wanly from the shadows of the banks. 
line 29681=>     'Look!' said Gandalf. 'Friends have laboured here.' 
line 29682=>     And they saw that  in  the midst  of the eyot  a mound was piled, ringed 
line 29683=>with stones, and set about with many spears. 
line 29684=>     'Here  lie  all the  Men of the Mark that fell  near this place,'  said 
line 29685=>Gandalf. 
line 29686=>     'Here let them rest!' said Jomer. 'And when  their  spears  have rotted 
line 29687=>and rusted, long still may their mound stand and guard the Fords of Isen!' 
line 29688=>     'Is  this  your work  also, Gandalf,  my  friend?'  said Thjoden.  'You  
line 29689=>accomplished much in an evening and a night!' 
line 29690=>     'With  the help of Shadowfax  -- and others,' said Gandalf. 'I rode fast  
line 29691=>and  far.  But here beside the  mound I will say this for your comfort: many 
line 29692=>fell in the battles of the Fords, but fewer than rumour made them. More were 
line 29693=>scattered than were slain;  I gathered together all that I  could find. Some 
line 29694=>men I sent with Grimbold of Westfold  to join Erkenbrand. Some I set to make 
line 29695=>this burial. They  have now followed your marshal,  Elfhelm. I sent him with 
line 29696=>many Riders  to Edoras.  Saruman  I  knew had  despatched  his full strength 
line 29697=>against you, and his  servants  had turned aside from all  other errands and 
line 29698=>gone to Helm's Deep: the  lands seemed empty  of enemies; yet I  feared that 
line 29699=>wolf-riders and plunderers might ride nonetheless  to Meduseld, while it was 
line 29700=>undefended. But now I  think you need not fear:  you will find your house to 
line 29701=>welcome your return.' 
line 29702=>     'And glad shall I be to see it again,' said Thjoden, 'though brief now, 
line 29703=>I doubt not, shall be my abiding there.' 
line 29704=>     With that the  company said  farewell to the island  and the mound, and 
line 29705=>passed over the river, and climbed the further bank. Then they rode on, glad 
line 29706=>to have left the mournful  Fords. As they  went  the  howling of the  wolves 
line 29707=>broke out anew. 
line 29708=>     There  was an  ancient highway that  ran  down  from  Isengard  to  the 
line 29709=>
line 29710=>####-crossings. For some way i t took its course beside the river, bending with it 
line 29711=>east  and  then north; but at  the last it  turned away  and  went  straight 
line 29712=>towards the gates of Isengard; and these were under the mountain-side in the  
line 29713=>west of the valley, sixteen miles  or more from its mouth.  This  road  they 
line 29714=>followed but they  did not ride upon it;  for the ground beside it  was firm 
line 29715=>and level, covered for many miles about with short springing turf. They rode  
line 29716=>now more swiftly, and by midnight the Fords were nearly five leagues behind. 
line 29717=>Then they halted, ending their night's journey, for the King was weary. They 
line 29718=>were come to  the feet  of the  Misty  Mountains, and the long  arms of  Nan 
line 29719=>Curunnr stretched down to  meet them. Dark lay the vale before them, for the 
line 29720=>moon had  passed  into  the West, and its light was hidden by the hills. But 
line 29721=>out of the deep shadow of the dale rose a vast spire of smoke and vapour; as 
line 29722=>it mounted, it caught the rays of the sinking moon, and spread in shimmering 
line 29723=>billows, black and silver, over the starry sky. 
line 29724=>     'What do you  think  of that,  Gandalf?' asked Aragorn.  'One would say 
line 29725=>that all the Wizard's Vale was burning.' 
line 29726=>     'There  is ever a fume above  that  valley in these  days,' said Jomer: 
line 29727=>'but I have never seen aught like this before. These are  steams rather than 
line 29728=>smokes. Saruman is brewing some devilry to greet us. Maybe he is boiling all 
line 29729=>the waters of Isen, and that is why the river runs dry.' 
line 29730=>     'Maybe he is,' said Gandalf. 'Tomorrow we shall learn what he is doing. 
line 29731=>Now let us rest for a while,  if we can.' 
line 29732=>     They camped  beside  the bed of the Isen river; it was still silent and 
line 29733=>empty. Some of them slept a little. But late in the night the watchmen cried 
line 29734=>out, and all awoke. The moon was gone.  Stars were  shining  above; but over 
line 29735=>the ground there crept a darkness blacker than the night.  On both  sides of 
line 29736=>the river it rolled towards them, going northward. 
line 29737=>     'Stay where you are!' said Gandalf. 'Draw no weapons! Wait! and it will 
line 29738=>pass you by!' 
line 29739=>     A mist gathered about  them. Above  them a  few stars  still  glimmered 
line 29740=>faintly;  but  on either side there arose  walls of impenetrable gloom; they 
line 29741=>were in a narrow  lane between moving towers of shadow. Voices  they  heard, 
line 29742=>whisperings  and groanings and an  endless  rustling sigh;  the  earth shook 
line 29743=>under them. Long  it  seemed to them that they sat  and  were afraid; but at 
line 29744=>last the darkness and the rumour passed, and vanished between the mountain's 
line 29745=>arms. 
line 29746=>     Away south upon the Hornburg, in the  middle  night  men heard a  great 
line 29747=>
line 29748=>####-noise, as a wind  in the valley, and the ground trembled; and all were afraid 
line 29749=>and no one ventured to go forth. But in the morning  they went  out and were 
line 29750=>amazed; for  the slain Orcs were gone, and the trees also. Far down into the 
line 29751=>valley of the Deep  the grass was crushed   and trampled brown,  as if  giant 
line 29752=>herdsmen had  pastured  great droves of  cattle there;  but a mile below the 
line 29753=>Dike a huge pit had  been delved in the earth, and over it stones were piled 
line 29754=>into  a  hill.  Men believed that the Orcs whom they had  slain  were buried 
line 29755=>there;  but whether those  who had  fled into  the wood were with them, none 
line 29756=>could say, for no man  ever  set foot upon that hill. The Death Down it  was 
line 29757=>afterwards called, and no grass would grow there. But the strange trees were 
line 29758=>never seen in Deeping-coomb again; they had  returned at night, and had gone 
line 29759=>far  away to the dark dales  of  Fangorn.  Thus they were  revenged upon the 
line 29760=>Orcs. 
line 29761=>     The king  and his company slept  no more that  night;  but they saw and 
line 29762=>heard  no other strange thing,  sa ve one: the voice of the river beside them 
line 29763=>suddenly  awoke. There  was a  rush of water hurrying down among the stones;  
line 29764=>and when it had  passed, the Isen flowed and bubbled in its bed again, as it 
line 29765=>had ever done. 
line 29766=>     At  dawn  they made ready to go on. The light came grey  and pale,  and 
line 29767=>they  did  not see  the rising of the sun. The air above was heavy with fog, 
line 29768=>and a reek lay on the land about them. They went slowly, riding now upon the 
line 29769=>highway.  It  was broad and  hard, and  well -tended. Dimly through the mists 
line 29770=>they could  descry the long arm of the mountains rising on  their left. They 
line 29771=>had passed into Nan Curunnr, the Wizard's Vale. That was a sheltered valley, 
line 29772=>open only to the South. Once  it had been fair and green, and through it the 
line 29773=>Isen flowed, already deep and strong before it found  the plains; for it was 
line 29774=>fed by many springs and lesser streams among  the rain-washed hills. and all  
line 29775=>about it there had lain a pleasant, fertile land. 
line 29776=>     It was not so now. Beneath the walls of Isengard there still were acres 
line 29777=>tilled  by  the  slaves  of Saruman;  but  most  of the valley had  become a  
line 29778=>wilderness of  weeds and  thorns.  Brambles  trailed  upon  the  ground,  or 
line 29779=>clambering over bush and  bank, made shaggy caves where small beasts 
line 29780=>housed. 
line 29781=>No  trees grew there; but among  the rank  grasses  could still be  seen the 
line 29782=>burned and axe-hewn stumps of ancient groves. It  was  a sad country, silent  
line 29783=>now  but for the stony noise  of quick  waters. Smokes and steams drifted in  
line 29784=>sullen clouds and lurked  in the  hollows.  The  riders did  not speak.  Many 
line 29785=>
line 29786=>####-doubted in their hearts, wondering to what dismal end their journey led. 
line 29787=>     After they had ridden for some miles, the highway became a wide street,  
line 29788=>paved with great flat stones, squared and laid with skill; no blade of  grass 
line 29789=>was seen in any joint. Deep  gutters, filled with  trickling water. ran down 
line 29790=>on either side. Suddenly  a tall pillar loomed up before them. It was black; 
line 29791=>and set upon it was a great stone, carved and painted in the likeness  of  a  
line 29792=>long  White Hand. Its finger pointed north. Not far now they knew  that  the 
line 29793=>gates of Isengard  must stand, and  their hearts  were heavy; but their eyes 
line 29794=>could not pierce the mists ahead. 
line 29795=>     Beneath  the  mountain's  arm within  the  Wizard's Vale through  years 
line 29796=>uncounted had stood that ancient place that  Men called Isengard.  Partly it 
line 29797=>was shaped  in  the making of  the mountains, but  mighty works  the  Men of 
line 29798=>Westernesse had wrought there of  old; and Saruman  had dwelt there long and 
line 29799=>had not been idle. 
line 29800=>     This  was  its fashion,  while Saruman was at  his height, accounted by 
line 29801=>many the chief of Wizards. A great ring-wall of stone, like towering cliffs, 
line 29802=>stood out from the shelter of the mountain-side, from which it ran  and then 
line 29803=>returned again. One entrance only was there made in  it, a great arch delved 
line 29804=>in the  southern wall. Here  through the black  rock a long  tunnel had been 
line 29805=>hewn, closed at either end with mighty  doors of iron.  They were so wrought 
line 29806=>and poised upon their  huge hinges, posts of  steel driven  into the  living 
line 29807=>stone, that  when unbarred they could  be moved with  a light  thrust of the 
line 29808=>arms, noiselessly. One who passed in and came at length out of  the  echoing  
line 29809=>tunnel,  beheld a  plain,  a great  circle, somewhat  hollowed  like a  vast  
line 29810=>shallow bowl: a mile it measured from rim to rim. Once it had been green and 
line 29811=>filled  with avenues, and  groves of fruitful trees, watered by streams that 
line 29812=>flowed  from the mountains to  a lake. But no green thing grew there  in the 
line 29813=>latter  days of Saruman. The  roads wer e  paved with stone-flags,  dark  and 
line 29814=>hard;  and beside their borders instead of trees there marched long lines of 
line 29815=>pillars, some of marble, some of copper and of iron. joined by heavy chains.  
line 29816=>     Many  houses  there  were,  chambers,  halls,  and  passages,  cut  and 
line 29817=>tunnelled back into the  walls upon their  inner side, so that all  the open 
line 29818=>circle  was overlooked by countless windows and dark doors. Thousands  could 
line 29819=>dwell  there,  workers, servants, slaves, and warriors with  great  store of 
line 29820=>arms; wolves  were fed and stabled in deep dens beneath. The plain, too, was 
line 29821=>bored and delved. Shafts were driven deep into the  ground; their upper ends  
line 29822=>were  covered by low mounds and domes of stone, so that in the moonlight the 
line 29823=>
line 29824=>####-Ring  of Isengard looked like a  graveyard  of  unquiet dead. For the ground  
line 29825=>trembled. The shafts  ran  down by many slopes and  spiral stairs to caverns 
line 29826=>far under; there Saruman had treasuries,  store-houses, armouries, smithies,  
line 29827=>and  great  furnaces.  Iron  wheels  revolved  there endlessly, and  hammers 
line 29828=>thudded. At night plumes of vapour steamed from the vents, lit  from beneath 
line 29829=>with red light, or blue, or venomous green. 
line 29830=>     To the  centre  all the roads ran between  their chains. There stood  a  
line 29831=>tower of  marvellous shape.  It  was  fashioned by  the builders of old, who 
line 29832=>smoothed  the  Ring of Isengard, and yet it seemed  a thing not  made by the 
line 29833=>craft  of Men, but riven from the bones of the  earth in the ancient torment 
line 29834=>of the hills. A peak and isle of rock  it was. black and gleaming hard: four 
line 29835=>mighty piers of many-sided stone were  welded  into one, but near the summit 
line 29836=>they  opened  into gaping  horns. their  pinnacles sharp  as the  points  of 
line 29837=>spears, keen-edged as  knives. Between  them was a narrow  space,  and there 
line 29838=>upon a floor of   polished stone,  written  with  strange signs,  a man might  
line 29839=>stand  five  hundred feet above the plain. This was Orthanc,  the citadel of 
line 29840=>Saruman, the  name of which had (by design or chance) a twofold meaning; for  
line 29841=>in the Elvish  speech orthanc  signifies Mount Fang,  but in the language of 
line 29842=>the Mark of old the Cunning Mind. 
line 29843=>     A strong  place  and wonderful  was  Isengard,  and  long  it had  been 
line 29844=>beautiful;  and there great lords had dwelt, the wardens of  Gondor upon the 
line 29845=>West, and wise men that watched the stars.  But Saruman had slowly shaped it 
line 29846=>to  his  shifting  purposes,  and made  it  better.  as  he  thought,  being 
line 29847=>deceived-for  all  those arts and  subtle devices, for which  he forsook his 
line 29848=>former  wisdom, and which fondly  he imagined  were his own. came  but  
line 29849=>from 
line 29850=>Mordor; so that what he made was naught, only a little copy, a child's model  
line 29851=>or a slave's  flattery, of that  vast fortress. armoury, prison,  furnace of 
line 29852=>great power, Barad-dyr, the Dark Tower, which suffered no rival, and laughed 
line 29853=>at  flattery, biding its  time, secure  in  its pride and  its  immeasurable 
line 29854=>strength. 
line 29855=>     This  was  the stronghold of  Saruman, as  fame reported it; for within 
line 29856=>living memory the men of Rohan had not passed its gates, save perhaps a few,  
line 29857=>such as Wormtongue, who came in secret and told no man what they saw.  
line 29858=>     Now Gandalf rode to the great pillar of the Hand, and passed it: and as 
line 29859=>he did so the Riders  saw to  their wonder that  the Hand appeared no longer  
line 29860=>white. It was stained as with dried blood; and looking closer they perceived 
line 29861=>
line 29862=>####-that its  nails were red.  Unheeding  Gandalf rode  on  into  the mist,  and 
line 29863=>reluctantly  they followed him. All about them now,  as if  there had been a  
line 29864=>sudden flood.  wide pools of water lay beside the road, filling the hollows.  
line 29865=>and rills went trickling down among the stones.  
line 29866=>     At last Gandalf  halted  and beckoned to them; and they  came, and  saw 
line 29867=>that beyond him  the mists  had cleared, and a pale sunlight shone. The hour  
line 29868=>of noon had passed. They were come to the doors of Isengard. 
line 29869=>     But the  doors lay  hurled and twisted  on the ground.  And  all about, 
line 29870=>stone, cracked  and  splintered into  countless jagged shards, was scattered 
line 29871=>far and wide, or piled in ruinous heaps. The great arch  still stood, but it 
line 29872=>opened now upon a roofless chasm: the tunnel was laid bare.  and through the 
line 29873=>cliff-like walls  on  either side great  rents  and  breaches had been torn; 
line 29874=>their towers were beaten into  dust. If the Great Sea had risen in wrath and 
line 29875=>fallen on the hills with storm. it could ha ve worked no greater ruin. 
line 29876=>     The ring beyond was filled with steaming water: a bubbling cauldron, in 
line 29877=>which  there heaved  and floated  a wreckage of beams and  spars, chests and 
line 29878=>casks and broken  gear. Twisted and leaning pillars reared their  splintered 
line 29879=>stems above the  flood. but all the roads were drowned. Far off, it  seemed, 
line 29880=>half veiled in  winding cloud, there loomed the  island rock. Still dark and 
line 29881=>tall, unbroken by the storm,  the tower of Orthanc stood. Pale waters lapped  
line 29882=>about its feet. 
line 29883=>     The  king and all his company  sat silent on  their horses, marvelling, 
line 29884=>perceiving  that the power of Saruman was overthrown; but how they could not 
line 29885=>guess.  And  now they turned their eyes towards the archway  and  the ruined 
line 29886=>gates. There they  saw close  beside  them a great rubble-heap; and suddenly 
line 29887=>they were aware  of two small figures  lying on it at their ease, grey-clad, 
line 29888=>hardly  to  be seen  among  the  stones. There were  bottles and  bowls  and 
line 29889=>platters  laid beside them, as if  they had just eaten  well, and now rested 
line 29890=>from their labour. One seemed asleep; the other, with crossed legs  and arms 
line 29891=>behind his head,  leaned  back against a broken rock and sent from his mouth 
line 29892=>long wisps and little rings of thin blue smoke. 
line 29893=>     For  a  moment Thjoden  and Jomer  and all  his men  stared at  them in 
