line 30221=>Forest itself  was  moving  behind  us. I thought  I was dreaming  an entish 
line 30222=>dream, but  Pippin had noticed  it too. We were both frightened; but  we did  
line 30223=>not find out more about it until later. 
line 30224=>     'It  was  the  Huorns,  or so the Ents call them  in "short  language". 
line 30225=>Treebeard  won't say much about them,  but  I think they are Ents that  have 
line 30226=>become almost  like trees, at least to look at. They stand here and there in 
line 30227=>the wood or under its eaves, silent, watching endlessly over the trees;  but 
line 30228=>deep  in the  darkest  dales there  are hundreds and  hundreds  of  them,  I 
line 30229=>believe. 
line 30230=>     'There is a great power in  them, and they seem able to wrap themselves 
line 30231=>in shadow: it  is difficult to see  them moving. But  they do. They can move 
line 30232=>very quickly, if  they are angry.  You  stand still  looking at the weather, 
line 30233=>
line 30234=>####-maybe, or listening to the rustling of  the wind, and then  suddenly you find 
line 30235=>that  you  are in the middle of a wood with great  groping trees  all around 
line 30236=>you. They still have voices, and can speak with the Ents  -- that is why they 
line 30237=>are called Huorns, Treebeard says  -- but they  have  become queer and  wild.  
line 30238=>Danger ous. I should be terrified of meeting them, if there were no true Ents 
