line 30867=>####-shame. How comes  it  that you  can  endure such company? For you are proud, 
line 30868=>Gandalf-and not  without reason, having a noble mind and eyes that look both 
line 30869=>deep and far. Even now will you not listen to my counsel?' 
line 30870=>     Gandalf stirred, and looked up. 'What have you to say that you did  not 
line 30871=>say at our last meeting?' he asked. 'Or, perhaps, you have things to unsay?' 
line 30872=>     Saruman paused. 'Unsay?' he mused, as if puzzled. 'Unsay? I endeavoured 
line 30873=>to advise you for your own good, but  you scarcely listened. You  are  proud 
line 30874=>and  do not love advice,  having  indeed  a store of your own wisdom. But on 
line 30875=>that occasion  you erred, I think, misconstruing my  intentions wilfully.  I 
line 30876=>fear that in my eagerness to persuade you, I  lost  patience.  And  indeed I 
line 30877=>regret it. For I bore you no ill-will; and even now  I bear none, though you  
line 30878=>return to me in the company  of the violent and  the ignorant. How should I?  
line 30879=>Are  we not both members of  a high  and  ancient order, most  excellent  in 
line 30880=>Middle-earth? Our friendship would profit us both alike. Much we could still 
line 30881=>accomplish together, to heal the disorders of the  world.  Let us understand 
line 30882=>one another,  and  dismiss from thought these lesser folk! Let  them wait on 
line 30883=>our decisions! For the common good I am  willing to redress the past, and to 
line 30884=>receive you. Will you not consult with me? Will you not come up?' 
line 30885=>     So  great was the power that Saruman  exerted in this  last effort that 
line 30886=>none that stood  within hearing were unmoved. But  now the  spell was wholly 
line 30887=>different.  They  heard the  gentle remonstrance  of  a kindly  king with an 
line 30888=>erring but much-loved minister. But they were shut out, listening at a  door 
