line 31541=>and Elendil's Stone was on the Tower Hills that look towards M ithlond in the 
line 31542=>Gulf of Lune where the grey ships lie. 
line 31543=>     'Each palantnr replied to each, but all those in Gondor were  ever open 
line 31544=>to the view of Osgiliath.  Now  it appears that,  as the rock of Orthanc has 
line 31545=>withstood  the  storms of time, so  there  the palantnr  of  that tower  has 
line 31546=>remained.  But alone  it could do nothing but see small images of things far 
line 31547=>off  and days remote. Very  useful, no doubt, that  was  to Saruman;  yet it 
line 31548=>seems that he was not content. Further and further abroad he gazed, until  he 
line 31549=>cast his gaze upon Barad-dyr. Then he was caught! 
line 31550=>     'Who knows where the lost Stones of Arnor and Gondor now lie buried, or  
line 31551=>drowned deep? But  one. at least Sauron  must have obtained and  mastered to 
line 31552=>his purposes. I guess that  it was the Ithil-stone,  for he took Minas Ithil 
line 31553=>long ago and turned it into an evil place: Minas Morgul, it has become. 
line 31554=>     'Easy  it  is  now to guess how quickly the roving  eye of Saruman  was 
line 31555=>trapped and held; and how  ever  since he has been persuaded  from afar, and 
line 31556=>daunted when persuasion  would not serve. The biter bit, the  hawk under the 
line 31557=>eagle's foot, the spider  in a  steel web!  How long, I  wonder, has he been 
line 31558=>constrained to  come often to his glass for inspection and instruction,  and 
line 31559=>the Orthanc-stone so bent towards Barad-dyr  that, if  any  save  a will  of 
line 31560=>adamant now looks into it,  it will bear his mind and sight swiftly thither? 
line 31561=>And  how it draws  one to itself! Have I  not  felt it?  Even now  my  heart 
line 31562=>desires to test my will  upon it,  to see if I could not wrench it from  him 
line 31563=>and turn it where I  would-to look across the wide seas of water and of time 
line 31564=>to Tirion the Fair, and perceive the unimaginable hand and mind of Flanor at 
line 31565=>their work, while both  the  White Tree and the  Golden were  in flower!' He 
line 31566=>sighed and fell silent. 
line 31567=>     'I wish I had known all this before,' said Pippin. 'I had  no notion of 
line 31568=>what I was doing.' 
line 31569=>     'Oh yes,  you had,' said  Gandalf. 'You  knew you were behaving wrongly 
line 31570=>and  foolishly;  and you told yourself so,  though you did not listen. I did 
line 31571=>not tell you all this before, because  it is only by  musing on all that has 
line 31572=>
line 31573=>####-happened that I have at last  understood, even as we ride together. But if I  
line 31574=>had spoken sooner, it would not have lessened your desire, or made it easier  
line 31575=>to  resist.  On the  contrary! No, the burned hand teaches best. After  that 
line 31576=>advice about fire goes to the heart.' 
line 31577=>     'It does,' said  Pippin. 'If all the seven  stones were laid out before 
line 31578=>me now, I should shut my eyes and put my hands in my pockets.' 
line 31579=>     'Good!' said Gandalf. 'That is what I hoped.' 
line 31580=>     'But I should like to know--' Pippin began. 
line 31581=>     'Mercy!' cried Gandalf. 'If the giving of information is to be the cure 
line 31582=>of your inquisitiveness, I shall spend all the rest of my  days in answering 
line 31583=>you. What more do you want to know?' 
line 31584=>     'The  names  of all the stars, and of all living  things, and the whole 
line 31585=>history of Middle-earth and Over -heaven and of  the Sundering Seas ' laughed 
line 31586=>Pippin. 'Of  course!  What less? But I  am  not in  a hurry tonight.  At the 
line 31587=>moment  I was  just wondering about the  black  shadow. I  heard  you  shout 
line 31588=>"messenger of Mordor". What was it? What could it do at Isengard?' 
line 31589=>     'It was a Black Rider on wings, a Nazgyl,' said Gandalf. 'It could have 
line 31590=>taken you away to the Dark Tower . ' 
line 31591=>     'But it was not  coming  for me, was  it?' faltered Pippin. 'I mean, it 
line 31592=>didn't know that I had... ' 
line 31593=>     'Of course not,' said  Gandalf. 'It is two hundred  leagues or  more in 
line 31594=>straight  flight  from Barad-dyr to Orthanc, and even a Nazgyl  would take a  
line 31595=>few hours to fly between  them.  But Saruman certainly looked  in  the Stone  
line 31596=>since the orc-raid, and more of his secret thought, I do not doubt, has been 
line 31597=>read than he  intended. A  messenger has  been sent  to  find out what he is 
line 31598=>doing. And  after what has happened tonight another will come, I think,  and 
line 31599=>swiftly. So Saruman will come to  the last pinch of the vice that he has put 
line 31600=>his  hand in. He has  no captive to  send. He has no Stone to see  with, and 
line 31601=>cannot answer the summons. Sauron will  only  believe that he  is withholding 
line 31602=>the captive and refusing to use the Stone. It will not  help Saruman to tell 
