line 31667=>     'Well, master,  we're in  a fix and  no mistake,'  sa id Sam  Gamgee. He 
line 31668=>stood despondently with hunched shoulders beside Frodo, and peered out  with 
line 31669=>puckered eyes into the gloom. 
line 31670=>     It was the third evening since they had fled from  the Company,  as far 
line 31671=>as they could  tell:  they had  almost lost count of  the  hours during which 
line 31672=>they had climbed and laboured among the barren slopes and stones of the 
line 31673=>Emyn 
line 31674=>Muil,  sometimes retracing  their  steps  because  they could  find  no  way 
line 31675=>forward,  sometimes discovering  that they  had wandered in a circle back to 
line 31676=>where they  had been hours before. Yet on the whole they had worked steadily 
line 31677=>eastward, keeping as near as they could find a way to the outer edge of this 
line 31678=>strange  twisted  knot of hills. But  always  they  found its  outward faces 
line 31679=>sheer,  high  and  impassable, frowning  over  the plain  below;  beyond its 
line 31680=>tumbled skirts lay livid festering marshes where nothing moved and not  even 
line 31681=>a bird was to be seen. 
line 31682=>     The hobbits stood now on the brink of a tall cliff, bare and bleak, its 
line 31683=>feet wrapped in mist; and behind them rose the broken highlands crowned with 
line 31684=>drifting  cloud. A chill wind` blew from the East. Night was gathering  over  
line 31685=>the shapeless  lands before them; the sickly  green of them was fading  to a  
line 31686=>sullen brown. Far away to the right the Anduin, that had gleamed fitfully in 
line 31687=>sun-breaks during the day, was now  hidden in shadow. But their eyes did not 
line 31688=>look beyond the  River,  back to Gondor, to  their friends, to the lands  of 
line 31689=>Men. South and east they stared to where, at the edge of the oncoming night,  
line 31690=>a dark line hung, like distant mountains  of motionless smoke. Every now and 
line 31691=>again a  tiny red gleam far away  flickered upwards on the rim of earth  and 
line 31692=>sky. 
line 31693=>     `What a fix! ' said Sam.  `That's the one place  in all the lands we've 
line 31694=>ever heard of that we  don't want to see any closer; and that's the one place 
line 31695=>we're trying  to  get  to! And  that's just where we can't get, nohow. We've 
line 31696=>come the wrong way altogether, seemingly. We can't get down;  and if  we did 
line 31697=>
line 31698=>####-get down, we'd find all that green land a nasty bog, I'll warrant. Phew! Can 
line 31699=>you smell it?' He sniffed at the wind. 
line 31700=>     'Yes, I can smell  it,'  said Frodo, but he did not move,  and his eyes 
line 31701=>remained fixed, staring out towards the  dark line and the flickering flame. 
line 31702=>`Mordor! ' he muttered under his breath. 'If I  must go there I wish I could 
line 31703=>come there quickly and make an  end! ' He shuddered. The wind was chilly and 
line 31704=>yet heavy with an odour of cold decay.  `Well,' he said, at last withdrawing 
line 31705=>his eyes, `we cannot stay here all night, fix or no fix. We must find a more 
line 31706=>sheltered spot,  and camp once more; and perhaps another  day will show us a 
line 31707=>path.' 
line 31708=>     'Or another and another and another,' muttered Sam.  `Or  maybe no day.  
line 31709=>We've come the wrong way.' 
line 31710=>     'I wonder,' said Frodo. 'It's my  doom, I think, to go  to  that Shadow 
line 31711=>yonder, so that a way will  be found.  But will good or evil show it to  me?  
line 31712=>What hope we had was in speed. Delay plays into the Enemy's hands-and here I 
line 31713=>am: delayed. Is it the will of the Dark Tower that steers us? All my choices 
line 31714=>have proved ill. I should have  left the Company long  before, and come down 
line 31715=>from the North, east of the River and of the Emyn Muil, and so over the hard 
line 31716=>of Battle Plain  to the passes of Mordor. But now it isn't possible  for you  
line 31717=>and me alone to find a way back, and the Orcs are prowling on the east bank. 
line 31718=>Every  day that passes is a precious day lost. I am tired, Sam. I don't know 
line 31719=>what is to be done. What food have we got left?' 
line 31720=>     'Only those, what d'you call 'em, lembas, Mr. Frodo. A fair supply. But 
line 31721=>they are better than naught, by a long bite. I never thought, though, when I 
line 31722=>first set tooth in them, that I should ever come to wish for a change. But I 
line 31723=>do now: a bit of plain bread, and a mug -- aye, half  a mug  -- of beer would 
line 31724=>go down proper. I've lugged my cooking-gear all the way from the last  camp, 
line 31725=>and what use  has  it been? Naught  to  make a fire with, for  a start;  and 
line 31726=>naught to cook, not even grass!' 
line 31727=>     They turned  away and went down into a  stony hollow. The westering sun 
line 31728=>was caught into clouds,  and night came swiftly. They slept as  well as they 
line 31729=>could  for the  cold, turn and  turn about,  in a  nook among  great  jagged 
line 31730=>pinnacles of weathered rock; at  least they were sheltered from the easterly 
line 31731=>wind. 
line 31732=>     `Did you see them  again, Mr . Frodo?' asked Sam, as they sat, stiff and 
line 31733=>chilled, munching wafers of  lembas, in the cold grey of early morning. 
line 31734=>     'No,' said Frodo. `I've heard nothing, and seen nothing, for two nights 
line 31735=>
line 31736=>####-now.' 
line 31737=>     `Nor me,' said  Sam. `Grrr!  Those eyes did give me a  turn! But perhaps 
line 31738=>we've shaken  him off at  last, the miserable slinker. Gollum! I'll give him 
line 31739=>gollum in his throat, if ever I get my hands on his neck.' 
line 31740=>     'I  hope  you'll never need to,'  said  Frodo.  `I don't  know  how  he 
line 31741=>followed us; but it may be that  he's lost us again, as you say. In this dry 
line 31742=>bleak  land we  can't leave  many  footprints, nor much scent, even  for his 
line 31743=>snuffling nose.' 
line 31744=>     'I hope that's the way of it,' said Sam. 'I wish we could be rid of him 
