line 31746=>     'So do I,' said Frodo; 'but he's not my chief trouble. I wish we  could 
line 31747=>get away from these hills! I hate them. I feel all naked on  the  east side, 
line 31748=>stuck up here with  nothing but  the  dead  flats between me and that Shadow 
line 31749=>yonder. There's an Eye in it. Come on! We've got to get down today somehow.' 
line 31750=>     But  that day wore on, and  when  afternoon faded towards evening  they 
line 31751=>were still scrambling along the ridge and had found no way of escape. 
line 31752=>     Sometimes in the silence of that barren country they fancied  that they 
line 31753=>heard faint sounds behind  them, a stone falling,  or the  imagined step  of 
line 31754=>flapping feet on the rock. But if they halted  and  stood  still  listening, 
line 31755=>they heard  no more,  nothing but  the  wind sighing over  the  edges of the 
line 31756=>stones -- yet even that reminded them of breath softly hissing through sharp 
line 31757=>teeth. 
line 31758=>     All that  day  the  outer  ridge of the  Emyn  Muil  had  been  bending 
line 31759=>gradually northward,  as  they  struggled  on.  Along  its  brink there  now 
