line 32303=>     One Ring to rule them all and in the Darkness bind them. 
line 32304=>     Would you  commit your promise to that, Smjagol? It  will hold you. But 
line 32305=>
line 32306=>####-it is more treacherous than you are. It may twist your words. Beware!' 
line 32307=>     Gollum cowered. 'On the Precious. on the Precious! ' he repeated. 
line 32308=>     `And what would you swear? ' asked Frodo. 
line 32309=>     `To be very very good,' said Gollum.  Then crawling to Frodo's  feet he 
line 32310=>grovelled before him, whispering hoarsely: a shudder ran over him, as if the 
line 32311=>words shook his very  bones with fear. 'Smjagol will swear never,  never, to 
line 32312=>let Him  have  it.  Never! Smjagol will save  it. But  he  must swear on the 
line 32313=>Precious.' 
line 32314=>     'No! not on it,' said Frodo, looking  down at him with stern pity. 'All 
line 32315=>you wish is  to see it and touch it, if  you can,  though you know  it would 
line 32316=>drive you mad. Not on it. Swear by it,  if you  will. For you know  where it 
line 32317=>is. Yes,  you know, Smjagol. It is before you.' 
line 32318=>     For  a moment it appeared to Sam that  his master had  grown and Gollum 
line 32319=>had shrunk: a  tall stern shadow, a mighty lord  who hid  his  brightness in 
line 32320=>grey cloud, and at his feet  a little whining  dog. Yet the two were in some 
line 32321=>way akin and not alien: they could reach one another's  minds. Gollum raised 
line 32322=>himself and began pawing at Frodo, fawning at his knees. 
line 32323=>     'Down! down! ' said Frodo. `Now speak your promise!' 
line 32324=>     `We promises, yes I promise!' said Gollum. 'I  will serve the  master of 
line 32325=>the Precious. Good master, good Smjagol, gollum, gollum!' Suddenly he  began 
line 32326=>to weep and bite at his ankle again. 
line 32327=>     'Take the rope off, Sam!' said Frodo. 
line 32328=>     Reluctantly Sam obeyed. At once Gollum got up and began prancing about, 
line 32329=>like a whipped cur  whose master  has patted it. From  that moment a change, 
line 32330=>which lasted for some time,  came over him. He spoke  with less  hissing and 
line 32331=>whining, and he spoke to his companions direct, not to his precious self. He 
line 32332=>would  cringe and  flinch,  if  they stepped  near  him or  made any  sudden 
line 32333=>movement,  and  he  avoided  the  touch of  their elven-cloaks; but  he  was 
line 32334=>friendly,  and  indeed pitifully anxious  to  please.  He would cackle  with 
line 32335=>laughter and caper, if any jest was made, or even  if Frodo  spoke kindly to 
line 32336=>him, and weep if Frodo rebuked  him. Sam said little to  him of any sort. He 
line 32337=>suspected him more  deeply than ever,  and if possible liked the new Gollum, 
line 32338=>the Smjagol, less than the old. 
line 32339=>     'Well, Gollum, or whatever it is we're to call you,' he  said. 'now for 
line 32340=>it! The Moon's gone. and the night's going. We'd better start.' 
line 32341=>     'Yes, yes,' agreed Gollum, skipping about. 'Off we go! There's only one 
line 32342=>way across between the North-end and the South-end. I found it, I  did. Orcs 
line 32343=>
line 32344=>####-don't use it,  Orcs  don't know  it.  Orcs don't cross the  Marshes, they go 
line 32345=>round for miles and  miles. Very  lucky  you  came  this way. Very lucky you 
line 32346=>found Smjagol, yes. Follow Smjagol!' 
line 32347=>     He took  a few  steps away  and  looked  back  inquiringly,  like a dog 
line 32348=>inviting  them for  a  walk. 'Wait a bit, Gollum!'  cried Sam. `Not too  far 
line 32349=>ahead now! I'm going to be at your tail, and I've got the rope handy.' 
line 32350=>     'No, no! ' said Gollum. 'Smjagol promised.' 
line 32351=>     In the  deep of night under hard  clear stars they set  off. Gollum led 
line 32352=>them back northward for a while along the way they had come; then he slanted 
line 32353=>to  the right away from  the steep edge  of the Emyn Muil,  down  the broken 
line 32354=>stony slopes towards the vast fens below. They faded swiftly and softly into  
line 32355=>the darkness. Over all the leagues of waste before the gates of Mordor there 
line 32356=>was a black silence. 
line 32357=> 
line 32358=>
line 32359=>####- 
line 32360=>
line 32361=>Chapter 2. The Passage of the Marshes 
line 32362=>
line 32363=> 
line 32364=> 
line 32365=>     Gollum moved  quickly,  with his  head and  neck  thrust forward, often 
line 32366=>using  his hands as well as his  feet. Frodo  and  Sam were hard put to it to 
line 32367=>keep up with  him; but he seemed  no longer to have any thought of escaping, 
line 32368=>and if they fell  behind, he  would turn and wait for  them. After a time he 
line 32369=>brought  them to the brink of the narrow gully that they   had struck before; 
line 32370=>but they were now further from the hills. 
line 32371=>     `Here it  is!'  he cried.  'There is  a  way down inside, yes.  Now  we 
line 32372=>follows it  -- out,  out away over there.' He pointed south and east  towards 
line 32373=>the marshes. The reek of them came to their nostrils, heavy and foul even in 
line 32374=>the cool night air. . 
line 32375=>     Gollum  cast up and down along the  brink,  and at length he  called to 
line 32376=>them.  `Here! We can get down here. Smjagol went  this way once: I went this 
line 32377=>way, hiding from Orcs.' 
line 32378=>     He led the way, and following him  the  hobbits climbed  down into  the 
line 32379=>gloom. It  was  not difficult,  for  the  rift was at this  point only  some 
line 32380=>fifteen feet deep and about  a dozen across. There  was running water at the 
line 32381=>bottom: it was in fact the bed of one of the many small rivers that trickled 
line 32382=>down  from the  hills to feed  the  stagnant pools and mires beyond.  Gollum 
line 32383=>turned to the  right, southward  more  or less, and splashed  along with his 
line 32384=>feet in the  shallow  stony stream. He seemed greatly  delighted to feel the 
line 32385=>water, and chuckled to himself, sometimes even croaking in a sort of song. 
line 32386=>     The cold hard lands, 
line 32387=>     they bites our hands, 
line 32388=>     they gnaws our feet. 
line 32389=>     The rocks and stones 
line 32390=>     are like old bones 
line 32391=>     all bare of meat. 
line 32392=>     But stream and pool 
line 32393=>     is wet and cool: 
line 32394=>     so nice for feet! 
line 32395=>     And now we wish -- 
line 32396=>     'Ha! ha! What does we wish?' he said,  looking sidelong at the hobbits.  
line 32397=>'We'll tell you.' he croaked. `He  guessed it long ago, Baggins guessed it.' 
line 32398=>A glint  came  into his  eyes, and Sam  catching the gleam in  the  darkness 
line 32399=>
line 32400=>####-thought it far from pleasant. 
line 32401=>     Alive without breath; 
line 32402=>     as cold as death; 
line 32403=>     never thirsting, ever drinking; 
line 32404=>     clad in mail, never clinking. 
line 32405=>     Drowns on dry land, 
line 32406=>     thinks an island 
line 32407=>     is a  mountain; 
line 32408=>     thinks a fountain  
line 32409=>     is a puff of air. 
line 32410=>     So sleek, so fair! 
line 32411=>     What a joy to meet! 
line 32412=>     We only wish 
line 32413=>     to catch a fish, 
line 32414=>     so juicy-sweet! 
line 32415=>     These  words only made  more pressing to Sam's mind a problem that  had 
line 32416=>been  troubl ing him  from the moment when he  understood that hir master was 
line 32417=>going  to adopt Gollum as a guide: the problem of food. It  did not occur to 
line 32418=>him that his master might also  have thought of  it. hut he  supposed Gollum 
line 32419=>had.  Indeed how had Gollum kept  himself  in all his lonely wandering? 'Not 
line 32420=>too well,'  thought Sam. 'He looks fair famished. Not too dainty to try what 
line 32421=>hobbit tastes like  if there ain't  no  fish, I'll wager -- supposing  as he 
line 32422=>could catch us napping. Well, he won't: not Sam Gamgee for one. ' 
line 32423=>     They stumbled along in the dark winding gully for a long time, or so it 
line 32424=>seemed to the tired feet of Frodo and Sam. The gully turned eastward, and as 
line 32425=>they went on it broadened and got gradually shallower. At last the sky above  
line 32426=>grew faint with the  first  grey  of morning. Gollum  had shown  no signs of 
line 32427=>tiring, but now he looked up and halted. 
line 32428=>     `Day  is near,'  he whispered,  as  if  Day  was  something  that might 
line 32429=>overhear  him and spring on  him. `Smjagol will stay here: I will stay here, 
line 32430=>and the Yellow Face won't see me.' 
line 32431=>     `We should be glad to see the Sun;' said Frodo, `but we will stay here: 
line 32432=>we are too tired to go any further at present.' 
line 32433=>     `You are not  wise  to  be glad of the  Yellow Face,' said  Gollum. `It 
line 32434=>shows you up. Nice sensible hobbits stay with Smjagol. Orcs and nasty things 
line 32435=>are about. They can see a long way. Stay and hide with me! ' 
line 32436=>     The three of them settled down to rest at the foot of the rocky wall of 
line 32437=>
line 32438=>####-the gully.  It was not much more than a  tall man's  height now,  and at its 
line 32439=>base there were wide flat shelves  of dry stone; the water ran in a  channel 
line 32440=>on  the  other side. Frodo and Sam sat  on one of  the  flats, resting their 
line 32441=>backs. Gollum paddled and scrabbled in the stream. 
line 32442=>     `We must  take a little food,' said Frodo. `Are you hungry, Smjagol? We 
line 32443=>have very little to share, but we will spare you what we can.' 
line 32444=>     At the word hungry a greenish light  was kindled in Gollum's pale eyes,  
line 32445=>and they seemed to protrude further than ever from his thin sickly face. For  
line 32446=>a  moment  he  relapsed into his old  Gollum-manner. 'We are famisshed,  yes 
line 32447=>famisshed we are. precious,' he  said. `What is it they eats? Have they nice 
line 32448=>fisshes? ' His tongue lolled out between his sharp yellow teeth. licking his 
line 32449=>colourless lips.  
line 32450=>     `No, we have  got no fish,' said Frodo. `We have only  got this'  -- he 
line 32451=>held up a wafer of lembas -- 'and water, if the water here is fit to drink.' 
line 32452=>     `Yess,  yess,  nice water,' said  Gollum. `Drink it, drink it, while we 
line 32453=>can! But what is it they've got, pr ecious? Is it crunchable? Is it tasty? ' 
line 32454=>     Frodo  broke  off a portion  of a wafer  and handed it  to him  on  its 
