line 32473=>he apparently convinced that they had no hidden dainties that he could share 
line 32474=>in. Then he went and sat by himself a few paces away and whimpered a little. 
line 32475=>
line 32476=>####-     'Look here!  ' Sam whispered to Frodo, not too softly: he did not really 
line 32477=>care whether Gollum heard him or  not. `We've got to get some sleep; but not 
line 32478=>both together with that hungry villain nigh, promise or no  promise. Smjagol 
line 32479=>or Gollum,  he won't change  his habits in a hurry, I'll warrant. You  go to 
line 32480=>sleep, Mr. Frodo, and I'll call you when I can't keep my eyelids propped up. 
line 32481=>Turn and about, same as before, while he's loose.' 
line 32482=>     'Perhaps you're right, Sam,'  said Frodo  speaking openly. 'There is  a 
line 32483=>change  in him, but  just what kind of a change  and  how deep, I'm not sure 
line 32484=>yet.  Seriously though,  I  don't think  there is any  need  for fear --  at 
line 32485=>present.  Still watch if you wish.  Give me about  two hours, not more,  and 
line 32486=>then call me.' 
line 32487=>     So  tired was Frodo that his head  fell forward  on his  breast  and he 
line 32488=>slept. almost as soon as he had spoken the words. Gollum seemed no longer to 
line 32489=>have any fears. He curled  up and  went quickly to sleep, quite unconcerned. 
line 32490=>Presently his breath was hissing softly through his clenched  teeth,  hut he 
line 32491=>lay still as stone.  After a while, fearing that he would  drop off himself, 
line 32492=>if he sat listening  to his two companions breathing, Sam  got up and gently 
line 32493=>prodded  Gollum.  His  hands  uncurled  and  twitched, but he made  no other 
line 32494=>movement.  Sam bent  down and said  fissh close to his ear, but there was  no 
line 32495=>response, not even a catch in Gollum's breathing. 
line 32496=>     Sam scratched his head. `Must really be asleep,' he muttered. `And if I 
line 32497=>was  like Gollum,  he wouldn't  wake up  never  aga in.'  He  restrained  the 
line 32498=>thoughts of his sword and the rope that sprang to his mind, and went and sat 
line 32499=>down by his master. 
line 32500=>     When he woke up the sky above was dim, not lighter but darker than when 
line 32501=>they had breakfasted. Sam leapt to his feet. Not least from  his own feeling 
line 32502=>of  vigour and hunger, he suddenly understood that he had slept the daylight  
line 32503=>away,  nine hours at least. Frodo was still fast asleep, lying now stretched 
line 32504=>on  his  side. Gollum  was  not to be seen. Various  reproachful  names  for  
line 32505=>himself  came  to  Sam's  mind,  drawn  from  the  Gaffer's  large  paternal 
line 32506=>word-hoard; then  it  also occurred to him that his  master had been  right:  
line 32507=>there  had  for the present been nothing  to guard against. They were at any 
line 32508=>rate both alive and unthrottled. 
line 32509=>     'Poor wretch! ' he said half remorsefully. 'Now I wonder where he's got 
line 32510=>to?  ' 
line 32511=>     'Not far, not far! ' said a  voice  above him. He looked up and saw the 
line 32512=>shape of Gollum's large head and ears against the evening sky. 
line 32513=>
line 32514=>####-     'Here, what are  you doing? ' cried Sam, his suspicions coming back  as 
line 32515=>soon as he saw that shape. 
line 32516=>     `Smjagol is hungry,' said Gollum. `Be back soon.' 
line 32517=>     'Come back now!' shouted Sam. 'Hi! Come back!' But Gollum had vanished. 
line 32518=>     Frodo  woke  at  the sound of Sam's shout and sat up, rubbing his eyes. 
line 32519=>'Hullo!' he said. 'Anything wrong? What's the time?' 
line 32520=>     'I dunno,' said Sam. 'After sundown, I  reckon. And he's gone off. Says 
line 32521=>he's hungry.' 
line 32522=>     `Don't worry!'  said Frodo. `There's  no help  for it. But  he'll  come 
line 32523=>back, you'll see. The promise will hold  yet a while. And he won't leave his 
line 32524=>Precious, anyway.' 
line 32525=>     Frodo made  light of it when he learned that they had slept soundly for 
line 32526=>hours with Gollum, and a very  hungry Gollum too, loose beside  them. `Don't  
line 32527=>think of any of your  Gaffer's hard names,' he said. 'You were worn out, and 
line 32528=>it has  turned out well: we are now  both rested. And  we  have a hard  road 
line 32529=>ahead, the worst road of all.' 
line 32530=>     `About the  food,' said Sam. 'How long's it going to take us to do this 
line 32531=>job? And  when it's done, what are we  going to do then? This waybread keeps 
line 32532=>you on  your legs in a wonderful way, though  it doesn't satisfy the innards 
line 32533=>proper, as you might say: not to my feeling anyhow, meaning no disrespect to 
line 32534=>them  as made it.  But you have  to eat some of it every day, and it doesn't  
line 32535=>grow. I  reckon we've got  enough to last, say,  three weeks or so, and that 
line 32536=>with a tight belt and a light tooth, mind you. We've been a bit free with it 
line 32537=>so far.' 
line 32538=>     `I  don't know how long we shall take to -- to finish,' said Frodo. `We 
line 32539=>were miserably delayed  in the hills. But Samwise Gamgee,  my dear hobbit  -- 
line 32540=>indeed, Sam my dearest  hobbit, friend of friends  --  I do not think we need 
line 32541=>give thought  to what comes after that. To  do the job as you put it  -- what 
line 32542=>hope is  there that we ever shall? And if we do, who knows what will come of 
line 32543=>that? If the One goes into the Fire, and we are at hand? I ask you, Sam, are 
line 32544=>we ever likely to need bread again? I think not. If  we can nurse  our limbs 
line 32545=>to bring  us to Mount Doom, that is  all we can do. More than I can, I begin 
line 32546=>to feel.' 
line 32547=>     Sam nodded silently. He took his master's hand and bent over it. He did 
line 32548=>not kiss it,  though his  tears fell on it. Then  he turned away,  drew  his 
line 32549=>sleeve  over his nose, and got up, a nd stamped about, trying to whistle, and 
line 32550=>saying between the efforts: 'Where's that dratted creature?' 
line 32551=>
line 32552=>####-     It was actually not long before Gollum returned; but he came so quietly 
line 32553=>that they did not hear him till  he stood before them. His  fingers and face 
line 32554=>were soiled with black mud. He was still chewing  and slavering. What he was 
line 32555=>chewing, they did not ask or like to think. 
line 32556=>     'Worms  or beetles or something slimy out of holes,' thought Sam. 'Brr! 
line 32557=>The nasty creature; the poor wretch! ' 
line 32558=>     Gollum  said  nothing to  them,  until he had  drunk deeply  and washed 
line 32559=>himself in the  stream. Then he  came up to them, licking  his lips. 'Better 
line 32560=>now,' he said. `Are we  rested? Ready to  go  on? Nice  hobbits,  they sleep 
line 32561=>beautifully. Trust Smjagol now? Very, very good.' 
line 32562=>     The next stage of their journey was much the same as the  last. As they 
line 32563=>went  on the gully became ever shallower and  the slope  of its  floor  more 
line 32564=>gradual. Its  bottom  was less stony and  more earthy, and slowly its  sides 
line 32565=>dwindled to mere ba nks. It began  to wind and wander. That night drew to its 
line 32566=>end, but clouds were now over moon and star, and they  knew of the coming of 
line 32567=>day only by the slow spreading of the thin grey light. 
line 32568=>     In  a chill hour they came  to the end of  the water-course. The  banks 
line 32569=>became moss-grown mounds. Over the  last shelf of rotting  stone the  stream 
line 32570=>gurgled  and fell  down into a brown bog and was lost. Dry  reeds hissed and  
line 32571=>rattled though they could feel no wind. 
line 32572=>     On either  side and in front wide  fens and  m ires now lay,  stretching 
line 32573=>away southward and eastward into the dim half-light. Mists curled and smoked 
line 32574=>from dark and noisome pools. The reek of  them hung  stifling  in the  still 
line 32575=>air.  Far away, now almost  due  south, the mountain-walls of Mordor loomed, 
line 32576=>like a black bar of rugged clouds floating above a dangerous fog-bound sea. 
line 32577=>     The hobbits were now wholly in the hands of  Gollum. They did now know,  
line 32578=>and  could not guess in that misty light. that they  were in  fact only just  
line 32579=>within the northern  borders of the marshes. the  main expanse of  which lay 
line 32580=>south of them. They could, if they had known the lands, with some delay have 
line 32581=>retraced their steps  a little, and then turning east have come  round  over  
line 32582=>hard roads  to the bare plain of Dagorlad: the field of  the  ancient battle 
line 32583=>before  the gates of Mordor. Not that there was great hope in such a course. 
line 32584=>On that stony  plain  there was no cover,  and across it ran the highways of 
line 32585=>the Orcs and the soldiers of the Enemy. Not even the cloaks of  Lurien would 
line 32586=>have concealed them there. 
line 32587=>     'How do we shape our course now, Smjagol? ' asked Frodo. 'Must we cross 
line 32588=>these evil-smelling fens?  ' 
line 32589=>
line 32590=>####-     `No need,  no  need at all,' said Gollum. 'Not if hobbits want to reach 
line 32591=>the dark mountains and go to see Him very quick.  Back a little, and round a  
line 32592=>little' -- his skinny arm waved north and  east -- `and you can come on hard 
line 32593=>cold roads to the  very gates of  His country.  Lots  of  His people will be 
line 32594=>there looking out for guests, very pleased to  take them straight  to Him, O 
line 32595=>yes. His Eye watches  that way all the  time. It caught  Smjagol there, long 
line 32596=>ago.' Gollum shuddered. 'But Smjagol has used his eyes since then, yes, yes:  
line 32597=>I've used  eyes  and feet  and  nose since then. l  know  other  ways.  More 
line 32598=>difficult, not so quick; but  better, if  we  don't want  Him to see. Follow 
line 32599=>Smjagol! He can take you through  the marshes, through the mists. nice thick 
line 32600=>mists. Follow  Smjagol very carefully, and you  may go  a long  way. quite a  
line 32601=>long way, before He catches you, yes perhaps. ' 
line 32602=>     It was already day, a windless and sullen morning, and the  marsh-reeks 
line 32603=>lay in heavy banks. No sun pierced the low  clouded  sky, and Gollum  seemed 
line 32604=>anxious to continue the journey at once. So after a brief  rest they set out 
line 32605=>again and were soon lost in a shadowy silent world, cut off from all view of 
line 32606=>the lands about, either the hills  that they  had left or the mountains that 
line 32607=>they sought. They went slowly in single file: Gollum, Sam, Frodo. 
line 32608=>     Frodo seemed the most weary of the three, and slow though they went. he 
line 32609=>often lagged. The hobbits soon  found that what had looked like one vast fen  
line 32610=>was  really  an  endless  network  of  pools,  and soft  mires. and  winding 
line 32611=>half-strangled water-courses.  Among  these  a cunning eye  and  foot  could 
line 32612=>thread  a wandering path. Gollum  certainly had that cunning, and needed all  
line 32613=>of it. His head on its long  neck  was ever turning this way and that, while 
line 32614=>he sniffed and muttered all the time to himself. Sometimes he would  hold up 
line 32615=>his  hand and halt  them, while he went forward a little, crouching, testing 
line 32616=>the ground with fingers or toes. or merely listening with one ear pressed to 
line 32617=>the earth. 
line 32618=>     It was dreary and wearisome. Cold clammy winter still held sway in this 
line 32619=>forsaken country. The only green was the scum  of  livid weed  on  the  dark  
line 32620=>greasy surfaces of the sullen waters. Dead grasses  and rotting reeds loomed 
line 32621=>up in the mists like ragged shadows of long-forgotten summers.  
line 32622=>     As the day wore on the light increased a little, and the mists  lifted, 
line 32623=>growing thinner and more  transparent. Far above  the rot and vapours of the 
line 32624=>world the Sun was riding high and golden now in a serene country with floors 
line 32625=>of dazzling  foam, but  only a  passing  ghost of her could they  see below, 
line 32626=>bleared,  pale, giving  no  colour  and  no  warmth. But even at this  faint 
line 32627=>
line 32628=>####-reminder of  her  presence  Gollum  scowled and  flinched. He  halted  their 
