line 32943=>careful  and  not to reveal that he had overheard  the debate. He let  out a  
line 32944=>loud sigh and gave a huge yawn. 
line 32945=>     `What's the time? ' he said sleepily. 
line 32946=>     Gollum sent  out a  long  hiss  through his  teeth. He stood  up  for a  
line 32947=>moment, tense and menacing; and then he collapsed, falling forward on to all 
line 32948=>fours and  crawling  up the bank  of the pit. 'Nice hobbits! Nice Sam! '  he 
line 32949=>said. 'Sleepy heads,  yes, sleepy  heads! Leave good  Smjagol to watch!  But 
line 32950=>it's evening. Dusk is creeping. Time to go.' 
line 32951=>     `High time!  ' thought Sam. 'And time we parted,  too.' Yet it  crossed 
line 32952=>his mind to wonder if indeed Gollum was not now as dangerous turned loose as 
line 32953=>kept with them. 'Curse him! I wish he was choked!' he muttered.  He stumbled 
line 32954=>down the bank and roused his master. 
line 32955=>     Strangely enough, Frodo felt  refreshed. He had been dreaming. The dark  
line 32956=>shadow  had  passed,  and  a  fair  vision  had visited him in  this land of 
line 32957=>disease. Nothing remained  of it in his  memory, yet  because of it he  felt 
line 32958=>glad and lighter of heart. His burden was less heavy on him. Gollum welcomed 
line 32959=>him  with  dog-like delight. He  chuckled and  chattered,  cracking his long 
line 32960=>fingers, and pawing at Frodo's knees. Frodo smiled at him. 
line 32961=>     'Come! ' he said. `You  have guided us well and faithfully. This is the 
line 32962=>last stage. Bring us to the Gate, and then I will not ask you to go further. 
line 32963=>Bring us to  the Gate,  and you  may  go where you wish  --  only not to our 
line 32964=>enemies.' 
line 32965=>     'To  the Gate, eh?' Gollum squeaked, seeming surprised  and frightened. 
line 32966=>'To the Gate, master  says! Yes, he says so.  And  good Smjagol does what he 
line 32967=>asks, O yes. But when we gets closer, we'll  see perhaps we'll  see then. It 
line 32968=>won't look nice at all. O no! O no!' 
line 32969=>
line 32970=>####-     'Go on with you! ' said Sam. `Let's get it over! ' 
line 32971=>     In the falling dusk they  scrambled out of the pit and slowly  threaded 
line 32972=>their way through the dead land. They had not gone far before they felt once 
line 32973=>more the fear that had fallen on them  when  the winged shape swept over the 
line 32974=>marshes.  They  halted, cowering  on the evil -smelling ground; but  they saw 
line 32975=>nothing  in the gloomy evening sky above, and soon the  menace  passed, high 
line 32976=>overhead, going maybe  on some swift errand  from Barad-dyr.  After  a while 
line 32977=>Gollum got up and crept forward again, muttering and shaking. 
line 32978=>     About an hour after midnight the fear fell on them a third time, but it 
line 32979=>now seemed more remote, as if it were passing far above the clouds,  rushing 
line 32980=>with terrible  speed  into  the  West.  Gollum,  however,  was helpless with 
line 32981=>terror, and was convinced that they were  being hunted, that  their approach 
line 32982=>was known. 
line 32983=>     `Three times! ' he  whimpered.  'Three times is  a threat. They feel us 
line 32984=>here, they feel the Precious. The Precious is their master. We cannot go any  
line 32985=>further this way, no. It's no use, no use! ' 
line 32986=>     Pleading and  kind words were no longer of any  avail. It was not until 
line 32987=>Frodo commanded him angrily and  laid a hand on  his sword-hilt  that Gollum 
line 32988=>would get up again. Then at last he rose with  a snarl, and went before them 
line 32989=>like a beaten dog. 
line 32990=>     So they stumbled on through  the weary end  of the night, and until the 
line 32991=>coming  of another  day of  fear they walked  in silence with  bowed  heads,  
line 32992=>seeing nothing, and hearing nothing but the wind hissing in their ears. 
line 32993=> 
line 32994=>
line 32995=>####- 
line 32996=>
line 32997=>Chapter 3. The Black Gate is Closed 
line 32998=>
line 32999=> 
line 33000=> 
line 33001=>     Before  the  next day dawned  their journey to  Mordor  was  over.  The 
line 33002=>marshes and the desert  were  behind them. Before  them, darkling  against a  
line 33003=>pallid sky, the great mountains reared their threatening heads.  
line 33004=>     Upon the west of  Mordor marched the gloomy range  of  Ephel DÂ®ath, the 
line 33005=>Mountains of Shadow, and upon the north  the broken peaks and barren  ridges 
line 33006=>of  Ered  Lithui, grey as ash. But as these ranges  approached one  another, 
line 33007=>being indeed  but  parts  of  one  great  wall about  the mournful plains of 
line 33008=>Lithlad and of Gorgoroth, and the bitter inland sea of NÂ®rnen amidmost, they 
line 33009=>swung out  long arms northward;  and between  these arms  there  was a  deep 
line 33010=>defile.  This was Cirith Gorgor,  the Haunted Pass, the entrance to the land 
line 33011=>of the Enemy. High cliffs lowered upon either side, and thrust forward  from 
line 33012=>its mouth were two  sheer  hills, black -boned and bare. Upon  them stood the 
line 33013=>Teeth  of  Mordor, two towers strong and  tall. In days long past they  were 
line 33014=>built by the Men of Gondor in their pride and power,  after the overthrow of 
line 33015=>Sauron and his flight, lest he  should seek to return to his old realm.  But 
line 33016=>the strength of Gondor  failed, and men slept, and for long years the towers 
line 33017=>stood  empty.  Then Sauron returned. Now  the watch-towers, which  had fallen 
line 33018=>into  decay,  were  repaired, and  filled  with arms,  and  garrisoned  with 
line 33019=>ceaseless vigilance. Stony-faced they were, with  dark  window-holes staring 
line 33020=>north and east and west, and each window was full of sleepless eyes. 
line 33021=>     Across the  mouth of the pass, from cliff to cliff,  the Dark Lord  had 
line 33022=>built a rampart of stone. In it  there  was a single gate of  iron, and upon 
line 33023=>its battlement sentinels paced unceasingly. Beneath the hills on either side 
line 33024=>the  rock  was bored into  a hundred caves and maggot -holes: there a host of 
line 33025=>orcs lurked, ready at a signal to issue forth like black ants going to  war. 
line 33026=>None could pass the  Teeth of  Mordor and not feel  their bite, unless  they 
line 33027=>were summoned by Sauron, or knew the  secret  passwords  that would open 
line 33028=>the 
line 33029=>Morannon, the black gate of his land. 
line 33030=>     The two hobbits  gazed at the towers and the wall in despair. Even from 
line 33031=>a distance they could see  in the dim light the movement of the black guards 
line 33032=>upon the wall,  and  the patrols before the gate. They lay now peering  over  
line 33033=>the edge of a rocky hollow beneath the out-stretched shadow of the northmost  
line 33034=>
line 33035=>####-buttress of Ephel DÂ®ath. Winging  the heavy air in a straight flight a crow, 
line 33036=>maybe, would have flown  but a furlong from  their hiding-place to the  black 
line 33037=>summit  of  the  nearer  tower. A faint smoke curled  above it, as  if  fire 
line 33038=>smouldered in the hill beneath. 
line 33039=>     Day  came, and the fallow sun blinked over the lifeless  ridges of Ered 
line 33040=>Lithui.  Then su ddenly the cry of brazen-throated  trumpets was  heard: from 
line 33041=>the watch-towers they blared, and far away from hidden holds and outposts in 
line 33042=>the  hills  came  answering calls; and  further  still, remote but  deep and 
line 33043=>ominous, there echoed in  the hollow land  beyond the mighty horns  and drums 
line 33044=>of Barad-dyr. Another dreadful day of fear and toil had come to Mordor;  and 
line 33045=>the night-guards were  summoned to their dungeons and  deep  halls, and  the 
line 33046=>day-guards, evil-eyed and fell,  were marching to their posts. Steel gleamed 
line 33047=>dimly on the battlement. 
line 33048=>     `Well, here we are! ' said Sam. `Here's the Gate, and it looks to me as 
line 33049=>if that's about as far as we are ever going  to get. My word, but the Gaffer  
line 33050=>would have a thing or two to say, if he saw me now! Often said I'd come to a 
line 33051=>bad  end, if I didn't watch my step, he  did. But  now I don't suppose  I'll 
line 33052=>ever see  the  old fellow again. He'll miss his chance of  I told'ee so, Sam: 
line 33053=>more's the  pity. He could go on telling me as  long as he'd got breath,  if 
line 33054=>only I could see his old face again. But I'd have to get a wash first, or he 
line 33055=>wouldn't know me. 
line 33056=>     `I suppose it's no good asking "what way do we go now?" We  can't go no 
line 33057=>further -unless we want to ask the orcs for a lift.' 
line 33058=>     `No, no! ' said Gollum. `No use. We can't  go further. Smjagol  said so. 
