line 33181=>the desire of it may betray you to a bitter end. You will never get it back. 
line 33182=>In  the last need, Smjagol, I should put  on the Precious; and the  Precious 
line 33183=>mastered you  long ago. If  I,  wearing  it, were to  command you, you would 
line 33184=>obey, even if it were to leap from a precipice  or to cast yourself into the 
line 33185=>fire. And such would be my command. So have a care, Smjagol!' 
line 33186=>
line 33187=>####-     Sam looked at his  master with approval, but also with surprise:  there 
line 33188=>was a look in his face and a tone in his voice that he had not known before. 
line 33189=>It had  always been a notion  of his that the kindness of dear Mr. Frodo was 
line 33190=>of  such a high  degree that it  must imply a fair measure of  blindness. Of 
line 33191=>course, he  also  firmly held the incompatible belief that Mr. Frodo was the 
line 33192=>wisest person in the world (with the possible exception of Old Mr. Bilbo and 
line 33193=>of Gandalf). Gollum in  his  own  way,  and with  much  more excuse  as  his 
line 33194=>acquaintance was  much briefer, may have _made a  similar mistake, confusing 
line 33195=>kindness and blindness.  At any rate  this speech abashed and terrified him. 
line 33196=>He grovelled on the ground and could speak no clear words but nice master. 
line 33197=>     Frodo waited patiently for a while,  then he spoke again less  sternly. 
line 33198=>`Come now, Gollum  or Smjagol if  you wish, tell  me of this other way,  and 
line 33199=>show me,  if you can,  what hope  there is in  it,  enough to justify me  in 
line 33200=>turning aside from my plain path. I am in haste.' 
line 33201=>     But  Gollum  was in  a  pitiable state, and  Frodo's  threat  had quite 
line 33202=>unnerved  him. It was not easy to get any clear account out of him, amid his 
line 33203=>mumblings and squeakings, and the frequent interruptions in which he crawled 
line 33204=>on the floor and begged them both to be kind to `poor little Smjagol'. After  
line 33205=>a  while he grew a  little calmer, and Frodo gathered bit by bit that, if  a  
line 33206=>traveller followed the road  that turned west of Ephel DÂ®ath,  he would come 
line 33207=>in  time to a  crossing in a circle of  dark trees. On the right a road went 
line 33208=>down to Osgiliath and the bridges of the Anduin; in the middle the road went 
line 33209=>on southwards.  
line 33210=>     `On,  on,  on,'  said Gollum. `We  never went that way, but they say it 
