line 34190=>Faramir. `Then maybe you can see it in your mind's eye: a great horn  of the  
line 34191=>wild ox of the East, bound with silver, and written with ancient characters. 
line 34192=>That horn the eldest son of our house has borne for many generations; and it  
line 34193=>is said that if it be blown at need anywhere within the bounds of Gondor, as 
line 34194=>the realm was of old, its voice will not pass unheeded. 
line 34195=>     'Five days ere I set out on this venture, eleven days ago at about this 
line 34196=>hour of  the  day, I heard  the blowing of that horn: from the northward  it 
line 34197=>seemed, but  dim, as if  it were but an echo in the mind. A boding of ill we 
line 34198=>thought it, my father and I, for no tidings had we heard of Boromir since he 
line 34199=>went away, and no watcher on our borders had seen him pass. And on the third 
line 34200=>night after another and a stranger thing befell me. 
line 34201=>     'I sat at night by  the waters of Anduin,  in the grey dark  under  the 
line 34202=>young pale moon, watching the ever -moving  stream;  and the  sad  reeds were 
line 34203=>rustling. So do we  ever watch the shores  nigh Osgiliath, which our enemies 
line 34204=>now partly hold,  and issue from it to harry our lands. Bu t  that night  all 
