line 34848=>     `But folk  must  grow weary  there, even  in their  gardens, as  do all 
line 34849=>things under the Sun  of this world. And you are far from  home and wayworn. 
line 34850=>No more tonight. Sleep, both  of you -- in peace, if you can. Fear not! I do 
line 34851=>not wish to  see it, or  touch  it, or know more of it than I know (which is 
line 34852=>enough), lest peril perchance waylay  me and I  fall lower  in the test than 
line 34853=>Frodo son of Drogo. Go now to rest -- but  first tell  me only, if you will, 
line 34854=>whither you wish to go,  and  what  to do.  For I  must watch, and  wait, and 
line 34855=>think.  Time passes.  In the morning  we  must each  go swiftly  on the ways 
line 34856=>appointed to us.' 
line 34857=>     Frodo had felt himself trembling as the first shock of fear passed. Now 
line 34858=>a great  weariness came  down on him like  a  cloud. He could dissemble  and 
line 34859=>resist no longer. 
line 34860=>     'I was going to find a way into Mordor,' he said faintly. `I  was going 
line 34861=>to Gorgoroth. I must  find  the Mountain of Fire and cast the thing into the 
line 34862=>
line 34863=>####-gulf of Doom. Gandalf said so. I do not think I shall ever get there.' 
line 34864=>     Faramir stared at him for a moment in grave astonishment. Then suddenly 
line 34865=>he caught him as he swayed, and lifting him gently, carried him  to the  bed 
line 34866=>and laid  him there,  and covered him warmly.  At  once he fell into a  deep 
line 34867=>sleep. 
line 34868=>     Another bed  was  set beside him for his  servant. Sam hesitated for  a  
line 34869=>moment, then bowing very low: `Good night, Captain, my lord,' he said.  `You  
line 34870=>took the chance, sir.' 
line 34871=>     `Did I so?' said Faramir. 
line 34872=>     `Yes sir, and showed your quality: the very highest.' 
line 34873=>     Faramir smiled. 'A pert servant, Master Samwise. But nay: the praise of 
line 34874=>the  praiseworthy is above all rewards.  Yet  there  was naught  in  this to 
line 34875=>praise. I had no lure or desire to do other than I have done.' 
line 34876=>     `Ah  well,  sir,' said Sam, `you said  my master had an elvish air  and 
line 34877=>that was good and true. But I can say this:  you have an air too, sir,  that 
line 34878=>reminds me of, of  -- well, Gandalf, of wizards.  
line 34879=>     'Maybe,'  said  Faramir. `Maybe you discern from  far away the  air  of 
line 34880=>NÂ®menor. Good n ight!' 
