line 34884=>
line 34885=>Chapter 6. The Forbidden Pool 
line 34886=>
line 34887=> 
line 34888=> 
line 34889=>     Frodo  woke to  find  Faramir bending over him. For a  second old fears 
line 34890=>seized him and he sat up and shrank away. 
line 34891=>     `There is nothing to fear,' said Faramir. 
line 34892=>     'Is it morning already? ' said Frodo yawning. 
line 34893=>     `Not yet, but night is drawing to an end, and the full moon is setting. 
line 34894=>Will  you  come and see it?  Also there  is a matter on which I desire  your 
line 34895=>counsel. I am sorry to rouse you from sleep, but will you come? ' 
line 34896=>     `I will,' said Frodo, rising and shivering a little as he left the warm 
line 34897=>blanket and pelts. It seemed cold in the  fireless  cave. The  noise of  the 
line 34898=>water was loud in the stillness. He put on his cloak and followed Faramir. 
line 34899=>     Sam, waking  suddenly  by some instinct of watchfulness,  saw first his 
line 34900=>master's empty  bed  and  leapt to his feet. Then  he saw  two dark figures, 
line 34901=>Frodo  and a  man, framed  against the archway, which was now filled with  a 
line 34902=>pale  white  light. He  hurried after  them,  past rows of men  sleeping  on 
line 34903=>mattresses along the  wall. As he went by  the  cave-mouth  he saw  that the 
line 34904=>Curtain was now become a dazzling veil of silk and pearls and silver thread: 
line 34905=>melting icicles of moonlight. But he did not pause to admire it, and turning 
line 34906=>aside he followed his  master thr ough the narrow  doorway in the wall of the 
line 34907=>cave. 
line 34908=>     They went first  along a black passage, then up  many wet steps, and so 
line 34909=>came to a small flat  landing cut in the stone  and  lit  by  the pale  sky, 
line 34910=>gleaming  high  above through a  long deep shaft.  From here two flights  of 
line 34911=>steps led: one going on, as it seemed, up on to the high bank of the stream; 
line 34912=>the other turning away to the left. This they  followed. It wound its way up 
line 34913=>like a turret-stair. 
line 34914=>     At last they came out of the stony darkness and looked about. They were 
line 34915=>on a wide  flat rock without rail or parapet. At their right, eastwards, the 
line 34916=>torrent fell, splashing over many terraces, and then,  pouring down  a steep 
line 34917=>race, it filled  a smooth-hewn channel with  a  dark  force of water flecked 
line 34918=>with  foam,  and curling and rushing almost at  their  feet it  plunged sheer  
line 34919=>over the  edge that  yawned  upon their left.  A man  stood  there, near the  
line 34920=>brink, silent, gazing down. 
line 34921=>     Frodo turned to  watch the sleek necks of the  water as they curved and 
line 34922=>
line 34923=>####-dived.  Then he lifted his  eyes and gazed far away. The world was quiet and  
line 34924=>cold,  as if dawn were near. Far off in  the West the full moon was sinking, 
line 34925=>round and white. Pale mists shimmered in the  great vale below:  a wide gulf 
line 34926=>of silver fume,  beneath which rolled the cool night-waters of the Anduin. A 
line 34927=>black  darkness  loomed beyond,  and  in  it glinted, here and  there, cold, 
line 34928=>sharp, remote, white as  the teeth of ghosts, the peaks of Ered Nimrais, the 
line 34929=>White Mountains of the Realm of Gondor, tipped with everlasting snow. 
line 34930=>     For a while Frodo  stood  there on  the  high stone, and  a shiver  ran 
line 34931=>through him,  wondering if anywhere in  the vastness  of the night -lands his 
line 34932=>old companions walked  or slept,  or lay dead  shrouded in  mist. Why was he 
line 34933=>brough t here out of forgetful sleep?  
line 34934=>     Sam was eager for  an answer to the same question and could not refrain 
line 34935=>himself from muttering, for  his master's ear alone as  he thought: 'It's  a  
line 34936=>fine view, no doubt, Mr. Frodo, but chilly to the heart, not to mention   the 
line 34937=>bones! What's going on? ' 
line 34938=>     Faramir heard and answered. `Moonset over Gondor. Fair Ithil as he goes 
line 34939=>from Middle-earth,  glances upon  the white  locks of old Mindolluin.  It is 
line 34940=>worth a few shivers. But that is not what I brought you to see-though as for 
line 34941=>you,  Samwise,  you  were not  brought, and  do but pay  the penalty of your  
