line 35217=>thoroughly approved. Indeed in the Shire such a matter would have required a  
line 35218=>great many more words and bows.  
line 35219=>     'Then I say  to you,'  said Faramir, turning to  Gollum, 'you  are under  
line 35220=>doom of  death; but while you walk with Frodo you are safe for our part. Yet 
line 35221=>if ever you be found by any man of Gondor astray without him, the doom shall 
line 35222=>fall. And may death find  you swiftly, within Gondor  or  without,  if you do 
line 35223=>not well serve him. Now answer me: whither would you go? You were his 
line 35224=>guide, 
line 35225=>he says. Whither were you leading him? ' Gollum made no reply. 
line 35226=>
line 35227=>####-     `This I will not  have secret,'  said Faramir. `Answer me,  or  I  will 
line 35228=>reverse my judgement! ' Still Gollum did not answer. 
line 35229=>     `I will answer for him,' said Frodo. `He brought  me to the Black Gate, 
line 35230=>as I asked; but it was impassable.' 
line 35231=>     `There is no open gate into the Nameless Land,' said Faramir. 
line 35232=>     `Seeing this, we  turned aside and came by  the Southward road '  Frodo 
line 35233=>continued; 'for he said that there is, or there may be, a path near to Minas 
line 35234=>Ithil.' 
line 35235=>     `Minas Morgul,' said Faramir. 
line 35236=>     `I do not know clearly,' said Frodo; `but the path  climbs, I think, up 
line 35237=>into  the mountains  on the  northern side of that vale  where  the old city 
line 35238=>stands. It goes up to a high cleft and so down to -- that which is beyond.' 
line 35239=>     `Do you know the name of that high pass? ' said Faramir. 
line 35240=>     'No,' said Frodo. 
line 35241=>     'It is  called Cirith Ungol.' Gollum hissed sharply and began muttering 
line 35242=>to himself. `Is not that its name? ' said Faramir turning to him. 
line 35243=>     `No! '  said  Gollum, and then he squealed, as if something had stabbed 
line 35244=>him. 'Yes, yes, we heard the name once. But what does the name matter to us? 
line 35245=>Master  says he must get in. So we must try some way. There is no  other way 
line 35246=>to try, no.' 
line 35247=>     'No  other way?  ' said  Faramir. `How do  you  know  that? And who has 
line 35248=>explored  all  the  confines  of  that  dark  realm? '  He  looked long  and 
line 35249=>thoughtfully at Gollum. Presently he spoke  again. `Take this creature away, 
line 35250=>Anborn. Treat  him gently, but watch  him.  And do not you,  Smjagol, try to 
line 35251=>dive into the falls.  The rocks  have such  teeth  there  as would  slay you  
line 35252=>before your time. Leave us now and take your fish! ' 
line 35253=>     Anborn  went out  and Gollum went cringing before him.  The curtain was 
line 35254=>drawn across the recess.  
line 35255=>     `Frodo, I think you do very unwisely in this,' said Faramir.  `I do not 
line 35256=>think you should go with this creature. It is wicked.' 
line 35257=>     'No, not altogether wicked,' said Frodo. 
line 35258=>     'Not wholly, perhaps,' said Faramir; 'but malice eats it like a canker, 
line 35259=>and the  evil is growing. He will lead you to no good. If you will part with 
line 35260=>him, I will give him safe-conduct and guidance to  any  point on the borders 
line 35261=>of Gondor that he may name.' 
line 35262=>     `He would not take  it,' said  Frodo.  'He would  follow after me as he 
line 35263=>long  has  done.  And I  have  promised  many  times  to  take him under  my  
line 35264=>
line 35265=>####-protection  and to go where he led. You would not ask me to break faith with 
line 35266=>him?' 
line 35267=>     'No,'  said  Faramir. `But my  heart would. For it  seems less  evil to 
line 35268=>counsel another man to break troth than to do so oneself, especially if  one 
line 35269=>sees a friend bound unwitting to his own  harm. But no  -- if he will go with 
line 35270=>you, you must  now endure him. But I do not think  you are  holden to go  to 
line 35271=>Cirith  Ungol, of which  he has told you  less than  he  knows. That much  I 
line 35272=>perceived clearly in his mind. Do not go to Cirith Ungol!' 
line 35273=>     `Where then shall  I  go?  ' said   Frodo.  `Back  to the Black Gate and 
line 35274=>deliver  myself  up  to the guard? What do  you know against this place that 
line 35275=>makes its name so dreadful? ' 
line 35276=>     `Nothing certain,' said Faramir. 'We of Gondor do not ever pass east of 
line 35277=>the Road in these days, and none of us younger men has ever done so, nor has 
line 35278=>any  of us  set foot upon the  Mountains of Shadow. Of them we know only old 
line 35279=>report and the  rumour of bygone  days. But there  is some  dark terror that 
line 35280=>dwells in the  passes above Minas Morgul. If Cirith Ungol  is named, old men 
line 35281=>and masters of lore will blanch and fall silent. 
line 35282=>     ,The valley  of Minas Morgul passed into evil very long ago, and it was 
line 35283=>a menace  and  a  dread while the banished  Enemy dwelt  yet far  away,  and 
line 35284=>Ithilien was still for the most par t in our keeping.  As you know, that city 
line 35285=>was once a strong place, proud and fair, Minas Ithil, the twin sister of our 
line 35286=>own city.  But it was taken by fell men whom the Enemy in his first strength 
line 35287=>had dominated, and who wandered homeless and masterless  aft er his fall.  It 
line 35288=>is said  that  their lords  were  men of  NÂ®menor  who had fallen  into dark 
line 35289=>wickedness; to them the Enemy had  given rings of power, and he had 
line 35290=>devoured 
line 35291=>them: living ghosts  they were become, terrible  and  evil. After  his going 
line 35292=>they took Minas  Ithil and  dwelt  there,  and they  filled  it, and all the 
line 35293=>valley about, with decay: it seemed empty  and was  not so,  for a shapeless 
line 35294=>fear  lived  within the ruined walls. Nine Lords there  were, and after  the 
line 35295=>return  of their Master, which they aided and prepared  in secret, they grew 
line 35296=>strong again.  Then the Nine Riders issued forth from  the  gates of horror, 
line 35297=>and we could not withstand them. Do not approach their  citadel. You will be 
line 35298=>espied. It  is a place of  sleepless malice, full of lidless eyes. Do not go 
line 35299=>that way!  ' 
line 35300=>     'But where else will you direct me? ' said Frodo. 'You cannot yourself,  
line 35301=>you say, guide me to the mountains, nor over  them. But over the mountains I 
line 35302=>
line 35303=>####-am bound, by solemn  undertaking to the  Council, to find a way or perish in 
line 35304=>the seeking. And if  I turn back, refusing the road in its bitter end, where 
line 35305=>then  shall I go  among Elves or Men? Would you have  me come to Gondor 
line 35306=>with 
line 35307=>this Thing, the Thing  that drove your  brother mad with  desire? What spell  
line 35308=>would it work in Minas Tirith?  Shall  there be two  cities of Minas Morgul,  
line 35309=>grinning at each other across a dead land filled with rottenness? ' 
line 35310=>     `I would not have it so,' said Faramir. 
line 35311=>     `Then what would you have me do? ' 
line 35312=>     `I know not. Only I would not have you go to death or to torment. And I 
line 35313=>do not think that Mithrandir would have chosen this way.' 
line 35314=>     'Yet since he is gone, I must take such paths as I can find.  And there 
line 35315=>is no time for long searching,' said Frodo. 
line 35316=>     `It is a hard doom and a hopeless errand,'  said  Faramir.  'But at the 
