line 35328=>Seeing-stones of NÂ®menor, farewell! ' 
line 35329=>     He rose and bowed low to Frodo, and drawing the curtain passed out into 
line 35330=>the cave. 
line 35331=> 
line 35332=>
line 35333=>####- 
line 35334=>
line 35335=>Chapter 7. Journey to the Cross-roads 
line 35336=>
line 35337=> 
line 35338=> 
line 35339=>     Frodo and Sam returned  to their  beds and lay there in silence resting 
line 35340=>for a little,  while men bestirred themselves  and  the business of the  day 
line 35341=>began. After a while water was brought to them,  and then they were led to a  
line 35342=>table where food was set for three. Faramir broke his fast with them. He had 
line 35343=>not slept since the battle on the day before, yet he did not look weary. 
line 35344=>     When they had finished they stood up. `May no hunger trouble you on the 
line 35345=>road,'  said  Faramir. `You  have little provision, but some small  store of 
line 35346=>food fit for travellers I have ordered to be stowed  in your packs. You will 
line 35347=>have  no lack  of  water as you walk in Ithilien,  but  do not  drink of any 
line 35348=>stream that flows from Imlad Morgul, the Valley of Living Death. This also I 
line 35349=>must tell you. My scouts and watchers  have all returned, even some that have 
line 35350=>crept within sight of the Morannon. They all find  a strange thing. The land 
line 35351=>is empty.  Nothing  is  on the  road,  and  no sound  of foot, or  horn,  or  
line 35352=>bowstring is anywhere  to be  heard.  A  waiting  silence broods  above  the 
line 35353=>Nameless Land.  I do not know what this portends. But the time draws swiftly 
line 35354=>to some great conclusion. Storm is coming. Hasten while you may! If  you are 
line 35355=>ready, let us go. The Sun will soon rise above the shadow.' 
line 35356=>     The hobbits' packs were brought to them (a little heavier than they had 
line 35357=>been), and  also two stout staves of polished wood, shod with iron, and with  
line 35358=>carven heads through which ran plaited leathern thongs.  
line 35359=>     'I  have no fitting  gifts  to  give you at our parting,' said Faramir ; 
line 35360=>`but take these staves. They may be of service to those who walk or climb in 
line 35361=>the wild.  The  men of  the White Mountains use them; though these have been 
line 35362=>cut  down to your  height and  newly  shod. They  are made of the fair  tree 
line 35363=>lebethron, beloved of   the woodwrights of Gondor, and a  virtue has been set 
line 35364=>upon them of finding  and returning.  May that virtue not wholly  fail under  
line 35365=>the Shadow into which you go!' 
line 35366=>     The hobbits  bowed low. `Most  gracious host,' said Frodo, 'it was said 
line 35367=>to me by Elrond Halfelven that I should find friendship upon the way, secret 
line 35368=>and unlooked  for. Certainly I looked  for no such  friendship  as you  have 
line 35369=>shown. To have found it turns evil to great good.' 
line 35370=>     Now they made ready to depart. Gollum was brought out of some corner or  
line 35371=>hiding-hole,  and he seemed  better pleased with himself  than he had  been,  
line 35372=>
line 35373=>####-though he kept close to Frodo and avoided the glance of Faramir.  
line 35374=>     'Your  guide  must  be  blindfolded,' said Faramir, 'but  you and  your 
line 35375=>servant Samwise I release from this, if you wish.' 
line 35376=>     Gollum squealed, and squirmed, and clutched at Frodo, when they came to 
line 35377=>bind his eyes; and Frodo said: 'Blindfold us all three, and cover up my eyes 
line 35378=>first, and then perhaps he will see that no harm  is meant.' This  was done, 
line 35379=>and they were led from the cave of Henneth Annyn. After they  had passed the 
line 35380=>passages  and stairs they felt the cool morning air, fresh and sweet,  about 
line 35381=>them. Still blind they went on for  some  little time,  up  and  then gently 
line 35382=>down. At last the voice of Faramir ordered them to be uncovered. 
line 35383=>     They stood under the boughs  of the woods again. No noise  of the falls 
line 35384=>could be heard,  for  a  long  southward slope lay now  between them and the 
line 35385=>ravine in which the stream flowed. To the west they could  see light through 
line 35386=>the trees, as if the  world came there  to a sudden end, at a  brink looking 
line 35387=>out only on to sky. 
line 35388=>     'Here  is the last parting of our ways,' said Faramir. 'If you take  my 
line 35389=>counsel, you will not turn eastward yet. Go  straight on, for  thus you will 
line 35390=>have the cover of the woodland for many miles. On your west is an edge where 
line 35391=>the land falls into the great vales, sometimes suddenly and sheer, sometimes 
line 35392=>in  long  hillsides. Keep near to this edge and the skirts of the forest. In 
line 35393=>the beginning of your journey you may walk under daylight, I think. The land 
line 35394=>dreams in  a false peace, and  for a while  all evil is  withdrawn. Fare you  
line 35395=>well, while you may!' 
line 35396=>     He embraced the hobbits then, after the manner of his people, stooping, 
line 35397=>and placing his hands upon their shoulders, and kissing their foreheads. 'Go 
line 35398=>with the good will of all good men!' he said. 
line 35399=>     They bowed to the ground. Then he  turned and without  looking back  he 
line 35400=>left them  and went to his  two guards that stood at a little distance away. 
line 35401=>They marvelled  to  see  with  what speed  these green-clad men  now  moved, 
line 35402=>vanishing almost in the twinkling of an  eye.  The forest  where Faramir had 
line 35403=>stood seemed empty and drear, as if a dream had passed. 
line 35404=>     Frodo sighed and turned back southward. As if to  mark his disregard of 
line 35405=>all such courtesy, Gollum was scrabbling in the mould at the foot of a tree. 
line 35406=>`Hungry again already?' thought Sam. `Well, now for it again!' 
line 35407=>     'Have they  gone at last? ' said Gollum. `Nassty wicked Men!  Smjagol's 
line 35408=>neck still hurts him, yes it does. Let's go! ' 
line 35409=>     `Yes, let  us go,' said Frodo. `But  if you can only speak ill of those 
line 35410=>
line 35411=>####-who showed you mercy, keep silent! ' 
line 35412=>     `Nice Master! ' said Gollum. `Smjagol was only joking. Always forgives,  
line 35413=>he  does, yes, yes, even nice Master's little trickses. Oh yes, nice Master, 
line 35414=>nice Smjagol! ' 
line 35415=>     Frodo and Sam did not  answer.  Hoisting their packs and  taking  their 
line 35416=>staves in hand, they passed on into the woods of Ithilien. 
line 35417=>     Twice that day they  rested  and took a little of the food provided  by 
line 35418=>Faramir:  dried fruits and  salted  meat, enough for  many  days;  and bread 
line 35419=>enough to last while it was still fresh. Gollum ate nothing. 
line 35420=>     The sun rose and  passed  overhead unseen, and began to sink,  and  the 
line 35421=>light through  the trees to the west grew golden; and always they  walked in 
line 35422=>cool green  shadow, and all about  them was silence. The birds seemed all to 
line 35423=>have flown away or to have fallen dumb. 
line 35424=>     Darkness came early  to the silent  woods, and before the fall of night 
line 35425=>they halted, weary, for they had walked  seven leagues or more  from Henneth 
line 35426=>Annyn. Frodo lay and  slept  away  the  night  on the  deep mould beneath an 
line 35427=>ancient tree. Sam beside  him was more uneasy: he woke many times, but there 
line 35428=>was never a sign of Gollum, who had slipped off as  soon as  the others  had 
line 35429=>settled to rest. Whether he had slept by himself in some hole nearby, or had 
line 35430=>wandered  restlessly prowling through  the  night, he did  not say;  but  he 
line 35431=>returned with the first glimmer of light, and roused his companions.  
line 35432=>     `Must get up, yes  they must!'  he  said. 'Long ways to go still, south 
line 35433=>and east. Hobbits must make haste!' 
line 35434=>     That day passed  much  as the  day  before had  gone,  except that  the 
line 35435=>silence seemed deeper; the air grew heavy, and it began to be stifling under  
line 35436=>the trees. It felt as if thunder was  brewing. Gollum often paused, sniffing 
line 35437=>the air, and then he would mutter to himself and urge them to greater speed.  
line 35438=>     As the third stage of  their day's  march drew on  and afternoon wa ned, 
line 35439=>the forest opened out, and the trees became larger and more scattered. Great 
line 35440=>ilexes of  huge girth stood  dark  and solemn in  wide glades with  here and 
line 35441=>there among  them  hoary ash-trees. and  giant oaks  just putting  out their 
line 35442=>brown-green  buds.  About them  lay long launds of green  grass dappled with 
line 35443=>celandine and anemones, white and blue, now folded for sleep; and there were 
line 35444=>acres  populous with  the leaves of  woodland hyacinths: already their sleek  
line 35445=>bell-stems were  thrusting through the  mould . No  living creature, beast or  
line 35446=>bird, was to be seen, but in these open places Gollum grew afraid, and  they  
line 35447=>walked now with caution, flitting from one long shadow to another. 
line 35448=>
line 35449=>####-     Light  was fading fast when they came to the forest -end. There they sat 
line 35450=>under  an old gnarled oak that  sent its roots twisting like snakes  down  a  
line 35451=>steep crumbling bank. A deep dim valley lay before them. On its further side 
line 35452=>the  woods gathered  again,  blue  and grey under  the  sullen  evening, and 
line 35453=>marched on southwards. To the  right the Mountains of Gondor  glowed, 
line 35454=>remote 
line 35455=>in  the  West,  under  a fire-flecked  sky. To  the left  lay darkness:  the 
line 35456=>towering walls of Mordor;  and  out of  that darkness the long valley  came, 
line 35457=>falling steeply in an ever -widening trough towards the Anduin. At its bottom 
line 35458=>ran a hurrying stream:  Frodo could  hear its stony voice coming  up through 
line 35459=>the silence; and beside  it on the hither side a road went winding down like 
line 35460=>a pale ribbon, down into chill grey mists that  no  gleam of sunset touched. 
line 35461=>There it seemed to  Frodo that he descried far off, floating as it were on a  
line 35462=>shadowy sea, the high  dim  tops and broken pinnacles of old  towers forlorn 
line 35463=>and dark. 
line 35464=>     He turned to Gollum. `Do you know where we are? ' he said. 
line 35465=>     'Yes,  Master. Dangerous places. This is the road from the Tower of the 
line 35466=>Moon, Master, down to the ruined city by the shores of the River. The ruined 
line 35467=>city, yes, very nasty place, full of  enemies. We shouldn't have taken Men's 
line 35468=>advice. Hobbits have come a long way out of the path. Must go east now, away 
line 35469=>up there.' He waved his skinny arm  towards  the darkling mountains. `And we 
line 35470=>can't  use  this  road. Oh  no!  Cruel peoples come this way, down  from the 
line 35471=>Tower.' 
line 35472=>     Frodo looked down on to the road. At any rate nothing was moving  on it  
line 35473=>now. It appeared lonely  and forsaken, running  down to empty  ruins  in the 
line 35474=>mist. But there was an evil feeling in the air, as if things might indeed be 
line 35475=>passing up and down that  eyes could  not see. Frodo shuddered  as he looked 
line 35476=>again  at the distant pinnacles now dwindling into  night, and the  sound of 
line 35477=>the water  seemed  cold  and cruel: the voice  of Morgulduin,  the  polluted 
line 35478=>stream that flowed from the Valley of the Wraiths.  
line 35479=>     'What shall we do?  ' he said.  'We have walked long  and far. Shall we 
line 35480=>look for some place in the woods behind where we can lie hidden? ' 
line 35481=>     'No good  hiding in the  dark,' said Gollum. 'It's in day that  hobbits 
line 35482=>must hide now, yes in day.' 
line 35483=>     `Oh come! ' said Sam.  'We must rest for a bit, even if we get up again 
line 35484=>in the middle of the night. There'll still be hours of dark then time enough 
line 35485=>for you to take us a long march, if you know the way.' 
line 35486=>
line 35487=>####-     Gollum  reluctantly agreed  to  this, and  he  turned  back towards the 
line 35488=>trees, working eastward for a  while along the straggling edges of the wood.  
line 35489=>He would not rest on the ground so near the evil road, and after some debate 
line 35490=>they  all climbed  up into  the  crotch of  a  large  holm-oak, whose  thick  
line 35491=>branches springing together from  the trunk made a good  hiding-place and  a 
line 35492=>fairly comfortable refuge.  Night fell and it grew altogether dark under the 
line 35493=>canopy of the  tree.  Frodo and Sam drank a  little water and ate some bread 
line 35494=>and dried fruit, but Gollum at once curled up and went to sleep. The hobbits 
line 35495=>did not shut their eyes. 
line 35496=>     It must have been a little after midnight when Gollum woke up: suddenly 
line 35497=>they were aware of his pale eyes unlidded gleaming at them. He  listened and 
line 35498=>sniffed,  which seemed,  as  they had noticed before,  his  usual method  of 
line 35499=>discovering the time of night. 
line 35500=>     'Are we rested? Have we had beautiful sleep?' he said. 'Let's go!' 
line 35501=>     'We aren't, and we haven't,' growled Sam. 'But we'll go if we must.' 
line 35502=>     Gollum dropped at once  from  the branches of the tree on to all fours,  
line 35503=>and the hobbits followed more slowly. 
line 35504=>     As  soon  as they  were down they  went  on again  with Gollum leading,  
line 35505=>eastwards, up the  dark sloping  land. They could see little,  for the night 
line 35506=>was  now so deep that  they were  hardly aware of the  stems of trees before 
line 35507=>they stumbled  against them. The ground  became more broken  and walking 
line 35508=>was 
line 35509=>more  difficult, but Gollum seemed in no  way troubled. He  led them through 
line 35510=>thickets and wastes of brambles; sometimes round  the lip of a deep cleft or  
line 35511=>dark pit, sometimes down into black bush-shrouded hollows and out again; but 
line 35512=>if ever they went a little downward, always the further slope was longer and 
line 35513=>steeper. They were climbing steadily. At their first  halt they looked back, 
line 35514=>and they could  dimly perceive the roofs of the forest they   had left behind 
line 35515=>lying like  a  vast  dense shadow, a darker night under the  dark blank sky. 
line 35516=>There seemed to be a great  blackness looming slowly out of the East, eating  
line 35517=>up the faint blurred stars. Later the sinking moon escaped from the pursuing 
line 35518=>cloud, but it was ringed all about with a sickly yellow glare. 
line 35519=>     At last  Gollum  turned  to the hobbits. 'Day soon,' he  said. 'Hobbits 
line 35520=>must hurry. Not safe to stay in the open in these places. Make haste! ' 
line 35521=>     He quickened his pace, and they  followed him wearily.  Soon they began 
line 35522=>to climb up on to a great hog-back of land. For the most part it was covered 
line 35523=>with a thick growth of gorse and whortleberry, and  low tough thorns, though 
line 35524=>
