line 36240=> 
line 36241=>
line 36242=>####- 
line 36243=>
line 36244=>Chapter 9. Shelob's Lair 
line 36245=>
line 36246=> 
line 36247=> 
line 36248=>     It  may indeed have been  daytime now, as Gollum said, but the  hobbits 
line 36249=>could see little difference, unless, perhaps, the heavy sky above  was  less 
line 36250=>utterly  black,  more like  a  great roof  of smoke; while  instead  of  the 
line 36251=>darkness  of deep night, which lingered still in  cracks and  holes, a  grey 
line 36252=>blurring shadow shrouded the stony world  about them. They passed on, 
line 36253=>Gollum 
line 36254=>in front and the hobbits  now side by side, up the long  ravine  between the 
line 36255=>piers  and columns of torn and wea thered  rock, standing like huge  unshapen 
line 36256=>statues on  either hand. There was no  sound. Some way ahead, a mile  or so,  
line 36257=>perhaps,   was  a  great  grey  wall,  a   last  huge  upthrusting  mass  of 
line 36258=>mountain-stone. Darker it loomed, and steadily it rose as  they  approached, 
line 36259=>until it towered up high above them, shutting  out the view of all that  lay 
line 36260=>beyond. Deep shadow lay before its feet. Sam sniffed the air. 
line 36261=>     `Ugh! That smell!' he said. `It's getting stronger and stronger.' 
line 36262=>     Presently they were under the shadow, and there in the midst of it they 
line 36263=>saw the  opening  of a cave. `This is the way in,' said Gollum softly. `This 
line 36264=>is  the entrance to the tunnel.' He did  not speak its name:  Torech  Ungol, 
line 36265=>Shelob's Lair. Out of it came a stench, not the sickly odour of decay in the 
line 36266=>meads  of  Morgul, but a foul  reek,  as if filth  unnameable were piled and 
line 36267=>hoarded in the dark within. 
line 36268=>     `Is this the only way, Smjagol? ' said Frodo. 
line 36269=>     'Yes, yes,' he answered. 'Yes, we must go this way now.' 
line 36270=>     'D'you mean to say you've been through this hole?' said Sam. `Phew! But 
line 36271=>perhaps you don't mind bad smells.' 
line 36272=>     Gollum's  eyes  glinted. `He  doesn't  know  what  we  minds,  does  he 
line 36273=>precious? No,  he  doesn't.  But Smjagol  can  bear things.  Yes.  He's been 
line 36274=>through. O yes, right through. It's the only way.' 
line 36275=>     `And what makes the smell, I  wonder,'  said Sam. `It's like  -- well, I 
line 36276=>wouldn't  like to say. Some beastly  hole of the  Orcs, I'll warrant, with a  
line 36277=>hundred years of their filth in it.' 
line 36278=>     'Well,'  said Frodo, 'Orcs or  no, if  it's the only  way, we must take 
line 36279=>it.' 
line 36280=>     Drawing a  deep breath they passed inside. In  a few steps they were in 
line 36281=>
line 36282=>####-utter and impenetrable dark. Not since the lightless passages  of  Moria had 
line 36283=>Frodo or  Sam known such darkness, and if  possible  here it was  deeper and 
line 36284=>denser. There,  there were airs moving,  and echoes,  and a sense  of space. 
line 36285=>Here the air was still, stagnant, heavy, and sound fell dead. They walked as 
line 36286=>it were  in a black vapour wrought of veritable darkness itsel f that, as  it 
line 36287=>was breathed,  brought blindness not only  to the  eyes but to the mind,  so 
line 36288=>that even the memory of colours and of  forms and of any light faded out  of 
line 36289=>thought. Night always had been, and always would be, and night was all. 
line 36290=>     But for a while  they could still feel, and  indeed the senses of their 
line 36291=>feet and fingers at first seemed sharpened almost painfully. The walls felt, 
line 36292=>to their surprise, smooth, and the floor, save for a step now and again, was 
line 36293=>straight and even, going ever  up  at the  same stiff slope. The  tunnel was 
line 36294=>high  and  wide,  so wide  that,  though  the hobbits  walked abreast,  only 
line 36295=>touching the side-walls with their  outstretched hands, they were separated, 
line 36296=>cut off alone in the darkness.  
line 36297=>     Gollum had gone in first and seemed to be only a few steps ahead. While 
line 36298=>they were still able to give heed to such things, they could hear his breath 
line 36299=>hissing and  gasping just in  front of them.  But  after a time their senses 
line 36300=>became duller, both touch and hearing seemed to grow numb, and they kept on, 
line 36301=>groping, walking, on and on, mainly by the force of the will with which they 
line 36302=>had  entered, will to go through and desire to come at last to the high gate 
line 36303=>beyond.  
line 36304=>     Before  they  had gone  very far, perhaps, but time and  distance  soon 
line 36305=>passed out of  his reckoning, Sam on the right, feeling  the wall, was aware 
line 36306=>that there was an opening at the side: for a moment he caught a faint breath 
