line 36308=>     'There's more  than one passage here,'  he whispered with an effort: it 
line 36309=>seemed hard to make his breath give any  sound. `It's as orc-like a place as 
line 36310=>ever there could be! ' 
line 36311=>     After that, first he on  the right, and  then Frodo on the left, passed 
line 36312=>three or four such openings, some wider, some smaller; but  there was as yet 
line 36313=>no doubt of  the main way,  for it was straight, and did not turn, and still 
line 36314=>went steadily up. But how long was it, how much more of this would they have 
line 36315=>to  endure, or could they  endure? The breathlessness of the air was growing 
line 36316=>as they climbed; and now they seemed often  in the  blind dark to sense some 
line 36317=>resistance  thicker  than  the  foul air. As they  thrust forward they  felt 
line 36318=>things brush against their heads, or against their hands, long tentacles, or  
line 36319=>
line 36320=>####-hanging growths perhaps:  they could not tell what  they were. And still the 
line 36321=>stench grew. It grew, until almost it seemed to them that smell was the only 
line 36322=>clear sense left tÂ¢  them. and  that was for their torment.  One  hour,  two 
line 36323=>hours,  three  hours: how many  had  they  passed  in  this  lightless  hole?  
line 36324=>Hours-days, weeks rather. Sam left the tunnel -side and shrank towards Frodo, 
line 36325=>and their hands met and clasped. and so together they still went on. 
line 36326=>     At length Frodo, groping along the  left-hand  wall, came suddenly to a  
line 36327=>void. Almost he fell sideways  into the emptiness. Here was some  opening in 
line 36328=>the rock far  wider than any  they had yet passed; and out of it came a reek  
line 36329=>so foul, and a sense of lurking malice so intense, that Frodo reeled. And at 
line 36330=>that moment Sam too lurched and fell forwards.  
line 36331=>     Fighting off both the sickness and  the fear, Frodo gripped Sam's hand. 
line 36332=>`Up!  ' he said in  a hoarse breath without  voice. 'It all comes from here, 
line 36333=>the stench and the peril. Now for it! Quick! ' 
line 36334=>     Calling up his remaining strength and resolution, he dragged Sam to his 
line 36335=>feet, and  forced his own limbs to move. Sam  stumbled beside him. One step, 
line 36336=>two steps, three steps-at last six steps. Maybe they had passed the dreadful 
line 36337=>unseen opening, but  whether  that was so  or not, suddenly it was easier to 
line 36338=>move,  as if  some  hostile will  for the moment  had  released  them.  They 
line 36339=>struggled on, still hand in hand. 
line 36340=>     But almost at once they came to a new difficulty. The tunnel forked, or  
line 36341=>so it  seemed, and in the dark they could  not tell wh ich was the wider way, 
line 36342=>or  which kept nearer to the straight. Which should they take, the  left, or  
line 36343=>the  right? They knew of  nothing  to guide  them, yet a false choice  would 
line 36344=>almost certainly be fatal. 
line 36345=>     `Which way has Gollum gone? ' panted Sam. 'And why didn't he wait? ' 
line 36346=>     `Smjagol!  ' said  Frodo,  trying  to  call. 'Smjagol! '  But his voice 
line 36347=>croaked, and the  name fell dead almost as  it left his lips.  There  was no 
line 36348=>answer, not an echo, not even a tremor of the air. 
line 36349=>     `He's really gone this time, I  fancy,'  muttered Sam. `I guess this is 
line 36350=>just exactly where  he meant to bring us. Gollum! If ever I lay hands on you  
line 36351=>again, you'll be sorry for it.' 
line 36352=>     Presently,  groping  and fumbling  in  the  dark, they  found  that the 
line 36353=>opening on the left wa s blocked: either it was  a blind, or else  some great 
line 36354=>stone had fallen in  the passage. 'This can't be the way,'  Frodo whispered. 
line 36355=>'Right or wrong, we must take the other.' 
line 36356=>     'And quick! ' Sam panted. 'There's something worse than Gollum about. I  
line 36357=>
line 36358=>####-can feel something looking at us.' 
line 36359=>     They had not gone  more than a  few yards  when from behind them came a  
