line 37185=>     'You'll find that difficult,' laughed Gorbag. 'He's nothing but carrion 
line 37186=>now. What LugbÂ®rz will do with such  stuff I can't guess. He might as well go 
line 37187=>in the pot.' 
line 37188=>     'You  fool,'  snarled Shagrat.  'You've been talking very  clever,  but 
line 37189=>there's a lot you don't  know, though most other folk do. You'll be  for the 
line 37190=>pot or for Shelob, if you don't take  care. Carrion! Is that all you know of 
line 37191=>Her Ladyship? When she binds with cords,  she's after meat. She  doesn't eat 
line 37192=>dead meat, nor suck cold blood. This fellow isn't dead! ' 
line 37193=>     Sam reeled, clutching at the stone. He felt as if  the whole dark world 
line 37194=>was turning upside  down. So great was the shock that he almost swooned, but 
line 37195=>even as he fought to keep a hold on his senses, deep inside him he was aware 
line 37196=>of the  comment: 'You  fool, he  isn't dead, and your heart  knew  it. Don't  
line 37197=>trust your head, Samwise, it is not the best part  of you. The  trouble with 
line 37198=>you is that you never really had any hope. Now what is to be done? ' Fur the  
line 37199=>moment nothing, but to prop himself against the  unmoving  stone and listen, 
line 37200=>listen to the vile orc-voices. 
line 37201=>     `Garn!'  said  Shagrat. 'She's got more than  one  poison.  When  she's 
line 37202=>
line 37203=>####-hunting, she just gives 'em a dab in the neck and  they go as limp as  boned 
line 37204=>fish, and then she has her way with them. D'you remember old Ufthak? We lost  
line 37205=>him for days.  Then we found him in a corner;  hanging up he was, but he was 
line 37206=>wide awake  and glaring. How we laughed! She'd  forgotten him, maybe, but 
line 37207=>we 
line 37208=>didn't  touch him-no  good interfering with Her. Nar  -- this  little filth, 
line 37209=>he'll wake up, in  a few hours; and  beyond feeling a  bit sick for  a  hit, 
line 37210=>he'll be  all right. Or would  be,  if LugbÂ®rz  would let him alone. And  of 
line 37211=>course, beyond wondering where he is and what's happened to him.' 
line 37212=>     'And what's going to happen to him,' laughed Gorbag. 'We can tell him a  
line 37213=>few stories at  any rate, if we can't do a nything else. I don't suppose he's 
line 37214=>ever been in lovely LugbÂ®rz, so he may  like to know what to expect. This is 
line 37215=>going to be more funny than I thought. Let's go!' 
line 37216=>     `There's going to be no fun, I tell  you,' said Shagrat.  'And he's got 
line 37217=>to be kept safe, or we're all as good as dead.' 
line 37218=>     `AII  right! But if I  were you, I'd catch the  big one  that's  loose, 
line 37219=>before you send in any report to LugbÂ®rz. It  won't sound too pretty  to say 
line 37220=>you've caught the kitten and let the cat escape.' 
line 37221=>     The voices began to move away. Sam heard the sound of feet receding. He 
line 37222=>was recovering from his shock, and now a wild fury was on him. `I got it all  
line 37223=>wrong!  ' he cried. `I knew I  would. Now they've  got him, the  devils! the 
line 37224=>filth! Never leave your master, never,  never: that was my right rule. And I 
line 37225=>knew  it in my heart. May  I be forgiven!  Now I've got to get  back to him. 
line 37226=>Somehow, somehow!  ' 
line 37227=>     He  drew his sword again and  beat on the stone with the  hilt, but  it 
line 37228=>only gave out a dull sound. The sword, however, bla zed so brightly now  that 
line 37229=>he could see dimly  in its light. To his surprise he noticed  that the great 
line 37230=>block was shaped like a heavy door, and  was less than twice his own height. 
line 37231=>Above it was a  dark blank  space between the top and the  low  arch of  the 
line 37232=>opening.  It was probably only meant to be a stop against the  intrusion  of 
line 37233=>Shelob, fastened on the inside with some latch or bolt  beyond the reach  of 
line 37234=>her cunning. With  his  remaining  strength  Sam leaped and caught the  top,  
line 37235=>scrambled up, and dropped;  and  then he ran  madly, sword blazing in  hand, 
line 37236=>round a bend and up a winding tunnel. 
line 37237=>     The news  that his master was still alive roused him  to a  last effort 
line 37238=>beyond thought  of weariness. He could not see anything  ahead. for this new 
line 37239=>passage twisted and turned constantly; but  he thought  he was  catching the  
line 37240=>
line 37241=>####-two Orcs up: their  voices were growing  nearer again. Now they seemed quite 
line 37242=>close. 
line 37243=>     `That's what I'm going  to do,'  said Shagrat in angry tones.  'Put him 
line 37244=>right up in the top chamber.' 
line 37245=>     `What for? ' growled Gorbag. `Haven't you any lock -ups down below? ' 
line 37246=>     `He's  going out of harm's way,  I  tell  you,' answered Shagrat. 'See?  
line 37247=>He's  precious.  I  don't trust  all  my lads,  and  none of yours;  nor you  
line 37248=>neither, when you're mad for fun. He's going where I want him, and where you  
line 37249=>won't come,  if you  don't keep civil. Up to the top,  I  say. He'll be safe 
line 37250=>there.' 
line 37251=>     `Will  he?'  said Sam. 'You're  forgetting the great big elvish warrior  
line 37252=>that's loose!' And with that he raced  round   the last corner, only to  find 
line 37253=>that by some trick of the tunnel, or of the hearing which the Ring gave him, 
line 37254=>he had misjudged the distance. 
line 37255=>     The two orc-figures were still some way ahead. He could  see  them now,  
line 37256=>black and squat against a red glare. The passage ran straight at last, up an 
line 37257=>incline;  and  at  the  end, wide open,  were  great  double doors,  leading 
line 37258=>probably to deep  chambers far below the high horn of the tower. Already the 
line 37259=>Orcs  with their burden  had  passed inside. Gorbag and Shagrat were drawing 
line 37260=>near the gate. 
line 37261=>     Sam  heard a burst  of hoarse singing, blaring of horns  and banging of 
line 37262=>gongs, a hideous clamour. Gorbag and Shagrat were already on the threshold. 
line 37263=>     Sam yelled  and brandished Sting, but his little  voice was  drowned in 
line 37264=>the tumult. No one heeded him. 
line 37265=>     The  great  doors slammed to. Boom.  The bars  of iron fell  into place 
line 37266=>inside. Clang.  The gate was  shut.  Sam  hurled  himself against the bolted 
line 37267=>brazen plates and fell senseless to the ground. He  was out in the darkness. 
line 37268=>Frodo was alive but taken by the Enemy. 
line 37269=>  
line 37270=>
line 37271=>####- 
line 37272=>    Here ends the second part of the history of the War of the Ring. 
line 37273=> 
line 37274=>     The third  part tells of  the  last defence against the Shadow, and the 
line 37275=>end of the mission of the Ring-bearer in  THE RETURN OF THE KING . 
