line 37288=>Chapter 1. Minas Tirith 
line 37289=>
line 37290=> 
line 37291=> 
line 37292=>     Pippin  looked out from  the shelter of Gandalf's cloak. He wondered if 
line 37293=>he was awake or still sleeping, still in the  swift-moving dream in which he 
line 37294=>had  been  wrapped so long since the  great  ride  began. The dark world was 
line 37295=>rushing by and  the wind sang loudly in his ears. He could  see nothing  but 
line 37296=>the wheeling stars, and away to his right vast shadows against the sky where 
line 37297=>the mountains of the  South  marched past.  Sleepily he tried  to reckon the 
line 37298=>times and stages of their journey, but his memory was drowsy and uncertain. 
line 37299=>     There  had been the first  ride at terrible speed without  a  halt, and 
line 37300=>then in the dawn he had  seen a pale gleam of gold, and they had come to the 
line 37301=>silent  town  and the great empty house on  the  hill.  And  hardly had they 
line 37302=>reached its shelter when the winged shadow  had passed  over once again, and 
line 37303=>men wilted with fear. But Gandalf had spoken  soft words to him,  and he had 
line 37304=>slept in a corner, tired but uneasy, dimly aware of  comings  and goings and  
line 37305=>of men talking and Gandalf giving orders. And then  again riding, riding  in 
line 37306=>the  night. This was the second, no, the third night since  he had looked in 
line 37307=>the Stone. And with that hideous memory he woke fully, and shivered, and the 
line 37308=>noise of the wind became filled with menacing voices.  
line 37309=>     A light kindled in the sky, a blaze of yellow fire behind dark barriers 
line 37310=>Pippin  cowered back, afraid for  a  moment,  wondering  into what  dreadful 
line 37311=>country Gandalf was bearing him. He rubbed his eyes, and then he saw that it 
line 37312=>was the moon rising above the eastern shadows, now  almost at  the full.  So 
line 37313=>the night was not  yet  old and  for hours the dark journey  would go on. He 
line 37314=>stirred and spoke. 
line 37315=>     'Where are we, Gandalf?' he asked. 
line 37316=>     'In the realm of Gondor,' the wizard answered. 'The land  of Anurien is 
line 37317=>still passing by.' 
line 37318=>     There was a silence again  for a  while. Then,  'What  is that?'  cried 
line 37319=>Pippin  suddenly,  clutching at Gandalf's cloak.  'Look! Fire, red fire! Are 
line 37320=>there dragons in this land?  Look, there is another!' 
line 37321=>     For  answer  Gandalf  cried aloud to his horse. 'On, Shadowfax! We must  
line 37322=>
line 37323=>####-hasten. Time is  short.  See! The beacons of Gondor are  alight, calling for  
line 37324=>aid. War  is  kindled.  See,  there is the  fire  on Amon  Don, and flame on 
line 37325=>Eilenach;  and  there they go speeding  west:  Nardol,  Erelas,  Min-Rimmon, 
line 37326=>Calenhad, and the Halifirien on the borders of Rohan.' 
line 37327=>     But Shadowfax  paused in  his stride, slowing  to  a  walk, and then he 
line 37328=>lifted up his head and neighed. And out of the  darkness the answering neigh  
line 37329=>of other  horses came; and  presently the  thudding of hoofs was heard,  and 
line 37330=>three riders swept up and passed like flying ghosts in the moon and vanished  
line 37331=>into the West. Then Shadowfax gathered himself together and sprang away, 
line 37332=>and 
line 37333=>the night flowed over him like a roaring wind. 
line 37334=>     Pippin became drowsy again and paid little attention to Gandalf telling 
line 37335=>him of the customs of Gondor, and how the Lord of the City had beacons built 
line 37336=>on the tops  of  outlying hills along both border s  of the great  range, and 
line 37337=>maintained posts at these points where fresh horses were always in readiness 
line 37338=>to bear  his errand-riders to  Rohan in the North,  or  to Belfalas  in  the 
line 37339=>South. 'It is long since the beacons of the North  were lit,' he said;  'and 
line 37340=>in the ancient days of  Gondor they were not needed, for  they had the Seven  
line 37341=>Stones.' Pippin stirred uneasily. 
line 37342=>     'Sleep  again, and do  not be  afraid!' said Gandalf. 'For you are  not 
line 37343=>going like Frodo to  Mordor, but  to Minas Tirith, and there you  will be as 
line 37344=>safe as you can  be anywhere in these days. If Gondor falls, or  the Ring is 
line 37345=>taken, then the Shire will be no refuge.' 
line 37346=>     'You do not comfort me,' said Pippin, but nonetheless  sleep crept over  
line 37347=>him. The last  thing that he remembered before he fell into deep dream was a 
line 37348=>glimpse of high white peaks, glimmering like floating isles above the clouds 
line 37349=>as they caught the light of the westering moon. He wondered where Frodo was,  
line 37350=>and if he was already in Mordor, or if he was dead; and he did not know that 
line 37351=>Frodo from far away looked on that same moon as it set beyond Gondor ere the 
line 37352=>coming of the day. 
line 37353=>     Pippin woke  to  the sound of voices. Another day of hiding and a night 
line 37354=>of journey had fleeted by. It was twilight: the cold dawn was at hand again, 
line 37355=>and chill grey mists were about them.  Shadowfax stood  steaming with sweat, 
line 37356=>but he held his neck proudly and showed  no sign of weariness. Many tall men 
line 37357=>heavily cloaked  stood beside him, and behind them in the mist loomed a wall 
line 37358=>of stone. Partly ruinous  it seemed, but already before the night was passed 
line 37359=>the sound  of  hurried labour  could  be heard:  beat  of hammers,  clink of 
line 37360=>
line 37361=>####-trowels,  and the creak of wheels. Torches and flares glowed dully here  and 
line 37362=>there in the fog. Gandalf was speaking  to the men that  barred his way, and 
line 37363=>as he listened Pippin became aware that he himself was being discussed. 
line 37364=>     'Yea truly, we know you, Mithrandir,' said the leader  of the men, 'and 
line 37365=>you know the pass-words of the  Seven  Gates and are free to go forward. But 
line 37366=>we do not know your companion. What  is he?  A dwarf out of the mountains 
line 37367=>in 
line 37368=>the North? We wish for no strangers in the land at this time, unless they be 
line 37369=>mighty men of arms in whose faith and help we can trust.' 
line 37370=>     'I will vouch  for him before the seat of Denethor,' said Gandalf. 'And 
line 37371=>as  for valour,  that  cannot be computed by stature. He has  passed through 
line 37372=>more  battles and  perils than you have,  Ingold, though  you  be twice  his 
line 37373=>height; and  he comes  now  from the storming of Isengard,  of which we bear 
line 37374=>tidings,  and great weariness is  on him, or  I would wake him. His name  is 
line 37375=>Peregrin, a very valiant man.' 
line 37376=>     'Man?' said Ingold dubiously; and the others laughed. 
line 37377=>     'Man!' cried Pippin,  now  thoroughly roused.  'Man! Indeed not! I am a  
line 37378=>hobbit and no more valiant  than I am a man,  save perhaps  now and again by 
line 37379=>necessity. Do not let Gandalf deceive you!' 
line 37380=>     'Many a doer of great deeds might say no more,' said Ingold.  'But what 
line 37381=>is a hobbit?' 
line 37382=>     'A Halfling,' answered Gandalf. 'Nay,  not the one that was spoken of,' 
line 37383=>he added seeing  the  wonder  in the  men's  faces. 'Not  he, yet one of his 
line 37384=>kindred.' 
line 37385=>     'Yes, and one  who  journeyed  with him,' said Pippin. 'And  Boromir of 
line 37386=>your City was with us, and he saved me in the snows of the North, and at the  
line 37387=>last he was slain defending me from many foes.' 
line 37388=>     'Peace!'  said Gandalf.  'The news of that grief should have  been told 
line 37389=>first to the father.' 
line 37390=>     'It  has  been  guessed  already,' said  Ingold;  'for there have  been 
line 37391=>strange portents here  of late. But pass  on now  quickly! For  the  Lord of 
line 37392=>Minas Tirith  will be eager to see any that bear the  latest tidings of  his 
line 37393=>son, be he man or --' 
line 37394=>     'Hobbit,' said Pippin.  'Little  service  can I offer to your lord, but 
line 37395=>what I can do, I would do, remembering Boromir the brave.' 
line 37396=>     'Fare you well!' said  Ingold; and the men made way for Shadow fax, and 
line 37397=>he  passed through a narrow gate in the wall. 'May you bring good counsel to 
line 37398=>
line 37399=>####-Denethor  in his need, and  to us all, Mithrandir!' Ingold  cried.  'But you  
line 37400=>come with tidings of grief and danger, as is your wont, they say.' 
line 37401=>     'Because I come seldom but  when my help  is needed,' answered Gandalf.  
line 37402=>'And as for counsel, to you I would  say that you are over -late in repairing 
line 37403=>the wall of the Pelennor. Courage will  now be your best defence against the 
line 37404=>storm that is at  hand - that and such  hope as  I  bring. For not  all  the 
line 37405=>tidings that I  bring are  evil.  But leave your  trowels  and  sharpen your 
line 37406=>swords!' 
line 37407=>     'The work will be finished ere evening, ' said Ingold. 'This is the last  
line 37408=>portion of  the wall  to be put in defence: the least open to attack, for it 
line 37409=>looks  towards our  friends of Rohan.  Do  you know aught of them? Will they 
line 37410=>answer the summons, think you?' 
line 37411=>     'Yes,  they will come. But  they have fought many battles at your back. 
line 37412=>This road and no road looks towards safety  any longer. Be vigilant! But for  
line 37413=>Gandalf Stormcrow you would have seen a host  of foes coming  out of 
line 37414=>Anurien 
line 37415=>and no Riders of Rohan. And you may yet. Fare you well, and sl eep not!' 
line 37416=>     Gandalf passed now into  the wide land  beyond the Rammas Echor. So the 
line 37417=>men of Gondor  called the out  wall that they had  built with great  labour, 
line 37418=>after Ithilien fell under the shadow of their Enemy. For ten leagues or more 
line 37419=>it ran from the  mountains' feet  and so back again, enclosing in its  fence 
line 37420=>the fields of the Pelennor:  fair and fertile townlands  on  the long slopes 
line 37421=>and terraces falling to the deep levels of the Anduin. At its furthest point 
line 37422=>from the  Great Gate of the City, north-eastward, the wall  was four leagues 
line 37423=>distant, and there from a frowning bank  it overlooked the long flats beside 
line 37424=>the river,  and men had  made it high and strong; for at  that point, upon a  
line 37425=>walled causeway, the  road came in from  the fords and bridges  of Osgiliath 
line 37426=>and passed  through a guarded gate between embattled towers. At its  nearest 
line 37427=>point the  wall was little more than one league from the  City, and that was 
line 37428=>south-eastward. There Anduin, going in a  wide knee about the  hills of Emyn 
line 37429=>Arnen in South Ithilien, bent sharply west, and  the out-wall rose  upon its 
line 37430=>very  brink; and beneath  it lay  the quays and  landings of the Harlond for  
line 37431=>craft that came upstream from the southern fiefs.  
line 37432=>     The  townlands  were rich,  with  wide  tilth  and many  orchards,  and 
line 37433=>homesteads there  were with oast  and garner, fold and byre, and  many rills 
line 37434=>rippling through  the  green from the  highlands  down  to Anduin.  Yet  the 
line 37435=>
line 37436=>####-herdsmen and husbandmen that dwelt there were not many, and the most part 
line 37437=>of 
line 37438=>the people of Gondor lived in the seven circles of the  City, or in the high 
line 37439=>vales of  the  mountain-borders,  in Lossarnach,  or  further south  in fair 
line 37440=>Lebennin with its five swift streams. There dwelt  a  hardy folk between the 
line 37441=>mountains and the sea. They were reckoned men of Gondor, yet their blood 
line 37442=>was 
line 37443=>mingled, and there were short  and swarthy  folk among them whose sires came 
line 37444=>more from the forgotten men who  housed in  the  shadow  of the hills in the 
line 37445=>Dark  Years  ere the coming of the kings. But  beyond,  in the great fief of 
line 37446=>Belfalas, dwelt Prince Imrahil  in  his castle of Dol Amroth by the sea, and 
line 37447=>he was of high blood,  and  his folk also, tall  men and proud with sea -grey 
line 37448=>eyes. 
line 37449=>     Now after Gandalf had ridden for some time the light of day grew in the 
line 37450=>sky, and Pippin roused himself and looked up. To his left lay a sea of mist, 
line 37451=>rising  to a  bleak  shadow  in the  East;  but to his right great mountains 
line 37452=>reared their heads, ranging  from the West  to a steep and sudden end, as if 
line 37453=>in  the  making of the land the  River  had burst  through a great  barrier, 
line 37454=>carving  out a mighty valley to be a  land  of battle and debate in times to 
line 37455=>come. And there where the White Mountains of Ered Nimrais  came to their 
line 37456=>end 
line 37457=>he saw, as Gandalf had promised, the dark mass of Mount  Mindolluin, the deep 
line 37458=>purple  shadows of its high glens, and its tall face whitening in the rising 
line 37459=>day. And upon its out-thrust knee was the Guarded City, with its seven walls 
line 37460=>of stone  so  strong and  old that  it seemed to have been  not builded  but 
line 37461=>carven by giants out of the bones of the earth. 
line 37462=>     Even  as Pippin gazed in wonder the walls  passed from  looming grey to 
line 37463=>white, blushing faintly in  the dawn;  and suddenly the sun climbed over the 
line 37464=>eastern shadow and sent forth a shaft that  smote the face of the City. Then 
line 37465=>Pippin cried aloud, for the Tower  of  Ecthelion, standing high  within  the 
line 37466=>topmost walls' shone  out against the  sky, glimmering like a spike of pearl 
line 37467=>and silver, tall and fair and shapely, and its pinnacle  glittered as if  it 
line 37468=>were wrought of crystals;  and white  banners  broke and  fluttered from the 
line 37469=>battlements in the morning breeze' and high and far he heard a clear ringing 
line 37470=>as of silver trumpets. 
line 37471=>     So Gandalf and Peregrin rode to the Great Gate  of the Men of Gondor at 
line 37472=>the rising of the sun, and its iron doors rolled back before them. 
line 37473=>
line 37474=>####-     'Mithrandir!  Mithrandir!' men  cried. 'Now we know that  the  storm is 
line 37475=>indeed nigh!' 
line 37476=>     'It is upon you,' said  Gandalf. 'I  have  ridden  on its wings. Let me 
line 37477=>pass!  I  must come  to  your  Lord Denethor, while his  stewardship  lasts.  
line 37478=>Whatever betide, you have come to the end of the Gondor that you have 
line 37479=>known. 
line 37480=>Let me pass!' 
line 37481=>     Then men  fell back before the command of his voice  and questioned him 
line 37482=>no further, though  they gazed in wonder  at the hobbit that sat before  him 
line 37483=>and at the horse that bore him. For the people of  the City used horses very 
line 37484=>little and they were seldom seen in their streets, save only those ridden by  
line 37485=>the errand-riders of their  lord. And they said: 'Surely that is one  of the 
line 37486=>great steeds of the  King  of  Rohan?  Maybe  the Rohirrim will come soon to 
line 37487=>strengthen us.' But Shadowfax walked proudly up the long winding road. 
line 37488=>     For the  fashion  of  Minas Tirith was such that it was built on  seven 
line 37489=>levels,  each  delved into the hill, and about each  was set a  wall, and in 
line 37490=>each wall was a  gate. But the gates were not set in a line:  the Great Gate 
line 37491=>in the City Wall was at  the  east  point of the circuit, but the next faced 
line 37492=>half south, and the third half north, and so to and fro upwards; so that the 
line 37493=>paved  way that climbed towards  the Citadel turned  first this way and then 
line 37494=>that across the face of  the hill. And each  time that it passed the line of 
line 37495=>the  Great Gate it went through an  arched  tunnel, piercing a  vast pier of 
line 37496=>rock whose  huge out-thrust bulk  divided in two all the circles of the City 
line 37497=>save the first. For partly in  the  primeval shaping  of the hill, partly by 
line 37498=>the mighty craft and labour of old, there stood up from the rear of the wide 
line 37499=>court behind the  Gate a  towering  bastion  of stone, its edge sharp  as  a  
line 37500=>ship-keel facing east. Up it rose, even to the level of the  topmost circle, 
line 37501=>and there was crowned  by  a battlement; so that those in the Citadel might, 
line 37502=>like mariners in a mountainous ship, look  from  its peak sheer down upon the 
line 37503=>Gate  seven  hundred  feet  below.  The entrance  to the Citadel also looked 
line 37504=>eastward,  but  was delved in the  heart of the rock; thence a long lamp-lit 
line 37505=>slope ran up to the seventh gate. Thus  men reached  at last the High Court, 
line 37506=>and the Place of the  Fountain before the feet of the  White Tower: tall and 
line 37507=>shapely,  fifty fathoms from its  base to the pinnacle, where the banner  of 
line 37508=>the Stewards floated a thousand feet above the plain. 
line 37509=>     A  strong citadel  it was indeed,  and  not to be taken  by  a  host of 
line 37510=>enemies, if  there were any within that could hold weapons;  unless some foe 
line 37511=>
line 37512=>####-could come behind and scale the lower skirts of Mindolluin, and so come upon 
line 37513=>the narrow shoulder that joined the Hill of Guard to the mountain  mass. But 
line 37514=>that shoulder, which rose to  the height of the fifth wall, was hedged  with 
line 37515=>great ramparts right up to the precipice that overhung its western end;  and 
line 37516=>in that  space stood the houses and  domed tombs of bygone kings  and lords, 
line 37517=>for ever silent between the mountain and the tower. 
line 37518=>     Pippin gazed in growing wonder at the great stone city, vaster and more 
line 37519=>splendid  than  anything that he had dreamed of;  greater and  stronger than 
line 37520=>Isengard, and far more beautiful.  Yet it was in truth falling year by  year 
line 37521=>into decay; and already it lacked half the men that could have dwelt at ease 
line 37522=>there. In  every street they passed  some  great house or  court  over whose 
line 37523=>doors and arched gates were carved many fair letters  of strange and ancient  
line 37524=>shapes: names Pippin  guessed of great men and kindreds that had once  dwelt 
line 37525=>there;  and  yet now they were silent,  and no footsteps rang  on their wide 
line 37526=>pavements, nor voice was heard in their halls, nor any face looked out  from 
line 37527=>door or empty window.  
line 37528=>     At last they came out of  shadow to the seventh gate,  and the warm sun 
line 37529=>that shone down beyond the river, as Frodo walked in the glades of Ithilien, 
line 37530=>glowed here on the smooth walls and rooted pillars, and the great arch  with  
line 37531=>keystone  carven  in  the  likeness of a crowned and  kingly  head.  Gandalf 
line 37532=>dismounted, for no horse was allowed in the Citadel,  and Shadowfax suffered 
line 37533=>himself to be led away at the soft word of his master. 
line 37534=>     The Guards of the gate  were robed  in black, and  their helms  were of 
line 37535=>strange  shape, high-crowned,  with long cheek -guards  close-fitting to  the 
line 37536=>face,  and above the cheek -guards were set the white wings of sea -birds; but 
line 37537=>the helms gleamed with a  flame of silver, for they were indeed  wrought  of 
line 37538=>mithril, heirlooms from the glory of old days. Upon  the black surcoats were 
line 37539=>embroidered in white a tree blossoming like  snow beneath a silver crown and 
line 37540=>many-pointed  stars. This  was the livery of the heirs of  Elendil, and none 
line 37541=>wore it now in all Gondor,  save the Guards of the Citadel  before the Court 
line 37542=>of the Fountain where the White Tree once had grown. 
line 37543=>     Already it  seemed that word of their coming had  gone before them: and 
line 37544=>at once they were admitted,  silently, and without question. Quickly Gandalf 
line 37545=>strode across  the white-paved court.  A  sweet fountain played there in the 
