line 37859=>came straight up to him. 
line 37860=>     'You are Peregrin the Halfling?' he said. 'I am told that you have been 
line 37861=>sworn to the  service of the  Lord and of the City. Welcome! He held out his 
line 37862=>hand and Pippin took it. 
line 37863=>     'I am named Beregond son of Baranor. I have no duty this morning, and I  
line 37864=>have been sent  to you to teach you the pass-words, and to  tell you some of 
line 37865=>the many things that  no doubt you  will  wish to know. And  for my part,  I 
line 37866=>would learn of you also.  For  never before have  we seen a halfling in this 
line 37867=>land and though we have heard rumour of them, little is said of them in  any 
line 37868=>tale that we know. Moreover you are a friend of Mithrandir.  Do you know him 
line 37869=>well?' 
line 37870=>     'Well,' said Pippin.  'I  have known of  him all my short  life, as you  
line 37871=>might say; and lately  I have travelled far with him. But there  is  much to 
line 37872=>read in that book, and I cannot claim to have seen more  than a page or two.  
line 37873=>Yet perhaps I know him as well as any but a few. Aragorn was the only one of 
line 37874=>our Company, I think, who really knew him.' 
line 37875=>     'Aragorn?' said Beregond. 'Who is he?' 
line 37876=>     'Oh,' stammered  Pippin, 'he was a  man who went  about with us. I think  
line 37877=>he is in Rohan now.' 
line 37878=>     'You have  been in Rohan, I hear. There is much that I would ask you of 
line 37879=>that land also;  for we put much of what little hope we have  in its people. 
line 37880=>But I am forgetting my errand, which was first to answer what you would ask. 
line 37881=>What would you know, Master Peregrin?' 
line 37882=>     'Er well,' said Pippin, 'if I may venture to  say so, rather  a burning 
line 37883=>question  in my mind at present is, well, what about breakfast and all that?  
line 37884=>I mean, what  are  the  meal-times, if you  understand me, and where is  the 
line 37885=>dining-room, if there is one?  And the inns? I looked, but never a one could 
line 37886=>I see as we rode up, though I had been borne up by the hope of a draught  of 
line 37887=>ale as soon as we came to the homes of wise and courtly men.' 
line 37888=>     Beregond looked at him  gravely. 'An old campaigner,  I see,'  he said. 
line 37889=>'They say that men who go warring afield look ever to the next  hope of food 
line 37890=>and of drink; though I am not a travelled man myself. Then you have not  yet 
line 37891=>
line 37892=>####-eaten today?' 
line 37893=>     'Well, yes,  to speak in courtesy, yes,' said Pippin. 'But no more than 
line 37894=>a cup of wine  and a white cake or two by the kindness of your lord; but  he 
line 37895=>racked me for it with an hour of questions, and that is hungry work.' 
line 37896=>     Beregond laughed. 'At the table small men may  do the greater deeds, we 
line 37897=>say. But you  have broken  your fast  as well as any man in the Citadel, and 
line 37898=>with  greater honour. This is a fortress and a tower  of guard and is now in 
line 37899=>posture  of war. We rise ere the Sun, and take  a morsel in the grey  light, 
line 37900=>and go  to our duties  at  the opening hour. But do not despair!' He laughed 
line 37901=>again,  seeing the  dismay in Pippin's  face. 'Those who have had heavy duty 
line 37902=>take somewhat  to refresh  their strength  in the mid-morning. Then there is 
line 37903=>the  nuncheon,  at noon or  after as  duties allow; and men  gather for  the 
line 37904=>daymeal, and such mirth as there still may be, about the hour of sunset. 
line 37905=>     'Come! We will walk a little and then go find us  some refreshment, and 
line 37906=>eat and drink on the battlement, and survey the fair morning.' 
line 37907=>     'One moment!' said Pippin blushing. 'Greed, or hunger by your courtesy,  
line 37908=>put it out of my mind. But Gandalf, Mithrandir as you call  him, asked me to 
line 37909=>see to his horse  - Shadowfax,  a  great steed of Rohan, and the apple of the 
line 37910=>king's  eye, I  am told, though he  has  given  him  to  Mithrandir  for his 
line 37911=>services. I think his new master loves the beast  better than  he loves many 
line 37912=>men, and if his  good  will is  of  any value to this  city,  you will treat 
