line 37950=>     'This  is the storehouse and buttery of my company of the  Guard.' said 
line 37951=>Beregond.  'Greetings,  Targon!' he called through the hatch.  'It  is early 
line 37952=>yet, but here is a newcomer that the Lord has taken into his service. He has 
line 37953=>ridden long and far with a tight belt, and has had sore labour this morning, 
line 37954=>and he is hungry. Give us what you have!' 
line 37955=>     They got there bread, and butter, and cheese  and  apples:  the last of 
line 37956=>the  winter store,  wrinkled but  sound and sweet;  and a leather flagon  of 
