line 37966=>standing tiptoe upon it to peer over the sill at the lands below. 
line 37967=>
line 37968=>####-     'I will not hide from you, Master Peregrin,' said Beregond, 'that to us 
line 37969=>you look almost as one of our children, a lad of nine summers or so; and yet  
line 37970=>you have endured  perils  and seen marvels that few of our  greybeards could 
line 37971=>boast of. I thought  it was the whim of  our Lord to take him  a noble page, 
line 37972=>after the manner of the kings of old, they say. But I see that it is not so, 
line 37973=>and you must pardon my foolishness.' 
line 37974=>     'I do,' said Pippin. 'Though you are  not far  wrong. I am still little 
line 37975=>more than a boy in the reckoning of my own people, and it will be four years 
line 37976=>yet  before I "come of age", as we say in the Shire: But do not bother about 
line 37977=>me. Come and look and tell me what I can see.' 
line 37978=>     The  sun was now  climbing, and the  mists in the  vale below  had been 
line 37979=>drawn up. The last of them  were  floating away, just  overhead, as wisps of 
line 37980=>white cloud borne  on  the  stiffening breeze from  the East,  that  was now 
