line 38126=>     Pippin looked at  him: tall and proud and noble, as all the men that he 
line 38127=>had yet seen in that land; and  with  a glitter in  his eye as he thought of 
line 38128=>the battle. 'Alas! my own hand feels as light as a feather,' he thought, but 
line 38129=>he  said nothing.  'A  pawn did  Gandalf  say?  Perhaps  but  on  the  wrong 
line 38130=>chessboard.' 
line 38131=>     So they  talked  until the  sun  reached  its height, and suddenly  the 
line 38132=>noon-bells were rung, and there was a  stir in the citadel; for all save the 
line 38133=>watchmen were going to their meal. 
line 38134=>     'Will you come with me?' said Beregond. 'You may join my  mess for this 
line 38135=>day. I do not know to  what  company  you will be  assigned; or the Lord may 
line 38136=>hold you at his own command. But you will be welcome. And it will be well to 
line 38137=>meet as many men as you may, while there is yet time.' 
line 38138=>     'I shall be glad  to come,' said Pippin. 'I am  lonely, to tell you the 
line 38139=>truth. I left my best friend behind in Rohan, and I have had  no one to talk  
line 38140=>to  or jest with. Perhaps  I could  really join your  company?  Are  you the  
line 38141=>captain? If so, you could take me on, or speak for me?' 
line 38142=>     'Nay, nay,' Beregond laughed, 'I am no captain. Neither office nor rank  
line 38143=>nor lordship  have I,  being but a plain man of arms of the Third Company of 
line 38144=>the Citadel. Yet, Master Peregrin, to be only a man of arms of the  Guard of 
line 38145=>the Tower of Gondor  is held worthy in the City, and such men have honour in 
line 38146=>the land.' 
line 38147=>     'Then it is far beyond me,' said Pippin. 'Take me back to our room, and 
line 38148=>if Gandalf is not there, I will go where you like  - as your guest. ' 
line 38149=>     Gandalf was not in the lodging and had sent no message; so  Pippin went  
line 38150=>with Beregond and was made known  to  the  men of the  Third Company. And 
line 38151=>it 
line 38152=>seemed that Beregond got as much honour from it as his guest, for Pippin was 
line 38153=>very welcome.  There  had  already  been  much talk  in  the  citadel  about 
line 38154=>Mithrandir's companion and his  long  closeting with the  Lord;  and  rumour 
line 38155=>declared that a Prince  of the Halflings had  come out of the North to offer  
line 38156=>allegiance to Gondor and five  thousand  swords.  And some said that when the 
line 38157=>
line 38158=>####-Riders came from Rohan each would bring behind him a halfling warrior, small 
line 38159=>maybe, but doughty. 
line 38160=>     Though Pippin had regretfully to destroy this  hopeful  tale,  he could 
line 38161=>not be rid of his new  rank, only fitting, men thought, to one befriended by 
line 38162=>Boromir and honoured by  the Lord Denethor; and they thanked him for  
line 38163=>coming 
line 38164=>among them, and  hung on his words and stories of the outlands, and gave him 
line 38165=>as much food and ale as he could  wish. Indeed his  only  trouble was to  be 
line 38166=>'wary' according  to the counsel of Gandalf, and  not to let  his tongue wag 
line 38167=>freely after the manner of a hobbit among friends. 
line 38168=>     At length  Beregond  rose. 'Farewell for  this time!'  he said. 'I have 
line 38169=>duty now till sundown, as have all the others here, I think. But if you  are 
line 38170=>lonely, as you  say, maybe  you would like a  merry guide about the City. My 
line 38171=>son would go with you gladly. A good lad, I may say. If that pleases you, go 
line 38172=>down to  the  lowest  circle and ask for  the Old  Guesthouse  in  the  Rath 
line 38173=>Celerdain, the Lampwrights' Street. You will find him  there with other lads 
line 38174=>that are remaining in the City. There may be things worth seeing down at the 
line 38175=>Great Gate ere the closing.' 
line 38176=>     He went out, and soon after all the  others followed. The day was st ill 
line 38177=>fine, though  it  was  growing hazy,  and it was  hot for March, even so far 
line 38178=>southwards. Pippin felt sleepy,  but  the  lodging seemed cheerless, and  he 
line 38179=>decided to go down and  explore the City. He took a few morsels that he  had 
line 38180=>saved to Shadowfax,  and  they were  graciously accepted,  though the  horse 
line 38181=>seemed to have no lack. Then he walked on down many winding ways.  
line 38182=>     People  stared  much  as  he  passed. To  his  face  men  were  gravely 
line 38183=>courteous, saluting him after the manner of Gondor with bowed head and hands 
line 38184=>upon the breast; but  behind him he heard many calls,  as those out of doors 
line 38185=>cried to others within  to come  and see the Prince  of the  Halflings,  the 
line 38186=>companion of Mithrandir. Many used some other tongue than the Common 
line 38187=>Speech, 
line 38188=>but  it  was not long before he  learned at least what was meant by  Ernil i 
line 38189=>Pheriannath  and knew that his title had gone down before him into the City. 
line 38190=>     He came at last by arched streets and many fair alleys and pavements to 
line 38191=>the lowest and widest circle, a nd there  he was directed to the Lampwrights' 
line 38192=>Street, a broad way running towards  the  Great Gate. In it he found the Old 
line 38193=>Guesthouse, a large building of grey weathered stone with  two wings running 
line 38194=>
line 38195=>####-back from the street, and between them a narrow greensward, behind which 
line 38196=>was 
line 38197=>the many-windowed house, fronted along its whole  width by  a pillared porch 
line 38198=>and  a flight of steps down on  to  the grass.  Boys were playing  among the 
line 38199=>pillars,  the only children  that Pippin had  seen  in Minas Tirith,  and he 
line 38200=>stopped to look at them. Presently one of them caught sight of him, and with 
line 38201=>a  shout  he sprang across  the grass and  came into the street, followed by 
line 38202=>several others. There he stood in front of Pippin, looking him up and down. 
line 38203=>     'Greetings!' said  the la d. 'Where do you come from? You are a stranger  
line 38204=>in the City.' 
line 38205=>     'I was,' said Pippin; 'but they say I have become a man of Gondor.' 
line 38206=>     'Oh  come!' said the lad. 'Then we are all men  here.  But how old  are 
line 38207=>you, and what is your name? I am ten  years a lready, and  shall soon be five 
line 38208=>feet.  I am  taller  than you. But then my father  is  a  Guard, one of  the 
line 38209=>tallest. What is your father?' 
line 38210=>     'Which question  shall  I  answer first?' said Pippin. 'My father farms 
line 38211=>the  lands  round Whitwell  near  Tuckborough in  the  Shire.  I  am  nearly 
line 38212=>twenty-nine, so I pass you there; though I am but four feet, and  not likely 
line 38213=>to grow any more, save sideways.' 
line 38214=>     'Twenty-nine!' said the lad  and whistled. 'Why, you are  quite old! As 
line 38215=>old as my  uncle Iorlas. Still,' he added hopefully, 'I  wager I could stand 
line 38216=>you on your head or lay you on your back.' 
line 38217=>     'Maybe you could, if I let you,' said Pippin with a laugh. 'And maybe I 
line 38218=>could  do  the  same  to  you: we know some  wrestling tricks in  my  little 
line 38219=>country.  Where,  let  me tell  you,  I am considered  uncommonly large  and 
line 38220=>strong; and I have never allowed anyone  to stand me  on  my  head. So if it 
line 38221=>came to a trial and nothing else would serve, I might have  to kill you. For  
line 38222=>when you  are older, you will learn that folk are not always what they seem;  
line 38223=>and though  you may have taken me for a soft stranger -lad and easy prey, let  
line 38224=>me  warn you: I am not,  I  am a halfling,  hard, bold,  and wicked!' Pippin 
line 38225=>pulled such  a  grim face  that the boy stepped  back a pace, but at once he 
line 38226=>returned with clenched fists and the light of battle in his eye. 
line 38227=>     'No!'  Pippin laughed. 'Don't  believe what strangers say of themselves 
line 38228=>either! I am  not a fighter.  But it  would be politer in any  case for  the 
line 38229=>challenger to say who he is.' 
line 38230=>     The boy drew himself  up  proudly.  'I am Bergil son of Beregond of the 
line 38231=>Guards,' he said. 
line 38232=>
line 38233=>####-     'So I thought,' said Pippin, 'for you look like your father. I know him 
line 38234=>and he sent me to find you.' 
line 38235=>     'Then why did you not say so at once?' said Bergil, and suddenly a look  
line 38236=>of dismay came over his face. 'Do not  tell me that he has changed his mind,  
line 38237=>and will send me away with the maidens! But no, the last wains have gone.' 
line 38238=>     'His message is less bad than that, if not good.' said Pippin. 'He says 
line 38239=>that if you would  prefer it to standing me  on  my head, you might show  me 
line 38240=>round the  City for  a while  and cheer my loneliness. I can  tell  you some 
line 38241=>tales of far countries in return.' 
line 38242=>     Bergil  clapped his hands,  and laughed with relief.  'All is well,' he 
line 38243=>cried. 'Come then! We were  soon going to the  Gate  to look  on. We will go 
line 38244=>now.' 
line 38245=>     'What is happening there?' 
line 38246=>     'The  Captains  of the  Outlands  are  expected up the South  Road  ere 
line 38247=>sundown. Come with us and you will see.' 
line 38248=>     Bergil proved a good comrade, the best company Pippin had had  since he 
