line 38363=>
line 38364=>Chapter 2. The Passing of the Grey Company 
line 38365=>
line 38366=> 
line 38367=> 
line 38368=>     Gandalf was gone, and the thudding  hoofs of Shadowfax were lost in the  
line 38369=>night, when Merry came  back to Aragorn. He  had only a light bundle, for he 
line 38370=>had lost his pack at Parth  Galen, and all he had was a few useful things he 
line 38371=>had picked up among the wreckage of  Isengard. Hasufel was  already saddled. 
line 38372=>Legolas and Gimli with their horse stood close by. 
line 38373=>     'So four of the Company still remain,'  said Aragorn. 'We  will ride on 
line 38374=>together.  But  we  shall  not  go alone,  as  I  thought. The  king is  now 
line 38375=>determined  to set out at  once.  Since the coming of the winged  shadow, he 
line 38376=>desires to return to the hills under cover of night.' 
line 38377=>     'And then whither?' said Legolas.  
line 38378=>     'I cannot say yet,' Aragorn answered. 'As for the king, he will  go  to 
line 38379=>the muster that he commanded at Edoras,  four  nights from now. And there, I 
line 38380=>think, he will hear tidings of war, and the Riders of Rohan  will go down to 
line 38381=>Minas Tirith. But for myself, and any that will go with me . . .' 
line 38382=>     'I for one!' cried Legolas. 'And Gimli with him!' said the Dwarf. 
line 38383=>     'Well, for myself,' said Aragorn, 'it is dark before me. I must go down 
line 38384=>also to Minas Tirith, but I  do not yet see the  road. An hour long prepared 
line 38385=>approaches.' 
line 38386=>     'Don't leave me behind!'  said Merry. 'I have not been of much use yet; 
line 38387=>but I don't want to be laid aside, like baggage to be called for when all is 
line 38388=>over. I don't think the Riders will want to be bothered with me now. Though, 
line 38389=>of  course, the  king did say that I was to sit by  him when  he came to his 
line 38390=>house and tell him all about the Shire.' 
line 38391=>     'Yes,' said Aragorn, 'and your road lies with him, I  think, Merry. But 
line 38392=>do  not  look for mirth at  the ending. It will be long, I fear, ere Thjoden 
line 38393=>sits  at ease  again  in  Meduseld.  Many hopes will wither  in this  bitter  
line 38394=>Spring.' 
line 38395=>     Soon all were ready  to depart:  twenty -four horses, with Gimli  behind 
line 38396=>Legolas,  and Merry  in front of Aragorn. Presently they were riding swiftly  
line 38397=>through the night. They had not long passed the mounds at the Fords of Isen, 
line 38398=>when a Rider galloped up from the rear of their line. 
line 38399=>     'My  lord,'  he said to  the king, 'there are horsemen behind us. As we 
line 38400=>crossed the fords I thought that  I heard them. Now we  are sure.  They  are 
line 38401=>
line 38402=>####-overtaking us, riding hard.' 
line 38403=>     Thjoden at once called a halt. The Riders turned about and seized their 
line 38404=>spears.  Aragorn  dismounted and  set Merry on the  ground, and drawing  his 
line 38405=>sword he stood by the king's stirrup. Jomer and his esquire rode back to the 
line 38406=>rear. Merry felt more  like unneeded baggage than  ever, and he wondered, if 
line 38407=>there was a fight, what  he should do. Supposing the king's small escort was 
line 38408=>trapped and overcome, but  he escaped into the darkness  - alone in the wild  
line 38409=>fields of Rohan  with no idea of where he was in all the  endless miles? 'No 
line 38410=>good!' he thought. He drew his sword and tightened his belt. 
line 38411=>     The sinking moon was obscured by a great sailing cloud, but suddenly it 
line 38412=>rode  out clear  again. Then they all  heard the sound of  hoofs, and at the 
line 38413=>same moment they saw dark shapes coming  swiftly on the path from the fords.  
line 38414=>The moonlight glinted here and  there  on the points of spears. The number of 
line 38415=>the pursuers could  not be told, but they seemed  no fewer than  the  king's 
line 38416=>escort, at the least. 
line 38417=>     When they were some  fifty paces off,  Jomer  cried  in  a  loud voice: 
line 38418=>'Halt! Halt! Who rides in Rohan?' 
line 38419=>     The  pursuers  brought  their  steeds  to  a sudden  stand.  A  silence 
line 38420=>followed: and  then in the  moonlight, a  horseman could be seen dismounting 
line 38421=>and walking  slowly  forward. His hand  showed white as  he held it up, palm 
line 38422=>outward, in token of pea ce; but the king's men gripped their weapons. At ten 
line 38423=>paces the man stopped. He was  tall,  a dark standing shadow. Then his clear 
line 38424=>voice rang out. 
line 38425=>     'Rohan? Rohan did you say?  That is  a glad word.  We seek that land in 
line 38426=>haste from long afar.' 
line 38427=>     'You have found it,' said Jomer. 'When you crossed the fords yonder you  
line 38428=>entered it. But it is the realm of Thjoden  the King. None ride here save by 
line 38429=>his leave. Who are you? And what is your haste?' 
line 38430=>     'Halbarad DÂ®nadan, Ranger  of the North I am,' cried the man. 'We  seek  
line 38431=>one Aragorn son of Arathorn, and we heard that he was in Rohan.' 
line 38432=>     'And  you have  found  him also!' cried  Aragorn. Giving his  reins  to 
line 38433=>Merry, he ran  forward and embraced  the newcomer. 'Halbarad!' he said.  'Of 
line 38434=>all joys this is the least expected!' 
line 38435=>     Merry breathed a sigh of relief. He had thought that this was some last 
line 38436=>trick of Saruman's, to waylay  the king  while he  had  only a few men about 
line 38437=>him;  but it seemed that there would be no need to die in Thjoden's defence,  
line 38438=>not yet at any rate. He sheathed his sword. 
line 38439=>
line 38440=>####-     'All is well,' said Aragorn, turning back. 'Here are some of my own kin 
line 38441=>from  the far land where I dwelt. But why they come, and how many  they  be, 
line 38442=>Halbarad shall tell us.' 
line 38443=>     'I  have thirty  with me,' said Halbarad. 'That is  all  of our kindred 
line 38444=>that could be gathered in  haste; but the  brethren Elladan and Elrohir have 
line 38445=>ridden with us, desiring to go to  the  war. We rode as swiftly as we  might 
line 38446=>when your summons came.' 
line 38447=>     'But  I  did  not summon you,' said Aragorn,  'save  only  in wish.  My 
line 38448=>thoughts have often turned to you, and seldom more than tonight; yet I  have 
line 38449=>sent  no  word. But come! All such matters must wait. You find us riding  in 
line 38450=>haste and danger. Ride with us now, if the king will give his leave. ' 
line 38451=>     Thjoden was indeed glad of the news. 'It  is well!' he said.  'If these 
line 38452=>kinsmen be in any way like to yourself, my lord Aragorn, thirty such knights 
line 38453=>will be a strength that cannot be counted by heads.' 
line 38454=>     Then the Riders  set out again, and Aragor n  for a while rode with  the 
line 38455=>DÂ®nedain; and when they had spoken of tidings in the North and in the South, 
