line 38466=>thongs. 
line 38467=>     'It is a gift that  I bring  you  from the Lady of Rivendell,' answered 
line 38468=>Halbarad.  'She wrought it in secret,  and long was the making. But she also 
line 38469=>sends word  to you: The days now are short.  Either our hope cometh, or  all  
line 38470=>hopes end. Therefore I  send  thee what I have  made  for  thee. Fare  well, 
line 38471=>Elfstone!' 
line 38472=>     And Aragorn said:  'Now I  know  what you bear. Bear it still for  me a  
line 38473=>while!' And  he turned and  looked away to the North under  the great stars,  
line 38474=>and then he fell silent and spoke no more while the night's journey lasted. 
line 38475=>     The night  was old  and the East grey  when  they rode  up at last from 
line 38476=>Deeping-coomb and came back to the Hornburg. There they were to lie and rest  
line 38477=>
line 38478=>####-for a brief while and take counsel. 
line 38479=>     Merry  slept  until  he was  roused by Legolas and  Gimli.  'The Sun is 
line 38480=>high,'  said Legolas. 'All others are  up and doing.  Come, Master Sluggard, 
line 38481=>and look at this place while you may!' 
line 38482=>     'There  was a  battle here  three  nights ago,' said Gimli,  'and  here 
line 38483=>Legolas and  I  played a game that I won only  by a single orc. Come and see 
line 38484=>how it was!  And there  are caves, Merry, caves of  wonder!  Shall we  visit 
line 38485=>them, Legolas, do you think?' 
line 38486=>     'Nay!  There is no  time,' said the Elf. 'Do  not spoil the wonder with 
line 38487=>haste! I have given you my wor d to return hither with you, if a day of peace 
