line 38850=>you have leave to  be burned in the house, for the men will need it no more. 
line 38851=>But I  am of the House of Eorl and not a serving-woman. I can ride and wield 
line 38852=>blade, and I do not fear either pain or death.' 
line 38853=>     'What do you fear, lady?' he asked. 
line 38854=>     'A cage,' she said. 'To stay behind bars, until use and old age  accept 
line 38855=>them, and all chance of doing great deeds is gone beyond recall or desire.' 
line 38856=>     'And  yet you  counselled  me  not  to adventure on the road that I had 
line 38857=>
line 38858=>####-chosen, because it is perilous?' 
line 38859=>     'So may one counsel another,' she said. 'Yet I do not bid you flee from  
line 38860=>peril, but to ride to battle where your sword may win renown and victory.  I 
line 38861=>would not see a thing that is high and excellent cast away needlessly.' 
line 38862=>     'Nor would I,' he  said. 'Therefore  I  say to you, lady: Stay! For you  
line 38863=>have no errand to the South.' 
line 38864=>     'Neither have those others who go with thee. They go  only because they 
line 38865=>would not be parted from thee  - because they love thee.' Then she turned and 
line 38866=>vanished into the night. 
line 38867=>     When the light of day was come into the  sky  but  the sun was  not yet 
line 38868=>risen above the high  ridges in the East,  Aragorn made ready to depart. His 
line 38869=>company was all mounted, and he was  about to leap into the saddle, when the 
line 38870=>Lady  Jowyn came to bid them farewell. She was clad as a Rider and girt with 
line 38871=>a sword. In her hand she bore a cup, and  she set it to her lips and drank a  
line 38872=>little, wishing them  good speed; and then she gave the cup to Aragorn,  and 
line 38873=>he drank, and he said:  'Farewell, Lady of Rohan! I drink to the fortunes of 
line 38874=>your House, and of you, and of all  your people. Say to your brother: beyond  
line 38875=>the shadows we may meet again!' 
line 38876=>     Then it seemed to Gimli  and Legolas who were nearby that she wept, and 
line 38877=>in one  so  stern and proud that seemed  the  more grievous.  But  she said: 
line 38878=>'Aragorn, wilt thou go?' 
line 38879=>     'I will,' he said. 
line 38880=>     'Then wilt thou not let me ride with this company, as I have asked?' 
line 38881=>     'I will not, lady,' he said. 'For that I  could not grant without leave 
line 38882=>of the king and  of  your brother; and they will not return until  tomorrow.  
line 38883=>But I count now every hour, indeed every minute. Farewell!' 
line 38884=>     Then she fell on her knees, saying: 'I beg thee!' 
line 38885=>     'Nay, lady,' he said, and taking her by the hand he raised her. Then he 
line 38886=>kissed her hand, and sprang into the saddle, and rode away, and did not look  
line 38887=>back; and only  those who knew  him well and were  near to him saw  the pain 
line 38888=>that he bore. 
line 38889=>     But Jowyn stood still as  a figure carven in stone,  her hands clenched 
line 38890=>at her sides, and she watched  them until they passed into the shadows under  
line 38891=>the  black Dwimorberg,  the Haunted Mountain, in which was  the Gate of  the 
line 38892=>Dead.  When they were lost  to view, she turned,  stumbling  as  one that is 
line 38893=>blind, and went back to her lodging. But none of her folk  saw this parting, 
line 38894=>for they hid themselves in fear and would not come forth until  the  day was 
line 38895=>
line 38896=>####-up, and the reckless strangers were gone. 
line 38897=>     And some  said: 'They are Elvish wights. Let them go where they belong,  
line 38898=>into the dark places, and never return. The times are evil enough.' 
line 38899=>     The light was  still grey as they rode, for the sun had not yet climbed 
line 38900=>over the black ridges of the Haunted Mountain before  them. A dread  fell on 
line 38901=>them, even as they passed between the lines of ancient stones and so came to 
line 38902=>the Dimholt.  There under the  gloom of  black  trees  that not even Legolas 
line 38903=>could long  endure they found a hollow place opening at the mountain's root, 
line 38904=>and right in their path stood a single mighty stone like a finger of doom. 
line 38905=>     'My blood runs chill,'  said Gimli, but the others were silent, and his 
line 38906=>voice fell dead on  the  dank fir-needles at his feet. The horses  would not 
line 38907=>pass the threatening stone, until the riders dismounted and led them  about. 
line 38908=>And so they came at last deep into the glen; and there stood a sheer wall of 
line 38909=>rock, and in  the wall the Dark  Door  gaped  before them like  the mouth of 
line 38910=>night.  Signs and figures were  carved above its  wide arch too dim to read, 
line 38911=>and fear flowed from it like a grey vapour. 
line 38912=>     The company halted, and there was  not a  heart among them that did not  
line 38913=>quail, unless it were the heart of Legolas of the Elves, for whom the ghosts 
line 38914=>of Men have no terror. 
line 38915=>     'This is an  evil door,' said Halbarad, 'and my death lies beyond it. I 
line 38916=>will dare to pass it nonetheless; but no horse will enter.' 
line 38917=>     'But  we must go  in,  and therefore  the horses  must  go  too,'  said 
line 38918=>Aragorn.  'For if ever  we  come  through this  darkness,  many  leagues lie 
line 38919=>beyond, and every hour  that is lost there will bring the triumph  of Sauron 
line 38920=>nearer. Follow me!' 
line 38921=>     Then Aragorn led the way, and such was the strength of his will in that 
line 38922=>hour  that all the DÂ®nedain and  their horses  followed him. And  indeed the 
line 38923=>love that the horses of the Rangers bore for their riders was  so great that 
line 38924=>they were willing  to face even the  terror  of the Door, if  their masters' 
line 38925=>hearts were steady as they walked beside them. But Arod, the horse of Rohan, 
line 38926=>refused  the  way, and he stood sweating and trembling  in a  fear  that was 
line 38927=>grievous to see. Then Legolas laid his hands on his eyes and sang some words 
line 38928=>that  went  soft in the  gloom, until he  suffered himself  to  be  led, and 
line 38929=>Legolas passed in. And there stood Gimli the Dwarf left all alone. 
line 38930=>     His knees shook,  and  he  was wroth  with himself.  'Here is  a  thing 
line 38931=>unheard of!' he said. 'An  Elf  will go underground and a  Dwarf  dare not!' 
line 38932=>With that he plunged in. But it seemed to him  that he dragged his feet like 
line 38933=>
line 38934=>####-lead over the threshold; and at once a blindness  came  upon him,  even upon 
line 38935=>Gimli Gluin's son who had walked unafraid in many deep places of the world. 
line 38936=>     Aragorn  had  brought  torches from Dunharrow,  and  now he went  ahead 
line 38937=>bearing one  aloft; and Elladan with  another went  at the rear, and  Gimli, 
line 38938=>stumbling behind, strove to overtake him. He could  see nothing  but the dim 
line 38939=>flame  of the tor ches; but  if the company halted, there  seemed  an endless 
line 38940=>whisper of voices all about him, a murmur of words in no tongue  that he had 
line 38941=>ever heard before. 
line 38942=>     Nothing assailed  the  company  nor  withstood  their passage,  and yet 
line 38943=>steadily fear grew on the Dwarf as  he went on:  most of all because he knew 
line 38944=>now that there could be no  turning back; all the paths behind were thronged 
line 38945=>by an unseen host that followed in the dark. 
line 38946=>     So time unreckoned passed, until Gimli  saw a  sight that he  was  ever 
line 38947=>afterwards loth to recall. The road was  wide, as far as he could judge, but 
line 38948=>now the company came  suddenly  into a great empty space, and there  were no 
line 38949=>longer any walls upon either side. The dread  was  so  heavy on him  that he 
line 38950=>could  hardly walk. Away  to the  left  something glittered  in the gloom as 
line 38951=>Aragorn's  torch drew near.  Then Aragorn halted and  went  to look  what it  
line 38952=>might be. 
line 38953=>     'Does  he  feel no fear?' muttered the  Dwarf. 'In any other cave Gimli 
line 38954=>Gluin's son would have been  the first to run to the gleam of gold.  But not 
line 38955=>here! Let it lie!' 
line 38956=>     Nonetheless he drew near,  and saw Aragorn kneeling, while Elladan held 
line 38957=>aloft both torches. Before him were the bones of  a  mighty man. He had been 
line 38958=>clad  in  mail, and still his harness lay there  whole; for the cavern's air 
line 38959=>was as dry as dust, and his  hauberk  was gilded. His belt  was  of gold and 
line 38960=>garnets, and rich with gold was the helm upon his bony head face downward on 
line 38961=>the floor. He  had fallen  near the far  wall  of the cave, as now could  be 
line 38962=>seen, and before  him stood a  stony door closed fast: his finger -bones were 
line 38963=>still clawing at the cracks. A notched and broken sword lay by him, as if he 
line 38964=>had hewn at the rock in his last despair. 
line 38965=>     Aragorn did  not touch him, but after gazing silently for  a  while  he 
line 38966=>rose  and sighed. 'Hither  shall the flowers of  simbelmynl come never  unto 
line 38967=>world's  end,' he murmured. 'Nine mounds and seven there are now  green with 
line 38968=>grass, and through all the long years he has lain at the door that  he could 
line 38969=>not unlock. Whither does it lead? Why would he pass? None shall ever know!  
line 38970=>     'For that is not my errand!' he cried, turning back and speaking to the 
line 38971=>
line 38972=>####-whispering darkness behind. 'Keep your hoards and your secrets hidden in the 
line 38973=>Accursed Years! Speed only we ask.  Let us pass, and then come! I summon 
line 38974=>you 
line 38975=>to the Stone of Erech!' 
line 38976=>     There was no answer, unless it were an utter silence more dreadful than 
