line 39083=>Chapter 3. The Muster of Rohan 
line 39084=>
line 39085=> 
line 39086=> 
line 39087=>     Now all roads were running together to  the  East to meet the coming of 
line 39088=>war and the onset of the Shadow. And even as Pippin  stood at the Great Gate 
line 39089=>of the City  and saw the Prince of Dol Amroth ride in with  his banners, the 
line 39090=>King of Rohan came down out of the hills. 
line 39091=>     Day  was waning. In  the last  rays  of the  sun  the Riders  cast long 
line 39092=>pointed shadows that went on before them. Darkness had already crept beneath 
line 39093=>the murmuring fir-woods that clothed the steep mountain-sides. The king rode 
line 39094=>now  slowly at the end  of  the day. Presently the  path turned round a huge 
line 39095=>bare  shoulder of rock and plunged into the  gloom  of  soft -sighing  trees.  
line 39096=>Down, down they went in a long winding file. When  at last they came  to the 
line 39097=>bottom of  the gorge they  found that evening had fallen in the deep places.  
line 39098=>The sun was gone. Twilight lay upon the waterfalls. 
line 39099=>     All day far below them a leaping stream had run down from the high pass 
line 39100=>behind, cleaving its narrow way between pine-clad  walls; and now  through a  
line 39101=>stony  gate it flowed out and passed into a wider vale. The Riders  followed 
line 39102=>it, and suddenly Harrowdale lay before  them, loud with  the noise of waters 
line 39103=>in the evening. There the white Snowbourn, joined by the lesser stream, went 
line 39104=>rushing, fuming on  the  stones,  down to Edoras and the green hills and the 
line 39105=>plains. Away to the right at the head of the great dale the mighty Starkhorn 
line 39106=>loomed up above its  vast buttresses swathed in cloud; but  its jagged peak, 
line 39107=>clothed in everlasting snow, gleamed far above the world, blue-shadowed upon 
line 39108=>the East, red-stained by the sunset in the West. 
line 39109=>     Merry looked out in wonder upon this strange country,  of which he  had 
line 39110=>heard many tales upon their long road.  It was a skyless world, in which his 
line 39111=>eye; through dim gulfs of shadowy  air, saw only ever-mounting slopes, great 
line 39112=>walls of  stone behind  great  walls, and  frowning precipices wreathed with 
line 39113=>mist.  He sat  for a moment half dreaming, listening to  the noise of water, 
line 39114=>the  whisper of dark trees, the crack of stone, and the vast waiting silence 
line 39115=>that brooded  behind all sound. He  loved  mountains,  or he had  loved  the 
line 39116=>thought of them marching  on the edge of  stories brought from far away;  but 
line 39117=>now he was borne down by the insupportable weight of Middle-earth. He 
line 39118=>longed 
line 39119=>to shut out the immensity in a quiet room by a fire. 
line 39120=>     He was very tired, for though they had  ridden slowly, they had  ridden 
line 39121=>
line 39122=>####-with very  little  rest. Hour after  hour for nearly three weary days he had 
line 39123=>jogged  up  and down, over passes, and through long dales,  and  across many 
line 39124=>streams. Sometimes where the way  was  broader he  had ridden at  the king's 
line 39125=>side, not noticing that many  of the Riders smiled to see  the two together: 
line 39126=>the  hobbit  on his little shaggy grey pony,  and the Lord of  Rohan on  his 
line 39127=>great white horse. Then he had talked to Thjoden, telling him about his home 
line 39128=>and the doings of  the Shire-folk, or listening in turn to tales of the Mark 
line 39129=>and its  mighty  men of old.  But most of the time, especially  on this last 
line 39130=>day, Merry had ridden  by himself just behind the  king, saying nothing, and 
line 39131=>trying to understand the slow sonorous speech of Rohan that he heard the men 
line 39132=>behind him using. It was  a  language in which there seemed to be many words 
line 39133=>that he  knew, though spoken more richly and strongly than in the Shire, yet  
line 39134=>he could not piece the words together. At times some Rider would lift up his 
line 39135=>clear voice in stirring song,  and Merry felt his heart leap, though he  did 
line 39136=>not know what it was about. 
line 39137=>     All the  same  he had been lonely, and  never more so  than now at  the 
line 39138=>day's end.  He wondered where  in all this strange world  Pippin had got to; 
line 39139=>and what would become of Aragorn and Legolas and Gimli. Then suddenly 
line 39140=>like a 
line 39141=>cold touch on his heart he thought of Frodo and Sam. 'I am forgetting them!' 
line 39142=>he said  to himself reproachfully. 'And yet they are more important than all 
line 39143=>the  rest of us. And I  came to help them; but now  they must be hundreds of 
line 39144=>miles away, if they are still alive.' He shivered. 
line 39145=>     'Harrowdale at  last!' said Jomer. 'Our journey  is almost at  an end.' 
line 39146=>They halted. The paths out of the narrow gorge fell steeply. Only a glimpse,  
line 39147=>as  through a tall window, could be seen of the great valley in the gloaming 
line 39148=>below. A single small light could be seen twinkling by the river. 
line 39149=>     'This journey is over, maybe,' said Thjoden, 'but I have far yet to go. 
line 39150=>Last night the  moon was full, and in the morning I shall ride to Edoras  to 
line 39151=>the gathering of the Mark.' 
line 39152=>     'But if you would take my  counsel,'  said  Jomer  in a low voice, 'you  
line 39153=>would then return hither, until the war is over, lost or won.' 
line 39154=>     Thjoden smiled.  'Nay,  my son, for  so I will call you, speak  not the 
line 39155=>soft words of Wormtongue in my old ears!' He drew himself up and looked 
line 39156=>back 
line 39157=>at the long line of his men fading into the dusk behind. 'Long years  in the 
line 39158=>space of days it seems since I rode west;  but never  will I lean on a staff 
line 39159=>
line 39160=>####-again. If the war is lost, what good will be my hiding in the hills? And  if 
line 39161=>it is won, what grief will it be, even if I fall, spending my last strength?  
line 39162=>But we will leave this now. Tonight I will lie in the Hold of Dunharrow. One 
line 39163=>evening of peace at least is left us. Let us ride on! ' 
line 39164=>     In  the  deepening  dusk  they came  down  into  the  valley. Here  the 
line 39165=>Snowbourn flowed near  to the western walls of  the dale, and soon the  path 
line 39166=>led them to a ford where the shallow  waters murmured  loudly on the stones. 
line 39167=>The ford was guarded.   As the king approached many men sprang up out of  the 
line 39168=>shadow of the rocks; and when they saw the king they cried with glad voices:  
line 39169=>'Thjoden King! Thjoden King! The King of the Mark returns!' 
line 39170=>     Then one blew a long call on  a horn.  It  echoed in the  valley. Other  
line 39171=>horns answered it, and lights shone out across the river. 
line 39172=>     And suddenly  there  rose a great chorus of  trumpets from high  above, 
line 39173=>sounding from some hollow  place, as  it seemed, that gathered  their  notes 
