line 39181=>     'At dawn three  days ago,  lord,' he  said. 'Shadowfax came like a wind 
line 39182=>out of  the West to  Edoras, and Gandalf brought  tidings of your victory to 
line 39183=>gladden  our  hearts.  But  he  brought also  word from you  to  hasten  the 
line 39184=>gathering of the Riders. And then came the winged Shadow.' 
line 39185=>     'The winged Shadow?' said Thjoden. 'We saw it also, but that was in the 
line 39186=>dead of night before Gandalf left us.' 
line 39187=>     'Maybe, lord,' said DÂ®nhere. 'Yet the same, or  another like to  it,  a  
line 39188=>flying darkness in  the shape of a  monstrous bird, passed  over Edoras that 
line 39189=>morning, and all men were  shaken with fear. For it  stooped  upon Meduseld, 
line 39190=>and  as it came low, almost to the gable,  there came a cry that stopped our 
line 39191=>hearts.  Then  it was that  Gandalf  counselled  us  not to  assemble in the 
line 39192=>fields, but to meet you here in the valley under the mounta ins. And  he bade 
line 39193=>us to kindle no more lights or fires than  barest need asked. So it has been 
line 39194=>done. Gandalf spoke with great authority. We trust that it is as  you  would 
line 39195=>wish. Naught has been seen in Harrowdale of these evil things.' 
line 39196=>     'It is well,' said Thjoden. 'I  will ride  now  to  the Hold, and there 
line 39197=>
line 39198=>####-before  I go to rest I will meet the marshals and captains. Let them come to 
line 39199=>me as soon as may be!' 
line 39200=>     The road now led eastward straight across the valley, which was at that 
line 39201=>point little more than half a mile in width. Flats and meads of rough grass,  
line 39202=>grey now in the falling night,  lay all about, but  in front on the far side 
line 39203=>of the dale Merry saw a frowning wall, a last outlier of the great  roots of 
line 39204=>the Starkhorn, cloven by the river in ages past . 
line 39205=>     On all the level spaces there was great concourse of men. Some thronged 
line 39206=>to the  roadside, hailing  the king and the riders  from the West with  glad 
line 39207=>cries; but stretching away into the distance behind there  were ordered rows 
line 39208=>of tents and booths, and lines of picketed horses,  and great store of arms, 
line 39209=>and piled spears bristling like  thickets of new-planted trees. Now  all the 
line 39210=>great assembly was falling into shadow, and yet, though the night -chill blew 
line 39211=>cold  from  the heights  no  lanterns  glowed, no fires  were  lit. Watchmen 
line 39212=>heavily cloaked paced to and fro. 
line 39213=>     Merry wondered  how many Riders there  were. He  could  not guess their 
line 39214=>number in the gathering gloom, but it  looked to him like a great army, many 
line 39215=>thousands strong. While  he was  peering from side  to side the king's party 
line 39216=>came up under the looming cliff on the eastern side of the valley; and there 
line 39217=>suddenly the path began to climb, and Merry looked up in  amazement.  He 
line 39218=>was 
line 39219=>on a road the like of which he had never seen before,  a great work of men's 
line 39220=>hands in years beyond the  reach of  song. Upwards it wound, coiling  like a  
line 39221=>snake, boring its way across the  sheer slope of rock.  Steep as a stair, it 
line 39222=>looped  backwards and forwards as it  climbed. Up it horses  could walk, and 
line 39223=>wains  could be slowly hauled; but no  enemy could come that way, except out 
line 39224=>of the air,  if it was defended from above. At each turn  of the road  there 
line 39225=>were great standing stones that had been carved in the likeness of men, huge 
line 39226=>and clumsy-limbed, squatting cross-legged  with  their stumpy arms folded on 
line 39227=>fat bellies. Some in the wearing of the years had lost all features save the 
line 39228=>dark  holes of  their eyes that  still stared  sadly  at the passers-by. The 
line 39229=>Riders hardly glanced at them.  The  PÂ®kel-men they  called them, and heeded 
line 39230=>them little:  no power or terror was left in them; but  Merry  gazed at them 
line 39231=>with wonder  and a feeling almost of pity,  as they loomed up  mournfully in 
line 39232=>the dusk. 
line 39233=>     After a while he looked back and found that he had already climbed some 
line 39234=>hundreds of feet  above the valley, but still far below he could dimly see a  
line 39235=>
line 39236=>####-winding  line of Riders crossing the ford and filing along the  road towards 
line 39237=>the camp prepared for  them. Only the king  and his guard were going up into 
line 39238=>the Hold. 
line 39239=>     At last the king's company came to a sharp brink, and the climbing road 
line 39240=>passed into a cutting between walls of rock, and  so went  up a  short slope 
line 39241=>and  out  on  to a  wide  upland.  The  Firienfeld  men called it,  a  green 
