line 39525=>you shall serve the Lady Jowyn, who will govern the folk in my stead.' 
line 39526=>     'But, but, lord,' Merry  stammered, 'I offered you my sword.  I do  not 
line 39527=>want  to be parted  from you like this, Thjoden King. And as all my  friends 
line 39528=>have gone to the battle' I should be ashamed to stay behind.' 
line 39529=>     'But we ride on horses tall and swift,' said Thjoden; 'and great though 
line 39530=>your heart be, you cannot ride on such beasts.' 
line 39531=>     'Then tie me on  to the back of one,  or let me hang  on a  stirrup, or  
line 39532=>something,' said Merry. 'It  is a long way to  run; but  run  I shall, if  I 
line 39533=>cannot ride, even if I wear my feet off and arrive weeks too late.' 
line 39534=>     Thjoden smiled.  'Rather  than  that  I  would  bear  you  with  me  on 
line 39535=>Snowmane,'  he said. 'But at the least you shall ride with me to  Edoras and 
line 39536=>look on Meduseld;  for that way I  shall go. So far Stybba can bear you: the 
line 39537=>great race will not begin till we reach the plains.' 
line 39538=>     Then Jowyn rose  up. 'Come now,  Meriadoc!' she said. 'I will show  you  
line 39539=>
line 39540=>####-the gear that  I have  prepared  fur  you.' They  went out  together.  'This 
line 39541=>request only did  Aragorn make to me,' said Jowyn, as  they passed among the 
line 39542=>tents, 'that you should be armed for battle. I have  granted it, as I could. 
line 39543=>For my heart tells me that you will need such gear ere the end.' 
line 39544=>     Now she led Merry to a booth among the lodges of the king's  guard  and 
line 39545=>there an armourer brought out to her a  small  helm, and a round shield, and 
line 39546=>other gear. 
line 39547=>     'No mail have we to fit you,' said Jowyn, 'nor any time for the forging 
line 39548=>of such a hauberk; but here is also a stout jerkin of leather, a belt, and a  
line 39549=>knife. A sword you have.' 
line 39550=>     Merry bowed,  and  the lady showed  him  the shield, which was like the 
line 39551=>shield that had  been given  to Gimli, and  it bore on  it the device of the 
line 39552=>white horse. 'Take  all  these things,' she  said, 'and  bear  them  to good 
line 39553=>fortune! Farewell now, Master  Meriadoc! Yet maybe we  shall meet again, you  
line 39554=>and I.' 
line 39555=>     So  it was that amid a  gathering gloom the King of the Mark made ready 
line 39556=>to lead  all  his  Riders on  the eastward road. Hearts were heavy  and  many 
line 39557=>quailed  in the shadow. But they were  a stern people, loyal to  their lord, 
line 39558=>and  little weeping or  murmuring was heard, even in  the  camp in  the Hold 
line 39559=>where the exiles from Edoras  were housed, women and children  and old  men. 
line 39560=>Doom hung over  them, but they faced it silently. 
line 39561=>     Two  swift hours passed, and now the king  sat  upon  his  white horse, 
line 39562=>glimmering in the half light. Proud and tall he seemed, though the hair that 
line 39563=>flowed beneath his high helm was  like  snow; and  many marvelled a t him and 
line 39564=>took heart to see him unbent and unafraid. 
line 39565=>     There on the wide  flats beside the noisy river were marshalled in many 
line 39566=>companies well nigh five and fifty  hundreds of Riders fully armed, and many 
line 39567=>hundreds of other men  with spare  horses lightly burdened. A single trumpet 
line 39568=>sounded. The king raised his  hand, and then silently  the host  of the Mark 
line 39569=>began to  move. Foremost went twelve of the king's household-men,  Riders of 
line 39570=>renown. Then the king followed with Jomer on his right. He had said farewell 
line 39571=>to Jowyn above in  the Hold, and the  memory was grievous; but now he turned 
line 39572=>his mind to the  road that lay ahead. Behind him Merry  rode  on Stybba with 
line 39573=>the errand riders of Gondor, and behind them again twelve more of the king's 
line 39574=>household. They passed  down  the long ranks of  waiting  men with stern  and 
line 39575=>unmoved faces.  But when they had  come  almost  to the end of  the line one 
line 39576=>looked up  glancing  keenly at the hobbit. A young man,  Merry thought as he 
line 39577=>
line 39578=>####-returned the glance, less in height and girth than most. He caught the glint 
line 39579=>of clear grey eyes; and then he  shivered, for  it came suddenly to him that 
line 39580=>it was the face of one without hope who goes in search of death. 
line 39581=>     On  down  the grey road they went beside  the  Snowbourn rushing on its 
line 39582=>stones; through the hamlets of Underharrow and Upbourn, where many sad 
line 39583=>faces 
line 39584=>of women looked out from dark doors; and so without horn or harp or music of 
line 39585=>men's voices the great  ride into the East  began with  which  the songs  of 
line 39586=>Rohan were busy for many long lives of men thereafter. 
line 39587=>     From dark Dunharrow in the dim morning 
line 39588=>     with thane and captain rode Thengel's son: 
line 39589=>     to Edoras he came, the ancient halls 
line 39590=>     of the Mark-wardens mist-enshrouded; 
line 39591=>     golden timbers were in gloom mantled. 
line 39592=>     Farewell he bade to his free people, 
line 39593=>     hearth and high-seat, and the hallowed places, 
line 39594=>     where long he had feasted ere the light faded. 
line 39595=>     Forth rode the king, fear behind him, 
line 39596=>     fate before him. Fealty kept he; 
line 39597=>     oaths he had taken, all fulfilled them. 
line 39598=>     Forth rode Thjoden. Five nights and days 
line 39599=>     east and onward rode the Eorlingas 
line 39600=>     through Folde and Fenmarch and the Firienwood, 
line 39601=>     six thousand spears to Sunlending, 
line 39602=>     Mundburg the mighty under Mindolluin, 
line 39603=>     Sea-kings' city in the South -kingdom 
line 39604=>     foe-beleaguered, fire-encircled. 
line 39605=>     Doom drove them on. Darkness took them, 
line 39606=>     Horse and horseman; hoofbeats afar 
line 39607=>     sank into silence: so the songs tell us. 
line 39608=>     It was indeed in deepening gloom that the king came to Edoras, although 
line 39609=>it  was then but noon by the  hour. There  he halted only  a short while and 
line 39610=>strengthened his host by some three  score  of Riders that  came late to the 
line 39611=>weapontake. Now having eaten he made ready to set out  again, and  he wished 
line 39612=>his esquire  a kindly farewell. But Merry begged for the last time not to be 
line 39613=>parted from him. 
line 39614=>     'This is no journey for  such steeds  as  Stybba,  as I have told you ' 
line 39615=>
line 39616=>####-said  Thjoden.  'And  in such a battle as we think to  make on the fields of 
line 39617=>Gondor what  would  you do, Master   Meriadoc, sword-thain though you be, 
line 39618=>and 
line 39619=>greater of heart than of stature?' 
line 39620=>     'As  for that,  who can tell?' answered Merry. 'But why, lord,  did you  
line 39621=>receive me as sword-thain, if not to stay by your side? And I would not have 
line 39622=>it said of me in song only that I was always left behind!' 
line 39623=>     'I  received you for your safe-keeping,' answered Thjoden; 'and also to 
line 39624=>do  as I might bid. None of my Riders can  bear you as burden. If the battle 
line 39625=>were before my gates, maybe your deeds would be remembered by the 
line 39626=>minstrels; 
line 39627=>but it  is a  hundred leagues and two to Mundburg  where Denethor is lord. I  
line 39628=>will say no more.' 
line 39629=>     Merry  bowed and  went  away  unhappily,  and  stared  at the lines  of 
line 39630=>horsemen. Already the companies were preparing to start: men were tightening 
line 39631=>girths, looking  to saddles, caressing their horses; some gazed uneasily  at 
line 39632=>the lowering sky. Unnoticed a Rider came up and spoke softly in the hobbit's 
line 39633=>ear. 
line 39634=>     'Where will wants not, a way opens, so we say,' he whispered; 'and so I 
line 39635=>have found myself.' Merry looked up and saw that it was the young Rider 
line 39636=>whom 
line 39637=>he had  noticed in the morning. 'You wish to go whither the Lord of the Mark 
line 39638=>goes: I see it in your face.' 
line 39639=>     'I do,' said Merry. 
line 39640=>     'Then you  shall go with me,'  said the Rider. 'I will bear  you before 
line 39641=>me, under my cloak until we are far afield, and this darkness is yet darker. 
line 39642=>Such good will should not be denied. Say no more to any man, but come!' 
line 39643=>     'Thank you indeed!' said Merry. 'Thank you, sir, though I  do not  know 
line 39644=>your name.' 
line 39645=>     'Do you not?' said the Rider softly. 'Then call me Dernhelm.' 
line 39646=>     Thus it  came to pass that  when the  king set out, before Dernhelm sat 
line 39647=>Meriadoc the hobbit, and the great  grey steed  Windfola  made little of the 
line 39648=>burden; for Dernhelm  was  less in  weight than many men, though  lithe  and 
line 39649=>well-knit in frame. 
line 39650=>     On  into the shadow they  rode. In  the willow-thickets where Snowbourn 
line 39651=>flowed into Entwash, twelve leagues east of Edoras,  they camped that night. 
line 39652=>And  then on  again  through the Folde; and through  the  Fenmarch, where to 
line 39653=>
line 39654=>####-their  right great  oakwoods climbed on the skirts of the  hills  under  the 
line 39655=>shades of dark Halifirien by the borders of Gondor; but  away  to their left  
line 39656=>the mists lay on the marshes fed by the mouths of Entwash. And as they  rode 
line 39657=>rumour came of war in the North. Lone men, riding wild, brought word of foes 
line 39658=>assailing their east -borders, of orc-hosts marching in the Wold of Rohan. 
line 39659=>     'Ride on! Ride on!'  cried Jomer. 'Too late now to turn aside. The fens 
line 39660=>of Entwash must guard our flank. Haste now we need. Ride on!' 
line 39661=>     And  so King Thjoden departed from his own realm, and mile  by mile the 
line 39662=>long  road  wound  away,  and  the  beacon  hills  marched  past:  Calenhad, 
line 39663=>Min-Rimmon, Erelas, Nardol. But  their fires  were  quenched. All  the lands 
line 39664=>were grey and still;  and  ever the shadow  deepened before them,  and  hope  
line 39665=>waned in every heart. 
line 39666=> 
line 39667=>
line 39668=>####- 
line 39669=>
line 39670=>Chapter 4. The Siege of Gondor 
line 39671=>
line 39672=> 
line 39673=> 
line 39674=>     Pippin was  roused by Gandalf. Candles  were lit in their chamber,  for  
line 39675=>only  a dim  twilight came  through the  windows; the air  was  heavy as with 
line 39676=>approaching thunder. 
line 39677=>     'What is the time?' said Pippin yawning. 
line 39678=>     'Past the second hour,' said Gandalf. 'Time to get up and make yourself 
line 39679=>presentable.  You  are summoned to  the Lord  of the City to learn your  new 
line 39680=>duties.' 
line 39681=>     'And will he provide breakfast?' 
line 39682=>     'No! I have provided  it: all that you will get till noon. Food  is now 
line 39683=>doled out by order.' 
line 39684=>     Pippin  looked  ruefully  at  the  small  loaf  and  (he  thought) very 
line 39685=>inadequate  pat of   butter which was set out for him,  beside  a cup of thin 
line 39686=>milk.  'Why did you bring me here?' he said. 
line 39687=>     'You know quite well,' said Gandalf. 'To keep you out  of mischief; and 
line 39688=>if you do  not  like being here, you can remember  that  you  brought it  on 
line 39689=>yourself.' Pippin said no more. 
line 39690=>     Before  long  he was  walking  with  Gandalf  once  more down  the cold  
line 39691=>corridor to the  door of the Tower Hall. There Denethor sat in a grey gloom,  
line 39692=>like an old patient spider, Pippin  thought: he  did not seem  to have moved 
line 39693=>since the day before. He beckoned Gandalf to a seat, but Pippin was left for  
line 39694=>a while standing unheeded. Presently the old man turned to him: 
line 39695=>     'Well, Master Peregrin,  I hope that you used yesterday to your profit, 
line 39696=>and to your liking? Though  I fear that the board is barer in this city than 
line 39697=>you could wish.' 
line 39698=>     Pippin had  an uncomfortable feeling that most  of what he had said  or  
line 39699=>done was somehow known to the Lord of the City, and much was guessed of 
line 39700=>what 
line 39701=>he thought as well. He did not answer. 
line 39702=>     'What would you do in my service?' 
line 39703=>     'I thought, sir, that you would tell me my duties.' 
line 39704=>     'I will, when I learn what you are fit for,' said Denethor. 'But that I 
line 39705=>shall learn soonest,  maybe,  if  I  keep you beside  me. The esquire of  my 
line 39706=>chamber  has begged leave to  go to the out-garrison, so  you shall take his 
line 39707=>
line 39708=>####-place for a while. You shall wait  on me, bear errands,  and talk to me,  if 
line 39709=>war and council leave me any leisure. Can you sing?' 
line 39710=>     'Yes,' said Pippin.  'Well, yes, well enough for my  own people. But we 
line 39711=>have no songs  fit for  great halls and evil times, lord. We seldom  sing of 
line 39712=>anything more terrible  than wind  or rain. And most  of  my songs are about 
line 39713=>things that make us laugh; or about food and drink, of course.' 
line 39714=>     'And why should such songs be unfit for my halls, or for such  hours as 
line 39715=>these? We who have lived long under the  Shadow may surely listen to  echoes 
line 39716=>from  a land  untroubled  by  it? Then we may  feel that our  vigil was  not 
line 39717=>fruitless, though it may have been thank less.' 
line 39718=>     Pippin's heart sank. He did not  relish the idea of singing any song of 
line 39719=>the Shire to the Lord of Minas Tirith, certainly not the comic  ones that he 
line 39720=>knew best; they were too, well, rustic for such an  occasion. He was however 
line 39721=>spared the ordeal  for  the present. He  was not commanded  to sing. Denethor 
line 39722=>turned to Gandalf, asking questions about  the Rohirrim and  their policies,  
line 39723=>and the position of Jomer, the king's nephew. Pippin marvelled at the amount 
line 39724=>that the Lord seemed to  know about a people that  lived far away, though it  
line 39725=>must, he thought, be many years since Denethor himself had ridden abroad. 
line 39726=>     Presently Denethor waved to Pippin and dismissed him again for a while. 
line 39727=>'Go to the armouries of the Citadel,' he said, 'and get you there the livery 
line 39728=>and gear of the  Tower. It will be ready. It was commanded yesterday. Return 
line 39729=>when you are clad!' 
line 39730=>     It was  as he said; and Pippin soon  found himself  arrayed in  strange 
line 39731=>garments, all of black and silver. He  had a small hauberk, its rings forged 
line 39732=>of steel,  maybe,  yet black  as  jet; and a high-crowned  helm  with  small 
line 39733=>raven-wings on  either  side, set with  a  silver star in the centre of  the 
line 39734=>circlet.  Above the mail was a short surcoat  of black, but broidered on the 
line 39735=>breast in silver with the token of the Tree. His old clothes were folded and 
line 39736=>put away, but he was permitted to  keep the grey cloak of Lurien, though not  
line 39737=>to wear it  when  on duty.  He looked now, had he  known it, verily Ernil  i 
line 39738=>Pheriannath , the Prince of  the Halflings, that folk had  called him; but he 
line 39739=>felt uncomfortable. And the gloom began to weigh on his spirits.  
line 39740=>     It  was  dark and dim all day. From the sunless dawn until evening  the 
line 39741=>heavy shadow  had deepened,  and all hearts in the City were oppressed.  Far 
line 39742=>above  a great cloud streamed slowly westward from the Black Land, 
line 39743=>devouring 
line 39744=>light, borne upon a wind of war; but below the air was still and breathless,  
line 39745=>
line 39746=>####-as if all the Vale of Anduin waited for the onset of a ruinous storm. 
line 39747=>     About  the eleventh hour, released  at  last for  a while from service. 
line 39748=>Pippin came  out and  went  in search  of food and  drink to cheer his heavy 
line 39749=>heart  and make his task of waiting more  supportable. In  the messes he met 
line 39750=>Beregond again, who  had just  come from an errand over the Pelennor  out to 
line 39751=>the Guard-towers upon the Causeway. Together they strolled out to the walls;  
line 39752=>for  Pippin felt imprisoned indoors, and stifled even in the  lofty citadel. 
line 39753=>Now  they sat  side by side again  in the embrasure  looking eastward, where 
line 39754=>they had eaten and talked the day before. 
line 39755=>     It was the sunset-hour, but  the great pall had  now stretched far into 
line 39756=>the  West, and  only  as it sank at last into the Sea did the Sun escape  to 
line 39757=>send  out a brief farewell  gleam before  the night, even as Frodo saw it a t 
line 39758=>the Cross-roads touching the head of the fallen king. But  to  the fields of 
line 39759=>the Pelennor, under the shadow of Mindolluin, there came no gleam: they were 
line 39760=>brown and drear. 
line 39761=>     Already it  seemed years to  Pippin  since he had sat  there before, in 
line 39762=>some half-forgotten time when he had still  been a hobbit,  a  light-hearted 
line 39763=>wanderer touched little by the perils he had passed through. Now  he was one 
line 39764=>small soldier in a city preparing for a great assault, clad in the proud but 
line 39765=>sombre manner of the Tower of Guard. 
line 39766=>     In some  other time and place Pippin  might have been pleased with  his 
line 39767=>new array,  but he knew  now  that he was taking part in no  play; he was in 
line 39768=>deadly  earnest the servant of  a grim  master  in the  greatest  peril. The 
line 39769=>hauberk was burdensome, and the helm weighed upon his head. His cloak he 
line 39770=>had 
line 39771=>cast aside  upon the seat. He turned his tired  gaze away from  the darkling 
line 39772=>fields below and yawned, and then he sighed. 
line 39773=>     'You are weary of this day?' said Beregond. 
line 39774=>     'Yes,'  said Pippin,  'very: tired out with idleness and waiting. I have 
line 39775=>kicked my  heels  at the door of my master's  chamber  for many  slow hours, 
line 39776=>while  he  has  debated with Gandalf and the Prince and other great persons.  
line 39777=>And I'm not  used,  Master Beregond, to waiting hungry on others while  they 
line 39778=>eat. It is a sore trial for a hobbit, that. No doubt you will think I should 
line 39779=>feel the honour more  deeply. But  what is the good  of such honour?  Indeed 
line 39780=>what is the  good even of  food  and  drink under this creeping shadow? What 
line 39781=>does it  mean?  The very air seems thick and brown! Do  you often  have such 
line 39782=>glooms when the wind is in the East?' 
line 39783=>
line 39784=>####-     'Nay,'  said  Beregond, 'this is no weather of the world. This  is some 
line 39785=>device  of his  malice; some broil of fume from the Mountain of Fire that he 
line 39786=>sends  to darken hearts and counsel. And so it doth indeed. I wish the  Lord 
line 39787=>Faramir would  return. He  would not be dismayed. But now,  who  knows if he 
line 39788=>will ever come back across the River out of the Darkness?' 
line 39789=>     'Yes,' said Pippin, 'Gandalf, too, is anxious.  He was disappointed.  I 
line 39790=>think, not  to  find Faramir here. And where has he  got to himself? He left 
line 39791=>the  Lord's council before the noon -meal,  and  in  no good  mood either,  I 
line 39792=>thought. Perhaps he has some foreboding of bad news.' 
line 39793=>     Suddenly as they talked  they were  stricken dumb, frozen as it were to 
line 39794=>listening  stones. Pippin cowered down  with his hands pressed to his  ears;  
line 39795=>but Beregond, who  had been  looking out from the battlement  as he spoke of 
line 39796=>Faramir, remained  there, stiffened, staring  out with starting eyes. Pippin 
line 39797=>knew the shuddering cry that he had heard: it was the same that he had heard 
line 39798=>long  ago  in  the Marish  of the Shire, but now it was grown  in  power and 
line 39799=>hatred, piercing the heart with a poisonous despair . 
line 39800=>     At last Beregond spoke with an effort. 'They have come!' he said. 'Take 
line 39801=>courage and look! There are fell things below.' 
line 39802=>     Reluctantly Pippin climbed on to the seat and looked out over the wall. 
line 39803=>The Pelennor lay dim  beneath him, fading away to the scarce guessed line of 
line 39804=>the  Great  River. But  now  wheeling  swiftly across  it,  like  shadows of 
line 39805=>untimely  night, he  saw in  the middle airs  below him five birdlike forms, 
line 39806=>horrible as carrion-fowl  yet greater than  eagles, cruel as death. Now they 
line 39807=>swooped near, venturing almost within bowshot of the walls, now they circled 
line 39808=>away. 
line 39809=>     'Black Riders!'  muttered Pippin.  'Black  Riders  of the air! But see, 
line 39810=>Beregond!' he cried. 'They are  looking for something, surely? See  how they 
line 39811=>wheel and swoop,  always down to that  point over  there!  And  can  you see 
line 39812=>something moving on the ground? Dark little things. Yes, men on horses: four 
line 39813=>or five. Ah! I cannot stand it! Gandalf! Gandalf save us!' 
line 39814=>     Another  long screech rose and fell,  and  he threw  himself back again 
line 39815=>from the  wall, panting like  a  hunted  animal.  Faint and seemingly remote 
line 39816=>through that shuddering cry he  heard  winding  up from below the sound of a 
line 39817=>trumpet ending on a long high note. 
line 39818=>     'Faramir!  The  Lord Faramir! It is  his call!' cried  Beregond. 'Brave 
line 39819=>heart! But how can he win to the  Gate, if these  foul hell-hawks have other  
line 39820=>weapons than fear? But look! They hold on. They will make the Gate.  No! the 
line 39821=>
line 39822=>####-horses are running mad. Look! the men are thrown; they are running  on foot. 
line 39823=>No,  one is  still  up, but he  rides  back to the others. That will be  the 
line 39824=>Captain: he can master both beasts and men. Ah! there one of the foul things 
line 39825=>is stooping on him. Help! help! Will no one go out to him? Faramir!' 
line 39826=>     With  that Beregond sprang  away  and ran off into the gloom. Ashamed of 
line 39827=>his terror, while Beregond of the Guard thought first of the captain whom he 
line 39828=>loved,  Pippin got up and peered out.  At that  moment he caught  a flash of 
line 39829=>white and silver coming from the  North, like a small star down on the dusky 
line 39830=>fields. It moved with the speed of an arrow and grew as it came,  converging  
line 39831=>swiftly with  the flight of  the four men  towards the  Gate.  It seemed  to 
line 39832=>Pippin that a  pale light was spread about it and the heavy shadows gave way 
line 39833=>before it; and then as  it drew near he thought that he heard, like  an echo 
line 39834=>in the walls, a great voice calling. 
line 39835=>     'Gandalf!' he  cried. 'Gandalf!  He always  turns  up  when things  are 
line 39836=>darkest.  Go on!  Go on,  White Rider! Gandalf, Gandalf!' he shouted wildly, 
line 39837=>like  an  onlooker  at  a  great race urging on a runner who is  far  beyond 
line 39838=>encouragement. 
line 39839=>     But now  the dark  swooping shadows  were  aware  of  the newcomer. One 
line 39840=>wheeled towards  him; but it seemed to Pippin that he raised  his hand,  and 
line 39841=>from  it a  shaft of  white light  stabbed upwards.  The Nazgyl  gave a long 
line 39842=>wailing  cry  and swerved away; and with  that the  four others wavered, and 
line 39843=>then rising in swift spirals they  passed away  eastward  vanishing into the 
line 39844=>lowering cloud  above; and down  on the Pelennor it seemed for a  while less 
line 39845=>dark. 
line 39846=>     Pippin watched,  and he  saw the  horseman and the White Rider meet and 
line 39847=>halt, waiting for those on foot. Men now hurried out to them from the  City;  
line 39848=>and soon they all passed from sight under the  outer walls, and he knew that 
line 39849=>they were  entering the Gate. Guessing  that they would  come at once to the 
line 39850=>Tower and the Steward, he  hurried to the entrance of the citadel.  There he 
line 39851=>was  joined by  many others who had watched the race and the rescue from the 
line 39852=>high walls.  
line 39853=>     It was not long before a clamour  was heard  in the streets leading  up 
line 39854=>from the outer circles, and there was much cheering and crying of  the names 
line 39855=>of Faramir  and Mithrandir. Presently Pippin saw torches, and followed by  a 
line 39856=>press of people two horsemen riding slowly:  one was in white but shining no 
line 39857=>longer, pale in the twilight as if his  fire was spent  or veiled; the other  
line 39858=>was dark  and his  head  was  bowed.  They  dismounted, and  as  grooms took  
line 39859=>
line 39860=>####-Shadowfax and the  other  horse,  they walked forward to the sentinel at the 
line 39861=>gate: Gandalf  steadily,  his  grey  cloak  flung  back,  and  a fire  still 
line 39862=>smouldering in his eyes; the  other,  clad all in green, slowly,  swaying  a  
line 39863=>little as a weary or a wounded man. 
line 39864=>     Pippin pressed  forward  as  they passed  under the  lamp  beneath  the 
line 39865=>gate-arch, and when he saw the pale face of Faramir he caught his breath. It  
line 39866=>was the face  of one who has been assailed by a great fear  or anguish,  but 
line 39867=>has  mastered it and now is quiet. Proud and grave he stood for  a moment as 
line 39868=>he spoke to the guard, and Pippin gazing at him saw how closely he resembled 
line 39869=>his brother  Boromir - whom Pippin had liked from  the  first,  admiring the 
line 39870=>great man's lordly but kindly manner. Yet suddenly for Faramir his heart was 
line 39871=>strangely moved with a feeling that  he had  not known before. Here was  one 
line 39872=>with  an  air of high nobility such as  Aragorn at times revealed, less high 
