line 40201=>
line 40202=>####-     Denethor laughed bitterly. 'Nay, not  yet, Master Peregrin! He will not 
line 40203=>come save  only to triumph over me when all is  won. He uses  others as  his 
line 40204=>weapons. So do  all great lords, if they  are wise,  Master Halfling. Or why 
line 40205=>should I sit here in  my tower and think, and watch, and wait, spending even 
line 40206=>my sons? For I can still wield a brand.' 
line 40207=>     He stood up and cast open his long black cloak, and behold! he was clad 
line 40208=>in mail beneath,  and girt  with a  long sword, great-hilted in a sheath  of 
line 40209=>black and silver. 'Thus have I walked, and thus  now  for many years  have I  
line 40210=>slept,' he said, 'lest with age the body should grow soft and timid.' 
line 40211=>     'Yet now under the Lord of Barad-dyr the most  fell of all his captains 
line 40212=>is already master of your outer  walls,'  said Gandalf. 'King of Angmar long 
line 40213=>ago, Sorcerer, Ringwraith, Lord of the Nazgyl, a spear of terror in the hand 
line 40214=>of Sauron, shadow of despair.' 
line 40215=>     'Then, Mithrandir, you  had a  foe to  match you,'  said Denethor. 'For  
line 40216=>myself, I  have long known who is the chief captain of the hosts of the Dark 
line 40217=>Tower. Is this all that you have returned to say? Or can it be that you have 
line 40218=>withdrawn because you are overmatched?' 
line 40219=>     Pippin  trembled, fearing  that Gandalf would be stung to sudden wrath, 
line 40220=>but his fear was needless.  'It  might be so,' Gandalf answered softly. 'But 
line 40221=>our trial of strength is not yet come. And if words  spoken  of old be true, 
line 40222=>not by the hand of man  shall he fall, and hidden from the Wise  is the doom 
line 40223=>that awaits him.  However that may be, the Captain of Despair does not press 
line 40224=>forward,  yet.  He rules rather according to  the  wisdom that you have just 
line 40225=>spoken, from the rear, driving his slaves in madness on before. 
line 40226=>     'Nay, I came  rather to guard the hurt men that can yet be  healed; for 
line 40227=>the Rammas is  breached far and wide, and soon the host of Morgul will enter  
line 40228=>in at many points. And I came chiefly to say this. Soon there will be battle 
line 40229=>on  the  fields. A sortie must be made  ready.  Let it be of mounted men. In 
line 40230=>them lies our  brief hope, for in one thing only is  the enemy  still poorly 
line 40231=>provided: he has few horsemen.' 
line 40232=>     'And we also have few. Now  would the coming of Rohan be in the nick of 
line 40233=>time,' said Denethor. 
line 40234=>     'We are likely to see other newcomers first,' said  Gandalf. 'Fugitives 
line 40235=>from Cair Andros have  already reached us. The isle has fallen. Another army 
line 40236=>is come from the Black Gate, crossing from the north-east.' 
line 40237=>     'Some have accused  you, Mithrandir,  of  delighting to bear ill news,' 
line 40238=>said Denethor, 'but to  me  this is  no longer news: it  was known to mw ere 
line 40239=>
line 40240=>####-nightfall yesterday. As for the sortie,  I had already given thought to  it. 
line 40241=>Let us go down.' 
line 40242=>     Time  passed. At length watchers on the walls could  see the retreat of 
line 40243=>the  out-companies. Small bands of weary  and  often wounded  men came first  
line 40244=>with  little  order; some  were running wildly  as if  pursued. Away to  the 
line 40245=>ea stward the distant fires flickered; and  now it seemed that here and there 
line 40246=>they crept across the plain. Houses and barns were burning.  Then from  many 
line 40247=>points little  rivers of red flame  came  hurrying on,  winding through  the 
line 40248=>gloom,  converging  towards   the line of  the broad  road that  led from the 
line 40249=>City-gate to Osgiliath. 
line 40250=>     'The enemy,' men  murmured. 'The  dike is  down. Here they come pouring 
line 40251=>through the  breaches! And they carry  torches,  it seems. Where are our own 
line 40252=>folk?' 
line 40253=>     It drew now to evening by the hour, and  the light was so dim that even 
line 40254=>far-sighted men upon the  Citadel could  discern little clearly out upon the 
line 40255=>fields, save only the  burnings that ever multiplied, and the lines  of fire 
line 40256=>that grew in length and speed.  At last, less than a mile  from  the City, a  
line 40257=>more ordered mass of men came into view, marching not running, still holding 
line 40258=>together. 
line 40259=>     The watchers held their breath. 'Faramir must be there,' they said. 'He 
line 40260=>can govern man and beast. He will make it yet.' 
line 40261=>     Now  the  main retreat  was scarcely  two furlongs distant. Out of  the 
line 40262=>gloom behind a small company of horsemen galloped, all that was  left of the 
line 40263=>rearguard. Once again they turned at bay, facing the oncoming lines of fire. 
