line 40524=>last they came to  the Silent Street,  Rath  Dnnen, between  pale  domes and 
line 40525=>empty halls and images of men long dead;  and they entered into the House of 
line 40526=>the Stewards and set down their burden. 
line 40527=>     There  Pippin,  staring uneasily about  him, saw that he was in  a wide 
line 40528=>vaulted chamber,  draped as it  were with the great shadows that  the little 
line 40529=>lantern threw upon its shrouded  walls. And dimly to  be seen were many rows 
line 40530=>of tables, carved of marble;  and upon each table lay a sleeping form, hands 
line 40531=>folded, head pillowed upon stone. But one table near at hand stood broad and 
line 40532=>bare. Upon it at a sign from Denethor they laid Faramir  and his father side 
line 40533=>by side, and covered them with one covering, and stood then with bowed heads 
line 40534=>as mourners beside a bed of death. Then Denethor spoke in a low voice. 
line 40535=>     'Here we will wait,' he said. 'But send not for the embalmers. Bring us 
line 40536=>wood quick to  burn, and lay it all about us, and beneath; and pour oil upon 
line 40537=>it. And when I bid you thrust in  a torch. Do this and speak no more to  me. 
line 40538=>Farewell!' 
line 40539=>     'By your leave, lord!' said Pippin and turned and fled  in terror  from 
line 40540=>the  deathly house. 'Poor Faramir!' he thought.  'I must find Gandalf.  Poor 
line 40541=>Faramir!  Quite likely he needs medicine  more than  tears.  Oh, where can I  
line 40542=>find Gandalf? In the thick of things, I suppose; and he will have no time to 
line 40543=>
line 40544=>####-spare for dying men or madmen.' 
line 40545=>     At the door he turned to one  of the servants who had remained on guard 
line 40546=>there.  'Your master is not himself,' he  said. 'Go slow! Bring  no fire  to 
line 40547=>this place while Faramir lives! Do nothing until Gandalf comes!' 
line 40548=>     'Who is  the  master  of  Minas  Tirith?' the  man  answered. 'The Lord 
line 40549=>Denethor or the Grey Wanderer?' 
line 40550=>     'The Grey Wanderer or no one, it would seem,' said Pippin, and he  sped 
line 40551=>back and up the winding way as swiftly as his feet would carry him, past the 
line 40552=>astonished porter, out through  the door, and on, till he came near the gate 
line 40553=>of the Citadel. The sentinel hailed him as he went by, and he recognized the 
line 40554=>voice of Beregond. 
line 40555=>     'Whither do you run, Master Peregrin?' he cried. 
line 40556=>     'To find Mithrandir,' Pippin answered. 
line 40557=>     'The Lord's errands are urgent and should not be hindered by me,'  said 
line 40558=>Beregond;  'but tell  me quickly, if you may:  what goes forward? Whither has 
line 40559=>my  Lord gone? I have just come on duty, but I  heard that he passed towards 
line 40560=>the Closed Door, and men were bearing Faramir before him.' 
line 40561=>     'Yes,' said Pippin, 'to the Silent Street.' 
line 40562=>     Beregond bowed his  head  to  hide his tears.  'They said that  he  was 
line 40563=>dying,' he sighed, 'and now he is dead.' 
line 40564=>     'No,' said Pippin, 'not yet. And even now his death might be prevented, 
line 40565=>I think. But the Lord of  the City, Beregond,  has fallen before his city is 
line 40566=>taken. He is fey and dangerous.' Quickly he told of Denethor's strange words 
line 40567=>and deeds. 'I must find Gandalf at once.' 
line 40568=>     'Then you must go down to the battle.' 
line 40569=>     'I  know. The Lord has given me  leave. But,  Beregond, if you can,  do 
line 40570=>someth ing to stop any dreadful thing happening.' 
line 40571=>     'The Lord  does not permit those who wear the black and silver to leave 
line 40572=>their post for any cause, save at his own command.' 
line 40573=>     'Well,  you  must  choose between orders and the life of Faramir,' said 
line 40574=>Pippin.   'And as for orders,  I think you  have a madman to deal with, not a  
line 40575=>lord. I must run. I will return if I can.' 
line 40576=>     He ran on,  down, down towards the outer city. Men flying back from the 
line 40577=>burning passed him, and some  seeing his livery turned  and shouted, but  he 
line 40578=>paid no heed. At last he was through  the Second Gate,  beyond  which  great 
line 40579=>fires  leaped up between the walls. Yet it seemed strangely silent. No noise 
line 40580=>or shouts of battle or din of arms could be heard. Then suddenly there was a  
line 40581=>
line 40582=>####-dreadful cry a nd a great shock,  and a deep echoing boom. Forcing himself on 
line 40583=>against a gust of fear and horror that shook him almost to his knees. Pippin 
line 40584=>turned a  corner opening on the wide place behind  the City Gate. He stopped 
line 40585=>dead. He had found Gandalf; but he shrank back, cowering into a shadow.  
line 40586=>     Ever since the middle  night the  great assault had gone  on. The drums 
line 40587=>rolled. To the  north and to the  south company upon company  of  the  enemy 
line 40588=>pressed to the walls. There came great beasts, like moving houses in the red  
line 40589=>and fitful light, the mymakil  of  the Harad dragging through the lanes  amid 
line 40590=>the fires huge towers and engines. Yet their Captain cared not  greatly what 
line 40591=>they  did or how many might be slain:  their purpose was  only to  test  the 
line 40592=>strength of the defence and to  keep the men  of Gondor busy in many places.  
line 40593=>It was against the Gate that he would throw his heaviest weight. Very strong 
line 40594=>it might be, wrought of steel and iron, and guarded with towers and bastions 
line 40595=>of indomitable stone, yet it was the key, the weakest point in all that high 
line 40596=>and impenetrable wall. 
line 40597=>     The drums  rolled louder. Fires leaped up. Great engines crawled across 
line 40598=>the field; and in the midst was a huge ram, great as a forest -tree a hundred 
line 40599=>feet in length,  swinging on mighty chains. Long had  it been forging in the 
line 40600=>dark smithies  of Mordor, and  its hideous head, founded of black steel, was 
line 40601=>shaped in  the likeness of a ravening wolf; on it spells of  ruin lay. Grond 
line 40602=>they named it,  in memory of  the Hammer of the  Underworld  of  old.  Great 
line 40603=>beasts drew it,  Orcs surrounded  it, and  behind  walked mountain-trolls to 
line 40604=>wield it. 
line 40605=>     But about the Gate resistance still was stout, and there the knights of 
line 40606=>Dol Amroth and the hardiest of the garrison stood at bay. Shot and dart fell 
line 40607=>thick; siege-towers crashed or blazed  suddenly like torches. All before the 
line 40608=>walls on either side of the Gate the  ground was choked  with wreck and with 
line 40609=>bodies of the slain; yet still driven as by a madness more and more came up.  
line 40610=>     Grond crawled on. Upon  its housing no fire would catch; and though now 
line 40611=>and again some great beast that  hauled it would go  mad and spread stamping 
line 40612=>ruin among  the  orcs  innumerable  that guarded  it, their bodies were cast  
line 40613=>aside from its path and others took their place. 
line 40614=>     Grond crawled on. The drums  rolled wildly. Over the  hills of slain  a  
line 40615=>hideous shape appeared: a horseman, tall,  hooded, cloaked in black. Slowly, 
line 40616=>trampling the fallen,  he rode forth, heeding no  longer any dart. He halted 
line 40617=>and held up  a long pale sword. And as he did so a great  fear  fell on all, 
line 40618=>defender  and foe alike; and the hands of men drooped to their sides, and no  
line 40619=>
line 40620=>####-bow sang. For a moment all was still. 
line 40621=>     The drums rolled and rattled. With a vast rush Grond was hurled forward 
line 40622=>by  huge hands. It reached the Gate. It  swung. A  deep boom rumbled through 
line 40623=>the City like thunder running in the clouds. But the doors of iron and posts 
line 40624=>of steel withstood the stroke. 
line 40625=>     Then  the  Black Captain rose  in  his  stirrups and  cried  aloud in a  
line 40626=>dreadful voice, speaking in some forgotten tongue words of power and  terror 
line 40627=>to rend both heart and stone. 
line 40628=>     Thrice he cried.  Thrice  the great ram boomed.  And suddenly  upon the 
line 40629=>last  stroke the Gate of Gondor broke. As if stricken by some blasting spell 
line 40630=>it burst asunder:  there  was  a flash of searing  lightning, and the  doors 
line 40631=>tumbled in riven fragments to the ground. 
line 40632=>     In rode the Lord  of the Nazgyl. A great black  shape against the fires 
line 40633=>beyond he loomed up, grown  to a vast menace of despair. In rode the Lord of 
line 40634=>the Nazgyl, under  the  archway that no  enemy ever yet had  passed, and all  
line 40635=>fled before his face. 
line 40636=>     All save one. There waiting,  silent and still in the  space before the 
line 40637=>Gate, sat Gandalf upon Shadowfax: Shadowfax who alone  among the free 
line 40638=>horses 
line 40639=>of  the earth endured the terror, unmoving,  steadfast as  a graven image in 
line 40640=>Rath Dnnen. 
line 40641=>     'You  cannot enter here,' said Gandalf, and the huge shadow halted. 'Go 
line 40642=>back to the abyss prepared  for you! Go back! Fall into the nothingness that 
line 40643=>awaits you and your Master. Go!' 
line 40644=>     The Black Rider flung back his hood, and behold! he had a kingly crown;  
line 40645=>and yet upon no head visible was it set. The red fires  shone between it and 
line 40646=>the mantled shoulders vast and dark. From a mouth unseen there came a deadly 
line 40647=>laughter. 
line 40648=>     'Old fool!' he  said. 'Old fool! This is my hour. Do you not know Death 
line 40649=>when you see it? Die  now and curse in vain!' And  with that he lifted  high 
line 40650=>his sword and flames ran down the blade. 
line 40651=>     Gandalf did  not move.  And in that  very moment,  away  behind in some 
line 40652=>courtyard  of the City, a cock crowed. Shrill and clear  he crowed,  recking 
line 40653=>nothing of wizardry or war, welcoming  only  the morning that in the sky far  
line 40654=>above the shadows of death was coming with the dawn. 
line 40655=>     And  as  if in  answer there  came from far away  another note.  Horns,  
line 40656=>horns, horns. In dark Mindolluin's sides  they dimly  echoed. Great horns of 
line 40657=>
line 40658=>####-the North wildly blowing. Rohan had come at last. 
