line 40663=>Chapter 5. The Ride of the Rohirrim 
line 40664=>
line 40665=> 
line 40666=> 
line 40667=>     It was dark and Merry could see  nothing as he lay on the ground rolled 
line 40668=>in a blanket; yet  though the night was airless and windless, all  about him 
line 40669=>hidden  trees were sighing  softly. He lifted  his  head.  Then he heard  it 
line 40670=>again: a  sound like faint drums in the wooded hills and mountain-steps. The 
line 40671=>throb would cease suddenly and then be taken up again  at some other  point, 
line 40672=>now nearer, now further off. He wondered if the watchmen had heard it. 
line 40673=>     He  could not see  them,  but he  knew  that  all  round  him were  the 
line 40674=>companies of the Rohirrim. He could smell the horses in  the dark, and could 
line 40675=>hear their shiftings  and their soft stamping on  the needle-covered ground. 
line 40676=>The host  was bivouacked in  the  pine-woods that  clustered about  Eilenach  
line 40677=>Beacon, a tall  hill standing up from  the long ridges of the DrÂ®adan Forest  
line 40678=>that lay beside the great road in East Anurien. 
line 40679=>     Tired as he was Merry could not sleep. He had ridden now  for four days 
line 40680=>on end,  and the ever -deepening gloom had slowly  weighed down his heart. He 
line 40681=>began to wonder   why he had been so  eager to come,  when he had  been given 
line 40682=>every excuse, even his lord's command, to  stay behind. He wondered, too, if 
line 40683=>the  old  King knew  that he had been disobeyed and  was angry. Perhaps not. 
line 40684=>There seemed  to be  some understanding   between Dernhelm  and Elfhelm,  
line 40685=>the 
line 40686=>Marshal  who commanded  the  jored in which they were riding. He and all  his 
line 40687=>men ignored Merry and  pretended not to hear if he spoke. He might have been 
line 40688=>just  another bag that  Dernhelm was  carrying. Dernhelm was  no comfort: he 
line 40689=>never spoke to anyone. Merry felt small, unwanted, and  lonely. Now the time 
line 40690=>was anxious, and  the host was in peril.  They were less than a  day's  ride 
line 40691=>from the out-walls of Minas Tirith  that encircled the townlands. Scouts had 
line 40692=>been sent ahead. Some  had not returned.  Others hastening back had reported 
line 40693=>that the  road was  held in  force against  them.  A  host  of the enemy was 
line 40694=>encamped upon it, three miles west of Amon Don, and some strength of men 
line 40695=>was 
line 40696=>already  thrusting along the road  and  was no more than three  leagues away.  
line 40697=>Orcs were roving in  the hills  and  woods along the  roadside. The king and  
line 40698=>Jomer held council in the watches of the night. 
line 40699=>     Merry  wanted somebody to  talk to, and he thought of Pippin.  But that 
line 40700=>
line 40701=>####-only increased his  restlessness. Poor Pippin, shut up in the great city  of 
line 40702=>stone,  lonely and  afraid. Merry wished he was a tall Rider  like Jomer and 
line 40703=>could  blow  a horn or something and go galloping to his rescue.  He sat up, 
line 40704=>listening  to the  drums  that  were  beating again,  now  nearer  at  hand. 
line 40705=>Presently  he  heard  voices  speaking  low, and  he  saw  dim half-shrouded  
line 40706=>lanterns passing  through the trees. Men nearby began to move uncertainly in 
line 40707=>the dark. 
line 40708=>     A tall figure loomed up and stumbled over  him, cu rsing the tree-roots.  
line 40709=>He recognized the voice of the Marshal, Elfhelm. 
line 40710=>     'I am not a tree-root, Sir,' he said, 'nor a bag, but a bruised hobbit. 
line 40711=>The least you can do in amends is to tell me what is afoot.' 
line 40712=>     'Anything that  can keep so  in this  devi l's mirk,' answered  Elfhelm. 
line 40713=>'But my lord sends word that we must  set ourselves in readiness: orders may 
line 40714=>come for a sudden move.' 
line 40715=>     'Is  the enemy coming then?' asked Merry  anxiously.  'Are those  their 
line 40716=>drums? I began to think I was  imagining them, as no one else seemed to take 
line 40717=>any notice of them.' 
line 40718=>     'Nay, nay,' said  Elfhelm, 'the enemy  is on the road not in the hills.  
line 40719=>You hear the Woses, the Wild Men of the Woods: thus they talk together  from 
line 40720=>afar. They still haunt DrÂ®adan Forest, it is said. Remnants of an older time 
line 40721=>they be, living few and  secretly, wild and wary as the beasts. They go  not 
line 40722=>to war with Gondor or  the Mark; but  now they  are troubled by the darkness 
line 40723=>and the  coming of the orcs:  they fear lest the Dark Years be returning, as 
line 40724=>seems  likely enough.  Let us be thankful that they are  not hunting us: for  
line 40725=>they use poisoned  arrows,  it is  said,  and  they  are  woodcrafty  beyond 
line 40726=>compare. But  they have offered their services to  Thjoden. Even now one  of 
line 40727=>their headmen is being taken to  the king. Yonder  go the lights.  So much I 
line 40728=>have heard but no more. And now I must busy myself with my  lord's 
line 40729=>commands. 
line 40730=>Pack yourself up, Master Bag!' He vanished into the shadows.  
line 40731=>     Merry did not like this talk of wild men  and poisoned darts, but quite 
line 40732=>apart from that a great weight of dread  was on him. Waiting was unbearable. 
line 40733=>He  longed to know  what was going to happen. He got up and soon was 
line 40734=>walking 
line 40735=>warily in pursuit of the last lantern before it disappeared among the trees.  
line 40736=>     Presently he came to an open  space  where a small tent had been set up 
line 40737=>for the king under a great tree. A large lantern, covered above, was hanging 
line 40738=>
line 40739=>####-from a bough and cast  a  pale circle of  light below. There sat Thjoden and 
line 40740=>Jomer, and before  them  on the ground sat a strange  squat shape of a  man,  
line 40741=>gnarled as an old  stone, and the hairs of his scanty beard straggled on his 
line 40742=>lumpy chin like  dry  moss.  He was  short-legged and fat-armed,  thick  and 
line 40743=>stumpy, and  clad only  with grass about his waist. Merry  felt  that he  had 
line 40744=>seen  him  before  somewhere, and suddenly  he remembered  the  PÂ®kel-men 
line 40745=>of 
line 40746=>Dunharrow. Here  was one of those old  images  brought to life, or  maybe  a 
line 40747=>creature descended  in true line through endless years from the models  used 
line 40748=>by the forgotten craftsmen long ago. 
line 40749=>     There was  a silence as Merry crept nearer, and then the Wild Man began 
line 40750=>to speak, in answer to some  question, it  seemed.  His  voice  was deep and 
line 40751=>guttural,  yet to Merry's  surprise he spoke  the Common Speech, though in a 
line 40752=>halting fashion, and uncouth words were mingled with it. 
line 40753=>     'No, father of  Horse-men,' he  said,  'we fight not. Hunt  only.  Kill 
line 40754=>gorgyn  in woods, hate orc-folk. You hate gorgyn too. We help as we can. Wild 
line 40755=>Men have long ears and long eyes; know all  paths. Wild Men live here before 
line 40756=>Stone-houses; before Tall Men come up out of Water.' 
line 40757=>     'But our need is for aid in battle,' said Jomer. 'How will you and your 
line 40758=>folk help us?' 
line 40759=>     'Bring news,' said  the Wild Man. 'We look out from hills. We climb big 
line 40760=>mountain  and look down.  Stone-city is shut. Fire burns there  outside; now 
line 40761=>inside too. You  wish to come there? Then you must be  quick. But gorgyn and 
line 40762=>men out  of  far-away,'  he waved a  short gnarled  arm  eastward,  'sit  on 
line 40763=>horse-road. Very many, mor e than Horse-men.' 
line 40764=>     'How do you know that?' said Jomer. 
line 40765=>     The old man's flat face and dark eyes showed nothing, but his voice was 
line 40766=>sullen  with displeasure.  'Wild  men are wild, free, but not  children,' he 
line 40767=>answered. 'I am great headman, Ghvn-buri-Ghvn. I count many things: stars in 
line 40768=>sky, leaves  on trees, men in  the dark. You have a score of scores  counted 
line 40769=>ten  times and five. They  have more.  Big fight, and who will win? And many 
line 40770=>more walk round walls of Stone-houses.' 
line 40771=>     'Alas! he speaks all too shrewdly,' said  Thjoden. 'And our scouts  say 
line 40772=>that they have  cast trenches  and  stakes across the road.  We cannot sweep 
line 40773=>them away in sudden onset.' 
line 40774=>     'And yet we need great haste,' said Jomer. 'Mundburg is on fire!' 
line 40775=>     'Let Ghvn-buri-Ghvn finish!' said the Wild Man. 'More than one road  he  
line 40776=>
line 40777=>####-knows. He will lead you by road where no pits are, no gorgyn walk, only Wild 
line 40778=>Men  and  beasts. Many paths were  made  when Stonehouse-folk were 
line 40779=>stronger. 
line 40780=>They carved  hills as  hunters carve beast -flesh.  Wild  Men  think they ate 
line 40781=>stone for food. They  went through DrÂ®adan  to Rimmon with great wains. 
line 40782=>They 
line 40783=>go  no longer. Road is forgotten, but not by Wild  Men. Over hill and behind 
line 40784=>hill it  lies still  under grass and tree, there behind Rimmon  and down  to 
line 40785=>Don, and back at the  end to  Horse -men's road. Wild Men will show  you that 
line 40786=>road. Then you will kill gorgyn  and drive away bad dark  with  bright iron, 
line 40787=>and Wild Men can go back to sleep in the wild woods.' 
line 40788=>     Jomer  and  the king  spoke  together  in their  own  tongue. At length 
line 40789=>Thjoden turned to the Wild Man.   'We will receive your offer,' he said.  'For  
line 40790=>though we leave a host of foes behind, what matter? If the Stone-city falls, 
line 40791=>then we shall  have  no returning. If it  is saved, then the orc-host itself 
line 40792=>will be cut off. If you are faithful, Ghvn-buri-Ghvn, then we will  give you  
line 40793=>rich reward, and you shall have the friendship of the Mark for ever.' 
line 40794=>     'Dead  men are not friends to living men, and give them no gifts,' said 
line 40795=>the Wild Man.  'But if you live after the Darkness, then leave Wild Men alone 
line 40796=>in the woods and do  not hunt them like beasts any more. Ghvn-buri-Ghvn will 
line 40797=>not lead  you into trap. He will go himself with father of Horse-men, and if 
line 40798=>he leads you wrong, you will kill him.' 
line 40799=>     'So be it!' said Thjoden. 
line 40800=>     'How long will it take to pass by the enemy and come back to the road?' 
line 40801=>asked Jomer. 'We must go at foot-pace, if you guide us; and  I doubt not the 
line 40802=>way is narrow.' 
line 40803=>     'Wild Men go quick on feet,' said Ghvn. 'Way is wide for four horses in 
line 40804=>Stonewain  Valley  yonder,'  he waved his hand southwards;  'but  narrow  at 
line 40805=>beginning and at end.  Wild  Man could walk from here to Don between sunrise 
line 40806=>and noon.' 
line 40807=>     'Then we must allow at least seven hours for the leaders,' said  Jomer; 
line 40808=>'but  we must reckon rather on some ten hours for all. Things unforeseen may 
line 40809=>hinder us, and if our host is all strung out, it will be long  ere it can be 
line 40810=>set in order when we issue from the hills. What is the hour now?' 
line 40811=>     'Who knows?' said Thjoden. 'All is night now.' 
line 40812=>     'It is all dark, but  it is not all night.' said Ghvn.  'When Sun comes 
line 40813=>we   feel   her,  even  when  she   is  hidden.   Already  she  climbs  over  
line 40814=>
line 40815=>####-East -mountains. It is the opening of day in the sky-fields.' 
line 40816=>     'Then  we must  set  out  as soon as may be,' said Jomer.  'Even so  we 
line 40817=>cannot hope to come to Gondor's aid today.' 
line 40818=>     Merry waited to  hear  no  more, but slipped away to get ready for  the 
line 40819=>summons to the march. This was  the last stage before the battle. It did not 
line 40820=>seem  likely to him  that  many of them would survive it. But he thought  of 
line 40821=>Pippin and the flames in Minas Tirith and thrust down his own dread. 
line 40822=>     All  went well that day, and no sight  or sound had  they  of the enemy 
line 40823=>waiting to waylay them. The Wild Men had put  out a screen  of wary hunters,  
line 40824=>so that no orc or roving spy should learn of the movements in the hills. The 
line 40825=>light was more dim  than ever as they drew nearer to  the  beleaguered city, 
line 40826=>and the Riders  passed  in long files like dark shadows  of men and  hor ses. 
line 40827=>Each  company  was guided by  a wild woodman; but old Ghvn walked beside 
line 40828=>the 
line 40829=>king. The  start had been slower than was  hoped, for it had  taken time for  
line 40830=>the Riders, walking and leading their horses, to find paths over the thickly 
line 40831=>wooded ridges behind   their camp  and down into the hidden Stonewain Valley. 
line 40832=>It was  late in the afternoon  when the leaders came  to wide  grey thickets 
line 40833=>stretching beyond the eastward side of  Amon Don, and masking a great gap in 
line 40834=>the line of hills that from Nardol to Don ran east and west. Through the gap 
line 40835=>the forgotten wain-road long ago had run down,  back into the main horse -way 
line 40836=>from the City  through Anurien; but now for many lives of men  trees had had 
line 40837=>their way with  it, and it had vanished, broken and buried under  the leaves 
line 40838=>of uncounted years. But  the  thickets offered to the Riders their last hope 
line 40839=>of cover before they went into open battle; for beyond them lay the road and 
line 40840=>the plains  of Anduin,  while east and southwards  the slopes  were bare and  
line 40841=>rocky,  as the writhen hills  gathered  themselves  together and climbed up, 
line 40842=>bastion upon bastion, into the great mass and shoulders of Mindolluin. 
line 40843=>     The leading company was halted, and as those behind filed up out of the 
line 40844=>trough of the Stonewain Valley they spread out  a nd passed to camping-places 
line 40845=>under the grey trees. The king  summoned the captains to council. Jomer sent 
line 40846=>out scouts to spy upon the road; but old Ghvn shook his head. 
line 40847=>     'No good to send Horse-men,' he said. 'Wild Men  have already  seen all 
line 40848=>that can be seen in the bad air. They will come soon and speak to me here.' 
line 40849=>     The  captains came;  and  then  out of  the  trees crept  warily  other  
line 40850=>pÂ®kel-shapes so like old Ghvn that Merry  could hardly tell them apart. They 
line 40851=>spoke to Ghvn in a strange throaty language. 
line 40852=>
line 40853=>####-     Presently Ghvn turned to the king. 'Wild Men say many things ' he said. 
line 40854=>'First, be wary! Still many  men in camp beyond Don, an hour's walk yonder,' 
line 40855=>he waved  his arm west  towards the black beacon. 'But  none  to see between 
line 40856=>here and Stone-folk's new walls. Many busy  there. Walls stand up no longer: 
line 40857=>gorgyn  knock them down with earth -thunder and with clubs of black iron. They 
line 40858=>are unwary and do not  look about  them. They think  their friends watch all  
line 40859=>roads!' At that old  Ghvn made a curious gurgling noise, and it seemed  that 
line 40860=>he was laughing. 
line 40861=>     'Good tidings!' cried Jomer. 'Even in this gloom hope gleams again. Our 
line 40862=>Enemy's devices  oft serve us in his  despite.  The accursed darkness itself 
line 40863=>has been a cloak to us. And now, lusting to destroy Gondor and throw it down 
line 40864=>stone from stone, his  orcs have  taken away  my greatest fear. The out-wall 
line 40865=>could have been held long against us. Now we  can sweep through - if once we 
line 40866=>win so far.' 
line 40867=>     'Once again I thank you, Ghvn-buri-Ghvn of  the woods,'  said  Thjoden.  
line 40868=>'Good fortune go with you for tidings and for guidance!' 
line 40869=>     'Kill  gorgyn! Kill orc-folk! No other words please Wild Men ' answered  
line 40870=>Ghvn. 'Drive away bad air and darkness with bright iron!' 
line 40871=>     'To do these things we have ridden far,'  said the king,  'and we shall 
line 40872=>attempt them. But what we shall achieve only tomorrow will show.' 
line 40873=>     Ghvn-buri-Ghvn  squatted down and touched the earth with his horny brow 
line 40874=>in token of farewell. Then he got up as if to depart.  But suddenly he stood 
line 40875=>looking u p like some startled  woodland  animal snuffling  a  strange air. A 
line 40876=>light came in his eyes.  
line 40877=>     'Wind  is  changing!' he cried, and  with  that, in a  twinkling as  it 
line 40878=>seemed, he and his fellows had vanished into the glooms, never to be seen by 
line 40879=>any Rider of Rohan again. Not long after far away  eastward  the faint drums 
line 40880=>throbbed again. Yet  to no heart in all the host came any fear that the Wild 
line 40881=>Men were unfaithful, strange and unlovely though they might appear. 
line 40882=>     'We need  no further  guidance,' said E lfhelm; 'for there are riders in 
line 40883=>the host who have ridden down to Mundburg in days of peace. I for  one. When 
line 40884=>we come to  the road it will veer south, and there will lie before  us still 
line 40885=>seven leagues ere we reach the wall of the townlands. Along most of that way 
line 40886=>there  is  much  grass  on  either side  of  the road. On that  stretch  the 
line 40887=>errand-riders of  Gondor reckoned to  make their greatest speed. We may ride 
line 40888=>it swiftly and without great rumour.' 
line 40889=>     'Then  since we  must  look  for  fell deeds and  the  need  of all our 
line 40890=>
line 40891=>####-strength,' said Jomer,  'I  counsel that we  rest now, and set out hence  by 
line 40892=>night, and so  time our going that we come upon the fields  when tomorrow is 
line 40893=>as light as it will be, or when our lord gives the signal.' 
line 40894=>     To this the king  assented, and the captains departed. But soon Elfhelm 
line 40895=>returned.  'The scouts  have found naught  to  report beyond  the grey wood, 
line 40896=>lord,' he said, 'save two men only: two dead men and two dead horses.' 
line 40897=>     'Well?' said Jomer. 'What of it?' 
line 40898=>     'This, lord: they were errand-riders  of  Gondor; Hirgon was one maybe. 
line 40899=>At least his hand  still clasped  the Red Arrow, but his head was  hewn off. 
line 40900=>And this  also:  it would  seem by the signs that they were fleeing westward 
line 40901=>when they fell. As I read it, they found the enemy already on the  out-wall, 
line 40902=>or assailing it, when they  returned - and that would  be two nights ago, if 
line 40903=>they  used  fresh  horses  from the posts, as is their wont. They  could not 
line 40904=>reach the City and turned back.' 
line 40905=>     'Alas!' said  Thjoden. 'T hen  Denethor has heard  no news of our riding 
line 40906=>and will despair of our coming.' 
line 40907=>     'Need brooks no delay, yet late is better than never,' said Jomer. 'And 
line 40908=>mayhap in this time shall the old saw be proved truer than ever before since  
line 40909=>men spoke with mouth.' 
line 40910=>     It was night. On either side of the  road the  host of Rohan was moving 
line 40911=>silently.  Now  the  road  passing  about the skirts  of  Mindolluin  turned 
line 40912=>southward. Far away and almost straight ahead there was a red glow under the 
line 40913=>black sky and  the sides of the great mountain  loomed dark against it. They  
line 40914=>were drawing near the Rammas of the Pelennor; but the day was not yet come. 
line 40915=>     The  king rode in the  midst  of the leading company, his household-men 
line 40916=>about him. Elfhelm's  jored came  next; and now Merry noticed  that  Dernhelm 
line 40917=>had left his place and in the darkness was moving steadily forward, until at 
line 40918=>last he was riding  just  in rear of the  king's guard. There came  a check. 
line 40919=>Merry  heard voices  in front speaking softly.  Out-riders had come back who 
line 40920=>had ventured forward almost to the wall. They came to the king. 
line 40921=>     'There are great  fires, lord,'  said one. 'The City is  all set  about 
line 40922=>with flame, and the field  is full of foes.  But all seem drawn off  to  the 
line 40923=>assault. As well as we could guess, there  are  few left  upon the out-wall, 
line 40924=>and they are heedless, busy in destruction.' 
line 40925=>     'Do you remember the  Wild Man's words,  lord?' said another.  'I  live 
line 40926=>upon the open Wold in days of peace;  Wndfara is my name, and to me also the 
line 40927=>air brings messages. Already the  wind  is turning. There comes a breath out 
line 40928=>
line 40929=>####-of the South;  there  is a sea -tang in it, faint  though it be.  The morning 
line 40930=>will bring new things.  Above  the reek  it will  be dawn  when you pass the 
line 40931=>wall.' 
line 40932=>     'If  you speak truly, Wndfara, then  may  you live beyond  this day  in 
line 40933=>years of blessedness!' said Thjoden.  He turned to the  men of his household 
line 40934=>who were  near, and he spoke now  in a clear voice  so that many also of the 
line 40935=>riders of the first jored heard him: 
line 40936=>     'Now is the hour come, Riders of the Mark, sons  of Eorl! Foes and fire 
line 40937=>are before you,  and your homes far  behind.  Yet, though you fight upon  an 
line 40938=>alien field, the glory that you reap there shall be your own for ever. Oaths 
line 40939=>ye  have  taken:  now fulfil them  all,  to  lord  and  land  and league  of 
line 40940=>friendship!' 
line 40941=>     Men clashed spear upon shield. 
line 40942=>     'Jomer, my son! You  lead the first jored,' said Thjoden; 'and it shall 
line 40943=>go behind the king's banner in the centre. Elfhelm, lead your company to the 
line 40944=>right when we pass the wall.  And  Grimbold shall lead his towards the left. 
line 40945=>Let  the other companies behind follow these three that lead,  as  they have 
line 40946=>chance.  Strike wherever the  enemy gathers. Other plans we cannot make, for  
line 40947=>we know  not  yet  how things  stand upon the field.  Forth now, and fear no  
line 40948=>darkness!' 
line 40949=>     The leading company rode off as swiftly as they could, for it was still 
line 40950=>deep dark,  whatever change Wndfara  might forebode. Merry was riding 
line 40951=>behind 
line 40952=>Dernhelm,  clutching  with the  left hand  while  with the other he tried to 
line 40953=>loosen his sword in its sheath. He felt now  bitterly  the  truth of the old 
line 40954=>king's  words: in such  a battle what would you do Meriadoc?  Just this,' he 
line 40955=>thought: 'encumber a rider, and hope at best to stay in my  seat and  not be 
line 40956=>pounded to death by galloping hoofs!' 
line 40957=>     It was no  more than a  league  to where the out-walls had stood.  They 
line 40958=>soon reached them; too soon for  Merry. Wild cries broke out, and  there was 
line 40959=>some clash of arms, but it was brief. The orcs busy about the walls were few  
line 40960=>and amazed, and they were quickly  slain or driven off. Before the  ruin  of 
line 40961=>the north-gate  in the Rammas the king halted again. The first  jored drew up 
line 40962=>behind  him and about him on either side.  Dernhelm kept close to the  king,  
line 40963=>though Elfhelm's company was away on  the right. Grimbold's men turned 
line 40964=>aside 
line 40965=>and passed round to a great gap in the wall further eastward. 
line 40966=>
line 40967=>####-     Merry peered from behind Dernhelm's  back. Far away, maybe ten miles or  
line 40968=>more, there was a great burning, but between it and the Riders lines of fire 
line 40969=>blazed in  a vast crescent, at the nearest point less than a league distant. 
line 40970=>He could make out little more on the dark plain,  and as yet he  neither saw 
line 40971=>any hope of morning, nor felt any wind, changed or unchanged. 
line 40972=>     Now silently the host of Rohan moved forward  into the field of Gondor,  
line 40973=>pouring in slowly but steadily, like the rising  tide through breaches in  a  
line 40974=>dike  that men  have  thought secure.  But  the  mind  and will of the Black  
line 40975=>Captain were bent wholly on the falling city, and   as yet no tidings came to 
line 40976=>him warning that his designs held any flaw. 
line 40977=>     After a while the  king led  his  men away somewhat  eastward, to  come 
line 40978=>between  the  fires  of  the siege  and the outer  fields. Still  they  were 
line 40979=>unchallenged,  and  still Thjoden gave  no signal. At last  he  halted  once 
line 40980=>again. The City was now nearer. A smell of burning was in the air and a very 
line 40981=>shadow  of  death.  The horses were uneasy. But the king sat upon  Snowmane, 
line 40982=>motionless, gazing upon the agony of Minas Tirith,  as i f  stricken suddenly 
line 40983=>by  anguish, or by  dread.  He  seemed to shrink  down, cowed by  age. Merry 
line 40984=>himself  felt as  if a great weight of horror and doubt had settled  on him. 
line 40985=>His  heart  beat slowly. Time  seemed poised in  uncertainty. They  were too 
line 40986=>late! Too late was worse  than never! Perhaps Thjoden would  quail,  bow his 
line 40987=>old head, turn, slink away to hide in the hills.  
line 40988=>     Then suddenly Merry felt  it at  last, beyond doubt: a change. Wind was 
line 40989=>in his face! Light was glimmering. Far, far  away, in  the  South the clouds 
line 40990=>could be dimly seen as remote grey shapes, rolling up, drifting: morning lay 
line 40991=>beyond them. 
line 40992=>     But at that same moment  there was a flash, as if lightning  had sprung 
line 40993=>from the earth beneath the City. For a searing second it stood dazzling  far 
line 40994=>off in black and white, its topmost tower like a glittering needle: and then 
line 40995=>as the darkness closed  again  there came rolling over  the fields  a  great 
line 40996=>boom. 
line 40997=>     At that sound  the bent shape  of the king sprang suddenly  erect. Tall 
line 40998=>and  proud he seemed again; and  rising in his  stirrups he  cried in a loud 
line 40999=>voice, more clear than any there had ever heard a mortal man achieve before: 
line 41000=>     Arise, arise, Riders of Thjoden! 
line 41001=>     Fell deeds awake: fire and slaughter! 
line 41002=>     spear shall be shaken, shie ld be splintered, 
line 41003=>     a sword-day, a red day, ere the sun rises! 
line 41004=>
line 41005=>####-     Ride now, ride now! Ride to Gondor! 
