line 41036=> 
line 41037=>     But  it was  no  orc-chieftain or  brigand that led  the  assault  upon 
line 41038=>Gondor. The darkness was breaking too soon, before the date  that his Master 
line 41039=>had set for it:  fortune had betrayed him for  the moment, and the world had 
line 41040=>turned against him; victory was slipping from his grasp even as he stretched 
line 41041=>out his  hand  to seize it.  But  his arm was long. He was still  in command, 
line 41042=>wielding  great  powers. King, Ringwraith,  Lord of the Nazgyl, he  had many 
line 41043=>weapons. He left the Gate and vanished. 
line 41044=>     Thjoden  King of  the  Mark  had reached the road from the Gate to  the 
line 41045=>River, and he turned towards the City that was now less than a mile distant. 
line 41046=>He slackened his speed  a little, seeking new foes,  and  his  knights  came 
line 41047=>about him, and Dernhelm was with  them. Ahead nearer the walls Elfhelm's 
line 41048=>men 
line 41049=>were among the  siege-engines, hewing, slaying, driving their foes into  the 
line 41050=>fire-pits. Well nigh all the northern half of the Pelennor was overrun,  and 
line 41051=>there camps were  blazing, orcs were  flying towards  the  River like  herds 
line 41052=>before the hunters; and the Rohirrim went hither  and thither at their will. 
line 41053=>But they had not yet overthrown the siege, nor won the Gate. Many foes stood 
line 41054=>before  it, and on the  further  half of the  plain were  other hosts  still 
line 41055=>unfought. Southward beyond the road lay  the main force of the Haradrim, and 
line 41056=>there  their  horsemen were gathered about the standard of  their chieftain. 
line 41057=>And he looked  out, and in the growing light he saw the banner of  the king,  
line 41058=>and that  it was far  ahead of the battle with few men about it. Then he was 
line 41059=>filled with a  red wrath  and shouted aloud, and  displaying  his  standard, 
line 41060=>black serpent upon  scarlet, he  came against the white  horse and the green 
line 41061=>with great press of men; and  the  drawing of the scimitars of the Southrons 
line 41062=>was like a glitter of stars.  
line 41063=>     Then Thjoden was  aware of  him, and  would not wait for his onset, but 
line 41064=>crying to Snowmane he  charged headlong to greet him. Great was the clash of 
line 41065=>their  meeting. But the white fury  of the Northmen burned the  hotter,  and 
line 41066=>more skilled  was  their knighthood with long spears  and bitter. Fewer were 
line 41067=>they  but they  clove through the Southrons  like a fire-bolt  in  a forest. 
line 41068=>Right  through the press  drove  Thjoden Thengel's son,  and  his  spear was 
line 41069=>
line 41070=>####-shivered as he threw down  their chieftain.  Out  swept  his sword,  and  he 
line 41071=>spurred  to  the  standard,  hewed staff  and bearer;  and the black serpent 
line 41072=>foundered. Then all that was left unslain of  their cavalry  turned and fled 
line 41073=>far away. 
line 41074=>     But  lo! suddenly in  the  midst of the glory  of the  king his  golden 
line 41075=>shield was dimmed. The new morning was blotted from the sky. Dark fell 
line 41076=>about 
line 41077=>him. Horses reared and screamed. Men cast  from the saddle lay grovelling on 
line 41078=>the ground. 
line 41079=>     'To  me!  To me!' cried Thjoden. 'Up Eorlingas!  Fear no darkness!' But 
line 41080=>Snowmane wild with terror stood up  on high, fighting with the air, and then 
line 41081=>with a great scream he crashed upon his side: a black dart had pierced  him. 
line 41082=>The king fell beneath him. 
line 41083=>     The great shadow  descended like a falling cloud. And behold!  it was a  
line 41084=>winged  creature: if bird, then  greater than all  other  birds, and it  was 
line 41085=>naked, and neither quill nor  feather did it bear, and its vast pinions were 
line 41086=>as webs of hide between horned fingers; and it stank. A creature of an older  
line 41087=>world maybe it  was,  whose  kind,  fingering  in  forgotten mountains  cold 
line 41088=>beneath the Moon,  outstayed their day,  and in hideous eyrie bred this last 
line 41089=>untimely brood, apt to evil. And the Dark  Lord took it, and nursed it  with 
line 41090=>fell meats, until  it grew beyond the measure of all  other things that fly; 
line 41091=>and he gave it to his servant to be his steed. Down, down it came, and then, 
line 41092=>folding its fingered webs, it gave a croaking cry, and settled upon the body 
line 41093=>of Snowmane, digging in its claws, stooping its long naked neck. 
line 41094=>     Upon it  sat a shape, black -mantled , huge and threatening. A  crown  of 
line 41095=>steel he bore, but between rim and robe naught was there to see, save only a  
line 41096=>deadly  gleam of eyes: the Lord  of the  Nazgyl. To the air he had returned, 
line 41097=>summoning  his  steed ere the darkness failed,  and now he was  come  again, 
line 41098=>bringing ruin,  turning hope to despair, and victory to death. A great black  
line 41099=>mace he wielded. 
line 41100=>     But Thjoden  was  not utterly forsaken. The  knights of  his house  lay 
line 41101=>slain about him, or else mastered by the madness of  their steeds were borne 
line 41102=>far away. Yet one stood  there still:  Dernhelm  the  young, faithful beyond 
line 41103=>fear; and he wept, for he had  loved his lord as a father. Right through the 
line 41104=>charge Merry had  been borne unharmed behind him, until the Shadow came; 
line 41105=>and 
line 41106=>then  Windfola  had thrown  them in his terror, and now  ran  wild upon  the 
line 41107=>
line 41108=>####-plain. Merry crawled on all fours like a dazed beast, and  such a horror was 
line 41109=>on him that he was blind and sick. 
line 41110=>     'King's man! King's man!' his heart cried within him. 'You must stay by 
line 41111=>him. As a father you shall be to me, you said.' But his will made no answer, 
line 41112=>and his body shook. He dared not open his eyes or look up. 
line 41113=>     Then out of the blackness in his mind he thought that he heard Dernhelm 
line 41114=>speaking; yet now the voice seemed strange, recalling  some other voice  that 
line 41115=>he had known. 
line 41116=>     'Begone, foul dwimmerlaik, lord of carrion! Leave the dead in peace!' 
line 41117=>     A cold voice answered: 'Come not between the Nazgyl and his prey! Or he 
line 41118=>will not slay thee  in thy turn. He  will  bear  thee away to the houses  of 
line 41119=>lamentation, beyond all darkness, where thy flesh shall be devoured, and thy 
line 41120=>shrivelled mind be left naked to the Lidless Eye.' 
line 41121=>     A sword rang as it was drawn. 'Do what you will; but  I will hinder it, 
line 41122=>if I may.' 
line 41123=>     'Hinder me? Thou fool. No living man may hinder me!' 
line 41124=>     Then  Merry heard of all sounds in that  hour the  strangest. It seemed 
