line 41138=>were  hard  and fell, and yet tears were  on  her cheek. A sword was in  her  
line 41139=>hand, and she raised her shield against the horror of her enemy's eyes.  
line 41140=>     Jowyn  it  was,  and  Dernhelm  also. For into Merry's mind flashed the 
line 41141=>memory of the face that he saw at the riding from Dunharrow: the face of one 
line 41142=>that goes seeking death, having no  hope. Pity  filled his heart  and  great 
line 41143=>wonder, and suddenly the slow-kindled courage of his race awoke. He clenched 
line 41144=>his hand. She should not die, so fair, so desperate At  least she should not 
line 41145=>
line 41146=>####-die alone, unaided. 
line 41147=>     The face of their enemy was not turned towards him, but still he hardly 
line 41148=>dared  to move,  dreading lest  the deadly eyes should fall  on him. Slowly, 
line 41149=>slowly he began to crawl aside; but the Black  Captain, in doubt  and malice 
line 41150=>intent upon the woman before him, heeded him no more than a worm in the 
line 41151=>mud. 
line 41152=>     Suddenly the great beast beat its hideous  wings, and the  wind of them 
line 41153=>was foul.  Again it  leaped into the  air, and then  swiftly fell  down upon 
line 41154=>Jowyn, shrieking, striking with beak and claw.  
line 41155=>     Still  she  did  not blench:  maiden of  the Rohirrim, child of  kings,  
line 41156=>slender but as a steel -blade, fair but terrible.  A  swift stroke she dealt, 
line 41157=>skilled and deadly.  The outstretched neck she clove asunder,  and the  hewn 
