line 41187=>laboured. 
line 41188=>     'Farewell, Master Holbytla!'  he said. 'My body  is broken. I go to  my 
line 41189=>fathers.  And  even  in their mighty  company  I shall not now be ashamed. I  
line 41190=>felled the black serpent. A grim morn, and a glad day, and a golden sunset!' 
line 41191=>     Merry could  not speak, bu t wept anew. 'Forgive me,  lord,' he  said at 
line 41192=>last, 'if  I broke  your command, and  yet have done no more in your service 
line 41193=>than to weep at our parting.' 
line 41194=>     The old king smiled. 'Grieve not! It is forgiven. Great  heart will not 
line 41195=>be denied. Live now  in blessedness; and when  you  sit  in peace with  your  
line 41196=>pipe, think  of  me! For  never now shall I  sit with you in Meduseld,  as I 
line 41197=>promised, or listen to your herb-lore.' He closed his eyes, and Merry  bowed  
line 41198=>beside him. Presently  he spoke again. 'Where is  Jomer? For my eyes darken, 
line 41199=>and I would see him ere I go.  He must be  king after  me. And  I would send  
line 41200=>word to Jowyn. She, she would not have me leave her, and now I shall not see 
line 41201=>her again, dearer than daughter.' 
line 41202=>     'Lord,  lord,' began Merry brokenly, 'she  is--';  but  at that  moment 
line 41203=>there  was  a  great clamour, and all  about  them horns and  trumpets  were 
line 41204=>blowing. Merry looked round:  he had forgotten  the war, and  all  the world 
line 41205=>beside, and many hours it  seemed since the king rode to his fall, though in 
line 41206=>truth it was only a little while. But now he saw that they were in danger of 
line 41207=>being caught  in  the  very midst  of the great  battle that would  soon  be 
line 41208=>joined. 
line 41209=>     New forces of the enemy were hastening up the road from the River;  and  
line 41210=>from  u nder the walls came  the  legions of Morgul; and  from  the southward 
line 41211=>fields came footmen of Harad with horsemen before them, and behind them 
line 41212=>rose 
line 41213=>the huge backs of the mymakil with war-towers  upon them. But  northward the 
line 41214=>white crest of Jomer led the great front of  the Rohirrim which he had again 
line 41215=>gathered and marshalled;  and out of the City  came all the  strength of men 
line 41216=>that  was in  it, and  the silver swan of Dol Amroth was borne  in  the van, 
line 41217=>driving the enemy from the Gate. 
line 41218=>     For  a  moment  the thought flitted through  Merry's  mind:  'Where  is 
line 41219=>Gandalf? Is he not here? Could he not  have saved the  king and Jowyn?'  But 
line 41220=>thereupon Jomer rode  up  in haste, and with him  came the  knights  of  the 
line 41221=>
line 41222=>####-household that still lived and had now mastered their horses. They looked in 
line 41223=>wonder  at  the carcase of the fell  beast that lay there:  and their steeds 
line 41224=>would  not go near. But Jomer leaped from the  saddle, and  grief and dismay 
line 41225=>fell upon him as he came to the king's side and stood there in silence. 
line 41226=>     Then one of the knights took the king's banner from the hand of Guthlbf 
line 41227=>the banner -bearer who  lay  dead, and he lifted it up. Slowly Thjoden opened 
line 41228=>his eyes. Seeing the banner he made a sign that it should be given to Jomer. 
line 41229=>     'Hail, King of  the Mark!' he said.  'Ride now  to  victory!  Bid Jowyn 
line 41230=>farewell!' And so he died,  and knew  not that Jowyn lay near him. And those 
line 41231=>who stood by wept, crying: 'Thjoden King! Thjoden King!' 
line 41232=>     But Jomer said to them: 
line 41233=>     Mourn not overmuch! Mighty was the fallen, 
line 41234=>     meet was his ending. When his mound is raised, 
line 41235=>     women then shall weep. War now calls us! 
line 41236=>     Yet  he himself wept  as he spoke.  'Let  his knights remain  here,' he 
line 41237=>said; 'and bear his body in honour from the field, lest the battle ride over  
line 41238=>it! Yea, and all these other of the king's men that lie here.' And he looked 
line 41239=>at  the  slain,  recalling their  names. Then suddenly he beheld  his sister  
line 41240=>Jowyn as she lay, and he knew her. He stood a moment as a man who is 
line 41241=>pierced 
line 41242=>in the midst of a cry by  an arrow through the heart;  and then his face went 
line 41243=>deathly white;  and a cold  fury rose in him, so that  all speech failed him 
line 41244=>for a while. A fey mood took him. 
line 41245=>     'Jowyn,  Jowyn!'  he  cried at last:  'Jowyn,  how come you  here? What 
line 41246=>madness or devilry is this? Death, death, death! Death take us all!' 
line 41247=>     Then without taking  counsel or waiting for the approach of  the men of 
line 41248=>the City, he spurred headlong back  to the front of the great host, and blew 
line 41249=>a horn, and cried  aloud for  the onset. Over the field rang his clear voice 
line 41250=>calling: 'Death! Ride, ride to ruin and the world's ending!' 
line 41251=>     And with that the host  began to move. But the Rohirrim sang  no  more. 
line 41252=>Death  they cried with one voice loud and terrible, and gathering speed  like 
line 41253=>a  great tide their battle swept about their fallen king and passed, roaring 
line 41254=>away southwards.  
line 41255=>     And still  Meriadoc  the hobbit stood there blinking through  his tears 
line 41256=>and no one spoke to him, indeed none seemed to heed him. He brushed away 
line 41257=>the 
line 41258=>tears, and stooped to pick up the green shield that Jowyn had given him; and 
line 41259=>
line 41260=>####-he slung it at his back.  Then he looked for his sword that he had let fall; 
line 41261=>for even as he struck his blow his arm was numbed, and now he could only use 
line 41262=>his left hand. And behold! there  lay his weapon, but the blade  was smoking  
line 41263=>like a dry branch that has been thrust in  a fire; and as  he watched it, it 
line 41264=>writhed and withered and was consumed. 
line 41265=>     So passed the sword  of the Barrow-downs, work of Westernesse. But glad 
line 41266=>would  he have been  to know its fate who wrought  it slowly long ago in the  
line 41267=>North-kingdom when the DÂ®nedain were young,  and chief among  their foes 
line 41268=>was 
line 41269=>the dread realm of Angmar and its sorcerer king. No other blade, not  though 
line 41270=>mightier hands had wielded it, would have dealt that foe a wound  so bitter, 
line 41271=>cleaving the undead flesh, breaking the spell that knit his unseen sinews to 
line 41272=>his will. 
line 41273=>     Men now raised the  king, and laying cloaks upon  spear -truncheons they 
line 41274=>made shift to bear him away towards the City; and others lifted Jowyn gently 
line 41275=>up and bore her after him.  But  the  men of the king's household they could 
line 41276=>not yet bring from  the  field; for seven of the king's knights  had  fallen 
line 41277=>there, and Djorwine their chief was among them. So they laid them apart from 
line 41278=>their foes and the fell beast and set spears about them. And afterwards when 
line 41279=>all was over men returned  and  made a fire there  and burned the carcase of 
line 41280=>the beast; but for Snowmane  they dug a grave and set up a stone  upon which 
line 41281=>was carved in the tongues of Gondor and the Mark: 
line 41282=>     Faithful servant yet master's bane 
line 41283=>     Lightfoot's foal, swift Snowmane. 
line 41284=>     Green and long  grew the grass  on  Snowmane's Howe, but ever black and 
line 41285=>bare was the ground where the beast was burned. 
line 41286=>     Now slowly and sadly Merry  walked beside the bearers,  and he gave  no 
line 41287=>more  heed to  the battle.  He was weary and  full  of  pain, and  his limbs 
line 41288=>trembled as  with  a chill. A great  rain came out of the Sea, and it seemed 
line 41289=>that all things wept for Thjoden and  Jowyn, quenching the fires in the City 
line 41290=>with grey tears.  It was through a mist that presently he saw the van of the 
line 41291=>men of Gondor  approaching. Imrahil,  Prince of Dol Amroth, rode up and 
line 41292=>drew 
line 41293=>rein before them. 
line 41294=>     'What burden do you bear, Men of Rohan?' he cried. 
line 41295=>     'Thjoden King,' they answered. 'He is dead. But Jomer King now rides in  
line 41296=>the battle: he with the white crest in the wind.' 
line 41297=>
line 41298=>####-     Then the prince went from his horse, and knelt by the bier in honour of 
line 41299=>the  king and  his  great onset; and  he wept. And  rising he looked then on 
line 41300=>Jowyn and  was amazed. 'Surely,  here  is a  woman?' he said. 'Have even the 
line 41301=>women of the Rohirrim come to war in our need?' 
line 41302=>     'Nay!  One only,'  they  answered.  'The Lady Jowyn is  she, sister  of 
line 41303=>Jomer; and we knew naught of her riding  until this hour, and greatly we rue 
line 41304=>it.' 
line 41305=>     Then the prince seeing her beauty, though her face  was pale  and cold, 
line 41306=>touched her hand as he bent to look more  closely on her. 'Men of Rohan!' he 
line 41307=>cried. 'Are there no leeches among you? She is hurt to the death  maybe, but 
line 41308=>I deem that  she yet lives.' And  he held the bright-burnished vambrace that 
line 41309=>was upon his arm before her cold tips, and behold! a little mist was laid on 
line 41310=>it hardly to be seen. 
line 41311=>     'Haste now is needed,'  he said, and he sent one riding back swiftly to 
line 41312=>the City to bring aid. But he bowing low to the fallen, bade  them farewell, 
line 41313=>and mounting rode away into battle. 
line 41314=>     And now  the  fighting waxed furious on the fields of the Pelennor; and 
line 41315=>the din of arms rose upon  high, with  the crying of men and the neighing of 
line 41316=>horses. Horns were blown  and trumpets  were  braying, and  the mymakil were 
line 41317=>bellowing as they  were goaded to war. Under the south walls of the City the  
line 41318=>footmen of Gondor now  drove against the legions  of Morgul that were  still  
line 41319=>gathered there in strength. But the horsemen rode eastward to the succour of 
line 41320=>Jomer:  HÂ®rin the Tall Warden of  the Keys, and the Lord of  Lossarnach, and 
line 41321=>Hirluin of the Green Hills, and Prince Imrahil the fair with his knights all 
line 41322=>about him. 
line 41323=>     Not too  soon came  their  aid to  the Rohirrim; for fortune had turned 
line 41324=>against Jomer,  and his fury had betrayed him.  The great wrath of his onset 
line 41325=>had  utterly  overthrown the front of  his enemies, and  great wedges of his 
line 41326=>Riders had passed clear through  the ranks of  the   Southrons,  discomfiting 
line 41327=>their  horsemen and riding their footmen to ruin.  But  wherever the mymakil 
line 41328=>came  there the horses would not go, but  blenched and swerved away; and the 
line 41329=>great  monsters were  unfought, and  stood  like towers of defence,  and the 
line 41330=>Haradrim rallied about them. And if the Rohirrim at  their onset were thrice 
line 41331=>outnumbered by  the Haradrim alone,  soon their case  became  worse; for new 
line 41332=>strength came  now streaming to the field  out of  Osgiliath. There they had 
line 41333=>been mustered for the sack of  the City and the rape of Gondor,  waiting  on  
line 41334=>the call of their Captain. He  now was destroyed; but Gothmog the lieutenant 
line 41335=>
line 41336=>####-of  Morgul had flung them into the fray; Easterlings  with axes, and Variags 
line 41337=>of  Khand. Southrons  in  scarlet, and  out  of  Far  Harad  black  men  like 
line 41338=>half-trolls with white eyes and red tongues. Some now hastened up behind the 
line 41339=>Rohirrim, others  held westward to hold off the forces of Gondor and prevent 
line 41340=>their joining with Rohan. 
line 41341=>     It was even as the day thus began to turn against Gondor and their hope 
line 41342=>wavered that a new cry went up in the City, it being  then midmorning, and a 
line 41343=>great wind blowing,  and the rain flying north, and the sun shining. In that 
line 41344=>clear air watchmen on the walls saw afar a new sight of fear, and their last 
line 41345=>hope left them. 
line 41346=>     For Anduin, from the bend at  the Harlond, so flowed that from the City 
line 41347=>men  could look down it lengthwise for  some leagues,  and  the  far-sighted  
line 41348=>could  see  any  ships  that  approached. And looking thither they cried  in  
line 41349=>dismay; for black against the glittering stream they beheld a fleet borne up 
line 41350=>on the wind: dromunds, and  ships  of great draught with many oars, and with 
line 41351=>black sails bellying in the breeze. 
line 41352=>     'The Corsairs of Umbar!' men shouted. 'The Corsairs of Umbar! Look! The 
line 41353=>Corsairs of Umbar  are  coming!  So  Belfalas is  taken, and the  Ethir, and 
line 41354=>Lebennin is gone. The Corsairs are upon us! It is the last stroke of doom!' 
line 41355=>     And some without order, for none could he found to command them  in the 
line 41356=>City,  ran to  the bells and tolled the alarm;  and  some blew the  trumpets 
line 41357=>sounding the retreat. 'Back to the walls!' they  cried. 'Back to the  walls!  
line 41358=>Come back to the City before all are overwhelmed!' But the  wind  that  sped 
line 41359=>the ships blew all their clamour away. 
line 41360=>     The Rohirrim indeed had no  need  of news or  alarm.  All too well they 
line 41361=>could  see for themselves the black sails. For Jomer was now scarcely a mile  
line 41362=>from the Harlond, and a great press of  his first  foes was between  him and 
line 41363=>the haven  there, while new  foes came swirling behind, cutting him off from 
line 41364=>the Prince. Now he looked to the River,  and hope died in his heart, and the 
line 41365=>wind  that he had blessed  he  now  called accursed. But the hosts of Mordor  
line 41366=>were enheartened, and filled  with a new lust  and fury they came yelling to 
line 41367=>the onset. 
line 41368=>     Stern now  was Jomer's mood, and  his mind clear again. He let blow the 
line 41369=>horns to rally all men to his banner that could come thither; for he thought 
line 41370=>to make a great shield-wall at the last, and stand, and  fight there on foot 
line 41371=>till all fell, and do deeds of song on the fields of Pelennor, though no man 
line 41372=>should be left in the West to remember the last King of the Mark. So he rode  
line 41373=>
line 41374=>####-to  a green hillock and  there  set  his banner,  and  the  White Horse  ran 
line 41375=>rippling in the wind. 
line 41376=>     Out of doubt, out of dark to the day's rising 
line 41377=>     I came singing in the sun, sword unsheathing. 
line 41378=>     To hope's end I rode and to heart's breaking: 
line 41379=>     Now for wrath, now for ruin and a red nightfall! 
line 41380=>     These staves  he spoke, yet he laughed as  he  said them. For once more 
line 41381=>lust of battle was on him; and he was still unscathed, and he was young, and 
line 41382=>he was king:  the  lord  of a  fell  people. And lo! even  as he  laughed at 
line 41383=>despair he looked  out  again on the black ships, and he lifted up his sword 
line 41384=>to defy them. 
line 41385=>     And then wonder took him, and a great joy; and he cast  his sword up in 
line 41386=>the sunlight  and sang as he caught it. And all eyes followed his gaze,  and 
line 41387=>behold!  upon  the  foremost  ship  a great  standard  broke,  and the  wind 
