line 41484=>Chapter 7. The Pyre of Denethor 
line 41485=>
line 41486=> 
line 41487=> 
line 41488=>     When the dark shadow at the Gate withdrew Gandalf still sat motionless.  
line 41489=>But Pippin rose to his  feet, as if a great weight had been lifted from him; 
line 41490=>and  he stood listening to  the horns, and it seemed to  him that they would 
line 41491=>break his  heart  with joy. And  never in after years could  he  hear a horn 
line 41492=>blown in the distance  without tears starting in  his eyes. But now suddenly 
line 41493=>his errand  returned  to  his memory,  and  he  ran forward.  At that moment 
line 41494=>Gandalf stirred and spoke to Shadowfax, and was  about to  ride through  the 
line 41495=>Gate. 
line 41496=>     'Gandalf, Gandalf! ' cried Pippin, and Shadowfax halted. 
line 41497=>     'What are you  doing here?'  said Gandalf. 'Is it not a law in the City 
line 41498=>that  those who  wear the black and  silver must stay in the Citadel, unless 
line 41499=>their lord gives them leave?' 
line 41500=>     'He has,' said Pippin. 'He sent me away. But I am frightened. Something 
line 41501=>terrible may happen up  there. The  Lord is  out of his  mind, I think. I am 
line 41502=>afraid he will kill himself, and kill Faramir too. Can't you do something?' 
line 41503=>     Gandalf looked through the  gaping  Gate, and already  on the fields he 
line 41504=>heard the gathering sound of  battle. He clenched his  hand. 'I must go ' he 
line 41505=>said. 'The Black Rider is abroad, and he will yet  bring ruin on  us. I have 
line 41506=>no time.' 
line 41507=>     'But Faramir!' cried Pippin.  'He is  not dead, and they will  burn him 
line 41508=>alive, if someone does not stop them.' 
line 41509=>     'Burn him alive?' said Gandalf. 'What is this tale? Be quick!' 
line 41510=>     'Denethor  has gone  to  the  Tombs,'  said Pippin, 'and  he has  taken 
line 41511=>Faramir, and  he says we are all to burn, and he will not wait, and they are 
line 41512=>to make a pyre and  burn him on it, and Faramir as well. And he has sent men 
line 41513=>to fetch  wood and  oil.  And I have told Beregond, but I'm afraid  he won't  
line 41514=>dare  to  leave his post: he is on  guard. And what can  he  do  anyway?' So 
line 41515=>Pippin poured out  his tale, reaching up  and  touching  Gandalf's knee with 
line 41516=>trembling hands. 'Can't you save Faramir?' 
line 41517=>     'Maybe I can,' said Gandalf;  'but  if  I do, then  others will die,  I 
line 41518=>fear. Well, I must come, since no  other  help can  reach  him. But evil and 
line 41519=>sorrow will come of this. Even in the heart of our stronghold the Enemy  has 
line 41520=>power to strike us: for his will it is that is at work.' 
line 41521=>
line 41522=>####-     Then  having made up  his mind he acted swiftly; and catching up Pippin 
line 41523=>and setting him before him, he turned Shadowfax with a word. Up the climbing 
line 41524=>streets of Minas  Tirith they clattered, while the noise of  war rose behind 
line 41525=>them. Everywhere men were rising from their despair and dread, seizing their 
line 41526=>weapons, crying  one to another: 'Rohan  has come!'  Captains were shouting, 
line 41527=>companies were mustering; many already were marching down to the Gate. 
line 41528=>     They  met  the Prince Imrahil,  and  he called  to them: 'Whither  now, 
line 41529=>Mithrandir?  The Rohirrim are  fighting  on  the  fields  of Gondor! We must  
line 41530=>gather all the strength that we can find.' 
line 41531=>     'You will need every man and more,' said  Gandalf.  'Make  all haste. I 
line 41532=>will come when I can. But I  have  an errand to the  Lord Denethor that will 
line 41533=>not wait. Take command in the Lord's absence!' 
line 41534=>     They passed on; and  as they climbed and drew near to the Citadel  they 
line 41535=>felt the wind blowing in their faces, and they caught the glimmer of morning  
line 41536=>far away, a light growing in the southern sky. But it brought little hope to 
line 41537=>them, not knowing what evil lay before them, fearing to come too late. 
line 41538=>     'Darkness is passing,' said Gandalf, 'but it still lies heavy  on  this 
line 41539=>City.' 
line 41540=>     At the  gate  of the  Citadel they found no guard.  'Then Beregond  has 
line 41541=>gone,' said  Pippin  more hopefully. They turned away and hastened along the 
line 41542=>road to  the Closed Door. It stood wide open,  and the porter lay before it. 
line 41543=>He was slain and his key had been taken. 
line 41544=>     'Work of the Enemy!' said Gandalf. 'Such  deeds he loves: friend at war 
line 41545=>with friend; loyalty divided in  confusion of hearts.' Now he dismounted and 
line 41546=>bade  Shadowfax return to his stable. 'For, my friend,' he said, 'you and  I 
line 41547=>should have ridden to  the fields long  ago, but other matters delay me. Yet 
line 41548=>come swiftly if I call!' 
line 41549=>     They passed the Door  and walked on down the steep winding  road. Light 
line 41550=>was  growing, and the tall columns and carven  figures beside the  way  went 
line 41551=>slowly by like grey ghosts.  
line 41552=>     Suddenly the silence was broken,  and  they  heard below them cries and  
line 41553=>the ringing of swords: such  sounds as had not been  heard in  the  hallowed 
line 41554=>places since the building of  the City. At  last they came to Rath Dnnen and 
line 41555=>hastened towards the  House of the Stewards,  looming in the  twilight under  
line 41556=>its great dome. 
line 41557=>     'Stay!  Stay!'  cried Gandalf,  springing  forward  to the stone  stair 
line 41558=>before the door. 'Stay this madness!' 
line 41559=>
line 41560=>####-     For there were  the servants of  Denethor with  swords and  torches  in 
line 41561=>their hands; but  alone in the  porch upon  the topmost step stood Beregond, 
line 41562=>clad in the black and silver of  the  Guard;  and he held  the door  against 
line 41563=>them. Two of them had already fallen to his sword, staining the hallows with 
line 41564=>their blood;  and the others cursed  him, calling him outlaw and  traitor to 
line 41565=>his master. 
line 41566=>     Even  as Gandalf and  Pippin  ran forward,  they heard from  within the 
line 41567=>house of the dead  the voice of Denethor crying: 'Haste, haste! Do as I have 
line 41568=>bidden!  Slay me this renegade! Or must I do so myself?' Thereupon  the door  
line 41569=>which Beregond held  shut  with  his left  hand was wrenched open, and there 
line 41570=>behind him stood the Lord of the City, tall and fell; a light like flame was 
line 41571=>in his eyes, a nd he held a drawn sword. 
line 41572=>     But Gandalf sprang up  the steps, and  the men fell  back from  him and 
line 41573=>covered their eyes; for his  coming  was like the incoming of a  white light 
line 41574=>into  a dark place, and he came with great anger. He lifted up his hand, and 
line 41575=>in  the very stroke, the sword of Denethor flew  up and left  his  grasp and 
line 41576=>fell  behind him in the shadows of the house; and  Denethor stepped backward 
line 41577=>before Gandalf as one amazed. 
line 41578=>     'What is this, my lord?' said the wizard. 'The houses  of the  dead are 
line 41579=>no  places for the living.  And why  do men  fight here in the  Hallows when 
line 41580=>there  is  war enough before  the  Gate? Or has our  Enemy come even to Rath 
line 41581=>Dnnen?' 
line 41582=>     'Since  when  has  the Lord  of  Gondor been answerable to thee?'  said 
line 41583=>Denethor.  'Or may I not command my own servants?' 
line 41584=>     'You may,' said Gandalf.  'But others may contest your will, when it is 
line 41585=>turned to madness and evil. Where is your son, Faramir?' 
line 41586=>     'He lies  within,' said Denethor, 'burning, already burning. They  have 
line 41587=>set a fire in his flesh. But soon all shall be burned. The  West has failed. 
line 41588=>It shall  all  go up in a  great fire, and all shall be  ended. Ash! Ash and 
line 41589=>smoke blown away on the wind!' 
line 41590=>     Then  Gandalf  seeing the madness  that was on  him feared that he  had 
line 41591=>already done some evil deed, and he thrust forward, with Beregond and Pippin 
line 41592=>behind him, while Denethor gave back until he stood beside the table within. 
line 41593=>But  there they found Faramir,  still dreaming in  his fever, lying upon the 
line 41594=>table. Wood was piled under it, and high all about it, and all  was drenched 
line 41595=>with oil, even the garments of Faramir and the coverlets; but as yet no fire 
line 41596=>had been set to the fuel. Then Gandalf revealed the strength that lay hid in 
line 41597=>
line 41598=>####-him; even as the light of  his  power was hidden u nder his  grey mantle.  He 
line 41599=>leaped up on to the faggots, and raising the sick man lightly he sprang down 
line 41600=>again, and bore him towards the door. But as he did  so  Faramir moaned  and 
line 41601=>called on his father in his dream. 
line 41602=>     Denethor started as one waking from a trance, and the flame died in his 
line 41603=>eyes,  and he wept; and he said: 'Do not take my son from me!  He calls  for  
line 41604=>me.' 
line 41605=>     'He calls,' said Gandalf, 'but you cannot come to him yet.  For he must  
line 41606=>seek healing on the threshold of death, and maybe find it no t. Whereas  your  
line 41607=>part is to go out to  the battle of your City, where maybe death awaits you. 
line 41608=>This you know in your heart.' 
line 41609=>     'He will not wake again,' said Denethor. 'Battle is vain. Why should we 
line 41610=>wish to live longer? Why should we not go to death side by side?' 
line 41611=>     'Authority is not given to you, Steward of Gondor, to order the hour of 
line 41612=>your  death,'  answered  Gandalf.  'And only the  heathen  kings, under  the 
line 41613=>domination of the Dark Power, did  thus,  slaying  themselves  in pride  and 
line 41614=>despair, murdering their kin to ease their  own death.' Then passing through 
line 41615=>the door he took  Faramir from the deadly house and laid him  on the bier on  
line 41616=>which he had been brought, and which had now been set in the porch. Denethor  
line 41617=>followed him, and  stood trembling,  looking with longing on the face of his 
line 41618=>son. And for a moment, while all were silent and still, watching the Lord in 
line 41619=>his throes, he wavered. 
line 41620=>     'Come!' said  Gandalf.  'We  are needed. There is much that you can yet 
line 41621=>do.' 
line 41622=>     Then suddenly Denethor laughed . He stood up  tall  and proud again, and 
line 41623=>stepping swiftly back to the table he lifted from it the pillow on which his 
line 41624=>head  had lain.  Then coming to the  doorway he drew aside the covering, and 
line 41625=>lo! he had between his hands  a palantnr. And as he held it up, it seemed to 
line 41626=>those that  looked on that the  globe began to  glow with an inner flame, so 
line 41627=>that the lean face of the Lord was lit as with a red fire, and it seemed cut 
line 41628=>out of hard stone, sharp with black shadows, noble, proud, and terrible. His 
line 41629=>eyes glittered. 
line 41630=>     'Pride and despair!' he cried.  'Didst thou  think that the eyes of the 
line 41631=>White  Tower were blind? Nay, I have seen more than thou knowest, Grey 
line 41632=>Fool. 
line 41633=>For  thy hope is  but ignorance. Go then and labour in healing! Go forth and  
line 41634=>fight! Vanity. For a little space you may triumph  on the field, for a  day. 
line 41635=>
line 41636=>####-But against the Power that now arises there is no victory. To this City only 
line 41637=>the first finger of its hand has yet been stretched. All the East is moving. 
line 41638=>And even now the  wind of thy  hope cheats thee and wafts up Anduin a  fleet 
line 41639=>with black  sails. The West has failed. It is  time for all  to  depart  who 
line 41640=>would not be slaves.' 
line 41641=>     'Such  counsels  will make the  Enemy's victory  certain  indeed,' said 
line 41642=>Gandalf. 
line 41643=>     'Hope on then!' laughed Denethor. 'Do  I not know thee, Mithrandir? Thy  
line 41644=>hope is to rule in my stead, to stand behind every throne,  north, south, or  
line 41645=>west. I  have read  thy  mind  and  its  policies.  Do I  not  know that you  
line 41646=>commanded this halfling here to keep silence? That you brought him hither to 
line 41647=>be a spy  within  my  very  chamber?  And yet  in our speech together I have 
line 41648=>learned  the names and purpose of all thy companions. So! With the left hand 
line 41649=>thou wouldst use me  for a little while as a shield against Mordor, and with 
line 41650=>the right bring up this Ranger of the North to supplant me. 
line 41651=>     'But  I say to thee, Gandalf Mithrandir, I will not  be  thy tool! I am 
line 41652=>Steward of the  House  of Anbrion.  I will not step  down  to be  the dotard 
line 41653=>chamberlain of an upstart. Even  were his claim proved to me, still he comes 
line 41654=>but of the line of Isildur. I will not bow to such a  one, last of  a ragged 
line 41655=>house long bereft of lordship and dignity.' 
line 41656=>     'What then would  you have,' said Gandalf, 'if your will could have its 
line 41657=>way?' 
line 41658=>     'I would have things as they were in all the days of my life,' answered 
line 41659=>Denethor,  'and in the days of  my  longfathers before me: to be the Lord of 
line 41660=>this City in peace,  and leave my chair to  a son after me, who would be his 
line 41661=>own master and no wizard's pupil. But if doom denies this to me, then I will 
line 41662=>have naught: neither life diminished, nor love halved, nor honour abated.' 
line 41663=>     'To me it would  not seem that a Steward who  faithfully surrenders his 
line 41664=>charge is diminished in love  or in honour,' said Gandalf. 'And at the least 
line 41665=>you shall not rob your son of his choice while his death is still in doubt.' 
line 41666=>     At those words Denethor's eyes flamed again, and taking the Stone under  
line 41667=>his arm  he drew a knife and  strode towards the  bier. But  Beregond sprang 
line 41668=>forward and set himself before Faramir. 
line 41669=>     'So!' cried Denethor. 'Thou hadst  already  stolen  half my son's love. 
line 41670=>Now thou stealest the hearts of  my knights also, so that they rob me wholly  
line 41671=>of my son at the last. But in this at least thou shalt not defy  my will: to 
line 41672=>rule my own end.' 
line 41673=>
line 41674=>####-     'Come  hither!'  he cried  to his servants. 'Come,  if you are  not all 
line 41675=>recreant!'  Then two of them ran up the steps to  him. Swiftly he snatched a  
line 41676=>torch from the hand of  one  and  sprang back into the house. Before Gandalf 
line 41677=>could hinder him he  thrust the brand amid the fuel, and at once it crackled 
line 41678=>and roared into flame. 
line 41679=>     Then Denethor  leaped upon  the  table, and  standing there wreathed in 
line 41680=>fire and smoke he took up the staff  of his stewardship that lay at his feet 
line 41681=>and broke  it on his  knee.  Casting the pieces into  the blaze he bowed and 
line 41682=>laid himself  on  the table, clasping the palantnr with both hands upon  his 
line 41683=>breast. And  it was said that ever after, if  any man  looked in that Stone, 
line 41684=>unless he had a great strength of will to  turn it to other purpose, he  saw 
line 41685=>only two aged hands withering in flame. 
line 41686=>     Gandalf in grief and horror turned his face away  and closed the  door. 
line 41687=>For  a  while  he stood in thought,  silent  upon the threshold, while those 
line 41688=>outside heard the greedy roaring of  the fire within. And then Denethor gave 
line 41689=>a great cry, and afterwards spoke no more, nor was ever again seen by mortal 
line 41690=>men. 
line 41691=>     'So passes Denethor, son of Ecthelion,' said Gandalf: Then he turned to 
line 41692=>Beregond and the Lord's servants that stood there aghast.  'And so pass also 
line 41693=>the days of Gondor that you have known; for good or evil they are ended. Ill 
line 41694=>deeds  have been done here; but let now  all enmity that lies between you be 
line 41695=>put away, for  it  was contrived by the Enemy and works  his  will. You have 
line 41696=>been  caught  in a net of warring duties that  you did not weave. But think, 
line 41697=>you servants of the Lord, blind in your obedience, that but  for the treason 
line 41698=>of Beregond Faramir, Captain of the White Tower, would now also be burned. 
line 41699=>     'Bear away  from this unhappy place your comrades who  have fallen. And 
line 41700=>we  will bear  Faramir, Steward of Gondor, to  a place where he can sleep in 
line 41701=>peace, or die if that be his doom.' 
line 41702=>     Then Gandalf and Beregond taking  up the bier bore  it away towards the 
line 41703=>Houses of  Hea ling,  while behind them walked Pippin with downcast head. 
line 41704=>But 
line 41705=>the servants of the Lord  stood gazing as stricken  men  at the house of the 
line 41706=>dead; and even  as Gandalf  came to the end of Rath Dnnen there was a  great 
line 41707=>noise. Looking back  they  saw the  dome of the house crack and smokes issue 
line 41708=>forth; and then with a rush and rumble of stone it fell in a flurry of fire; 
line 41709=>but still unabated the flames danced and  flickered among the ruins. Then in 
line 41710=>terror the servants fled and followed Gandalf.  
line 41711=>
line 41712=>####-     At length they came back  to  the Steward's Door,  and  Beregond looked  
line 41713=>with grief  at  the porter. 'This deed I  shall  ever rue,'  he said; 'but a  
line 41714=>madness of haste was on  me, and he would not listen, but drew sword against  
line 41715=>me.' Then  taking  the key that he had  wr ested from the slain man he closed 
line 41716=>the door and locked it.  'This should now be given to the Lord  Faramir,' he 
line 41717=>said. 
line 41718=>     'The Prince  of Dol Amroth is in  command in the absence of  the Lord,' 
line 41719=>said Gandalf; 'but since he is not here,  I must take this on  myself. I bid 
line 41720=>you keep the key and guard it, until the City is set in order again.' 
line 41721=>     Now  at last they passed  into the high circles of the City, and in the 
line 41722=>light of morning  they went their way towards  the  Houses  of Healing;  and 
line 41723=>these were  fair houses set apart, for the care of those who were grievously 
line 41724=>sick, but now  they were prepared  for the tending of men  hurt in battle or  
line 41725=>dying. They stood not far from  the  Citadel-gate, in the sixth circle, nigh 
line 41726=>to  its southward  wall, and about  them was a  garden and a greensward with 
line 41727=>trees,  the only such place in the City. There dwelt the few women  that had 
line 41728=>been permitted to remain in Minas Tirith, since they were skilled in healing 
line 41729=>or in the service of the healers.  
line 41730=>     But even  as Gandalf and his companions came  carrying the bier  to the 
line 41731=>main door of the  Houses, they heard a great cry that went up from the field 
line 41732=>before the Gate and rising shrill and piercing into the sky passed, and died 
line 41733=>away on the wind. So terrible was the cry that for a moment all stood still, 
line 41734=>and  yet when it  had passed, suddenly their hearts were lifted up in such a  
line 41735=>hope as they had not known  since the darkness came  out of the East; and it  
line 41736=>seemed  to them that  the  light grew  clear and the sun  broke  through the 
line 41737=>clouds. 
line 41738=>     But Gandalf's  face was  grave and sad, and bidding Beregond and Pippin 
line 41739=>to take  Faramir into the Houses  of Healing, he  went  up on  to  the walls 
line 41740=>nearby; and there like a figure carven in white he stood  in the new sun and 
line 41741=>looked out. And he beheld with the sight that was given to him all that  had 
line 41742=>befallen; and when Jomer rode out from the forefront of his battle and stood 
line 41743=>beside those who lay upon the field, he sighed, and he cast  his cloak about 
line 41744=>him again,  and went  from  the  walls.  And Beregond  and  Pippin found him 
line 41745=>standing in thought before the door of the Houses when they came out. 
line 41746=>     They looked at him, and for  a  while he was  silent. At last he spoke. 
line 41747=>'My friends,' he  said, 'and all you people of this city and of the  Western 
line 41748=>lands! Things of great sorrow and renown have come to pass. Shall we weep or  
line 41749=>
line 41750=>####-be glad? Beyond hope the Captain  of  our foes has been  destroyed,  and you 
line 41751=>have heard the echo of his last despair. But he has not gone without woe and 
line 41752=>bitter loss. And that I might have averted but for the madness of  Denethor. 
line 41753=>So long  has the reach of our Enemy become! Alas! but now I perceive how his 
line 41754=>will was able to enter into the very heart of the City. 
line 41755=>     'Though  the  Stewards  deemed  that  it  was  a secret  kept  only   by 
line 41756=>themselves, long ago I guessed that here in the White Tower, one at least of 
line 41757=>the Seven Seeing  Stones was preserved. In  the days of his  wisdom Denethor  
line 41758=>did not presume to  use it,  nor to  challenge Sauron, knowing the limits of 
line 41759=>his own strength. But his wisdom failed; and I fear that as the peril of his 
line 41760=>realm grew he looked in the Stone and was deceived: far too often, I  guess,  
line 41761=>since Boromir departed.  He was too great to  be subdued  to the will of the 
line 41762=>Dark Power, he saw nonetheless only those things which  that Power permitted 
line 41763=>him to see. The knowledge which he obtained was, doubtless, often of service 
line 41764=>to  him; yet the vision of the great might  of Mordor that was  shown to him 
line 41765=>fed the despair of his heart until it overthrew his mind.' 
line 41766=>     'Now I understand what seemed so strange to me!' said Pippin shuddering 
line 41767=>at his memories as he spoke. 'The Lord went away from the room where 
line 41768=>Faramir 
line 41769=>lay; and it was only when  he  returned that I first thought he was changed, 
line 41770=>old and broken.' 
line 41771=>     'It was  in the very hour  that  Faramir was brought to the Tower  that 
line 41772=>many of us saw  a strange light in the topmost chamber,' said Beregond. 'But 
line 41773=>we have  seen that light before, and it has  long been rumoured in the City, 
line 41774=>that the Lord would at times wrestle in thought with his Enemy.' 
line 41775=>     'Alas!  then I  have guessed rightly,' said Gandalf. 'Thus  the will of 
line 41776=>Sauron entered into Minas  Tirith; and thus  I  have  been delayed here. And 
line 41777=>here I shall still be forced to remain, for I shall soon have other charges,  
line 41778=>not Faramir only. 
line 41779=>     'Now I must go down to meet those  who come. I have seen  a  sight upon 
line 41780=>the field that is very grievous to my heart, and greater sorrow may yet come 
line 41781=>to  pass.  Come  with me, Pippin! But you,  Beregond,  should  return to the 
line 41782=>Citadel and tell the chief of the Guard there what has befallen. It  will be 
line 41783=>his duty, I fear, to withdraw you from the Guard; but  say to him that, if I 
line 41784=>may give him counsel, you should be sent to the Houses of Healing, to be the 
line 41785=>guard and servant of your captain, and to be at his side when he awakes  - if 
line 41786=>that shall ever be again. For by you  he  was saved from the fire. Go now! I 
line 41787=>
line 41788=>####-shall return soon.' 
line 41789=>     With  that  he  turned away and went with Pippin down towards the lower 
line 41790=>city. And even as they  hastened on their way the wind brought  a grey rain,  
line 41791=>and all the fires sank, and there arose a great smoke before them. 
