line 41795=>
line 41796=>Chapter 8. The Houses of Healing 
line 41797=>
line 41798=> 
line 41799=> 
line 41800=>     A mist was in Merry's eyes of tears  and weariness when they  drew near  
line 41801=>the  ruined  Gate of  Minas Tirith. He gave  little  heed to the  wreck  and 
line 41802=>slaughter that lay about all. Fire and smoke and  stench was in the air; for  
line 41803=>many engines  had been burned  or cast into  the fire-pits, and many  of the 
line 41804=>slain also, while here  and there lay  many  carcases of the great  Southron 
line 41805=>monsters, half-burned, or broken by stone-cast, or shot through  the eyes by 
line 41806=>the  valiant archers of Morthond. The flying rain had ceased for a time, and 
line 41807=>the sun  gleamed  up above;  but all the lower city  was still  wrapped in a  
line 41808=>smouldering reek. 
line 41809=>     Already men were labouring to clear a way through the jetsam of battle; 
line 41810=>and now out from the Gate came some bearing litters. Gently  they laid Jowyn 
line 41811=>upon soft pillows; but the king's body  they covered  with a great  cloth of 
line 41812=>gold,  and  they bore  torches about  him, and  their flames,  pale  in  the 
line 41813=>sunlight, were fluttered by the wind. 
line 41814=>     So Thjoden and Jowyn came  to  the City of Gondor, and all who saw them 
line 41815=>bared their heads and bowed; and they passed through the ash and fume of the 
line 41816=>burned circle, and went on and up  along the  streets of stone. To Merry the 
line 41817=>ascent seemed  agelong,  a  meaningless journey in a hateful dream, going on 
line 41818=>and on to some dim ending that memory cannot seize. 
line 41819=>     Slowly the  lights of  the torches in front of  him flickered  and went 
line 41820=>out,  and he was walking in  a darkness; and he  thought: 'This  is a tunnel 
line 41821=>leading to a tomb; there we shall stay forever.' But suddenly into his dream 
line 41822=>there fell a living voice. 
line 41823=>     'Well, Merry! Thank goodness I have found you!' 
line 41824=>     He looked up  and the mist before his eyes  cleared a little. There was 
line 41825=>Pippin! They were face  to face in a narrow lane,  and but for themselves it 
line 41826=>was empty. He rubbed his eyes.  
line 41827=>     'Where is the  king?' he said.  'And Jowyn?' Then he stumbled  and  sat 
line 41828=>down on a doorstep and began to weep again. 
line 41829=>     'They have gone up  into the Citadel,'  said  Pippin. 'I think you must  
line 41830=>have fallen  asleep on your  feet and taken the wrong turning. When we found 
line 41831=>that you were  not  with them,  Gandalf sent me to  look  for you.  Poor old 
line 41832=>Merry! How glad  I am to see you again!  But  you are worn out, and  I won't 
line 41833=>
line 41834=>####-bother you with any talk. But tell me, are you hurt, or wounded?' 
line 41835=>     'No,' said Merry. 'Well, no, I don't think so. But I can't use my right 
line 41836=>arm, Pippin, not since I stabbed  him.  And my  sword burned all away like a 
line 41837=>piece of wood.' 
line 41838=>     Pippin's face was anxious. 'Well, you had better come with me  as quick  
line 41839=>as you can,' he said. 'I wish I could carry you. You aren't fit to walk  any 
line 41840=>further. They shouldn't have let you walk at all; but you must forgive them. 
line 41841=>So  many dreadful things have  happened  in the  City, Merry, that  one poor  
line 41842=>hobbit coming in from the battle is easily overlooked.' 
line 41843=>     'It's not  always  a misfortune being overlooked,' said Merry.  'I  was 
line 41844=>overlooked just now by  - no, no, I can't speak of it.  Help me, Pippin! It's 
line 41845=>all going dark again, and my arm is so cold.' 
line 41846=>     'Lean on me, Merry lad!' said Pippin. 'Come now! Foot by foot. It's not 
line 41847=>far.' 
line 41848=>     'Are you going to bury me?' said Merry. 
line 41849=>     'No, indeed!' said Pippin, trying  to sound cheerful, though  his heart 
line 41850=>was wrung with fear and pity. 'No, we are going to the Houses of Healing.' 
line 41851=>     They turned out of the lane that ran  between tall houses and the outer  
line 41852=>wall of the fourth circle, and they  regained the main street climbing up to 
line 41853=>the Citadel. Step by step they  went, while Merry swayed and murmured as one 
line 41854=>in sleep. 
line 41855=>     'I'll never  get him there,' thought  Pippin. 'Is there  no one to help 
line 41856=>me? I can't leave him here.' Just then to his surprise a boy came running up 
line 41857=>behind, and as he passed he recognized Bergil Beregond's son. 
line 41858=>     'Hullo,  Bergil!' he  called.  'Where  are you going?  Glad to  see you  
line 41859=>again, and still alive!' 
line 41860=>     'I am running errands for the Healers,' said Bergil.  'I cannot stay.' 
line 41861=>     'Don't!'  said  Pippin.  'But  tell  them up  there that I have a  sick  
line 41862=>hobbit, a perian  mind you, come from the battle-field. I don't think he can 
line 41863=>walk so far. If Mithrandir is there, he will be glad of the message.' Bergil 
line 41864=>ran on. 
line 41865=>     'I'd better wait here,'  thought  Pippin. So he let Merry  sink  gently 
line 41866=>down on to the pavement in a patch of sunlight,  and then he sat down beside 
line 41867=>him, laying Merry's head  in his lap. He felt his body and limbs gently, and 
line 41868=>took his friend's hands in his own. The right hand felt icy to the touch. 
line 41869=>     It was  not long  before Gandalf himself  came  in  search  of them. He 
line 41870=>stooped over Merry and caressed  his brow; then he lifted him carefully. 'He 
line 41871=>
line 41872=>####-should have  been  borne in  honour  into this  city,' he said.  'He has well 
line 41873=>repaid my trust; for  if Elrond had  not yielded to me, neither of you would 
line 41874=>have  set  out; and then far more grievous would the  evils of this day have 
line 41875=>been.' He sighed. 'And yet here is another charge on my hands, while all the 
line 41876=>time the battle hangs in the balance.' 
line 41877=>     So at last  Faramir and  Jowyn and Meriadoc  were laid  in  beds in the 
line 41878=>Houses of  Healing; and there they were tended well. For though all lore was 
line 41879=>in  these latter days fallen  from its  fullness  of old, the  leechcraft of 
line 41880=>Gondor was still wise, and skilled in the healing of wound and hurt, and all 
line 41881=>such  sickness as east of  the Sea mortal men  were subject to. Save old age 
line 41882=>only. For that  they had  found no  cure; and indeed the span of their lives 
line 41883=>had now waned to little more than that of  other men, and those  among  them 
line 41884=>who passed the tale of  five score years with vigour were grown few, save in  
line 41885=>some houses of purer blood.  But now their art and  knowledge were  baffled; 
line 41886=>for there  were  many sick of a  malady that  would not  be healed; and  they 
line 41887=>called it the Black Shadow, for it came from the Nazgyl.  And those who were 
line 41888=>stricken with it fell slowly into an ever deeper  dream, and  then passed to 
line 41889=>silence and a deadly cold, and so died. And it seemed to  the tenders  of the 
line 41890=>sick that on the Halfling and  on the Lady of Rohan this malady lay heavily.  
line 41891=>Still  at whiles as  the  morning wore away  they would speak,  murmuring in 
line 41892=>their  dreams; and  the  watchers  listened  to all that  they said,  hoping 
line 41893=>perhaps  to learn something that  would help them to understand their hurts.  
line 41894=>But  soon they  began to fall down into the darkness, and as the sun  turned 
line 41895=>west a  grey shadow crept over  their faces. But Faramir burned with a fever  
line 41896=>that would not abate. 
line 41897=>     Gandalf  went  from one to the other full of care, and he was told  all 
line 41898=>that the watchers could hear. And so  the day passed, while the great battle 
line 41899=>outside went on with shifting  hopes and strange  tidings; and still Gandalf 
line 41900=>waited and watched and did not  go forth; till at last the red sunset filled 
