line 42235=>dared hope in the dark  days, when it seemed that the House of Eorl was sunk 
line 42236=>in honour less than  any shepherd's cot. And what of the king's esquire, the 
line 42237=>Halfling? Jomer, you shall make him a knight  of  the Riddermark, for he  is 
line 42238=>valiant!' 
line 42239=>     'He lies nearby  in this  House,  and I will go  to him,' said Gandalf.  
line 42240=>'Jomer  shall stay here for a while. But do  not  speak  yet of  war or woe, 
line 42241=>until you are made whole  again. Great gladness  it is to see you wake again  
line 42242=>to health and hope, so valiant a lady!' 
line 42243=>     'To health?' said  Jowyn. 'It  may  be so. At  least  while there is an 
line 42244=>empty saddle of some  fallen Rider that I can  fill, and there  are deeds to 
line 42245=>do. But to hope? I do not know.' 
line 42246=>     Gandalf and Pippin came to Merry's room, and there  they found  Aragorn 
line 42247=>standing by  the  bed.   'Poor  old Merry!' cried Pippin, and  he ran to  the 
line 42248=>bedside, for it seemed to  him that  his friend looked worse, and a greyness 
line 42249=>was in his face, as if a weight of years of sorrow  lay on him; and suddenly 
line 42250=>
line 42251=>####-a fear seized Pippin that Merry would die. 
line 42252=>     'Do not be afraid,'  said Aragorn. 'I came in  time, and  I have called 
line 42253=>him back. He  is weary now, and grieved, and  he has taken a hurt  like  the 
line 42254=>Lady Jowyn, daring  to  smite  that deadly  thing. But  these  evils can  be 
line 42255=>amended, so strong and gay a sp irit is in him. His grief he will not forget; 
line 42256=>but it will not darken his heart, it will teach him wisdom.' 
line 42257=>     Then Aragorn laid his hand on Merry's head, and passing his hand gently  
line 42258=>through the brown curls, he touched the eyelids, and called him by name. And 
line 42259=>when  the fragrance  of athelas stole through the room, like  the  scent  of 
line 42260=>orchards, and of heather in the sunshine full of bees, suddenly Merry awoke,  
line 42261=>and he said: 
line 42262=>     'I am hungry. What is the time?' 
line 42263=>     'Past supper -time  now,' said Pippin; 'though I daresay  I could  bring 
line 42264=>you something, if they will let me.' 
line 42265=>     'They will indeed,' said Gandalf. 'And anything else that this Rider of 
line 42266=>Rohan  may desire, if it can be found in Minas Tirith, where  his name is in 
line 42267=>honour.' 
line 42268=>     'Good!' said Merry.  'Then I  would  like supper first, and after that a  
line 42269=>pipe.' At that his face clouded. 'No, not a pipe.  I don't think I'll  smoke 
line 42270=>again.' 
line 42271=>     'Why not?' said Pippin. 
line 42272=>     'Well,' answered Merry slowly. 'He is dead. It  has brought it all back  
line 42273=>to me.  He said he was sorry he  had never had a chance of talking herb-lore 
line 42274=>with me. Almost the last thing he ever said. I shan't ever be able to  smoke 
line 42275=>again without  thinking of  him, and  that day, Pippin, when he  rode up  to 
line 42276=>Isengard and was so polite.' 
line 42277=>     'Smoke then, and  think of  him!' said  Aragorn.  'For he  was a gentle 
line 42278=>heart and a great king and kept his oaths; and he rose out of the shadows to 
line 42279=>a last fair  morning.  Though your  service to him was brief, it should be a  
line 42280=>memory glad and honourable to the end of your days.' 
line 42281=>     Merry  smiled. 'Well then,' he said, 'if  Strider will  provide what is 
line 42282=>needed, I will smoke and think. I had some of Saruman's best in my pack, but 
line 42283=>what became of it in the battle, I am sure I don't know.' 
line 42284=>     'Master  Meriadoc,'  said  Aragorn,  'if  you  think that  I have passed 
line 42285=>through the  mountains and the realm of Gondor with  fire and sword to bring 
line 42286=>herbs to a  careless soldier who throws away his gear,  you are mistaken. If 
line 42287=>your pack has not been found, then you must send for the herb-master of this 
line 42288=>
line 42289=>####-House. And he will tell you that he  did  not know that the herb  you desire 
line 42290=>had  any  virtues, but  that it is  called westmansweed by  the vulgar,  and 
line 42291=>galenas by the  noble,  and  other names  in other tongues more learned, and 
line 42292=>after adding  a few half-forgotten  rhymes that he  does not understand,  he 
line 42293=>will regretfully inform  you  that there is none in the  House, and  he will 
line 42294=>leave you  to reflect  on  the history of tongues.  And so now must I. For I 
line 42295=>have not slept in such a bed as this, since I rode from Dunharrow, nor eaten 
line 42296=>since the dark before dawn.' 
line 42297=>     Merry seized his hand and kissed it. 'I am frightfully sorry,' he said. 
line 42298=>'Go at once!  Ever since that night at Bree we have been  a nuisance to you. 
line 42299=>But it is the way of my people to use light words at such times and say less 
line 42300=>than they mean. We fear to say too much. It robs us of the  right words when  
line 42301=>a jest is out of place.' 
line 42302=>     'I  know that well, or I would not deal with you in the same way ' said 
line 42303=>Aragorn. 'May the Shire live for ever unwithered!' And kissing Merry he went 
line 42304=>out, and Gandalf went with him.  
line 42305=>     Pippin  remained behind. 'Was  there  ever any one like him?'  he said. 
line 42306=>'Except Gandalf, of course. I think they  must be related. My dear ass, your 
line 42307=>pack is lying by your bed, and you  had  it on your back when I  met you. He 
line 42308=>saw it all the time, of course. And anyway I have some stuff of my own. Come 
line 42309=>on now! Longbottom Leaf it is.  Fill up while I run and see about some food. 
line 42310=>And  then let's be  easy for  a bit. Dear me!  We Tooks  and Brandybucks, we 
line 42311=>can't live long on the heights.' 
line 42312=>     'No,' said Merry. 'I can't. Not yet, at any rate. But at least, Pippin, 
line 42313=>we can now see them, and honour them. It is best to  love first what you are 
line 42314=>fitted to love, I suppose: you must start somewhere and have some roots, and 
line 42315=>the soil of the Shire is deep. Still there are things deeper and higher; and 
line 42316=>not a gaffer could tend his garden  in  what he calls  peace  but  for them, 
line 42317=>whether  he knows about them or not.  I am  glad that   I know about them,  a  
line 42318=>little. But I don't know why I am talking like this. Where is that leaf? And 
line 42319=>get my pipe out of my pack, if it isn't broken.' 
line 42320=>     Aragorn and  Gandalf went now to the  Warden of the  Houses of Healing, 
line 42321=>and they counselled him that Faramir and Jowyn should remain there and still 
line 42322=>be tended with care for many days. 
line 42323=>     'The Lady Jowyn,' said Aragorn, 'will wish soon to rise and depart; but 
line 42324=>she should not be  permitted to do so,  if you  can in any way restrain her, 
line 42325=>until at least ten days be passed.' 
line 42326=>
line 42327=>####-     'As for Faramir,' said Gandalf, 'he must soon  learn that his father is 
line 42328=>dead. But the full  tale of the  madness  of Denethor should  not be told to 
