line 42360=> 
line 42361=> 
line 42362=>     The morning came after  the  day of battle, and it was fair with  light 
line 42363=>clouds and the wind turning  westward. Legolas and  Gimli were early abroad, 
line 42364=>and  they  begged leave to go up  into the City; for  they were eager to see 
line 42365=>Merry and Pippin. 
line 42366=>     'It is good to learn that they are still alive,' said Gimli;  'for they 
line 42367=>cost us great pains in our march over Rohan, and I would not have such pains 
line 42368=>all wasted.' 
line 42369=>     Together the  Elf and the Dwarf entered Minas Tirith, and folk that saw 
line 42370=>them  pass  marvelled to see such companions; for Legolas was fair  of  face 
line 42371=>beyond the measure of Men, and  he sang an elven-song in a clear voice as he 
line 42372=>walked in the morning; but Gimli stalked  beside him, stroking his beard and 
line 42373=>staring about him. 
line 42374=>     'There is  some  good  stone-work here,'  he said as he  looked  a t the 
line 42375=>walls;  'but also  some that is  less good, and  the streets could be better  
line 42376=>contrived. When Aragorn comes into his own, I shall offer him the service of 
line 42377=>stonewrights of the Mountain, and we will make this a town to be proud of.' 
line 42378=>     'They need more gardens,' said Legolas. 'The houses are dead, and there 
line 42379=>is too little  here that grows and is glad.  If Aragorn comes into his  own, 
line 42380=>the people of the Wood shall bring him birds that sing and trees that do not 
line 42381=>die.' 
line 42382=>     At  length they came to the Prince  Imrahil, and  Legolas  looked at him 
line 42383=>and bowed  low; for he  saw that here  indeed was one who had elven-blood in 
line 42384=>his veins. 'Hail, lord!' he said.  'It is long since the people  of Nimrodel 
line 42385=>left the woodlands of Lurien, and yet still one may see that  no t all sailed 
line 42386=>from Amroth's haven west over water.' 
line 42387=>     'So it is said in the lore of my land,' said the Prince; 'yet never has 
line 42388=>one of the fair folk been seen there for years beyond count. And I marvel to 
line 42389=>see one here now in the midst of sorrow and war. What do you seek?' 
line 42390=>     'I  am  one of the Nine  Companions  who  set  out with Mithrandir from 
line 42391=>Imladris, said Legolas and with  this Dwarf, my friend, I came with the Lord 
line 42392=>Aragorn. But now we wish to see  our friends. Meriadoc and Peregrin, who are 
line 42393=>in your keeping, we are told.' 
line 42394=>     'You  will  find them  in  the Houses of Healing, and  I will  lead you  
line 42395=>
line 42396=>####-thither,' said Imrahil. 
line 42397=>     'It will be  enough if you send one to guide  us,  lord,' said Legolas.  
line 42398=>'For Aragorn sends this message to you. He does not wish  to  enter the City 
line 42399=>again at this  time. Yet there is need  for the captains to hold  council at 
line 42400=>once, and he prays that you and Jomer of  Rohan will come down to his tents,  
line 42401=>as soon as may be. Mithrandir is already there.' 
line 42402=>     'We will come,' said Imrahil; and they parted with courteous words. 
line 42403=>     'That  is  a  fair lord and a great captain of men,'  said Legolas. 'If 
line 42404=>Gondor has such men still in these  days of fading, great must have been its 
line 42405=>glory in the days of its rising.' 
line 42406=>     'And doubtless the good stone-work is the older and  was wrought in the 
line 42407=>first building,' said  Gimli. 'It is ever so with the things that Men begin: 
line 42408=>there  is a frost  in Spring, or a blight in Summer, and they  fail of their 
line 42409=>promise.' 
line 42410=>     'Yet seldom do they fail of their seed,' said  Legolas. 'And that  will 
line 42411=>lie in the dust and rot to spring up again in times and places unlooked-for. 
line 42412=>The deeds of Men will outlast us, Gimli.' 
line 42413=>     'And yet come to naught in the end but might-have-beens, I guess,' said 
line 42414=>the Dwarf. 
line 42415=>     'To that the Elves know not the answer,' said Legolas.  
line 42416=>     With that the servant of the  Prince came and led them to the Houses of 
line 42417=>Healing; and there they found their friends in the garden, and their meeting 
line 42418=>was a merry one.  For a while  they walked and talked, rejoicing for a brief 
