line 42574=>run like fire in the dark. 
line 42575=>     'And  that  is near the end  of our tale.  For  during  that evening and 
line 42576=>night many ships were  made ready and  manned; and in the morning the  fleet 
line 42577=>set forth. Long  past it now seems,  yet it was but the morn of  the day ere 
line 42578=>yesterday, the  sixth  since  we rode  from Dunharrow. But still Aragorn was 
line 42579=>driven by fear that time was too short. 
line 42580=>     '  "It is forty leagues and  two from Pelargir to  the  landings at the 
line 42581=>Harlond,"  he  said.  "Yet to  the  Harlond we must  come tomorrow  or  fail  
line 42582=>utterly." 
line 42583=>     'The oars were now wielded by free men, and manfully they laboured; yet 
line 42584=>slowly we passed up  the Great River, for  we strove against its stream, and 
line 42585=>
line 42586=>####-though that is not swift down in  the South,  we had no help  of wind. Heavy 
line 42587=>would my heart have been, for all our victory at the  havens, if Legolas had 
line 42588=>not laughed suddenly. 
line 42589=>     ' "Up  with your beard, Durin's son! " he said. "For thus is it spoken: 
line 42590=>Oft hope is  born, when  all is forlorn." But what hope  he saw from afar he 
line 42591=>would  not tell. When  night came it  did  but deepen  the darkness, and our 
line 42592=>hearts were  hot, for away in  the North we saw a red glow under the  cloud,  
line 42593=>and Aragorn said: "Minas Tirith is burning." 
line 42594=>     'But at midnight hope was indeed born anew. Sea -crafty men of the Ethir  
line 42595=>gazing southward spoke  of a change coming  with a fresh  wind from the Sea. 
line 42596=>Long  ere day the masted ships  hoisted sail; and our speed grew, until dawn 
line 42597=>whitened the foam at our prows. And so it was, as  you know, that we came in 
line 42598=>the third  hour of the morning with a fair wind and the Sun unveiled, and we 
line 42599=>unfurled the great standard in battle. It was a great  day and a great hour, 
line 42600=>whatever may come after.' 
line 42601=>     'Follow what may, great deeds are not lessened in worth,' said Legolas.  
line 42602=>'Great  deed was the riding of  the Paths  of the Dead, and great  it  shall 
line 42603=>remain, though none be left  in Gondor to sing of it in the days that are to 
line 42604=>come.' 
line 42605=>     'And  that may well befall,' said Gimli.  'For the faces of Aragorn and 
line 42606=>Gandalf are grave. Much I  wonder what counsels they are taking in the tents 
line 42607=>there below. For my part, like Merry, I wish that with our victory  the  war 
line 42608=>was now over.  Yet whatever is still to do, I hope to have a part in it, for  
line 42609=>the honour of the folk of the Lonely Mountain.' 
line 42610=>     'And I for the folk of the Great Wood,' said Legolas, 'and for the love 
line 42611=>of the Lord of the White Tree.' 
line 42612=>     Then the companions fell silent, but a while they sat there in the high 
line 42613=>place, each busy with his own thoughts, while the Captains debated. 
line 42614=>     When the Prince Imrahil had parted  from Legolas and Gimli, at once  he 
