line 42617=>where King Thjoden had  fallen.  And there they took  counsel together  with 
line 42618=>Gandalf and Aragorn and the sons of Elrond. 
line 42619=>     'My lords,' said Gandalf, 'listen to the words of the Steward of Gondor  
line 42620=>before he died: You may triumph on the fields of the Pelennor for a day, but 
line 42621=>against the Power that has  now arisen there is no victory. I do not bid you  
line 42622=>despair, as he did, but to ponder the truth in these words. 
line 42623=>
line 42624=>####-     'The  Stones of Seeing do  not lie, and not even  the Lord of Barad-dyr 
line 42625=>can make  them do so. He can, maybe, by his will choose what things shall be 
line 42626=>seen by weaker minds, or cause them to mistake the meaning of what they see. 
line 42627=>Nonetheless it cannot be doubted that when Denethor saw great forces arrayed 
line 42628=>against him  in Mordor,  and more  still being gathered, he  saw  that which 
line 42629=>truly is. 
line 42630=>     'Hardly has our strength sufficed to beat off the first  grea t assault. 
line 42631=>The next will be greater.  This war  then is without final hope, as Denethor  
line 42632=>perceived. Victory  cannot be  achieved by  arms, whether  you sit  here  to 
line 42633=>endure siege after siege, or  march  out to be overwhelmed beyond the River. 
line 42634=>You  have  only a  choice  of  evils;  and prudence  would  counsel  you  to 
line 42635=>strengthen such strong places as you have, and there await the onset; for so 
line 42636=>shall the time before your end be made a little longer.' 
line 42637=>     'Then you would have  us retreat to Minas Tirith, or Dol  Amroth, or to 
line 42638=>Dunharrow, and  there sit  like children on  sand-castles when  the tide  is 
line 42639=>flowing?' said Imrahil. 
line 42640=>     'That would  be no new  counsel,' said Gandalf. 'Have you not done this 
line 42641=>and  little more in all the  days of Denethor?  But no! I sa id this would be 
line 42642=>prudent. I do not counsel prudence. I said  victory could not be achieved by 
line 42643=>arms. I still hope for victory, but not by arms.  For into the midst  of all 
line 42644=>these policies comes the Ring of Power, the foundation of Barad-dyr, and the 
line 42645=>hope of Sauron. 
line 42646=>     'Concerning  this  thing,  my  lords, you now  all know enough for  the 
line 42647=>understanding of our plight, and of  Sauron's. If he regains it, your valour 
line 42648=>is  vain, and his victory will be swift and complete: so  complete that none 
line 42649=>can foresee the  end of it while this world lasts. If it is destroyed,  then 
line 42650=>he will fall; and his  fall will be so low that none can foresee his arising 
line 42651=>ever again. For he will lose the best part of the  strength  that was native 
line 42652=>to him in his beginning, and all that was made or begun with that power will  
line 42653=>crumble, and he will  be maimed  for ever, becoming a mere  spirit of malice 
line 42654=>that  gnaws itself in the shadows, but cannot again grow  or take shape. And 
line 42655=>so a great evil of this world will be removed. 
line 42656=>     'Other evils there are  that may come;  for  Sauron  is  himself  but a  
line 42657=>servant or emissary.  Yet it is  not our part to master all the tides of the 
line 42658=>world, but to do what is in us for the succour of those years wherein we are 
line 42659=>set, uprooting the  evil in the fields that we know, so  that those who live 
line 42660=>after may have clean earth to till. What weather they shall have is not ours 
line 42661=>
line 42662=>####-to rule. 
line 42663=>     'Now Sauron knows all this, and he knows that this precious thing which 
line 42664=>he lost has been found again; but he does not yet know where it is, or so we 
line 42665=>hope. And therefore he is now  in great doubt. For  if we  have  found  this 
line 42666=>thing, there are some among us with strength enough to wield it. That too he 
line 42667=>knows. For do I not guess rightly, Aragorn, that you have shown  yourself to 
line 42668=>him in the Stone of Orthanc?' 
line 42669=>     'I did so  ere I rode from the Hornburg,' answered  Aragorn. 'I  deemed 
line 42670=>that the time was ripe, and that the  Stone had  come to me  for just such a  
line 42671=>purpose. It was  then ten  days since the Ring-bearer went east from Rauros,  
line 42672=>and the Eye of Sauron, I thought, should be drawn out from his own land. Too 
line 42673=>seldom has he been challenged since he  returned to his  Tower. Though if  I 
line 42674=>had foreseen how swift would be his onset in answer, maybe I should not have 
line 42675=>dared to show myself. Bare time was given me to come to your aid.' 
line 42676=>     'But how is  this?' asked Jomer. 'All is  vain, you say,  if he has the 
line 42677=>Ring. Why should he think it not vain to assail us, if we have it?' 
line 42678=>     'He is not yet sure,' said Gandalf, 'and  he has not built up his power 
line 42679=>by waiting until his enemies are secure,  as we have done. Also we could not  
line 42680=>learn how to wield the  full  power all in a day. Indeed it can be used only 
line 42681=>by one master alone, not by many; and he will look for a time of strife, ere 
line 42682=>one  of the great among us makes himself master and puts down the others. In 
line 42683=>that time the Ring might aid him, if he were sudden. 
line 42684=>     'He  is  watching. He sees  much and hears much.  His Nazgyl  are still 
line 42685=>abroad. They passed over this field ere the sunrise, though few of the  weary 
line 42686=>and sleeping were aware of them. He studies the signs: the Sword that robbed 
line 42687=>him of his treasure re-made; the winds of fortune turning in our favour, and 
line 42688=>the defeat unlooked-for of his first assault the fall of his great Captain. 
line 42689=>     'His doubt will  be  growing, even  as we  speak here. His  Eye is  now 
line 42690=>straining towards us,  blind  almost to all  else that is moving. So we must 
line 42691=>keep it. Therein  lies all our hope. This, then, is my  counsel. We have not 
line 42692=>the Ring. In wisdom or  great folly it has been sent away  to be  destroyed, 
line 42693=>lest it destroy  us. Without it we  cannot by force defeat his force. But we 
line 42694=>must  at all  costs  keep his Eye  from his true  peril. We  cannot  achieve 
line 42695=>victory  by  arms, but by arms we can give the Ring-bearer his  only chance, 
line 42696=>frail though it be. 
line 42697=>     'As Aragorn has begun, so  we must go  on. We must push  Sauron  to his 
line 42698=>last throw. We must call out his hidden strength, so that he shall empty his 
line 42699=>
line 42700=>####-land. We must march out to meet him at  once.  We  must  make ourselves  the 
line 42701=>bait, though his jaws  should close  on us. He will take that bait,  in hope 
line 42702=>and in  greed, for he will think that in  such rashness he sees the pride of 
line 42703=>the new Ringlord: and he will say: "So!  he pushes out his neck too soon and 
line 42704=>too far. Let him come on, and behold I will have him in a trap from which he 
