line 42804=>     Two days later the army of the West was all assembled on the  Pelennor.  
line 42805=>The host of Orcs and Easterlings had turned back out of Anurien, but harried 
line 42806=>and scattered by the Rohirrim they had  broken and fled with little fighting 
line 42807=>towards Cair  Andros;  and with  that  threat  destroyed  and  new  strength 
line 42808=>arriving out of the South the City  was as well  manned  as might be. Scouts 
line 42809=>reported  that  no  enemies remained  upon the  roads  east  as  far  as the 
line 42810=>Cross-roads of the Fallen King. All now was ready for the last throw.  
line 42811=>     Legolas and Gimli were to ride again together in the company of Aragorn 
line 42812=>and Gandalf, who went in the  van with the DÂ®nedain  and the sons of Elrond. 
line 42813=>But Merry to his shame was not to go with them. 
line 42814=>     'You are  not fit for  such a  journey,' said  Aragorn. 'But  do not be 
line 42815=>ashamed.  If  you do no  more  in  this  war, you have already earned  great 
line 42816=>honour. Peregrin shall go and represent the Shirefolk; and do not grudge him 
line 42817=>his chance of peril, for  though  he has done as well as his fortune allowed 
line 42818=>him, he has yet to match your deed. But in truth all now are in like danger. 
line 42819=>Though it may be our part to  find bitter end before the  Gate of Mordor, if 
line 42820=>we do so,  then you will come also to a last  stand, either here or wherever  
line 42821=>the black tide overtakes you. Farewell!' 
line 42822=>     And  so  despondently Merry now  stood and watched the mustering of the 
line 42823=>army. Bergil was with him, and  he  also was downcast; for his father was to 
line 42824=>march leading a company of the  Men  of the City:  he could not  rejoin  the 
line 42825=>Guard until his case was judged. In that same company Pippin was also to go, 
line 42826=>as a soldier of Gondor. Merry could see him not far off, a small but upright 
line 42827=>figure among the tall men of Minas Tirith. 
line 42828=>     At last the  trumpets  rang and the army began to move. Troop by troop, 
line 42829=>and company by company,  they wheeled and went off  eastward. And long 
line 42830=>after 
line 42831=>they had passed away out of sight down the great road to the Causeway, Merry 
line 42832=>stood there. The  last glint of the morning sun  on  spear and helm twinkled 
line 42833=>and was lost, and still he remained with bowed head and heavy heart, feeling 
line 42834=>friendless  and  alone. Everyone  that  he cared for had  gone away into the 
line 42835=>gloom  that  hung over the distant eastern sky;  and little  hope at all was 
line 42836=>left in his heart that he wou ld ever see any of them again. 
line 42837=>
line 42838=>####-     As if recalled by his mood of despair,  the  pain in his arm  returned, 
line 42839=>and he felt weak and old, and the sunlight seemed thin. He was roused by the 
line 42840=>touch of Bergil's hand. 
line 42841=>     'Come, Master Perian!' said the lad. 'You are still  in pain, I see.  I 
line 42842=>will help you back to the Healers. But do not fear! They will come back. The 
line 42843=>Men  of  Minas Tirith  will never be overcome. And  now they  have the  Lord 
line 42844=>Elfstone, and Beregond of the Guard too.' 
line 42845=>     Ere  noon the army  came  to  Osgiliath.  There  all  the  workers  and 
line 42846=>craftsmen  that  could  be  spared were  busy. Some were  strengthening  the 
line 42847=>ferries and boat-bridges that the  enemy had made and in part destroyed when 
line 42848=>they fled; some  gathered  stores and booty; and others  on the eastern side 
line 42849=>across the River were throwing up hasty works of defence. 
line 42850=>     The vanguard passed on through the ruins  of  Old Gondor, and  over the 
line 42851=>wide River, and  on up the long straight road that in the high days had been 
line 42852=>made to run  from the fair  Tower of the Sun to the tall  Tower of the Moon,  
line 42853=>which now was Minas Morgul in its accursed vale. Five miles beyond Osgiliath 
line 42854=>they halted, ending their first day's march. 
line 42855=>     But  the  horsemen  pressed  on  and  ere  evening  they  came  to  the 
line 42856=>Cross-roads and the great ring of trees, and all was silent. No sign of  any 
line 42857=>enemy  had they seen, no cry or  call had been heard, no shaft had sped from 
line 42858=>rock or  thicket by the  way, yet  ever as they went  forward  they felt the 
line 42859=>watchfulness  of  the land  increase. Tree and stone,  blade  and leaf  were 
line 42860=>listening. The darkness had been dispelled, and far away westward sunset was 
line 42861=>on the  Vale of  Anduin, and the white peaks of the mountains blushed in the  
line 42862=>blue air; but a shadow and a gloom brooded upon the Ephel DÂ®ath. 
line 42863=>     Then Aragorn set trumpeters at each of the four roads that ran into the 
line 42864=>ring  of trees,  and they blew a great fanfare, and the heralds cried aloud: 
line 42865=>'The Lords  of Gondor have returned  and all this  land  that is theirs they 
line 42866=>take back.'  The  hideous orc-head that  was  set upon the carven figure was 
line 42867=>cast down and  broken in pieces, and the old king's head was raised  and set 
line 42868=>in its place once more, still crowned with white and golden flowers: and men 
line 42869=>laboured  to wash and pare away all the foul scrawls that orcs  had put upon  
line 42870=>the stone. 
line 42871=>     Now in their debate  some had counselled that Minas Morgul should first  
line 42872=>be assailed, and if  they  might take  it,  it should  be utterly destroyed. 
line 42873=>'And, maybe,'  said Imrahil, 'the road that leads thence to  the pass  above 
line 42874=>will prove  an easier way of  assault upon the Dark Lord  than  his northern 
line 42875=>
line 42876=>####-gate.' 
line 42877=>     But against this Gandalf had spoken urgently, because of  the evil that 
line 42878=>dwelt in the valley, where the minds of living men would turn to madness and 
line 42879=>horror, and because also of the  news  that Faramir had brought.  For if the 
line 42880=>Ring-bearer had indeed attempted that  way,  then above  all they should not 
line 42881=>draw the Eye of Mordor thither.  So the next day when the main host came up, 
line 42882=>they set a strong guard upon the Cross-roads to make some defence, if Mordor  
