line 42884=>the South. For that guard  they chose mostly archers  who knew  the ways  of 
line 42885=>Ithilien and would lie hid in the woods and slopes about the meeting  of the 
line 42886=>ways. But Gandalf and Aragorn rode with the  vanguard  to  the  entrance  of 
line 42887=>Morgul Vale and looked on the evil city. 
line 42888=>     It was dark and  lifeless; for the Orcs and lesser creatures of  Mordor  
line 42889=>that  had  dwelt  there had been destroyed in  battle,  and the  Nazgyl were 
line 42890=>abroad. Yet the air of the valley was heavy  with fear and enmity. Then they 
line 42891=>broke the evil bridge and set red flames in the noisome fields and departed. 
line 42892=>     The  day  after, being the  third day  since they  set  out  from Minas 
line 42893=>Tirith, the army  began its  northward  march along  the  road.  It was some 
line 42894=>hundred  miles by that  way  from the  Cross-roads to the Morannon, and what 
line 42895=>might befall  them before they  came so  far  none knew They went openly but 
line 42896=>heedfully, with mounted scouts before them  on the road, and others on  foot 
line 42897=>upon either  side, especially  on  the  eastward flank;  for there lay  dark 
line 42898=>thickets, and  a tumbled  land of rocky ghylls  and crags,  behind which the 
line 42899=>long  grim slopes of the Ephel DÂ®ath clambered up. The weather of  the world 
line 42900=>remained fair and the wind held in the west, but nothing could waft away the 
line 42901=>glooms  and the sad  mists  that clung  about  the Mountains of  Shadow; and 
line 42902=>behind them at whiles great smokes would arise and hover in the upper winds.  
line 42903=>     Ever and anon Gandalf let blow the trumpets, and the heralds would cry:  
line 42904=>"The  Lords of Gondor are come! Let  all leave this land  or yield them up!' 
line 42905=>But Imrahil said: 'Say not  The Lords of Gondor.  Say The King Elessar.  For 
line 42906=>that is true, even though he has  not yet  sat  upon the throne; and it will 
line 42907=>give the Enemy more thought, if  the  heralds use that name.' And thereafter  
line 42908=>thrice a day the heralds proclaimed the coming of the King Elessar. But none 
line 42909=>answered the challenge. 
line 42910=>     Nonetheless, though they marched in seeming  peace,  the hearts  of all 
line 42911=>the army, from the highest to the lowest, were downcast, and with every mile 
line 42912=>that they went  north foreboding  of evil grew heavier  on them. It was near 
line 42913=>
line 42914=>####-the  end of the second day of their  march  from  the Cross-roads  that they 
line 42915=>first met any offer  of battle.  For a strong force  of Orcs and Easterlings 
line 42916=>attempted to  take their leading companies in an ambush; and that was in the 
line 42917=>very place where Faramir  had waylaid the men of Harad, and the road went in 
line 42918=>a deep cutting through an out-thrust of the eastward hills. But the Captains 
line 42919=>of the West were well warned by their scouts, skilled men from Henneth 
line 42920=>Annyn 
line 42921=>led by Mablung; and so the ambush was itself trapped. For horsemen went 
line 42922=>wide 
line 42923=>about westward and  came  up on the flank of  the enemy and from behind, and 
line 42924=>they were destroyed or driven east into the hills. 
line 42925=>     But  the victory did  little to  enhearten the captains.  'It  is but a  
line 42926=>feint,' said Aragorn; 'and its chief purpose, I  deem, was  rather to draw us 
line 42927=>on by a false guess of our Enemy's weakness than to  do us much hurt,  yet.' 
line 42928=>And from that evening onward the Nazgyl came and followed every move  of 
line 42929=>the 
line 42930=>army. They still  flew  high and out  of sight of all  save Legolas, and  yet 
line 42931=>their presence could  be felt, as a deepening of shadow and a dimming of the  
line 42932=>sun; and though the Ringwraiths did not  yet stoop low upon  their foes  and  
line 42933=>were silent, uttering no cry, the dread of them could not be shaken off. 
line 42934=>     So time and  the hopeless  journey wore away. Upon the fourth day  from  
line 42935=>the Cross-roads and the sixth from Minas Tirith they came at last to the end 
line 42936=>of  the living lands,  and began to pass into the desolation that lay before 
line 42937=>the gates of the Pass of Cirith Gorgor; and  they could  descry the  marshes 
line 42938=>and the desert that  stretched north and west to  the Emyn Muil. So desolate 
line 42939=>were those places and so  deep  the horror that lay on them that some of the 
line 42940=>host were unmanned, and they could neither walk nor ride further north. 
line 42941=>     Aragorn looked  at them,  and there was pity  in his  eyes  rather than 
line 42942=>wrath;  for  these were young men from Rohan,  from Westfold  far  away,  or  
line 42943=>husbandmen  from  Lossarnach, and to them Mordor had been  from childhood  
line 42944=>a 
line 42945=>name  of evil,  and yet  unreal, a  legend that had no part in  their simple 
line 42946=>life; and now  they walked like men in a  hideous dream made true,  and they 
line 42947=>understood not this war nor why fate should lead them to such a pass.  
line 42948=>     'Go!' said Aragorn. 'But  keep what honour you may, and do not run! And 
line 42949=>there is a task which you may attempt and so be not wholly shamed. Take your 
line 42950=>way  south-west till you come to Cair Andros, and  if that is still  held by  
line 42951=>
line 42952=>####-enemies, as I think, then re-take it, if you can; and hold it to the last in 
line 42953=>defence of Gondor and Rohan!' 
line 42954=>     Then some being shamed by  his mercy  overcame their fear and  went on, 
line 42955=>and the others took new hope, hearing of a manful  deed within their measure 
line 42956=>that  they  could turn to, and they  departed.  And so,  since many men  had 
line 42957=>already  been left  at the Cross-roads,  it was with less than six thousands 
line 42958=>that the Captains of the West came at last  to challenge the  Black Gate and 
line 42959=>the might of Mordor. 
line 42960=>     They advanced  now slowly, expecting at every hour some answer to their 
line 42961=>challenge, and they drew together, since it was but waste of men to send out 
line 42962=>scouts or small parties from the main host. At nightfall of the fifth day of 
line 42963=>the march from Morgul Vale they made their last camp, and set fires about it  
line 42964=>of such dead wood and  heath as they  could find. They  passed the hours  of 
line 42965=>night  in  wakefulness  and they were aware  of many things  half-seen  that 
line 42966=>walked and prowled all about them, and they heard the howling of wolves. The 
line 42967=>wind had  died  and all  the air  seemed still. They  could see  little, for  
line 42968=>though it was cloudless and the waxing moon was four nights  old, there were 
line 42969=>smokes  and  fumes  that rose  out of the earth and  the white  crescent was 
line 42970=>shrouded in the mists of Mordor. 
line 42971=>     It grew cold. As morning came the wind bega n to stir again,  but now it 
line 42972=>came from  the North,  and  soon it  freshened to a  rising breeze. All  the 
line 42973=>night-walkers were gone, and the land seemed empty. North amid their 
line 42974=>noisome 
line 42975=>pits lay the first of the great heaps and hills of slag and broken  rock and 
line 42976=>blasted earth,  the vomit of the maggot-folk of Mordor;  but south  and  now 
line 42977=>near loomed the great rampart of Cirith Gorgor, and the Black Gate amidmost, 
line 42978=>and the two Towers of the Teeth tall and dark upon either side. For in their 
line 42979=>last march  the Capta ins had turned away from the old road as it  bent east,  
line 42980=>and avoided the peril of the lurking hills, and so now they were approaching 
line 42981=>the Morannon from the north-west, even as Frodo had done. 
line 42982=>     The two  vast iron doors of the Black Gate under its frowning arch were 
line 42983=>fast closed. Upon the battlement nothing could be seen. All was  silent  but 
line 42984=>watchful. They  were come to the last end of their folly, and stood  forlorn 
line 42985=>and chill in the grey light of early day before towers and walls which their 
line 42986=>army could not assault with hope, not even if it had brought thither engines 
line 42987=>of great power, and  the Enemy had no more force than would suffice  for the 
line 42988=>manning of  the gate  and wall alone. Yet  they  knew that all the hills and 
line 42989=>
line 42990=>####-rocks  about  the Morannon  were filled with hidden  foes, and  the  shadowy 
line 42991=>defile beyond was bored and tunnelled  by teeming broods of evil things. And 
line 42992=>as they stood they saw all the Nazgyl gathered together, hovering  above the 
line 42993=>Towers of the Teeth like vultures; and they knew that they were watched. But 
line 42994=>still the Enemy made no sign. 
line 42995=>     No  choice was left them but to play their part  to  its end. Therefore 
line 42996=>Aragorn now set the host in such array as could  best be contrived; and they  
line 42997=>were drawn up on two great  hills of blasted stone and earth  that orcs  had 
line 42998=>piled in years of labour. Before them towards Mordor lay like a moat a great 
line 42999=>mire  of  reeking  mud and foul-smelling  pools. When all  was  ordered, the 
line 43000=>Captains rode  forth towards the Black Gate with  a great  guard of horsemen 
line 43001=>and  the  banner and heralds  and  trumpeters.  There  was Gandalf as  chief 
line 43002=>herald,  and  Aragorn  with  the sons of Elrond,  and  Jomer  of Rohan,  and 
line 43003=>Imrahil; and Legolas and Gimli and Peregrin were bidden to  go also, so that 
line 43004=>all the enemies of Mordor should have a witness. 
line 43005=>     They came within cry of the Morannon, and unfurled the banner, and blew 
line 43006=>upon their trumpets; and the heralds stood out and sent their voices up over  
line 43007=>the battlement of Mordor. 
line 43008=>     'Come forth!'  they cried. 'Let the Lord of the Black   Land come forth!  
line 43009=>Justice shall be done upon  him. For wrongfully he  has made war upon Gondor  
line 43010=>and  wrested its lands. Therefore the King  of Gondor demands that he should 
line 43011=>atone for his evils, and depart then for ever. Come forth!' 
line 43012=>     There was  a long  silence, and from wall and gate no cry or sound  was 
line 43013=>heard in  answer. But Sauron had already laid his plans,  and he had a  mind  
line 43014=>first to play these mice cruelly before he struck to kill.  So  it was that, 
line 43015=>even  as  the  Captains were about to  turn  away, the  silence  was  broken 
line 43016=>suddenly.  There came  a  long rolling  of great  drums like thunder in  the 
line 43017=>mountains,  and  then  a  braying  of horns that  shook the very  stones and 
line 43018=>stunned men's ears.  And thereupon the  middle  door  of the Black Gate  was 
line 43019=>thrown open with a great clang, and out of it there came an embassy from the 
line 43020=>Dark Tower. 
line 43021=>     At its  head there rode a  tall  and evil  shape, mounted  upon a black  
line 43022=>horse, if  horse it was;  for it was huge  and hideous,  and its face was  a  
line 43023=>frightful mask, more like a skull than a living head,  and in the sockets of 
line 43024=>its eyes and in its nostrils there burned a flame. The  rider was robed  all 
line 43025=>in  black, and black was his lofty helm;  yet this  was  no Ringwraith but a  
line 43026=>living man. The Lieutenant of the Tower of Barad-dyr he was, and his name is 
line 43027=>
line 43028=>####-remembered  in no  tale; for he himself had forgotten it, and he said: 'I am 
line 43029=>the Mouth of Sauron.' But it is told that he was a renegade, who came of the 
line 43030=>race of those  that are named the Black  NÂ®menureans;  for   they established 
line 43031=>their dwellings in Middle-earth during the years of Sauron's domination, and 
line 43032=>they worshipped him, being enamoured  of evil knowledge.  And he entered the 
line 43033=>service of the  Dark Tower when it  first rose again,  and  because  of  his 
line 43034=>cunning  he grew  ever  higher  in the Lord's favour;  and  he learned  great 
line 43035=>sorcery, and knew much of the mind of Sauron; and he was more cruel than 
line 43036=>any 
line 43037=>orc. 
line 43038=>     He it was that now rode out, and with him came only a small company  of 
line 43039=>black-harnessed soldiery, a nd a  single  banner, black but  bearing on it in 
line 43040=>red the Evil Eye. Now halting a few paces before the Captains of the West he 
line 43041=>looked them up and down and laughed. 
line 43042=>     'Is  there  anyone in this rout  with authority to treat  with me?'  he 
line 43043=>asked. 'Or indeed with wit to  understand me? Not thou at least!' he mocked, 
line 43044=>turning to Aragorn with scorn. 'It needs more to make a king than a piece of 
line 43045=>elvish glass, or a rabble  such as this. Why, any brigand  of the  hills can 
line 43046=>show as good a following!' 
line 43047=>     Aragorn said naught in answer, but he took the other's eye and held it, 
line 43048=>and for a moment they strove thus; but soon, though Aragorn did not stir nor  
line 43049=>move hand to weapon, the other  quailed and  gave back as if menaced with  a  
line 43050=>blow. 'I am a herald and ambassador, a nd may not be assailed!' he cried. 
line 43051=>     'Where such  laws hold,'  said  Gandalf, 'it is  also  the  custom  for  
line 43052=>ambassadors to use less insolence. But  no one  has threatened you. You have 
line 43053=>naught to fear  from us,  until your errand is done. But unless  your master  
line 43054=>has  come  to new  wisdom, then with all  his servants  you will be in great 
line 43055=>peril.' 
line 43056=>     'So!' said the  Messenger. 'Then thou art the spokesman, old greybeard?  
line 43057=>Have we not  heard of  thee at whiles, and  of thy wanderings, ever hatching 
line 43058=>plots a nd mischief at a safe distance? But this time thou hast stuck out thy 
line 43059=>nose too far, Master Gandalf; and thou shalt see what comes to him  who sets 
line 43060=>his foolish webs before  the feet of Sauron the Great. I have  tokens that I 
line 43061=>was bidden  to show to thee -  to thee in especial, if thou shouldst dare to 
line 43062=>come.' He signed to  one of his guards, and he came forward bearing a bundle 
line 43063=>swathed in black cloths.  
line 43064=>     The Messenger put  these  aside, and there to the wonder and  dismay of 
line 43065=>
line 43066=>####-all the Captains he held up first the short sword that Sam had carried,  and 
line 43067=>next a grey  cloak with  an elven-brooch,  and last the coat of mithril-mail 
line 43068=>that  Frodo  had  worn  wrapped  in  his tattered garments. A blackness came  
