line 43160=>each 
line 43161=>hill a ring was made facing all ways, bristling with spear and sword. But in 
line 43162=>the front  towards Mordor  where the  first bitter  assault would come there 
line 43163=>stood the sons of Elrond on  the left with the DÂ®nedain  about them,  and on 
line 43164=>the right  the  Prince Imrahil with the men of Dol Amroth tall and fair, and 
line 43165=>picked men of the Tower of Guard. 
line 43166=>     The  wind blew, and the trumpets sang, and  arrows whined; but the  sun 
line 43167=>now  climbing  towards  the South was  veiled  in the reeks  of Mordor,  and 
line 43168=>through a threatening haze it  gleamed, remote, a  sullen red, as if it were 
line 43169=>the ending of the day, or the  end maybe of all the world of  light. And out 
line 43170=>of the gathering  mirk the Nazgyl came with. their  cold voices crying words 
line 43171=>of death; and then all hope was quenched. 
line 43172=>     Pippin had bowed crushed with horror when  he  heard Gandalf reject the  
line 43173=>terms and  doom Frodo  to the torment  of  the  Tower;  but  he had mastered  
line 43174=>himself, and now he  stood beside Beregond in the front  rank of Gondor with 
line 43175=>Imrahil's men. For  it seemed best to him to die  soon and  leave the bitter  
line 43176=>story of his life, since all was in ruin. 
line 43177=>     'I wish Merry  was here,' he  heard himself saying, and quick  thoughts 
line 43178=>raced  through his mind, even as he watched  the enemy  come charging to the 
line 43179=>
line 43180=>####-assault. 'Well, well, now at  any rate  I understand  poor Denethor a little 
line 43181=>better. We might die together, Merry and  I, and since die we must, why not? 
line 43182=>Well, as he is not  here, I hope he'll find an easier end. But now I must do 
line 43183=>my best.' 
line 43184=>     He drew  his sword and looked at it, and the intertwining shapes of red 
line 43185=>and gold; and  the flowing characters of NÂ®menor glinted like fire upon  the 
line 43186=>blade. 'This was made for just  such an hour,' he thought. 'If only  I could 
line 43187=>smite that foul Messenger with  it, then almost I should draw level with old 
line 43188=>Merry.  Well, I'll smite some of this beastly brood before the end. I wish I 
line 43189=>could see cool sunlight and green grass again!' 
line 43190=>     Then  even  as he thought  these things the  first assault crashed into 
line 43191=>them.  The orcs hindered by the  mires that  lay before the hills halted and 
line 43192=>poured their arrows into the defending ranks.  But through them  there  came 
line 43193=>striding  up,  roaring  like beasts, a  great company of  hill-trolls out of 
line 43194=>Gorgoroth. Taller and broader than Men they were, and they were clad only in 
line 43195=>close-fitting mesh of  horny  scales, or maybe  that was their hideous hide; 
line 43196=>but they bore round  bucklers  huge and black and wielded heavy  hammers  in 
line 43197=>their  knotted hands.  Reckless they sprang into the pools and waded across,  
line 43198=>bellowing as they came. Like a  storm they broke upon the line of the men of 
line 43199=>Gondor, and beat upon helm and head, and arm and shield as smiths hewing the 
line 43200=>hot bending iron. At Pippin's  side Beregond was stunned  and overborne, and 
line 43201=>he fell;  and the great  troll-chief that  smote  him  down  bent over  him, 
line 43202=>reaching out  a  clutching  claw; for  these  fell creatures would bite  the 
line 43203=>throats of those that they threw down. 
line 43204=>     Then  Pippin  stabbed  upwards, and  the  written blade of  Westernesse 
line 43205=>pierced through the hide and went deep into the vitals of the troll, and his 
line 43206=>black blood came gushing out. He toppled forward and came crashing down 
line 43207=>like 
line 43208=>a falling rock, burying those beneath him. Blackness and stench and crushing 
line 43209=>pain came upon Pippin, and his mind fell away into a great darkness. 
line 43210=>     'So  it ends  as I  guessed  it  would,' his  thought said,  even as it 
line 43211=>fluttered away; and  it laughed a little within him ere it fled, almost  gay 
line 43212=>it seemed to  be  casting off at last all doubt and care and  fear. And then 
line 43213=>even as  it  winged away into forgetfulness it heard voices, and they seemed 
line 43214=>to be crying in some forgotten world far above: 
line 43215=>     'The Eagles are coming! The Eagles are coming!' 
line 43216=>     For one moment more Pippin's thought hovered.  'Bilbo!'  it  said. 'But 
line 43217=>
line 43218=>####-no! That came in his tale, long long  ago. This is my  tale, and it is ended 
line 43219=>now. Good-bye!' And his thought fled far away and his eyes saw no more. 
