line 44559=>further.' 
line 44560=>     Sam  crept  out,  and flitting  from  stone to  stone  with  more  than 
line 44561=>hobbit-care, he went down to the water -course, and then followed it for some 
line 44562=>way as it climbed  north, until he came to the rock -steps where long ago, no  
line 44563=>doubt,  its spring had come gushing  down  in  a little  waterfall. All  now 
line 44564=>seemed dry and silent; but refusing to despair Sam stooped and listened, and 
line 44565=>to his  delight he caught the sound of  trickling. Clambering a few steps up 
line 44566=>he found a tiny stream of dark water that came out  from the  hill -side  and 
line 44567=>filled a  little bare pool,  from which again it spilled, and vanished  then 
line 44568=>under the barren stones. 
line 44569=>     Sam tasted the water, and it seemed good enough. Then  he drank deeply,  
line 44570=>refilled the  bottle,  and turned  to go back.  At that  moment he caught  a  
line 44571=>glimpse of a black form or shadow flitting among the rocks away near Frodo's 
line 44572=>hiding-place.  Biting  back  a cry, he leapt  down from the spring and  ran, 
line 44573=>jumping from stone to stone. It was  a  wary creature, difficult to see, but 
line 44574=>Sam had little doubt about it: he longed to get  his hands on its  neck. But 
line 44575=>it heard him coming and  slipped quickly away.  Sam  thought he  saw a  last  
line 44576=>fleeting  glimpse  of  it,  peering  back  over  the  edge  of the  eastward 
line 44577=>precipice, before it ducked and disappeared. 
line 44578=>     'Well, luck did not let me  down,' muttered Sam,  'but that was a  near 
line 44579=>thing! Isn't it enough  to have orcs by the  thousand  without that stinking 
line 44580=>villain coming nosing round? I wish he had been  shot!' He sat down by Frodo 
line 44581=>and did not rouse him; but he did not dare to  go to  sleep himself. At last  
line 44582=>when he felt his eyes closing and knew that his struggle to keep awake could 
line 44583=>not go on much longer, he wakened Frodo gently. 
line 44584=>     'That  Gollum's  about   again,  I'm  afraid,  Mr.  Frodo,'   he  said. 
line 44585=>'Leastways, if  it wasn't  him, then there's two of him. I went away to find 
line 44586=>some water and  spied  him nosing  round just as I  turned back. I reckon it 
line 44587=>isn't safe  for us  both to sleep  together,  and begging your pardon, but I 
line 44588=>
line 44589=>####-can't hold up my lids much longer.' 
line 44590=>     'Bless you, Sam!' said Frodo. 'Lie down  and take your pr oper turn! But 
line 44591=>I'd rather have Gollum than orcs. At any rate he  won't give us away to them 
line 44592=>- not unless he's caught himself.' 
line 44593=>     'But he might do a bit of robbery and murder on  his own,' growled Sam.  
line 44594=>'Keep your eyes open,  Mr. Frodo! There's  a bottle full of water. Drink up. 
line 44595=>We can fill it again when we go on.' With that Sam plunged into sleep. 
line 44596=>     Light was fading when  he  woke.  Frodo sat  propped  against  the rock  
line 44597=>behind, but he  had fallen asleep. The water-bottle  was empty. There was no 
line 44598=>sign of Gollum. 
line 44599=>     Mordor -dark  had returned, and the watch-fires on  the  heights  burned 
line 44600=>fierce and red, when the hobbits  set out  again on the most dangerous stage 
line 44601=>of all  their  journey.  They  went first  to  the  little  spring, and then 
line 44602=>climbing warily up they  came to the road at the  point  where it swung east  
line 44603=>towards  the Isenmouthe  twenty miles away. It was not a broad road, and  it  
line 44604=>had  no wall  or parapet along the edge and as it ran on the sheer drop from 
line 44605=>its brink became deeper and deeper. The hobbits could hear no movements, and 
line 44606=>after listening for a while they set off eastward at a steady pace. 
line 44607=>     After doing some twelve miles, they halted. A short  way back the  road 
line 44608=>had  bent a  little northward and  the stretch that they had passed over was 
line 44609=>now screened  from  sight.  This proved  disastrous. They  rested  for  some 
line 44610=>minutes and then went on; but they had not taken many steps when suddenly in 
line 44611=>the stillness of  the  night they  heard the  sound that all along  they had 
line 44612=>secretly dreaded: the   noise of marching feet. It was still some way  behind 
line 44613=>them, but looking  back they could see  the twinkle of torches  coming round 
line 44614=>the  bend less  than  a mile away,  and they  were moving fast: too fast for  
line 44615=>Frodo to escape by flight along the road ahead. 
line 44616=>     'I feared  it, Sam,' said Frodo. 'We've  trusted to luck,  and  it  has 
line 44617=>failed  us.  We're trapped.' He looked wildly up at the frowning wall, where 
line 44618=>the road-builders of old had cut the rock sheer for many fathoms above their  
line 44619=>heads. He ran to the other side and looked over the brink into a dark pit of 
line 44620=>gloom.  'We're trapped at last!' he said He sank to the  ground beneath  the 
line 44621=>wall of rock and bowed his head. 
line 44622=>     'Seems so,' said Sam. 'Well, we can but wait and see.' And with that he 
line 44623=>sat down beside Frodo under the shadow of the cliff. 
line 44624=>     They did  not have  to wait long. The orcs were going at a  great pace. 
line 44625=>Those in the foremost files  bore torches.  On they  came, red flames in the 
line 44626=>
line 44627=>####-dark, swiftly growing. Now Sam too bowed his head, hoping that it  would hide 
line 44628=>his face when the  torches reached  them; and he  set  their  shields before 
line 44629=>their knees to hide their feet. 
line 44630=>     'If only  they  are in a hurry and will let a couple of tired  soldiers 
line 44631=>alone and pass on!' he thought. 
line 44632=>     And so it  seemed that they would. The leading  orcs came loping along, 
line 44633=>panting, holding their  heads down. They  were  a gang of the smaller breeds 
line 44634=>being driven unwilling to their Dark Lord's wars; all they cared for  was to 
line 44635=>get the march over and escape the whip. Beside them, running up and down the 
line 44636=>line, went two of the large fierce uruks, cracking lashes and shouting. File 
line 44637=>after file passed, and the tell-tale torchlight was  already some way ahead. 
line 44638=>Sam held his  breath. Now more than half the line had gone by. Then suddenly 
line 44639=>one of the slave-drivers spied the two figures  by the road-side. He flicked 
line 44640=>a whip at them and yelled:  'Hi, you! Get up!' They did not answer, and with 
line 44641=>a shout he halted the whole company. 
line 44642=>     'Come on, you slugs!' he cried.  'This is  no time  for  sl ouching.' He 
line 44643=>took a step towards them, and even in the gloom he recognized the devices on 
line 44644=>their shields.  'Deserting,  eh?'  he snarled.  'Or thinking of it? All your 
line 44645=>folk  should  have been inside Udyn before yesterday evening. You know that. 
line 44646=>Up you get and fall in, or I'll have your numbers and report you.' 
line 44647=>     They  struggled to their  feet, and keeping bent, limping like footsore 
line 44648=>soldiers, they shuffled back towards the rear  of  the line. 'No, not at the 
line 44649=>rear!' the slave-driver shouted.  'Three files up. And stay there, or you'll 
line 44650=>know it,  when I come down the line!' He sent his  long  whip-lash  cracking  
line 44651=>over their heads; then with another crack  and a yell he started the company 
line 44652=>off again at a brisk trot. 
line 44653=>     It was hard enough for poor Sam, tired a s he was;  but for Frodo it was 
line 44654=>a torment, and soon a nightmare. He set his teeth and tried to stop his mind 
line 44655=>from  thinking, and he struggled  on. The stench of the sweating  orcs about 
line 44656=>him was stifling, and he began to gasp with thirst. On, on they went, and he 
line 44657=>bent  all  his will to draw his breath and to make  his legs keep going; and 
line 44658=>yet to  what evil end  he toiled and endured he did not dare to think. There 
line 44659=>was no hope of falling out  unseen: Now and  again the orc-driver fell  back  
line 44660=>and jeered at them. 
line 44661=>     'There now!' he laughed, flicking at their  legs. 'Where there's a whip 
line 44662=>there's a  will, my slugs. Hold up! I'd give you a nice freshener  now, only 
line 44663=>you'll get  as much lash as your skins will  carry when you come in late  to 
line 44664=>
line 44665=>####-your camp. Do you good. Don't you know we're at war?' 
line 44666=>     They had gone some miles, and the road was at  last running down a long  
line 44667=>slope into the plain, when  Frodo's  strength began to give out and his will 
line 44668=>wavered. He lurched and stumbled. Desperately Sam tried to help him and hold 
line 44669=>him up,  though  he felt  that he could  himself hardly  stay  the pace much 
line 44670=>longer.  At any moment now he knew that the end would come: his master 
line 44671=>would 
line 44672=>faint or fall, and  all would be discovered, and  their bitter efforts be in 
line 44673=>vain.  'I'll have that big slave-driving devil anyway,' he thought. 
line 44674=>     Then just as  he  was putting his hand  to the hilt of his sword, there 
line 44675=>came an unexpected relief.  They were out on the plain now and drawing  near 
line 44676=>the entrance to Udyn. Some  way in  front  of it,  before  the  gate  at the 
line 44677=>bridge-end, the  road  from the  west converged with others coming from  the 
line 44678=>south, and from Barad-dyr.  Along all the roads troops were moving; for  the  
line 44679=>Captains  of  the  West  were  advancing  and the Dark Lord was speeding his 
line 44680=>forces  north.  So it  chanced that  several companies came together at  the 
line 44681=>road-meeting, in the dark beyond the light of  the watch-fires on the  wall. 
line 44682=>At once there was great  jostling  and  cursing as  each troop  tried to get 
line 44683=>first to the gate and the ending of  their march.  Though the drivers yelled 
line 44684=>and plied  their whips, scuffles broke out and  some blades  were  drawn.  A 
line 44685=>troop of heavy-armed uruks from Barad-dyr charged into the Durthang line and 
line 44686=>threw them into confusion. 
line 44687=>     Dazed as he  was with  pain and weariness, Sam woke up, grasped quickly 
line 44688=>at his chance, and  threw  himself to the  ground, dragging Frodo down  with  
line 44689=>him. Orcs fell over them, snarling and  cursing. Slowly on hand and knee the 
line 44690=>hobbits  crawled  away  out of  the  turmoil, until  at last unnoticed  they 
line 44691=>dropped  over the  further edge of the road. It  had a  high kerb  by  which 
line 44692=>troop-leaders could  guide  themselves  in black night or  fog,  and it  was 
line 44693=>banked up some feet above the level of the open land. 
line 44694=>     They  lay still   for a while.  It  was too dark to  seek  for cover, if 
line 44695=>indeed there was any to  find; but Sam felt that  they ought at least to get 
line 44696=>further away from the highways and out of the range of torch-light. 
line 44697=>     'Come on, Mr. Frodo!' he whispered.  'One more  crawl, and then you can 
line 44698=>lie still.' 
line 44699=>     With a last despairing effort Frodo  raised  himself on  his hands, and 
line 44700=>struggled on for maybe twenty yards. Then he pitched down into a shallow pit 
line 44701=>that opened unexpectedly before them, and there he lay like a dead thing. 
line 44702=>
line 44703=>####- 
line 44704=> 
line 44705=>
line 44706=>Chapter 3. Mount Doom 
line 44707=>
line 44708=> 
line 44709=> 
line 44710=>     Sam put his ragged orc-cloak under  his master's head, and covered them 
line 44711=>both with the grey robe of Lurien; and as he did so his thoughts went out to 
line 44712=>that fair land, and to the Elves, and he hoped that the cloth woven by their 
line 44713=>hands  might  have some virtue to keep them  hidden beyond all hope  in this 
line 44714=>wilderness of fear. He heard the  scuffling and cries die down as the troops 
line 44715=>passed  on through the Isenmouthe. It seemed that in the confusion  and  the 
line 44716=>mingling of many  companies of various  kinds  they had not been missed, not 
line 44717=>yet at any rate. 
line 44718=>     Sam  took a sip of water, but pressed Frodo  to  drink,  and  when  his 
line 44719=>master had recovered a little he gave  him a whole  wafer of their  precious 
line 44720=>waybread and made  him  ea t it. Then, too worn out even to  feel  much fear,  
line 44721=>they stretched themselves out. They slept a little in uneasy fits; for their 
line 44722=>sweat grew chill on  them, and the  hard stones bit them, and they shivered. 
line 44723=>Out of  the north from the  Black Gate  through  Cirith  Gorgor there flowed 
line 44724=>whispering along the ground a thin cold air. 
line 44725=>     In the morning a  grey light came again, for  in  the high regions  the 
line 44726=>West Wind  still blew, but down on the stones behind the fences of the Black 
line 44727=>Land the air seemed almost dead, chill  and yet stifling. Sam looked  up out 
line 44728=>of the hollow.  The land  all about was  dreary, flat  and drab-hued. On the 
line 44729=>roads nearby nothing was moving now; but Sam feared the watchful eyes on 
line 44730=>the 
line 44731=>wall  of  the  Isenmouthe,  no  more   than   a   furlong   away  northward. 
line 44732=>South-eastward, far off like a  dark standing shadow. loomed  the  Mountain. 
line 44733=>Smokes  were  pouring from  it and while those that rose into  the upper air 
line 44734=>trailed away  eastward, great rolling clouds  floated  down  its  sides  and 
line 44735=>spread over the land. A  few miles to the north-east the  foothills  of  the 
line 44736=>Ashen  Mountains stood  like  sombre grey  ghosts, behind  which  the  misty 
line 44737=>northern heights rose  like  a line of distant cloud hardly darker than  the 
line 44738=>lowering sky. 
line 44739=>     Sam  tried to  guess the distances and to decide what way they ought to 
line 44740=>take.  It looks every step  of fifty miles,' he muttered gloomily staring at 
line 44741=>the threatening mountain, 'and that'll take a week, if it takes  a day, with 
line 44742=>Mr. Frodo as he is.' He shook his  head,  and as he worked things out, slowly  
line 44743=>
line 44744=>####-a new dark thought  grew in his mind. Never  for long had  hope died in  his 
line 44745=>staunch  heart, and  always until now he  had  taken some thought  for their 
line 44746=>return.  But the  bitter  truth  came  home to him  at  last:  at best their 
line 44747=>provision  would take them to  their goal; and when the task was done, there 
line 44748=>they would come to  an end,  alone, houseless, foodless  in  the midst  of a  
line 44749=>terrible desert. There could be no return. 
line 44750=>     'So that was the job I felt I had to  do when  I started,' thought Sam: 
line 44751=>'to help  Mr. Frodo to the last step and then die with him? Well, if that is 
line 44752=>the job then I must do it. But I would dearly like to see Bywater again, and 
line 44753=>Rosie Cotton and her brothers, and the Gaffer and Marigold  and all. I can't 
line 44754=>think somehow that Gandalf would have sent Mr. Frodo on this errand if there 
line 44755=>hadn't a' been  any hope  of his  ever coming back at all. Things  all  went 
line 44756=>wrong when  he went  down  in Moria.  I  wish he hadn't. He  would have done 
line 44757=>something.' 
line 44758=>     But even as hope died in Sam, or seemed to  die, it was turned to a new 
line 44759=>strength. Sam's  plain  hobbit-face  grew stern,  almost  grim, as  the will 
line 44760=>hardened in him, and he felt through  all his  limbs a thrill,  as if he was 
line 44761=>turning into  some  creature  of   stone  and steel  that neither despair nor  
line 44762=>weariness nor endless barren miles could subdue. 
line 44763=>     With  a new sense of responsibility he  brought  his  eyes  back to the 
line 44764=>ground  near at hand, studying the  next move. As the light grew a little he 
line 44765=>saw  to  his  surprise  that  what  from  a  distance  had  seemed  wide and 
line 44766=>featureless  flats  were in fact  all broken  and tumbled. Indeed the  whole 
line 44767=>surface of the plains of Gorgoroth was pocked with great holes, as if, while 
line 44768=>it was still a waste of soft mud,  it had been smitten with a shower of bolts 
line 44769=>and huge slingstones. The largest of these holes  were rimmed with ridges of 
line 44770=>broken  rock, and broad fissures ran out from them in all directions. It was 
line 44771=>a land in which it would be possible to  creep from hiding to hiding, unseen 
line 44772=>by all but the most watchful eyes: possible at least for one  who was strong 
line 44773=>and had no need for speed. For the hungry and worn, who had far to go before 
line 44774=>life failed, it had an evil look. 
line 44775=>     Thinking  of all  these things Sam went back to his  master.  He had no 
line 44776=>need to rouse  him.  Frodo was lying on his  back with eyes open, staring at 
line 44777=>the  cloudy sky. 'Well, Mr. Frodo,' said Sam, 'I've been having a look round 
line 44778=>and thinking a bit. There's  nothing on the roads, and we'd best  be getting 
line 44779=>away while there's a chance. Can you manage it?' 
line 44780=>     'I can manage it,' said Frodo. 'I must.' 
line 44781=>
line 44782=>####-     Once more they started, crawling from hollow to hollow, flitting behind 
line 44783=>such  cover  as they could find,  but moving always in  a slant towards  the 
line 44784=>foothills of the northern  range. But as they went the  most easterly of the 
line 44785=>roads followed them, until it ran  off, hugging the skirts of the mountains, 
line 44786=>away into a wall of black shadow far ahead. Neither  man  nor orc now  moved 
line 44787=>along its flat grey stretches; for the Dark Lord  had almost  completed  the 
line 44788=>movement of his forces, and even in the  fastness of his own realm he sought 
line 44789=>the secrecy of night, fearing the winds of the world that had turned against 
line 44790=>him, tearing aside his veils, and troubled with  tidings of  bold spies that 
line 44791=>had passed through his fences. 
line 44792=>     The hobbits had  gone a few weary  miles when they halted. Frodo seemed 
line 44793=>nearly  spent. Sam saw that he could not  go much further in  this  fashion, 
line 44794=>crawling, stooping, now picking  a doubtful way very slowly, now hurrying at 
line 44795=>a stumbling run. 
line 44796=>     'I'm  going  back on to the road while the light lasts, Mr.  Frodo,' he 
line 44797=>said. 'Trust to  luck again! It nearly failed us  last time,  but  it didn't 
line 44798=>quite. A steady pace for a few more miles, and then a rest.' 
line 44799=>     He was taking a far greater risk  than he knew; but  Frodo was too much 
line 44800=>occupied  with his burden and with the  struggle in  his mind to debate, and 
line 44801=>almost too hopeless  to care. They climbed  on to the  causeway and  trudged 
line 44802=>along, down the hard cruel road that led to the Dark Tower itself. But their 
line 44803=>luck held, and for the rest of that day they  met no living or moving thing; 
line 44804=>and when night fell they vanished into the darkness of Mordor. All  the land 
line 44805=>now brooded as at the coming of a  great storm: for the Captains of the West  
line 44806=>had passed  the Cross-roads and  set  flames  in  the deadly fields of Imlad 
line 44807=>Morgul. 
line 44808=>     So  the  desperate  journey  went  on, as the Ring went  south and  the 
line 44809=>banners of the  kings rode  north. For the hobbits each day,  each mile. was 
line 44810=>more  bitter than the one before, as  their  strength lessened and  the land 
line 44811=>became more  evil.  They met no enemies by day. At times  by night,  as they 
line 44812=>cowered or drowsed uneasily in some hiding beside the road, they heard cries 
line 44813=>and the  noise  of  many  feet or the swift passing of some  cruelly  ridden 
line 44814=>steed. But far  worse than all  such  perils was the ever -approaching threat 
line 44815=>that  beat  upon them as they went: the  dreadful menace of  the  Power that 
line 44816=>waited, brooding in  deep thought and sleepless malice behind  the dark veil  
line 44817=>about  its  Throne.  Nearer  and nearer it drew,  looming blacker, like  the 
line 44818=>oncoming of a wall of night at the last end of the world. 
line 44819=>
line 44820=>####-     There  came at  last a dreadful nightfall; and even  as the Captains of 
line 44821=>the West drew near to the end of the living lands, the two wanderers came to  
line 44822=>an  hour of blank despair. Four days had passed since they had  escaped from 
line 44823=>the orcs,  but the  time lay behind  them like an ever -darkening  dream. All 
line 44824=>this  last  day Frodo  had not  spoken,  but had  walked  half-bowed,  often 
line 44825=>stumbling, as if his eyes no longer saw the way before his feet. Sam guessed 
line 44826=>that  among  all their  pains he  bore the worst, the growing weight  of the 
line 44827=>Ring, a  burden on  the  body and a torment  to his  mind. Anxiously Sam had 
line 44828=>noted  how his master's left hand would often be raised  as if to ward  on a  
line 44829=>blow,  or to  screen his shrinking eyes from a dreadful  Eye that sought  to 
line 44830=>look  in them.  And sometimes  his right  hand  would creep  to  his breast, 
line 44831=>clutching, and  then  slowly,  as  the will recovered mastery, it  would  be 
line 44832=>withdrawn. 
line 44833=>     Now as the blackness of night  returned Frodo sat, his head between his 
line 44834=>knees, his arms  hanging wearily  to the ground where  his hands lay  feebly  
line 44835=>twitching. Sam watched him, till  night covered them both and hid them  from 
line 44836=>one another. He could no longer find any words to say;  and he turned to his 
line 44837=>own dark thoughts. As for himself, though weary and under a  shadow of fear, 
line 44838=>he still  had some strength left. The lembas had a virtue without which they 
line 44839=>would  long  ago have  lain down to die. It did  not satisfy desire, and  at 
line 44840=>times Sam's mind  was filled with the memories of food, and the  longing for 
line 44841=>simple  bread  and meats.  And yet this waybread of the  Elves had a potency 
line 44842=>that increased as travellers  relied on it alone and did  not mingle it with 
line 44843=>other foods. It fed the will, and  it gave strength to endure, and to master  
line 44844=>sinew  and limb beyond the measure of mortal  kind. But  now a  new decision 
line 44845=>must be  made. They could not follow  this road any  longer; for  it went on 
line 44846=>eastward  into  the  great Shadow, but the Mountain  now  loomed  upon their 
line 44847=>right, almost due south, and they must turn towards it. Yet  still before it 
line 44848=>there stretched a wide region of fuming, barren, ash-ridden land. 
line 44849=>     'Water, water!'  muttered  Sam.  He had  stinted  himself,  and in  his 
line 44850=>parched mouth his tongue seemed thick and swollen; but for all his care they  
line 44851=>now  had  very little left, perhaps half  his bottle, and  maybe there  were 
line 44852=>still days to go.  All would long ago have been spent, if they had not dared 
line 44853=>to follow the  orc-road. For at long intervals on that highway  cisterns had 
line 44854=>been built  for  the use  of troops  sent in  haste  through  the  waterless 
line 44855=>regions. In one  Sam had found some water left, stale, muddied by  the orcs,  
line 44856=>but still sufficient  for their desperate case. Yet that was now a  day ago. 
line 44857=>
line 44858=>####-There was no hope of any more. 
line 44859=>     At last  wearied with his cares Sam drowsed, leaving the morrow till it 
line 44860=>came; he could do no more. Dream and waking mingled uneasily. He saw  
line 44861=>lights 
line 44862=>like gloating yes, and dark creeping shapes, and he heard noises as of  wild 
line 44863=>beasts  or  the dreadful cries of tortured things; and he would start  up to 
line 44864=>find the world all dark and only  empty b lackness all about him. Once  only,  
line 44865=>as he stood and stared wildly round,  did it seem that, though now awake, he 
line 44866=>could still see pale lights like eyes; but soon they flickered and vanished. 
line 44867=>     The hateful night  passed  slowly  and  reluctantly. Such  da ylight  as 
line 44868=>followed was dim; for here as the Mountain drew near the air was ever mirky, 
line 44869=>while  out  from the Dark Tower  there crept the veils of Shadow that Sauron 
line 44870=>wove about himself. Frodo was lying on his back not moving. Sam stood 
line 44871=>beside 
line 44872=>him, reluctant  to speak, and yet knowing that the word now lay with him:  he 
line 44873=>must set his  master's will to work for another effort. At  length, stooping 
line 44874=>and caressing Frodo's brow, he spoke in his ear. 
line 44875=>     'Wake up, Master!' he said. 'Time for another start.' 
line 44876=>     As   if roused by a sudden  bell,  Frodo rose quickly,  and stood up and 
line 44877=>looked away southwards; but when his eyes beheld the Mountain and the desert 
line 44878=>he quailed again. 
line 44879=>     'I can't manage it, Sam,' he said. 'It is such a weight to carry,  such 
line 44880=>a weight.' 
line 44881=>     Sam knew before he spoke, that  it was vain, and that  such words might 
line 44882=>do more harm than good, but in his pity he could not  keep silent. 'Then let 
line 44883=>me carry it a bit  for you, Master,' he said. 'You know I would, and gladly, 
line 44884=>as long as I have any strength. ' 
line 44885=>     A wild light came  into Frodo's  eyes. 'Stand away! Don't touch me!' he 
line 44886=>cried. 'It is mine,  I say. Be off!' His hand strayed to his sword-hilt. But 
line 44887=>then quickly his voice changed.  'No, no,  Sam,' he said sadly.  'But you must  
line 44888=>understand. It is my   burden,  and no  one  else can bear it. It is too late 
line 44889=>now, Sam dear. You can't help me in that way again. I am almost in its power  
line 44890=>now. I could not give it up, and if you tried to take it I should go mad.' 
line 44891=>     Sam  nodded. 'I understand,'  he  said.  'But  I've been thinking,  Mr. 
line 44892=>Frodo, there's other things we might do without. Why not lighten  the load a  
