line 45741=>
line 45742=>Chapter 5. The Steward and the King 
line 45743=>
line 45744=> 
line 45745=> 
line 45746=>     Over  the city of Gondor doubt and  great  dread had hung. Fair weather  
line 45747=>and clear  sun had seemed but a mockery to men whose days  held  little hope, 
line 45748=>and  who  looked each  morning  for  news  of doom. Their lord was  dead and 
line 45749=>burned, dead lay the King of Rohan in their citadel,  and the  new king that 
line 45750=>had  come to them in the night was gone again to  a war with powers too dark 
line 45751=>and terrible for any might or valour to conquer. And no news came. After the 
line 45752=>host left Morgul Vale and  took the northward road beneath the shadow of the 
line 45753=>mountains no messenger had  returned nor any rumour  of what was passing  in 
line 45754=>the brooding East. 
line 45755=>     When the Captains were but two days gone, the Lady Jowyn bade the 
line 45756=>women 
line 45757=>who tended her  to  bring her  raiment, and she would  not  be gainsaid, but 
line 45758=>rose; and when they had clothed her and set her arm in a sling of linen, she 
line 45759=>went to the Warden of the Houses of Healing. 
line 45760=>     'Sir,' she  said, 'I am in great  unrest,  and  I cannot lie longer  in 
line 45761=>sloth.' 
line 45762=>     'Lady,' he answered, 'you are  not  yet  healed, and I was commanded to 
line 45763=>tend you  with especial care. You should  not  have risen  from your bed for  
line 45764=>seven days yet , or so I was bidden. I beg you to go back.' 
line 45765=>     'I am  healed,' she said,  'healed at  least in body, save  my left arm 
line 45766=>only, and  that is at ease. But I shall sicken anew, if there is naught that 
line 45767=>I can do. Are there no tidings of war? The women can tell  me nothing.' 
line 45768=>     'There are  no tidings,' said the Warden,  'save  that  the  Lords have 
line 45769=>ridden to Morgul Vale; and men say that the new captain out  of the North is 
line 45770=>their chief. A great lord is that, and a  healer;  and it is a thing passing 
line 45771=>strange to me that  the healing hand should  also wield the sword. It is not 
line 45772=>thus  in Gondor now,  though once it was  so, if old tales be  true. But for  
line 45773=>long years we healers have only sought to patch the rents made by the men of 
line 45774=>swords. Though we should still have enough  to do without them: the world is 
line 45775=>full enough of hurts and mischances without wars to multiply them.' 
line 45776=>     It needs but one foe to breed a war, not two,  Master  Warden, answered 
line 45777=>Jowyn. 'And those who  have not swords can  still die  upon them. Would  you  
line 45778=>have  the folk  of Gondor gather you herbs  only, when the Dark Lord gathers 
line 45779=>
line 45780=>####-armies? And it  is not  always good  to be healed in  body. Nor is it always 
line 45781=>evil to die in battle, even  in bitter pain. Were I permitted,  in this dark 
line 45782=>hour I would choose the latter.' 
line 45783=>     The Warden looked at her. Tall she stood there, her eyes  bright in her  
line 45784=>white face, her hand clenched as she turned and gazed out of his window that 
line 45785=>opened to the East. He sighed and shook his head. After a pause  she  turned 
line 45786=>to him again. 
line 45787=>     'Is there no deed to do?' she said. 'Who commands in this City?' 
line 45788=>     'I do not  rightly know,' he  answered. 'Such things are  not my  care. 
line 45789=>There is a marshal over the Riders  of Rohan; and the Lord HÂ®rin, I am told, 
line 45790=>commands the men of Gondor. But  the Lord Faramir is by right the Steward of 
line 45791=>the City.' 
line 45792=>     'Where can I find him?' 
line 45793=>     'In this house, lady. He was sorely  hurt,  but is now set again on the 
line 45794=>way to health. But I do not know--' 
line 45795=>     'Will you not bring me to him? Then you will know. ' 
line 45796=>     The Lord  Faramir was  walking  alone in  the garden  of the  Houses of 
line 45797=>Healing, and the sunlight warmed him, and he felt life run new in his veins; 
line 45798=>but his heart  was heavy, and he looked  out  over the  walls  eastward. And 
line 45799=>coming, the Warden  spoke his name, and he turned and saw the Lady  Jowyn 
line 45800=>of 
line 45801=>Rohan; and he  was  moved with pity, for  he saw that she was hurt,  and his 
line 45802=>clear sight perceived her sorrow and unrest. 
line 45803=>     'My lord,' said  the Warden, 'here is the Lady Jowyn of Rohan. She rode 
line 45804=>wi th the king and  was sorely hurt, and dwells now in my keeping. But she is 
line 45805=>not content, and she wishes to speak to the Steward of the City.' 
line 45806=>     'Do not misunderstand him, lord,'  said Jowyn. 'It is not lack  of care 
line 45807=>that  grieves me.  No  houses  could be  fairer, for those who  desire to be 
line 45808=>healed.  But I  cannot  lie  in sloth,  idle,  caged. I looked  for death in 
line 45809=>battle. But I have not died, and battle still goes on.' 
line 45810=>     At a sign from  Faramir, the Warden bowed and departed. 'What would you  
line 45811=>have me do, lady?' said Faramir.  'I also am a prisoner of the healers.'  He 
line 45812=>looked  at her, and being a man  whom pity deeply stirred,  it seemed to him 
line 45813=>that her loveliness amid her grief would pierce his heart. And she looked at 
line 45814=>him and saw the grave tenderness in his eyes, and yet knew, for she was bred 
line 45815=>among men of war, that here was one whom no Rider of the Mark would 
line 45816=>outmatch 
line 45817=>
line 45818=>####-in battle. 
line 45819=>     'What  do you wish?' he said again. 'If  it lies in my power, I will do 
line 45820=>it.' 
line 45821=>     'I would have  you  command this  Warden, and bid him  let me go,'  she 
line 45822=>said; but though her words were still proud, her heart faltered, and for the 
line 45823=>first time she doubted herself. She  guessed  that this tall man, both stern 
line 45824=>and  gentle, might think  her merely wayward, like a child that has not  the 
line 45825=>firmness of mind to go on with a dull task to the end. 
line 45826=>     'I myself am  in the Warden's  keeping,' answered Faramir. 'Nor  have I 
line 45827=>yet taken  up my authority in the City. But  had I done so,  I  should still 
line 45828=>listen to  his counsel,  and should  not cross  his will in  matters of  his 
line 45829=>craft, unless in some great need.' 
line 45830=>     'But I do not desire healing,' she said. 'I wish to ride to war like my 
line 45831=>brother Jomer, or better  like  Thjoden the king, for he  died  and has both 
line 45832=>honour and peace.' 
line 45833=>     'It  is too late, lady,  to follow the Captains, even  if you  had  the 
line 45834=>strength,'  said Faramir.  'But death  in battle  may  come  to  us all yet, 
line 45835=>willing  or unwilling. You will be  better prepared to  face it in your  own 
line 45836=>manner, if while there is still time you do as the Healer commanded. You and 
line 45837=>I, we must endure with patience the hours of waiting.' 
line 45838=>     She  did not answer, but  as  he looked  at her it  seemed to  him that 
line 45839=>something  in her  softened, as though  a bitter frost  were yielding at the 
line 45840=>first faint presage of Spring. A  tear sprang in her  eye  and fell down her  
line 45841=>cheek, like  a  glistening rain-drop.  Her proud head drooped a little. Then 
line 45842=>quietly, more as if speaking  to herself than to him: 'But the healers would 
line 45843=>have me lie abed seven days yet,'  she said. 'And  my  window does not  look 
line 45844=>eastward.' Her voice was now that of a maiden young and sad. 
line 45845=>     Faramir  smiled, though his heart was  filled with  pity.  'Your window 
line 45846=>does not look eastward?'  he said. 'That  can be  amended.  In  this I  will 
line 45847=>command  the Warden. If  you will stay in this  house in our care, lady, and 
line 45848=>take your rest, then you  shall walk in this garden in the sun, as you will; 
line 45849=>and you shall  look east, whither all our hopes have gone. And here you will  
line 45850=>find me, walking and waiting, and also looking east.  It would ease my care,  
line 45851=>if you would speak to me, or walk at whiles with me.' 
line 45852=>     Then she raised her head and looked him in the eyes again; and a colour 
line 45853=>came in her  pale face.  'How should I ease your care,  my  lord?' she said. 
line 45854=>'And I do not desire the speech of living men.' 
line 45855=>
line 45856=>####-     'Would you have my plain answer?' he said. 
line 45857=>     'I would.' 
line 45858=>     'Then, Jowyn  of Rohan, I say to  you  that you  are  beautiful. In the 
line 45859=>valleys  of our hills there are flowers fair  and bright, and maidens fairer  
line 45860=>still; but neither flower nor lady have I seen till now in Gondor so lovely, 
line 45861=>and so sorrowful. It may be that only a few days are left ere darkness falls 
line 45862=>upon our world,  and when it comes I hope to  face it steadily; but it would 
line 45863=>ea se my heart, if while the Sun yet shines, I  could see you  still. For you  
line 45864=>and I have both passed under the wings of the Shadow, and the same hand drew 
line 45865=>us back.' 
line 45866=>     'Alas, not me, lord!' she said. 'Shadow  lies on me still.  Look not to 
line 45867=>me for healing! I am a shieldmaiden and my hand is ungentle. But I thank you  
line 45868=>for this at least, that I need not keep to my chamber. I will walk abroad by 
line 45869=>the grace of the Steward of the City.' And she did him a courtesy and walked 
