line 45871=>and his glance now strayed rather to the house than to the eastward walls. 
line 45872=>     When he returned to his chamber he called for the Warden, and heard all  
line 45873=>that he could tell of the Lady of Rohan. 
line 45874=>     'But I doubt  not,  lor d,'  said the Warden, 'that you would learn more 
line 45875=>from the Halfling that is with us; for he was in the riding of the king, and 
line 45876=>with the Lady at the end, they say.' 
line 45877=>     And so Merry was sent to Faramir, and while that day lasted they talked 
line 45878=>long  together, and  Faramir  learned  much, more  even  than Merry put into 
line 45879=>words; and  he  thought  that he understood now  something of the grief  and 
line 45880=>unrest of Jowyn of Rohan. And in the  fair evening Faramir and  Merry walked 
