line 45882=>     But in the morning, as Faramir came from the Houses, he saw her, as she 
line 45883=>stood upon the walls; and she was clad all in white, and gleamed in the sun. 
line 45884=>And he called to her, and she came down, and they walked on the grass or sat 
line 45885=>under a green  tree  together , now in  silence, now in speech. And  each day 
line 45886=>after they did likewise. And the Warden looking  from his window was glad in 
line 45887=>heart.  for  he was a healer. and his care was lightened; and certain it was 
line 45888=>that, heavy as was the dread and foreboding of those days upon the hearts of 
line 45889=>men, still these two of his charges prospered and grew daily in strength. 
line 45890=>     And so the  fifth day came since the Lady Jowyn went  first to Faramir; 
line 45891=>and they stood now together once more upon the walls of  the City and looked 
line 45892=>out. No tidings  had  yet come, and all hearts  were darkened. The  weather, 
line 45893=>
line 45894=>####-too, was  bright  no  longer. It was cold. A wind  that had sprung up in the 
line 45895=>night was  blowing  now keenly from  the North, and it was  rising; but  the 
line 45896=>lands about looked grey and dr ear. 
line 45897=>     They were clad in warm  raiment and heavy cloaks, and over all the Lady  
line 45898=>Jowyn wore a  great blue  mantle of  the colour of deep summer -night, and it  
line 45899=>was set with silver stars  about hem and  throat. Faramir had  sent for this 
line 45900=>robe and had wrapped  it about her;  and he thought that  she looked fair and  
line 45901=>queenly indeed as  she stood there at  his  side. The mantle was wrought for  
line 45902=>his  mother,  Finduilas of Amroth,  who died untimely, and was  to him but a 
line 45903=>memory of loveliness in far days and of his first grief; and her robe seemed 
