line 46919=>too. At least as far as Bree. I want to see Butterbur.' 
line 46920=>     In  the evening  they went to say good-bye to Bilbo. 'Well, if you must  
line 46921=>go, you must,' he said.  'I am sorry.  I shall miss you.  It is nice just to 
line 46922=>know that  you are about the  place. But I am getting very sleepy.' Then  he 
line 46923=>gave Frodo his mithril-coat  and Sting, forgetting that he had  already done 
line 46924=>so;  and  he gave him  also three books of lore that he had made  at various 
line 46925=>times,  written  in  his spidery hand,  and labelled  on  their  red  backs: 
line 46926=>Translations from the Elvish, by B.B. 
line 46927=>     To Sam he gave a little bag of gold. 'Almost the last drop of the Smaug 
line 46928=>vintage,' he  said.  'May come in  useful,  if you think of getting married, 
line 46929=>Sam.' Sam blushed. 
line 46930=>     'I have nothing  much to give to you young fellows,' he said   to  Merry 
line 46931=>and Pippin, 'except  good advice.'  And when he had given them a fair sample 
line 46932=>of  this, he added a last item in Shire-fashion:  'Don't let your heads  get 
line 46933=>too big for  your hats! But  if you don't  finish growing  up soon,  you are 
line 46934=>going to find hats and clothes expensive.' 
line 46935=>     'But if you want to  beat  the Old Took,' said Pippin, 'I don't see why 
line 46936=>we shouldn't try and beat the Bullroarer.' 
line 46937=>     Bilbo laughed, and he produced out of a pocket two beautiful pipes with 
line 46938=>pearl mouth-pieces and bound with fine-wrought silver.  'Think of me when you  
line 46939=>smoke them!' he said. 'The  Elves made them for  me, but I don't smoke now.' 
line 46940=>And then suddenly he nodded and went to sleep for a little; and when he woke 
line 46941=>up again he said: 'Now where were we? Yes, of course, g iving presents. Which 
line 46942=>reminds me: what's become of my ring, Frodo, that you took away?' 
line 46943=>     'I have lost it, Bilbo dear,' said Frodo. 'I got rid of it, you know.' 
line 46944=>     'What a  pity!' said  Bilbo. 'I should have liked to see  it again. But 
line 46945=>
line 46946=>####-no, how silly  of me! That's what you went for, wasn't it: to get rid of it?  
line 46947=>But it is all so confusing, for such a lot of  other things seem to have got 
line 46948=>mixed  up  with it: Aragorn's affairs, and the White Council and Gondor, and 
line 46949=>the Horsemen, and Southrons, and oliphaunts - did you really see one, Sam? - 
line 46950=>and caves and towers and golden trees, and goodness knows what besides. 
line 46951=>     'I  evidently came  back  by much too straight a  road from my trip.  I 
line 46952=>think Gandalf might have shown  me round  a bit. But then the  auction  would 
line 46953=>have been  over  before I got back,  and I should have had even more trouble 
line 46954=>than I  did. Anyway  it's  too  late  now; and really I think it's much more 
line 46955=>comfortable to sit  here and hear about it all.  The fire's  very cosy here, 
line 46956=>and the food's very good, and there are Elves when you want  them. What more 
line 46957=>could one want?  
line 46958=>     The Road goes ever on and on  
line 46959=>     Out from the door where it began. 
line 46960=>     Now far ahead the Road has gone, 
line 46961=>     Let others follow it who can! 
line 46962=>     Let them a journey new begin, 
line 46963=>     But I at last with weary feet 
line 46964=>     Will turn towards the lighted inn, 
line 46965=>     My evening-rest and sleep to meet.' 
line 46966=>     And  as Bilbo murmured the last words his head dropped on his chest and 
line 46967=>he slept soundly. 
line 46968=>     The evening deepened in the room,  and the  firelight  burned brighter; 
line 46969=>and they looked at Bilbo  as he slept and saw that his face was smiling. For  
line 46970=>some time they sat in silence; and then Sam  looking round  at  the room and 
line 46971=>the shadows flickering on the walls, said softly: 
line 46972=>     'I don't think, Mr. Frodo, that he's done much writing while we've been 
line 46973=>away. He won't ever write our story now.' 
line 46974=>     At that  Bilbo opened an eye, almost as if he had heard. Then he roused 
line 46975=>himself. 'You see, I am getting so  sleepy,' he said. 'And when I have  time 
line 46976=>to write, I only really like writing poetry. I wonder, Frodo my dear fellow,  
line 46977=>if you  would very much mind  tidying things up a bit before you go? Collect 
line 46978=>all my notes and  papers, and my diary too, and  take them with you, if  you  
line 46979=>will. You see, I haven't much time for the selection and the arrangement and 
line 46980=>all that.  Get Sam to help, and when you've knocked things into  shape, come 
line 46981=>back, and I'll run over it. I won't be too critical.' 
line 46982=>     'Of course I'll do it!' said Frodo. 'And of course I'll come back soon: 
line 46983=>
line 46984=>####-it won't be dangerous any  more. There  is a real king now and he  will soon 
line 46985=>put the roads in order.' 
line 46986=>     'Thank  you, my dear fellow!' said Bilbo. 'That really is a  very great 
line 46987=>relief to my mind.' And with that he fell fast asleep again. 
line 46988=>     The next day Gandalf and the hobbits took leave  of Bilbo  in his room, 
line 46989=>for it was cold out of doors; and then they said farewell to Elrond  and all 
line 46990=>his household. 
line 46991=>     As Frodo stood upon  the threshold, Elrond  wished him  a fair journey, 
line 46992=>and blessed him, and he said: 
line 46993=>     'I think,  Frodo, that maybe you will not need to come back, unless you  
line 46994=>come  very soon. For  about this time of the year, when the  leaves are gold 
line 46995=>before they fall, look for Bilbo in  the woods of the Shire. I shall be with 
line 46996=>him.' 
line 46997=>     These wor ds no one else heard, and Frodo kept them to himself.  
line 46998=> 
