line 47001=>
line 47002=>Chapter 7. Homeward Bound 
line 47003=>
line 47004=> 
line 47005=> 
line 47006=>     At last  the  hobbits had  their  faces  turned towards home. They were 
line 47007=>eager now to see the  Shire again; but at first they  rode  only slowly, for  
line 47008=>Frodo had been il l at  ease.  When they came to the  Ford of Bruinen, he had 
line 47009=>halted, and seemed loth  to ride into the stream; and they  noted that for a  
line 47010=>while his eyes appeared not to see them or things about him. All that day he  
line 47011=>was silent. It was the sixth of October. 
line 47012=>     'Are you in  pain,  Frodo?' said Gandalf quietly  as he rode by Frodo's 
line 47013=>side. 
line 47014=>     'Well, yes I am,' said Frodo. 'It is my shoulder. The  wound aches, and 
line 47015=>the memory of darkness is heavy on me. It was a year ago today.' 
line 47016=>     'Alas!  there  are  some  wounds  that  cannot be  wholly  cured,' said 
line 47017=>Gandalf. 
line 47018=>     'I  fear it may be so with  mine,'  said Frodo. 'There is no real going 
line 47019=>back. Though I may come to the Shire, it will not seem the same; for I shall 
line 47020=>not  be the same.  I am  wounded  with  knife, sting,  and tooth, and a long 
line 47021=>burden. Where shall I find rest?' 
line 47022=>     Gandalf did not answer. 
line 47023=>     By the end of the next day  the pain and  unease had passed, and  Frodo 
line 47024=>was merry again, as merry as if he did not remember the blackness of the day 
line 47025=>before. After that the journey went well,  and the days went quickly by; for  
line 47026=>they rode  at leisure,  and often they lingered in the fair  woodlands where 
line 47027=>the leaves were red  and yellow  in the  autumn  sun. At length they came to  
line 47028=>Weathertop; and  it was then drawing  towards  evening and the shadow of the 
line 47029=>hill lay  dark  on the road. Then Frodo begged them to  hasten, and he would  
line 47030=>not look towards the hill,  but rode through its shadow with  head bowed and 
line 47031=>cloak drawn close about him. That night the weather changed, and a wind came 
line 47032=>from the  West laden with rain, and it blew loud and  chill,  and the yellow 
line 47033=>leaves whirled like birds in the air. When they came to the Chetwood already 
line 47034=>the boughs were almost bare, and a great  curtain  of rain  veiled Bree Hill 
line 47035=>from their sight. 
line 47036=>     So it was that near the end of a wild and wet  evening in the last days 
line 47037=>of October the  five travellers rode up  the  climbing road and came  to the 
line 47038=>South-gate of Bree.  It was locked fast; and the rain  blew in  their faces,  
line 47039=>
line 47040=>####-and in the darkening sky low clouds went hurrying  by, and their hearts sank  
line 47041=>a little, for they had expected more welcome. 
line 47042=>     When they had called many times, at last  the Gate-keeper came out, and 
line 47043=>they saw that  he  carried a great cudgel. He looked at them  with  fear and 
line 47044=>suspicion; but  when he saw that Gandalf  was there, and that his companions 
line 47045=>were hobbits,  in spite of their strange gear, then he brightened and wished 
line 47046=>them welcome. 
line 47047=>     'Come in!' he said,  unlocking  the  gate. 'We  won't stay for news out 
line 47048=>here  in the  cold  and the wet, a ruffianly evening. But old Barley will no 
line 47049=>doubt give you a welcome at The Pony, and there you'll hear all there is  to 
line 47050=>hear.' 
line 47051=>     'And  there  you'll hear  later all  that  we say,  and  more,' laughed 
line 47052=>Gandalf. 'How is Harry? ' 
line 47053=>     The Gate-keeper scowled. 'Gone,' he said. 'But you'd best ask Barliman. 
line 47054=>Good evening!' 
line 47055=>     'Good  evening  to  you!' they said, and passed through; and then  they 
line 47056=>noticed  that  behind the  hedge at  the road-side a long low  hut had  been 
line 47057=>built, and a  number of  men had come out and were staring at  them over the 
line 47058=>fence. When they  came  to  Bill Ferny's house they saw that the hedge there 
line 47059=>was tattered and unkempt, and the windows were all boarded up. 
line 47060=>     'Do you think you killed him with that apple, Sam?' said Pippin. 
line 47061=>     'I'm not so hopeful, Mr. Pippin,' said Sam. 'But  I'd like to know what 
line 47062=>became  of that poor  pony. He's  been on my mind many a time and the wolves 
line 47063=>howling and all.' 
line 47064=>     At last they  came  to  The Prancing  Pony,  and that at  least  looked 
line 47065=>outwardly unchanged;  and  there were lights behind the red curtains  in the 
