line 47131=>don't  say,  Master  Gandalf! Well I never!  Who'd  have  thought it in  our 
line 47132=>times!' 
line 47133=>     But he did say much on  his  own account. Things were far from well, he 
line 47134=>would say. Business was  not even fair, it was downright bad.  'No one comes 
line 47135=>nigh Bree  now from Outside,'  he said. 'And the inside  folks, they stay at 
line 47136=>home mostly and keep their doors barred. It all comes of those newcomers and 
line 47137=>gangrels that began coming up the Greenway  last year,  as you may remember; 
line 47138=>but  more came later. Some were just poor bodies running away from  trouble; 
line 47139=>but most were bad men, full o' thievery and  mischief. And there was trouble 
line 47140=>right here  in Bree, bad trouble. Why, we had a real set-to, and there  were 
line 47141=>some folk killed, killed dead! If you'll believe me.' 
line 47142=>     'I will indeed,' said Gandalf. 'How many?' 
line 47143=>     'Three  and two,' said  Butterbur,  referring to the big  folk  and the 
line 47144=>little. 'There was poor  Mat Heathertoes, and  Rowlie Appledore,  and little 
line 47145=>Tom Pickthorn from over the Hill; and  Willie Banks from up-away, and one of 
line 47146=>the Underhills from Staddle: all good fellows, and they're missed. And Harry 
line 47147=>Goatleaf that used to be on the West -gate, and that Bill Ferny, they came in 
