line 47149=>they let them in. On the night of the  fight, I  mean. And that was after we 
line 47150=>showed them the gates and  pushed them out: before the year's end, that was; 
line 47151=>and the fight was early in the New Year, after the heavy snow we had. 
line 47152=>
line 47153=>####-     'And now they're gone for robbers and live outside, hiding in the woods 
line 47154=>beyond Archet, and out  in the wilds north-away. It's like a  bit of the bad 
line 47155=>old  times tales tell of, I say. It  isn't safe  on the road and nobody goes 
line 47156=>far, and folk lock up  early. We have to keep watchers all round  the  fence 
line 47157=>and put a lot of men on the gates at nights.' 
line 47158=>     'Well, no one troubled us,' said Pippin, 'and we came along slowly, and 
line 47159=>kept no watch. We thought we'd left all trouble behind us.' 
line 47160=>     'Ah, that you haven't, Master,  more's the pity,'  said Butterbur. 'But 
line 47161=>it's  no wonder they left  you a lone. They wouldn't go for  armed folk, with 
line 47162=>swords and helmets and  shields  and all. Make them think twice, that would. 
line 47163=>And I must say it put me aback a bit when I saw you.' 
line 47164=>     Then the hobbits suddenly realized  that people had looked at them with 
line 47165=>amazement  not out of surprise at their return so much as in wonder at their 
line 47166=>gear.  They  themselves  had  become  so  used to warfare and  to  riding in 
line 47167=>well-arrayed  companies  that they had quite  forgotten that the bright mail 
line 47168=>peeping from  under their cloaks, and the helms of Gondor and the Mark,  and 
