line 47171=>in white with a great mantle of blue and silver over all, and the long sword 
line 47172=>Glamdring at his side. 
line 47173=>     Gandalf  laughed. 'Well,  well,'  he  said, 'if they are afraid of just 
line 47174=>five of us, then we have met worse enemies on our travels. But  at any  rate 
line 47175=>they will give you peace at night while we stay.' 
line 47176=>     'How long will that be?' said Butterbur.  'I'll  not deny we  should be 
line 47177=>glad to have you about for a bit. You see, we're not used to  such troubles; 
line 47178=>and  the  Rangers have all gone  away,  folk tell  me.  I don't  think we've 
line 47179=>rightly understood  till  now what  they did for us. For there's  been worse 
line 47180=>than robbers about.  Wolves  were howling round  the fences last winter. And 
line 47181=>there's  dark shapes in the woods, dreadful  things that it makes the  blood 
line 47182=>run cold to think of. It's been very disturbing, if you  understand me.' 
line 47183=>     'I expect it has,' said Gandalf. 'Nearly all  lands have been disturbed 
line 47184=>these days, very disturbed. But cheer up,  Barliman!  You  have been  on the 
line 47185=>edge  of very great troubles, and I  am only glad to hear that  you have not 
line 47186=>been  deeper in.  But  better times are  coming. Maybe,  better than any you  
line 47187=>remember. The Rangers have returned. We came back with them.  And there is 
line 47188=>a 
line 47189=>king again, Barliman. He will soon be turning his mind this way. 
line 47190=>
line 47191=>####-     'Then the Greenway will  be opened again , and his  messengers will come 
