line 47236=>doubt  you'll be glad  of your beds too. Hey, Nob!' he called, going to  the 
line 47237=>door.  'Nob, you slowcoach!' 
line 47238=>     'Now!' he said to himself, slapping his  forehead. 'Now what  does that 
line 47239=>remind me of?' 
line 47240=>     'Not  another letter  you've forgotten. I hope,  Mr.  Butterbur?'  said 
line 47241=>Merry. 
line 47242=>     'Now, now, Mr.  Brandybuck, don't go reminding me of  that! But  there,  
line 47243=>you've  broken my  thought. Now where was I? Nob,  stables, ah! that was it. 
line 47244=>I've something that  belongs to  you.  If you recollect Bill  Ferny  and the 
line 47245=>horsethieving: his pony as you bought,  well,  it's  here. Come  back all of 
line 47246=>itself, it did. But where it had been to you know better than me. It was  as 
line 47247=>shaggy as an old dog and as lean as a clothes-rail, but it  was alive. Nob's 
line 47248=>looked after it.' 
line 47249=>     'What! My Bill?' cried Sam. 'Well, I was born lucky, whatever my gaffer  
line 47250=>may say. There's another  wish come true! Where is he?' Sam  would not go to 
line 47251=>bed until he had visited Bill in his stable. 
line 47252=>     The travellers stayed in Bree all the next day, and Mr. Butterbur could 
line 47253=>not complain of his  business next evening at any  rate. Curiosity  overcame  
line 47254=>all fears,  and his house was  crowded.  For a while  out of politeness  the 
line 47255=>hobbits  visited the Common  Room in the evening  and  answered a  good 
line 47256=>many 
line 47257=>questions. Bree memories being retentive,  Frodo was  asked many times if he 
line 47258=>had written his book. 
line 47259=>     'Not yet,' he answered. 'I am going home now to put my notes in order.' 
line 47260=>He promised to deal  with the amazing events at Bree, and so  give a bit  of 
line 47261=>interest to  a book that appeared likely to  treat mostly of  the remote and 
line 47262=>less important affairs 'away south'.  
line 47263=>     Then  one of  the  younger folk called for  a song. But at that a  hush 
line 47264=>fell,  and he was frowned  down,  and the  call  was not repeated. Evidently 
line 47265=>there was no wish for any uncanny events in the Common Room again. 
line 47266=>
line 47267=>####-     No trouble by day, nor  any sound by night, disturbed the peace of Bree 
line 47268=>while the travellers remained there; but the next morning they got up early, 
line 47269=>for  as the  weather  was still rainy they wished to reach the  Shire before 
line 47270=>night, and it was a long ride. The Bree folk were  all out  to see them off,  
line 47271=>and were in merrier mood than they had  been  for a year; and  those who had 
line 47272=>not seen the  strangers in all  their gear before gaped with wonder at them: 
line 47273=>at Gandalf with his white beard,  and  the light that  seemed to  gleam from 
line 47274=>him, as if his  blue mantle was on ly a  cloud over sunshine; and at the four 
line 47275=>hobbits like riders upon errantry out of almost  forgotten tales. Even those 
line 47276=>who had laughed at all the talk about the King began to think there might be 
line 47277=>some truth in it. 
line 47278=>     'Well, good luck on your road,  and good luck to your home-coming! said 
line 47279=>Mr. Butterbur. 'I  should have warned you before that  all's not well in the 
line 47280=>Shire neither, if what we  hear is true.  Funny goings on, they say. But one 
line 47281=>thing drives out another, and I was full of my own troubles. But i f I may be 
line 47282=>so  bold, you've come back  changed from your travels, and you look now like 
line 47283=>folk as  can deal with troubles  out of hand. I don't  doubt you'll soon set 
line 47284=>all to rights. Good  luck to you! And the  oftener you  come back the better  
line 47285=>I'll be pleased.' 
line 47286=>     They wished  him  farewell  and  rode  away,  and  passed  through  the 
line 47287=>West-gate and on  towards  the  Shire. Bill the  pony was with them, and  as 
line 47288=>before he  had a  good deal of  baggage, but he trotted along beside Sam and 
line 47289=>seemed well content. 
line 47290=>     'I wonder what old Barliman was hinting at,' said Frodo. 
line 47291=>     'I can guess some of it,' said Sam gloomily. 'What I saw in the Mirror: 
line 47292=>trees cut down and all, and my old gaffer turned out of the Row.  I ought to 
line 47293=>have hurried back quicker.' 
line 47294=>     'And something's wrong  with the Southfarthing evidently,'  said Merry. 
line 47295=>'There's a general shortage of pipe-weed.' 
line 47296=>     'Whatever it  is,' said Pippin, 'Lotho will be at the bottom of it: you  
line 47297=>can be sure of that.' 
line 47298=>     'Deep in,  but not at the bottom,' said Gandalf.  'You  have  forgotten 
line 47299=>Saruman. He began to take an interest in the Shire before Mordor did.' 
line 47300=>     'Well,  we've  got you  with us,' said Merry,  'so things  will soon be 
line 47301=>cleared up.' 
line 47302=>     'I am with you at  present,' said Gandalf, 'but soon I  shall not be. I 
line 47303=>am not coming to the Shire. You must  settle its affairs yourselves; that is 
line 47304=>
line 47305=>####-what  you have been trained for. Do you not yet understand? My time is over: 
line 47306=>it is no longer my  task to set things to rights, nor to help folk to do so. 
line 47307=>And  as for you ,  my dear friends, you will need no  help. You are  grown up 
line 47308=>now. Grown indeed very high; among the  great you are,  and I have no longer  
line 47309=>any fear at all for any of you. 
line 47310=>     'But if you would know, I am turning aside soon.  I  am going to have a  
line 47311=>long talk with Bombadil: such a talk as I have not had in all my time. He is 
line 47312=>a moss-gatherer, and I have been a  stone doomed to rolling. But  my rolling 
line 47313=>days are ending, and now we shall have much to say to one another.' 
line 47314=>     In a little while  they came to the point on the East  Road  where they 
line 47315=>had taken  leave of  Bombadil; and  they hoped and  half expected to see him 
line 47316=>standing there to greet them as they went by. But there was no sign  of him; 
line 47317=>and  there was  a grey mist on the Barrow-downs southwards, and  a deep veil 
line 47318=>over the Old Forest far away. 
line 47319=>     They halted and Frodo looked south wistfully. 'I should dearly  like to 
line 47320=>see the old fellow again,' he said. 'I wonder how he is getting on?' 
line 47321=>     'As well as ever, you may be sure,' said Gandalf. 'Quite untroubled and 
line 47322=>I  should guess, not much interested in anything  that we have done or seen, 
line 47323=>unless perhaps in our visits to the Ents. There may be a time  later for you  
line 47324=>to go and see him. But if I were you, I should press on now for home, or you  
line 47325=>will not come to the Brandywine Bridge before the gates are locked.' 
line 47326=>     'But there aren't any  gates,' said  Merry, 'not  on the Road; you know 
line 47327=>that quite well.  There's  the  Buckland Gate, of course; but they'll let me 
line 47328=>through that at any time.' 
line 47329=>     'There  weren't any  gates,  you mean,'  said Gandalf. 'I think you will 
line 47330=>find some  now. And  you might have  more trouble even  at the Buckland Gate 
line 47331=>than you think. But you'll! manage all right. Good -bye dear friends! Not for  
line 47332=>the last time, not yet. Good-bye!' 
line 47333=>     He turned Shadowfax off the  Road, and the great horse leaped the green 
line 47334=>dike that here ran beside  it;  and then at a cry from Gandalf he  was gone, 
line 47335=>racing towards the Barrow-downs like a wind from the North. 
line 47336=>     'Well here we are, just the four of us that started out together,' said 
line 47337=>Merry. 'We have left all the rest behind, one after another. It seems almost  
line 47338=>like a dream that has slowly faded.' 
line 47339=>     'Not to  me,'  said  Frodo. 'To me it  feels  more  like falling asleep 
line 47340=>again.' 
line 47341=> 
line 47342=>
line 47343=>####- 
line 47344=>
line 47345=>Chapter 8. The Scouring of the Shire 
line 47346=>
line 47347=> 
line 47348=> 
line 47349=>     It was after nightfall when, wet and tired, the travellers came at last  
line 47350=>to  the Brandywine, and  they found  the way  barred. At  either  end of the 
line 47351=>Bridge there was a great  spiked gate;  and on the further side of the river  
line 47352=>they could see that some new houses had been built: two-storeyed with narrow 
line 47353=>straight-sided   windows,  bare   and   dimly  lit,  all  very   gloomy  and 
line 47354=>un-Shirelike. 
line 47355=>     They  hammered on  the outer gate and called, but there was at first no  
line 47356=>answer;  and then to their  surprise someone blew a horn, and  the lights in 
line 47357=>the windows went out. A voice shouted in the dark: 
line 47358=>     'Who's that?  Be off! You  can't come in: Can't you read the notice: No 
line 47359=>admittance between sundown and sunrise?' 
line 47360=>     'Of  course we can't read the notice  in the  dark.' Sam shouted  back. 
line 47361=>'And if hobbits of the Shire are to be  kept out in the wet on  a night like 
line 47362=>this, I'll tear down your notice when I find it.' 
line 47363=>     At that a  window slammed, and a crowd  of hobbits with lanterns poured  
line 47364=>out of the house on the  left. They opened the  further gate, and some  came 
line 47365=>over the bridge. When they saw the travellers they seemed frightened. 
line 47366=>     'Come along!' said Merry, recognizing one of the hobbits. 'If you don't 
line 47367=>know me, Hob Hayward, you ought to. I am Merry Brandybuck, and I should 
line 47368=>like 
line 47369=>to know what  all this is  about,  and  what a Bucklander  like you is doing 
line 47370=>here. You used to be on the Hay Gate.' 
line 47371=>     'Bless  me!  It's Master Merry, to  be sure,  and all  dressed  up  for  
line 47372=>fighting!'  said  old Hob. 'Why,  they  said you was  dead! Lost in  the Old 
line 47373=>Forest by all accounts. I'm pleased to see you alive after all!' 
line 47374=>     'Then  stop gaping  at  me  through the  bars, and open the gate!' said 
line 47375=>Merry. 
line 47376=>     'I'm sorry, Master Merry, but we have orders.' 
line 47377=>     'Whose orders?' 
line 47378=>     'The Chief's up at Bag End.' 
line 47379=>     'Chief? Chief? Do you mean Mr. Lotho?' said Frodo. 
line 47380=>     'I suppose  so,  Mr.  Baggins;  but  we have  to say  just  "the Chief" 
line 47381=>nowadays.' 
line 47382=>
line 47383=>####-     'Do you indeed!'  said  Frodo. 'Well,  I am  glad he  has  dropped  the 
line 47384=>Baggins at any  rate. But  it is evidently high  time that the  family dealt 
line 47385=>with him and put him in his place.' 
line 47386=>     A  hush fell  on the hobbits  beyond the  gate. 'It  won't do  no  good 
line 47387=>talking that  way,' said one. 'He'll  get to hear  of it. And if you make so 
line 47388=>much noise, you'll wake the Chief's Big Man.' 
line 47389=>     'We shall wake him up in a way that will surprise him,' said Merry. 'If 
line 47390=>you mean that your precious Chief has  been hiring ruffians out of the wild, 
line 47391=>then we've not come back too  soon.' He sprang from his pony, and seeing the 
line 47392=>notice in  the light of the lanterns, he  tore it down and threw it over the 
line 47393=>gate. The  hobbits  backed  away and  made no move  to open  it.  'Come  on, 
line 47394=>Pippin!' said Merry. 'Two is enough.' 
line 47395=>     Merry and Pippin  c limbed the gate, and the hobbits fled.  Another horn 
line 47396=>sounded. Out of the bigger house on the right a large heavy figure  appeared 
line 47397=>against a light in the doorway. 
line 47398=>     'What's all this,' he snarled as he  came  forward. 'Gate-breaking? You  
line 47399=>clear out, or I'l l break your filthy little necks!' Then he  stopped, for he 
line 47400=>had caught the gleam of swords. 
line 47401=>     'Bill Ferny,' said Merry, 'if you don't open that gate in ten  seconds,  
line 47402=>you'll regret it. I shall set steel  to you, if you don't obey. And when you  
line 47403=>have opened the gates you will go  through  them and never return. You are a 
line 47404=>ruffian and a highway-robber.' 
line 47405=>     Bill  Ferny flinched and shuffled to the gate and unlocked it. 'Give me 
line 47406=>the key!' said Merry. But  the ruffian flung it  at his head and then darted 
line 47407=>out into the darkness. As he  passed the ponies one of them let fly with his 
line 47408=>heels  and just caught him as he ran. He went off with a yelp into the night 
line 47409=>and was never heard of again. 
line 47410=>     'Neat work, Bill,' said Sam, meaning the pony. 
line 47411=>     'So much for your  Big Man,' said Merry. 'We'll see the Chief later. In 
line 47412=>the meantime we want a lodging for the night, and as you seem to have pulled 
line 47413=>down the Bridge Inn and built  this dismal place instead, you'll have to put 
line 47414=>us up.' 
line 47415=>     'I am sorry, Mr. Merry,' said Hob, 'but it isn't allowed.' 
line 47416=>     'What isn't allowed?' 
line 47417=>     Taking in folk off-hand like and eating extra food, and  all that, said 
line 47418=>Hob. 
line 47419=>     'What's the  matter  with the place?'  said Merry. 'Has it  been a  bad 
line 47420=>
line 47421=>####-year, or what? I thought it had been a fine summer and harvest.' 
line 47422=>     'Well no, the year's been good enough,'  said  Hob. 'We grows a lot  of 
line 47423=>food,  but  we  don't  rightly  know what  becomes  of  it.  It's all  these 
line 47424=>"gatherers" and "sharers", I reckon, going round counting and measuring  and 
line 47425=>taking off to storage. They do more gathering than sharing, and we never see 
line 47426=>most of the stuff again.' 
line 47427=>     'Oh  come!' said  Pippin yawning.  'This  is all too  tiresome  for  me 
line 47428=>tonight.  We've  got food in our bags.  Just give  us a room to lie down in. 
line 47429=>It'll be better than many places I have seen.' 
line 47430=>     The hobbits at the gate still seemed ill  at  ease, evidently some rule 
line 47431=>or other was being broken;  but there was no gainsaying four such  masterful 
line 47432=>travellers, all armed, and two of them uncommonly  large and strong-looking. 
line 47433=>Frodo ordered the gates to be locked again. There was some sense at any rate 
line 47434=>in  keeping  a  guard,  while  ruffians  were  still about.  Then  the  four 
line 47435=>companions   went  into  the  hobbit  guard-house  and  made  themselves  as 
line 47436=>comfortable as they  could. It was a bare and ugly place, with a mean little 
line 47437=>grate that would not allow a good fire. In the upper  rooms were little rows 
line 47438=>of  hard  beds, and on every wall  there was  a notice and a list  of Rules. 
line 47439=>Pippin tore them down. There was no beer and very little food, but with what 
line 47440=>the travellers brought and shared out they all made a  fair meal; and Pippin 
line 47441=>broke Rule 4 by putting most of next day's allowance of wood on the fire. 
line 47442=>     'Well now,  what  about a  smoke,  while  you tell  us  what  has  been 
line 47443=>happening in the Shire?' he said. 
line 47444=>     'There isn't  no pipe-weed  now,' said  Hob; 'at  least  only  for  the 
line 47445=>Chief's  men. All the stocks seem to have gone. We do hear that waggon-loads 
line 47446=>of  it went away down the  old road out of the Southfarthing, over Sarn Ford 
line 47447=>way. That would  be the end  o' last year, after you left.  But it  had been 
line 47448=>going away quietly before that, in a small way. That Lotho--' 
line 47449=>     'Now you  shut up, Hob Hayward!' cried several of the others. 'You know 
line 47450=>talk o' that sor t isn't allowed. The Chief will hear of it, and we'll all be 
line 47451=>in trouble.' 
line 47452=>     'He wouldn't hear naught, if some of you here weren't sneaks,' rejoined 
line 47453=>Hob hotly. 
line 47454=>     'All right, all right!' said Sam. "That's quite enough. I don't want to 
line 47455=>hear no more. No welcome, no beer, no smoke, and a lot of rules and orc-talk 
line 47456=>instead.  I  hoped  to have a rest, but I can see there's work  and  trouble 
line 47457=>ahead. Let's sleep and forget it till morning!' 
line 47458=>
line 47459=>####-     The new  'Chief' evidently had  means of getting news. It  was  a  good 
line 47460=>forty miles from  the Bridge to Bag End,  but someone made the journey  in a 
line 47461=>hurry. So Frodo and his friends soon discovered. 
line 47462=>     They had not made any definite plans, but  had vaguely thought of going  
line 47463=>down to Crickhollow together first, and resting there a bit. But now, seeing 
line 47464=>what things  were like, they decided to go straight to Hobbiton. So the next 
line 47465=>day they  set out  along  the Road and jogged  along  steadily. The wind had 
line 47466=>dropped but the sky was grey. The land looked rather sad and forlorn; bu t it 
line 47467=>was after all the first of  November and the fag-end of Autumn. Still  there 
line 47468=>seemed  an unusual  amount of burning  going  on, and  smoke rose  from many 
line 47469=>points  round  about.  A great cloud of  it  was  going up  far  away in the 
line 47470=>direction of the Woody End. 
line 47471=>     As evening fell they were  drawing near to  Frogmorton, a village right 
line 47472=>on the Road, about  twenty -two  miles  from the Bridge. There  they meant to 
line 47473=>stay  the night; The Floating Log at  Frogmorton was a good inn. But as they  
line 47474=>came to the  east  end of the village they met a barrier with  a large  board 
line 47475=>saying NO ROAD; and behind it stood a large band of Shirriffs with staves in 
line 47476=>their hands  and  feathers in their caps,  looking both important and rather  
line 47477=>scared. 
line 47478=>     'What's all this?' said Frodo, feeling inclined to laugh. 
line 47479=>     This is  what it is, Mr. Baggins, said  the leader  of the Shirriffs, a  
line 47480=>two-feather hobbit: 'You're arrested for  Gate-breaking,  and  Tearing up of 
line 47481=>Rules,  and  Assaulting  Gate-keepers,  and  Trespassing,  and  Sleeping  in 
line 47482=>Shire-buildings without Leave, and Bribing Guards with Food.' 
line 47483=>     'And what else?' said Frodo. 
line 47484=>     'That'll do to go on with,' said the Shirriff-leader. 
line 47485=>     'I  can add some more, if  you like it,' said Sam. 'Calling your  Chief 
line 47486=>Names, Wishing to punch his Pimply Face, and Thinking you  Shirriffs look  a  
line 47487=>lot of Tom-fools.' 
line 47488=>     'There now, Mister, that'll do.  It's the Chief's orders that you're to 
line 47489=>come  along quiet. We're going to  take you to Bywater and hand  you over to 
line 47490=>the Chief's Men; and when he deals with your case you can have your say. But 
line 47491=>if  you don't want  to  stay in the  Lockholes any longer than you  need,  I 
line 47492=>should cut the say short, if I was you.' 
line 47493=>     To  the  discomfiture  of  the Shirriffs  Frodo  and his companions all 
line 47494=>roared with laughter.  'Don't  be absurd!' said Frodo.  'I am  going where I 
line 47495=>please, and in my own time. I happen to be going to Bag End on business, but 
line 47496=>
line 47497=>####-if you insist on going too, well that is your affair.' 
line 47498=>     'Very  well, Mr. Baggins,' said the  leader, pushing the barrier aside. 
line 47499=>'But don't forget I've arrested you.' 
line 47500=>     'I won't,'  said Frodo. 'Never.  But  I may forgive  you. Now I am  not 
line 47501=>going any  further today, so if you'll kindly escort me to The Floating Log, 
line 47502=>I'll be obliged.' 
line 47503=>     'I   can't  do   that,  Mr.  Baggins.  The  inn's   closed.  There's  a  
line 47504=>Shirriff-house at the far end of the village. I'll take you there. ' 
line 47505=>     'All right,' said Frodo. 'Go on and we'll follow.' 
line 47506=>     Sam had been looking the Shirriffs up and down and had spotted one that 
line 47507=>he knew.  'Hey, come here  Robin Smallburrow!' he called.  'I want a word with 
line 47508=>you.' 
line 47509=>     With a sheepish glance at his leader, who looked  wrathful but did  not  
line 47510=>dare to interfere, Shirriff Smallburrow fell back and walked beside Sam, who 
line 47511=>got down off his pony. 
line 47512=>     'Look here, Cock -robin!' said  Sam. 'You're Hobbiton-bred and ought  to 
line 47513=>have more sense,  coming a -waylaying Mr. Frodo and all.  And what's all this 
line 47514=>about the inn being closed?' 
line 47515=>     'They're all closed,' said Robin.  'The  Chief  doesn't hold with beer. 
line 47516=>Leastways  that is how it started. But now I reckon it's his Men that has it 
line 47517=>all.  And he  doesn't  hold with folk moving about; so if they  will or they 
line 47518=>must, then they has to go to the Shirriff-house and explain their business.' 
line 47519=>     'You  ought to   be ashamed of  yourself having anything to do with such 
line 47520=>nonsense,' said Sam. 'You used to like the inside of an inn better than  the 
line 47521=>outside yourself. You were always popping in, on duty or off.' 
line 47522=>     'And so I would be still,  Sam,  if I  could. But don't be  hard on me. 
line 47523=>What  can I  do? You know  how I went for a Shirriff seven years ago, before 
line 47524=>any of this began. Gave me a chance of walking round the  country and seeing 
line 47525=>folk, and hearing the news,  and knowing where the  good beer was.  But  now 
line 47526=>it's different.' 
line 47527=>     'But you can give it  up,  stop Shirriffing, if it has  stopped being a  
line 47528=>respectable job,' said Sam. 
line 47529=>     'We're not allowed to,' said Robin. 
line 47530=>     'If  I hear  not allowed much oftener,' said  Sam, 'I'm  going  to  get 
line 47531=>angry.' 
line 47532=>     'Can't say as I'd be sorry to see  it,'  said Robin lowering his voice. 
line 47533=>'If we  all got angry together something might be done. But  it's these Men, 
line 47534=>
line 47535=>####-Sam, the Chief's Men. He sends them round everywhere, and if any of us small 
line 47536=>folk stand  up for our rights, they drag him off to the Lockholes. They took  
line 47537=>old Flourdumpling, old Will Whitfoot the Mayor,  first,  and they've taken a  
line 47538=>lot more. Lately it's been getting worse. Often they beat 'em now.' 
line 47539=>     'Then  why do you do their work far them?' said Sam  angrily. 'Who sent 
line 47540=>you to Frogmorton?' 
line 47541=>     'No one did. We stay  here in the big  Shirriff-house. We're the  First 
line 47542=>Eastfarthing Troop now. There's hundreds of Shirriffs all told and they want  
line 47543=>more, with  all these new rules. Most of them  are in it against their will, 
line 47544=>but not all. Even in  the Shire there are some as like  minding other folk's 
line 47545=>business and talking big. And there's worse than  that: there's a  few as do 
line 47546=>spy-work for the Chief and his Men.' 
line 47547=>     'Ah! So that's how you had news of us, is it?' 
line 47548=>     'That's right. We  aren't allowed to send by it  now, but they use  the 
line 47549=>old Quick Post service,  and keep  special runners at  different points. One 
line 47550=>came in  from  Whitfurrows  last  night with a "secret message", and another  
line 47551=>took it on from  here. And a message came back this afternoon saying you was 
line 47552=>to be  arrested and taken to Bywater, not direct to the Lockholes. The Chief 
line 47553=>wants to see you at once, evidently.' 
line 47554=>     'He won't be so eager when Mr. Frodo has finished with him,' said Sam. 
line 47555=>     The Shirriff-house at Frogmorton was as bad as the Bridge-house. It had 
line 47556=>only one storey,  but it  had the  same narrow windows, and it was built  of 
line 47557=>ugly pale bricks,  badly laid. Inside  it was damp and cheerless, and supper 
line 47558=>was served on a long  bare table that  had not been scrubbed  for weeks. The 
line 47559=>food  deserved no better  setting. The travellers  were  glad  to  leave the 
line 47560=>place.  It was about eighteen  miles to  Bywater,  and they  set off at  ten 
line 47561=>o'clock  in the morning. They  would have started earlier, only the delay so 
line 47562=>plainly annoyed the Shirriff-leader. The west wind had shifted northward and 
line 47563=>it was turning colder, but the rain was gone. 
line 47564=>     It was rather  a comic  cavalcade that left the village, though the few 
line 47565=>folk that came out to  stare at the  'get-up' of the travellers did not seem 
line 47566=>quite sure whether laughing was allowed. A dozen Shirriffs had been told off 
line 47567=>as escort to the  'prisoners'; but Merry made  them  march  in front,  while 
line 47568=>Frodo and his friends rode behind. Merry, Pippin, and  Sam sat at their ease 
line 47569=>laughing and talking  and singing, while the Shirriffs stumped along  trying 
line 47570=>to  look stern and important. Frodo, however, was  silent  and looked rather  
line 47571=>sad and thoughtful. 
line 47572=>
line 47573=>####-     The last person  they passed was a sturdy  old gaffer clipping a hedge. 
line 47574=>'Hullo, hu llo!' he jeered. 'Now who's arrested who?' 
line 47575=>     Two of the Shirriffs immediately  left the  party and went towards him. 
line 47576=>'Leader!' said  Merry. 'Order your  fellows back to their places at once, if 
line 47577=>you don't want me to deal with them!' 
line 47578=>     The two hobbits at a sharp word from the leader came back sulkily. 'Now 
line 47579=>get on!' said Merry,  and after that  the  travellers  saw  to it that their 
line 47580=>ponies'  pace was quick enough to  push  the Shirriffs along as fast as they 
line 47581=>could go. The sun came out,  and in spite of the  chilly wind they were soon  
line 47582=>puffing and sweating. 
line 47583=>     At  the Three-Farthing  Stone they  gave  it  up.  They had done nearly 
line 47584=>fourteen  miles with only one rest  at noon. It was now three  o'clock. They 
line 47585=>were hungry and very footsore and they could not  stand the pace. 
line 47586=>     'Well, come along in your own time!' said Merry. 'We are going on.' 
line 47587=>     'Good-bye, Cock -robin!' said Sam. 'I'll wait for you outside  The Green 
line 47588=>Dragon, if you haven't forgotten where that is. Don't dawdle on the way!' 
line 47589=>     'You're  br eaking  arrest,  that's what you're doing,'  said the leader  
line 47590=>ruefully, 'and I can't be answerable.' 
line 47591=>     'We shall  break  a  good many things  yet, and not ask you to answer ' 
line 47592=>said Pippin. 'Good luck to you!' 
line 47593=>     The  travellers trotted on, and as the  sun began to  sink towards  the 
line 47594=>White Downs far away on the western horizon they came to Bywater by its 
line 47595=>wide 
line 47596=>pool; and there  they had their first really  painful shock. This  was Frodo 
line 47597=>and Sam's own country, and they found out  now that they cared about it  more 
line 47598=>than any other place in  the world. Many  of  the houses that they had known  
line 47599=>were missing. Some seemed to  have been burned down. The pleasant row of 
line 47600=>old 
line 47601=>hobbit-holes in the  bank on the north  side  of the Pool were deserted, and 
line 47602=>their little  gardens that used to run down bright to the water's  edge were 
line 47603=>rank with weeds. Worse,  there was a whole line  of the ugly new houses  all 
line 47604=>along Pool Side, where the Hobbiton Road ran close to the bank. An avenue of 
line 47605=>trees had stood there. They were all  gone.   And  looking with dismay up the 
line 47606=>road towards Bag  End they saw  a  tall chimney of brick in the distance. It 
line 47607=>was pouring out black smoke into the evening air. 
line 47608=>     Sam was beside himself. 'I'm going right on, Mr. Frodo!' he cried. 'I'm 
line 47609=>going to see what's up. I want to find my gaffer.' 
line 47610=>
line 47611=>####-     'We  ought  to find  out first what we're in for, Sam,'  said Merry. 'I  
line 47612=>guess  that  the "Chief" will have a gang of ruffians handy.  We  had better  
line 47613=>find someone who will tell us how things are round here.' 
line 47614=>     But in the village of Bywater all  the houses and holes  were shut, and 
line 47615=>no  one greeted them. They wondered  at  this, but they soon  discovered the 
line 47616=>reason  of  it. When they  reached  The Green Dragon, the last house  on the 
line 47617=>Hobbiton side, now lifeless and with broken  windows, they were disturbed to 
line 47618=>see half a dozen  large ill-favoured Men lounging against the inn-wall; they 
line 47619=>were squint-eyed and sallow-faced. 
line 47620=>     'Like that friend of Bill Ferny's at Bree,' said Sam. 
line 47621=>     'Like many that I saw at Isengard,' muttered Merry. 
line 47622=>     The ruffians had clubs in their  hands  and  horns by their  belts, but 
line 47623=>they had no other weapons, as far as could be seen.  As the  travellers rode 
line 47624=>up they left the wall and walked into the road, blocking the way. 
line 47625=>     'Where d'you  think   you're  going?'  said  one,  the largest and  most  
line 47626=>evil-looking of the crew.  'There's no road for you any  further.  And where 
line 47627=>are those precious Shirriffs?' 
line 47628=>     'Coming along nicely,'  said  Merry.  'A  little  footsore, perhaps. We 
line 47629=>promised to wait for them here.' 
line 47630=>     'Garn, what did I  say?' said the ruffian to his mates. 'I told Sharkey 
line 47631=>it was no  good trusting those little fools. Some of our chaps ought to have 
line 47632=>been sent.' 
line 47633=>     'And  what difference would that have made,  pray?' said Merry. 'We are 
line 47634=>not used to footpads in this country, but we know how to deal with them.' 
line 47635=>     'Footpads, eh?'  said the man: 'So that's your tone, is  it? Change it, 
line 47636=>or we'll change  it for you.  You little folk are getting too  uppish. Don't  
line 47637=>you trust too much in the Boss's kind heart. Sharkey's come now and he'll do 
line 47638=>what Sharkey says.' 
line 47639=>     'And what may that be?' said Frodo quietly. 
line 47640=>     'This country wants waking up and setting to rights,' said the ruffian, 
line 47641=>'and Sharkey's going to do it; and make it hard, if you drive him to it. You  
line 47642=>need a  bigger Boss. And you'll get one  before the year is  out, if there's 
line 47643=>any more trouble. Then you'll learn a thing or two, you little rat-folk.' 
line 47644=>     'Indeed. I am glad to hear of your plans,' said Frodo. 'I am on  my way 
line 47645=>to call on Mr. Lotho, and he may be interested to hear of them too.' 
line 47646=>     The ruffian laughed. 'Lotho! He knows all right. Don't you worry. He'll 
line 47647=>do what  Sharkey says. Because if a  Boss  gives trouble, we can change him. 
line 47648=>
line 47649=>####-See? And if little folks try to push in where they're not wanted, we can put 
line 47650=>them out of mischief. See?' 
line 47651=>     'Yes, I see,' said Frodo.  'For one thing, I see that you're behind the 
line 47652=>times  and the news here. Much has happened  since you  left the South. Your 
line 47653=>day is over, and all other ruffians'. The Dark Tower has  fallen, and  there 
line 47654=>is  a  King in  Gondor. And  Isengard has been destroyed,  and your precious 
line 47655=>master is  a beggar in  the wilderness. I passed him on the road. The King's 
line 47656=>messengers will ride up the Greenway now not bullies from Isengard. ' 
line 47657=>     The  man stared at him  and smiled.  'A  beggar in  the wilderness!' he 
line 47658=>mocked.  'Oh, is he  indeed? Swagger it, swagger it, my little cock -a -whoop.  
line 47659=>But that won't  stop us  living  in this fat  little country  where you have 
line 47660=>lazed long enough. And' - he snapped his fingers in Frodo's face   -  'King's 
line 47661=>messengers! That for them! When I see one, I'll take notice, perhaps.' 
line 47662=>     This was too much for  Pippin. His thoughts  went back to  the Field of 
line 47663=>Cormallen, and here was a squint-eyed rascal calling the Ring-bearer  'little 
line 47664=>cock -a -whoop'. He cast back his cloak, flashed out his sword, and the silver  
line 47665=>and sable of Gondor gleamed on him as he rode forward. 
line 47666=>     'I  am a  messenger of  the  King,' he  said. 'You are speaking  to the 
line 47667=>King's friend,  and one  of the most renowned in all the lands  of the West. 
line 47668=>You are a ruffian and a fool. Down on your knees in the road and ask pardon, 
line 47669=>or I will set this troll's bane in you!' 
line 47670=>     The sword glinted in the westering sun. Merry and Sam drew their swords 
line 47671=>also a nd rode  up to support  Pippin;  but Frodo did  not move. The ruffians 
line 47672=>gave back. Scaring  Breeland peasants, and  bullying bewildered hobbits, had 
line 47673=>been their work. Fearless  hobbits with  bright swords and grim faces were a  
line 47674=>great surprise.  And there  was a note in the voices of these newcomers that 
line 47675=>they had not heard before. It chilled them with fear. 
line 47676=>     'Go!'  said Merry. 'If you trouble this  village again, you will regret 
line 47677=>it.'  The three  hobbits  came  on, and then  the ruffians  turned and  fled 
line 47678=>running away up the Hobbiton Road; but they blew their horns as they ran. 
line 47679=>     'Well, we've come back none too soon,' said Merry. 
line 47680=>     'Not a day too soon. Perhaps too late, at any rate to save Lotho,' said 
line 47681=>Frodo. 'Miserable fool, but I am sorry for him.' 
line 47682=>     'Save Lotho? Whatever do you mean?' said Pippin. 'Destroy  him I should 
line 47683=>say.' 
line 47684=>     'I don't think you quite understand things, Pippin,' said Frodo. 'Lotho 
line 47685=>never meant things to come to this pass. He has been a wicked fool, but he's 
line 47686=>
line 47687=>####-caught now. The  ruffians are on top, gathering, robbing  and bullying,  and 
line 47688=>running or ruining things  as they  like, in his name.  And not  in his name 
line 47689=>even for much longer. He's a  prisoner in Bag  End  now,  I expect, and very 
line 47690=>frightened. We ought to try and rescue him.' 
line 47691=>     'Well I  am staggered!' said  Pippin.  'Of all the ends to  our journey 
line 47692=>that is the very last I should  have thought  of: to have to fight half-orcs 
line 47693=>and ruffians in the Shire itself - to rescue Lotho Pimple!' 
line 47694=>     'Fight?'  said  Frodo.  'Well,  I  suppose it  may  come  to  that. But 
line 47695=>remember: there is to be  no  slaying of hobbits, not even if they have gone 
line 47696=>over to the other side. Really gone over, I mean; not just obeying ruffians' 
line 47697=>orders  because they  are  frightened.  No hobbit has ever killed another on  
line 47698=>purpose in the Shire, and it is not to begin now. And nobody is to be killed 
line 47699=>at all,  if it  can be helped. Keep your tempers and hold your hands  to the 
line 47700=>last possible moment!' 
line 47701=>     'But  if  there  are many of  these  ruffians,'  said  Merry,  'it will 
line 47702=>certainly mean fighting. You won't rescue Lotho, or the Shire, just by being 
line 47703=>shocked and sad, my dear Frodo.' 
line 47704=>     'No,'  said Pippin. 'It  won't be  so easy scaring them  a second time. 
line 47705=>They were taken by  surprise. You heard  that horn-blowing? Ev idently  there 
line 47706=>are other ruffians near at hand. They'll be much bolder when there's more of 
line 47707=>them together. We ought  to think of taking cover somewhere for  the  night. 
line 47708=>After all we're only four, even if we are armed.' 
line 47709=>     'I've an idea,' said  Sam.  'Let's go  to old  Tom Cotton's down  South 
line 47710=>Lane! He  always was a  stout fellow. And he has a lot of lads that were all 
line 47711=>friends of mine.' 
line 47712=>     'No!'  said Merry.  'It's  no good "getting under cover".  That is just  
line 47713=>what people have been  doing, and just what these  ruffians like.  They will 
line 47714=>simply come  down on us in force, corner us, and  then drive us out, or burn 
line 47715=>us in. No, we have got to do something at once.' 
line 47716=>     'Do what?' said Pippin. 
line 47717=>     'Raise the Shire!' said Merry. 'Now! Wake all our people! They hate all 
line 47718=>this, you can  see: all of them except perhaps one or two rascals, and a few 
line 47719=>fools that want to be important, but  don't at all understand what is really 
line 47720=>going  on. But Shire-folk have  been  so comfortable so long they don't know 
line 47721=>what to  do. They just want  a match, though, and they'll go up in fire. The 
line 47722=>Chief's Men must know that. They'll try to stamp on us and put us out quick. 
line 47723=>We've only got a very short time. 
line 47724=>
line 47725=>####-     'Sam, you can make  a  dash for  Cotton's  farm, if  you like. He's the 
line 47726=>chief person round here,  and the sturdiest. Come on! I am going to blow the 
line 47727=>horn of Rohan, and give them all some music they have never heard before.' 
line 47728=>     They rode back to the middle of the village. There Sam turned aside and 
line 47729=>galloped off down the  lane that led south to Cotton's.  He had not gone far 
line 47730=>when he heard a sudden clear horn-call go up ringing  into the sky. Far over  
line 47731=>hill and field it echoed; and  so compelling  was that call that Sam himself 
line 47732=>almost turned and dashed back. His pony reared and neighed. 
line 47733=>     'On, lad! On!' he cried. 'We'll be going back soon.' 
line 47734=>     Then  he heard  Merry  change the  note, and  up went the  Horn-cry  of 
line 47735=>Buckland, shaking the air. 
line 47736=>     Awake! Awake! Fear, Fire, Foes! Awake! 
line 47737=>     Fire, Foes! Awake! 
line 47738=>     Behind him Sam heard a hubbub of voices and a great din and slamming of 
line 47739=>doors. In front of him lights sprang out in  the gloaming; dogs barked; feet 
line 47740=>came running. Before he got  to the lane's end there was Farmer Cotton  with 
line 47741=>three  of his lads, Young Tom,  Jolly, and Nick,  hurrying towards him. They 
line 47742=>had axes in their hands, and barred the way. 
line 47743=>     'Nay! It's not one of them ruffians,' Sam heard the farmer say. 'It's a  
line 47744=>hobbit by the size of it, but all dressed up queer. Hey!' he cried. 'Who are 
line 47745=>you, and what's all this to-do? ' 
line 47746=>     'It's Sam, Sam Gamgee. I've come back.' 
line 47747=>     Farmer Cotton came up close  and stared at him in the twilight. 'Well!' 
line 47748=>he exclaimed. 'The voice is right, and your face is  no worse  than  it was,  
line 47749=>Sam. But  I should a' passed you in the street in that gear. You've been  in 
line 47750=>foreign parts, seemingly. We feared you were dead.' 
line 47751=>     'That I ain't!'  said Sam.  'Nor Mr. Frodo. He's here and  his friends. 
line 47752=>And  that's  the to-do. They're raising the Shire. We're going to clear  out 
line 47753=>these ruffians, and their Chief too. We're starting now.' 
line 47754=>     'Good, good!' cried Farmer Cotton.  'So  it's  begun at last! I've been 
line 47755=>itching for trouble all this year, but folks wouldn't help. And I've had the 
line 47756=>wife  and Rosie to think of. These ruffians don't stick at nothing. But come 
line 47757=>on now, lads! Bywater is up! We must be in it!' 
line 47758=>     'What about Mrs.  Cotton and Rosie?' said Sam. 'It  isn't safe  yet for  
line 47759=>them to be left all alone.' 
line 47760=>     'My Nibs  is  with them. But you  can  go and help him,  if you  have a  
line 47761=>mind,' said Farmer Cotton with a grin. Then  he and his sons ran off towards 
line 47762=>
line 47763=>####-the village. 
line 47764=>     Sam hurried  to  the house. By the  large round  door at the top of the 
line 47765=>steps  from the wide yard stood  Mrs. Cotton and Rosie, and Nibs in front of 
line 47766=>them grasping a hay-fork. 
line 47767=>     'It's  me!' shouted Sam  as he trotted up.  'Sam Gamgee! So  don't  try 
line 47768=>prodding me, Nibs. Anyway, I've a mail -shirt on me.' 
line 47769=>     He  jumped down from his pony and went up the steps. They stared at him 
