line 47772=>but I've been expecting you since the Spring. You haven't hurried have you?' 
line 47773=>     'Perhaps  not,'  said Sam abashed. 'But I'm hurrying now. We're setting 
line 47774=>about the ruffians, and I've got to get back to Mr. Frodo. But I thought I'd 
line 47775=>have a look and see how Mrs. Cotton was keeping, and you, Rosie.' 
line 47776=>     'We're keeping nicely, thank you,' said Mrs. Cotton.  'Or should be, if 
line 47777=>it weren't for these thieving ruffians.' 
line 47778=>     'Well, be  off with you!' said Rosie. 'If you've been looking after Mr. 
line 47779=>Frodo all this while, what d'you want  to leave  him for, as soon  as things 
line 47780=>look dangerous?' 
line 47781=>     This  was  too much  for Sam. It  needed a  week's answer, or none.  He 
line 47782=>turned away and mounted his pony. But as he started off, Rosie  ran down the 
line 47783=>steps. 
line 47784=>     'I think you look fine, Sam,'  she  said. 'Go on now! But  take care of 
line 47785=>yourself, and come straight back as soon as you have settled the ruffians!' 
line 47786=>     When  Sam  got back  he found the  whole village roused. Already, apart  
line 47787=>from many younger lads,  more  than a hundred sturdy hobbits were  assembled 
line 47788=>with axes, and heavy  hammers, and  long knives, and stout staves: and a few 
line 47789=>had hunting-bows. More were still coming in from outlying farms. 
line 47790=>     Some of the village-folk had lit  a large fire, just to enliven things,  
line 47791=>and also because it was one of the things forbidden by the Chief. It  burned 
line 47792=>bright as  night came on. Others at Merry's orders  were setting up barriers 
line 47793=>across the road at each end of the  village. When  the Shirriffs  came up to 
line 47794=>the lower  one  they were  dumbfounded; but  as soon as they saw how  things 
line 47795=>were, most of  them took off  their  feathers and joined in  the revolt. The 
line 47796=>others slunk away. 
line 47797=>     Sam found Frodo and his friends by the  fire talking to old Tom Cotton, 
line 47798=>while an admiring crowd of Bywater folk stood round and stared. 
line 47799=>     'Well, what's the next move?' said Farmer Cotton. 
line 47800=>
line 47801=>####-     'I  can't  say,'  said Frodo, 'until  I  know more. How  many  of these 
line 47802=>ruffians are there?' 
line 47803=>     'That's  hard  to tell,' said  Cotton. 'They moves  about and comes and 
line 47804=>goes. There's  sometimes  fifty of them  in their sheds up Hobbiton way; but 
line 47805=>they go out  from there roving round,  thieving  or "gathering" as they call 
line 47806=>it. Still there's seldom  less  than a score  round the  Boss, as they names 
line 47807=>him. He's at Bag End, or was; but he don't go outside the rounds now. No one 
line 47808=>s seen him at all, in fact, for a week or two; but the Men  don't let no one 
line 47809=>go near.' 
line 47810=>     'Hobbiton's not their only place, is it?' said Pippin. 
line 47811=>     'No, more's the pity,' said Cotton. 'There's a  good few down south  in 
line 47812=>Longbottom and by Sarn Ford, I hear; and some more lurking in the Woody 
line 47813=>End; 
line 47814=>and they've sheds at Waymeet.  And then there's  the Lockholes, as they call  
line 47815=>'em:  the old  storage-tunnels  at  Michel Delving  that  they've made  into 
line 47816=>prisons  for  those as stand up to  them. Still I  reckon there's  not above 
line 47817=>three hundred of  them in the Shire all told, and  maybe less. We can master  
line 47818=>them, if we stick together.' 
line 47819=>     'Have they got any weapons?' asked Merry. 
line 47820=>     'Whips,  knives, and  clubs, enough for their dirty  work:  that's  all 
line 47821=>they've showed so far,' said Cotton. 'But I dare say they've got other gear, 
line 47822=>if it comes to fighting. Some have bows, anywa y. They've shot one or two  of 
line 47823=>our folk.' 
line 47824=>     'There  you are, Frodo!' said Merry. 'I knew we should have  to  fight. 
line 47825=>Well, they started the killing.' 
line 47826=>     'Not exactly,' said Cotton. 'Leastways not the  shooting. Tooks started 
line 47827=>that. You see our dad Mr. Peregrin, he's never had no truck with this Lotho, 
line 47828=>not  from the beginning: said that if anyone was going to play the chief  at 
line 47829=>this time of day,  it would  be the right Thain of the Shire and no upstart. 
line 47830=>And when Lotho sent his Men they got no  change out of him. Tooks are lucky, 
line 47831=>they've got those deep holes in the Green Hills,  the Great  Smials and all, 
line 47832=>and the  ruffians can't come at 'em; and they won't let the ruffians come on 
line 47833=>their land.  If they  do, Tooks hunt  'em. Tooks shot three for prowling and 
line 47834=>robbing.  After  that the  ruffians turned nastier. And they  keep  a pretty 
line 47835=>close watch on Tookland. No one gets in nor out of it now.' 
line 47836=>     'Good  for the  Tooks!' cried Pippin.  'But someone is going  to get in 
line 47837=>again, now. I am off to the Smials. Anyone coming with me to Tuckborough?' 
line 47838=>
line 47839=>####-     Pippin rode off with half  a dozen lads on ponies.  'See you soon!'  he 
line 47840=>cried. 'It's only  fourteen miles or so over the fields. I'll bring you back  
