line 47860=>down  the  road. They saw the barrier and laughed. They did not imagine that 
line 47861=>ther e  was anything in  this little  land  that would stand up to  twenty of 
line 47862=>their kind together. 
line 47863=>     The hobbits  opened the barrier and stood aside.  'Thank you!' the  Men 
line 47864=>jeered. 'Now run home to bed before you're whipped.' Then they marched along 
line 47865=>the street  shouting: 'Put those lights out! Get indoors  and stay there! Or 
line 47866=>we'll take fifty  of you  to the Lockholes for  a year. Get in!  The Boss is 
line 47867=>losing his temper.' 
line 47868=>     No one paid any heed to their orders; but as the  ruffians passed, they 
line 47869=>closed in  qu ietly behind and followed them.  When the  Men reached the fire 
line 47870=>there was Farmer Cotton standing all alone warming his hands. 
line 47871=>     'Who  are   you,  and  what   d'you   think  you're  doing?'  said  the 
line 47872=>ruffian-leader. 
line 47873=>     Farmer Cotton looked at him slowly. 'I was just going to ask you that,' 
line 47874=>he said. 'This isn't your country, and you're not wanted.' 
line 47875=>     'Well, you're wanted  anyhow,' said the leader. 'We want you.  Take him 
line 47876=>
line 47877=>####-lads! Lockholes for him, and give him something to keep him quiet!' 
line 47878=>     The Men took one step forward  and stopped short. There rose a  roar of 
line 47879=>voices all round them,  and suddenly  they were aware that Farmer Cotton was 
line 47880=>not  all  alone. They  were surrounded.  In  the dark  on  the  edge  of the 
