line 47882=>There was nearly two hundred of them, all holding some weapon. 
line 47883=>     Merry stepped  forward. 'We have met before,' he  said  to  the leader, 
line 47884=>'and I warned you not to come  back here. I warn you again: you are standing 
line 47885=>in  the  light and you are covered  by archers. If you lay a finger on  this 
line 47886=>farmer, or on anyone  else, you will be  shot at once.  Lay down any weapons 
line 47887=>that you have!' 
line 47888=>     The leader looked round. He was trapped. But he was not scared, not now 
line 47889=>with a score of his fellows to  back  him.  He knew too little of hobbits to 
line 47890=>understand his peril.  Foolishly he  decided to  fight. It  would be easy to 
line 47891=>break out. 
line 47892=>     'At 'em lads!' he cried. 'Let 'em have it!' 
line 47893=>     With a  long knife in his left hand and a  club in  the other he made a  
line 47894=>rush  at the  ring, trying  to burst out back towards Hobbiton.  He aimed  a  
line 47895=>savage blow at Merry who stood in his way.  He fell dead with four arrows in 
line 47896=>him: 
line 47897=>     That was enough for the others.  They gave in. Their weapons were taken  
line 47898=>from them, and they were roped  together,  and marched  off to  an empty hut 
line 47899=>that they had built themselves, and there they were tied hand  and foot, and 
line 47900=>locked up under guard. The dead leader was dragged off and buried. 
line 47901=>     'Seems almost too easy  after all, don't it?' said Cotton.  'I said  we 
line 47902=>could master them. But we needed a call. You came  back in the nick o' time, 
line 47903=>Mr. Merry.' 
line 47904=>     'There's more to be done still,' said Merry. 'If  you're  right in your 
line 47905=>reckoning, we haven't dealt with a tithe of them yet. But it's  dark now.  I 
line 47906=>think the  next stroke must  wait  until morning. Then  we must  call on the 
line 47907=>Chief.' 
line 47908=>     'Why not  now?' said Sam.  'It's not much more than  six o'clock. And I 
line 47909=>want to see my gaffer. D'you know what's come of him, Mr. Cotton?' 
line 47910=>     'He's not too  well,  and not too bad, Sam,' said the farmer. 'They dug 
line 47911=>up Bagshot Row, and that  was a sad blow  to  him. He's in one of  them  new 
line 47912=>houses that  the Chief's Men  used to  build while  they still did any  work 
line 47913=>other than burning and thieving:  not  above a mile from the end of Bywater. 
line 47914=>
line 47915=>####-But he comes around to me, when he gets a chance,  and I see he's better fed 
line 47916=>than some of the poor bodies. All against The Rules, of course. I'd have had 
line 47917=>him with me, but that wasn't allowed.' 
line 47918=>     'Thank'ee indeed, Mr. Cotton, and I'll never forget it,' said Sam. 'But 
line 47919=>I want to see him. That Boss and that Sharkey, as they  spoke of, they might  
line 47920=>do a mischief up there before the morning.' 
line 47921=>     'All right, Sam,' said Cotton.  'Choose a  lad or two, and go and fetch 
line 47922=>him to my  house. You'll not have need to  go near the old  Hobbiton village 
line 47923=>over Water. My Jolly here will show you.' 
line 47924=>     Sam went off. Merry arranged for look -outs round the village and guards 
line 47925=>at  the barriers during  the  night. Then he and Frodo went off with  Farmer  
line 47926=>Cotton. They sat with  the family in the warm kitchen, and the Cottons asked 
line 47927=>a  few polite  questions about  their travels,  but hardly  listened  to the 
line 47928=>answers: they were far more concerned with events in the Shire. 
line 47929=>     'It all began with Pimple, as we call him,' said Farmer Cotton; 'and it 
line 47930=>began as soon as you'd  gone off, Mr. Frodo.  He'd funny  ideas had  Pimple. 
line 47931=>Seems he wanted to own everything himself, and  then order other folk about. 
line 47932=>It soon came out that he already did own a sight more than was good for him; 
line 47933=>and  he was  always grabbing  more, though  where he got  the  money  was  a  
line 47934=>mystery:  mills and malt-houses and  inns,  and farms, and leaf-plantations.  
line 47935=>He'd already bought Sandyman's mill before he came to Bag End, seemingly. 
line 47936=>     'Of course he started with a lot of property in the Southfarthing which 
line 47937=>he had from his dad; and it seems he'd been selling a  lot o' the best leaf,  
line 47938=>and sending it away quietly for a year or two.  But at the end o'  last year 
line 47939=>he began sending away  loads of  stuff,  not only leaf. Things  began to get 
line 47940=>short, and winter coming on, too. Folk got angry, but  he had his answer.  A 
line 47941=>lot of Men, ruffians mostly,  came with great waggons, some to carry off the 
line 47942=>goods south-away,  and  others  to stay. And  more came.  And before we knew 
line 47943=>where we were they were planted here  and there all over the Shire, and were 
line 47944=>felling trees  and digging and building themselves sheds and houses just  as 
line 47945=>they liked. At first goods and damage was paid  for by Pimple; but soon they 
line 47946=>began lording it around and taking what they wanted. 
line 47947=>     'Then there was a bit  of trouble,  but not  enough. Old Will the Mayor  
