line 48264=>grovelled, and  turned and made off. But at that something snapped: suddenly 
line 48265=>Wormtongue rose up, drawing a hidden knife, and then with a snarl like a dog 
line 48266=>he sprang on Saruman's back, jerked his head back, cut his throat, and  with 
line 48267=>a yell  ran off  down the lane. Before Frodo could recover or  speak a word, 
line 48268=>three hobbit-bows twanged and Wormtongue fell dead. 
line 48269=>     To the dismay of those that stood by, about the  body of Saruman a grey 
line 48270=>mist gathered, and  rising slowly to a great height like smoke  from a fire, 
line 48271=>as a pale shrouded  figure it loomed over the Hill. For a moment it wavered,  
line 48272=>looking to the West; but out of the West came a cold wind, and it bent away,  
line 48273=>and with a sigh dissolved into nothing. 
line 48274=>     Frodo looked down at the body with pity and horror, for as he looked it 
line 48275=>seemed that long years of death were suddenly revealed in it, and it shrank, 
line 48276=>and the shrivelled face became rags of skin upon a hideous skull. Lifting up 
line 48277=>the skirt  of the dirty cloak  that sprawled beside  it, he covered it over, 
line 48278=>and turned away. 
line 48279=>     'And  that's  the end of that,'  said Sam. 'A nasty end,  and I  wish I 
line 48280=>needn't have seen it; but it's a good riddance.' 
line 48281=>     'And the very last end of the War, I hope,' said Merry. 
line 48282=>     'I hope so,' said Frodo and sighed. 'The very last stroke. But to think  
line 48283=>that it  should fall here, at the very  door  of Bag End! Among all my hopes 
line 48284=>and fears at least I never expected that.' 
line 48285=>     'I shan't call it  the end, till we've cleared  up  the mess,' said Sam 
line 48286=>gloomily. 'And that'll take a lot of time and work.' 
line 48287=> 
line 48288=>
line 48289=>####- 
line 48290=>
line 48291=>Chapter 9. The Grey Havens 
line 48292=>
line 48293=> 
line 48294=> 
line 48295=>     The clearing up certainly needed a lot of work, but  it took  less time 
line 48296=>than Sam had feared. The day  after the battle Frodo  rode to Michel Delving 
line 48297=>and released the prisoners from  the Lockholes. One  of the first  that they 
line 48298=>found was  poor Fredegar Bolger, Fatty no longer. He had been taken when the 
line 48299=>ruffians smoked  out a band of rebels that  he  led from their hidings up in 
line 48300=>the Brockenbores by the hills of Scary. 
line 48301=>     'You  would have  done better  to  come with us  after  all,  poor  old 
line 48302=>Fredegar!' said Pippin, as they carried him out too weak to walk. 
line 48303=>     He opened an eye and tried gallantly to  smile. 'Who's this young giant  
line 48304=>with the loud voice?' he  whispered. 'Not little Pippin! What's your size in 
line 48305=>hats now?' 
line 48306=>     Then  there  was Lobelia. Poor thing, she looked very old and thin when 
line 48307=>they rescued her  from a dark and narrow  cell. She insisted on hobbling out 
line 48308=>on her own feet; and she had such a welcome, and there was such clapping and 
line 48309=>cheering when she appeared,  leaning on Frodo's arm but still clutching  her  
line 48310=>umbrella, that she was quite touched, and drove away in tears. She had never 
line 48311=>in her life been popular before. But she was crushed  by the news of  Lotho's 
line 48312=>murder, and she would' not return to Bag End. She gave it back to Frodo, and 
line 48313=>went to her own people, the Bracegirdles of Hardbottle. 
line 48314=>     When the poor  creature died next Spring-she  was after all more than a  
line 48315=>hundred years  old  - Frodo was  surprised and much  moved: she had left all  
line 48316=>that remained of her money and of Lotho's for him to use in helping  hobbits 
line 48317=>made homeless by the troubles. So that feud was ended. 
line 48318=>     Old Will Whitfoot had been in the Lockholes longer than any, and though 
line 48319=>he had  perhaps  been treated  less harshly  than  some,  he needed a lot of 
line 48320=>feeding up before he could look the part of Mayor; so Frodo agreed to act as 
line 48321=>his Deputy, until Mr. Whitfoot was  in shape again. The  only  thing that he 
line 48322=>did as  Deputy Mayor was  to reduce the Shirriffs to  their proper functions 
line 48323=>and numbers. The task of  hunting  out the last remnant of  the ruffians was 
line 48324=>left to Merry and  Pippin,  and  it was soon done. The southern gangs, after  
line 48325=>hearing the news of the Battle of  Bywater, fled out of the land and offered 
line 48326=>little resistance to the Thain. Before the Year's End the few survivors were 
line 48327=>rounded  up in  the  woods,  and those  that  surrendered were shown  to the 
line 48328=>
line 48329=>####-borders.  
line 48330=>     Meanwhile the  labour  of  repair went on apace, and   Sam was kept very 
line 48331=>busy. Hobbits can work like bees when the mood  and the need comes on  
line 48332=>them. 
line 48333=>Now  there were thousands of willing  hands of all ages, from the  small but 
line 48334=>nimble ones of the hobbit lads and lasses to the well-worn and horny ones of 
line 48335=>the gaffers  and gammers.  Before Yule not a brick was left standing of  the 
line 48336=>new Shirriff-houses  or of anything that had been built by 'Sharkey's  Men';  
line 48337=>but the bricks were used to repair many an old hole, to make it snugger  and  
line 48338=>drier. Great stores of goods a nd  food, and beer,  were found that had  been 
line 48339=>hidden away  by  the  ruffians in  sheds and barns and deserted  holes,  and 
line 48340=>especially in the tunnels  at Michel  Delving  and  in the  old quarries  at 
line 48341=>Scary; so that there was a great deal better cheer that Yule than anyone had 
line 48342=>hoped for. 
line 48343=>     One of the first  things done in Hobbiton,  before even  the removal of 
line 48344=>the new mill, was the clearing of the Hill and Bag End, and the  restoration 
line 48345=>of Bagshot Row. The front of the new sand-pit was all levelled and made into 
line 48346=>a large sheltered garden, and new holes were dug in the southward face, back 
line 48347=>into the Hill, and they  were lined with brick. The Gaffer  was  restored to 
line 48348=>Number Three; and he said often and did not care who heard it: 
line 48349=>     'It's an  ill wind as  blows nobody no good, as I always say. And All's 
line 48350=>well as ends Better!' 
line 48351=>     There was some discussion of the name that the new row should be given. 
line 48352=>Battle  Gardens  was thought  of,  or Better  Smials.  But  after a while in 
line 48353=>sensible hobbit-fashion it was just called New Row. It was a purely  Bywater  
line 48354=>joke to refer to it as Sharkey's End. 
line 48355=>     The trees were the worst loss and damage, for at Sharkey's bidding they 
line 48356=>had been  cut down recklessly far  and wide over the Shire; and Sam  grieved 
line 48357=>over this more than anything else. For  one thing, this hurt would take long 
line 48358=>to heal, and only  his great-grandchildren, he thought,  would see the Shire 
line 48359=>as it ought to be. 
line 48360=>     Then  suddenly  one day, for he had  been too busy for  weeks to give a  
line 48361=>thought to  his adventures,   he remembered the gift of Galadriel. He brought  
line 48362=>the box  out and showed it to  the  other Travellers (for  so they were  now 
line 48363=>called by everyone), and asked their advice. 
line 48364=>     'I wondered when you would think of it,' said Frodo. 'Open it!' 
line 48365=>     Inside it was filled with a grey  dust, soft and fine, in the middle of 
line 48366=>
line 48367=>####-which was a seed, like a small nut with a  silver shale. 'What can I do with 
line 48368=>this?' said Sam. 
line 48369=>     'Throw it in the air on  a breezy day  and  let it do  its  work!' said 
line 48370=>Pippin. 
line 48371=>     'On what?' said Sam. 
line 48372=>     'Choose one spot  as  a  nursery, and  see what happens  to the  plants 
line 48373=>there,' said Merry. 
line 48374=>     'But I'm  sure  the Lady  would not like me to keep it all  for my  own 
line 48375=>garden, now so many folk have suffered,' said Sam. 
line 48376=>     'Use all the wi ts and knowledge you have of your own, Sam,' said Frodo,  
line 48377=>'and then  use the  gift to  help  your  work  and  better  it. And  use  it 
line 48378=>sparingly. There is not much here, and I expect every grain has a value.' 
line 48379=>     So Sam planted saplings in all the  places where specially beautiful or  
line 48380=>beloved trees had been destroyed, and he put a grain of the precious dust in 
line 48381=>the soil at the root of each. He went up and  down the Shire in this labour; 
line 48382=>but if he  paid special attention to Hobbiton and Bywater no one blamed h im. 
line 48383=>And  at  the end he found that he still had a little of the dust left; so he 
line 48384=>went to the Three-Farthing  Stone, which is as near the centre of the  Shire 
line 48385=>as no matter, and cast it  in  the air with his  blessing. The little silver  
line 48386=>nut he  planted  in the Party Field where the tree had  once  been;  and  he 
line 48387=>wondered  what would  come  of  it. All through  the winter  he remained  as 
line 48388=>patient  as  he  could,  and tried  to  restrain himself  from  going  round 
line 48389=>constantly to see if anything was happening. 
line 48390=>     Spring surpassed his wildest hopes. His trees began to sprout and grow, 
line 48391=>as if time was in a hurry and  wished to make one year do for twenty. In the 
line 48392=>Party Field a beautiful young sapling leaped up: it had silver bark and long 
line 48393=>leaves and burst into golden flowers  in April. It was indeed a mallorn, and 
line 48394=>it was the wonder of the neighbourhood.  In after years, as it grew in grace 
line 48395=>and beauty, it was known far and wide and people would come long journeys 
line 48396=>to 
line 48397=>see it: the only mallorn  west of the Mountains and east of the Sea, and one 
line 48398=>of the finest in the world. 
line 48399=>     Altogether 1420 in  the Shire was a marvellous year. Not only was there 
line 48400=>wonderful sunshine and delicious rain, in due times and perfect measure, but 
line 48401=>there seemed something more: an air of richness and growth, and a gleam of a  
line 48402=>beauty  beyond  that  of  mortal summers  that flicker  and  pass  upon this 
line 48403=>Middle-earth. All the children born or begotten in that year, and there were 
line 48404=>
line 48405=>####-many, were fair to see and strong, and most of them  had a rich golden  hair 
line 48406=>that had before  been rare  among hobbits.  The fruit was so  plentiful that 
line 48407=>young  hobbits very nearly bathed in  strawberries and cream; and later they 
line 48408=>sat on the lawns under the plum-trees  and ate, until they had made piles of 
line 48409=>stones  like  small pyramids or  the  heaped skulls of a conqueror, and then 
line 48410=>they  moved on. And no  one was ill,  and everyone was pleased. except those 
line 48411=>who had to mow the grass.  
line 48412=>     In the  Southfarthing the vines were laden, and the yield of 'leaf' was 
line 48413=>astonishing; and everywhere there was  so much  corn that at  Harvest  every 
line 48414=>barn was stuffed. 'The  Northfarthing barley  was so fine  that the beer  of 
line 48415=>1420 malt was long remembered and became a byword. Indeed a generation 
line 48416=>later 
line 48417=>one might hear an  old gaffer  in an inn, aft er  a good pint  of well-earned 
line 48418=>ale,  put  down his mug with a sigh:  'Ah! that was  proper fourteen-twenty, 
line 48419=>that was!' 
line 48420=>     Sam stayed at first at  the Cottons'  with Frodo; but when  the New Row 
line 48421=>was ready he went  with the Gaffer. In addition to all his  other  labours he 
line 48422=>was  busy  directing  the cleaning up and restoring  of Bag End; but he  was 
line 48423=>often away in the Shire on his forestry work. So he was not at home in early 
line 48424=>March and did not know that  Frodo had  been ill. On the  thirteenth of that 
line 48425=>month  Farmer Cotton found Frodo lying on his bed; he was clutching  a white 
line 48426=>gem that hung on a chain about his neck and he seemed half in a dream. 
line 48427=>     'It is gone for ever,' he said, 'and now all is dark and empty.' 
line 48428=>     But the fit  passed, and  when Sam got back on  the twenty-fifth, Frodo 
line 48429=>had  recovered, and he said nothing about  himself. In the meanwhile Bag End 
line 48430=>had  been  set  in order,  and Merry and Pippin came over  from  Crickhollow 
line 48431=>bringing back  all the old furniture  and gear, so that  the  old hole  soon 
line 48432=>looked very much as it always had done. 
line 48433=>     When all was at last ready Frodo said: 'When are you  going to  move in 
line 48434=>and join me, Sam?' 
line 48435=>     Sam looked a bit awkward. 
line 48436=>     'There is no need to come yet, if you don't want to,'  said Frodo. 'But 
line 48437=>you k now the Gaffer  is close at hand, and he will be very well looked after  
line 48438=>by Widow Rumble.' 
line 48439=>     It s not that, Mr. Frodo, said Sam, and he went ver red. 
line 48440=>     'Well, what is it?' 
line 48441=>     'It's Rosie, Rose Cotton,' said Sam. 'It seems she didn't like my going 
line 48442=>
line 48443=>####-abroad at all, poor lass; but as I hadn't spoken, she couldn't say so. And I 
line 48444=>didn't speak, because I had  a job to  do first. But now I have  spoken, and 
line 48445=>she says:  "Well, you've  wasted  a year,  so why wait longer?"  "Wasted?" I  
line 48446=>says. "I wouldn't call it that." Still I see what she means. I feel torn  in 
line 48447=>two, as you might say.' 
line 48448=>     'I see,' said Frodo: 'you want to get married, and yet you want to live 
line 48449=>with me in  Bag End too? But my dear  Sam, how easy! Get  married as soon as 
line 48450=>you  can, and then move in with Rosie. There's room enough in Bag End for as 
line 48451=>big a family as you could wish for.' 
line 48452=>     And so it was settled. Sam Gamgee married Rose Cotton in the Spring  of 
line 48453=>1420 (which was  also famous  for its weddings), and they came and lived  at 
line 48454=>Bag End. And if Sam thought himself lucky, Frodo knew that he was more 
line 48455=>lucky 
line 48456=>himself; for there was not a hobbit in the  Shire that was looked after with 
line 48457=>such care. When the labours of repair  had all been planned and set going he 
line 48458=>took to a quiet life, writing a great dea l and  going through all his notes. 
line 48459=>He resigned the office of Deputy Mayor at the Free Fair that mid-summer, and 
line 48460=>dear old Will Whitfoot had another seven years of presiding at Banquets.  
line 48461=>     Merry and Pippin lived together for some time at Crickhollow, and  there 
line 48462=>was  much coming  and  going between  Buckland and Bag  End.  The two  
line 48463=>young 
line 48464=>Travellers cut a great  dash in the Shire  with  their songs and their tales 
line 48465=>and their finery,  and  their wonderful  parties. 'Lordly' folk called them, 
line 48466=>meaning nothing bu t good; for it warmed all hearts to see them go  riding by 
line 48467=>with their mail-shirts so bright and their shields so splendid, laughing and 
line 48468=>singing songs of far away; and if they were now large and magnificent,  they  
line 48469=>were unchanged otherwise, unless they were  indeed  more fairspoken and 
line 48470=>more 
line 48471=>jovial and full of merriment than ever before. 
line 48472=>     Frodo and Sam, however, went back to ordinary attire,  except that when 
line 48473=>there was need they both wore long grey cloaks,  finely woven and clasped at 
line 48474=>the throat with beautiful brooches; and Mr. Frodo wore always a  white jewel 
line 48475=>on a chain that he often would finger. 
line 48476=>     All things now went well, with  hope always of becoming  still  better; 
line 48477=>and Sam  was  as busy and as  full of delight as even a hobbit  could  wish. 
line 48478=>Nothing  for him marred that whole year, except  for some vague anxiety about 
line 48479=>his  master. Frodo dropped quietly  out of all the doings of the  Shire, and 
line 48480=>
line 48481=>####-Sam was  pained to notice how little  honour he  had in his own country. Few 
line 48482=>people  knew  or  wanted  to  know about  his  deeds and  adventures;  their 
line 48483=>admiration  and  respect were given mostly  to Mr. Meriadoc and Mr. Peregrin 
line 48484=>and (if Sam had known it) to himself. Also in  the  autumn there appeared  a  
line 48485=>shadow of old troubles.  
line 48486=>     One evening Sam came into the  study and  found his master looking very 
line 48487=>strange. He was very pale and his eyes seemed to see things far away. 
line 48488=>     'What's the matter, Mr. Frodo?' said Sam. 
line 48489=>     'I am wounded,' he answered, 'wounded; it will never really heal.' 
line 48490=>     But then  he  got   up, and the  turn seemed to  pass, and he  was quite 
line 48491=>himself the next day. It was not until afterwards that Sam recalled that the 
line 48492=>date  was October the sixth. Two years before on that day it was dark in the 
line 48493=>dell under Weathertop. 
line 48494=>     Time went on, and 1421 came  in. Frodo was ill again in March, but with 
line 48495=>a great effort he concealed it, for Sam had other things to think about. The 
line 48496=>first of  Sam and Rosie's children was born on the twenty-fifth of  March, a  
line 48497=>date that Sam noted. 
line 48498=>     'Well,  Mr. Frodo,' he said. 'I'm in a bit of  a fix.  Rose  and me had 
line 48499=>settled  to  call him Frodo, with  your leave; but it's  not  him , it's her. 
line 48500=>Though as pretty a maidchild  as any one  could hope for, taking after  Rose 
line 48501=>more than me, luckily. So we don't know what to do.' 
line 48502=>     'Well,  Sam,' said Frodo,  'what's wrong with the old customs? Choose a  
line 48503=>flower name like Rose. Half the maidchildren in the Shire are called by such  
line 48504=>names, and what could be better?' 
line 48505=>     'I  suppose  you're  right,  Mr.  Frodo,'  said  Sam.  'I've heard some 
line 48506=>beautiful names on my travels,  but  I  suppose they're  a bit too grand for 
line 48507=>daily wear and tear, as you  might say. The Gaffer, he says: "Make it short, 
line 48508=>and  then you won't have to cut it short before you can use it." But if it's 
line 48509=>to be a  flower-name, then I don't  trouble about  the length: it  must be a  
line 48510=>beautiful  flower, because, you see, I  think  she is very beautiful, and is 
line 48511=>going to be beautifuller still.' 
line 48512=>     Frodo  thought  for  a  moment.  'Well,  Sam,  what  about  elanor, the 
line 48513=>sun-star, you remember the little golden flower in the grass of Lothlurien?' 
line 48514=>     'You're  right  again, Mr. Frodo!' said  Sam delighted.  'That's what I 
line 48515=>wanted.' 
line 48516=>     Little  Elanor  was nearly six months  old, and 1421  had passed to its 
line 48517=>autumn, when Frodo called Sam into the study. 
line 48518=>
line 48519=>####-     'It will be Bilbo's Birthday on Thursday, Sam,'  he  said. 'And he will 
line 48520=>pass the Old Took. He will be a hundred and thirty-one!' 
line 48521=>     'So he will!' said Sam. 'He's a marvel!' 
line 48522=>     'Well,  Sam,' said Frodo. 'I want you to see Rose  and  find out if she 
line 48523=>can spare  you, so that you and I can go off together.  You can't go  far or  
line 48524=>for a long time now, of course,' he said a little wistfully. 
line 48525=>     'Well, not very well, Mr. Frodo.' 
line 48526=>     'Of course not.  But never mind.  You can see me on my way.  Tell  Rose 
line 48527=>that you won't be away very long, not more than a fortnight; and you'll come  
line 48528=>back quite safe.' 
line 48529=>     'I wish I could go all  the way  with  you to Rivendell, Mr. Frodo, and 
line 48530=>see Mr. Bilbo,' said Sam. 'And yet the only place I really want to  be in is 
line 48531=>here. I am that torn in two.' 
line 48532=>     'Poor Sam! It will feel like that, I am  afraid,'  said Frodo. 'But you  
line 48533=>will be healed. You were meant to be solid and whole, and you will be.' 
line 48534=>     In the next day or  two Frodo went through his papers and  his writings 
