line 48561=>     'Why, you  have  nearly finished  it, Mr. Frodo!' Sam exclaimed. 'Well, 
line 48562=>you have kept at it, I must say.' 
line 48563=>     'I have quite finished, Sam,' said Frodo. 'The last pages are for you.' 
line 48564=>     On September the twenty-first  they set out together, Frodo on the pony 
line 48565=>that  had  borne him  all the  way  from  Minas  Tirith, and was  now called 
line 48566=>Strider; and Sam on his beloved Bill. It  was a fair golden morning, and Sam 
line 48567=>did not ask where they were going: he thought he could guess. 
line 48568=>     They took the Stock Road over the hills and went towards the Woody End, 
line 48569=>and they let their ponies walk  at their leisure.  They camped  in the Green 
line 48570=>Hills,  and  on September the twenty-second  they rode gently down  into the 
line 48571=>beginning of the trees as afternoon was wearing away. 
line 48572=>     'If that isn't the very tree you hid  behind when the Black Rider first 
line 48573=>showed up, Mr. Frodo!' said Sam pointing to the left. 'It seems like a dream 
line 48574=>now.' 
line 48575=>     It  was  evening, and the stars were glimmering  in the  eastern sky as 
line 48576=>they passed the ruined oak and turned and went on  down the hill between the 
line 48577=>hazel-thickets. Sam  was  silent,  deep in his memories. Presently he became 
line 48578=>aware   that  Frodo  was  singing  softly  to  himself,   singing   the  old 
line 48579=>walking-song, but the words were not quite the same. 
line 48580=>     Still round the corner there may wait 
line 48581=>     A new road or a secret gate; 
line 48582=>     And though I oft have passed them by, 
line 48583=>     A day will come at last when I 
line 48584=>     Shall take the hidden paths that run 
line 48585=>     West of the Moon, East of the Sun. 
