line 48607=>     Elrond greeted  them gravely and graciously, and Galadriel  smiled upon  
line 48608=>them. 'Well, Master Samwise,'  she said.  'I hear and see that you have used 
line 48609=>my  gift well. The Shire shall now be  more than ever blessed  and beloved.' 
line 48610=>Sam bowed, but found nothing to say. He had forgotten how beautiful the Lady 
line 48611=>was. 
line 48612=>     Then Bilbo woke up and opened his eyes. 'Hullo, Frodo!' he said. 'Well, 
line 48613=>I have passed the  Old Took today! So that's  settled. And now I think I  am 
line 48614=>quite ready to go on another journey. Are you coming?' 
line 48615=>     'Yes, I am coming,' said Frodo. 'The Ring-bearers should go together.' 
line 48616=>     'Where are you going, Master?' cried Sam, though at last he  understood 
line 48617=>what was happening. 
line 48618=>     'To the Havens, Sam,' said Frodo. 
line 48619=>     'And I can't come.' 
line 48620=>     'No, Sam. Not yet anyway, not  further  than the Havens. Though you too 
line 48621=>were a Ring-bearer, if only  for a little while. Your  time may come. Do not 
line 48622=>be too  sad, Sam. You cannot be always torn in two. You will  have to be one 
line 48623=>and whole, for many years. You have so much to enjoy and to be, and to do.' 
line 48624=>     'But,' said  Sam, and tears started  in his eyes, 'I  thought  you were 
line 48625=>going  to  enjoy the  Shire, too.  for years and  years, after all you  have 
line 48626=>done.' 
line 48627=>     'So I thought too, once. But I have been too deeply hurt, Sam. I  tried 
line 48628=>to  save the Shire, and it has been saved, but not  for me. It must often be 
line 48629=>so, Sam, when things are in danger: some one has to give them up, lose them, 
line 48630=>so that others may keep them. But you are my  heir: all that I had and might  
line 48631=>have had I leave to you.  And also you  have Rose, and Elanor; and Frodo -lad 
line 48632=>
line 48633=>####-will  come,  and  Rosie-lass,  and Merry, and  Goldilocks,  and Pippin;  and 
line 48634=>perhaps more  that I  cannot see. Your  hands and  your wits will  be needed 
line 48635=>everywhere. You will be the Mayor, of course, as long a s you want to be, and 
line 48636=>the most famous gardener in history; and you will read things out of the Red 
line 48637=>Book, and keep alive the memory of the age that is gone. so that people will  
line 48638=>remember the Great Danger and so love their beloved land all the  more.  And 
line 48639=>that will  keep  you as busy and as  happy as anyone can be, as long as your 
line 48640=>part of the Story goes on. 
line 48641=>     'Come now, ride with me!' 
line 48642=>     Then Elrond and  Galadriel rode on; for the Third Age was over, and the  
line 48643=>Days of the Rings were passed, and an end was come of the story and  song of 
line 48644=>those  times. With them  went many  Elves of the High Kindred  who  would 
line 48645=>no 
line 48646=>longer stay in  Middle-earth; and among them, filled with a sadness that was 
line 48647=>yet  blessed and without bitterness, rode Sam, and Frodo, and Bilbo, and the 
line 48648=>Elves delighted to honour them. 
line 48649=>     Though they rode through the midst of the Shire all the evening and all 
line 48650=>the night, none saw them  pass,  save the wild creatures; or here  and there 
line 48651=>some wanderer in the dark who saw a swift  shimmer  under  the trees,  or  a  
line 48652=>light and shadow flowing  through the grass as the Moon  went westward.  And 
line 48653=>when  they had passed from the  Shire,  going about the  south skirts of the 
line 48654=>White Downs, they came to the Far Downs,  and to the Towers,  and  looked on 
line 48655=>the  distant Sea; and  so they  rode down at  last to Mithlond,  to the Grey 
line 48656=>Havens in the long firth of Lune. 
line 48657=>     As  they  came  to the gates Cnrdan the Shipwright came  forth to greet 
line 48658=>them. Very tall he was,  and his beard  was long, and he  was grey  and old, 
line 48659=>save that  his eyes were keen as stars; and he looked at them and bowed, and  
line 48660=>said: 'All is now ready.' 
line 48661=>     Then Cnrdan led  them to the Havens, and there  was a white ship lying, 
line 48662=>and upon the  quay  beside a  great  grey horse stood a  figure robed all in 
line 48663=>white awaiting them.  As  he turned and came  towards  them  Frodo saw  that 
line 48664=>Gandalf now wore openly  upon his  hand the Third Ring, Narya the Great, and 
line 48665=>the stone upon it was red as fire.  Then those who were to go were glad, for  
line 48666=>they knew that Gandalf also would take ship with them. 
line 48667=>     But Sam  was now sorrowful at  heart,  and it seemed to him that if the 
line 48668=>parting would be bitter,  more grievous  still would  be  the long road home 
line 48669=>alone. But  even as they stood there, and the Elves were  going aboard,  and 
line 48670=>
line 48671=>####-all was being made ready to depart, up rode Merry and Pippin in great haste.  
line 48672=>And amid his tears Pippin laughed. 
line 48673=>     'You tried to give us the slip once before and failed, Frodo.' he said. 
line 48674=>'This time you have nearly  succeeded, but you have failed again. It was not  
line 48675=>Sam, though, that gave you away this time, but Gandalf himself!' 
line 48676=>     'Yes,' said Gandalf; 'for it will be better to ride back three together  
line 48677=>'than one alone. Well, here at  last, dear friends, on the shores of the Sea  
line 48678=>comes the end of our fellowship in Middle-earth.  Go in peace!  I  will  not 
line 48679=>say: do not weep; for not all tears are an evil.' 
line 48680=>     Then Frodo  kissed Merry  and Pippin,  and last  of all  Sam,  and went 
line 48681=>aboard; and the sails were drawn up, and  the wind blew, and slowly the ship 
line 48682=>slipped away  down  the  long  grey firth;  and the  light of  the  glass of 
line 48683=>Galadriel that Frodo bore glimmered and was lost. And the ship went out into 
line 48684=>the  High Sea and passed on into the West, until at  last on a night of rain 
line 48685=>Frodo smelled  a sweet  fragrance on the air  and heard the sound of singing  
line 48686=>that came over the water. And  then it seemed to him that as in his dream in 
line 48687=>the house of Bombadil, the grey rain-curtain turned all to silver  glass and  
line 48688=>was  rolled back, and he beheld white  shores and beyond  them  a far  green 
line 48689=>country under a swift sunrise. 
line 48690=>     But to Sam  the evening deepened to darkness as he  stood at the Haven; 
line 48691=>and as he looked at the grey sea he saw only a shadow on the waters that was 
line 48692=>soon lost in the West. There still he stood  far into the night, hearing only 
line 48693=>the  sigh and murmur of  the  waves on  the shores  of Middle-earth, and the 
line 48694=>sound of them sank deep into his  heart.  Beside him stood Merry and Pippin, 
line 48695=>and they were silent. 
line 48696=>     At last the three companions  turned away, and never again looking back  
line 48697=>they rode slowly homewards; and they spoke no word to one another until they 
line 48698=>came  back to the  Shire. but each had great comfort  in his friends  on the 
line 48699=>long grey road. 
line 48700=>     At last they rode over the downs and took the East Road, and then Merry 
line 48701=>and Pippin rode on to Buckland; and already they  were singing again as they 
line 48702=>went. But Sam turned to Bywater,  and so came back up  the Hill,  as day was 
line 48703=>ending  once  more. And  he  went on, and there  was  yellow light, and fire 
line 48704=>within; and the evening meal was ready, and he  was expected.  And Rose drew 
line 48705=>him in, and set him in his chair, and put little Elanor upon his lap. 
line 48706=>     He drew a deep breath. 'Well, I'm back,' he said. 
